<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 00:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0586 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-H     01-13 1405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Ican see him each time I walk down the hallway, the ball in his
hands, his head tilted up slightly at the basket, mouth barely open
with that famous tongue ready to sneak out to one corner, the fury
in those sparkling brown eyes telling you the shot, most certainly,
is going in.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan has been standing in this part of our house for
several years now. More accurately, a life-sized cardboard cutout
of Jordan peers out from a corner of my daughter's room, and I
can't begin to tell you the number of times in the first few months
he took up residence that a 6-6 Jordan replica scared the bejabbers
out of my wife and me, just the way the real thing must have taken
the breath away from Karl Malone when Jordan sneaked up from behind
and stole the ball in the final minute of Game 6 of the NBA Finals
last June at the Delta Center.
</P>
<P>
   Over there on one wall of a kid's shrine to the icon of our
times _ between the poster of the original Dream Team, an
autographed photo of a younger Jenna and Michael, and a plastic
wall clock on which the upper half of No. 23's body remains fixed
as he drives for a dunk while the legs move back and forth, ticking
off each second _ hangs the image to remember.
</P>
<P>
   It is a glossy 8x10 print of the last shot of Jordan's NBA
career, right after he picked the Mailman's pocket and at the
precise moment he stabbed the final dagger into the hearts of the
Jazz and the entire state of Utah.
</P>
<P>
   The photo shows Malone and John Stockton standing in the lane to
the right of the basket, Antoine Carr boxing out Dennis Rodman to
the left, and Bryon Russell _ the last victim, who had been beaten
by a stutter step right and a pull-up jumper from the head of the
key _ watching helplessly from the free-throw line with 5.6 seconds
frozen on the clock. Jordan's arm is perfectly extended, the ball
is splashing through the net, and so many pairs of hands are
clapped over shocked mouths in the background.
</P>
<P>
   Bulls 87, Jazz 86.
</P>
<P>
   Our memories are filled with so many snapshots, from that bold
jumper out on the left wing launched by a nervy North Carolina
freshman to beat Georgetown for the 1982 NCAA championship, to the
shot over an anguished Craig Ehlo in 1989 that sank Cleveland in a
first-round playoff series, to that most dramatic exit in Salt Lake
City.
</P>
<P>
   Call it the end of an Air-a. Not just on the basketball court,
but all through our multimedia, interconnected, global village of a
modern society, where Jordan has become, quite likely, the most
recognizable person on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   I have ridden subway trains in Tokyo, walked through the palace
gardens of Versailles, toured Hitler's Eagles Nest at Berchtesgaden
and been inside mom-and-pop stores in frozen Norway where people
have worn his jersey or displayed his face on a poster. What's the
old saying that 900 million Chinese don't care? Well, on a visit to
the Great Wall last year, NBA commissioner David Stern met a young
girl who wanted to talk about the ``Team of the Red Ox.'' Da Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Our grandfathers saw the incomparable Babe Ruth. Our fathers saw
the unbeatable Rocky Marciano. We saw the virtually indescribable,
all-encompassing Jordan. Each generation has its enduring symbol in
the games we play and watch.
</P>
<P>
   There were the rim-rattling dunks. The clutch 3-pointers. The
pit-bull defense by which he sank in his teeth and wouldn't let go.
</P>
<P>
   There was the tongue. The smile. The Swoosh.
</P>
<P>
   From Nike to Gatorade, from batteries to breakfast cereal, he
raised the level of the celebrity pitchman to lofty, unprecedented
heights and, in the process, became so much more than a great
athlete. Just his silhouette _ on athletic clothing or a cologne
bottle _ is enough to drive millions in sales across the spectrum
of consumers in every culture in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody wants to be like Mike. He became more than a black man
who crossed over and appealed to a white corporate audience. He
seemed to transcend race and any other barriers. He was making
movies and playing basketball with cartoon characters like Bugs
Bunny and Daffy Duck, selling long-distance telephone service with
Tweety Bird. I tawt I taw a superstar.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the flamboyance in his game, what seemed to set
Jordan apart was an ability to carry himself with a kind of quiet
dignity in the eye of the hurricane. And for all of his clean,
happy, smiling image, what allowed him to stand above his peers on
the court was this: He was a cold-blooded killer.
</P>
<P>
   From the day he cried in Los Angeles as he first hugged the NBA
championship trophy to the evening five years later on Father's Day
when he sprawled out all alone on the floor of the United Center
locker room cradling a basketball, tearfully remembering his own
pop, the late James Jordan, he defined himself by winning.
</P>
<P>
   Bulls and basketball fans everywhere always enjoyed the show.
But the question remains whether enough of them _ kids, adults and
the players he leaves behind in the NBA _ paid attention to
Jordan's total commitment to winning.
</P>
<P>
   In the early part of his career, he learned what it took from
Magic Johnson, Larry Bird and Isiah Thomas and used his own
tremendous inner pressure to turn those lessons, like coal, into
championship diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   In the early years of his NBA career, Jordan was probably the
best athlete on the planet. But he won titles by becoming the best
basketball player. He committed himself to learning the complex
triangle offense of Tex Winter and embraced all of his teammates in
a complete game. He was no longer Superman leaping tall buildings
in a single bound, but more like a basketball Einstein, a genius at
work.
</P>
<P>
   The great Jerry West once said: ``Just when you really learn how
to play the game, it's time to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan understood in time and was probably at his most
impressive after an earlier 1{-year retirement to pursue a baseball
career. We wondered if he would tarnish his reputation after the
time spent swinging and missing at the curveball. But he returned
as less of an acrobat and more of a Swiss watchmaker who knows
every single thing about how the machinery ticks. He showed us his
accumulated wisdom, his smarts, his competitive nature. No one
wants to win more than him. At any time.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was suffering from the flu on the night of Game 5 of the
1997 NBA Finals in Salt Lake City and could barely stand up. Yet
all he did was score 38 points, including 15 in the fourth quarter,
to carry the Bulls. On Jordan's only trip into Houston last season,
the Bulls defeated the Rockets, and his buddy Charles Barkley
wanted a souvenir to remember what would prove to be their final
head-to-head game. He sent a ballboy into the Bulls' locker room to
ask for Jordan's shoes _ signed, of course. Michael promptly sent
the shoes back, autographed and also inscribed with the final
score.
</P>
<P>
   ``That S.O.B.,'' said Barkley. ``I should have known.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we should all have known Jordan meant it when he said last
summer that he'd had enough and was prepared to walk away. He
claims he never picked up a basketball after hitting that shot in
Utah and spent the past seven months playing golf, smoking cigars,
drinking wine and even acquiring a bit of a paunch.
</P>
<P>
   Did he do this to claim victory over the lords of the NBA, who
eventually beat down his side of the argument in the protracted
labor war and need him now more than ever to resell their game? Did
the killer finally find a way to score the ultimate win over Bulls
owner Jerry Reinsdorf and general manager Jerry Krause, who always
made the team's championship rides bumpy?
</P>
<P>
   Where does he turn now? What can he do to be fulfilled?
</P>
<P>
   It is not like he can become an ordinary citizen and take his
kids on an unhassled vacation to Disney World or even an unescorted
trip to the mall. He can retire from the Bulls and from the NBA.
But he can never retire from being Air Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   He left before and came back. And because we know that deep
inside he is happiest when he is playing basketball, that the court
is his refuge, there will always be hope that he will return once
more to prove something to himself and to shock us.
</P>
<P>
   As with the life-sized figure standing in the corner of a kid's
room, we had just gotten used to always having Michael Jordan
around.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
