<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0589 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-JORDAN-HNS &LR;      01-13 1280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JORDAN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
A basketball career will end, and a tenure hailed as among sports'
most transcendent will be over.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Jordan will retire from the NBA today, leaving a gaping
void behind. But more than his time in the Chicago Bulls' No. 23
will be history.
</P>
<P>
   An era in sports _ and in America, perhaps _ will end. And in
ways that go beyond the legends who have come before and will
surely come again, Jordan will stand, as the day leading up to his
farewell clearly showed, as a unique, towering sports icon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy is, to me, the greatest athlete that's ever played
sports,'' Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich said. ``You say, `This guy
is an athlete; he has skills; he has strength; he has a tremendous
will to win.' In years to come, with the way we talk about (Joe)
DiMaggio, Babe Ruth, this guy has done the most.''
</P>
<P>
   Said former Detroit Pistons star Isiah Thomas, ``He was the
greatest of the greatest. He took basketball to heights we never
thought it could go.''
</P>
<P>
   The third player chosen in the 1984 NBA draft behind the
Rockets' Hakeem Olajuwon and Portland Trail Blazers footnote Sam
Bowie, Jordan became one of the most charismatic, compelling sports
figures ever and one of the world's most powerful celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   For the NBA, scarred by its six-month labor impasse and work
stoppage, the loss of its greatest hero comes as an ill-timed, if
inevitable, blow. Jordan had pledged to end his career if Phil
Jackson stepped aside as the Bulls' coach. And though Jordan had
refused to announce his departure during the lockout, only his
reticence on the topic gave rise to hope he might return.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a blessing playing against a player like that,''
Rockets veteran Mario Elie said. ``When I have children, I can show
tapes and tell them, `This is the best player who ever touched a
basketball.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Wilt Chamberlain was a great player Jerry West. There
was no one in the NBA that had the impact like Michael Jordan. Even
if he was playing the worst team in the league, that game was going
to sell out. They just came to see Michael Jordan.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans began to find out they wouldn't get another chance to see
him play late Monday as word spread that Jordan had chosen to
retire, leaving the NBA after its lockout similar to the way he
ended his baseball experiment in March 1995 as that sport was still
enduring its protracted strike.
</P>
<P>
   But more than simply choosing not to take part in the Bulls'
transition and the league's rushed, make-do season, Jordan will
leave with little else to accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   The lines on the rsum are staggering. Jordan carried the Bulls
to six championships, winning the title in each of his last six
complete seasons. He won 10 NBA scoring championships and scored
31.5 points a game for his career, both NBA records. In total
points for a career, Jordan walks away behind only Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar and Chamberlain. Jordan was the league's Most Valuable
Player five times and the NBA Finals MVP six times.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was named to the All-NBA first team 10 times and made the
league's defensive first team on nine occasions. He won two Olympic
gold medals (one before his rookie season) and was All-Star Game
MVP three times, Rookie of the Year in 1985 and slam-dunk champion
twice.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to turning pro after three seasons at North Carolina, he
won an NCAA championship _ sinking the game-winner against
Georgetown as a freshman in 1982 _ and was a two-time selection as
National Player of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   There are snapshots of sublime moments. His machine-gun,
between-the-legs dribble against Larry Bird in his 63-point playoff
effort vs. the Celtics in 1986. The foul-line leap to win a
slam-dunk contest. The reverse-direction dunk over Patrick Ewing.
The playoff-series winning jumper against Craig Ehlo and Cleveland.
The six 3-pointers in the NBA Finals against the Trail Blazers. His
Game 5, 38-point triumph over the flu and the Jazz in 1997. And his
final-minute Game 6 dominance of Utah to claim his last title this
past June.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond the highlights, awards and records, Jordan was
endlessly respected by his peers. It was as if the videos and
commercials could not capture what fellow players saw when sharing
the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes to every category,'' Lakers forward Robert Horry said.
``If you had to rank on a scale of one to 10, he had 10s. Smarts,
to knowing the game, ability, agility, anything you wanted to say,
he was No. 1 on the list. If you ever played against him and you
ran into him, it was like running into a brick wall. He was strong.
He was smart. He was talented.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you step on the court with Michael, you think, `Michael
Jordan _ the best.'''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's exit will be just another part of his amazing legacy.
He not only went out on top with his sixth championship, he
departed as the league's undisputed best player even to his final
game. When Jordan posed for just a moment as his shot defeated the
Jazz for last season's title, his freeze frame seemed to capture a
final, definitive moment in sports history.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't write a better script than that,'' Elie said. ``The
guy did everything. He accomplished everything. That's the way to
end your career, on a sweet jumper to win the championship. That's
a storybook ending.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the NBA's icons, only Bill Russell went out in similar
style, announcing his retirement after leading the Celtics to their
11th championship in 13 years. But even that did not make him his
era's unquestioned best player. Because of the presence of
Chamberlain, Russell was a first-team All-NBA selection only three
times.
</P>
<P>
   While Russell was hailed as the quintessential team player and
leader, Jordan holds that distinction for his generation in
addition to towering above his sport as its brightest individual
star.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a lot of great players,'' said Atlanta Hawks
coach Lenny Wilkens, a Hall of Famer as a player and coach. ``He
(Jordan) combined the best of everybody I've ever seen. He did it
all, on and off the court.''
</P>
<P>
   While his talent on the court was unquestioned, a rare
combination of athletic gifts and powerful will, it was off the
court where Jordan became an icon beyond sports.
</P>
<P>
   More like the singers and movie stars of other generations,
Jordan changed style. He made baldness fashionable. Shorts were
made long and baggy, sneakers produced in multicolored, often
garish splashes.
</P>
<P>
   As society adopted much of his personal style, companies far
beyond his chosen profession clamored for his Midas touch, making
him a prolific salesmen for everything from hamburgers, hot dogs
and cereal to cologne, underwear, batteries and long-distance
service.
</P>
<P>
   It is said Jordan can be in no public place for longer than 30
minutes before being overrun and overwhelmed by his supporters.
Like teen-agers pursuing Elvis Presley or the Beatles, fans have
risked their safety to touch the team bus that carried him.
</P>
<P>
   Elvis died. The Beatles broke up. Russell, Chamberlain,
Abdul-Jabbar, Bird and Magic Johnson all retired. Icons from Ruth
and DiMaggio through Muhammad Ali left their pastimes to the next
generation.
</P>
<P>
   But there has perhaps never been a sports star as clearly in
command of his time in his own time. It has long been understood
that one of sport's legends was passing through. And after today,
what might be the most celebrated, cherished career of them all
will be a memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will never be another Michael Jordan,'' Wilkens said.
``There will be great players who come through this league. But
never another Jordan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
