<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0591 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JETS-JOHNSON-HNS &LR;      01-13 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-JOHNSON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN TRUEX  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the NFL's No. 1 draft choice playing for its 30th-best team,
Keyshawn Johnson felt compelled to speak out _ or rather, write it
out.
</P>
<P>
   Just Give Me The Damn Ball! was his first literary effort, and
in it he suggested that 63 pass receptions amounted to little when
the New York Jets were 1-15 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   This season, the Jets went 12-4 and Johnson caught 83 passes for
1,131 yards. Now, they're heading into the AFC Championship Game,
thanks in large part to Johnson's efforts in their playoff opener,
a 34-24 dispatching of Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Jaguars, Johnson caught nine passes for 121 yards
and a touchdown, and he rushed for 28 yards on two end arounds, one
of which went for a 10-yard score.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets gave him the ball repeatedly. When they didn't, he took
it anyway. He recovered a fumble after chasing the play for 60
yards. And on Jacksonville's final try for the end zone, he lined
up at safety and intercepted a Hail Mary fling.
</P>
<P>
   He also blocked ferociously on numerous downfield plays.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is 26 but not too young to contemplate his legacy.
``People are going to say that I'm one of the most physical
receivers in the game,'' he says. ``Most receivers, all they care
about is catching touchdowns.''
</P>
<P>
   His performance Sunday had echoes of mythology, so complete and
so contrarian in this era of specialization. To Baby Boomers and
younger, this was Mount Olympus-at-the-Meadowlands, part Jim
Thorpe, part Deion Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   But actually, it was Jack Manders who previously put together
this combination of playoff dominance _ a receiving touchdown, a
rushing touchdown, a fumble recovery and an interception. Manders
did it in 1937, when versatility was not so rare a virtue.
</P>
<P>
   Humility is still not in Johnson's expansive repertoire. He is
not happy unless the key player is Keyshawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a team player, but I am an individual first,'' he says.
``I am going to shine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I have electricity. My electricity can make everyone
soar. I want the football. I want to block. I want to win. I want
to do it all, and I can. And I have to be the No. 1 guy with the
football, not No. 2 or No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a rookie, I had to demand the ball because we were losing
and they weren't getting it to me,'' he says. ``I don't have to
demand the ball with these coaches. They know and they recognize
talent, and they know how to exploit defenses. They know what it's
going to take to beat people.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Johnson still pleads for the football, arguing that at
6-3 and 212 pounds, he can reach just about any pass, and if he
can't catch it, he'll make sure no opponent does.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keyshawn lobbies a lot,'' says Jets quarterback Vinny
Testaverde, the AFC's leading passer. ``But it's a high-percentage
play with him. If you throw it up high enough, he's going to catch
it, and if it's a bad throw, he's going to knock it down.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets tolerate Johnson's unabashed me-first attitude because
he's possibly the hardest worker on the team.
</P>
<P>
   He slept only four hours the night before Sunday's game, and he
was at the stadium at 7:30 a.m., long before any other players. His
adrenalin count must have been off the chart. Throughout the game,
he was telling teammates, ``I'm hot, I'm hot today.''
</P>
<P>
   As Testaverde puts it, ``Keyshawn makes plays, all kinds of
plays.''
</P>
<P>
   He will need to make lots of them Sunday in Denver if the Jets
are to return to the Super Bowl for the first time in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is not talking down the Broncos, who bashed Miami 38-3.
``From what they showed against Miami, they are not beatable,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets figure their only chance to upset the defending champs
is in a shootout. The Broncos' one weakness is their secondary, so
the Jets will try to make maximum use of Johnson, hoping he can
break loose for big plays.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, not everyone appreciates Johnson's cockiness.
Much has been made of his frosty relationship with fellow receiver
Wayne Chrebet, whom Johnson called ``the team mascot'' in his book.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't like each other from the start,'' Chrebet says.
``Long before the book. He was a young kid throwing his weight
around. I don't like guys saying, `I'm gonna do this, I'm gonna do
that.'''
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Chrebet (75 receptions for 1,083 yards) and Johnson have
downplayed their dislike for each other. They have neighboring
lockers, and they display no open hostility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get asked more questions about Keyshawn than about myself,''
Chrebet says.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson empathizes with him on that point. ``What was being
talked about my first year is being talked about now,'' he says.
``You'd think it would be over with.''
</P>
<P>
   But in New York, the tabloid city, old feuds are slow to die.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, Johnson and Chrebet are much alike in their
approach to the game. Both are fearless over-the-middle
pass-catchers, while neither has the speed to be a long-ball
threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not the fastest group of wide receivers I've played
with,'' Testaverde says, ``but heart-wise and hands-wise they're up
there.''
</P>
<P>
   And if you give either one of them the ball, they can make the
most of it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
