<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: 
PUBLIC LIVES
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Answer Man &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ MIKE McCURRY, the former White House press secretary,
is still taking questions. But Tuesday night they came not from
reporters but from an invitation-only crowd that included authors
GAY TALESE, LILLIAN ROSS and GEORGE PLIMPTON.
</P>
<P>
   The first question from the audience at the question-and-answer
session, organized by the New Yorker and held at Michael's
restaurant, on West 55th Street near the Avenue of the Americas,
came from someone who could get a subpoena to force an answer:
Manhattan District Attorney ROBERT MORGENTHAU.
</P>
<P>
   Morgenthau observed that Independent Counsel KENNETH STARR, the
, began with a reputation as ``a pretty reasonable fellow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then he goes and violates every rule in the book,'' Morgenthau
said. ``What accounted for the big change in Ken Starr?''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said, ``Your opinion, in and of itself, counts for a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   A moment later he added: ``Starr was not seen as somebody you
had to do combat with. It seems to me he is an enormously righteous
person and a pious person. I don't mean that in a pejorative sense.
But clearly, it's now become a personal crusade that has clouded
his judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends for Lunch &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LESLEY STAHL's Ladies' Lunch Group does not always get together
at lunchtime.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, for example, the group (a six-year-old
confederation that Ms. Stahl said began when she and a few friends
``went through the newspapers and picked names out'') gathered at
Elaine's, the celebrity watering hole on the Upper East Side. The
occasion was a party celebrating Ms. Stahl's memoir, ``Reporting
Live'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster), which covers everything from her days as
a Watergate reporter for CBS to her present job as a correspondent
for ``60 Minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Who is in her group? In alphabetical order, the ladies are:
ELLEN FUTTER, president of the American Museum of Natural History;
LINDA FAIRSTEIN, head of the sex crimes unit of the Manhattan
district attorney's office; JURATE KAZICKAS, a freelance writer;
ANNA QUINDLEN, an author; ESTHER NEWBERG, a literary agent; LYNN
SHERR, a correspondent for the ABC News magazine ``20/20''; FAY
WATTLETON, former president of Planned Parenthood, and Judge KIMBA
WOOD of U.S. District Court in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   They get together once a month and talk about ``everything,''
Ms. Sherr said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stahl likes her lunch groups. This is one of three she
belongs to.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's embarrassing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   No Handouts Here &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is the administration of New Jersey GOV. CHRISTIE WHITMAN taking
a page from City Hall in New York?
</P>
<P>
   The Giuliani administration banned news conferences and
demonstrations on the steps last summer in a security crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   At the State Capitol in Trenton Tuesday, officials moved to stop
CURTIS FISHER, the executive director of the New Jersey Public
Interest Research Group, from passing out leaflets about an energy
deregulation bill.
</P>
<P>
   Lobbyists like Fisher have long contributed to the hubbub in the
hallways as they try to influence lawmakers before important votes
are taken.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday was the first time in memory that officials had
tried to stop the arm-twisting.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher he said that he had a permit to distribute the leaflets.
But RICHARD LA ROSSA, the executive director of the State Capitol
Joint Management Commission, which is responsible for the building
and the grounds, said Fisher had gone beyond the ``confines of the
permit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People who worked in the building were complaining,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
