<HEADER>
A0604 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JORDAN-IMMORTALS-LADN     01-13 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-IMMORTALS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDAN TRULY ONE FOR THE AGES AS HE SOARS INTO PANTHEON OF HEROES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The classic Michael Jordan story? Probably the
one about how he wrote the Gettysburg Address on the back of an
envelope on a train.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan's most memorable performance? ``The Ed Sullivan
Show'' in 1964, when the first U.S. appearance by Michael, Paul,
George and Ringo stopped crime in New York City for a night.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan's greatest team? The Nina, the Pinta and the
Santa Maria, with which he discovered America.
</P>
<P>
   The title of Michael Jordan's book? ``Origin of the Species,''
on his theory of organic evolution.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan's most memorable shot? That 6-iron on the moon.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, who is scheduled to announce his retirement today, will
go from basketball to the hall of the immortals, where he will mix
gracefully with the icons of Western culture.
</P>
<P>
   And dunk on their heads.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham Lincoln, Christopher Columbus, Charles Darwin and Alan
Shepard may be dead, The Beatles long since splintered. Few of us
can say we saw Babe Ruth, Elvis Presley or FDR in the flesh. Last
year, we lost Frank Sinatra, Roy Rogers, Tom Bradley and Harry
Caray.
</P>
<P>
   Heroes get harder to find. But we'll always have Jordan. When
our parents or grandparents say, ``I saw the Babe hit a home run,''
we'll always be able to answer, ``I saw Michael drive the lane.''
</P>
<P>
   Casual sports fans can be forgiven for asking if he was that
good, that great. So many ``superstars'' turn out to be products of
unmatchable hype, or turn out to be secretly flawed. Didn't Mickey
Mantle drink too much, and wasn't Magic Johnson a playboy?
</P>
<P>
   In a time when there are few absolutes, Jordan was one. He was
that good, that great.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   --Extraordinary skills refined by hard work: Jordan, who once
failed to make his high school team and was only the No. 3 pick in
the 1984 NBA draft, went on to be the Rookie of the Year as well as
a five-time league Most Valuable Player and a record 10-time
scoring leader.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody had his combination of talents -- the ability to freeze a
defender with the threat of a 20-foot jump shot, to blow past the
poor opponent with explosive acceleration, and to finish the play
with a sleight-of-hand layup or a powerful dunk. He also made the
league's All-Defense Team year after year.
</P>
<P>
   Part of it was that Jordan aimed high. It didn't matter that in
his 1993-95 foray into baseball, he fell short of the major
leagues. That was an admirable misadventure. He looked for a
challenge the only place he could -- beyond basketball.
</P>
<P>
   When he failed at baseball, he came back to basketball and
dominated as if he'd never been away.
</P>
<P>
   --Winning: Let this be a lesson to talented young players -- the
Lakers' Kobe Bryant leaps to mind -- who believe individuality is
the way to the Wheaties box. What set Jordan apart from Wilt
Chamberlain and Julius Erving and a handful of other spectacular
players was that Jordan's teams won championship after
championship, and he often made the decisive shots.
</P>
<P>
   He won an NCAA championship with North Carolina, two Olympic
gold medals, six NBA titles with the Chicago Bulls. He capped his
college career in his first year with the title-winning 17-footer
for the Tar Heels in '82, and capped his pro career with the
title-winning 18-footer for the Bulls last June.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls won the NBA crown in every one of Jordan's complete
seasons in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   --Style: Some players sink a big shot and then taunt their
opponents or roar into the baseline camera. Jordan would shrug. He
was so cool about it.
</P>
<P>
   It was almost as if he willed it. His 38 points in 44 minutes in
Game 5 of the '97 NBA Finals victory over the Utah Jazz, while
playing with a case of the flu so debilitating he had to be
practically carried to the bench in the fourth quarter, was the the
closest thing we'll see to real heroism on a basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   Style? Jordan literally set the style for the sport. His fashion
statement, the baggy shorts, became universal. Now we laugh at old
clips of Magic and Larry Bird in their short shorts.
</P>
<P>
   --Commercial appeal: Jordan endorsed Nike; Nike promoted Jordan.
No African-American athlete ever enjoyed the influence with the
predominantly white buying public that Jordan has.
</P>
<P>
   Although Nike announced it will continue to honor its contract
with Jordan, the price of Nike stock fell 5.4 percent Tuesday on
news of his retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan maintained his broad popularity in part by avoiding
personal scandal and controversy.
</P>
<P>
   An acknowledged penchant for high-stakes casino gambling never
tarnished him; the conspiracy theory that linked gambling to his
father's murder didn't fly. Sidestepping controversy over Nike's
pricing and labor practices wasn't particularly noble, but it's
hard to say any athlete or entertainer would do better in the same
position since none has ever attained it.
</P>
<P>
   --Timing: Jordan didn't revive the NBA; Magic and Bird had
already done that. Michael merely taught it to dance again.
</P>
<P>
   Merely? Fortune magazine calculated that Jordan's popularity was
responsible for $165 million in NBA ticket sales and $366 million
in TV and merchandise revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Now we'll see if that revenue stream dries up without him.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan's most clever quote? After Lady Astor groused,
``Mr. Jordan, if you were my husband, I would put poison in your
coffee,'' Michael retorted, ``Madam, if I were your husband, I
would drink it!''
</P>
<P>
   Odd personal fact about Michael Jordan? He had wooden teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan's greatest creation? His blueprint for the
Guggenheim Museum.
</P>
<P>
   An unforgettable Michael Jordan movie? ``On the Waterfront,''
featuring his classic ``I coulda been a contenda'' scene.
</P>
<P>
   He fits right in with Winston Churchill, George Washington,
Frank Lloyd Wright and Marlon Brando.
</P>
<P>
   That's why we won't soon stop humming his theme song: ``Thanks
for the Memories.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
