<HEADLINE>
AFTER LOSING $6 MILLION, PUBLIC THEATER TO CLOSE `ON THE TOWN'
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Faced with faltering ticket sales for ``On the
Town,'' the Joseph Papp Public Theater said on Tuesday that it
would close the production on Sunday at a loss of an estimated $6
million.
</P>
<P>
   George C. Wolfe, the artistic director of the Public and the
show's director, announced the decision to the cast at the Gershwin
Theater late Tuesday afternoon. After the final matinee, it will
have played 65 performances and 37 previews.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released by the theater, Wolfe said he had hoped
a recent advertising campaign emphasizing some of the show's good
reviews would ``surmount the annual January doldrums on Broadway.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This unfortunately was not the case,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The closing notice for ``On the Town'' brings to an end an
18-month tale surrounding the show, a 1944 musical that tells the
story of three sailors on a 24-hour leave in wartime New York.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe first staged the musical in August 1997 at the Delacorte
Theater in Central Park, where it received mixed reviews. Most
critics faulted that production's weak dance sequences, a fact many
veterans pointed to as an ominous sign for any Broadway prospects
for the show.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the weak reviews, Wolfe pushed on with plans for a
Broadway run, hiring a series of choreographers and eventually
booking the Gershwin, the largest theater on Broadway, for an
open-ended run. Wolfe himself was slowed by kidney failure and a
subsequent kidney transplant last March.
</P>
<P>
   The show finally opened in November, three days late, to
lukewarm reviews. Ticket sales soon decreased, and by late
December, the producers had bought air time to broadcast slick,
expensive television advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   They did not help. Last week, the show saw its weekly gross
sales dip to a paltry $255,653, a figure that represented a loss of
about $200,000. For Wolfe, the acclaimed director of such Tony
Award-winning productions as ``Bring In da Noise, Bring In da
Funk'' and ``Angels in America,'' the show's closing marked an
unexpected, and personal, defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a joyous experience working with all the talented
creators, designers and performers associated with `On the Town,'
he said in a statement. ``I thank them for their commitment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
