<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-GOV-ADDRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITMAN SETS APRIL 15 FOR PROPERTY TAX PLAN
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JENNIFER PRESTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Gov. Christie Whitman asked state lawmakers
Tuesday to enact her proposed five-year, $1 billion property tax
relief package by April 15 so homeowners can get their first rebate
check by Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   Republican and Democratic lawmakers applauded the plan, which
Whitman outlined Tuesday in her fifth annual address to a joint
session of the state Legislature. The proposal would provide an
average rebate check of $120 to homeowners this year and an average
of $600 annually beginning in the fifth year. Tenants would receive
an average of $100 annually under the program when it is fully
phased in.
</P>
<P>
   But Whitman acknowledged that using state budget dollars to pay
for property tax rebates in future years would require ``fiscal
discipline from those of us in Trenton.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fiscal discipline means being very cautious about any new
spending programs,'' she said. ``Fiscal discipline means constantly
reminding ourselves that the No. 1 priority is helping you, the
taxpayer. The fiscal discipline we show today will deliver a check
to you tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Democratis lawmakers expressed concern about the long-term
fiscal implications of the property tax rebate plan. Others
questioned the fairness of making the rebates available even to the
state's wealthiest residents.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the other new initiatives that the governor presented
Tuesday focused on education, health care and open space, as well
as an issue that is a concern of a growing number of middle-class
families: caring for chronically ill elderly relatives.
</P>
<P>
   In her 35-minute address at the recently renovated War Memorial
building here, Whitman called for imposing tougher standards on new
teachers, offering cash incentives to landowners who donate open
space or farmland to the state or private land trusts, hiring more
park maintenance workers, and expanding the program providing
health insurance to uninsured children.
</P>
<P>
   Although the state is expected to end the current fiscal year
with a budget surplus between $800 million and $1 billion, most of
the governor's plans would require modest or no spending increases
or would be paid for from existing funds or windfalls, like the
tobacco settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Although Whitman defeated former Gov. Jim Florio in 1993 with
the enthusiastic support of the National Rifle Association, she
disappointed some gun owners and the gun lobby Tuesday. She
announced that she would propose legislation requiring that every
gun sold in New Jersey include either a safety lock or the new
``smart gun'' technology, preventing anyone other than the gun's
owner from firing the weapon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want one more gun sold in this state without built-in
protection for our children,'' Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   But Whitman is likely to face a battle from some lawmakers over
the gun legislation, particularly from Assembly Speaker Jack
Collins, a fellow Republican. He was among a handful of lawmakers
who did not applaud when she talked about the gun bill.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said later that he would be reluctant to impose
requirements on gun owners before the ``smart gun'' technology was
widely available.
</P>
<P>
   Several Democrats took credit Tuesday for Whitman's decision to
make property tax relief the centerpiece of her address.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, Whitman cut state income tax rates by 30
percent, but polls showed that voters did not give her much credit
for the tax cuts during her hard-fought 1997 re-election campaign.
Whitman won re-election, but narrowly, in part because voters
complained that she did not do enough to bring down the state's
property tax rates, the highest in the nation. They also complained
about auto insurance, which Whitman addressed last year but did not
mention in Tuesday's speech.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
