</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PATAKI-PROBE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI INAUGURAL TEAM TOLD TO DISCLOSE COSTS
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ A ruling Tuesday by the state's highest court
forces Gov. George Pataki's supporters to disclose detailed
expenses paid by his 1995 inaugural and transition organizations,
information they have fought for four years to keep secret.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, by the Court of Appeals, is the latest in a long
string of court losses for associates of the governor, who have
opposed a bid by the majority Democrats in the state Assembly to
learn how the two organizations raised and spent more than $2.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   The Court of Appeals refused to hear the Pataki team's appeal,
meaning that orders by two lower courts to turn over the
information stand. With no higher state court to appeal to, the
transition and inaugural organizations have 15 days to provide the
information to the Assembly Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's decision deals specifically with $60,000 in credit
card charges. The two groups had given only a general description
of the charges and had not said who made each one. The Assembly
Democrats won the right Tuesday to see the credit card receipts.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats said Tuesday they had no idea what they would find
in the data. ``What we've been trying to do for four years now is
just plain public disclosure, and this is a big step in that
direction,'' said Patricia Lynch, a spokeswoman for Assembly
Speaker Sheldon Silver, a Manhattan Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling also gives the Democrats the right to take sworn
testimony from Charles Gargano, who was Pataki's chief fund-raiser
in 1994 and headed the inaugural team. He is now the state
commissioner of economic development. Ms. Lynch said it was not
clear whether the Assembly would call Gargano to testify.
</P>
<P>
   Michael McKeon, the governor's press secretary, said of
Tuesday's ruling: ``This has been a politically motivated case from
the very beginning, and it still is today. Nevertheless, we will
comply.''
</P>
<P>
   In late 1994, after Pataki defeated Gov. Mario Cuomo, the
governor-elect's aides and supporters formed a corporation to pay
for his lavish, three-day inaugural festivities, which cost $1.6
million, and another to finance a transition team, which spent
$900,000.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Pataki said the organizations would make full
disclosure of their finances and would abide by the rules governing
campaign fund-raising, although there was no legal requirement that
they do so. But after he took office, the two corporations declined
to make their records public, and it was disclosed that some
corporate sponsors gave far more than the $5,000 limit on corporate
campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Not until July 1996 did the organizations, under court order,
release the names of contributors and the amounts they gave, which
showed that the total raised was much higher than administration
officials had said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the money came from corporations and business people
whose interests were regulated by the state or who were seeking
state contracts, and the records showed that many corporate
sponsors had given far more than the $5,000 limit on corporate
campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   It was also disclosed that many of the governor's advisers
collected salaries from the transition fund, including some who
failed to disclose the income on the forms they filed with the
state Ethics Commission, as required by law.
</P>
<P>
   Later court rulings forced the release of most information on
how the money was spent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 0023EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
