<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-SCHOOP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A WEEK TO MAKE SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With one half-court shot by Adam Spanich against
Oregon last week, USC's basketball team seeped into national
prominence with exposure on nearly every sports highlight show.
</P>
<P>
   But whether the Trojans turn out to be more than a one-night
story will be determined in the next seven days, when USC faces a
critical juncture of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans have a rare three-game Pacific-10 Conference
homestand against Stanford, California and UCLA. The Cardinal and
Bruins are ranked in the top 15, and the Bears are hovering just
outside the top 25.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Trojans are one of the conference's surprise teams
with a 10-3 record, how they fare in the next three games could
play a significant role in their chances of making the NCAA
Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first got our schedule, I looked at these games
first,'' center Brian Scalabrine said. ``I looked at that and I
said that we will make or break our season here.''
</P>
<P>
   Scalabrine actually believes the Trojans are entering a
four-game stretch of critical games, because USC follows up its
homestand with a trip to Seattle to play Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really need these four games in a row,'' Scalabrine said.
</P>
<P>
   That might be wishful thinking, but the games are particularly
important because the Trojans already dropped a home game against
Arizona, and can probably only afford one more loss at home.
</P>
<P>
   USC had a chance to make up for the Arizona loss by sweeping the
Oregon schools last weekend. But after Spanich's unlikely 3-pointer
beat the Ducks, the Trojans lost in overtime at Oregon State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel there's pressure every game, but it really started when
we lost to Arizona,'' Scalabrine said. ``It's three home games and
we have to win our home games. It's big.''
</P>
<P>
   Add to that to the Trojans 0-2 record against top-10 teams
(Kansas, Arizona), and the trio of games become even more important
to their psyche and power ratings. Two wins would be considered
good, and winning three. . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Sweeping will be what we want to do. If we win three games,
we're like a tournament team,'' Scalabrine said. ``We've proved
ourselves. We'd have beaten top-ranked teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be positive if we get two out of three. One out of three
would be a bad week for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The thought of emphasizing games on the schedule flies in the
face of everything USC coach Henry Bibby believes in, so he
naturally has little to say other than he looks forward to playing
Stanford on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure that's the wrong question to ask me. I'm not looking
at three games. I'm looking at one game. Hopefully, we can get
Stanford,'' Bibby said. ``It's important that we have these games.
It doesn't matter where we play them because they're all good
teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps these games will be more interesting for the Trojans
than any other team in the Pac-10, because it will show whether
they have homecourt advantage against the conference's elite. USC
is 7-1 at the Sports Arena, despite averaging a conference-low
2,926.
</P>
<P>
   After losing to Arizona last week, the Trojans wondered if they
receive the same treatment from officials that teams like Stanford
and Arizona do when they play at home before sellout crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even at home, we don't get much respect because we're not a
big basketball school,'' Spanich said. ``You saw what happened
against Arizona. Sometimes, it's like playing five on eight, and
that's not knocking the refs, but it seems like we don't get a lot
of calls. Maybe because we're not expected to win those games.
</P>
<P>
   ``These games are huge. This is what we've got to do to help
make our season. We've got to defend the homecourt. We've got to
get that mentality for these games.''
</P>
<P>
   USC, tied for second in the Pac-10 at 2-2, also needs Spanich
and Elias Ayuso to find their shooting touch.
</P>
<P>
   While Scalabrine, power forward Sam Clancy, forward Jeff
Trepagnier and point guard Brandon Granville have solidified their
roles, the shooting- guard position has been inconsistent. Spanich
and Ayuso made 11 of their 15 3-point attempts in USC's 85-84
victory over Oregon. Two nights later, they were 4 for 16 in a
69-66 loss to Oregon State.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we come through, it controls everything. (Ayuso) and I are
the X-factor,'' Spanich said. ``It's been a tough year for us, the
way we've played.''
</P>
<P>
   Just in case some of the Trojans don't realize the importance of
this stretch, Scalabrine said he will probably bring it up before
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure that the team thinks these three games will make
or break the season,'' he said. ``I'm gonna talk to the senior
leaders . . . and stress the importance of these games. If we can
win these games, we can be a legit team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
