<SLUG> BC-NY-VA-TRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT ON TRASH FROM NEW YORK HAS VIRGINIA IN A TIZZY 
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hey, New York: Virginia is for lovers, not trash.
</P>
<P>
   That was the message Tuesday from some politicians and
environmentalists in Virginia, a state already saddled with the
dubious distinction as the nation's No. 2 importer of trash (after
Pennsylvania). They were responding to a report that the country's
largest waste-disposal company might be about to ship up to 4,000
more tons a day of New York garbage to Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The company, Waste Management Inc., and New York officials
hastened to insist that no change was imminent in their contractual
arrangement, under which 2,400 tons of New York trash a day is now
shipped to Virginia and other states. But just the possibility of
more Gotham garbage created an uproar among Virginians.
</P>
<P>
   Through Waste Management and other companies, New York already
supplies 60 percent of Virginia's imported trash, said state Sen.
William Bolling, a leader in his state's battle to stem the rising
tide of garbage. New York has been exporting large volumes of
garbage as it prepares to shut down the Fresh Kills landfill on
Staten Island in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post reported Tuesday that a contract had been
signed that would increase the daily tonnage of New York garbage
handled by Waste Management to 4,000, from 2,400, and permit all of
it to be sent to Virginia by barge.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Meket, a Waste Management spokeswoman in Virginia,
said the company had signed a contract with a barge company that
would allow up to 4,000 tons of garbage a day to be transported to
a new port on the James River that the company has been building.
</P>
<P>
   But she denied that a new contract had been signed with New York
to increase the tonnage from the city or to specify that its sole
destination would be Virginia. ``What needs to be taken into
consideration,'' she said, ``is that Waste Management has a lot of
operations on the East Coast.''
</P>
<P>
   Paula Young, a spokeswoman for the New York City Department of
Transportation, said, ``There has been no change in the city's
contract with Waste Management.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the Post report fanned anxieties in Virginia, where
just this week, Gov. James Gilmore said for the first time that he
would support measures to limit the amount of trash entering
Virginia's landfills and ban the transporting of trash by barge.
Mark Miner, a spokesman for the governor, said Tuesday that Gilmore
would make the trash issue a major theme of Wednesday night's State
of the Commonwealth address.
</P>
<P>
   ``As governor of Virginia, he will not sit idly by and allow
out-of-state garbage to be randomly dumped in Virginia,'' Miner
said.
</P>
<P>
   The day before the governor's announcement, Virginia
Commonwealth University released a poll showing that 87 percent of
those surveyed supported limiting the amount of out-of-state
garbage coming into Virginia. Only 9 percent said that limits
should not be imposed because of the additional revenues the trash
brings to the communities where the landfills are located.
</P>
<P>
   Bolling, a Republican, said the huge volume of imported garbage
_ now up to 4 million tons a year _ was exhausting the state's
landfill capacity, raising questions about whether there will be
room for the state's own garbage, creating environmental problems
and interfering with the state's efforts to attract tourists.
``Obviously, it's a good deal for New York,'' he said. ``They are
able t
</P>
<P>
   o transfer their problems to us. But it's not a very good thing
for Virginia.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Young said it was up to Waste Management, not New York City,
to decide where the garbage goes. ``We are their client,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Sharp, the executive director of Campaign Virginia, a
nonprofit environmental lobby, acknowledged that somehow New York
trash was more irksome to Virginians than trash from other places.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't explain it,'' he said. ``It's a Virginia thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
