<SLUG> BC-FACULTY-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY OF PUBLIC UNIVERSITIES ADVISES CHANGING FACULTY OF THE
FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  ((nk) 
 By ETHAN BRONNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new report by administrators and trustees of public
universities urges that the nation's expanding number of part-time
instructors be better paid and more fully integrated into their
institutions while tenured professors be subject to reviews ending
in reward or punishment.
</P>
<P>
   The report also calls for greater accountability over
sabbaticals, including written proposals before and reports after,
as part of a set of measures intended to persuade legislators and
the public that state universities are running themselves more like
private corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are at the point where we have had an easy 30 years for
funding and now we need to relearn how to explain ourselves,'' said
John H. Hammang, director of special projects at the American
Association of State Colleges and Universities and the coordinator
of the 18-month study, ``Facing Change: Building the Faculty of the
Future.''
</P>
<P>
   The report's chairman, Charles B. Reed, chancellor of the
California State University system, said the main concern was
waning public confidence in the way public universities ran their
affairs, including tenure. The proportion of part-time instructors
has reached 50 percent of the faculty at many institutions, Reed
added.
</P>
<P>
   The number of part-time instructors has nearly doubled since
1970, largely a result of cost-saving efforts, according to a
report issued a year ago by the Modern Language Association of
America. That report said that from 1990 to 1995, 55 percent of the
7,598 Ph.D.'s who graduated in English and foreign-language
programs failed to find full-time tenure-track positions in the
year they received their degrees. It warned that such trends were
threatening the quality of higher education. Part-time instructors
often get a fraction of full-time salaries with no benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The new report made clear that a large percentage of part-time
instructors was inescapable and universities should train them,
evaluate them and pay them more like full-time teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The report also defended the importance of tenure for full-time
faculty in the name of academic freedom but said it should not
serve as a shield for nonproductive scholars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 0037EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
