<SLUG> BC-BKC-LIU-JONES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES, EX-LIU STAR, FACING GUN CHARGE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By LENA WILLIAMS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Charles Jones, the former Long Island University
basketball player who led the nation in scoring the last two
seasons, was arraigned Monday in Brooklyn Criminal Court on gun
possession charges stemming from an incident at a campus dormitory
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 23, was also charged with menacing and harassment, the
Brooklyn district attorney's office said. He was released on $500
bail and faces a maximum sentence of one year in prison and a
$1,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   According to a complaint filed Tuesday, Jones and two other men,
identified as Norman Epps, 38, and Gregory Cordew, 25, displayed a
firearm and threatened a security guard at LIU's Brooklyn campus
about 3 a.m. Sunday. Jones and the two other men, who were charged
along with him, threatened to rob the guard, Otho Babs, along with
other security guards, the complaint alleged.
</P>
<P>
   An unloaded .357 Magnum handgun was recovered from a planter in
front of a building in downtown Brooklyn where the defendants were
arrested, the complaint said.
</P>
<P>
   In a news release issued Tuesday, Brooklyn District Attorney
Charles J. Hynes described the charges against Jones as serious.
``They will be prosecuted swiftly and fairly,'' Hynes said.
</P>
<P>
   An LIU official said that Jones was no longer a student there
and that he was believed to have graduated last year.
</P>
<P>
   The incident may seal the fate of one of the most promising
college players in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, a 6-foot-5-inch guard, transferred to LIU after two
seasons at Rutgers. Recruited by former LIU coach Ray Haskins, who
has known Jones since he was 8 and lives near his family in
Bedford-Stuyvesant, Jones blossomed under Haskins' run-and-gun
style.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was instrumental in helping the Blackbirds (21-9) win the
Northeast Conference championship in 1997 and a bid to the National
Collegiate Athletic Association tournament, where they lost in the
first round to Villanova. That year, Jones won the Haggerty Award,
given annually to the outstanding Division I player in the New York
area.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Blackbirds were 21-11 and went to the National
Invitational Tournament, where Jones scored 45 points in a losing
effort against Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   Pro scouts predicted that Jones would be picked in the early
rounds of last June's National Basketball Association draft. But
for reasons some attribute to a poor showing during the second half
of last season and to a one-dimensional game unsuited for an NBA
point guard, Jones was bypassed. Teammates and friends said Jones
was disappointed that he was not drafted, shattering his childhood
dream.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 0039EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 00:41 </DATE_TIME>
