<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-McDONOUGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARROLL RETURNING BUT FIRES TWO ASSISTANTS 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL McDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some coaches are taking the fall in Foxborough, but not Pete
Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Carroll's assistants, offensive line coach Paul Boudreau
and wide receivers coach Steve Walters, were fired Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe has been told that Carroll did the firing himself and
gave the impression that he was going to be head coach next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have scheduled a teleconference Wednesday, but the
fired coaches aren't supposed to be on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, vice president of player personnel Bobby Grier is
expected to give a ``State of the Patriots'' address that will end
speculation about Carroll being fired.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville Jaguars offensive coordinator Chris Palmer, who
would have been the first choice to succeed Carroll if the Patriots
fired him, was in Baltimore Tuesday interviewing for the Ravens'
head coaching job.
</P>
<P>
   Three other coaches on the New England staff _ Carl Smith (tight
ends), Bo Pelini (linebackers), and Ron Lynn (defensive backs) _
have contracts that have expired, and they have not been told their
fate yet, so more assistants could be made the scapegoats for the
Patriots' disappointing season.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, offensive coordinator Larry Kennan was fired after
just one season and replaced by Ernie Zampese, who had been fired
in Dallas when Chan Gailey became head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Boudreau and Walters were two of the coaches most respected by
the players on the team.
</P>
<P>
   Boudreau always drew praise from quarterback Drew Bledsoe and
the offensive linemen. When he was selected to the Pro Bowl a year
ago, Bruce Armstrong gave credit to Boudreau and showed his
appreciation by giving the coach and his wife a trip to Hawaii as a
reward.
</P>
<P>
   Walters was in his second go-around with the Patriots. He came
to pro football in 1982 when Ron Meyer was named head coach in New
England but spent most of his career on Jim Mora's staff in New
Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll may have a hard time finding quality replacements. Right
now there is an abundance of coaching jobs open in the NFL, and the
Patriots figure to get last call.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Holmgren in Seattle, George Seifert in Carolina, Mike Riley
in San Diego, Andy Reid in Philadelphia, and Ray Rhodes in Green
Bay are all starting out in new jobs with long-term contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the Patriots stage an amazing turnaround to win the AFC
East and get to the Super Bowl, Carroll undoubtedly will be fired
at the end of next season. So what assistant would want to come to
New England with a one-year contract?
</P>
<P>
   After this season ended with a playoff loss in Jacksonville in
the wild-card round, the Krafts, Bob and Jonathan, said there would
be a three-week evaluation of Carroll and the coaching staff. There
was no mention of evaluating Grier or vice president Andy
Wasynczuk, who have been in charge of hiring and firing players the
last two years as the team started a slide from the Super Bowl days
of two seasons ago.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll told his coaches when he met with them after the season
that he did not want to make any changes. But obviously, by firing
Boudreau and Walters, Carroll is getting his marching orders from
the front office, most likely Grier, who is the relay station
through which the Krafts' directives come.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have not run the ball well the last two years,
which is why Boudreau is paying. However, they didn't run the ball
well when they went to the Super Bowl, either. The linemen Boudreau
was handed are excellent pass protectors but not run-blockers.
</P>
<P>
   Walters is most likely getting burned for the disappearance of
Terry Glenn the last two years. There must be some attempt by upper
management to explain why Glenn has not reached the heights he
attained as a rookie under Bill Parcells and his staff.
</P>
<P>
   There is speculation that Grier could reach out for Harold
Jackson as the next receivers coach. Jackson, who is currently with
the Saints, was a popular player in New England and later coached
here.
</P>
<P>
   The Saints, however, might not give permission for New England
to talk to Jackson. They don't have to if all the Patriots are
offering is a lateral move.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
