<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 00:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0639 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS &LR;      01-13 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
Michael Jordan will tip over the first domino today, removing
himself from the NBA's three-time defending champions.
<TEXT>
<P>
   And while the fallout from his retirement will shake the Chicago
Bulls to their foundation, it has already reached Houston and the
Rockets' offices as swiftly as a Jordan drive to an open basket.
</P>
<P>
   With Jordan gone, one of the primary reasons for running mate
Scottie Pippen to stay in Chicago no longer exists. And without
Jordan to send the team's payroll toward the court in Space Jam,
the Bulls can join the chase for free agent Antonio McDyess.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets have cleared enough room under the salary cap to
pursue either frontcourt star and have initiated conversations with
the representatives of both.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rockets have interest. Scottie has interest,'' said
Pippen's agent, Jimmie Sexton. ``It's something he's considering
strongly. What really makes it look so inviting is with Charles
(Barkley), Hakeem (Olajuwon) and Scottie, there's a three-person
nucleus that's very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Sexton said Jordan's decision ``doesn't really affect anything''
in regard to his client. But Jordan's decision does not make that
of the Rockets any easier, not that anyone is ready to describe
their dilemma as simply making a choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had two goals (going into this offseason's rebuilding),''
Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich said. ``One is to stay competitive
with our eye on a championship. The other one is to induce some
youth into this organization.''
</P>
<P>
   That would seem to address both players and their vastly
different qualifications, as either _ along with the Rockets' three
draft picks _ would help the Rockets take a step toward answering
the need to win now and build for later.
</P>
<P>
   McDyess, in addition to considering the Rockets, is weighing
whether to remain with the Phoenix Suns or return to the Denver
Nuggets, his original pro team. He has also said he would consider
the Bulls, and sources said his representatives have heard often
from Chicago officials since teams and agents were allowed to begin
talking Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen is expected to be targeted by the Suns, Orlando Magic and
Los Angeles Lakers, who would likely try to work out a
sign-and-trade deal with the Bulls involving Elden Campbell or
Eddie Jones.
</P>
<P>
   But as unpredictable as the recruiting of top NBA talent will
surely be when players can begin signing next week, the Rockets
must weigh how different talents will fit.
</P>
<P>
   McDyess, 24, would offer a young, blossoming talent likely to
still be in his prime through a six-year deal, the longest teams
signing other teams' free agents are permitted to offer. He
averaged 15.1 points and 7.6 rebounds while sharing time in the
crowded Suns frontcourt last season.
</P>
<P>
   Any team interested in McDyess will likely have to offer the
maximum contract permitted, beginning at $9 million in the first
season, with 10-percent raises each year.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen, who is seeking a five-year deal, is already established
as one of the top 50 players in league history, with six
championships and seven All-Star appearances. But he is 33 and,
though reportedly ready for the season, coming off back surgery.
</P>
<P>
   And if Pippen demands the maximum salary allowed an 11-year
veteran, beginning at $14 million per season, the Rockets might
have trouble fitting him under the cap.
</P>
<P>
   But if a window opened with Jordan's decision, even at an
inconvenient, baffling time, the Rockets' pursuit of a marquee free
agent might have been changed as much as the Bulls' chances at a
seventh title.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
