<HEADER>
A0640 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      01-13 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING BEST OF BAD SITUATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Let's look at the good side:
</P>
<P>
   -- Chicago will cease to be the most annoyingly insufferable
sports city in America. It will be Milwaukee with hockey.
</P>
<P>
   -- Nike's share value lost 5.4 percent Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   -- Casinos in Las Vegas and Atlantic City increased staffing 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
   -- Bulls owner Jerry Reinsdorf, who also owns the White Sox,
needs to have great things happen from Bill Wennington and Nardi
Contreras.
</P>
<P>
   -- Unable to find someone to cover for his frequent brainlocks,
Scottie Pippen will become the NBA's version of Kenny in ``South
Park'' _ killed every show.
</P>
<P>
   -- Ahmad Rashad will need to find someone else's hip pocket to
be carried around in.
</P>
<P>
   -- Toni Kukoc will have to break a sweat.
</P>
<P>
   -- A team that has not employed one among Jordan, Hakeem
Olajuwon, Isiah Thomas, Julius Erving, Larry Bird or Magic Johnson
will win an NBA championship for the first time since the Sonics'
championship 20 years ago, so NBC will be forced to file Chapter
11.
</P>
<P>
   -- George Karl will move back one more spot, to No. 1,238, just
behind Roseanne, on the list to eventually succeed Dean Smith at
North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   -- Dennis Rodman will have more time to spend on his marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Now let's look at the bad side:
</P>
<P>
   -- Jordan isn't taking us with him.
</P>
<P>
   Can you believe this guy? All the stuff bought with his name on
it, and he leaves us with a broken-down league in a bastard season.
</P>
<P>
   Tempting as it is to call him an ingrate, it's hard to argue
with his reasoning.
</P>
<P>
   This will be the worst pro sports season since the NFL's use of
strike-breaking scab players in 1987. Fifty games will be played in
about 100 days mostly by guys who are fat, old and hurt and don't
know each other. By May each team is going to look like the
Iditarod dog sled team that had to pull a grand piano.
</P>
<P>
   Why would Jordan want any part of this? Why would a basketball
fan want a part of this? I'd prefer a presentation of Kevin
Calabro's chickens flyin' in a barnyard.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday the Sonic brass, including owner Barry Ackerley, called
a news conference to announce an effort to win back fans that was
breathtakingly lame.
</P>
<P>
   The goodies: free open scrimmage, free exhibition game, a fix-up
of some local basketball courts.
</P>
<P>
   Woo-eee. For this, the fan is supposed to say, ``All is
forgiven''?
</P>
<P>
   The feeble gestures were yet another example of the arrogant
attitudes that fueled the lockout. I asked Ackerley, in light of
the half-season, why all tickets shouldn't be half-price.
</P>
<P>
   He deferred to a henchman, John Dresel, who said the good news
was the Sonics decided not to raise ticket prices, and that no
price cuts were contemplated ``to reflect the value of Sonic
basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   A case can be made that this NBA season will have almost no
value. The '99 title will bear an asterisk bigger than Shawn Kemp's
ballooning waistline. The half-season will be almost devoid of
training camp and practices, players will have no clue about new
teammates, they will be forced to play beyond exhaustion, injuries
will be pervasive and the games will be officiated by the handful
of NBA veteran referees not in jail.
</P>
<P>
   But hey, the owners have cost certainty, and for that I can't
begin to describe my sense of relief. The mere thought of Ackerley,
Reinsdorf, Paul Allen, Ted Turner, etc., having to pick up the
phone to transfer funds to cover a temporary cash shortfall in a
minor business operation has interrupted my sleep with screams
every night.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is Jordan's concern anymore. He claims to be done,
and the rest of us are left to sort and catalogue the legacy.
Here's five fresh entries.
</P>
<P>
   Best local Jordan tale I heard Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was playing with the Bulls in the '80s, we had a
reserve guard named Pete Myers,'' said Billy McKinney, the Sonics'
basketball VP and former journeyman guard. ``He had some talent,
but his job was to guard Jordan in practice. We all wondered how
much damage was done to his potential by that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll never know how good Pete might have been if he didn't
have to go up against a guy who every single day was trying to tear
his heart out.''
</P>
<P>
   Worst advice to Jordan:
</P>
<P>
   McKinney, again: ``Before the 1985-86 season, I told him that if
he continues to work at his pace, he'll burn out in six or seven
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Most hapless task:
</P>
<P>
   Attempting to use the written word to capture the most majestic
physical artist in sports history.
</P>
<P>
   Best guess:
</P>
<P>
   He'll be back.
</P>
<P>
   Worst outcome:
</P>
<P>
   For that to happen, the NBA will have to be here.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 0058EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 01:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0641 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     01-13 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU HAD TO LOVE JORDAN, EVEN AS HE BROKE HEARTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It is impossible not to suspect that Michael Jordan
the pitch man, Michael Jordan the business man, Michael Jordan the
golfer and Michael Jordan the world's greatest celebrity will have
a plentiful life after today.
</P>
<P>
   But the other Jordan _ Michael Jordan the world's greatest
basketball player _ will be missed, should this second retirement
stick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sad day for the NBA and fans,'' Sonic guard and Chicago
native Hersey Hawkins said Tuesday. ``For the players who enjoyed
playing against him, we're going to miss that. He was the best
player in the NBA. He was the most recognized face in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, Hawkins was a bit skeptical that someone as
competitive, as driven, as on top of his game as Jordan could
really walk away from basketball right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's official yet,'' Hawkins said, as news of
today's planned retirement ceremony in Chicago was pulsing across
the country.
</P>
<P>
   The point is, no one can quite believe it, which is funny,
because along with the joy of Jordan during all his years _ from
North Carolina's 1982 NCAA title win over Georgetown to that sixth
NBA title over Utah last June _ he inflicted so much pain, denying
everyone but himself and his teammates the ultimate glory.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the love, along with the adoration, Michael Jordan
broke hearts everywhere he went.
</P>
<P>
   Be it at Madison Square Garden, where he owned the Knicks; or in
Cleveland, where he stalked and killed the helpless Cavaliers.
</P>
<P>
   He once rose like a phoenix in Phoenix, where Sir Charles' NBA
title dreams died.
</P>
<P>
   And, most recently, he stamped his everlasting superlative image
in Utah, where Karl Malone was the NBA's 1997 MVP out of pity's
sake and Jordan still crushed any shred of self-respect in the
Jazz, not once but two years in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Right in the middle of all this, Jordan showed Seattle how
deadly it was to ever doubt him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had not returned (to the NBA midway through the 1994-95
season),'' Hawkins said, ``we would have won (the 1996 NBA
Finals).''
</P>
<P>
   Just their luck, the 1995-96 Sonics had their franchise-best
season the first full season after Jordan returned from his first
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   He was there to deny them, 64-wins and all.
</P>
<P>
   He added a fadeaway jumper. He added more attitude, stoked
against the naysayers who said Jordan could not come back the way
he was when he gave Chicago its first three-peat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year he managed to get better when he was already at the
top of his game,'' Hawkins said, thinking back to '96 and the
Sonics' brush with greatness.
</P>
<P>
   ``To improve on that was a little astounding. And not only did
he get better physically, he got smarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``His basketball IQ got smarter, especially as he learned to
play with others. He learned he couldn't do it by himself, and he
needed everyone on his team to be part of that effort.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Bulls won Games 1 and 2 of the '96 Finals in Chicago
and then stretched their lead to 3-0 in a blowout at KeyArena,
something funny started to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, after the grueling 72-win season that secured the Bulls'
place in history, started to wilt. The year with gamblin' man
Dennis Rodman was wearing on him. So was the relentless effort to
get teammates like Toni Kukoc, Luc Longley, Derek Harper and even
Scottie Pippen to play like champions.
</P>
<P>
   And as the Bulls were being manhandled by the Sonics in Games 4
and 5, Jordan spent his five days in Seattle playing too much golf
_ as much as 36 holes at Broadmoor one day alone.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was desperate for the end of the season, but the Sonics
won two straight.
</P>
<P>
   Were the Bulls and Jordan finally stoppable?
</P>
<P>
   The answer would come, swiftly, in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   If Jordan's quest (under coach Phil Jackson's guidance) for the
Bulls to win 72 regular-season games had done anything, it ensured
that Jordan would be back home at the United Center for the finale.
</P>
<P>
   And, as Jordanesque karma would have it, Game 6 was played on
Father's Day _ a day for which Jordan had to hold onto every ounce
of self-control in order to persevere for the one thing that could
soothe him. His father, murdered in 1993, would be honored by the
actions of his son on this day.
</P>
<P>
   That evening, I sat in the United Center, four rows from
courtside. And on that night, Michael Jordan seemed merely mortal.
He looked not so much like Superman, but like an everyday man from
whom pain and loss had taken a toll.
</P>
<P>
   And on that night, Rodman's strength and rebounds were more than
necessary. Harper's defense was critical, if the Bulls were going
to win.
</P>
<P>
   Those two Bulls came through for their leader that night.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Sonics, they could only hang around, incapable of a
winning surge, understanding perhaps they were up against a force
of nature beyond their control.
</P>
<P>
   When the buzzer sounded, an exhausted Jordan collapsed on the
floor, weeping, only to get up, run into the Bulls locker room and
collapse again. He lay there on the floor so still, weeping so
silently, no one was sure he wasn't going to expire himself.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Michael Jordan that moment, before the TV camera was
shooed away and as he was left to mourn in peace, you understood
that this was awesome.
</P>
<P>
   You understood this most gifted basketball player was the only
one in the world who could summon every shred of his mind, body and
spirit and direct it toward one, singular, relentless, graceful,
uncompromised, mind-bending, jaw-dropping display of supernatural
achievement.
</P>
<P>
   He could beat you, beat your team, beat the odds, beat the
expectations, and still, you shook your head in joyful amazement.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the consummate professional,'' Hawkins said about what
he learned, what we all learned about Jordan that moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was going to stay the best in the game by any means
necessary,'' Hawkins said.
</P>
<P>
   And he was going to walk away that very same way.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 0100EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
