<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 01:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0643 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-SPI &LR;      01-13 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLS' LOSS IS NBA'S GAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ While the end of Michael Jordan's supernatural journey
might elicit a tear or two, don't expect any sympathy for the
Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's expected retirement today may not be good short-term
for the NBA, which is trying to improve its image after a long
labor battle. However, the path is clear for another organization
to stand tall in June.
</P>
<P>
   When Jordan has played a full season, no team other than the
Bulls has won the NBA championship in the '90s. As Cleveland
Cavaliers forward Shawn Kemp once said: ``I'm tired of watching
Michael and the Bulls celebrate championships on television.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The day he leaves is the day we all elevate our teams without
making one iota of a personnel move,'' Orlando Magic general
manager John Gabriel said. ``Many a team and fan have been
heartbroken by his last-minute heroics. They won't shed a tear for
him I'm sure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Please don't ask me to cry any tears for (Chicago general
manager) Jerry Krause. Even without Michael, they came out of the
lockout better than anybody,'' said one general manager. ``They're
not being held hostage by Michael's decision. They're in a great
position to re-sign all their guys from last year.''
</P>
<P>
   However, they have only four players under contract _ Ron
Harper, Toni Kukoc, Randy Brown and Keith Booth _ from last year's
championship team, with Harper the only starter.
</P>
<P>
   They have a league-high 10 free agents. The Bulls must decide if
they want to re-sign high-priced free agent Scottie Pippen and try
to build around him _ possibly with some of their other free agents
like Steve Kerr, Luc Longley, Jud Buechler and Scott Burrell _ or
rebuild from scratch. Regardless, they probably won't be favored to
win it all.
</P>
<P>
   What the league loses in Jordan's luster, it will make up in
competitive balance, said New Jersey's Rony Seikaly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's terrible for basketball, but it's a great chance for all
of the other teams,'' said Seikaly, whose Nets were eliminated from
last year's playoffs by Jordan and the Bulls. ``Right now, you can
pick a name out of a hat and that's the team that's going to
advance to the finals.''
</P>
<P>
   Indiana seems to be the team in place to take the reins in the
Eastern Conference. The Pacers, who pushed the Bulls to seven games
in the conference finals last year, have nine players signed. In
the West, Utah has 10 players under contract, including the same
nucleus that finished second to the Bulls each of the past two
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the league, you want to see him stay around. He has a
great following and has been a wonderful ambassador,'' said Utah
forward Adam Keefe. ``From a selfish respect, if he hadn't been
around, we would have won two championships.''
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Lakers, San Antonio, New York and Miami also
must be considered solid contenders.
</P>
<P>
   The league suddenly will go from praising His Airness to
appreciating parity.
</P>
<P>
   NBA commissioner David Stern kept bracing himself for this day,
saying throughout the lockout that Jordan's retirement ``is
inevitable.'' Albeit never a good time, Jordan's departure at this
juncture squeezes the league as it attempts to rebound from a
bitter labor dispute.
</P>
<P>
   So who or what can spark interest if the fans are still
apathetic?
</P>
<P>
   Several players have tried to anoint the ``next'' Jordan.
Detroit's Grant Hill was supposed to be the new prince. Most
recently, Lakers phenom Kobe Bryant has gotten the nod.
</P>
<P>
   But aside from his charisma and mass appeal, no one has yet to
approach Jordan's skill level. He departed the game unable to be
stopped or beaten. In a sense, Jordan left without passing the
torch.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could survive without him,'' Bulls free agent Bill
Wennington said. ``But it would really be a setback. People love to
watch him play. I love to watch him play.''
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg News Service and The Associated Press contributed to
this story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 0102EST &QL; 
