<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0644 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ERICKSON-SPI &LR;      01-13 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ERICKSON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW OSU COACH DENNIS ERICKSON GETS HERO'S WELCOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORVALLIS, Ore. _ A band played. Cheerleaders squealed. People
stood and applauded wildly. Dennis Erickson caused the commotion
when he emerged from a black, balloonlike helmet and formally
introduced himself as the Oregon State football coach.
</P>
<P>
   It was an entry better suited for a game-show host, and a far
cry from the NFL, but Erickson didn't seem to mind. He had a job
again after being unemployed for two weeks _ and for the first time
in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   After a fast-track courtship, the former Seahawks coach on
Tuesday took over the nation's losingest Division I program,
promising to stay awhile and make things happen on the field and
not off it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully I'm here for a long time,'' Erickson said in the
1{-year-old Valley Football Center. ``But that's a two-way street.
We have to win some games.''
</P>
<P>
   Wearing one of two national championship rings he earned at
Miami, Erickson was reluctant to spell out specific goals, other
than to take immediate aim at the Beavers' 27 consecutive losing
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But his players, many awed by a resum &UR; gfacute &LR; e that includes
four college stops and his Seahawks stint, figure an end to the
losing streak is a given. They're making postseason plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to a bowl game this year, a good bowl game,''
reserve running back Avery Cummings said.
</P>
<P>
   The inflated helmet seemed to dwarf Erickson as he made his way
to a roomful of reporters, boosters and players. Otherwise, it was
the coach who cast a huge shadow over the Pac-10's smallest
football program.
</P>
<P>
   Cummings, seated atop a red mountain bike as he headed to class,
rubbed sleep and stars from his eyes after a 7 a.m. team meeting to
acquaint him and teammates with Erickson.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I could think about was he's a celebrity,'' the junior
said. ``When I met him, I really wanted to ask him for his
autograph.''
</P>
<P>
   Erickson, 51, agreed to a five-year contract that will pay him
$300,000 per season, with a base of $150,000. For the first year,
as part of his Seahawks severance, he also will collect $1 million
from his former employers _ the difference between his NFL salary
and his current one.
</P>
<P>
   The Everett native becomes the Beavers' 27th coach, replacing
Mike Riley, who resigned last Thursday to become the San Diego
Chargers coach. Riley, in town for a few days to gather his
belongings, attended Tuesday's news conference but stayed in the
background.
</P>
<P>
   Erickson was hired almost within 36 hours after the job opened.
He called Oregon State athletic director Mitch Barnhart the night
of Riley's resignation to express interest. Barnhart, whose other
possibilities were Idaho's Chris Tormey, Colorado State's Sonny
Lubick and Kansas State offensive coordinator Ron Hudson, initially
was skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing you think is this can't work,'' the Beaver AD
said, alluding to fiscal restraints. ``I was surprised. I was
intrigued. I began to think of the possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Interviewing other candidates the next day, Barnhart tried to
fly back into Portland and was rerouted to Seattle because of fog.
Taking a chance, he called Erickson at home at 11:30 that night.
They agreed to meet the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   Barnhart said he was looking for a head coach with a West Coast
background. Erickson, shunning a couple of NFL assistant job
offers, decided he was better suited to becoming a college head
coach again.
</P>
<P>
   At Seattle's Roosevelt Hotel early Saturday, a deal was struck.
Erickson was now 1-for-2 with the Beavers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, Erickson, who was at Idaho, tried to move to Oregon
State when Joe Avezzano was fired. Then athletic director Dee
Andros gave him a vote of confidence. Then president John Byrne
chose the much more conservative Dave Kragthorpe, who was fired in
1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to wait 15 years to get him,'' Andros said of Erickson.
``I was overruled. But I think Denny has got the right idea now.
He'll get some kids in here who will help us. I don't know what we
could have done better.''
</P>
<P>
   People at Miami and Washington State might differ. In 1994, the
Florida school was stripped of 24 scholarships and banned from a
bowl for one season for a wide variety of NCAA offenses that
occurred on Erickson's watch. The second of his two teams in
Pullman had a cumulative 1.94 grade-point average.
</P>
<P>
   He had to answer to his past Tuesday, first to an athletic
advisory committee, then to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He addresssed that in our meeting,'' said Bob Foreman, Beaver
Club president. ``He said that was a long time ago and you win two
national titles (in Miami) and it turns into a carnival atmosphere.
He said everybody has skeletons in their closet. He's matured.''
</P>
<P>
   To media members, Erickson simply said he was never directly
implicated in any wrongdoing. Barnhart seemed satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no concern about that,'' said the Beaver official, who
spent 13 years as a Tennessee assistant AD. ``I know he's going to
get it done the right away. I feel very confident we will conduct
ourselves in the fashion that the institution wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Moving from an NFL head coaching job to a similar collegiate
post, Erickson joins a rare breed. Others in modern times who have
backtracked: George Allen (Long Beach State), Lou Holtz (Arkansas,
Minnesota, Notre Dame, South Carolina), John Mackovic (Illinois,
Texas), John Ralston (San Jose State), John Robinson (USC), Gene
Stallings (Alabama) and Bill Walsh (Stanford).
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had shown the slightest interest in the Washington
job, Erickson answered with a quip: ``I coached at Washington
State.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor did he take any shots at the Seahawks, who replaced him with
Mike Holmgren over the weekend: ``No hard feelings. They decided
they wanted to go another way. We inherited a 2-14 team and we got
it respectable. I wish them luck. That's history.''
</P>
<P>
   Erickson said he will bring Seahawk assistants Gregg Smith and
Eric Yaber to Corvallis, and possibly more. He also will interview
five holdover Beaver assistants.
</P>
<P>
   His arrival spurred a flurry of calls Tuesday to the OSU ticket
office. It is hoped that with instant success and beefed-up crowds,
a second deck at Parker Stadium can be built, enlarging capacity
from 37,000 to 55,000. But that's long-range dreaming.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Beavers need to break the losing-season streak;
then they might become Kansas State West, a longtime loser turned
winner. No question, Erickson has people excited.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he wanted us to get the respect of the nation and have
fun,'' sophomore offensive lineman Dustin Janz said. ``He said it's
going to happen. We're going to win here.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State?
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not?'' Erickson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
