<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0651 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-JORDAN-SUNS-REAX-     01-13 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JORDAN-SUNS-REAX-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OTHERS WILL MAKE HEADLINES, SUNS SAY  
 JORDAN'S TALENT, WILL TO WIN INSPIRED PLAYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Suns guard Rex Chapman picked up his newspaper Tuesday morning
and showed it to his 6-year-old son, Zeke, who is just learning to
read.
</P>
<P>
   The father asked his son to read the headline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jordan Returns?'' Zeke said, hopefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, try again,'' Zeke's dad said, patiently.
</P>
<P>
   Zeke looked over the black print again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jordan Retires,'' he said, his voice falling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one who really hates to see him go is my son. He was a
little upset about it,'' Chapman said.
</P>
<P>
   Zeke isn't alone.
</P>
<P>
   While it wasn't unexpected, the news that the Chicago Bulls
superstar will announce his retirement today shook a league already
on loose footing from a labor lockout that has left fans more
apathetic than angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't fool ourselves,'' Suns guard Jason Kidd said. ``There
is going to be an impact. First, the lockout hurt basketball, and
now this is going to be another black eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan leaves with six NBA championship rings, and he takes with
him much of the responsibility for the league's growth over the
past decade. He took the torch from Larry Bird and Magic Johnson
and carried the game to new levels of popularity and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will definitely be one of the big stories in basketball,''
Suns forward Danny Manning said. ``Who will the torch be passed to?
We don't know. Who can carry it like Michael has? No one.''
</P>
<P>
   But Manning said the league will go on and will prosper.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Kleine, who played last season with the Bulls, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will never be another guy like him,'' Kleine said. ``I
don't think there will be another Bird or Magic or Bill Russell or
(Kareem Abdul-) Jabbar. But there will be guys who carve their own
niche.''
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to imagine one who will have the impact Jordan
did, at least in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved playing against Michael because he's the best who has
ever played the game,'' said Suns Coach Danny Ainge, who twice
faced Jordan's Bulls in the NBA Finals. ``Having a chance just to
do that, to say you've played against the best ever, to say you
blocked his shot once _ from behind _ but the biggest thing of all
that I admire is that he came to play hard every night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had to live up to being Michael Jordan, and people can't
relate to how difficult that is. Every single night, knowing that
if he doesn't score 30 points or do something special, fans are
going to go away disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Night in and night out, he played at that level against the
best players in the world, knowing that everything they're doing
defensively is geared to stop him.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's talent was hard to match, but his competitiveness made
him legendary.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was with Washington, we had back-to-back games,
home-and-home against the Bulls,'' Chapman said. ``I wasn't
playing, but I was on the trip to Chicago and LaBradford Smith had
something like 38 points against Michael.
</P>
<P>
   ``They still beat us, and we went back to Washington for a game
the next night. I went in early to get treatment (for an injury)
and got there about 2{ hours early, and Michael was already there
shooting. You just had the feeling he was embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came out and scored 36 in the first three quarters and held
LaBradford to four or five points. It was real personal for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't have to do that. He didn't need to do that. He's the
best player in the world. But inside him, a fire burns that a lot
of people don't have, especially guys with his kind of talent. He
put on a show.''
</P>
<P>
   It's what Jordan always did best.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the greatest player because he could do it on both ends
of the floor,'' Ainge said. ``But he was also the most
entertaining, the most exciting player. He could do all that
acrobatic stuff, but he was also the toughest competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone has a favorite Jordan memory. He scored 63 in the
playoffs against Boston, when Ainge guarded him for much of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Kleine's is of Jordan's final 42 seconds: ``We're down three, he
scores on a drive to the basket, steals the ball from (Utah's Karl)
Malone, then hits the game-winning shot. That's as good as it
gets.''
</P>
<P>
   Kidd's is of his first game against Jordan: ``I remember the
first time I guarded him my rookie year (with Dallas). We switched
(defensively), and I was on him. He always likes to let you know
when you're a rookie. He said, `I got a young guy here.' I didn't
want him to do anything to get the crowd excited, so I conceded the
jump shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those things stick in your mind. I just remember somebody
yelled, `Switch.' You don't want to hear `Switch' when No. 23 is
coming across the lane.''
</P>
<P>
   Suns President Jerry Colangelo, who began his NBA career with
the Bulls, said there will be only one Jordan. But the game will go
on, and new stars will emerge, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say, `Who takes over?' '' Colangelo said. ``Nobody
takes over. People, things, situations evolve. We may not know who,
or what, or what circumstances, but somewhere in the world, there
is somebody dribbling a basketball who will no doubt have a
tremendous impact one day.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe his name is Zeke. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
