<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABORTION DOCTOR ARRESTED ON MANSLAUGHTER CHARGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSIE STECKNER  
 and JODIE SNYDER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The doctor and clinic administrator accused of
allowing a patient to bleed to death after an abortion have been
indicted and arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Biskind, a Cleveland gynecologist who regularly flew to
Phoenix to perform abortions at the A-Z Women's Center, and Carol
Stuart, were indicted on manslaughter charges Monday in the death
of Lou Anne Herron.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody can make mistakes. You don't hold people criminally
responsible for innocent mistakes,'' County Attorney Rick Romley
said at a news conference late Tuesday. ``The conduct by Dr.
Biskind is so outrageous, it shocks the conscience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our opinion that Lou Anne Herron did not have to die.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Stuart, Romley said the administrator was more concerned
with the interest of the clinic than with Herron's medical care.
</P>
<P>
   Biskind was arrested Tuesday afternoon at his winter home in
Scottsdale; Stuart also was arrested Tuesday in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   An investigation is still pending into a near-abortion at the
clinic in which Biskind attempted to abort a fetus that was 37
weeks old. Biskind later said he believed the fetus was no more
than 24 weeks, but when the abortion proved too difficult he ended
up delivering a full-term baby girl.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart also was at the clinic the day of the near-abortion.
</P>
<P>
   In the Herron case, employees have described for police a scene
of medical chaos at the clinic: inexperienced staff members, a
doctor too busy eating lunch to check on his patient, an
administrator who sought help from a medical assistant 20 minutes
away instead of calling 911 or taking Herron to the hospital across
the street.
</P>
<P>
   Romley also said he will expand the criminal investigations to
include the clinic's owner, Moshe Hachamovitch, a New York abortion
doctor whose other clinics in Texas and New York have had their
share of problems.
</P>
<P>
   The death of a 19-year-old patient at one clinic in New York
prompted state medical officials to revoke Hachamovitch's license
for a month, although the doctor is fighting that action and still
practicing medicine.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, state health officials went to court to shut down one
of his clinics after finding conditions so unsanitary that patient
care was endangered. That state investigation came on the heels of
the death of a 15-year-old patient.
</P>
<P>
   Hachamovitch was not at the Phoenix clinic, near 10th Street and
McDowell Road, during either of the incidents. But according to a
Phoenix police investigation by Detective Mark Stribling,
Hachamovitch may have known about Herron prior to her abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Employees told police that, based on ultrasound results, they
believed Herron was too far along in her pregnancy for a legal
abortion. But when they challenged Stuart, they were told by her
that Herron was a private patient of Hachamovitch's.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, nurse Victoria Kimball, who quit A-Z after Herron's
death and who went public with her concerns, said she was ``happy
that justice was being served.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of thing should not have happened,'' she said.
``They need to take away the perpetrators of this. Sometimes
justice doesn't always work, but I am glad that it did in this
case.''
</P>
<P>
   Biskind's attorney declined to comment Tuesday night; Stuart's
attorney could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Romley said Biskind and Stuart are facing manslaughter charges,
rather than the lesser charge of criminal negligence, because the
case meets the standard of showing ``reckless disregard for life.''
</P>
<P>
   The penalties for manslaughter range from probation to 12 years
in prison. Bond has been set for each at $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   Problems began at A-Z in April, when Herron, 33, a mother of
two, sought a late-term abortion.
</P>
<P>
   She made several visits to the McDowell Road clinic and the
affiliated clinic in Glendale for ultrasounds. Employees told
police that the results ranged from 26 weeks to 24 weeks and two
days. They said that Biskind chose one of the ultrasounds and that
the abortion was later performed.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately after the procedure, employees said, Herron
began to have complications and was bleeding heavily. For the next
three hours, she complained about being in pain, worried that her
legs were numb and cried out for help.
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't a registered nurse on duty, and inexperienced
employees said they could not help her. They said they pleaded with
Stuart to call 911. Instead, Stuart called in a medical assistant
at an affiliated office in Scottsdale and then paged Biskind for
guidance.
</P>
<P>
   Biskind, who already had left the clinic, reportedly told an
employee over the phone, ``Well what do you want me to do? Call
911,'' according to the Phoenix police report.
</P>
<P>
   Then in June, the clinic had more troubles with the
near-abortion of a full-term baby. The baby suffered
non-life-threatening injuries and later was adopted.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Hachamovitch was evicted from the McDowell Road office
complex. He later was forced to close the west Phoenix and
Scottsdale clinics because he said no doctors would work for him.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Biskind gave up his Arizona medical license, avoiding
a state medical board probe into Herron's death. A month later, he
surrendered his medical license in his home state of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart, meanwhile, left A-Z when it closed and took a job as a
youth counselor.
</P>
<P>
   Herron's family is expected to file a lawsuit naming
Hachamovitch, Biskind and Stuart.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Board of Medical Examiners, meanwhile, is
investigating two complaints against Hachamovitch of improper
and/or inadequate supervision or collaboration.
</P>
<P>
   Biskind had come to the attention of the Arizona Board of
Medical Examiners several times for various complaints. The most
severe discipline was a censure in 1996 for gross negligence after
the death of another patient, Lisa Bardsley. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
