<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-GYMNASTICS-PHELPS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIAN RETURNS TO GYM OF HER YOUTH  
 NOW GYMNAST IS A TEACHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jaycie Phelps is living in Tempe and spending most every day at
Desert Devils Gymnastics in Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   Just like she did when she was 12.
</P>
<P>
   But at 19, Phelps owns a house 10 minutes from Arizona State,
where she will begin college in the fall. She is coaching the
Desert Devils elites, whereas seven years ago she was the youngest
of an astounding 1992 team that produced collegiate All-Americans
Sandy Woolsey, Elizabeth Crandall, Kim Arnold and Tiffany Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   She is even an investor in SportsTech International, now the
parent company of Desert Devils, which is moving forward with plans
for an elite multisport training complex in north Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   She's also been involved in a yearlong romance with Mesa's Jason
Gatson, who in 1997 at age 17 became the youngest American male
gymnast to compete at a World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   So while the geography is the same for Phelps, life is vastly
different.
</P>
<P>
   She is an adult, counseling 1996 Olympic teammate Dominique
Moceanu through the ugly separation from her father and in the
process gaining an increased appreciation for how her parents
handled the abnormalities inherent with elite athletic training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to help as much as I can,'' said Phelps, who next to
Moceanu was the youngest of the Magnificent Seven that won the
Olympic women's team gold medal in Atlanta. ``She's really confused
about everything in life right now. She doesn't know if she wants
to do gymnastics. She wants to, but then again, she wants to be a
normal kid.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are obviously some things I missed in high school, like
homecoming, but it doesn't bother me because I've gotten to do so
much more. My parents have been supportive of my decisions and
didn't get upset if I made a mistake in competition. Everything
looked good to them. I've definitely had a great life up to this
point.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Reese's Gymnastics Cup on Saturday at Wells Fargo Arena
proves to be Phelps' farewell to competitive gymnastics, she is
ready to move on and able to say: ``I accomplished more than I set
out to do.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Phelps moved from Indiana to Arizona with her mother,
Cheryl, to train at Desert Devils under the late Stormy Eaton. But
Jaycie missed her father, Jack, and others in the family and
returned to the Midwest to train for the Olympics under Mary Lee
Tracy at the Cincinnati Gymnastics Academy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I lived out there before, I loved it and said I would end
up out here anyway,'' Phelps said.
</P>
<P>
   Having remained friends with Eaton's son, Geoff, who became
owner-head coach at Desert Devils after his father died in 1995,
Phelps called last year to say she planned to enroll at ASU.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her, `You'd better be working for me,' '' Eaton said.
Phelps quickly agreed, even delaying classes to concentrate on a
job she ``wasn't sure I'd like as much as I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Phelps is coaching not only the half-dozen Desert Devils
elite/level 10 gymnasts, including Chelsea Otto, who was 24th in
juniors at the 1998 U.S. Championships, but also teaming with
Eaton's wife, Shelly, to motivate a group of level 4s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone can coach a great athlete,'' Eaton said. ``The real
coaching is at the lower levels. I wanted to put Jaycie on a young
group of kids, and she rose to the occasion. She immediately turned
their whole view of gymnastics, brightened their spirits and got
them going.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a gold medalist, someone who's reached the
cream of the crop, maintain the same disposition like Jaycie. You
wouldn't know she's ever done anything. She has a crystal-clear
personality and view of life. She's going to be a brilliant coach.
We're thrilled to have her, and she's got a place here as long as
she wants it.''
</P>
<P>
   Phelps' competitive career has been on hold since December 1997,
when she had surgery to replaced the meniscus in her left knee. It
was in '97 that she met and exchanged Internet addresses with
Gatson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been dating for over a year, so I guess you can say
we're an item,'' said Phelps of a relationship that was the subject
of a ``Parade'' magazine Q&AMP;A last month.
</P>
<P>
   Gatson, also entered in the Reese's Cup, lives at the U.S.
Olympic Training Center in Colorado Springs, so the two see each
other once a month and at holidays.
</P>
<P>
   The all-around silver medalist and floor exercise/high bar
champion at the 1998 U.S. Championships, Gatson seemingly is a lock
for the 2000 Olympics. Phelps can relate to the pressure he faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives us more to talk about,'' Phelps said. ``He's
seriously training and I'm not really, so I can help him to relax a
little.''
</P>
<P>
   Phelps has been cleared by her doctor to ``do whatever I can''
and plans to compete on uneven parallel bars and balance beam with
watered-down dismounts Saturday. She is paired with 16-year-old
Vanessa Atler, the 1998 Goodwill Games gold medalist on vault and
floor exercise and '97 co-national all-around champion.
</P>
<P>
   Her Magnificent Seven teammates Amanda Borden, an ASU student
and manager of the Sun Devils team, and Amy Chow also are in the
field. Moceanu and Shannon Miller are appearing to sign
autographs. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
