<HEADLINE>
TKACHUK VOWS TO RETURN NEXT WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB McMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Captain Coyote is almost ready to return to the lineup. Left
wing Keith Tkachuk, sidelined since Dec. 28 because of a fractured
rib, said he expects to play next week when the Coyotes host the
St. Louis Blues.
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk, injured when he was cross checked from behind by
Mattias Norstrom of the Los Angeles Kings, will miss three more
games, including tonight's match-up with the Pittsburgh Penguins,
and games Friday at Nashville and Sunday at Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Without Tkachuk, Phoenix is 3-6-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm almost there,'' said Tkachuk, who practiced for the third
consecutive day Tuesday, when he was selected to participate in his
third consecutive All-Star Game. ``I'm still a little sore, but
that's to be expected. The bottom line is, I'm playing Tuesday.
That's my target date, and I don't plan on missing it.'' &QL;  &QL; 
Jagr-meister &QL;  &QL; 
Center Jeremy Roenick, who will join Tkachuk as a reserve for the
North American All-Star squad, said the Coyotes will have their
work cut out tonight against the Penguins and perennial All-Star
Jaromir Jagr.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best one-on-on player in the game in terms of
strength and puck handling,'' Roenick said of Jagr, who ranks third
in the league in scoring with 50 points. ``We have to make sure we
don't let him hold the puck too long or let him get into the open,
because he's the kind of guy who can kill you.'' &QL;  &QL; 
Waiting for 400 &QL;  &QL; 
With just three goals in his past 15 games, veteran Rick Tocchet
remains three goals shy of the 400-goal milestone for his career.
The wait, he admits, has been bothersome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been thinking about it lately, but before I was,''
said Tocchet, third on the team with 12 goals. ``The last 10 games,
I just haven't been getting the chances I was earlier, and I'm
starting to get frustrated. It's not like I'm not going to the net
or anything. The puck's just not bouncing my way. But it's going to
come.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always prided myself on being a consistent scorer, not
going into too many prolonged slumps. So hopefully I can get over
this and start bagging some.'' &QL;  &QL; 
No O in Oleg &QL;  &QL; 
After scoring four goals and five points in his first seven games,
defenseman Oleg Tverdovsky has managed just one goal and seven
assists in his past 30 games. Part of the problem has been the
Coyotes' recent woes on the power play (0 for 32). Another reason
is the team's tight defensive system once they get a lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the players have to fit the system, the system can't fit
the player,'' Tverdovsky said. ``It's working. But individually, it
can't always be great for everybody.'' &QL;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
