<HEADER>
A0656 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-ASU-EVANS-OLSON-A     01-13 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ASU-EVANS-OLSON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVANS, OLSON SHARE HISTORY OF ADMIRATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Thursday, Arizona State's Rob Evans will coach a basketball
team for the first time against a Lute Olson squad when the Sun
Devils play host to Arizona. But Evans and Olson are
well-acquainted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lute and I have gone back a long way,'' Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, Evans said, Olson tried to hire him.
</P>
<P>
   Olson was head coach at Iowa, which had just gone to the Final
Four. Evans was an assistant coach at Texas Tech. Evans said Olson
offered him a job as an assistant.
</P>
<P>
   After thinking it over for no more than 15 or 20 minutes, Evans
said no, thank you. He reasoned that his wife, Carolyn (who was
working toward a degree), and their children, Damon and Amber, were
better off staying in Lubbock, Texas, instead of moving to Iowa
City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just decided that was the best place for my family,'' he
said. ``My family's the most important thing to me, and my kids
were doing tremendous in school, my wife was doing well in the
community and in school.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was more to it than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like at that particular point, I was needed more at
Texas Tech,'' Evans said. ``Texas Tech was struggling, trying to
get national recognition. And I felt like with my recruiting
ability in that area, especially being from New Mexico, I was
needed more there.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans said Iowa assistant Ken Burmeister ``told me I was nuts''
for turning down the offer, because it would have led to a head
coaching job more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I felt I was going to get a head coaching job if I
deserved it, regardless of where I was,'' Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   Olson's memory was a little fuzzy about offering Evans a job at
Iowa, but he did recall talking to Evans in 1988 when Olson was at
Arizona. Again, he had just been to the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is, we had been in contact to try to get him
hired,'' Olson said. ``He's always done a good job and he's always
done it in a first-class way.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans had been at Texas Tech for five years when he turned down
the Iowa offer, 13 when Olson again asked. He had become in great
demand _ as an assistant. But that wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was getting a lot of overtures,'' he said. ``I wasn't
interested in becoming an assistant coach. I had that job. I was
interested in becoming a head coach.''
</P>
<P>
   It finally happened in 1992 when Evans was hired at Mississippi,
but only after he didn't get the Texas Tech job and went to
Oklahoma State to work as Eddie Sutton's assistant for two years.
</P>
<P>
   There is another link between Evans and Olson, a more recent
one. Wildcats forward Michael Wright is probably making the
greatest impact of any freshman in the Pac-10, leading them all in
scoring and rebounding.
</P>
<P>
   But before he started playing for Olson, Wright played for
Evans.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, the 6-foot-7, 235-pound Wright was the most
valuable player on the USA Basketball Men's Junior World
Championship qualifying team that won the gold medal in the
Dominican Republic. Jim Boeheim of Syracuse was head coach. Evans
was an assistant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael's a tough kid,'' Evans said. ``He's really a tough
kid. A very, very hard-working kid. Strong. He was probably the
best player we had, and we had some good ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all the high school kids on the team, Wright was the most
serious-minded, Evans said. ``He's a very mature freshman.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans described Wright as quiet and introspective, but the two
developed a strong relationship. It started when Wright, who is
from Chicago, asked Evans about Auvee Story, a transfer from
Illinois also from Chicago now enrolled at ASU and sitting out the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got along pretty well,'' Wright said. ``I'm kind of quiet,
and he tried to get stuff out of me.''
</P>
<P>
   A left-hander, Wright said Evans got him to work on using his
right hand, developing the 15-foot jump shot and defense. Olson
stresses the same things and, like Evans, marvels at his attitude
and work ethic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael Wright,'' said Olson, ``wants to be the best player he
can possibly be.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob Evans already knew that. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 0121EST &QL; 
