r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDINAL-S-NOTES-     01-13 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINAL-S-NOTES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
5 RESERVES AVAILABLE TO BROWNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last time the NFL had an expansion draft, then-Cardinals
Coach Buddy Ryan left players in his doghouse on the unprotected
list.
</P>
<P>
   He made starting quarterback Steve Beuerlein available, and
Jacksonville chose him with the first pick in the 1995 expansion
draft.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan also planned to leave wide receiver Ricky Proehl
unprotected but then removed him at the last second when he
realized Proehl had trade value. Proehl was sent to the Seattle
Seahawks for a 1995 fourth-round draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals aren't giving away any starters to Cleveland in
this year's expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   The team announced Tuesday that it didn't protect defensive
tackle Jerry Drake, linebacker Terry Irving, wide receiver Fred
Brock, cornerback J.B. Brown and tight end Jarius Hayes.
</P>
<P>
   Each team was required to submit their unprotected list to
Cleveland by Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Only Brown and Drake started any games this season. Brown had
six starts in place of injured Tom Knight at right cornerback.
Drake started the season opener at Dallas in place of Andre
Wadsworth but suffered a back injury and was placed on the injured
reserve list.
</P>
<P>
   If the Browns take any of the players in the Feb. 9 draft, the
Cardinals can pull another player off the list. They cannot lose
more than two players. &QL; 
Medical update &QL; 
Starting outside linebacker Jamir Miller is expected to see Dr.
Robert Wilson, a hand and wrist specialist in Phoenix, later this
week to see whether he needs off-season surgery on his dislocated
left wrist.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals medical personnel are hopeful that kicker Joe Nedney,
recovering from a torn anterior cruciate ligament in his left
(kicking) leg, will be ready for the start of training camp in
July.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle Eric Swann, also recovering from knee surgery,
will remain on crutches for at least another month. &QL; 
Attention-getter &QL;  &QL; 
With nine games against eight playoff teams next season, Cardinals
Coach Vince Tobin knows his team will be playing one of the NFL's
tougher schedules.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals play San Francisco, Green Bay, Buffalo, New
England, the New York Jets, Atlanta, Miami and Dallas twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would prefer to play the teams you can beat the easiest,''
he said. ``But one thing this schedule does is get the attention of
the players in the off-season. They enjoyed making the playoffs and
getting to the `Final Eight' and want to do it again. So, they know
the have to come in prepared and ready.'' &QL;  &QL; 
Prime time &QL;  &QL; 
An ABC TV official said Tuesday that the network hopes to televise
the Cardinals' home game against the 49ers on Monday Night Football
next season.
</P>
<P>
   The network official said it would be ``great to have a
quarterback who's been compared to Joe Montana (Jake Plummer)
against Montana's (old) team.'' &QL;  &QL; 
Best wishes &QL;  &QL; 
Return specialist Eric Metcalf, also the team's No. 3 receiver,
likely has played his last game with the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   His contract is up next month, and he struggled on kick and punt
returns for most of the season. The Cardinals were 22nd in the
league in kick returns and 29th in punt returns in the regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   Metcalf had his best punt return in last Sunday's NFC playoff
loss at Minnesota, a 36-yarder that set up a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our return game needs to be improved,'' Tobin said. &QL;  &QL; 
Endorsement &QL;  &QL; 
Miller said he thinks the Chicago Bears should give defensive
coordinator Dave McGinnis strong consideration for their head
coaching position.
</P>
<P>
   McGinnis is scheduled to interview today or Thursday in Phoenix
with Bears Vice President Mark Hatley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd hate to see him go, but if he does, it would make the
Bears a better team,'' Miller said. ``I always wish good luck for
someone who can improve their situation.'' &QL;  &QL; 
Moonlighting &QL;  &QL; 
Rookie cornerback Corey Chavous has been hired to co-host an NFL
draft show with Dallas radio personality Norm Hitzges.
</P>
<P>
   Chavous, who has a film library of 400 tapes, hopes to have a
career in broadcasting when he's finished in the NFL. &QL;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 0122EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
