<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0658 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES_ALL-STARS     01-13 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES_ALL-STARS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TKACHUK, ROENICK NAMED ALL-STARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today, they are the Fabulous Five.
</P>
<P>
   But hit the rewind button and review your memory banks about
Keith Tkachuk, Jeremy Roenick, Teppo Numminen, Nikolai Khabibulin
and Coach Jim Schoenfeld, the five men who will represent the
Coyotes at this month's NHL All-Star Game in Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   One of them (Tkachuk) was labeled as a greedy money-grubber who
dominated the sports pages last summer with his second
controversial holdout in two years.
</P>
<P>
   Another (Roenick) recently acknowledged that all he used to care
about was making money, looking good and playing well individually
without a care about how his team made out.
</P>
<P>
   One of them (Numminen) made so many headlines about being the
most underrated defenseman in the league, it made his hard-luck
story start to sound like overkill.
</P>
<P>
   Another (Khabibulin) is a nice enough fellow, but a strangely
silent star who has yet to melt the media, the same guy who said,
when asked three years ago if he knew what a real coyote was, said,
``It is big cat with claws, duh?''
</P>
<P>
   And then there is their boss (Schoenfeld), a coach who nearly
lost his job a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Fab Five or the Misfits? Call them what you want, but they're
all headed toward hockey heaven on Jan. 24, when they will
participate in the 49th annual midseason classic at the Ice Palace
in Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   ``After everything we've went through in the past year, this
just makes it all that much better,'' Coyotes veteran Rick Tocchet
said. ``I can't tell you how happy I am for all the guys. They all
deserve it. It's a great reward for our team, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk and Roenick on Tuesday were named as reserves for the
North American All-Star squad. A day earlier, Numminen and
Khabibulin were named to the World All-Star team. Schoenfeld,
meanwhile, will serve as an assistant coach for the North American
team, a selection based on the Coyotes' winning percentage a few
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The four player selections are the most ever in the
organization's 20-year history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an honor. It's a privilege to play in,'' said Tkachuk,
who will be making his third straight All-Star trip despite
presently being sidelined because of a cracked rib. ``It's
definitely something me and my family are going to enjoy once we
get there. I'm looking forward to playing with a bunch of players
you never really get to play with _ or play against.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Numminen and Khabibulin, who for once, will be on opposite
sides of the ice from Tkachuk and Roenick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, Keith's been joking around lately, saying he's going to
take a run at me,'' Numminen said, adding his own snappy comeback
by saying, ``I'm going to play it tough on him and try and move his
big butt out from the front of our net if he parks it there.''
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk couldn't resist adding a friendly shot in return.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason Teppo's there,'' he said, ``is because he's
one of the commissioner's special picks.''
</P>
<P>
   All kidding aside, the selections are a direct result of the
Coyotes' impressive 22-10-5 record, which represents their best
start in franchise history. A big part of that has been a
rededication to the game and the team by players such as Tkachuk
and Roenick and others, who claim all that matters now in their
careers is winning the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a while for me, but I'm excited, I'm going to soak
it up and it's something I had to work really hard for,'' said
Roenick, who leads the Coyotes in scoring with 40 points and will
be making his fifth All-Star appearance _ his first in five years.
``It wasn't one of my goals, though. My goals were very limited
this year. I just wanted to be the best player I can be and help my
team win the Stanley Cup, that's it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I feel very fortunate. If I knew who to thank, I'd thank
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The soft-spoken Khabibulin, coming off a 1-0 shutout over
Buffalo and fellow All-Star Dominik Hasek on Monday, sounded more
like Charles Barkley than himself when asked for his reaction to
making his second straight All-Star appearance. Khabibulin said
after a long pause:
</P>
<P>
   ``Well . . . I think I deserve it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 0123EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
