<HEADER>
A0660 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BICKLEY_JORDAN-AZ     01-13 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BICKLEY_JORDAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAIRY TALE ENDS HAPPILY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The end comes just like it should. As a fairy tale. A jump shot
that wins a championship. A hero smart enough to understand that
timing can be his friend, and time can be his enemy.
</P>
<P>
   And this time, Michael Jordan is not coming back. The greatest
basketball player ever to lace up his shoes, the second-most
influential athlete in world history, is done.
</P>
<P>
   Take a moment to understand the implications, the magnitude of
his career. How your grandchildren will ask about Jordan. If you're
lucky, at some point, you set the VCR and labeled the tape.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a superstar gets it right. For the first time since Jim
Brown, one who doesn't push the envelope of greatness until it is
stained with tragedy. Remember: A bloated Babe Ruth flailing away.
Muhammad Ali _ the only athlete whose impact exceeded Jordan's _
getting pummeled by Larry Holmes. Willie Mays thrown out at home
plate in a Mets jersey, looking gray and weary. Jesse Owens turned
circus freak, racing horses to make a buck. Pete Rose, manager,
penciling himself in the lineup until his career average threatens
to dip below .300. Joe Montana, in a Chiefs jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan deserves this. Not for all the clutch shots that almost
became cliche. Not for the highlight films. Not even for the six
championships when his mental will was simply impenetrable, when
even Pat Riley admitted that no other team would win a title until
Jordan retired.
</P>
<P>
   He deserves this because, for all the fame and money, he
remained remarkably grounded. The fame and money that turned
Michael Jackson into God knows what, that made Prince change his
name to a symbol, the kind that will chew up all sensibility and
leave behind nothing but ego.
</P>
<P>
   With Jordan, it never happened. He never forgot to work. To get
better. To practice as hard as he played. To never make excuses.
His priority started with winning, ended with winning, and
everything in between was a means to that end.
</P>
<P>
   He could be mean-spirited to his teammates. He once gave Steve
Kerr a black eye in practice. He once threw the ball at Luc
Longley's head. He once told his teammates not to pass to Bill
Cartwright.
</P>
<P>
   Until you met his intensity, until you understood the sacrifice
to win, he could be downright cruel.
</P>
<P>
   And while he would remind everybody that he was king of the
court, he never acted like he was a better person than you. That is
the greatest tribute to Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   His intimacy with media broke down after his father died, amid
rampant speculation that his penchant for gambling somehow
precipitated a senseless killing. It eroded a bit when national
magazines made fun of his attempt to play baseball, only the
bravest thing he's ever done. And it was never the same when he
came back, when the Bulls became bigger than life, when the media
horde became too much to handle on an individual basis.
</P>
<P>
   But Jordan was always forthright and honest, always shared
himself, treating every question with dignity. Much of this was due
to his image, the one he kept squeaky clean for corporate purposes.
But most of it was real.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Brooklyn, raised in North Carolina. A kid who
shied away from girls, afraid they'd make fun of his big ears. A
kid cut from his high school basketball team, who, no matter how
far he traveled, always hung on to his roots.
</P>
<P>
   One day, during his attempt to play baseball, a Japanese
reporter asked Jordan about the game of . Jordan could've rolled
his eyes, laughed, disregarded the strange query. Instead, he broke
into a 45-second answer, expounding on the virtues of two paddles
and a little plastic ball.
</P>
<P>
   Other memories:
</P>
<P>
   The day he slapped me in the back of the head for no reason, so
hard that I saw stars. The day he dragged me off the practice court
in a headlock, just for fun. The night in a bar when I introduced
Jordan to my wife and she almost fainted. The moments when he came
to bat for the Chicago White Sox, when a baseball stadium would go
completely silent.
</P>
<P>
   He loved talking trash. He loved throwing barbs around the
locker room, to see who would engage in a war of insults. And, of
course, he loved challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan also loves playing the martyr. When he walked
away from baseball, he said it was because of a labor impasse,
because the White Sox wanted him to side with management.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, Jordan would never have been successful in baseball.
Good maybe, but not great. That much was clear, and the labor
skirmish was a perfect out.
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forward to 1998, and Jordan is in a similar situation. A
league full of copycats and imitators, young players who bought
into the dunks and the flash but never understood that Jordan was
really about winning. A league full of rich kids who are bathing in
money because of Jordan, rich kids who have ridden his coattails
and haven't proved a damn thing. A league where the commissioner,
upon announcing the end of the lockout, begged Jordan to return.
</P>
<P>
   If he came back, he would've been the bridge to recovery. He
wouldn't have made all the animosity go away, but he would've been
the perfect salve for all the wounds. And, come now, why would he
want to help the owners like that? Especially the owner and general
manager in Chicago, an owner he's grown to loathe and a general
manager he's always despised.
</P>
<P>
   It's always been this way. Fight Jordan and he leaves you
bloody.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan is also shrewd enough to know that he is out of shape.
That he turned his private, indoor basketball court into a cigar
bar. That the Indiana Pacers have been practicing six days a week
during the lockout. That his career can't end like so many others.
</P>
<P>
   So, in the end, he went from burning Bryon Russell to smoking
Cuban cigars. Smart enough to turn his career into a fairy tale.
With the ending intact. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at dan.bickley(at)pni.com. via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
