r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HACKER-SENTENCED-LADN     01-13 0307
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HACKER-SENTENCED-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER HACKER GETS FIVE-MONTH JAIL TERM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PETER HARTLAUB  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- A federal judge sentenced computer hacker Justin
Petersen on Tuesday to five months in jail, saying the former FBI
informant was ``sticking his thumb at the system'' during his
latest run from the law.
</P>
<P>
   Petersen was a fugitive from Sept. 30 until Dec. 11, when U.S.
marshals arrested him in a suburban Studio City apartment. The
38-year-old already has served 35 months in prison for hacking into
a bank to get $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   While U.S. District Judge Stephen Wilson didn't hand down the
two-year sentence that he could have, he compared Petersen to a
drug addict who refuses to be helped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're going to teach him a lesson . . . there's
nothing at this point, absent a miracle, that would bring him back,
in my view.''
</P>
<P>
   The self-proclaimed playboy hacker's Web site is filled with
pictures of him accompanied by beautiful women at Sunset Strip
nightclubs.
</P>
<P>
   Petersen admitted to Wilson that he fled after violating the
terms of his supervised release from prison, which required that he
get a steady job and pay about $40,000 to his victims.
</P>
<P>
   He disappeared in September, after a hearing at which Wilson
ordered him to go to a halfway house and possibly seek
psychological counseling.
</P>
<P>
   Petersen's lawyer, Nathan Hochman, pointed out that his client
was ``a few keystrokes away from committing a crime'' after his
1997 release, but chose not to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Hochman said Petersen was beaten the last time he was in prison
because of his role as an FBI informant.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lives in fear of physical attack,'' the attorney said. ``If
he goes back to this Texas facility, he goes as a marked man.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
