<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 01:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0662 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-EXPANSION     01-13 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-EXPANSION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `MOOSE' IS LOOSE FOR EXPANSION DRAFT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Fullback Daryl Johnston battled back from a
severe neck injury to start 16 games for the Cowboys this season.
Now, he faces the possibility that his career with the Cowboys
might be finished.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston, 32, joined receiver Billy Davis as the only starters
the Cowboys will expose to the league's veteran player draft for
the expansion Cleveland Browns.
</P>
<P>
   Also left unprotected for the Feb. 9 draft were defensive
linemen Antonio Anderson and Hurvin McCormack and center Clay
Shiver. The Browns can draft no more than two players from any
team, so there is a chance all five could remain with the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys owner Jerry Jones wouldn't go into any specifics about
his decisions but said the process was difficult.
</P>
<P>
   The most difficult decision might have been regarding Johnston,
a 10-year veteran and one of the team's most popular players. But
Johnston's agent, Leigh Steinberg, indicated that the Cowboys
thought Johnston's $1.65 million salary for next season was too
high.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg said the Cowboys put Johnston on the expansion list
after trying to find a way to reduce his salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially, it was made clear that it was an economic
issue,'' Steinberg said. ``Daryl was sort of given a choice: cut
his salary dramatically or put him on the list.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made it clear that they value Daryl, just not at those
economics.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones did not say if the decision was made in an attempt to
reduce Johnston's salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We considered a lot of things _ cap impact, salary impact,
where they are in their career, the entire gamut went into it,''
Jones said. ``Our strategy was to expose players in the best
interest of the team, and it was convoluted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No one appreciates what D.J. is about on and off the field
\Rmore than we do\S,'' Jones said. ``It goes without saying what
kind of player we think Daryl is, and he enjoyed a very productive
year. I reiterate it was a very difficult decision. I visited with
him a couple of times. I know he understands the things we took
into consideration, whether he agrees or not.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have 43 players already under contract for 1999 at a
cap impact of roughly $61 million. The cap is expected to be $57.5
million. If taken by the Browns, Johnston's entire salary would
move to the Browns' cap.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg said Johnston, who had neck surgery during the 1997
season, is not bitter and still wants to finish his career with the
Cowboys. Steinberg said Johnston feels he has a lot of good
football left and would report to the Browns if selected.
</P>
<P>
   The decision on Davis is considered to be based on money and
production. Davis, who is expected to count $1.1 million against
the cap next season, caught 39 passes for 691 yards and three
touchdowns in his first season as a starter. However, he tailed off
at the end of the season and is not expected to retain his starting
job.
</P>
<P>
   His salary is thought to be too high for a backup receiver and
special teams player _ though the Browns could come to the same
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   McCormack is the only other salary concern on the list, as the
Cowboys could save $750,000 if the backup defensive tackle is
selected.
</P>
<P>
   Shiver, a restricted free agent who could earn roughly $500,000
next season if the Cowboys re-sign him, lost his starting job to
Mike Kiselak and is not considered part of the Cowboys' future.
Anderson dropped on the depth chart after suffering a knee injury
midway through the season and finished as a third-string player at
end and tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Notable for not being on the list is cornerback Kevin Smith, who
lost his starting job to Kevin Mathis and counts $3.3 million
against the cap next season. Smith's presence and salary for next
season could be justified because Mathis is earning the minimum and
still is unproven. It is also reasonable to want three experienced
cornerbacks on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   However, Jones acknowledged players were not exposed at certain
positions because the Cowboys didn't want to reveal what their
off-season plans were for
</P>
<P>
   free agency or the draft.
</P>
<P>
   He also added that not being on the list doesn't guarantee a
player a roster spot for next season. Middle linebacker Fred
Strickland, set to make $1.1 million next year, could be released.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
