<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BECK-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDAN LEAVES NOTHING BUT NET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   History, and a well-worn videotape, will show Michael Jordan's
last NBA shot was good. Maybe even perfect. History offers that
indelible final image of an unparalleled career.
</P>
<P>
   History lies. Shut off the VCR.
</P>
<P>
   That Michael Jordan is one of the greatest players, if not
!ital!the greatest player ever, is indisputable. That he won six
titles in six full seasons, and five legue MVP trophies are simple,
impressive facts.
</P>
<P>
   And that he won the last game of his career with a
picture-perfect jumper to clinch championship No. 6 is a matter of
record.
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Jordan doesn't leave the NBA on that shot.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves now _ not in June but in January. Not clutching the
Larry O'Brien trophy, but letting the last great challenge of his
career slip away _ the chance to rescue the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   While Jordan vacationed and golfed and chewed Cuban cigars these
past few months, the league that made him an immensely wealthy
global icon was busy destroying itself. A six-month labor war has
left the NBA's image in tatters, its relationship with fans
strained. Owners are greedy, players are greedy. Players choke
coaches, skip practices and insult fans.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA needs a savior, a superhero _ and the only man who fits
the description is hanging up his cape.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan is taking his last shot today, and it's big, fat
airball.
</P>
<P>
   Even his peers recognize it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sad thing,'' said the Lakers' Eddie Jones, ``because
especially what basketball is at this point right now, Michael
Jordan is desperately needed. It's a shame that everything went
down (with the lockout). We lose so many fans and Mike could bring
all of the fans back, and he's not with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Interesting that Jordan, a superstar who was willing to give
Steve Kerr the game-winning shot in 1997, is so selfish off the
court.
</P>
<P>
   Many will argue to the contrary, will say Jordan must be piously
selfless to pass up a guaranteed $35 million and the chance for a
seventh championship ring.
</P>
<P>
   Nonsense. Jordan is a corporation unto himself, rich beyond
belief. Passing up $35 million is no sacrifice. Returning for
another season when he doesn't need the money, or the records, or
the ring, or the acclaim, that would be the truly sefless act.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Jordan tosses up an airball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put ourselves in a hard predicament right now,'' the
Lakers' Kobe Bryant said. ``But the league has always made it. . .
He's not here, so we've got to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball faced the same battle three years ago, after a strike
canceled the 1994 World Series. The damage was immense and
attendance plummeted.
</P>
<P>
   But there was Cal Ripken Jr., breaking the
consecutive-games-played record the next season, and the ill
feelings seemed to fade along with Lou Gehrig's record. And then
Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa came along last year chasing Roger
Maris and finished the job. The slate was wiped clean. The
once-bitter American public went from forgive to forget in the
space of a single September.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA stands where baseball did. An ESPN online poll showed 54
percent of those voting had ``no interest'' in the
lockout-shortened season. Another 27.5 percent were ``mildly
interested.'' A CNN-SI poll was more ominous: 55 percent said yes
when asked, ``Without Michael Jordan, is the NBA doomed?''
</P>
<P>
   The NBA needs Ripken and McGwire and Babe Ruth rolled into one.
But he's sunning himself in the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another poll asked who will fill Jordan's shoes. Two-thirds
said ``nobody.'' And former Jordan teammate Steve Kerr had to
agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no replacing Michael Jordan,'' Kerr said. ``Can the
league go on? It has to. Will it be better? No way. We're talking
about the best, most charismatic player ever. That's a lot to
overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner David Stern knows as much. He practically begged
Jordan to return last week. But even the NBA's administrative MVP
couldn't change Jordan's mind.
</P>
<P>
   So Jordan will say goodbye today to the NBA, while the league
that gave birth to ``his Airness'' lies in a ditch, bleeding
profusely from self-inflicted wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Only a clutch player like Jordan can save it. But Jordan has
chosen the easy path, chosen not to risk it all for one more
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Remember Jordan for that game-winner last June if it helps. But
let the record reflect Jordan took his last NBA shot today, Jan.
13, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Let the record show that shot was an airball.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
