<HEADER>
A0685 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DUKE-ELLINGTON-$ADV17     01-13 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUKE-ELLINGTON-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATCHING THE SPIRIT OF A CENTURY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 17) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER WATROUS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What a world to step into, if you were inquisitive. And at the
beginning of the 1920s, Duke Ellington, touched by genius and
ambition, prepared by education and class privilege, walked into
the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine it from the perspective of a young musician: the
recording industry was flowering, radio had burst onto the scene.
Suddenly it was possible to live in Mississippi and know what was
happening in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Industry was boiling, cars, airplanes and telephones were
redefining personal freedom. And not only was the Harlem
Renaissance on its well-publicized way, with a huge surge of
artistic production, but the attentions of whites were fixed on
black creativity. There was an audience for the new arts, black and
white, and an audience with money.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country different musical styles were flourishing.
Melodies were everywhere, from childrens' songs, vaudeville tunes,
ragtime compositions, pop pieces, work chants, parlor piano hits,
river sounding chants, Broadway and light classical music to ring
shouts and gospel.
</P>
<P>
   In New Orleans, the improvisational impulse had produced a
sophisticated polyphonic music, and two improvising masters, Sidney
Bechet and Louis Armstrong, had both put their genius on record by
1923. In New York, symphonic jazz played by Paul Whiteman and
others wrestled with large dance bands and ragtime orchestras for
supremacy. The composer James Reece Europe was experimenting with a
large orchestra, and Wilbur Sweatman, Will Marion Cook and Prince's
Band were recording during the teens and 20s, with black and white
bands borrowing from each other.
</P>
<P>
   Itinerant musicians, whether they be boogie pianists schooled in
Southern turpentine camps or Mississippi blues men, toured the
country. Early jazz orchestras, including the band of Fletcher
Henderson, were working. Urban blues were selling millions of
copies, and in Europe the jazz explosion was already drawing
touring bands from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   When Duke Ellington, fresh from Washington, arrived in New York
in 1923, it was the present and future cultural capital of the
world. He began playing in what were known as black and tans,
joints that catered to black and white audiences, and in 1927, just
a year after his first wobbly recordings under his own name, he
fell into the job that changed American cultural history. King
Oliver rejected an offer to work in Harlem's whites-only Cotton
Club, and Ellington, then 28, took the job.
</P>
<P>
   It was a huge undertaking: he had to prepare nightly broadcasts
for a national audience and music for the chorus and specialty
dancing as well as collaborate with the songwriters Jimmy McHugh
and Dorothy Fields. Most important, he had to add a musical
background to the stereotype-laden narratives that powered the
black reviews for the white audiences.
</P>
<P>
   He was creating the ``jungle sound'' that, stripped of its
racial context, sounds radical to this day.
</P>
<P>
   Ellington turned to what he knew, taking from orchestral jazz
and incorporating the vocal aspect of the New Orleans style. In his
trumpeter Bubber Miley he had two things. First, Miley was a
virtuoso in his reinvention of his instrument; his vocabulary of
slurs, bitten, choked notes and bent tones was passed on to other
members of the orchestra, and from it came the shouting, vocal
aspect of the band. And Miley was an extraordinary composer who
produced the raw elements of both ``East St. Louis Toodle-oo'' and
``Black and Tan Fantasy.''
</P>
<P>
   In those works one hears a striking balance between form and the
power of Miley's cornet playing; Ellington's orchestral brilliance
begins to show. Ellington was gaining fame by the time he took the
Cotton Club job. Two years later, in 1929, he was featured in the
film ``Black and Tan.'' Ellington is presented as a serious
composer; his name is ``Duke'' in the film.
</P>
<P>
   The film showed both that Ellington was famous, and what he was
famous for. It also made clear that even at that time, a black,
serious composer could, by force of will, ability and the right
friends, present himself with dignity. And it showed the
development of Duke Ellington, the icon. Tall and handsome, and
affecting an almost English diction, he was perfecting the image of
the reserved, witty and intelligent serious composer.
</P>
<P>
   It was an image that lasted until his death in 1974, and it was
an image that affected people in and out of entertainment; its
democratic reach provided a meeting ground for people of all races.
B.B. King, as a child in Mississippi, was so moved by the image
that he modeled his stage demeanor after Ellington's.
</P>
<P>
   Though he was a master of the three-minute form imposed by the
limits of the 78, Ellington continued writing extended pieces in
the 30s, including ``Creole Rhapsody,'' ``Diminuendo and Crescendo
in Blue'' and ``Reminiscing in Tempo.''
</P>
<P>
   Such compositions challenged the lines between popular
entertainment and art music. Often enough the compositions were
tied to what he called ``the character and mood and feeling of my
people,'' and they culminated in the 1943 performance of his
masterpiece ``Black, Brown and Beige,'' a three-part work based on
the black experience in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   As with his previous longer pieces, ``Black, Brown and Beige''
sought a third way, a path between popular culture and art culture.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Ellington reaches ``Black, Brown and Beige,'' he has
written mood pieces and big-band pieces. He has revitalized blues _
``Ko-Ko'' _ and by 1940 he had written seven pieces about the black
condition using ``Harlem'' in the title.
</P>
<P>
   Ellington was the master of modernism, and where as a young
composer he had sipped the wine of the culture around him, ``Black,
Brown and Beige'' shows that he dominated it. He, like the other
great figures of American modernism, be they Buster Keaton or
Ernest Hemingway, had found a way to be both popular and
intelligent, to mesh the needs of the audience with those of the
artist.
</P>
<P>
   No other country in the Americas was blessed with a popular
culture so rich and lasting, and Ellington, by the time he was 40,
had set the paradigm for the most productive path of all, the third
way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 0159EST &QL; 
