<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 02:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0686 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DUKE-ELLINGTON-MUSIC-     01-13 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUKE-ELLINGTON-MUSIC-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELLINGTON CENTENNIAL: RECALLING SHIFT IN POPULAR TASTES
</HEADLINE>
 (For release Sunday, Jan. 17) 
Mark Tucker, a professor of music and American Studies at the
College of William &AMP; Mary, is the editor of ``The Duke Ellington
Reader.'' 
(bl) 
By MARK TUCKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Most musicians making their Carnegie Hall debut don't
open with ``The Star-Spangled Banner.'' But this was no ordinary
debut. On Jan. 23, 1943, Duke Ellington and his orchestra played to
a capacity crowd in a benefit concert for the Russian War Relief
fund.
</P>
<P>
   Ellington was riding high. At 43 he was one of the leading
exponents of swing, the exuberant style of jazz then reaching the
crest of its popularity. His music was known throughout the world.
Thousands bought his recordings, listened to his radio broadcasts,
danced to his rhythms and romanced to his songs.
</P>
<P>
   That evening at Carnegie Hall, though, Ellington chose to play
more than ``Mood Indigo,'' ``Don't Get Around Much Anymore'' and
the other hits his fans expected. He also made it clear that he
expected recognition as a serious composer. This was evident when
his orchestra gave the premiere of ``Black, Brown and Beige,'' a
work of symphonic proportions subtitled ``A Tone Parallel to the
History of the Negro in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellington turned the concert into a teach-in, portraying in his
music the struggles, hopes and achievements of African-Americans
from the time of slavery to the present. It was a bold gambit. But
the broad vision was characteristic of the man who years before had
declared ``the music of my race is something which is going to
live, something which posterity will honor in a higher sense than
merely that of the music of the ballroom today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Black, Brown and Beige'' and the concert as a whole drew mixed
reviews. In the long run, though, it didn't matter. Ellington and
his orchestra would be back, returning to Carnegie Hall on a
near-annual basis until 1948. With each concert Ellington
programmed new large-scale works side by side with shorter songs
and instrumentals, ignoring the protests of those who wished to
keep serious and popular music both separate and unequal.
</P>
<P>
   Ellington capitalized on his fame to make musical statements
that not only entertained but carried political meaning. Blurring
the boundaries of high and low art became his way of protesting
segregation and discrimination in society at large. Later, he
referred to his Carnegie Hall appearances as a series of
``social-significance thrusts.'' His piece ``New World A-Coming''
(1943), for example, projected better living conditions for
African-Americans after the war for democracy had been fought
overseas. The ``Deep South Suite'' (1946) opened with a movement
poking fun at what Ellington called ``the Dixie Chamber of Commerce
dream picture.'' Ellington even coded messages of protest into his
musical vocabulary. He once gave a race-based explanation for the
tension in his harmonies: ``Dissonance is our way of life in
America. We are something apart, yet an integral part.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ellington's role as a public figure extended beyond social
criticism. His celebrity status, regal bearing and diplomatic
locutions made him a symbolic leader for African-Americans _ an
authoritative voice for his people.
</P>
<P>
   When the nation mourned the death of President Franklin D.
Roosevelt in April 1945, Ellington's orchestra was the only dance
band selected to pay tribute to the leader in a memorial radio
broadcast. Through Duke Ellington's music, the sober announcer
intoned, the heart of the Negro weeps for Franklin Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   Ellington's elevated stature, though, rested uneasily on the
shifting sands of popular taste. As the big-band era waned in the
late 1940s and early '50s, so did Ellington's authority. Now he had
to fight for his own survival, not just for the well-being of
brothers and sisters across the land. Record sales dropped and
longtime sidemen like alto saxophone star Johnny Hodges departed.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ellington kept the organization rolling. By the 1950s,
though, it was clear his era had ended: from then on he was
increasingly seen as a tenacious survivor, a link to America's
musical past rather than the man of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   He still wrote longer works for the concert hall. ``Harlem,''
the most satisfying of Ellington's extended compositions, was a
brash and bluesy tribute to the urban community he loved above all
others. It had its premier in 1951 during a benefit for the NAACP
at the old Metropolitan Opera House. He explored collaborations
between jazz band and symphony orchestra in ``Night Creature''
(1955), later choreographed by Alvin Ailey.
</P>
<P>
   But he also had to confront the commercial pressures posed by
rhythm-and-blues and rock-and-roll. One way was to produce pieces
with catchy melodies, simpler harmonies and a heavier backbeat,
like ``Satin Doll'' (1953), co-written with Billy Strayhorn with
lyrics by Johnny Mercer, which became one of Ellington's biggest
hits.
</P>
<P>
   Other attempts to keep up with current trends were less
successful. Few jazz repertory orchestras during this centennial
year will be performing ``Bunny Hop Mambo'' or ``Echo Tango,'' both
recorded by the Ellington orchestra for Capitol in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1950s, as Elvis Presley and Chuck Berry rocked the
younger set and television became crucial for musicians seeking
national exposure, Ellington's career languished and his creative
energies flagged. For six weeks in the summer of 1955 his
internationally renowned orchestra performed in an aquatics show in
Flushing, Queens, sharing the bill with skaters, divers and dancing
fountains. Was this the rosy future Ellington had envisioned in
``New World A-Coming'' back in 1943?
</P>
<P>
   Not really. Soon Johnny Hodges and his silken alto returned to
the Ellington reed section. And the following summer, in Newport,
R.I., Ellington got lucky, according to his own definition: being
at the right place at the right time, and doing the right thing
before the right people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 0200EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 02:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0689 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THIN-RED-LINE-FILM-2T     01-13 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THIN-RED-LINE-FILM-2TAKES-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE THIN RED LINE': ABOVE THE BATTLE, MUSING ON THE PROFUNDITIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For release Sunday, Jan. 17)  
 Phillip Lopate is the author, most recently, of ``Totally,
Tenderly, Tragically,'' a collection of film criticism and essays. 
(bl) 
By PHILLIP LOPATE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Thin Red Line'' is a very odd movie. I think it one of the
pinnacles of American filmmaking in the 1990s, but I can also
appreciate the objections leveled against it by other film critics
who were baffled, irritated or chagrined by this three-hour
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the film had been so long-awaited (10 years in
the making, by Terrence Malick, a maverick legendary for both the
sparseness and self-consciousness of his output), that it could not
help disappointing such hyped expectations.
</P>
<P>
   For another, what is actually on the screen is so singular, so
peculiar, that there may not be many previous models by which to
judge it.
</P>
<P>
   After all, here is a major-studio Christmas release that begins
with a crocodile submerging itself in algaed water while an
unidentified voice-over muses about the origins of evil, the
breakup of community, the mystery of love, the proper way to meet
death, the existence or nonexistence of a higher plane of being.
These philosophical questions persist, breaking in sometimes at
moments of high drama, distancing us from the narrative or at least
impelling us to search for a larger meaning to it. Sometimes the
voice-over belongs clearly to one of the characters; at other
times, we are left to guess. The result is that all the voice-overs
seem to come from a universal mind; darting from self to self,
connected by invisible tendrils of fear and hunger for
understanding. The voices are obviously also fragments of the
director's own thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   I think what we have here is a strange hybrid: a picture that
seems to be a blood-and-guts war movie (and Malick shows surprising
gifts as an action director), but that asserts at the same time an
entirely other, centrifugal movement, akin to what might be called
``meditative cinema.''
</P>
<P>
   For starters, we can think of films like Mizoguchi's ``Sansho
the Bailiff,'' Renoir's ``River,'' Tarkovsky's ``Stalker,''
Sokurov's ``Mother and Son,'' Bresson's ``Man Escaped'' or John
Ford's ``She Wore a Yellow Ribbon.'' Each of these films seems to
put us in touch with eternal rhythms and spiritual questions
underneath their melodramas of survival. In meditative cinema, time
is often played with, distended, backed up. As viewers, we move
both forward and in circles.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, one of the climaxes of ``The Thin Red Line,'' you
would think, is when the C company troops break through and swarm
over the Japanese soldiers, taking them prisoner. In a more
straightforward war picture, such a victory would certainly have
been celebrated. Malick undercuts the triumph of the moment by
providing elegiac music as a counterpoint to the fast-moving
visuals, by dissolving dialogue into voice-over, and by filming the
Japanese in a stylized manner, naked, praying, as though caught in
the midst of a complex grief ritual.
</P>
<P>
   While there is no point in comparing ``The Thin Red Line'' with
the year's other formidable war movie, ``Saving Private Ryan,'' we
can note at least that Hans Zimmer's haunting, unresolved musical
score in the Malick picture is the polar opposite of the brashly
gung-ho score by John Williams for Steven Spielberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Thin Red Line'' has been criticized for its sketchy
historical context. But I don't think Malick's intent was to stage
a realistic recreation of World War II such that every veteran
would approve: the uniforms and weaponry are accurate, and that's
as far as it goes. It is a war movie in the same mythopoetic sense
that Sergio Leone's 1968 ``Once Upon a Time in the West'' is a
western. It comes late in the tradition, when it can only question,
doubt and celebrate a lost genre.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, ultimately, it is less about the war than it is about
living in one's head _ that primary theme of Malick's two earlier
movies.
</P>
<P>
   It may well be that his initial impulse was to use the James
Jones novel, ``The Thin Red Line,'' as a springboard to get him
beyond the sociopath-solipsist ironies of ``Badlands'' (1973) or
the arch, hothouse insularities of ``Days of Heaven'' (1978) and to
move him toward the materiality of troops and supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Malick's second draft screenplay, dated 1996, is a
fairly straightforward telling of a war story, without any
voice-overs. But having summoned the cast and crew of hundreds and
shot the endless footage, he was forced to consider what it all
meant: what was the reality behind the reality? Certain pockets of
surreal unreality, already in place (images of GIs fighting
bewilderingly in a fog, or enemy troops covered with vines) became
accentuated. Several characters and subplots got trimmed: we know
that Bill Pullman ended up on the cutting room floor, while Adrien
Brody, once the film's Everyman, got reduced to a near-mute
onlooker.
</P>
<P>
   The brilliantly acted conflict between Nick Nolte's harsh
Lieutenant Colonel Tall and Elias Koteas' ``soft-hearted'' Captain
Staros became even more dramatically pivotal. And a relative
unknown, Jim Caviezel, was built up to the central protagonist,
Witt, the film's sweetly thoughtful Prince Myshkin character, who
keeps looking for a lost spiritual harmony while easing his mates
in their dying moments.
</P>
<P>
   Witt tangles with his opposite number, the cynical, rock-hard
Sergeant Welsh (Sean Penn), who ridicules the other man's idealism
and hope: ``You're just running into a burning house where no one
can be saved,'' says Welsh. There's a wonderful scene between the
two of them, after the first battle has ended, when Witt comes
across the sergeant drinking alone in an abandoned house. (It is
staged in a restlessly subtle manner, the camera tracking around
both men). Welsh sneeringly asks Witt if he's still seeing ``the
beautiful light.'' Witt tells the other man sympathetically, ``I
still see a spark in you,'' as the camera advances toward Welsh,
who seems (to us) covered in shadows.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Light is the reigning literary metaphor and visual principle in
the film. John Toll's extraordinary cinematography parcels it out:
a typical shot will be three-fourths shaded, with shafts of light
sculpting the crucial forms. The men's heads are dark holes: their
foreheads truncated by helmets, their faces smeared with blackening
sweat.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the film seems to have been shot at twilight, the
``golden hour,'' when there is just enough sun left to transform
the muted image poetically. But in one stunning midday sequence,
the light plays an especially symbolic part: an officer waves two
advance men forward, and they are instantly shot down (the first
combat casualties). The man who sent them forward looks devastated;
then we see the field where they lie, as the sun sweeps across it,
pushing away a cloud, seeming to mark the boundary between life and
death. Malick is fond of these ``correspondences'' (to use
Steiglitz's term for his cloud studies) between the sky above and
the mental mood below. ``Guilt crosses over him like a
mustard-colored cloud,'' Malick writes in ``The Thin Red Line''
screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of excruciating battle tension, a soldier will
suddenly become mesmerized by a leaf pattern, or high grass waving
in the wind. We are treated continually to these layerings of
consciousness: past and present, exterior and interior, as when the
character played by Ben Chaplin crawls along on a dangerous solo
mission, thinking of his wife in her print dress.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics have complained that the characters in the film
aren't fleshed out. This is true, if what is meant is specific
sociological and psychological detail. Each soldier tends to be
characterized by a particular philosophical belief or fixed idea:
one thinks the war is motivated by property, another that all men
are part of a single soul, another that romantic love carries
ultimate meaning, another that we are merely dirt and grass.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Malick is anti-psychological (his next project, ``The
English-Speaker,'' is based on the case of Anna O., from Breuer and
Freud's ``Studies in Hysteria.'') It is that here he is interested
in the metaphysical, from which standpoint individuality becomes
less important; he is certainly interested as well in a soldier's
interiority, but as parts of an unseen reality or collective mind
rather than as imprimaturs of idiosyncrasy.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the two antagonists, played by Nolte and Koteas, both have
tender paternal feelings toward their men, thinking of them as
their ``sons.'' The film plays extensively with the notion of the
Army as family, both questioning and affirming it. What is
stressed, finally, is the commonality of human connection and
spiritual incompleteness.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Caviezel's character, Witt, feels he has come in contact
with another, better world (illustrated by the ``paradise gained''
sequence in which he plays with the Melanesians), so the movie
keeps groping for an unseen, transcendent reality. This is always a
chancy thing to do in the medium of film, which is so relentlessly
materialist: but it is finally the longing for that greater glory,
rather than any convincing delivery of it, which ``The Thin Red
Line'' embodies.
</P>
<P>
   The voice-over meditations that Malick superimposes on his
story, and that seem drawn from such disparate sources as American
Transcendentalism, Christianity, Whitman's ``Calamus'' poems and
Eastern religions, have irked some viewers, who regard them as
sophomoric dormitory blather. I see their point, but it depends on
whether you regard questions about the origins of evil and the
purpose of life as philosophically legitimate, or intrinsically
naive.
</P>
<P>
   It's interesting to remember that another large, ambitious war
movie, ``Apocalypse Now'' (1979), sought coherence at the last
moment by adding an overview narrative written by Michael Herr. The
difference is that the ``Apocalypse Now'' narrative line was
genuinely chaotic, and even the ending remained in question almost
until the moment of release, a problem that no voice-over could
hope to correct. Malick's narrative line was more delineated
throughout, but when he put it together he obviously felt it needed
another level of consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   One source he seems to have consulted is his own play, ``Sansho
the Bailiff,'' a loose adaptation of the Mizoguchi film. Malick
wrote it in 1993 while he was preparing ``The Thin Red Line.''
There is a long middle section in the play in which the hero
stumbles upon a land of spirits and demons. There, he meets a
character called the Mind, who is hungry for he knows not what.
``His appetite grows with each disappointment,'' Malick writes.
``And yet he feels he is free, that he can leap around endlessly,
go wherever he pleases.''
</P>
<P>
   This seems to be the prototype of the mind leaping from
character to character in ``The Thin Red Line.'' The hero, thinking
of his family, cries out: ``I would be ashamed for them to know
what I've come to _ what a ruin! _ how all their sacrifice, their
care, is poured out like water in the sand!'' Now note the
voice-over Malick gives to Nolte's Lieutenant Colonel Tall: ``My
family, my home. All they sacrificed for me, poured out like water
on the ground. All I might have given for love's sake. Too late!
Dying, slow as a tree.'' While Tall is looking snappy, alert,
unfazed, the career soldier personified, he knows he is dying
inside. Without this voice-over, we would regard his actions later
as merely those of a military bully. This way, we see him as part
of the fever-dream that is ``The Thin Red Line,'' part of that
larger, questing, self-tormented consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Charles Ives' ``Unanswered Question'' is quoted on
the music track; by its title alone, there could not be a better
reference for this movie, which invokes so many unanswered
questions and dares (in every way but visually) to be uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   We may still feel there is something not quite settled or
perfected in this ``Thin Red Line.'' Perhaps it tries to say too
much after having hacked away too much, or it feels, disquietingly,
both maximalist and minimalist.
</P>
<P>
   We may never stop wondering about other possibilities that may
have been carved from the footage, the alternate universes of ``The
Thin Red Line,'' the six-hour ``Iliad'' version, the one with Bill
Pullman and a speaking Adrien Brody, the one with no voice-overs,
and so on. But this is the one we have, and it is fascinating both
for its longing and achievement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
