<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0692 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANBY-THEATER-ART-2TA     01-13 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANBY-THEATER-ART-2TAKES-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN `FAR EAST,' A WASP TRIES TO FLEE THE NEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 17)  
 (af)  
 By VINCENT CANBY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The cover of the program for ``Far East,'' A.R.
Gurney's dark comedy now at the Mitzi E. Newhouse Theater at
Lincoln Center in Manhattan, promises something on the order of
``Madama Butterfly'': a United States Navy officer in his dress
whites stands against what looks to be an antique Japanese print of
a geisha.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, no, you think, not that story again, and not even a Puccini
score to go with it. Well, ``Far East'' is that story again, but
with a few important twists. Here is a ``Madama Butterfly'' in
which the lovesick geisha is a Japanese waitress whom you never
meet, the score is a collection of American standards from the
1950s, the cornier the better (``Love Is a Many-Splendored Thing,''
among others), and the Pinkerton character is a young man ready to
make a long-term commitment.
</P>
<P>
   As you might guess, ``Far East'' is not a tragic romance. It is
a sometimes sharply satiric consideration of Gurney's favorite
subject: the WASP, both as a mindless American predator and as a
victim of the value system that has shaped him, for better and
mostly for worse. ``Far East'' is also his most entertaining comedy
since ``Sylvia,'' the one about a man who falls in love with a dog,
which, when the dog was played by Sarah Jessica Parker in the
Manhattan Theater Club production, seemed a perfectly reasonable
thing to do. Gurney is a playwright who goes his own way.
</P>
<P>
   WASP writers, including the man who wrote ``Sylvia,'' ``The
Perfect Party'' and ``The Dining Room,'' are an endangered species.
They must be made to feel wanted, even relevant.
</P>
<P>
   As American society has grown increasingly, militantly
multicultural, the WASP experience has become more and more
peripheral to the fate of the nation. John Cheever would seem to
have had some of the last, most pungent words on the subject in his
short stories, those glowing suburban nightmares about infidelity,
booze and the loss of spiritual direction.
</P>
<P>
   John Updike soldiers on with novels and stories in which the
frayed WASP identity remains proudly evident, though even he seems
to be acknowledging the possibility of obsolescence. How else to
explain his nerviest creation, the Jewish writer Bech, back again
in a third novel, ``Bech at Bay''? It is as if Updike had applied
for a passport from a foreign country in case he has to get out of
town fast.
</P>
<P>
   In the theater, Sam Shepard is our most restless and innovative
chronicler of the WASP condition, though his characters have
nothing to do with the 19th-century Eastern establishment types who
set the pace for this country's arts, industries and financial
institutions. Shepard's WASP's aren't blood kin to Old Money, like
those in the plays of both Tina Howe and Gurney. Nor do they belong
to families hanging onto their manners while selling their
silverware.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they are the bewildered heirs to the God-fearing,
sun-dried homesteaders, farmers and ranchers who moved west to
settle a new land, which too quickly became a shopping mall. They
are dispossessed, having been disconnected from all tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard's people are the sort whose vocabularies are stocked
with brand names, whose sacred myths have been acquired from movies
and television.
</P>
<P>
   Lieutenant Junior Grade Wallace W. Watts (Michael Hayden),
nicknamed Sparky, the central figure in ``Far East,'' is another
kind of WASP entirely. The time is 1954. Sparky, an heir to his
mother's family's beer fortune back home in Milwaukee, seems to
wear his moneyed heritage with ease. In fact, he is intolerably
cocky when first met, as he reports for duty at the Yokosuka Naval
Base south of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid the draft and see the world, he entered the Navy after
graduating from Princeton. He has already served aboard a ship in
the Mediterranean. His plan now is to learn all about the Orient
and, on his discharge, to finish off his education at the Harvard
Business School. He doesn't realize it at the time, but his
schedule goes out the window his first night on the base when he
encounters an exquisitely pretty, docile young Japanese woman
working in the commissary.
</P>
<P>
   Being naive as well as brashly self-assured, Sparky is soon
flouting all the Navy's rules against fraternization. When the
affair prompts threats from his commanding officer and his family
in Milwaukee, he immediately makes plans to marry. He probably
hasn't read James Michener's ``Sayonara,'' published in 1954, but
he would certainly consider it his story.
</P>
<P>
   It's not an omission that the young woman never appears in ``Far
East.'' She is less important to Sparky and to the play than what
she represents, which is his freedom from the class he so freely
ridicules.
</P>
<P>
   There are only three other characters in ``Far East'': Captain
Anderson (Bill Smitrovich), Sparky's commander, an Annapolis man;
Julia (Lisa Emery), the captain's somewhat younger wife, who is an
old friend of Sparky's family, and Ensign Bob Munger (Connor
Trinneer), Sparky's best friend on the base. The one intense
relationship the audience sees on the stage is that of Julia and
Sparky.
</P>
<P>
   With her own marriage falling apart, she becomes obsessed by her
feelings for Sparky, alternately flirting and pushing him away,
while keeping his family in Milwaukee posted on his extracurricular
activities. He has no romantic feelings for her, but she is a very
intelligent, attractive woman.
</P>
<P>
   He is someone who could easily manage an uncomplicated affair
while remaining faithful to his mistress. That's the way he thinks.
But then Julia is just the kind of WASPy woman he is escaping with
his Asian lover. An uncomplicated affair? He knows better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Far East'' is an entertaining but awkwardly developed stage
piece that at times might remind you of notes for a novel. Its
characters, Julia in particular, but also Sparky, appear to need
more room for development, introspection and comment. There is also
a subplot dealing with blackmail that is far from convincing in its
specific details: something to do with a top-secret code book.
</P>
<P>
   Gurney can't be bothered to smooth out some of the bumps in the
narrative. His dialogue, however, can be as wittily to the point as
that of any playwright at work today. At important moments, he
nails these people to the wall.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Far East'' he is not sending up his WASP characters, only
trying to understand them. The play is illuminated and made
coherent by the succession of vivid scenes between Julia and
Sparky, and Sparky and Bob Munger, which are suddenly, surprisingly
poignant and revealing.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Emery gives a beautifully strong, edgy performance as the
self-destructing Julia, who is also self-aware. She kids herself
that she has no follow-through, in life as in her golf swing. That
is also true of Sparky who, as Hayden so exuberantly plays him,
could be well on his way to becoming a self-deceiving but
enthusiastic member of the corporate world.
</P>
<P>
   Smitrovich is staunch, plain and believable in the more
conventionally written role of a gruff Navy man who is more in love
with the service than with his wife. Trinneer is very good indeed
as the unhappy junior officer, caught in the subplot whose
mechanics are clumsy.
</P>
<P>
   The director, Daniel Sullivan, has given Gurney's detailed text
the fine, fluid, firm production it demands. The play is presented
as if it were under the influence of some exotic amalgam of Japan's
Kabuki, No and Bunraku (puppet) theaters.
</P>
<P>
   In the austere set designed by Thomas Lynch, the stage floor is
a piece of minimal art: a white wooden field with a rectangle of
royal blue at the center; on the back wall there are Japanese
printlike projections. The stage remains bare except for the
appearance of wooden stools to sit on from time to time and the
occasional props. These are silently whisked on and off by the two
stagehands, dressed in black with veils obscuring their faces, like
handlers of the nearly life-size Bunraku puppets.
</P>
<P>
   An actress identified as The Reader (Sonnie Brown) sits on a
raised platform at the right of the stage, speaking the lines of
the various unseen incidental characters. As the action progresses,
she signals scene changes by bringing together two wooden blocks to
create a delicate clicking sound. This may be Japanese theater as
remembered in a tourist's saki dream, but it is as evocative as it
is soothing.
</P>
<P>
   It is also the elegantly civilized setting in which to show off
the grossly conflicted psyches of Sparky and Julia, even as they
learn to cha-cha-cha at the Yokosuka Officers' Club. &QL; 
 &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS &QC;  &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Time was when every celebrated actress of her generation played
Jean Racine's ``Phedre,'' considered the glory of French classical
theater. Among those celebrated: Duse, Sarah Bernhardt, Edwige
Feuillere. It says something about our generation, and about the
availability of French classical theater in New York, that, until
10 days ago, the only celebrated actress I had ever seen in the
role was an actor: Everett Quinton.
</P>
<P>
   Now I've also seen Diana Rigg, who appears in the last of her 10
performances in the part Sunday at 3 p.m. at the Majestic Theater,
presented by the Brooklyn Academy of Music.
</P>
<P>
   This ends the Almeida Theater Company of London's 13-day visit,
during which Ms. Rigg, her co-star Toby Stephens and their
colleagues have been playing both ``Phedre'' (1677) and Racine's
``Britannicus'' (1669). Though adored in France, Racine is seldom
seen in the English-speaking theater, largely because the French
verse is so difficult to translate into English.
</P>
<P>
   For this production of ``Phedre,'' Ted Hughes, the English poet
laureate who died recently, composed a new adaptation, not in the
rhymed alexandrines of the original but in free verse. There is
also a new adaptation of ``Britannicus'' by Robert David MacDonald,
this one in English rhymed couplets, which manages to evoke some
measure of the severe formality of the original.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, Hughes' ``Phedre,'' which reads beautifully, plays as
if it were five hours long instead of the actual 1 hour and 45
minutes. On the other hand, MacDonald's ``Britannicus'' plays like
a breathless melodrama written yesterday, though it is nearly
impossible to read. When you see the words on the page, you can be
astonished by the Tin Pan Alley rhymes, and defeated by the
meaningless extra words stuffed into the lines to satisfy the
demands of the meter. You don't hear them in performance.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect, however, that the difficulty with ``Phedre'' may be
more with the production itself than with the Hughes adaptation. As
directed by Jonathan Kent, who also directed Ms. Rigg's ``Medea,''
seen here in 1994, the actress' performance is a tour de force in
terms of strength only.
</P>
<P>
   It is hysterical, without modulation, not helped by elaborate,
what appear to be Thai silk gowns and stoles that need as much
attention to maneuver gracefully as the lines require to be heard
properly.
</P>
<P>
   Though Ms. Rigg was both true and strong as Mother Courage in
Kent's recent Royal National Theater production of the Brecht
classic, she is not that richly accomplished in these would-be
bravura roles. She is a brilliant, subtle comedienne, as she proved
here in 1975 in the Royal National Theater production of ``The
Misanthrope.'' This is the quality that lights up her performance
in ``Britannicus,'' in which she plays the ruthlessly scheming
Agrippina, mother to the mad young Nero ( Stephens).
</P>
<P>
   Agrippina is a woman who will rule the Roman Empire or will die
in the attempt. There is something comic and theatrically bracing
about her high-handed ferocity. Phedre's incestuous love for her
stepson, Hippolytus ( Stephens), is large and all-consuming, but it
can't be communicated in what sounds like one long garrulous rant.
</P>
<P>
   Stephens, the son of Maggie Smith and Robert Stephens, obviously
has the proper theater genes. He has authority and intelligence on
the stage, without yet being able to create a singular stage
personality. He, too, isn't helped in ``Phedre'' by unbecoming
costumes, which, in his case, suggest that he needs an exercycle.
</P>
<P>
   He also fares far better in the roaring political melodrama of
``Britannicus,'' and not only because he wears more or less
contemporary business suits, which hide what they don't flatter.
Nero gives him latitude to be absolutely beastly and enjoy every
minute of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phedre'' could be taking place in Racine's mind. What we see
on the stage is a great, high-ceilinged, L-shaped hall that calls
up no particular time or place. Except for the self-conscious
lighting effects, it is virtually invisible, like a spasm of
emotion. The time of ``Britannicus'' would seem to be the 1950s and
the place an 18th-century royal palace in the center of London.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Bjornson designed the single set in a way that, with a few
superficial modifications, can meet the needs of each production.
Utterly sensible. So, too, are the excellent supporting
performances by Barbara Jefford, Julian Glover and David Bradley.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
