<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0695 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RICHTER-MUSIC-2TAKES-     01-13 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICHTER-MUSIC-2TAKES-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MODERN MINSTREL, ONCE WRAPPED IN MYSTERY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 17) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOHN RUSSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just 40 years ago, rumor in the West ran hot about a Russian
pianist named Sviatoslav Richter.
</P>
<P>
   His was a curious case. Since the death of Stalin in 1953, the
permafrost had gone out of musical relations between East and West.
David Oistrakh, Emil Gilels and Mstislav Rostropovich had all been
allowed out of the Soviet Union. These were big cards, played with
panache. But when new deals were brokered, there was someone who
could not be got, and that was Richter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Impossible,'' the word came back year after year. ``Richter is
not well enough to travel.'' It was said that he was too nervous to
face a foreign public, although he had played in Budapest and
Prague in 1954 with no signs of frailty.
</P>
<P>
   In 1957 Richter made friends with the Canadian pianist Glenn
Gould at a concert in Moscow. And now Bruno Monsaingeon, a Canadian
film director who collaborated on projects with Gould, has issued a
documentary, ``Richter: The Enigma,'' which will open the Lincoln
Center series ``Great Pianists of the 20th Century'' on Friday
evening at the Walter Reade Theater.
</P>
<P>
   After 1941, and not least during World War II, Richter pulled
his weight in Russian musical life. In 1959 he played at the
funeral of Olga Knipper, the widow of Anton Chekhov.
</P>
<P>
   Then, suddenly, Khrushchev spoke to Yekaterina Furtseva, the
Soviet culture minister, and in 1960 Richter played extensively in
the United States and Canada. He performed in England and France in
1961, and in Italy in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   How it was in the United States I cannot say. But in London in
July 1961 he made an unforgettable impression. He had a mighty
head, mighty shoulders, mighty legs and mighty coattails. He had
compact but very large hands, with which he dug deep into the
keyboard for what he called ``a singing sonority.''
</P>
<P>
   In his bearing he was impassive, with just one brief, unsmiling
bow and an occasional cock of his head to the right. He was fast
onto the stage and fast off it, but when he sat down, a long
silence might follow. ``Silence also has sound,'' he would say,
``and the element of surprise is vital.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not his style to serenade, let alone seduce, the public.
Nor did he choose for his debut in London the kind of program that
would have assured him a 20- or 30-minute ovation. Many in the
audience were disconcerted to find that after a Haydn sonata, the
rest was by Prokofiev: the Second and Eighth Sonatas and 11
``Visions Fugitives.''
</P>
<P>
   Many in that audience, not knowing that Haydn's sonatas are
miracles of wit and invention, thought they were being fobbed off
with schoolroom music instead of a pianistic equivalent of the
Overture to Glinka's ``Ruslan and Ludmila.''
</P>
<P>
   But Richter, all his life, was finding new marvels in Haydn, who
was also a favorite of Prokofiev. By 1960 Richter had 27 sonatas by
Haydn and 39 pieces by Prokofiev in his repertory, so the program
made perfect sense. The credentials Richter presented that evening
were not boilerplate, but they were his own.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of 1961, he had played enough in the United States,
and in England, to know that he did not want to live the life of a
mainline international virtuoso.
</P>
<P>
   The music industry in its standard forms repelled him. To know
where he would have to be two or three years ahead seemed to him a
recipe for self-destruction. So did the hype, the mandatory press
calls, the standard repertory and the company of backers and
managers.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted to be his own person and plot his career in his own
way. When asked about certain landmarks in the piano literature, he
would say: ``Oh, no, I shall never touch them. When I have heard
something played perfectly, I could not possibly take it up.'' This
reaction dated from his student days, when his teacher Heinrich
Neuhaus performed Beethoven's ``Emperor'' Concerto. ``After that, I
could have nothing to add,'' he said. The same thing happened when
he heard his classmate Gilels play Prokofiev's Third Sonata. ``I
loved that sonata,'' he said, ``but after Gilels I had nothing more
to say.''
</P>
<P>
   The resulting gaps in his repertory included Beethoven's
``Waldstein'' Sonata and Fourth Concerto, and the First Concerto of
Brahms. But with other, less widely loved pieces, he took unlimited
trouble. He spent two years learning Dvorak's Piano Concerto, with
its dreaded passages for double thirds in both hands. He spent a
year on rehearsals in his own apartment for Berg's Chamber
Concerto, for piano, violin and winds, with a student orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, he wanted to lead the life of a high-level wandering
minstrel who also happened to be a great pianist. He liked to go to
places that had never heard playing like his.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, at 71, he insisted on being driven from Moscow to
Vladivostok and back, to avoid flying all the way to Japan. He was
away from July 20 to Nov. 31. On that round trip he played 91
concerts in whatever places were on the route.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, he freshened up the concert formula in the Pushkin
Museum at the end of every year. These concerts were not the kind
at which people look straight ahead and dare not eye one another.
</P>
<P>
   The visitors (by invitation only) were faced with what amounted
to a low-cost scene of faerie. On the stage, branches powdered with
imitation snow dipped from the proscenium. People dressed in
19th-century costume sat on garden chairs and bandied idle
nothings. There was a hint of a lake. Richter had in mind the scene
at George Sand's house in Nohant when Chopin stayed there.
</P>
<P>
   This tiny wonderland was to be kept free from fuss, even if the
evening's debutant was Evgeny Kissin, then in his early teens.
There was often great music, but there was no showmanship. Richter
chose all the performers, and when he put on Benjamin Britten's
comic opera ``Albert Herring,'' he himself took the production in
hand. But he did not prance around like the lord of the manor.
Dressed like an English country gentleman, with a checked jacket
and a flat cap at the ready, he moved silently from place to place,
missing nothing.
</P>
<P>
   He was never taken in. One evening he looked even broodier than
usual. ``How ghastly this is,'' he said to my wife and me. ``How
did I ever invite this pianist?''
</P>
<P>
   He also loved the smaller, handmade festivals of Western Europe.
In 1964, he went to the Aldeburgh Festival, run by Britten and
Peter Pears. Monsaingeon's video illustrates the delight with which
Richter and Britten went like the wind in the last movement of a
four-hand sonata by Mozart.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-60s, Richter was ready to establish roots in Western
Europe. The Loire Valley was his first choice, but the famous
chateaux didn't suit. Then he heard of the Grange du Meslay, a
13th-century barn the size of a small cathedral, near Tours. It was
still in use but had enormous possibilities, and Richter fell in
love with it. The Fetes Musicales de Touraine opened there in June
1964, and for years the festival was, he said, ``one of the joys of
my existence.''
</P>
<P>
   During the Fetes, Richter and his wife lived in a secluded house
on the estate of the van de Veldes, who had backed the festival
from its beginnings. Life there was a Franco-Russian paradise.
</P>
<P>
   Conversations drifted this way and that in Chekhovian style.
Hugely gifted people drew on their sense of play, as when the
violist Yuri Bashmet rode around on a tiny bicycle. Private talks
could blaze up anywhere and at any time, as when Richter's wife,
Nina Dorleac, the incomparable Russian lieder singer, took shelter
from a rainstorm under a tree, the better to discuss the merits of
Solzhenitsyn's latest novel, ``1914.''
</P>
<P>
   Dinner was at no particular time and for no foreseeable number
of people. If Richter was there, it ran late. With good food and
good wine, collegial high humor approached wildness.
</P>
<P>
   One evening, it leaked out that we had to leave the next
morning. Richter pulled one of his more terrifying faces. ``But you
can't go,'' he said. ``We're going to play the Stravinsky Concerto
for Two Pianos tomorrow evening.'' Then he paused. ``Well, if you
really must leave, we'll play it for you now.''
</P>
<P>
   The dining room seated 8 or 10 and had two pianos, side by side.
Richter and Vasily Lobanov came over and sat with their backs to
us, just an inch or two away.
</P>
<P>
   Whether in public or private, Richter gave all he had. The
Stravinsky concerto is strenuous from beginning to end. In short
sleeves, Richter played as if he were laying his life on the line.
That huge head, that rocklike back and those formidable arms and
hands radiated an implacable power. ``That's not the whole
program,'' he said at the end; he added two sizable encores before
the evening was over.
</P>
<P>
   It was impossible to maintain, year-round, that kind of
collegiality: with Oistrakh, Bashmet, the violinist Oleg Kagan, the
cellist Natalia Gutman (whom Richter prized as ``the incarnation of
honesty in art'') and a flotilla of younger pianists.
</P>
<P>
   But before long, with the help of Yamaha, the Japanese piano
maker to which he had given exclusivity, Richter became what he had
wished to be: a minstrel with privileges. When he arrived in a new
country in Western Europe, he bought a large map and marked the
places that piqued his interest. It was agreed that he would never
have to travel on major roads.
</P>
<P>
   Within the hour, the cortege was on its way, led by a limo,
fitted out with a first-rate stereo apparatus, for Richter and his
friends. Not far behind would be the big van from Yamaha, with one
or two pianos, and a car for the technicians who kept them in
perfect shape.
</P>
<P>
   Richter scouted for a promising town _ not too big, and not
famous _ deep in the countryside of France, Germany or Italy. He
looked for a local theater, an ancient chapel or even a school that
fired his fancy. If there was a decent hotel, the cortege halted
overnight. Once the concert space was secured, local worthies were
happy to paste up the program and pass the word around.
</P>
<P>
   These were happy days. It is clear from the notes Richter kept
on his musical experiences from 1970 to 1995 that where music was
concerned, he was as sharp as ever. And in what turned out to be
his last concert (in Lubeck, Germany, on March 30, 1995) he refused
to coast, following three Haydn sonatas with Reger's colossal
Variations and Fugue on a Theme by Beethoven, for two pianos. Reger
was never one to go easy with the notes, but in the concluding
fugue of this redoubtable piece Richter and his young colleague,
Andreas Lucewicz, set up a percussive clatter of a size and quality
rarely heard in the concert hall. (And all that, be it noted, on
Richter's 80th birthday.)
</P>
<P>
   But he was not spared the wretchedness of aging. He noted its
progress, stage by stage, in the memoirs he dictated near the end
of his life to Monsaingeon.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most ``as told to'' narratives, this one is plain and
direct. Almost until the end of the 1970s, Richter played
everything from memory. He had perfect hearing and perfect pitch,
and neither had ever failed him. But then he began to have memory
lapses.
</P>
<P>
   A terrible episode occurred during the Fetes de Touraine, when
he had set himself to play eight of Liszt's ``Transcendental
Etudes.'' And in Japan he was scared almost out of his wits at the
thought of launching into Beethoven's Opus 106. After that, he
decided that he would never again play without the score in front
of him.
</P>
<P>
   This gave him a new security, but it did not give him back the
power of hearing correctly. More and more, he would play in one key
and hear the results in another. Trebles he would hear higher, and
basses lower, than they actually were. Not only was this unnerving
in itself but it made him doubt his fingering.
</P>
<P>
   In his 81st year, he fell and broke a knee. He had always been a
tremendous walker, eagerly covering 25 or 30 miles a day. His legs,
like his hands, never tired. To be a cripple was a mortal blow to
him, relieved only by the fact that he could take part in the film
Monsaingeon was preparing. Though a wraith of his former self, he
was clear and steadfast before the camera.
</P>
<P>
   As well he might have been, for he had fulfilled his life's
dream in those impromptu, out-of-the-way concerts. An eager,
unsnobbish public filled every seat and went home wreathed in
smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd do it for nothing,'' Richter said, ``but I'd never hear
the end of it from the concert managers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
