<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0698 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARISSAUX-PHOTOGS-2TA     01-13 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARISSAUX-PHOTOGS-2TAKES-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RAREFIED BELGIAN WHO SPECIALIZED IN MOURNFUL BEAUTY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 17) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By VICKI GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photography festivals have flourished like weeds ever since
Jean-Luc Monterosso _ now the director of the Maison Europenne de
la Photographie _ organized the first biennial Mois de la Photo in
Paris in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Many festivals were founded in the intervening years; now
photographs stream en masse to international gatherings in Arles,
Barcelona, Berlin, Caracas, Houston, London, Montreal, Moscow, Sao
Paulo and Stockholm; to cities in Australia, Bulgaria, Korea, Mali,
Mexico (which puts up 700 exhibitions around the country, including
one in Texas), Portugal and more. Slovakia has two festivals, one
of them annual. The Netherlands has three.
</P>
<P>
   A well-organized festival is likely to harbor discoveries, good
shows and the inescapable quota of bad ones. (The Lord arranged an
abundant supply of talent but neglected to insure that it be
properly parceled out. Not everyone in line at the distribution
center is given a fair share.) The Mois de la Photo this year seems
to have had all of the above.
</P>
<P>
   One of the discoveries was a Belgian pictorialist named Gustave
Marissiaux, who was widely shown in Belgium, Paris, Berlin and
Italy in the first decade or so of this century, then largely
forgotten even in his own country until a 1997 retrospective at the
Musee de la Photographie in Charleroi.
</P>
<P>
   A show during the Mois at the Wallonie-Bruxelles Center in Paris
closed on Nov. 26, but a beautifully illustrated and
well-researched catalog, ``Gustave Marissiaux: La Possibilite de
l'Art,'' by Marc-Emmanuel Melon, has been published by the
Charleroi museum.
</P>
<P>
   It is not altogether surprising to chance upon an unknown
pictorialist, even a good one, wielding (as most of them did) a
soft-focus lens and painterly printing techniques to fashion ideal
scenes of domestic tranquillity, Edenic nature or feminine beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Pictorialists seem to have sprouted like mushrooms in the damp
aftermath of the Symbolist movement in painting late in the last
century when gentlemen and gentlewomen were cultivating their
aspirations to art. Marissiaux had a good claim to art and a couple
of surprises in his repertory as well.
</P>
<P>
   Born in France in 1872, naturalized as a Belgian in 1893,
Marissiaux took up photography in 1894. His pictures may be less
meltingly beautiful than Heinrich Kuehn's, say, less innovative and
modern than Alvin Langdon Coburn's, but beautiful nonetheless, and
sometimes arresting.
</P>
<P>
   There are women poised expectantly by open doorways, or reading
or gazing out the window, always alone, indoors, searching for
fulfillment, perhaps merely for stimulation, from someone or some
place else. There are portraits of women even more alone, sunk into
their inner lives with downcast eyes. And pictures of Venice, that
isolated city, preternaturally empty, suspended in reverie, waiting
to be awakened.
</P>
<P>
   There are also landscapes with wistful trees and bony branches,
dream-struck gardens, marshes at dusk, where reeds grow tangled in
eternally still water _ places where mists linger and fog catches
in the foliage. Marissiaux raised melancholia to a delicate pitch
of perfection, as if he were exquisitely resigned to what Thomas
Hardy in 1891 called ``the chronic melancholy which is taking hold
of the civilized races with the decline of belief in a beneficent
power.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the surprises. One is his use by 1914 of a
virtually unknown color process that was never commercialized
because it was so difficult, devised by a Belgian photographer
named Joseph Sury, who asked Marissiaux to experiment secretly with
his discovery.
</P>
<P>
   Marissiaux had already shown autochromes, the first successful
color process on the market, which many pictorialists tried out.
Autochromes are not very stable; they are usually shown behind a
curtain or lighted for only a moment, because light bleaches them
out. A couple of Marissiaux's autochrome landscapes in the Paris
show were peculiarly pink, no doubt a sign of fading.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sury process was so stable that his pictures were hung
on the wall last year beside his platinum and gum prints without
special protection. This is astonishing for the second decade of
this century, and better still, Marissiaux's color sense was
delectable. His nudes stand against pinky-beige walls, as if the
entire picture were a reflection of flesh. A woman in a
pistachio-green gown is ensconced in an olive-green setting;
another in palest blue and dull orange is poised before a muted
aqua ground.
</P>
<P>
   The other big surprise is that Marissiaux created a form of
photographic spectacle, which Melon calls ``a sort of opera for
fixed images.'' Here slides projected on enormous screens (about 23
by 19 feet) were accompanied by an orchestra, a choir and soloists
performing contemporary music, followed by a poetry recitation.
</P>
<P>
   A partial tradition for such spectacles already existed in
Belgium. Once a year, beginning in 1888, the photographic society
put on a show of slides of individual pictures by its members,
alternating with short musical pieces by local composers, as a
benefit performance for local charities in Liege. The city's elite
attended these; who else turns out for benefit performances?
</P>
<P>
   In 1903, Marissiaux gave the occasion a theme _ Venice _ and
showed only his own and one other man's pictures. The evening now
had unity and probably some sense of progression, a kind of
narrative manque.
</P>
<P>
   The catalog implies that Marissiaux may have heightened the
drama of music and poetry that had long accompanied the various
photographers' slides. The next time Marissiaux put on this show it
had his pictures alone; it was performed 26 times until 1924, in
Liege, Brussels, Antwerp and Paris.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There was one moment in Marissiaux's career when his photography
changed direction under an external impulse: in 1904 he was
commissioned to make a series of pictures of mines. The series,
called ``La Houillere,'' was the only nod he made to a life beyond
an etiolated dream of paradise. Even these pictures are still and
faintly dreamlike, with the workers removed to the middle ground or
the rear and no one suffering or sweating.
</P>
<P>
   The series was shown as planned at the Universal Exposition in
Liege in 1905; then Marissiaux made this too into a performance.
For several years he showed ``Venice'' and ``La Houillere'' on the
same program in Belgium and Paris, with the same orchestra, to what
appears to have been the same audiences. It was a great success.
</P>
<P>
   In 1911, Edward S. Curtis produced a ``picture musicale,'' which
used slides, fragments of film and a score based on American Indian
songs, but after an initial success it quickly sank from view.
Perhaps the closest thing to Marissiaux's kind of spectacle is Nan
Goldin's slide-and-music shows, where the content is obviously a
bit different.
</P>
<P>
   In Marissiaux's day spectators had long been hungry for
magic-lantern and slide shows as entertainment and education, but
the first two decades of the century also witnessed the rise of
cinema. Movies, however, were low-class fare, shown in industrial
areas, in music halls, at fairs; Melon says that pictorialists
looked down on them as representing the cult of illusion that
pandered to a mass-audience taste.
</P>
<P>
   In America, cinema may have become acceptable for the upper
classes a few years before it did in Belgium; at all events, by
1924 Marissiaux's spectacle gave way to the new era.
</P>
<P>
   The catalog makes a very strong case _ occasionally slightly too
strong _ for pictorialism as a symptom of bourgeois reaction
against the disturbing rupture of the social fabric by the rise of
worker unrest. Belgium had bloodily suppressed worker outbreaks in
the 1880s and had finally instituted universal suffrage, after a
manner of speaking, allotting extra votes to people with money and
education, which insured that they could keep the workers at bay.
</P>
<P>
   Pictorialism depicted an idyllic, peaceful existence for the
bourgeois audience that went to museums and exhibitions and,
according to Melon, the educated bourgeoisie that attended
Marissiaux's spectacles found in them reinforcement of their
separate social identity.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the politics were not quite so clear-cut in this
country, American pictorialists were certainly striving to become
an elite, to be valued as artists and individuals rather than
craftsmen or cogs in the industrial machine. Alfred Stieglitz, who
believed true artists should live rarefied lives devoted to art,
essentially ignored Lewis Hine's tough pictures of child labor.
Pictorialism owed a debt to the Symbolists, many of whom, from
Baudelaire on, had expressed disdain for the masses and their
inferior taste.
</P>
<P>
   It was Symbolist, too, to cherish melancholy. Marissiaux himself
is said to have been reclusive, melancholic, probably
hypochondriacal; his images expressed his personality, his
personality the time. There are historical moments that favor
certain kinds of character and presentation; Ronald Reagan wouldn't
have stood a chance in the years following the American Revolution,
nor would Calvin Coolidge today.
</P>
<P>
   In Marissiaux's day Belgian poets sang of dying flowers,
vaporous apparitions and veils of pale thought, to all of which he
tried to give concrete representation. His times embraced him,
offering him the opportunity to make a virtue of his own weaknesses
and fears, to fixate on mournful beauty and deliver it to those who
yearned for nothing more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
