<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 02:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0702 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EIFMAN-BALLET-ART-2TA     01-13 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EIFMAN-BALLET-ART-2TAKES-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMOLDERING EMOTION KINDLED BY MOTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 17)  
 (af)  
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At supper in his studio in St. Petersburg or at lunch in a New
York restaurant, Boris Eifman, 52, is all good-humored gallantry.
It isn't until this Russian choreographer reveals his life story
that one understands how a surface calm harbors the emotional
intensity that blazes through his ballets.
</P>
<P>
   Not every choreographer has been housed in an underground pit
during a harsh early childhood in Siberia or had all his father's
relatives killed by the Germans during World War II. Nor have most
choreographers, at least in the West, had to invent themselves
within the closed society of the Soviet era. And rare is the
choreographer who, like Eifman, has never been a professional
dancer.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a passion for creating dances has consumed Eifman since he
was 13, and passionate dancing is synonymous with the Eifman Ballet
of St. Petersburg, which opens a two-week season Tuesday night at
City Center. The repertory will again include ``Tchaikovsky'' and
``Red Giselle,'' the highly theatrical psychodramas that became the
hot tickets in the company's New York debut last April.
</P>
<P>
   There are also United States premieres: ``The Karamazovs,'' set
mostly to Rachmaninoff's music, and plotless works on a double
bill, ``Requiem,'' set to Mozart, and ``My Jerusalem,'' which
includes a rock score.
</P>
<P>
   Although no one could be bored by the brilliantly expressive
choreography of Eifman, his scenarios struck some last spring as
provocative rather than persuasive. But he emphasized in an
interview that all his ballets reflect a personal point of view.
``My'' is the operative word.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Jerusalem'' is his response to seeing places of worship for
Jews, Christians and Moslems from a hill in Jerusalem. ``Because
people isolate themselves, I did not feel that people created this
juxtaposition. So God did it,'' Eifman said. ``We live in a world
of conflicts, but in the beginning, there was spiritual unity.'' If
Eifman's ideal vision reconciles these ``three paths to God'' in
``My Jerusalem,'' it is not because he wants to proselytize. ``It
is my way of seeing things,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, he did not set out to retell the story of ``The
Brothers Karamazov'' by Dostoyevsky but to interpret it. ``I was
seeking a new dance expression for philosophical ideas that had to
do with our time,'' he said. Dostoyevsky's discourse on freedom and
God in the novel cannot be literally rendered in ballet. But by
transforming two of the Karamazov brothers, Ivan and Aleksei, into
the Grand Inquisitor and Christ of Dostoyevsky's debate, Eifman
reached for a parable about Russia today.
</P>
<P>
   ``This dialogue is an amplification of the entire ballet,'' he
said. ``Aleksei opens the gates of a prison, but freedom results in
anarchy. At the end, Aleksei rises on a cross toward God and I see
this as the story of Russia, the religious country that became
Godless. Aleksei's hand moves up and he rises on the vertical, with
the erect spine that makes a person a person. Aleksei, in rising up
to God, becomes himself. It's my view, my reaction to
Dostoyevsky.''
</P>
<P>
   Eifman is Jewish and never changed his name, although prominent
Jewish dancers in the Soviet Union advised that it would be better
for his career. His parents did suggest, when he was 12, that dance
was not a profession for a nice Jewish boy. ``A doctor or a
musician was what they had in mind,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the path he took early in life, Eifman said: ``Choreography
is not a profession, although you can study and study for it. But
just as heroes in fairy tales understand the language of animals,
so choreographers have a special language to communicate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best of today's choreographers are like the early shamans,
who were the choreographers of their time. Shamans, through
movement and energy, could communicate energy to the people. I am
interested in an art form of the spirit and of emotion that comes
through movement. If it's just movement, it's not art.''
</P>
<P>
   Eifman was born on July 22, 1946, in Rubtsovsk, Siberia, where
his father, an engineer in Kharkov, Ukraine, had been ordered to
move to help the Soviet war effort in the hinterland. ``My father
had to go,'' Eifman said. ``But this move saved my parents from the
Germans in Kiev and Kharkov, where my father's entire family was
killed.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The kind of life my parents lived under Stalin was lived by
hundreds of thousands. My father could not refuse to go to Siberia,
where he worked in a factory. We didn't live in a camp, but it was
economically efficient to house us underground. We lived in a pit
with six rooms for six to 10 families. If the government did not
build real housing, it was not because of money, but because people
were not treated like people, but like cattle.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1953, after Stalin died, Eifman's father was able to move to
Kishinyev, in Soviet Moldavia. Boris studied ballet and folk dance
from the age of 7 in a Young Pioneers club, as did many Soviet
children. But it was without his parents' consent that he applied
for the ballet school attached to the opera house in Kishinyev.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was accepted, and my parents said I could go only if I
continued in a music school and went to an academic school at
night. At 13, I decided I was going to be a choreographer. It
sounds pretentious, but I kept a diary, noting down what I would
put into future ballets.''
</P>
<P>
   Although virtually all choreographers have been dancers, Eifman
had performed only as a student and started choreographing for a
group he formed at 15. In 1966, he entered the newly formed
choreography department of the Leningrad Conservatory.
</P>
<P>
   Even before graduation in 1972, Eifman had opportunities to
choreograph for television, ice shows and even Kirov ballerinas
like Natalia Makarova. ``She called me a boy, so I grew a beard and
have kept it since,'' Eifman said. From 1970 to 1977, he was the
official choreographer of the Vaganova Academy, the Kirov school.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you did what you were assigned, you were looked upon with
favor,'' Eifman said. In 1979, two years after forming his company
as an adjunct of the Leningrad Philharmonic, Eifman felt he could
use Western rock music (then under attack) and express freely what
he calls contemporary male-female relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Austin, a correspondent for The New York Times in
Moscow, wrote of Eifman's success, although Austin noted that the
authorities had just clamped down on writers in the ``Metropol''
affair, an attempt to publish an anthology without government
censors.
</P>
<P>
   Eifman said that after Austin's article appeared, he was
questioned by the KGB. ``I wasn't in that dissident milieu,'' he
said. ``But they began to say I was not doing Soviet art and that I
should emigrate. I did not.''
</P>
<P>
   The paradox was that Eifman ballets continued to be both
produced and attacked by the cultural authorities. He was accused
of encouraging desertion in ``The Duel'' because it showed a
soldier's breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   His ballet treatment of Mikhail Bulgakov's ``Master and
Margarita'' shocked by depicting Jesus onstage. A ballet based on
the Song of Songs in the Bible was deemed too erotic.
</P>
<P>
   Perestroika opened up touring, and the company appeared in the
West for the first time in 1989. Eifman, who is married to a former
dancer and has a 4-year-old son, has been busier than ever, but he
has not changed his basic belief about dance: ``I have always been
drawn toward dramatic ballet, not pure dance. It comes naturally to
me. What has changed is the technique, as I have developed it. But
as you grow older, your inner emotions grow stronger; you could say
there are stronger passions in my choreography.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 0210EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 02:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0704 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAYS-YOU-RADIO-2TAKES     01-13 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAYS-YOU-RADIO-2TAKES-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BETWEEN NEWS AND MUSIC, A PLACE FOR WORDPLAY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 17) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANDY MEISLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. (italics)Is the definition of the word ``crawk'' (a) the
distaff or downward-turning crook in a guard's spear, signifying
fealty to the king; (b) the fleshy red dewlap of a male turkey's
nether lip; or (c) a sound-effects technician who specializes in
imitating animals?
</P>
<P>
   2. What cheeses are brought to mind by the phrases ``entered
naked,'' ``Ozzie's offspring should'' and ``solo in northern
Utah''?
</P>
<P>
   3. The sentence ``Are you getting tired of me talking about
this?'' is grammatically incorrect. What is the correct version and
why?
</P>
<P>
   4. Who cares?
</P>
<P>
   Answers: (1) c. (2) Camembert, ricotta and provolone. (3) ``Are
you getting tired of my talking about this?'' because a pronoun
that precedes a gerund (``talking'') is always possessive. (4)
Enough public radio listeners, apparently, to keep an unabashedly
anachronistic, nonironically hyperliterate show on the air.(end
italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In fact, ``Says You!'' _ a low-budget, independently produced
half-hour quiz show reminiscent of the old-time radio series
``Information Please'' and the long-running BBC series ``My Word''
_ seems to have a good chance to join the quirky listener-supported
National Public Radio pantheon that includes ``Car Talk,'' ``This
American Life'' and ``A Prairie Home Companion.''
</P>
<P>
   Recorded over Sunday brunch in various Boston-area hotel banquet
rooms, ``Says You!'' is now broadcast on more than 60 public radio
stations nationwide (including WNYC-AM at 7 p.m. Saturdays and 5
a.m. Sundays).
</P>
<P>
   Its format is pure parlor game; those averse to puns, literary
and historical quotations, advanced Trivial Pursuit and cutthroat
Scrabble need not tune in. The heart of ``Says You!'' is the
ancient rainy-day pastime of dictionary bluffing, in which one side
concocts bogus definitions of an obscure word, presents them
alongside the correct meaning and dares the opposition to select
the right one.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of challenge occupies two rounds of the five-round
competition. The rest of the game consists of miscellaneous
literary, linguistic and grammatical questions. Categories include
``Who said what?'' ``Who or what came first?'' and ``What's the
difference?'' (Between wharf and pier, for instance, or nosegay and
bouquet.) The answers in all categories are difficult and/or
obscure.
</P>
<P>
   The quiz is moderated by its creator and producer, Richard Sher.
The two teams of fast-talking Bostonians include six permanent
panelists: Tony Kahn, host of the news program ``The World'' on
Public Radio International; Paula Lyons, a local television
consumer reporter and columnist for The Ladies' Home Journal;
Francine Achbar, a public television executive; Frances Faye Fox, a
columnist and critic; Arnie Reisman, a local television producer,
and _ a bit unexpectedly _ Barry Nolan, former host of the
syndicated tabloid television series ``Hard Copy.''
</P>
<P>
   Guest panelists appear frequently. They have included Art
Buchwald, Alan Dershowitz and the mystery author Robert B. Parker.
</P>
<P>
   The game is scored somewhat arbitrarily, with points awarded by
Sher for wit as well as accuracy. During one game a contestant
defined ``hoove'' as ``an unsuccessful Heimlich maneuver.'' In
another, ``eschatological'' was explained as ``the way they get rid
of cats in Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   The author of the quotation ``There is no gain without pain''
was misidentified enthusiastically as Jane Fonda. (It was actually
Benjamin Franklin.) Sher also gets into the act: once, for
instance, he slyly introduced a panelist to the audience as ``the
brother I never had but always feared.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The show is punctuated by long, puzzled silences and pained
admissions of befuddlement; without a sharp ear and a longtime
acquaintance with the panelists, it is often impossible to tell
exactly who is speaking. During breaks in the action a four-piece
band called Pluperfect and the Past Participles plays popular music
from days long gone by.
</P>
<P>
   In short, it's the kind of eccentric and eclectic show that
judging by the rest of the programs on the air, even noncommercial
radio programmers might think twice about commissioning. Which is
why its apparent success has been greeted with perhaps an extra
fillip or two of satisfaction, brushing ever so slightly against
self-satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Says You!' is a show that people like to engage with,'' says
Murray Horwitz, a former Ringling Brothers circus clown who is
NPR's vice president for cultural programming. ``It's a show for
people who like to think _ or at least like to think they can think
a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Seymour, the general manager of KCRW-FM in Santa Monica,
Calif., says: ``It's elitist in the old-fashioned sense. It's witty
and urbane and presupposes that it's fashionable and desirable to
be highly intelligent. Nowadays, there are some who think you have
to `dumb down' shows even for public radio.''
</P>
<P>
   She adds, ``It would seem to be the last program many people
would think would be a success in Los Angeles, which is one of the
main reasons I put it on the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Elitism in the off-putting sense would seem to be a significant
hazard in producing such a series, but so far very little smugness
can be detected in the banter and byplay among the contestants. The
credit for this would seem to go to Sher, 50, whose unalloyed love
of wordplay for its own sake comes through in the tone of both his
comments and those of his contestants, mostly friends and media
colleagues whom he asked to join the show when it was begun in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   The president of a Boston marketing and media development
company, Sher produced local commercial programming, advertising
campaigns and industrial films for 15 years. ``A few years ago I
was about to give up show business for life,'' he says. ``I was
sick of it. I was thinking landscape architecture, whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   His epiphany, he says, came one evening when he was playing
Trivial Pursuit and drew the question ``What do you call the band
of low pressure that surrounds the earth at the Equator?''
</P>
<P>
   ``My first thought was: `Who cares? It's a dumb, useless
question.' Until I realized that the answer was `the doldrums.'
Then I realized: `It's not that it's important to know the answer.
It's only important to like the answer.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The idea for starting ``Says You!'' came shortly afterward, he
says, and he fairly quickly enlisted the support of the local
public radio station, WGBH. In its first two seasons the show was
promoted mainly via word of mouth and a booth at public radio's
annual program fair; since September the show has been distributed
by NPR.
</P>
<P>
   As for the people on the other side of the dial: when queried,
Sher seems simply unable to believe that his potential audience is
limited by illiteracy, apathy or the siren songs of sitcoms,
heavy-metal or video games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see groups of students, getting together to listen and play
the game,'' he says. ``I see groups of friends, people gathering in
the same room to have fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see the people who simply cannot pass up doing the TV Guide
crossword puzzle. They don't talk about it much. But they're out
there, believe me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
