<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 02:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0707 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELLINGTON-RECORDINGS-     01-13 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLINGTON-RECORDINGS-2TAKES-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELLINGTON ON DISK, LIVE, LOOSENED AND OTHERWISE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 17) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the mid-1970s, the critic Leonard Feather included the
following in his liner notes to what was then a three-LP set, ``The
Duke Ellington Carnegie Hall Concerts _ January 1943'':
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are under 30, know Ellington principally as a legend
and perhaps saw the band a few times in Duke's waning years, these
six sides will provide a startling insight ... (The set) is a trip
through the mind of a man whose achievements in the elevation of
jazz to an orchestral art form are only now, decades after the
fact, gaining some measure of acceptance in the levels where he
once was condescended to or totally ignored.''
</P>
<P>
   The world has changed since Feather wrote those slightly
defensive words. I am in my 30s and, like most people of my
generation, never saw Ellington (he died when I was 5); yet his
form of ``orchestral'' jazz has not only gained some level of
acceptance but is the heart of a powerful cultural institution at
Lincoln Center.
</P>
<P>
   There is not an air of forced propriety about the centennial
events in 1999; Ellington is amazingly relevant, understood without
exaggeration as the obvious and only possible figure linking Wynton
Marsalis's latest long-form composition, the swing revival,
European experimental jazz and the Monday night big-band at the
Village Vanguard.
</P>
<P>
   His discography will be in particularly good shape this year: in
April, RCA will issue ``The Duke Ellington Centennial Edition: The
Complete RCA Victor Recordings 1924-1973,'' a 24-CD set, and for
the rest of the year the label will slowly issue the music from
that set in triple-CD bunches. By June, Columbia will have
reintroduced spruced-up versions of six albums, including the
film-score album ``Anatomy of a Murder'' and the
Shakespeare-inspired ``Such Sweet Thunder,'' as well as a three-CD
overview. But it's still a maze, so here's a selected guide to
what's currently available: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ELLINGTON IN ESSENCE If you're looking for modest, reliable
samplers of Ellington's work, you have to be ready to answer the
Picasso question: Which Ellington?
</P>
<P>
   For Ellington's early period, the best available introduction is
``The Okeh Ellington'' (Columbia C2K 46177), a two-disk set of
recordings from 1927 to 1930. There's no way to maximize how lovely
this inventive, witty music is, with its tang and balance and
delicately shaped soloists' roles; for its time, there's also a
shocking intimacy in the recordings.
</P>
<P>
   They begin with ``East St. Louis Toodle-oo,'' run through his
residency at the Cotton Club, the most important long engagement
any jazz peformer ever had, and end with ``Rockin' in Rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   While the big labels let their Ellington stock disappear and
reappear, you can always turn to a few volumes within the
chronological series on Classics, a French label which works
through the work of jazz performers year by year. ``Duke Ellington
1929'' (Classics 569) is particularly good, including the wonderful
``The Dicty Glide,'' a cheerful stomp that somehow has eluded the
canonizers of his early work. ``1935-1936'' (Classics 659) includes
``Reminiscing in Tempo,'' a 12-minute piece with a slow gait and an
unearthly beauty, originally recorded over four 78 sides.
</P>
<P>
   Though his late-30s period offered both popular songs and
groundbreaking composition, the Ellington of the early 40s is
particularly easy to anthologize because with a great new band,
Ellington made several dozen three-minute masterpieces during a
concentrated span for RCA; they feel natural grouped together.
</P>
<P>
   One mid-size package is indispensable: ``The
Blanton-Webster-Band'' (RCA/Bluebird 5659-2-RB), a three-disk set
that contains the best of the best from 1940-1942, including ``Ko
Ko,'' ``Jack the Bear,'' ``Main Stem'' and 63 others. A cheaper
place to start is ``Sophisticated Lady'' (RCA 09026-68516-2), a
single-disk of 1940s material including ``Concerto for Cootie,''
``Chelsea Bridge,'' ``Solitude'' and other famous grade-A pieces.
</P>
<P>
   For the next decade try ``Ellington Uptown'' (Columbia CK 40836)
from 1952, when Ellington had something to prove after assembling a
new band. It takes well-known works like `` `A' Train'' and ``The
Mooch'' and turns them into multipartite kaleidoscopes; it also
includes the studio version of his ``Harlem Suite.''
</P>
<P>
   The 60s and 70s have not been anthologized into
consumer-friendly packages, but for late Ellingtonia, you can't do
much better than ``... And His Mother Called Him Bill'' (RCA
6287-2-RB), a 1967 tribute to his co-composer, Billy Strayhorn,
recorded three months after Strayhorn's death.
</P>
<P>
   The band slugs out powerful, loose-limbed versions of
Strayhorn's songs, and the recording has a slightly blaring,
demo-like feel that heightens the intensity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SMALL GROUPS AND SOLO Ellington's piano playing had a massive
sound, reach and soul, and I prefer it over the work of many others
whose reputations rest on speed and chord substitutions. There's a
small canon of records spotlighting his playing, and the best place
to start is ``Piano Reflections'' (Capitol CDP 7 92863-2), mostly a
trio album, from 1953; it's got a subdued, wintry, cheery air.
``Money Jungle'' (Blue Note/Capitol B21Y46398), by contrast, is one
of the strangest jazz records ever made, a contentious 1962 one-off
session with Charles Mingus and Max Roach; Mingus goads Duke, Duke
fights back and Roach's skittering patterns try to tie it together.
``The Pianist'' (Fantasy OJCCD-717-2), a relaxed late-period
document, offers a valuable shot of Ellington with a great
late-period rhythm section, the bassist John Lamb and the drummer
Sam Woodyard. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   LIVE AND LOOSENED DUKE Too few documents like ``Fargo, North
Dakota, Nov. 7, 1940'' (Vintage Jazz Classics VJC-1019/20-2) exist:
it's not a buttoned-up ``concert'' recording, like the Carnegie
Hall recordings from the later 40s, but a snapshot of the Ellington
band playing a few sets at a dance. The numbers are kept short, the
tempos brisk. ``Cornell University: Second Set,'' from 1948
(Musicmasters/BMG 01612-65162-2) is a more collected, measured
performance, including a cameo by the saxophonist Ben Webster.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Newport,'' the 1956 record that re-established Ellington's
popular reputation, has gone out of print. (A revamped version of
that entire performance will be issued on Columbia in April.) But
instead there is ``Live at Newport 1958'' (Columbia Legacy C2K
53584), a double-disk set of Ellington's complete festival
appearance from that year; it includes Gerry Mulligan performing a
baritone-saxophone duet with Harry Carney and Mahalia Jackson's
blissful performance of ``Come Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   SUITES Ellington thought in large quantities; he lived in the
company of a 14-man band for a good part of his life, and so his
grand themes more often dealt with ethnicities, religions and
countries than the individual spirit. On the three-disk set
``Black, Brown and Beige'' (RCA/Bluebird 6641-2-RB), made of
material recorded from 1944-46, you'll find two important suites:
the one in the title, the famous ``tone-parallel to the history of
the Negro in America'' recorded in the studio nearly two years
after it made its debut at Carnegie Hall; and the ``Perfume
Suite,'' the first suite-length collaboration of Ellington with
Billy Strayhorn.
</P>
<P>
   A far greater example of that collaboration resulted in ``The
Far East Suite _ Special Mix,'' (RCA/Bluebird 66551-2), a work that
grew out of a State Department tour to Turkey, India and the Middle
East; the music, recorded in 1966 and written with hints of Eastern
tonality, is some of the best big-band work ever made after the
big-band era.
</P>
<P>
   Those interested in a different musical idea of Ellington _ a
far cry from the indefatigable popularizer who played ``Satin
Doll'' in cities around the world _ should look to ``The
Afro-Eurasian Eclipse: A Suite in Eight Parts'' (Fantasy
OJCCD-645-2). Using sketchier tunes, most of them based mainly on
rhythm, the suite dabbles in ideas of soul and rock and African
music filtered through his own imagination. It's a radically
percussive record, unafraid to test the limits of what jazz
audiences might be ready for, and it includes a few lengthy,
stunning tenor-saxophone solos by Harold Ashby.
</P>
<P>
   Though it has its detractors I still like the 1968 ``Second
Sacred Concert'' (Fantasy PCD-24045-2) for its stirring opening and
closing passages and for its warm depths; it was music that
obsessed Ellington in his late years. For sheer versatility,
however, try ``The River'' on ``The Private Collection _ Vol. 5''
(Saja/Atlantic 7 91045-2). Written in 1970 for the American Ballet
Theater, it keeps falling outside the realm of the expected; it
begins with a piece of floating piano minimalism, runs through
serene flute-led melodies, enters a passage with vibraphones,
kettle drums and sweet-and-sour harmonies that could be mistaken
for Frank Zappa at about the same period, and then gets to
blues-based swinging.
</P>
<P>
   But ``New Orleans Suite'' (Atlantic 01580), Ellington's last
masterpiece, is an indisputable success, full of brilliant
``portraits'' of New Orleans figures like Louis Armstrong, Sidney
Bechet and the bassist Wellman Braud. The jazz that Ellington
arrived at late in life was a highly theatrical music, and it
seemed infinitely expandable, stretching continuity from juke-joint
organ music to icy, tone-clashing delicacy; this disk's profound
pleasures prove he was absolutely the most wide-ranging jazz
composer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 0212EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 02:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0709 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEORGE-LANE-THEATER-A     01-13 1279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGE-LANE-THEATER-ART-2TAKES-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYBODY NEEDS HIM; NOT EVERYBODY LIKES HIM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 17)  
 (af)  
 By ROBIN POGREBIN  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Producers are not going to tell you what they really think of
George P. Lane: that they dislike him, that they believe he is too
demanding, that they dread his phone calls. That's because Lane
represents just about every hot young playwright and director in
the theater business these days, not to mention a crop of blue-chip
actors. So producers need him. They basically can't live without
him.
</P>
<P>
   Lane's clients, however, are happy to talk about him _ how loyal
he is, how passionate about the theater. And yet, though many count
themselves as friends, they describe him as difficult to fathom.
``All his clients spend a lot of time trying to figure him out,''
said the playwright Warren Leight. ``George's clients have their
own support group. He's very content to be like Oz.''
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in between these extremes lies the truth about this
tall, lean 46-year-old senior vice president at the William Morris
talent and literary agency who some liken to the next Sam Cohn, the
legendary theatrical agent at ICM. In the nine years since he took
over his agency's theater department, Lane has cornered the market
on a lot of bold-face names.
</P>
<P>
   ``He represents half the people in the industry,'' said Todd
Haimes, the artistic director of both the Roundabout Theater
Company and Livent Inc. ``He's fiercely supportive and protective
of his writers and directors and will fight to the death for them.
And as much as that can be difficult from a producer's standpoint,
it probably is pleasing to many clients.''
</P>
<P>
   Even producers who take issue with Lane's approach concede he
must be doing something right. ``He drives a hard bargain, but
that's what he's there for,'' said David Richenthal, a Broadway
producer. ``Though I've heard stories from other people, my
experience has been one of great professionalism.''
</P>
<P>
   James M. Nederlander, chairman of the Nederlander theater
organization, spoke to the heart of the issue of producers versus
creators: ``They all demand too much. It's a question of
negotiating something out.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes people in the theater business _ who refused to be
quoted _ roll their eyes about Lane is, they say, his adversarial
style, his abrasive telephone manner and that he drives too hard a
bargain with small nonprofit theaters that may have trouble
affording his terms.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are producers who say they actually like him, or have
learned to like him. ``He's very abrupt _ he will say goodbye when
you're in the middle of a sentence _ he'll hang up on you,'' said
Fran Weissler, who with her husband, Barry, has produced a number
of Broadway shows, including the current ``Chicago.'' ``But over a
period of years, I have come to not only respect but like him. I
used to tremble if I had to call him. No more.''
</P>
<P>
   Well aware of Lane's reputation, his clients say they are
grateful that he fights for them. ``To be an agent in the theater
now,'' said one, the playwright Jon Robin Baitz, ``you have to
preside over a slightly dwindling Broadway and its corporatization,
at the same time encouraging playwrights to remain playwrights. It
seems to me that George is fierce on behalf of artists who might
not be able to fend for themselves in what's now an even more
mercantile and frightening world.''
</P>
<P>
   Lane fights with a shield of glacial calm. Aside from a few
pictures of his 4-year-old twin son and daughter in his meticulous
office, there is little that conveys his personality. One
paperweight, two pieces of green sea glass and two shells were the
only clues during a visit some weeks ago. Lane said he had
straightened up, and that ``it never looks like this.''
</P>
<P>
   On first meeting, he comes across as stiffly formal and opaque,
talking in clinical terms about having a ``quantitative and
qualitative commitment to theater'' and insisting rather woodenly,
``I love theater; I love my entertainment live and with content.''
And he can quickly sing the praises of his agency in phrases worthy
of a press release: ``What the Morris office has is great
leadership, and from education there is growth, and from growth
there is progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of this might be deliberate on Lane's part. Until now _
except in a Variety special issue commemorating William Morris's
100th anniversary _ he had not been the subject of an article, and
he confessed to being nervous.
</P>
<P>
   But hints of his micromanaging style are confirmed by his
exactly planned schedule. Even leisure gets penciled in. Monday
through Friday evenings: Attend theater. Saturday: Play with kids.
Saturday night: Have dinner with wife (Suna Senman, a social worker
who is now a full-time mother). Sunday: Play with kids. Sunday
night: Read plays and screenplays until 3 or 4 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Lane's work, his clients say happily, is his life, and he is
known for traveling great distances to see their endeavors, showing
up at every opening night. In tracking his clients over last
summer, for example, Lane traveled to Los Angeles to see Richard
Greenberg's new play, ``Hurrah at Last,'' which will be presented
by the Roundabout Theater Company in New York this spring; to
London to see Edward Albee's latest work, ``The Play About the
Baby,'' expected on Broadway in the fall, and to Poughkeepsie,
N.Y., for a workshop of John Patrick Shanley's new play,
``Cellini,'' which will get a full production sometime this year.
</P>
<P>
   He also made several trips to the Williamstown Theater Festival
in Massachusetts to see A.R. Gurney's ``Far East,'' directed by
Daniel Sullivan (a client) and now at the Mitzi E. Newhouse Theater
at Lincoln Center; Scott Ellis's production of ``The Rainmaker,''
scheduled to come to Broadway in the fall; Jonathan Marc Sherman's
play ``Evolution,'' and David Rabe's new work, ``Corner,'' also
directed by Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   (Lane worked out the contract for Ellis when he directed the
Roundabout Theater Company production of the musical ``She Loves
Me'' in 1993. The Roundabout, in an ironic salute to the tough
bargaining involved, put Lane's name on the marquee for several
days.)
</P>
<P>
   If he isn't at the theater or having lunch at Remi near his
Manhattan office, Lane is on the telephone, putting projects
together. He calls producers, directors, publicists and Hollywood
executives to alert them to promising scripts.
</P>
<P>
   While some of this is typical agent stuff _ he gets a standard
10 percent commission _ most important, his clients say, is the
fact that he has stuck by them in the lean years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Writers go through periods where they get into terrible
trouble with themselves,'' said Baitz, who has been a client since
1985. ``And he never backs away from that _ never backs away from
the awful, infectious loneliness and free-floating failure that
just goes with the territory. When I retreat into a long, long
period of quiet work without coming up for air and I isolate
myself, it's sort of comforting to know that George Lane checks in
a lot, he doesn't forget.''
</P>
<P>
   Leight said he was amazed that Lane hadn't given up on him over
the last 14 years. ``For no reason that I can imagine, he stuck it
out,'' said Leight, whose well-received play, ``Side Man,'' has
moved to Broadway from Off Broadway. ``He was awfully patient. He
would go from an Albee opening at Lincoln Center to the basement of
the West Bank Cafe to see my stupid one act.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Some can just knock it out and some have to lock themselves in
a room and get to a fever pitch of self-loathing before they turn
in a first draft,'' Leight said. ``He understands that each
writer's process is screwed up in its own way.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Lane said, when he enters a negotiation he is
thinking less about individual contract provisions and more about a
client's long-term plans. ``My clients and I share a vision for
what's going to happen with their work beyond any one project,'' he
said. ``I'm not certain that that philosophy doesn't make some
producers uncomfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he is a stickler about contracts for projects immediately
at hand. While, for example, producers expect a 90-day period of
exclusivity from the date a play is to close, within which they
have the option to extend a production, Lane gives them 15 days or
less. ``I think that's a generous period of time to enter into an
option for future rights,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While many producers like to option a play for three years, Lane
said he granted options for three three-month periods or two
six-month periods. He is such a staunch supporter of the Dramatists
Guild that he asked to be photographed at their offices on
Broadway. The guild, he said, ``provides for authors to license
their rights, as opposed to the Writers Guild, which provides for
authors to sell their rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never lose ownership of your work,'' he added. ``Isn't that
what's in the best interest of the writer?''
</P>
<P>
   Among the performers who are clients are Alec Baldwin, Cherry
Jones, Cynthia Nixon, William Hurt, Vanessa Williams and John
Leguizamo. When Leguizamo was in San Francisco with his solo show
``Freak,'' Lane said he flew there with a squadron of William
Morris agents to figure out how to move the production to Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   When Kevin Spacey wanted to do ``The Iceman Cometh'' in London,
Lane said he helped make it happen because the Morris agency also
represents the estate of the author, Eugene O'Neill. Spacey will be
repeating his acclaimed performance when the play begins previews
in March on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a client wants in an agent,'' Lane said, ``is someone who
can understand his work, put him together with someone who can
execute his vision, and someone who can execute his deals.''
</P>
<P>
   He emphasized how his division and the others at William Morris
worked closely together, and Arnold Rifkin, the agency's president,
said this kind of coordination was essential. ``Our business has
become so vast, so technological, it's not just about sitting in
the Russian Tea Room and making a deal,'' Rifkin said.
</P>
<P>
   It was Lane's passion for the theater that Baldwin said
attracted him to William Morris: ``Other agencies I've been with _
they might not dissuade you from doing theater but they're
certainly not going to persuade you to (italics)do(end italics)
theater. They look at the theater as something that they want me to
go and get out of my system _ `Go do that' _ like it's a gambling
habit you have.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor, his clients say, does Lane try to ride their coattails to
fame. ``You always have the sense with him that the writers aren't
extensions of his ego,'' Baitz said. ``Each one of them is a little
country. He represents these countries. They're not jewels for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   George Powell Lane was born a foundling in St. Vincent's
Hospital, class of 1952. He spent the first four years of his
childhood in Brooklyn and the rest on Long Island in Garden City.
His adoptive parents died when he was a teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   Lane says he knew he wanted to be in entertainment from the time
he organized dances as social chairman for his fraternity at Hobart
&AMP; William Smith Colleges in Geneva, N.Y. After working for Gov.
Hugh Carey's campaign in New York, he landed at William Morris in
1976 with the classic job: mailroom clerk. Four years later, he was
an agent. His first client: Jack Hofsiss, who directed ``The
Elephant Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Lane still describes the first reading of a play and the first
preview as the two most exciting nights in the theater. And he says
he always ends one week looking forward to the next. ``So many
people can't sleep on Sunday nights because they're afraid to go to
work on Monday,'' he said. ``I can't wait.''
</P>
<P>
   One criticism of him is that he negotiates too hard for his
clients, at times to their own detriment. ``It's something you hear
people say,'' said Greenberg, the playwright, ``but nothing has
ever fallen through because of his tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the negotiating process is something that most would
rather have no part of. ``I can't ask for anything on my own
behalf,'' Baitz said. ``I can barely get coffee for myself without
feeling incredibly guilty about it, and I don't think I'm alone in
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to learn the point system, nor do I particularly
want to know how to handle some of the more rabid producers in the
world _ I don't want to learn that skill. I want to muddle through
a few plays and occasionally be sort of reasonably paid to try and
write a movie, and George makes that life style choice not
impossible to maintain.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 0214EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
