r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-WAY-1000&AMP;ADD-     01-13 1629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-WAY-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 THE WAY OF THE WORLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Dawn of Civilizations to the the 21st Century.
</P>
<P>
   By David Fromkin.
</P>
<P>
   253 pp. New York: Alfred A. Knopf. $25.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; LIFE, THE UNIVERSE AND EVERYTHING
</P>
<P>
   BY WILLIAM R. EVERDELL
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MANY historians nowadays write with more concern for a
nonprofessional audience than they did 40 years ago, but even so
relatively few of their books unabashedly invite nonhistorians to
enjoy and profit from them. One such is a tour de force called ``A
Peace to End All Peace'' (1989), about the diplomatic origins of
the modern Middle East. The author, David Fromkin, is a professor
of international relations, a branch of political science, and like
many in political science -- including Machiavelli himself among
its long-ago founders -- he is an unapologetic practitioner of his
field's parent discipline, history.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Way of the World,'' however, is quite a different project.
It began, Fromkin writes, when he was asked by a Wall Street hedge
fund manager over lunch, ``Can you tell the story of humanity in
the universe and make it whole?'' He answered that yes, he thought
he could, and began to produce this universal history in 222 pages
of text. Two hundred and twenty-two pages for everything? A
``History of the World in 300 Pages'' was written by Rene Sedillot
50 years ago, but the extra 78 pages have not made it any easier to
find today. Sir Walter Raleigh wrote ``an universall Historie'' to
while away prison time, but it went to more than one volume;
Puritans took it as an indispensable supplement to the sacred
history of the Bible, but few people consult it now. In a sense the
whole philosophy of Hegel is a universal history, as is a 50-page
reply to it, Marx and Engels's ``Communist Manifesto,'' but both
have lost their appeal. Toynbee's 10-volume ``Study of History''
has aged faster. William H. McNeill's still more recent ``Rise of
the West'' was only one volume but it was more than 1,000 pages.
Fromkin himself acknowledges only one model, the 1920 ``Outline of
History'' by H. G. Wells (and makes no mention of the book Wells
was replying to, Spengler's 1918 ``Decline of the West'').
</P>
<P>
   Fromkin distinguishes eight stages in universal history, most of
them hinging on events historians of many stripes can agree on as
the most significant in the history of humankind: the emergence of
the hominid line, apes with brains, in prehistoric Africa
(``Becoming Human''); the discovery of agriculture and the creation
of the first cities -- settlements whose residents were not all
farmers (``Inventing Civilization''); the sudden rise of
universalizing religious and moral systems all over civilized
Eurasia in the sixth century B.C. (``Developing a Conscience'');
the birth of the idea of world civilization with the empires of
ancient Eurasia (``Seeking a Lasting Peace''); the rise of
rationalism and empirical science (``Achieving Rationality''); the
irreversible encounter, after the 15th century, between human
societies in Eurasia and Africa and those in the Americas
(``Uniting the Planet''); the industrial modernization that began
in the 18th century (``Releasing Nature's Energies''); and finally
the steady movement toward democratic government centered in the
19th century and the unsteady movement toward decolonization and
world law in the 20th (``Ruling Ourselves'').
</P>
<P>
   This is of course a Western view, and it is a progressive one.
Fromkin is convinced, as against many post-moderns, that things
have got better for us humans since the Upper Paleolithic. Though
he easily imagines disasters that can interrupt or reverse the
long-term trends he describes, he sees no compelling argument for
turning back. In four concluding chapters, he attempts to
extrapolate a future, which he admits is not easy -- a little like
trying to predict global warming from one very warm November. He
expects further difficulties with population and environment; he
looks forward to the colonization of other planets, and he sees the
greatest immediate challenge as the tension between the rising need
for world law and the rising drive toward cultural
self-determination.
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder that such a book, a universal history in short
compass, is one of the great literary challenges. Think of all
those human lives lived since Australopithecus walked in Laetoli
three and a half million years ago, or even in the five and a half
thousand since prehistory ended in ancient Sumer (or was it Egypt?)
with the invention of writing. Those billions of lives, multiplied
by their experience, are the raw stuff of history, and yet the
history of a single family could easily fill a university library.
The art is in deciding how to cut, whom to leave out and why, all
the while facing the overwhelming odds that truth will be left on
the cutting room floor. ``Telling one story necessarily means not
telling another,'' Fromkin writes, and he has a pretty good idea of
what he has bitten off. Not only are you biased to begin with
toward your own culture, its past and its valuations of other
cultures; you are biased toward your own career as a historian,
which will necessarily have been concerned with a much narrower
slice. ``Life is a story that each of us tells to his or her self;
and it therefore is a tale told by an unreliable narrator,''
Fromkin admits. And finally, since no one can know enough to write
universal history alone, you will inevitably be indebted to other
writers and researchers. How will you find the space you need to
credit them?
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the problem of presentation. It is rarely new
discoveries that demand to be recounted in a universal history, and
as Pope observed, nothing needs to be so well expressed as that
which oft was thought. With enough left out of even ordinary
histories to make history elliptical by nature, universal history
has so much ellipsis that the only way to deal with it is to use a
style as elevated and a language as allusive and referential as the
ones we use for poetry. Fromkin can be allusive, as when he
disposes of World War II in a single daring sentence: ``The war
resumed in 1939-1945 and Germany lost again.'' He can often be
lapidary, too, as in ``Today's world is the world that America
wanted, but it is not a world that America made.'' This makes it
all the more clear when he falls short, as in ``Looking back, what
happened in modern history was that a millennium ago, Europe began
to develop a distinctive mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-WAY-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: distinctive mentality.'') &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fromkin deserves considerable credit for skirting or resisting
his guild interests. He spends only a few paragraphs rehearsing the
fruits of his own research on the modern Middle East. His use of
other historians' work is wise and acknowledged with unobtrusive
generosity, and only once or twice (for example on our knowledge of
Harappan and Mesoamerican writing) does he accept a tendentious or
obsolete source. If he is perhaps too insistently politically
incorrect, giving the Greeks too much credit for empirical
rationality, Europeans too much credit for democracy and Americans
too much for individualism, if he forgives dominant cultures more
than he should for imperialism, slavery, proletarian misery and
environmental destruction, he credits no culture for acting against
self-interest. This book might easily serve as a supplementary
textbook in secondary schools, especially with the addition of a
few pictures and time lines. Schoolchildren love to contemplate the
big picture, from both the moral and the long-term historical
points of view. There are hardly any textbooks in the prehistory
and ancient history of our planet for young people, probably
because of that silent struggle for power in local school
districts. A surprisingly large faction would be outraged if
children were taught that dinosaurs vanished from the earth some 60
million years before the first hominids walked upright on it. A
similarly large faction would be steamed if the approximate date
that cities first arose in Mesopotamia (4000 B.C.) were pre-empted
as the date of God's creation of the cosmos. The result is a
tremendous confusion about the definitions of terms and the
importance of events in what Fromkin rightly calls the unique and
therefore epic story of how we got here, and what it all means, if
anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Way of the World'' is a title famously used by the risque
Restoration playwright William Congreve. Perhaps Fromkin's idea was
to avoid freighting his book with the unmediated moral seriousness
universal history has traditionally demanded. More likely it was to
prefigure his central narrative, which is that the meaning of human
history is not divine but natural, and his central moral, which is
that humans must take responsibility even for the natural and make
their own history. The responsibility becomes heavier and heavier
as our numbers become greater and greater, our cultures less and
less various and our choices fewer and fewer. History is now
universal whether we like it or not. As Fromkin writes, in one of
his most lapidary pronouncements: ``Now we're all in the same boat.
It may be a seaworthy boat; but it would be less worrisome if there
were more than one.''
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   William R. Everdell is the author of ``The First Moderns.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
