<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 06:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0869 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-TRUTH-NYTSF     01-13 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-TRUTH-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 TRUTH
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four Stories I Am Finally Old Enough to Tell.
</P>
<P>
   By Ellen Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   221 pp. Chapel Hill, N.C.: Algonquin. $18.95.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; BEYOND FICTION
</P>
<P>
   BY LAURA JAMISON
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Southern writer Ellen Douglas (the pen name of Josephine
Haxton), now 77 years old, began publishing fiction 37 years ago
under a pseudonym in order to protect the privacy of two aunts who
figured prominently in her first novel. After eight works of
fiction, including ``Apostles of Light,'' ``The Rock Cried Out''
and ``A Lifetime Burning,'' Douglas offers her first nonfiction
book, whose title, ``Truth: Four Stories I Am Finally Old Enough to
Tell,'' suggests that she at long last possesses the wisdom, and
perhaps the freedom, to cast off the veil of fiction to write as
plainly as she'd like.
</P>
<P>
   These four ``stories'' are not so much dishy revelations as they
are intrepid inquiries as to how one approximates the truth. A
writer of considerable gifts and intelligence, Douglas takes up
tales that have long obsessed her, and in some cases provided
material for her fiction -- an illicit lifelong romance, the
execution of local slaves, a family suicide -- wondering if she can
write about them factually. ``Although I call up these memories,
although they are my own, I have reservations,'' she writes. ``I
know that I put words in the mouths of people who did not speak
them. I imagine scenes at which I was not present. I know that this
is my world and no one else's -- my stories, my history. Or myth,
perhaps, one among the myths that form the lives of families and
sometimes of larger worlds.''
</P>
<P>
   The most accessible piece is ``Grant,'' in which her husband's
uncle comes to die in her house. His nurse, a luminously beautiful
black woman named Rosalie, becomes acquainted with him in ways
Douglas cannot or will not; drawn together by Bible study and
impending death, a tender friendship forms. ``There is one more
thing about Rosalie and Grant,'' she writes. ``I had thought I
could leave it out but I find that I can't.'' One day after Grant
was entirely bedridden and perhaps morphine-addled, Rosalie, in
tears, said to Douglas: ``He wants me to touch him.'' Leaving this
out would have been a kindness to Grant's memory, Douglas knows,
but not to the story.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas's other meditations are far less linear, more overtly
about the inadequacies of memory and facts. ``Julia and Nellie'' is
a labyrinthine piece about her grandmother Nellie's friend Julia
and a distant cousin Dunny, who lived ``in sin'' for most of their
lives. The more details Douglas uncovers, the more oblique their
tale becomes. ``As I gather the fragments of this story, I have a
choice: I could invent -- I am a novelist, after all.'' Then,
testing out a pleasing scenario, she balks: ``But this is fiction
-- romantic nonsense.'' Likewise, when Douglas writes about
Hampton, her grandmother's longtime chauffeur, she must
acknowledge, ``Maybe there are so many things going on in every
life that it's not possible to do more than set down what one knows
and let it go at that.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``On Second Creek,'' Douglas charts her research on a local
incident in which slaves were tortured and executed ostensibly for
plotting an uprising (they most likely never did this); the
frustrating gaps in documentation bring to mind the story of her
grandfather's suicide, which she did not discover until she was in
her 60's and of which his own wife remained ignorant until her
death. ``It is impossible to make sense out of stories that purport
to be true. Something is always missing,'' she writes. ``All these
silences, all these unfinished tales, these lacunae in the
evidence, are intolerable to me.'' And yet, Douglas marches
fearlessly through them, surely getting closer to truth than most
because she so boldly acknowledges its elusiveness.
</P>
<P>
   A sly exchange between Douglas and a friend of her father's
named Gold Smith Sr. captures the essence of this curious, lovely
book. Smith says: '' 'In your book, that other book, you turned
your grandpa into a great-great aunt. You told a whole nother story
about her and her suicide -- made it O.K. for her to kill herself.
How come you to do that?'
</P>
<P>
   '' 'You know,' I say. 'You of all people know how come me to do
that.'
</P>
<P>
   '' 'Hmmm,' he says. ' 'Twas for your convenience I reckon.'
</P>
<P>
   '' 'I reckon,' I said. 'For the convenience of the story. For
the story.' ''
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Laura Jamison is a freelance writer living in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
