<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 06:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0876 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-EARTH-NYTSF     01-13 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-EARTH-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 EARTH ODYSSEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Search of Our Environmental Future.
</P>
<P>
   By Mark Hertsgaard.
</P>
<P>
   372 pp. New York: Broadway Books. $26.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; A DIRTY SHAME
</P>
<P>
   BY KEITH SCHNEIDER
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Mark Hertsgaard'S reputation as an astute journalist was made in
the 1980's when as a magazine and book writer he explored politics,
the press and pop culture. His best-known work, ``On Bended Knee:
The Press and the Reagan Presidency'' (1988), described the way the
Reagan White House deployed raw power and conventional wisdom to
intimidate Washington's television newsrooms. In the 1990's, his
attention turned to the even more formidable: the ecological fate
of the earth. Hertsgaard embarked upon a seven-year global tour to
investigate the environmental future. The journey spanned four
continents, 19 countries and hundreds of interviews. Hertsgaard
spoke with Vaclav Havel in Prague, he talked with industrial
workers in soot-choked China and retraced Winston Churchill's steps
in North Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Hertsgaard's central question in 1991 was ``whether the human
species would survive the next hundred years.'' By the time he
returned in the late 1990's to write in a cabin amid a majestic
grove of California sequoias, he was convinced the answer was yes.
But he finds few other reasons to be optimistic: The pace of global
population growth, rampant air and water pollution in the
developing world and the weakening resolve of the United States to
lead the environmental revolution it fostered spell big trouble for
the quality of human existence.
</P>
<P>
   This, of course, is hardly a novel message. But Hertsgaard is
after something different from the annual compendium of trends in
the planet's failing health put out by Lester R. Brown's Worldwatch
Institute, or the eloquent assessment, in Bill McKibben's ``End of
Nature,'' of the risks to the environment and the economy posed by
global climate change. Hertsgaard's focus is the human dimension to
global ecological decline, and in ``Earth Odyssey,'' he displays an
authentic talent for storytelling. By taking care to explain the
technical, by including just enough of himself and by giving full
breath to select characters, he has transformed a daunting subject
into a stirring contribution to the growing literature on the
global environment.
</P>
<P>
   The path Hertsgaard takes around the world is full of surprises
and unexplored places. Just as important, he does not berate or
moralize. His tone is generally that of an interested and
accomplished reporter seeking to understand communities and
assemble a foundation of facts from which to draw conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   The chapters on China are especially satisfying. In Chongqing, a
southwestern industrial city, Hertsgaard investigates a chlorine
plant that officials say is closed, but continues to operate and
pour a toxic waterfall of raw chlorine and other chemicals directly
into the Jialing River, a drinking water source for millions of
people. But this was hardly the worst pollution he saw there.
</P>
<P>
   Though residents of China's cities rarely see blue sky because
of air pollution caused by burning coal, and rivers are so choked
by raw sewage and chemical wastes that fish cannot survive, China's
1.2 billion people are still motivated by one concern. They want to
make enough money to escape poverty, joblessness and cramped living
conditions that Americans would never tolerate. Western
environmental concerns seem so inconsequential as to be almost
laughable. ``You may complain about our contributions to global
warming or the ozone hole,'' Hertsgaard is told. ``But how much
pollution we make, how many trees we cut or dams we build is
nobody's business but ours.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Social forces have been set in motion that will not be
contained,'' Hertsgaard writes. ``Electricity, telephones, running
water -- once humans experience these things, they want more of
them, no matter the ecological cost. As well they might. It is easy
for outsiders to warn against the long-term costs of damming
Africa's rivers, ruining its scenery, or destroying its woodlands,
but it is akin to a glutton admonishing a beggar on the evil of
carbohydrates -- he lacks a certain moral authority.''
</P>
<P>
   Where ``Earth Odyssey'' falters is its recommendations.
Hertsgaard's survey of the potential fixes for a world being
disfigured by the passion for wealth -- technology improvements,
more efficiently using resources, minimizing waste, even shifting
taxes to penalize pollution -- is so bogged down in statistics and
theory that it's like breathing through a dishrag. Hertsgaard could
have remedied this problem by focusing more intensely on the
solution he knows the most about: politics and government.
</P>
<P>
   It's been little more than a generation since the United States
invented and enacted the program that cleaned the air, cleared the
water and safeguarded millions of acres of wild lands. Presidents
of both parties and bipartisan Congressional action provided the
political foundation for visionary people to do something great.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960's, for example, Stewart L. Udall, the Secretary of
the Interior during eight years of the Kennedy and Johnson
Administrations, established four national parks, six national
monuments, nine national recreation areas, 20 national historic
sites and nine national lakeshores and seashores. Udall also wrote
the 1964 Wilderness Act, which preserved tens of millions of acres
of wild land, and helped to gain passage of the 1968 Wild and
Scenic Rivers Act. He championed Rachel Carson's warning about
toxic chemicals and set the stage for the pioneering environmental
legislation of the 1970's.
</P>
<P>
   The question Hertsgaard needed to address is why Washington
turned meek. It's not enough to spend pages criticizing Vice
President Al Gore for failing to act on a vow to make the
environment the ``central organizing principle'' of governance --
the conclusion of Gore's best-selling book ``The Earth in the
Balance'' (1992). Gore works in an economic and historic context
that has shrunk the political comfort zone for courageous policy
making. Business owners, lawmakers, the press and ultimately voters
are apparently satisfied with mediocre governing. Until the
political market for inspired ideas and passionate leadership
reawakens in the United States, what Hertsgaard calls ``the
material striving of the entire human family'' will never be
reconciled with the carrying capacity of the planet's environment.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Keith Schneider is executive director of the Michigan Land Use
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
