<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 06:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0877 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-PAPERBACKS-NY     01-13 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-PAPERBACKS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BY SCOTT VEALE &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   VIRGIL THOMSON: COMPOSER ON THE AISLE
</P>
<P>
   By Anthony Tommasini.
</P>
<P>
   Norton, $18 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   A music critic for The New York Times portrays Thomson as both a
vivacious Midwesterner affected by the hymns and band concerts of
his childhood, and a man capable of baffling cruelty. In 1997 our
reviewer, Nicholas Fox Weber, said this biography ``evokes the
composer's critical ear and describes his music with words that
bring us right into the concert hall.''
</P>
<P>
   CHARMING BILLY
</P>
<P>
   By Alice McDermott.
</P>
<P>
   Delta, $12.95 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   In a Bronx bar where the friends and family of a dreamy,
hard-drinking Irish-American named Billy Lynch gather after his
funeral, a corrosive 40-year-old lie about a woman tragically lost
and presumed dead is gradually unraveled. This novel, which won a
National Book Award in 1998, is about the power of romantic
mythmaking and the way a person's life can be shaped by the
expectations of others. Last year in the Book Review, Alida Becker
called it an ``eloquent and unsettling'' tale that ``like its title
character . . . works on our sympathies with an insistent sadness
and an ingratiating charm.'' The same publisher has reissued
McDermott's earlier novels, including That Night ($12.95), which
centers on a battle that breaks out in a Long Island suburb when
the parents of a pregnant teen-ager try to keep her from her
hoodlum boyfriend. In 1987 our reviewer, David Leavitt, admired the
``almost baroque richness of McDermott's sentences, the
intellectual complexity of her moral vision and the explicit
emotion of her voice.'' In A Bigamist's Daughter ($12.95), a young
woman working at a vanity press becomes involved with a novelist
whose work-in-progress about a bigamist stirs troubling memories of
her own elusive father. In 1982 in these pages, Anne Tyler said
``McDermott . . . writes with assurance and skill, and she has
created a fascinatingly prismatic story.''
</P>
<P>
   A HISTORY OF DOGS IN THE EARLY AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   By Marion Schwartz. Selected drawings by Susan Hochgraf.
</P>
<P>
   Yale University, $15. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A physical anthropologist reveals how man's best friend was many
things to many peoples before the Europeans arrived in the Americas
in the 1500's. In some places dogs were revered as deities, in
others eaten as dinner. In 1997 our reviewer, Timothy Foote, called
this ``a fascinating, scholarly mishmash, with extraordinary
drawings.'' Eminent Dogs, Dangerous Men, by Donald McCaig (Lyons,
$14.95), chronicles the author's difficult search through Scotland
for the perfect border collie to herd sheep on his Virginia farm.
This ``lively travelogue-history'' is ``rich in dog lore and by no
means poor as a study of human behavior,'' Christopher
Lehmann-Haupt wrote in The Times in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   BURDEN OF DESIRE
</P>
<P>
   By Robert MacNeil.
</P>
<P>
   Harvest/Harcourt Brace, $14. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   After a French freighter explodes and destroys part of Halifax,
Nova Scotia, in 1917, a clergyman stumbles onto a woman's
passionate diary, falls in love with its author and enlists a
friend to help track her down. In 1992 our reviewer, Susan Fromberg
Schaeffer, called this ``a novel filled with riches and alight with
understanding of the small events that lead to the huge upheavals
in life.''
</P>
<P>
   TRAPPED IN THE NET:
</P>
<P>
   The Unanticipated Consequences of Computerization
</P>
<P>
   By Gene I. Rochlin.
</P>
<P>
   Princeton University, $17.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Focusing on the current -- and expected -- effects of computers
and networking on everything from air travel to the financial
markets, the author argues that automation is making it nearly
impossible for people to make modest mistakes and learn from them.
In 1997 in these pages, Lawrence Hunter called this ``an insightful
and painstakingly documented book.'' Crystal Fire: The Invention of
the Transistor and the Birth of the Information Age, by Michael
Riordan and Lillian Hoddeson (Norton, $15), traces the careers of
three American physicists whose work paved the way for today's
microprocessor chips. ``Riordan and Hoddeson reconstruct the birth
of the transistor with considerable aplomb,'' John Durant wrote
here last year.
</P>
<P>
   FELIX IN THE UNDERWORLD
</P>
<P>
   By John Mortimer.
</P>
<P>
   Penguin, $12.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This British author's 27th book is a comic romp about a feckless
novelist who gets caught up in paternity-suit blackmail and murder
during a nightmarish book tour. In 1997 in the Book Review,
Christopher Buckley called this a ``witty work, reminiscent of
other late-period novels like Kingsley Amis's 'Russian Girl' and
Peter De Vries's 'Peckham's Marbles.' ''
</P>
<P>
   DREAM STATE: STORIES
</P>
<P>
   By Moira Crone.
</P>
<P>
   University Press of Mississippi, $14.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Many of the vaguely confused characters in these tales are
transplanted Northerners adrift in New Orleans and southern
Louisiana but unable to move on. '' 'Dream State' successfully
presents a fresh version of the Deep South, one that is exotic
without being either grotesque or romanticized,'' Gary Krist said
here in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   WITH CHATWIN: PORTRAIT OF A WRITER
</P>
<P>
   By Susannah Clapp.
</P>
<P>
   Penguin, $12.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The enigmatic Bruce Chatwin, who died of AIDS at the age of 48,
is portrayed by his first editor as a brilliant travel writer and
novelist, and an immensely talented art dealer. This is an
``adoring memoir'' by an observer ``graced with a special vantage
on his life and work,'' William Ferguson said here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
