A0878 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-SNOWFLAKE-NYT     01-13 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-SNOWFLAKE-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 SNOWFLAKE BENTLEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Jacqueline Briggs Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated by Mary Azarian.
</P>
<P>
   Unpaged. Boston: Houghton Mifflin. $16. (Ages 5 to 9)
 &UR; SNOW
</P>
<P>
   Written and illustrated by Uri Shulevitz.
</P>
<P>
   Unpaged. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. $16. (Ages 3 and up)
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; CHILDREN'S BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   By BETSY GROBAN (Distributed by New York Times Special
Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Hardly anyone would argue with the naturalist Wilson A.
Bentley's assertion that ``of all the forms of water, the tiny
six-pointed crystals of ice called snow . . . are incomparably the
most beautiful and varied.'' But almost no one would devote more
than 50 years to the close examination of this natural phenomenon,
as he did.
</P>
<P>
   We are, however, immeasurably richer for Bentley's scientific
inquiry. Before he began his research in the late 19th century,
virtually nothing was known about snowflakes; certainly no one
realized what almost everyone now knows: that every single
snowflake is unique. Bentley was born in 1865, and as a child in
the snow belt of Vermont, where annual snowfall can exceed 120
inches, he became fascinated with learning about, analyzing,
capturing and drawing snowflakes. His interest elicited the
ridicule of his neighbors, who considered snow ``as common as
dirt'' and couldn't imagine why anyone would want to know more
about it. But Bentley couldn't bear knowing that when a snowflake
melted away, ``that much beauty was gone, without leaving any
record behind.'' Fortunately, his parents were more than
supportive: they spent their savings on an expensive combination
camera and microscope for their son. The camera was ``taller than a
newborn calf, and cost as much as his father's herd of 10 cows.''
The rest, as they say, is history.
</P>
<P>
   In a story both lyrical and informative, Jacqueline Briggs
Martin traces the life of this self-taught and determined
scientist-farmer from his childhood obsession through the
recognition that followed on his publication of ``Snow Crystals,''
a book of snowflake photographs that is still in use today, to his
death in 1931.
</P>
<P>
   ``Snowflake Bentley'' is a tale of intense dedication to
something both mundane and glorious, and thus, I suspect, will
fascinate children. And Mary Azarian's lovely, perfectly pitched
color woodcuts evoke the simple landscape of life in
turn-of-the-century rural Vermont as well as the wonder of snow,
snow, everywhere. Several of Bentley's photographs are included, as
well as a photo of him using his beloved camera. There are also
source notes for the biographical information. This is picture-book
biography at its very best: written like a prose poem and
beautifully illustrated.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Snow,'' Uri Shulevitz, the author and illustrator of many
prizewinning books, uses the white stuff in a totally different
fashion. Here it becomes a metaphor for the faith young children
possess in the face of an adult world lacking in vision and
understanding.
</P>
<P>
   When a small fellow, ``boy with dog,'' encounters the first
snowflakes of the season, he is certain that much more is on its
way. The boy and the dog pass through their dreary gray town trying
to spread the good word about the impending storm. But they are met
time and again with the skepticism of disbelieving grown-ups: ''
'It's only a snowflake,' said grandfather with beard.'' (Try
telling that to Wilson Bentley!)
</P>
<P>
   When the snowstorm finally, inevitably arrives, ``circling and
swirling, spinning and twirling,'' the town is transformed into a
winter wonderland both natural and magical. In a charming visual
aside, not acknowledged in the text, the only buildings of any
distinction in the town are its two bookstores, one of which plays
an important role in the transformation of the town from grim to
fantastical. With minimal text and engaging, colorful
illustrations, ``Snow'' is a picture book that young children in
all climates are likely to relish.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Betsy Groban oversees publishing operations at WGBH-TV in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
