<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 06:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0879 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-CHILDRENS-BOO     01-13 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-CHILDRENS-BOOKSHELF-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKSHELF
</HEADLINE>
  (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE PIRATE'S SON. By Geraldine McCaughrean. Scholastic. $16.95.
(Ages 8 to 12) The premise of this engaging novel is that Tamo
White was sent back to England in the early 17th century by his
dying pirate father to obtain a proper education. At school, Tamo
befriends the orphaned siblings Nathan and Maud Gull, and they set
off for Madagascar, which Tamo considers his home. They reach the
island, which appears ``like a gigantic crocodile asleep along the
horizon,'' and many thrilling adventures ensue.
</P>
<P>
   THE COBBLE STREET COUSINS: A Little Shopping. By Cynthia Rylant.
Illustrated by Wendy Anderson Halperin. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $14.
(Ages 7 to 10) A new series of books for girls features two
sisters, Rosie and Lily, and their cousin Tess, who lives with them
in a pretty house on Cobble Street. This episode is about making a
dollhouse that looks like Aunt Lucy's flower shop. The pencil and
watercolor illustrations are as sweet as the story.
</P>
<P>
   RAISING YODER'S BARN. By Jane Yolen. Illustrated by Bernie
Fuchs. Little, Brown. $15.95. (Ages 5 to 9) After an awful
midsummer fire that destroys much of a farm, the Amish community
calls on wise old Samuel Stulzfoot to oversee the planning and
raising of a new barn for the Yoder family. The story is told in
the marveling voice of an 8-year-old, Matthew Yoder. The lush oil
paintings move the narrative from many different perspectives.
</P>
<P>
   I WAS A TEENAGE FAIRY. By Francesca Lia Block. Joanna
Cotler/HarperCollins. $14.95. (Ages 12 and up) The author of the
``Weetzie Bat'' novels is an accomplished stylist whose vision of
Los Angeles is convincingly surreal. Barbie Marks, named for the
doll and treated like one by her mother, who wants a star, not a
daughter, has a secret friend: Mab, a proper Victorian-style fairy.
</P>
<P>
   CITY BY NUMBERS. Written and illustrated by Stephen T. Johnson.
Viking. $15.99. (All ages) Following the dazzling conceit of
``Alphabet City'' and continuing his love affair with New York, the
author has found and then painted numbers that spring from the very
fabric of urban life, from iron railings to shadows on a wall to
trash baskets aligned to make a figure 8. The numbers are more
difficult to read than the letters of ``Alphabet City,'' but
perhaps the stretching of vision for this companion book makes it a
grander and more complex achievement.
</P>
<P>
   ARLENE ALDA'S 1 2 3. Written and photographed by Arlene Alda.
Tricycle Press. $12.95. (Ages 2 and up) Another inspired counting
book, this collection of color photographs finds the shape of
numerals in surprising places -- an 8 in an open bagel smeared with
cream cheese, a 5 in the shadow of a bicycle. The author's charming
notes tell a lot about serendipity and artistic purpose -- some
photographs were planned, some first appeared when film was
developed, some just happened: ``I ate a banana. I saw a 3,'' she
writes, and shows us the peel: no doubt about it, it's a 3.
</P>
<P>
   TOILETS, TOASTERS &AMP; TELEPHONES. By Susan Goldman Rubin.
Illustrated with photographs and with illustrations by Elsa
Warnick. Browndeer/Harcourt Brace. $20. (Ages 8 to 12) The
household appliances we use are all the products of industrial
design, but they have evolved in curious and interesting ways. A
brisk, cheerful history of some of the objects we use most often
and how they came to the forms -- by no means always the obvious
ones -- in which we find them.
</P>
<P>
   THE COW OF NO COLOR: Riddle Stories and Justice Tales From
Around the World. By Nina Jaffe and Steve Zeitlin. Illustrated by
Whitney Sherman. Holt. $15.95. (Ages 8 to 12) Because complex
problems, like impeachment, reach the family dinner table, this
fine collection of folk tales underscoring differing cultural
values and ways of considering justice and punishment seems
particularly timely for families with school-age children. The
authors, who are both folklorists, offer extensive source notes and
an excellent bibliography.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
