</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 06:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0880 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-CHILDRENS-BRI     01-13 1510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-CHILDRENS-BRIEFS-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 BOOKS IN BRIEF: CHILDREN
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The great political caricaturist and magazine artist Edward
Sorel has also illustrated children's books for years, and lately
he has taken to writing them as well. His latest collaboration with
himself, JOHNNY ON THE SPOT (Margaret K. McElderry, $16; ages 5 to
9), is an exciting yarn set in the old New York of radio serials,
when gangsters toted machine guns in violin cases. Sorel's vivid
and engaging illustrations include some big urban tableaus that
capture the romance and innocence of the era. The plot is just as
lively. When young Johnny's radio conks out during his favorite
program, he takes it to Dr. Zaga, the mysterious and eccentric
inventor (is there any other kind?) who lives downstairs. Dr. Zaga
zaps it with ``a small charge of electrostatic magnetism,'' which
causes the radio to broadcast not today's news but tomorrow's. This
allows Sorel to present, in quick, deft strokes, some of the usual
paradoxes and moral quandaries of time travel. Dr. Zaga tells
Johnny that they must not interfere with the future, but he does
not explain why, and in any event they do it anyhow, in various
ways. At first Johnny merely takes pictures of a bank robbery and
sells them to a newspaper, but soon he is rescuing a girl in a
burning building and hanging out at the race track, placing bets.
(``It's not gambling,'' Dr. Zaga explains to a reluctant Johnny.
``We know which horses will win.'')
</P>
<P>
   Some readers will want a little more rigor and consistency in
the ground rules, and some parents may find themselves concocting
explanations to fill in the gaps. The otherwise entertaining
overlay of science fiction on an already unfamiliar period piece
may also leave younger readers feeling a little baffled. One senses
that Sorel is writing about his own boyhood, when radios
represented the very limits of household technology. A mature adult
can read ``Johnny on the Spot'' in a home bursting and buzzing with
all manner of the latest circuitry and innovation, and be reminded
that there remains something singularly magical and otherworldly
about a voice on the radio. _ ADAM LIPTAK
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BEYOND THE MANGO TREE
</P>
<P>
   By Amy Bronwen Zemser.
</P>
<P>
   Greenwillow, $15. (Ages 10 and up) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   An American child discovers the darkness in her own heart when
her father's job takes her to live in Liberia. Like the family in
Barbara Kingsolver's ``Poisonwood Bible,'' 12-year-old Sarina and
her parents bring their delusions with them to Africa. Sarina hates
it. She's trapped in an unhappy home in a foreign place. Dad's away
with his ``important'' work upcountry most of the time, and she
must care for her diabetic, madly possessive mother, who won't
allow Sarina to leave the yard. When Mom's in one of her frequent
insulin-deprived rages, she actually ties Sarina to a mango tree,
yelling, ``You are mine only, I cannot share you with anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The servants can't do anything to help Sarina; they would lose
their jobs. The housekeeper, Te Te, is like Sarina's guard: harsh,
rigid, unfeeling. Then Sarina makes a friend, Boima, a gentle,
lively local boy, whose torn, loose-hanging clothes barely cover
his fragile figure. He unties her. They climb and hide in the mango
tree. He tells her stories in his Liberian English dialect, and
sometimes she steals away with him to get a glimpse of the world
outside. But her mother has another source for her obsessive rage:
Who is stealing from the kitchen pantry? When Sarina discovers that
the thief is Te Te, who has been giving the food to Boima, Sarina
breaks with her friend, furiously jealous that he and Te Te had a
secret from her: ``He was my friend, not yours,'' she raves -- and
hears herself in her mother's voice.
</P>
<P>
   The essence of this astonishing story is in Sarina's
uncomfortable first-person, present-tense narrative, its intimacy
and its self-centeredness. The details of place and culture are
authentic (the author spent time in Liberia as a child in the
1980's) and so also is the privileged stranger's view of things. It
never occurs to Sarina to think about what the servants go home to
after work, why they need their jobs so desperately -- until, in a
heartbreaking climax, she discovers why Te Te has risked her job to
steal food. Like Sarina, for a long time we readers don't get it.
We are so caught up in Sarina's trouble and her adventures with
Boima that we don't see what she is describing right there before
our eyes. Far from generic exotic adventure, this is a powerful
contemporary story that shows the outsider the way things are. _
HAZEL ROCHMAN
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHEN VERA WAS SICK
</P>
<P>
   Written and illustrated by Vera Rosenberry.
</P>
<P>
   Holt, $15.95. (Ages 4 to 7) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   An actor was showing illustrations from a wordless picture book
to his audience of preschoolers and encouraging their responses.
Now he was trying to quiet them with a story.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had spots all over her body,'' he read, ``even between her
toes and inside her ears.'' ``When Vera Was Sick,'' a kind of
measles memory by Vera Rosenberry, silenced the listeners. ``Vera's
mother put her in the spare room, away from everyone. The room was
quiet and dark. It was lonely and kind of scary.''
</P>
<P>
   The children seem to feel the little girl's misery and the
mother's worry. The ink and gouache illustrations are unusually
expressive. They are contemporary and sophisticated, but have the
character and directness of naive painting. Small details --
black-and-white linoleum, striped mattress ticking, floorboard wood
grain -- are evocative of home. The artist's strongest image is
also the story's most unexpected and satisfying character, the
``kitty'' -- a big, silky, stuffed pillow with arms. To the
children in the audience, the most arresting moment seems to come
when Vera, covered with spots, stands watching from the kitchen
doorway as her mother and older sister make gingerbread men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, what are you doing here?'' the sister shouts. ``YOU'RE
SICK!''
</P>
<P>
   Vera recovers, of course, and that is the end of the story. What
is surprising is that being sick and getting better, just this
alone, is such a compelling story. It's something we always knew,
adults say, yet something we might not have known so well without
this lovely book. _ JIM LATIMER
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-CHILDRENS-BRIEFS-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: JIM LATIMER) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MONSTER STEW
</P>
<P>
   Written and illustrated by Mitra Modaressi.
</P>
<P>
   DK Ink, $15.95. (Ages 5 to 9) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Parents easily grasp the basic rules of the ironically
reinterpreted fairy tale. Beautiful princesses aren't all they're
cracked up to be, and rampaging monsters are usually misunderstood
victims of class inequity. That such terrain may be more difficult
for children to negotiate isn't crucial to the genre's success; the
territory is a growing market niche, meant to awaken the jaded
sensibilities of modern parents too easily bored with recounting
the same old story over and over again.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Monster Stew,'' Mitra Modaressi tries to breathe new life
into ancient cultural tropes, reworking the classic texts of ``The
Princess and the Pea,'' ``Jack and the Beanstalk'' and that most
terrifying of all Grimm horror stories, ``Hansel and Gretel.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorgeously illustrated in a style happily luxuriating somewhere
between the Muppets and the Maurice Sendak of ``Where the Wild
Things Are,'' ``Monster Stew'' offers, pictorially, everything the
small child's mind desires: witches, monsters both cute and
fearsome and even princesses of various descriptions. But
textually, Modaressi is less successful -- by substituting frothy
irony (Jack's mother suggests the monster stay awhile after the
beanstalk is cut down because he's ``in no shape to travel
anyhow'') for the potent power of the original stories, ``Monster
Stew'' ends up tasting like watered-down myth. Parents may gently
smile; kids will wonder, ``What's the point?''
</P>
<P>
   There's no question that monsters, as a group, have been
unfairly slandered for generations. But to rectify this oppressive
history in Modaressi's title story, by inserting a pair of monster
fuzzballs in place of the human children Hansel and Gretel, wreaks
such havoc on the original narrative as to be ultimately
unsatisfactory. Gone is the wicked father who purposely abandons
his children. Gone, even, are the cages into which Hansel and
Gretel were thrown. Instead, we get a story with no sense of threat
or danger -- just two little monsters who eat a witch ``out of
house and home.'' An ironic twist, to be sure, but as with most
such literary exercises, the aftertaste doesn't last long enough. _
ANDREW LEONARD
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
