<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 06:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0881 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-FICTION-BRIEF     01-13 1391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-FICTION-BRIEFS-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 BOOKS IN BRIEF: FICTION
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Riding on a train to Vienna in search of her runaway husband, a
Canadian art historian named Helen Martin enters a twilight world
of strange hallucinations, astounding coincidences and deadly
conundrums. Awakening in the middle of the night, Helen finds
herself sharing a compartment with an old woman named Rosa
Kovslovsky, who is somehow linked to her -- so closely linked that
Anna starts to believe her own body parts are being replaced by
Rosa's. Then this odd companion hands her a small box full of
wonders and clues, which will accompany Helen on a tour of Europe
in search of much more than her missing spouse. The box contains a
book on human anatomy, jewels and notes. And, in a nice twist, the
design of Barbara Hodgson's novel THE SENSUALIST (Chronicle,
$22.95) incorporates all these visual aids. As readers follow
Helen, we see the same images she is seeing: illustrated plates
from ancient anatomy texts, medicine vials, a pearl-studded picture
frame. Like the historical works she researches, Helen's box -- and
Hodgson's book -- provides a way of interweaving ``the significance
of the words with the importance of the pictures.'' Helen soon
finds herself embroiled in a historical mystery as printing blocks
from the works of the anatomist Vesalius seem to have resurfaced
long after they were reportedly destroyed in World War II. Helen's
husband was on their trail, and she quickly resumes his quest.
``The Sensualist'' is a quirky and intense novel, full of weird
events and oddball characters (a man who is interviewing every
person in the Vienna telephone directory; a doctor who is inspired
to become a train conductor when the conductor on his own train
drops dead) built around an investigation of the senses. The best
part is Hodgson's combination of pictures and text: as a physical
object, ``The Sensualist'' becomes an integral part of the plot,
guiding the reader as the complex narrative unravels. _ ERIK BURNS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLIMBING THE GOD TREE
</P>
<P>
   A Novel in Stories.
</P>
<P>
   By Jaimee Wriston Colbert.
</P>
<P>
   Helicon Nine, paper, $12.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Rock Harbor, Me., is a rough-edged coastal town where much of
the economy centers on a maximum security prison. And in ``Climbing
the God Tree,'' a cycle of two dozen stories, the characters' lives
also have links to the prison. The first person we meet is Eli
Hyde, a 32-year-old painter who runs art therapy workshops for the
inmates while mourning a miscarriage that has all but ruined her
marriage to a handsome, increasingly cold-hearted carpenter. Soon
enough, we're introduced to Morton Salvitore, ``a lifer, different
from the others. . . . Hair the color of the prison wall, eyes flat
as a fish.'' He's been put away for murdering a girl named Jenna
Pierce -- and now he's obsessed with Eli. There are also
appearances by Jenna's mother, who's still bingeing on alcohol and
food to numb her pain 13 years after her daughter's sickening
death, and the Rev. Ellen Barnes, a formidable preacher bent on
guiding Morton to salvation. The scope of Jaimee Wriston Colbert's
storytelling is impressive, with no fewer than 16 central
characters delineated in intricately overlapping narratives. Yet
the plotting hinges on a string of tragic events -- a drowning in
the Atlantic, a rape, another miscarriage, a death from cancer, a
diagnosis of Alzheimer's disease -- that too frequently shift the
focus from complex characters to less developed if more imperiled
ones. While the early stories stand on their own as sensitive and
unsentimental evocations of unrelieved loss, eventually the novel's
power is diffused by its own restless form. _ MEGAN HARLAN
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE STORM
</P>
<P>
   By Frederick Buechner.
</P>
<P>
   HarperSanFrancisco, $18. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The author of 30 works of fiction and nonfiction, Frederick
Buechner is not only a well-regarded writer but also an ordained
Presbyterian minister. Drawing on both his literary and religious
credentials, he has used his latest novel to reinterpret ``The
Tempest'' by casting Shakespeare's drama as a contemporary tale of
redemption. The enchanted setting is Plantation Island in southern
Florida, where a successful writer named Kenzie Maxwell lives with
his wealthy third wife. Although he's about to turn 70, Kenzie is
still haunted by a 20-year-old scandal that occurred when he was
working in a South Bronx rescue mission -- and fathered a daughter
whose 17-year-old mother died in childbirth. Now, on the eve of a
gala birthday celebration, many of the figures from his past
reassemble, including the brother who betrayed him to the press,
the daughter he has never known and his wife's Ariel-like son.
There is, of course, a violent, potentially destructive storm; but
Buechner insures that all's well that ends well. _ RUTH COUGHLIN
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DARKNESS FALLS
</P>
<P>
   By John M. Del Vecchio.
</P>
<P>
   St. Martin's, $24.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In his latest book, John M. Del Vecchio (best known for the
Vietnam novel ``The 13th Valley'') explores the world of an unhappy
middle-aged advertising executive from a large Italian-American
family in Connecticut. Del Vecchio makes no secret of the fact that
his hero, Johnny Panuzio, plans to kill himself. Johnny's despised
but high-paying job may soon be eliminated. He feels rejected by
his wife, Julia; alienated from his teen-age son, Jason; and
frustrated in his attempts to take care of Rocco, his proud,
elderly father. But Johnny's problems move beyond the personal when
three of Jason's classmates are killed in a car accident and
Johnny's best friend's son -- handsome, a brilliant student and a
star of the soccer team -- is murdered. Tension builds as the
school and the town try to explain these deaths; in the process,
the precarious racial coexistence in this largely white suburb
starts to crumble. Johnny's still vivid childhood memories (which
punctuate the present-day action) only reactivate his youthful
insecurities, exacerbating his adult resentment and guilt. The
downward spiral of his life is convincingly horrific, and the
characters around him are realistically drawn. The only jarring
note appears in Johnny's melodramatic last thoughts, also spliced
in throughout the text. Despite this, the novel's ending achieves
an undeniable intensity -- although it would have been stronger if
Del Vecchio had jettisoned the spell-it-all-out epilogue and
14-page appendix. _ JOAN MOONEY
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RUDE BEHAVIOR
</P>
<P>
   By Dan Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   Doubleday, $24.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It's been a very long time since those lovable bad boys Billy
Clyde Puckett and Shake Tiller led the New York Giants to the Super
Bowl, and now they're back. The question is, Do we really want
them? Once upon a time, they were amusing in a wacky,
take-no-prisoners sort of way; but in ``Rude Behavior,'' Dan
Jenkins's sporadically entertaining sequel to ``Semi-Tough'' and
``Life Its Ownself,'' the novelty is more or less over. This time
around, their antics wear pretty thin. Too old (and too beat up) to
make it onto the field himself, Billy Clyde is acting as point man
for his father-in-law, Big Ed Bookman, in his quest to set up a new
N.F.L. franchise in West Texas. Meanwhile, Shake has gone to
Hollywood to make movies that seem destined for the back end of a
double bill at the local drive-in. The supporting characters who
fill this somewhat forced satire are supposed to be colorful, but
for the most part they're downright tedious. Names like ReRun
Moses, Pluribus Uram, Fryer Pye, LaDaminion Walls and Budget Fowler
are meant to provide a chuckle -- but a wince is more likely.
Jenkins, who can write witty dialogue, obviously had fun coming up
with offbeat names for local watering holes (He's Not Here, Not
Tonight I've Got the Blues, Mommie's Trust Fund, the Gimmee Putt),
but he may be alone in that. And lines like ``Men were from two
channels at once, women were from Oprah'' fall shorter than a
quarterback sneak on a long fourth down. _ CHARLES SALZBERG
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
