<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 06:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0882 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-NONFICTION-BR     01-13 1467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-NONFICTION-BRIEFS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS IN BRIEF: NONFICTION
</HEADLINE>
  (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps no one in our time has been able to capture the essence
of an individual's character in the snap of a shutter with as much
artistry as the French photographer Henri Cartier-Bresson. With a
searching eye and an intuitive grasp of human psychology, he has
roamed the world over the last seven decades, recording the faces
of the unnamed and anonymous as well as some of the greatest
artists of the century. In TETE A TETE: Portraits by Henri
Cartier-Bresson (Bulfinch/Little, Brown, $65), he has selected some
of the most haunting and memorable images of his prolific career.
Here we see a portrait of a robed Matisse, looking like a pampered
pasha; a young, distracted-looking Jean-Paul Sartre, pipe at his
lips as he converses on the Pont des Arts in Paris; a pudgy-faced
Jean Genet, dragging on a cigar with an expression of amused
indulgence; and an aging Colette, flashing the camera a coquettish
glance. Included too is a trove of photographs that are among his
most legendary -- a stunning picture of Samuel Beckett looking more
hawk than human, a classic shot of the melancholy Alberto
Giacometti lost in thought and an electrifying picture of a hoary
Ezra Pound, his brow furrowed in barely suppressed fury. Marcel
Duchamp shares the camera frame with one of his ready-mades, an
expression of ironic detachment suffusing his face. A bare-chested
Picasso stands beside a tousled bed, unabashed in his frank
physicality. ``In whatever picture-story we try to do, we are bound
to arrive as intruders,'' Cartier-Bresson once wrote. Yet his great
gift is to take us inside the intimate encounter without creating a
feeling that we have trespassed. _ ANDREA BARNET
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRULY BLESSED
</P>
<P>
   By Teddy Pendergrass and Patricia Romanowski.
</P>
<P>
   Putnam, $23.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The soul-music superstar Teddy Pendergrass's high-flying life
style ended abruptly on March 18, 1982, when his Rolls-Royce
crashed in Philadelphia, leaving him a quadriplegic. He awoke eight
days later, on his 32d birthday, to find himself strapped to a
large steel frame with a metal halo surgically attached to his
skull like ``some bizarre crucifixion,'' as he recalls in ``Truly
Blessed,'' a moving, at times harrowing, memoir. Pendergrass, who
started his recording career as the lead singer for Harold Melvin
and the Blue Notes with such seamless Philly soul classics as ``The
Love I Lost,'' and went on to become the first black male artist to
chart five consecutive platinum albums, found himself right back
where he started -- the hospital in which he was born, this time in
the spinal cord injury center. His story, written with Patricia
Romanowski, has the ragged edges and unresolved rage of reality:
``The road to recovery was more like the haunted house ride in a
boardwalk carnival.'' The book is both a richly textured history of
Pendergrass's musical roots in the creative explosion of 70's soul
that shaped his gruff, sexy style, and an unflinching look at what
it is like to be disabled. _ ERIC P. NASH
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THINKING WITH HISTORY
</P>
<P>
   Explorations in the Passage to Modernism.
</P>
<P>
   By Carl E. Schorske.
</P>
<P>
   Princeton University, $24.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Carl E. Schorske examines why he thinks we have abandoned
history; why, in this modern world, we think without history. For
Schorske, a professor emeritus of history at Princeton, the
decisive moment came in the 19th century when economic and
political changes proved so profound that the past appeared
increasingly irrelevant. One group of thinkers sought to restore
the importance of history by reforming modernity. Men like
Coleridge and Disraeli adopted a nostalgic historicism, a deep
longing to return to a golden age of social justice and harmony.
But in a clever analysis, Schorske illustrates how their own
sensibilities were shaped by modern reality; ironically, their
defense of the past belies how unbridgeable the gap between past
and present had become. Thus, their historicism was as useless as
the medieval finery adorning Victorian Gothic railway stations. In
contrast, modernists sought to wrest consciousness away from
history, the outmoded categories now impediments to the rich
possibilities created in the present. But they paid a price for
their originality -- they missed the coherence that a sense of
history brings to reality. Schorske, whose books include
``Fin-de-Siecle Vienna: Politics and Culture,'' illustrates the
efforts of modernist pioneers like Mahler and Freud to find new
categories of meaning, new foundations for thought. They, too, met
with disappointment; Schorske ends this subtle, important book with
an examination of Freud's reliance on the culture of ancient Egypt.
Even his retreat to within, the most successful response to this
new quest for meaning, required a grounding in history. _ DOUGLAS
A. SYLVA
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE SECOND BRAIN
</P>
<P>
   The Scientific Basis of Gut Instinct and a Groundbreaking New
Understanding of Nervous Disorders of the Stomach and Intestine.
</P>
<P>
   By Michael D. Gershon.
</P>
<P>
   HarperCollins, $24. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``The bowel just is not the kind of organ that makes the pulse
race,'' Michael D. Gershon admits. ``No poet would ever write an
ode to the intestine.'' Nevertheless, in ``The Second Brain,''
Gershon makes a persuasive, impassioned and, at times, downright
lyrical case for the counterintuitive notion that ``there is a
brain in the bowel, however inappropriate that concept might seem
to be.'' Gershon, who is chairman of the department of anatomy and
cell biology at Columbia University's College of Physicians and
Surgeons at Columbia-Presbyterian Medical Center and one of the few
neurobiologists to turn his attention to the ``lowly gut and its
nervous system,'' recounts with considerable warmth, humor and
dramatic flair how he valiantly endured ``the slings and arrows of
outrageous colleagues'' who initially dismissed his then heretical
discovery that serotonin, already established as an important mood
regulator in the brain, also functions as a neurotransmitter in the
bowel -- where more than 95 percent of the body's supply of this
chemical is produced. Moreover, the bowel, with its hundred
million-plus nerve cells, is ``the only organ that contains an
intrinsic nervous system that is able to mediate reflexes in the
complete absence of input from the brain or spinal cord.'' The
fruits of Gershon's painstaking research eventually helped persuade
fellow neuroscientists, physicians and drug companies to entertain
the possibility that gastrointestinal disorders heretofore thought
to be triggered by psychoneuroses may actually be precipitated by a
``mental disease'' of this ``second brain.'' Although at times his
elaborately detailed descriptions of intestinal research
methodology may be daunting, much of the book succeeds in
presenting an often grim and complex topic in a surprisingly witty
and engaging manner -- as well as delivering hopeful news to the
estimated 20 percent of Americans suffering from functional bowel
disease. _ JACQUELINE BOONE
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE HISTORY OF NORTH AMERICAN THEATER
</P>
<P>
   From Pre-Columbian Times to the Present.
</P>
<P>
   By Felicia Hardison Londre and Daniel J. Watermeier.
</P>
<P>
   Continuum, $95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The theaters of the indigenous cultures of North America and
Canada are usually overlooked in most survey books about
performance in the Americas. Felicia Hardison Londre, who teaches
theater at the University of Missouri, Kansas City, and Daniel J.
Watermeier, who teaches theater at the University of Toledo, are
the first to write a comprehensive history of North American
theater. Their study includes discussion of drama in Mexico, the
Caribbean, Canada and the United States from precolonial times to
the present. As with any survey, ``The History of North American
Theater'' inspires both admiration and frustration -- admiration
for the daunting research, frustration at the resulting
reductionism and the cursory discussions necessary to make vast
amounts of information manageable. At its best (which is most of
the time), the book offers clear and cogent information, well
organized and well presented; at its weakest it inundates the
reader with endless names and dates. ``The History of North
American Theater'' addresses a gap in the current literature,
although this impressive volume will probably best be appreciated
by theater students and scholars. _ BEVYA ROSTEN
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
