<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 06:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0884 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-AMY-NYTSF     01-13 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-AMY-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 AMY AND ISABELLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Elizabeth Strout.
</P>
<P>
   304 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Random House. $22.95.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; TEACHER'S PET
</P>
<P>
   BY SUZANNE BERNE
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IN the best stories about families, one is invariably led to
agree with Willa Cather's remark that ``human relationships are the
tragic necessity of human life.'' Since they are the most necessary
of bonds, family relationships are also the most imperfect, which
is what makes writing about them so particularly challenging.
Within each family, as Cather notes, there are ``innumerable shades
of sweetness and anguish which make up the pattern of our lives day
by day.'' Capturing this daily complexity is exactly what Elizabeth
Strout accomplishes in her evocative first novel, ``Amy and
Isabelle,'' one of those rare, invigorating books that take an
apparently familiar world and peer into it with ruthless intimacy,
revealing a strange and startling place.
</P>
<P>
   The novel's main characters are Amy, a shy 16-year-old, chiefly
noticeable for her lovely blond hair, and her prim, anxiously
single mother, Isabelle, a secretary at the local mill in the small
New England town of Shirley Falls. Set sometime in the 1960's, much
of the action occurs during one stultifying summer, when the river
looks like ``a dead brown snake,'' the air smells sulfurous and
``carrots stopped growing when they were no bigger than the fingers
of a child.'' A few months earlier, a girl had been kidnapped from
another town, and she is still missing; a series of burglaries has
also unnerved Shirley Falls. This ominous summer finds Amy and
Isabelle working in the same office -- an intolerable situation for
both since they have, just recently, begun to hate each other.
</P>
<P>
   That they also painfully love and need each other is what gives
``Amy and Isabelle'' its absorbing tension. Marooned on the edge of
town since Amy's babyhood -- neither part of the Basin, the
working-class Roman Catholic community, nor part of WASP Oyster
Point -- they have shared a relationship of exclusive dependency
and muted depression. For Isabelle, ``life was moving forward the
way that lives did, and yet she was no more grounded than a bird
perched on a fence.'' Out of sheer loneliness, she has fallen in
love with her stodgy boss at the mill. Though she could befriend
other women in the office, Isabelle thinks they're beneath her. As
self-conscious as Isabelle, Amy has almost no friends either, no
consuming interests, and often nurses ``a vague and puzzling
feeling of shame.'' Her terrible secret is that for years she has
``wanted a different mother,'' someone who ``looked like mothers in
television ads.'' Devoted to their quiet yearnings, Amy and
Isabelle seem doomed to pine forever. But of course they do not.
</P>
<P>
   In the leisurely pace of a 19th-century novel, Strout describes
what becomes of Amy and Isabelle when something does finally happen
to them. It will not ruin any surprises to disclose that Amy falls
in love with her math teacher, Mr. Robertson, or that her
infatuation with him has seismic repercussions on her relationship
with her mother. What Isabelle does to Amy in return is savage and
yet horribly understandable -- an act of unmoored maternity that
illuminates the contradictions in her nature. Strout is likewise
skillful in making Mr. Robertson both loathsome and attractive, and
Amy poignantly ignorant while also poignantly perceptive.
</P>
<P>
   But the story's true drama lies in the palpable, intricate way
it examines the ``scrape of longing'' that drives these characters
toward human contact, leaving them raw and bleeding yet also more
fully alive. The physical world is always suggesting the romantic
one Amy and Isabelle ache for, and Strout wonderfully captures the
beauty and absurdity of this connection. Consider, for example,
this scene, in which Amy visits the A.&AMP;P.: ``The grocery store made
her want to cry: a strange hope and hopelessness collided here --
the hope of all those brightly lit kitchens out there with
telephones ringing on the wall, silverware clattering down on
tables, steam rising from pots on the stove, and then the
hopelessness of these rows and rows of canned beets and canned
corn.'' Similarly, as Isabelle drives by a farm at twilight, the
scent of mown grass fills her ``with some tremor that was almost
erotic, some confluence of different longings.''
</P>
<P>
   It's often these small occurrences, these glints of sweetness
and anguish, that lead Amy and Isabelle to expansive insights. When
Amy, awakening intellectually under Mr. Robertson's encouragement,
corrects her mother's pronunciation of Yeats, the humiliated
Isabelle decides to educate herself. First she tries reading
``Hamlet,'' which is beyond her, and then ``Madame Bovary,'' which
is not. Gripped by the novel, she experiences a devastating
understanding of ``the terrible longings Emma had.'' ``Madame
Bovary'' so unsettles Isabelle, in fact, that she decides ``she
might not read another book for a while, that life was difficult
enough without bringing someone else's sorrows to crash down about
your head.''
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, this is an unsophisticated way to read a book;
on the other, it is exactly the way the best books are meant to be
read. Strout is shrewd in selecting two great stories of family
betrayal for Isabelle's education because she is utterly unprepared
for Amy's rebellion, for ``the sense that her daughter was
strikingly different from what she had thought.''
</P>
<P>
   What awkward moments exist in ``Amy and Isabelle'' occur mostly
when Strout tries too hard to wrap up her story; suddenly a
narrative that has felt large and luminous is resolved into a tidy
parcel. She is also overfond of using parentheses to tuck in
extraneous details. But this is such an eloquent, captivating novel
that its occasional missteps don't much signify. By focusing on the
``confluence of different longings'' that bedevils her characters
into harming and helping one another, Strout makes the drab little
world of Shirley Falls seem richly important.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't blame these things on God,'' Isabelle reflects
toward the end of the book, ``It was people, just ordinary, regular
people, who did this to each other. People ruined other people's
lives.'' With this simple observation, she recalls us to our
purpose as readers and as human beings: to struggle to appreciate
the sorrows of others and perhaps reach a wiser sympathy for our
own.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing (Christoph Abbrederis)
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne Berne is the author of a novel, ``A Crime in the
Neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
