<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-CONTENTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 (Editors: Following is a list of slugs and titles of the books
reviewed in the New York Times Book Review for Sunday, Jan. 17.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ----------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   ON THE COVER
</P>
<P>
   ----------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   NYTBOOK-PANCHO-NYTSF, THE LIFE AND TIMES OF PANCHO VILLA, By
Friedrich Katz. Illustrated. 985 pp. Stanford, Calif.: Stanford
University Press. Cloth, $85. Paper, $29.95. A biography of the
legendary Mexican outlaw and revolutionary leader.
</P>
<P>
   --------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   FICTION
</P>
<P>
   --------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   NYTBOOK-TRIUMPH-NYTSF, THE TRIUMPH OF LOVE, By Geoffrey Hill. 82
pp. Boston: Houghton Mifflin Company. $22. Geoffrey Hill's
book-length poem is an elegy for those consumed by our century's
horrors.
</P>
<P>
   NYTBOOK-TRUTH-NYTSF, TRUTH, Four Stories I Am Finally Old Enough
to Tell. By Ellen Douglas. 221 pp. Chapel Hill, N.C.: Algonquin.
$18.95. Ellen Douglas seeks to discover truth in four stories taken
from her family history.
</P>
<P>
   NYTBOOK-RIDINGHOOD-NYTSF, LITTLE RED RIDING HOOD IN THE RED
LIGHT DISTRICT, By Manlio Argueta. Translated by Edward Waters
Hood. 237 pp. Willimantic, Conn.: Curbstone Press. $14.95. A novel
about El Salvador in the 70's follows the trail of a poet turned
guerrilla.
</P>
<P>
   NYTBOOK-AMY-NYTSF, AMY AND ISABELLE, By Elizabeth Strout. 304
pp. New York: Random House. $22.95. A first novel charts the
escalating tension between a woman and her teen-age daughter in a
New England mill town.
</P>
<P>
   NYTBOOK-COUNTRYLIFE-NYTSF, THE COUNTRY LIFE, By Rachel Cusk. 342
pp. New York: Picador USA. $24. Everyone in this British novel
seems to lust after an unbalanced governess.
</P>
<P>
   --------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   NONFICTION
</P>
<P>
   --------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   NYTBOOK-WAY-NYTSF, THE WAY OF THE WORLD, From the Dawn of
Civilizations to the 21st Century. By David Fromkin.
</P>
<P>
   253 pp. New York: Alfred A. Knopf. $25.A brief history of the
world from the Big Bang to the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   NYTBOOK-BRAIN-NYTSF, PHANTOMS IN THE BRAIN, Probing the
Mysteries of the Human Mind. By V. S. Ramachandran and Sandra
Blakeslee. Illustrated. 328 pp. New York: William Morrow. $27. A
neurologist uses case studies to illuminate the workings of the
brain.
</P>
<P>
   NYTBOOK-GRATEFUL-NYTSF, SWEET CHAOS, The Grateful Dead's
American Adventure. By Carol Brightman. 356 pp. New York: Clarkson
Potter. $27.50. Dissecting the Grateful Dead and those curiosities
known as Deadheads.
</P>
<P>
   NYTBOOK-TURKEY-NYTSF TURKEY UNVEILED, A History of Modern
Turkey. By Nicole Pope and Hugh Pope. 373 pp. Woodstock, N.Y.:
Overlook. $29.95. Husband-and-wife journalists explore the culture
and politics of contemporary Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   NYTBOOK-BURTON-NYTSF, A RAGE TO LIVE, A Biography of Richard and
Isabel Burton. By Mary S. Lovell. Illustrated. 910 pp. New York: W.
W. Norton. $39.95. That's what Isabel Burton wanted, and Sir
Richard gave it to her.
</P>
<P>
   NYTBOOK-SOLITUDE-NYTSF, LANGUAGE AND SOLITUDE, Wittgenstein,
Malinowski and the Habsburg Dilemma. By Ernest Gellner. 209 pp. New
York: Cambridge. $54.95. Paper, $17.95. He made social criticism
impossible, a philosopher argues.
</P>
<P>
   NYTBOOK-APOSTLES-NYTSF, FRIENDS AND APOSTLES, Correspondence of
Rupert Brooke and James Strachey. Edited by Keith Hale.
Illustrated. 304 pp. New Haven: Yale Press. $35. Love letters and
other correspondence between Rupert Brooke and James Strachey.
</P>
<P>
   NYTBOOK-MEMORY-NYTSF, THE BURDEN OF MEMORY, THE MUSE OF
FORGIVENESS, By Wole Soyinka. 208 pp. New York: Oxford University
Press. $23. Three essays from Wole Soyinka on negritude and
Africa's future.
</P>
<P>
   NYTBOOK-EARTH-NYTSF, EARTH ODYSSEY, In Search of Our
Environmental Future. By Mark Hertsgaard. 372 pp. New York:
Broadway Books. $26. A journalist offers an environmental report
card on the planet.
</P>
