<HEADER>
A0890 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-OFFICE-LIFEBEAT-     01-13 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-OFFICE-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR HEADQUARTERS, TURN LEFT AT THE KITCHEN
</HEADLINE>
  Includes three color photos of home office furnishings, available
by e-mail. Call William Gonzales, graphics desk, at 212-499-3355. 
 By BILL DEAN 
 c.1999 NYT Regional Newspapers 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Where some see an empty closet, second bedroom, or garage
apartment, others see a home office.
</P>
<P>
   But today's home work spaces don't have to be rooms dedicated to
computers, files and fax machines.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on needs and workloads, a ``home office'' can be
anything from an elaborate L-shaped desk to a rollaway computer
cart, or even a hide-the-goods armoire.
</P>
<P>
   With 40 million of us doing at least some of our work at home,
and increasing tax incentives for setting up space exclusively
devoted to business, homeowners are seeking creative solutions to
fashioning home offices.
</P>
<P>
   It's best to start with the fundamental question: Where?
</P>
<P>
   Will the office dominate an entire room? Or will you make do
with a small wall panel in the den or family room?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you have no space at all to set up a computer desk full
time.
</P>
<P>
   Consultant and author Candace Ord Manroe, who wrote ``The Home
Office'' (Reader's Digest, 1997, $23), says once you evaluate your
needs and have a clear idea of what you want, a space can always be
found. She's designed offices that have been tucked under
stairwells, in closets, attics and former pantries.
</P>
<P>
   Components exist to fit just about every need for a home office,
which at a minimum often means a personal computer, monitor, and a
printer/fax machine. The typical workstation has a hutch, a place
for a computer monitor, a pullout printer stand, a work surface,
file drawers and little nooks for paper.
</P>
<P>
   Rooms that have an open 7-by-7-foot corner can accommodate
elaborate L-shaped centers of that size, with plenty of room for
accessories like a printer table.
</P>
<P>
   ``The L-shaped and U-shaped desks are becoming more popular due
to space. The traditional executive type set up is just not
functional for the home,'' says Christina Erridge, public relations
manager of Staples Inc., the office-supply chain based near Boston.
``And people want more of a choice in fabrics, cabinet facings,
wood finishings. Not just the typical metal filing cabinets.
Something that complements their home and doesn't stick out.''
</P>
<P>
   By 2000, nearly 50 percent of homes will have some form of home
office, Erridge says.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's tremendous growth. A lot of homes are now being built
with an office in mind,'' she says. ``Home offices are growing four
times as fast as any other kind of business, which is great for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Contemporary 30-by-60-inch computer desks and workstations can
fit into rooms where just one wall is available. For a standard
desk you would need a 6-foot wall space.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for L-shape centers can range from $199 to $800, while
desks and one-wall workstations are from $99 to $400.
</P>
<P>
   Most office furniture is made of laminated wood, and requires
assembly. If you'd rather someone else handle the screwdriver and
bolts, expect to pay an additional fee ranging from $35 to $125,
depending on the size of the unit.
</P>
<P>
   Desks and workstations are available in more than just
dark-stained wood, although that's still most common. Homeowners
can order hues from whitewash to cherry to match their decor.
</P>
<P>
   Armoires have become the fastest selling home-office components
on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Like entertainment centers, armoires allow owners to ``hide''
their computer behind closed doors when not in use. The armoire
then blends in with other furniture in the room, so the ``office''
literally closes up at the end of the day.
</P>
<P>
   If space is tight, the all-inclusive computer cart may be the
answer. Since it's on wheels, the computer can be rolled out for
work, then stashed away in a closet when done.
</P>
<P>
   Fitting into a space just 42-inches wide, the cart has space for
a computer, keyboard, monitor, printer and copy holder. It's a
popular option for a bedroom office.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for carts range from about $39 to $200, with a variety in
the $100 range. A matching hutch would cost about $50 more.
</P>
<P>
   Armoires and carts make even more sense these days as increasing
technology continues to shrink hardware. When home offices require
printers, copiers and fax machines, some companies have responded
with the ``all in one'' machine.
</P>
<P>
   These space savers combine a fax machine, printer, scanner,
copier, answering machine and telephone in a unit the size of a
typewriter.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Himowitz, who writes about his techno-addiction in
Fortune magazine, says his home office was greatly simplified by
the Concerto Switchboard, a $495 gadget from Centrepoint
Technologies that gives a home office the equivalent of a ``fancy
corporate phone system.'' It routes, screens or transfers calls,
coordinates the phone, fax and PC, and can even play music or
prerecorded messages while customers are on hold.
</P>
<P>
   Since one of the big advantages of home offices is comfort, make
sure furnishings provide ergonomic support.
</P>
<P>
   Use chairs that raise and lower pneumatically to match keyboard
height. Prices range from $20 for simple models to $400 for leather
desk chairs.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget inexpensive copy holders, mouse pads, wrist
pads, cord ducts or cable guides for hiding cords from view and
preventing tangling.
</P>
<P>
   Other items to consider are power strips with plug-ins for all
electronic equipment and a master switch to turn everything off at
once. They run about $50, with surge protectors built in.
</P>
<P>
   Functional desk lamps needn't be elaborate or expensive ($9 to
$60). Reading lamps with soft-white bulbs work well, regardless of
whether they're floor or desk models.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Bill Dean writes for The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla.) &LR;
</P>
