<SLUG> BC-FOOD-GOODSTUFF-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    FOOD BRIEFS
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ONE GOOD REMINDER
</P>
<P>
   When you dug into the Brie on the holiday table, did you wonder
whether it was OK to eat the rind? Some people just scoop out the
semisoft center. Others eat the cheese rind and all. Brie is aged
with the help of friendly bacteria called penicillium candidum,
which attach to the rind and encourage it to age
</P>
<P>
   from the outside in. The rinds are safe to eat, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ONE GOOD EXPLANATION
</P>
<P>
   What's the magic with chicken soup? It may just be the hot
fluids that soothe sufferers with colds. But Barbara Kafka, author
of Soup - A Way of Life (Artisan, $35), theorizes that chicken
soup's restorative reputation may be based on gelatin. Good chicken
soup requires good chicken stock. When you make your own stock from
chicken bones, gelatin (a body builder) is extracted from those
bones. If your stock comes from a can, you may be missing
something.
</P>
<P>
   Author casts light on healthy eating
</P>
<P>
   If the Jan. 1 resolution - and you know which one - is already
waning, get some inspiration from the new Light Basics Cookbook
(Morrow, $25). Martha Rose Shulman is a cookbook author known for
her Mexican Light, Provencal Light and Mediterranean Light books,
and she has a strong sense of flavor as well as an understated
commitment to lightening the food she sendsto the table. This one
targets beginning cooks.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
