<HEADER>
A1044 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHABOT-IMPEACH14-COX     01-13 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHABOT-IMPEACH14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former schoolteacher prepares to hear case against Clinton
 &HT;    (ATTN: OHIO editors)
 &HT;    By Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When U.S. Rep. Steve Chabot made his living as a
lawyer, he was the legal equivalent of the family doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Advertised in the Yellow Pages, Chabot's one-man law office
handled cases across the legal spectrum from criminal defense to
divorce court. It was a mix of work Chabot categorizes under the
heading of ``whatever came in the door.''
</P>
<P>
   But now, Chabot's legal profile is about to rise. Just weeks
into his third term in Congress, this former elementary school
teacher is part of the team of prosecutors that on Thursday will
begin presenting a case for removing President Clinton from office.
</P>
<P>
   Chabot's role in the trial will be to outline for Senators the
definitions and dangers of perjury, one of the core charges against
Clinton. Chabot's presentation will not deal directly with the
evidence, though he may make reference to it, but rather he will
talk in general terms about the laws on perjury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'll probably be talking for somewhere between 10
minutes and a half hour,'' Chabot said recently.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors, a group of 13 Republican members of the House
of Representatives, have 24 hours over several work days to make
the case against Clinton. Chabot said he expects to present his
piece of the case on the second day, although the schedule easily
could shift.
</P>
<P>
   Chabot is one of five members of the prosecution team that is
focusing on legal issues in preparation for the Senate trial. The
group includes U.S. Reps. Bill McCollum of Florida, George Gekas of
Pennsylvania, Bob Barr of Georgia and Chris Cannon of Utah. If the
White House makes any arguments on points of law, this group will
do the research to combat them.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Chabot's group is responsible for handling witnesses, if
they're called. The issue of whether to have live witnesses testify
remains a volatile one that the Senate, which dictates the rules of
the trial, has yet to decide.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and the White House oppose calling witnesses because
they say it will needlessly lengthen a trail for which a voluminous
record of sworn testimony already exists. Republican prosecutors
say having witnesses appear before the Senate is essential to the
trial because it's the only way to let Senators evaluate their
credibility.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate will settle the issue by voting later in the trial,
after both sides have presented their case. In the mean time,
Chabot's group is meeting ``usually more than one time in a day''
to discuss legal issues, and prepare a list of potential witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   If prosecutors are permitted to call witnesses, Chabot's group
will do the preliminary preparations, including interviews. Others
from the 13-member prosecution team would question the witnesses in
the Senate chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Chabot's coming performance in the impeachment trial should
signal the last phase of the long, pressure-filled task of judging
the president. Chabot is a member of the House Judiciary Committee
that began meeting last fall to review the Independent Counsel's
report on the extent to which Clinton sought to conceal his
relationship with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   While some lawmakers have said they were belatedly struck by the
historical reality of what they were doing when they had to cast
votes on impeachment articles, Chabot said wearily, ``It always has
been very real to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been living and breathing this for months now.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Montgomery writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
