A1045 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-DRUG-MOVIE14-COX     01-13 0505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-DRUG-MOVIE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Film commission backtracks after featuring local school in drug
movie
 &HT;    By Ron Hayes
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ While the students at Lake Worth High
School were being held to a strict ``Zero Tolerance'' anti-drug
policy last week, Palm Beach County's film commission was
unwittingly helping a low-budget film crew shoot a comic drug deal
in one of the school's bathrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Dave's Day Out begins when Dave buys some marijuana in the
bathroom. The scene was filmed Saturday with the cooperation of
both the school district and the county Film Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Did the county know the school would be used to film a drug
deal?
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't ask,'' writer-director Marlene Rogoff said.
``Nobody asked.''
</P>
<P>
   They should have. Even though the school will not be identified
in the film and the pot was fake, district policy allows the use of
school property only if the films don't ``contain scenes depicting
alcohol or drug usage.''
</P>
<P>
   Film Commissioner Chuck Elderd conceded Tuesday that his office
had not read the script before helping Rogoff gain access to the
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to request that any footage shot in conflict with
this policy be reshot on nonschool property,'' Elderd said.
</P>
<P>
   School District spokesman Nat Harrington was relieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though it's make-believe, it just makes it more difficult
for us to send a public message to young people that drugs are
wrong,'' Harrington said. ``Especially at school or anywhere near
school.''
</P>
<P>
   The feature film is not likely to be a blockbuster. Rogoff is
hoping to interest Blockbuster in a straight-to-video release.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a live-action Beavis &AMP; Butthead,'' Rogoff explained
Tuesday outside a Holiday Inn on Lake Worth Road, where filming
continued. ``The comedy is that they're oblivious.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave and his best friend, Fred, are ``only in search of the next
pleasure and girls, according to a press release touting the film.
Reality eventually catches up with them, but only after a fun-paced
twenty-four hours of misadventure.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the fight scene being shot Tuesday at the Holiday
Inn, teachers probably won't be recommending the Dave's Day Out,
which expects an R rating, even without the bathroom humor.
</P>
<P>
   When a leather-clad biker pulls a shotgun on Fred, Dave crowns
him with a concrete block.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got foul language galore, but no nudity,'' Rogoff said.
``They talk about it, but we don't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogoff is no stranger to local lovers of the cinema.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, she wrote and directed Scooter In Palm Beach, another
low-budget comedy that featured County Commissioner Carol Roberts
as a Palm Beach socialite.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner was so dazzled by her experience before the
cameras she persuaded the county to establish a film commission.
</P>
<P>
   She does not appear in Dave's Day Out.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Hayes writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
