A1050 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATSTUPID14-COX     01-13 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATSTUPID14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stupid PC signs contract to sell IBM equipment
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Stupid PC, the company trying to bring down-home
simplicity to home computer sales, is hoping to tap deeper into the
business market.
</P>
<P>
   The Norcross, Ga.-based PC retailer signed with the IBM Business
Partner program last week. The agreement lets the Po Folks of PC
sales peddle Big Blue's stuff, from Netfinity servers to ThinkPad
laptops.
</P>
<P>
   Stupid PC has also allied with Corporate Tele-Data, a South
Carolina company with an Marietta office, that will install the
servers and networks Stupid PC sells.
</P>
<P>
   This comes on the heels of a plan to open several retail stores
in five Southern cities.
</P>
<P>
   Stupid PC is on a roll.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, between 15 percent and 20 percent of the $4.3 million
in computers Stupid PC sold were to businesses. Most of that
business came from word of mouth, said Bart Brannon, president and
chief executive officer. The $4.3 million in revenue is up from
$3.5 million in sales in Stupid PC's first 12 months. Stupid PC
employs 18 people, most in offices off Peachtree Industrial
Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   Stupid PC was started in March 1997 over drinks at a Mexican
restaurant. The idea, Brannon said, was to make buying and setting
up a computer simple. Brannon tailored Stupid PC's business and
marketing plan accordingly. The company includes delivery and one
hour of instruction for each computer it sells. Promotional
material refers to processor speed as ``oomph.'' Stupid PC's Web
site refers to technical support as ``help with your 'puter.'' The
company's delivery and setup staff is known as ``the geeks.''
</P>
<P>
   But can a company that proudly dresses itself in overalls cater
to the blue-suit market?
</P>
<P>
   ``Our advertising seems to work with the business market as
well,'' said Brannon.
</P>
<P>
   He said he has no plans to change his marketing focus. ``At
least not a whole lot,'' he said. ``We've met with a marketing
company, and they seem to think we're on the right track. Maybe
we'll focus more on the geeks.''
</P>
<P>
   In November, Stupid PC completed its merger with World Net
Holdings. Stupid PC is traded on the OTC under the symbol STPX.
With the merger came about $600,000 from a London investment group,
Trident Trust Co. Stupid PC is using the investment and money from
stock sales to fuel expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Some of that expansion will come in the form of retail stores,
which Brannon expects to cost about $50,000 each to open and
promote. The first opens in Marietta, off North Marietta Parkway,
the first week in February. A Charlotte store opens later next
month. Branches in Orlando and southeast Atlanta are expected by
May, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Next is electronic commerce. Brannon said Stupid PC's Web site
received 170,000 hits in December. Customers can order a computer
by e-mail or with a toll-free phone number. He hopes adding the
ability to buy a computer with a credit card from the company site
will entice some of the 170,000 visitors to stop browsing and start
buying. The electronic commerce option is expected to be available
by April, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Clothier writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
