A1051 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-TESTS14-COX     01-13 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-TESTS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Company building a better Y2K trap
 &HT;    By Rob Chambers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Most PC software programs that test for Y2K problems
conduct limited searches. These explore only the computer's first
two layers, its real time clock and its BIOS, a chip in which basic
instructions have been hard wired.
</P>
<P>
   But most problems happen at the third level, in the operating
systems such as Windows or UNIX , claims Alpharetta, Ga.-based
Client/Server Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Their updated product tests all three layers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are unique things about our product, `Foundation/2000,
version 9,' '' said Alfred Nickles, president of the company.
``First, we test the operating system's application programming
interfaces, the path that programs use to access time and date
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do that in conjunction with testing the BIOS and the real
time clock. The issue here is, while individual pieces may be
compliant, the sum of the pieces may not be. There is no other test
product on the market that we are aware of that tests these
interfaces.''
</P>
<P>
   Competitors, though, aren't ready to acknowledge the Alpharetta
company has the better Y2K trap. ``There are a lot of products out
there and they all do things a little differently,'' said Suzanne
Sliter, spokesman for Centennial 2000 made by Centennial
International in Burlingame, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fix the BIOS with our product, and if the real time clock,
a hardware piece that can't be fixed using software, is OK, that's
all the fixing that's necessary,'' she said. ``The key is the BIOS.
You gotta fix the BIOS.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, it's important to obtain compliance statements from
application manufacturers. We provide all of this testing plus an
inventory of applications that can be used to obtain compliance
statements,'' Sliter said.
</P>
<P>
   Her company's product starts at $48 per PC and can be ordered at
650-373-2090.
</P>
<P>
   One of Client/Server Technologies' major customers doesn't agree
with Sliter's assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe there's a Year 2000 exposure that goes beyond
checking the BIOS and the real time clock, and this is the only
product we found that does that,'' said Jim Deffenbaugh, vice
president, technology, at Equifax. ``We've been real pleased with
the product and the level of support.''
</P>
<P>
   One problem: The Client/Server Technologies product tests for
Y2K and issues reports, but it doesn't fix the glitches.
</P>
<P>
   The company was founded in 1993, employs 11 and has been in the
Year 2000 business since 1995. In addition to Equifax, clients
include BellSouth and several U.S. intelligence agencies, Nickles
said.
</P>
<P>
   Client/Server Technologies is located at 3050 Royal Blvd. S.,
Suite 180, Alpharetta, GA 30022.
</P>
<P>
   Companies can order the testing program at 770-360-6302, and
individuals can download it from the Internet (http://www.f2k.com).
The cost is $49.95.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Chambers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
