<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Snow days are exciting...at first
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ On the first day school is canceled, it is all
joy and snowman-making and sled-riding. And guilty pleasure as the
routine of the work week fishtails like a Camaro on bald tires.
</P>
<P>
   On the second day, it is all joy and game-playing and
video-watching. Grandma and Grandpa are delighted to watch the kids
again. The boss is understanding when you can't make it in. The
older kids are thrilled to be home alone, impressed with their
newfound independence.
</P>
<P>
   On the third day, it is all joy and snowball fights and playing
with the Christmas presents, some of them for the first time. But
the grandparents have plans. The boss sounds a little less
understanding.
</P>
<P>
   On the fourth day, you become alarmed when your 3-year old has
memorized the script of Here Come the Teletubbies , and chortles
through dinner, ``Who spilled the Tubby c-c-custard?''
</P>
<P>
   The 7-year-old becomes so adept at playing Clue you wonder if
he's headed for a career as a private investigator. Or a life of
crime.
</P>
<P>
   The lists to the older kids become as elaborate as a war room
map, beginning with ``Do not put the Tupperware in the oven'' and
building up to ``Do not feed the Godiva to the pet iguana.''
</P>
<P>
   In a level 1 cabin fever emergency, you're excited about running
out of diapers and having an excuse to run to Kroger's.
</P>
<P>
   On the fifth day, you're muttering things you never thought
you'd say: ``Back in our day, we never had snow days for an entire
week. Back in our day, they sure cleared the streets a lot
faster.'' Your third cousin, 15 times removed, agrees to watch the
kids for $100 a day.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-year-old invites a friend over, pleads demonic possession
_ ``I don't know what came over me'' _ when dismembered doll parts
are found all over the basement floor.
</P>
<P>
   On the sixth day, you start to envision a future in which little
Johnny, 15, is still in the third grade.
</P>
<P>
   In a level 2 cabin fever emergency, you drag out the lawn chairs
and watch the parade of snow plows.
</P>
<P>
   On the seventh day, sinister thoughts creep into your mind about
a conspiracy between the road department and the board of
education. No doubt they're all hunkered down at the Club Med in
Maui, enjoying a good laugh over their daiquiris.
</P>
<P>
   In a level 3 cabin fever emergency, an invitation to Chuck E.
Cheese's is gratefully accepted.
</P>
<P>
   On the 45th day, the boss turns the cafeteria into a child care
center; food fights break out.
</P>
<P>
   On the 153rd day, Dayton records its first June snowfall: 27
inches.
</P>
<P>
   On the 401st day the snow holds off, but a lone ice patch
cancels school . . . for the entire Miami Valley.
</P>
<P>
   On the 845th day President Dole declares a state of emergency .
. . for the entire state.
</P>
<P>
   On the 1,251st day, Johnny looks over his fourth-grade book list
and shaves for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   On the 3,453rd day, President Clinton pardons her husband for
the third time; Johnny gets drafted, but requests an educational
deferment.
</P>
<P>
   On the 6,521st day, potholes the size of the baseball stadium
cancel school for a month.
</P>
<P>
   On the 21,419th day, the rains come and never stop. A giant ark
is built and nervous cityfolk scramble to get on. Elderly first,
declares the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with the third-graders.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
