</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Replacing paddles with gavels
 &HT;    (ATTENTION, Georgia, Texas editors.)
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Children and teen-agers should be disciplined by
their parents and teachers, not the government.
</P>
<P>
   Little wonder that the Supreme Court was openly skeptical of the
argument that a Georgia school system should be held liable under
federal law for failing to stop a male student from sexually
harassing a female student.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the support of feminist groups in behalf of the former
fifth-grader's efforts to extend Title IX's prohibition of sex
discrimination into elementary classrooms, Justice Stephen Breyer,
often identified as an anchor of the court's liberal wing, observed
that such a ruling ``would take that problem from educators and
psychologists and give that problem to lawyers and judges.''
</P>
<P>
   So little Johnnie taunts, teases and sexually harasses little
Susie. As a result, little Johnnie and a boatload of adults around
little Johnnie are hauled into federal court where the child's bad
behavior enriches lawyers and further clogs the nation's courts.
</P>
<P>
   The first time little Johnnie harasses little Susie he should be
hauled into the principal's office where his little fanny is
paddled. Then little Johnnie should be sent home with a note
describing his behavior.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, little Johnnie should be quaking in his Nikes.
The discipline he will receive from his parents will be far worse
than any punishment he would ever receive from his teachers or his
principal.
</P>
<P>
   With divine intervention his only hope to avoid his parents'
wrath, little Johnnie learns how to issue his first unprompted
heavenly petition.
</P>
<P>
   That's how children used to disciplined before the first
generation of parents in the 1960s rejected parental discipline as
fascist, authoritarian and destructive of their children's
creativity. That's when the inmates took over the asylum.
</P>
<P>
   The concept of permissive parenting eventually merged with
fallout from the destruction of traditional nuclear families. The
result of skyrocketing divorce rates, single-parent homes,
dual-wage earner homes and permissive parenting has been
generations of undisciplined children.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than discipline children, the trend over the past several
decades has been to understand why children misbehave.
</P>
<P>
   School counselors and family therapists now attempt to do the
job abdicated by parents and educators.
</P>
<P>
   In large measure, the result has been children who refuse to
obey parents. With no assured punishment for disobeying firm,
consistent and fair rules, children know they don't have to do
anything they don't want to do. The only consequence of misbehavior
might be a chat with a counselor or a therapist.
</P>
<P>
   Having never learned the lessons of discipline from their
parents or teachers, many of these children grow into teen-agers
who see no reason to obey the law anymore than they obeyed their
parents.
</P>
<P>
   As a consequence, lawmakers are asked to enforce discipline and
punishment on children with tougher juvenile crime laws and
curfews. They also pass anti-gang laws and build juvenile boot
camps. Taxpayers pony up to build alternative schools and hire more
counselors for undisciplined children.
</P>
<P>
   As surrogate parents, lawmakers use the power of the state to
restrict the ability to juveniles to get tatoos, pierce their
bodies, smoke cigarettes, drink alcohol, obtain a driver's license,
eat in restaurants where alcohol sales exceed food sales, play loud
music or sit anywhere in a vehicle without a seat belt.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Supreme Court is being asked to empower the federal
government's lawyers and bureaucrats to go into the nation's
elementary schools to ensure that little Johnnie doesn't sexually
harass little Susie.
</P>
<P>
   Little Johnnie's sexual harassment is inexcusable. But it should
be the job of Johnnie's parents and educators to teach him
discipline, not the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald. E-mail: RNeth(AT)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
