<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANIMAL-SCHOOL14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Class' wildlife at Bear Lakes eats up about $60 month
 &HT;    By Stephanie Desmon
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Your eighth-grade science class probably
wasn't like Branden Hursey's.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there was a fish tank or a gerbil or two.
</P>
<P>
   But did you have anything like Pete the prairie dog, who burrows
under the courtyard? Or Ferris the emu, who sits atop 14 eggs which
could mean as many as 14 baby birds in the coming weeks? Or Floyd
the iguana, found sunning himself on the Bear Lakes Middle School
roof Tuesday morning?
</P>
<P>
   ``We get to feed them _ things like that _ get to know them
better,'' said Branden, who is often reminded of his favorite
television network. ``This is the closest we've got (to The
Discovery Channel) because we've got lizards and pythons and
emus.''
</P>
<P>
   The class is Ag Science _ a basic care and feeding of plants and
animals. The elective is taught by Charlie McDaniel, who started
the menagerie with the standard gerbils and rabbits five years ago.
The first emu was donated by a friend a year later and over the
years, more and more have been added to _ or born into _ McDaniel's
collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this class, we study all kinds of things that relate to
environmental horticulture and that's how everything fits
together,'' he explained. ``The animals are just part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   There are too many animals to count. Three emus, three iguanas,
several snakes and many chickens. Three furry white guinea pigs
were born this week, bringing the total to more than 30 guinea
pigs. A gerbil was born during first period Tuesday, a hairless,
sightless creature for now. Then there are the mice, which are
actually bred to feed to those snakes (another class lesson).
</P>
<P>
   This is the only class of its kind in the Palm Beach County
schools and officials support it, said district spokesman Nat
Harrington. Still, he said, they are working on a policy to govern
the use of animals in the curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   The animals help keep the students in line, McDaniel said.
Behavior problems are next to nothing in Ag Science, partly because
his idea of punishment is: You can't feed the animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a real knack with (students),'' said Pam Witczak, a
special education teacher whose students also take McDaniel's
class. ``Children who have difficulty in other classes do really
well with him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's absolutely phenomenal,'' said Andrea Peppers,
Bear Lakes' principal. ``It's a one-of-a-kind program that does so
much for the children. . . . It has a calming effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the burden of taking care of the zoo falls on McDaniel,
who spends time on weekends and over holidays making sure they have
enough chow. The food costs about $60 a month, covered by
fund-raisers and supplemented by local nurseries who donate the
extra fruit some of the animals eat.
</P>
<P>
   Guinea pigs get oranges and grapefruit; iguanas get bananas.
Emus eat stuff that comes in a bag marked ``Emu Food.'' And Pete
the prairie dog eats everyone else's food.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest treat of all for the students could come next week,
when the first of Ferris' eggs are due to hatch (another lesson:
Male emus incubate the eggs, not the females). Emus are rarely born
out of the wild and though the last thing McDaniel needs is another
litter of animals, he's excited.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not even supposed to do this in captivity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Desmon writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
