<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 10:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1060 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDS-AT-WORK14-COX     01-13 1203
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-AT-WORK14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When every day is Take Your Child to Work Day
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Anais Hernandez has a dream setup at
work, an arrangement that might inspire rabid jealousy in any
mother who worries about putting her baby in day care.
</P>
<P>
   At 7:30 a.m., Hernandez arrives at Dr. John H. Merey's office
with her 14-month-old daughter, Alondra. She puts the toddler into
a portable playpen behind the front desk and starts her day as
part-time receptionist at the eye surgeon's office in West Palm
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Alondra sits in the playpen, content to fiddle with her toys and
yammer a steady vowel movement of baby talk. Occasionally, she
pulls herself up to ogle the latest person standing at the front
desk. Patients take turns cooing at the doe-eyed girl as they pay
their bills or schedule another appointment with her mother.
</P>
<P>
   As if the situation couldn't be more ideal, Hernandez leaves at
1:30 p.m. to go to her second part-time job, this time handling the
billing for internist Dr. Jose Allongo. Another portable playpen
and a second batch of toys at the new office keeps the little girl
happy while mommy works until 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond saving money that she and her husband, Ramon, would
otherwise spend on day care, Hernandez has the comfort of enjoying
every moment of her daughter's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more important for her to have me around at this age than
when she's 3 years old,'' Hernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   And Merey, who had the idea for Hernandez to bring Alondra to
work, gets to keep a valuable employee.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's more relaxed here with the baby than if she was here and
the baby was being watched by someone else,'' he says. ``I don't
see why more employers don't do this.''
</P>
<P>
   The kids-at-work concept is growing in popularity, labor experts
say. Some companies have found that employees _ who are spending
more time at the office and must juggle child-care arrangements _
are happier and more productive when the children are cared for
on-site. According to the National Childcare Survey, 12 million
children younger than 6, as well as 17 million school-age
youngsters, have their sole parent or both parents in the work
force.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, parents are flocking to family-friendly employers.
In its rankings of America's 100 best companies to work for,
Fortune magazine said 31 of those employers offer on-site child
care. Software developer SAS Institute in Cary, N.C., was ranked at
No. 4, mainly because it offers a 35-hour workweek, a child-care
facility that costs just $250 a month and a paid week off between
Christmas and New Year's _ when kids are out of school.
</P>
<P>
   Some employers, like NationsBank, try to help employees with
emergency child-care problems. NationsBank provides a child-care
subsidy to its lowest-paid workers who might not have alternatives
when school is out. Employees who earn less than $60,000 a year
receive a $35-a-week stipend. The banking giant also operates
child-care facilities at its main offices in Jacksonville, Fla. and
Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   But bringing children to the office _ either on a temporary
basis or full-time _ still has many pitfalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's wonderful in an emergency situation, such as when
the day care is closed one day or if the baby sitter is sick, but I
don't think it's the ideal situation,'' said Robin Hardman, a
spokeswoman for the Families and Work Institute in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, mothers who repeatedly bring children to the
office eventually bump into problems either keeping the child
content, keeping pace with the workload at hand or avoiding the
stigma from co-workers who assume they aren't focused enough on
their job.
</P>
<P>
   Hardman should know. When her son was born in 1996, she brought
him to the office three times a week for the first eight months.
Co-workers loved it so much, they adopted him as the office mascot.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we knew that once he started to crawl, it would be all
over,'' Hardman said. ``There is no way that I could childproof the
whole office. There were paper clips people dropped, all sorts of
things on the floor. Plus, it wasn't fair for him, to be stuck in a
swing with no one paying attention.''
</P>
<P>
   It was difficult to concentrate on her job and her child at the
same time, she said. Enough so that when her daughter was born five
months ago, she didn't consider bringing her to the office. ``It's
just not practical.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez said she understands how rare her arrangement is. It
helps that she works in a small office with few co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   It also helps that she introduced Alondra to the office and the
playpen early on instead of waiting until she was 6 months old. The
little girl has always come to the office, so she is familiar with
the constant stream of visitors and acts as if she's at home.
</P>
<P>
   There are days when decorum breaks down into a crying jag.
Alondra is, after all, a toddler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I will let her cry and not pay attention to her,''
Hernandez said. ``It lasts 10, 15 minutes, tops.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Hernandez doesn't miss anything in her daughter's
life. That alone makes up for the effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a baby sitter I could use,'' she said. ``But no one
takes care of her better than I do.'' Guidelines to let kids
whistle while you work
</P>
<P>
   If you take your child to work, it doesn't matter whether your
office is at home or in a corporate tower: You have to keep that
youngster entertained long enough to get some work done.
</P>
<P>
   Workplace experts pose these questions, which you should
consider before bringing a child into the workplace:
</P>
<P>
   Will your boss, co-workers and human resources department be
sympathetic?
</P>
<P>
   Do you work directly with the public or in a job where
interruptions can't be tolerated?
</P>
<P>
   Is your child old enough that she doesn't require frequent
attention? How long is his attention span? Are engaging activities
available, or will your child bother you because he or she is
bored?
</P>
<P>
   Is your workplace safe for children?
</P>
<P>
   Is a private place available where your child can be isolated,
should that become necessary?
</P>
<P>
   Could your child damage delicate equipment or merchandise?
</P>
<P>
   Is your child well-behaved and polite?
</P>
<P>
   Do you have the right toys at the office? Make sure they're
quiet, engaging and flexible enough that a kid can use them over
and over and not get bored. Construction toys such as Legos or
Tinkertoys are fine for school-age kids 5 and up. For younger
children, stick to a pack of paper and crayons. Older children will
enjoy storybook tapes and a cassette player with headphones.
</P>
<P>
   Have you established rules, such as no playing on the computer
or no touching the copying machine? Let them know what they can and
cannot do.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of break are you planning? Give them an escape from
the office near the middle of the day so the child will know this
won't last forever.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: Working Mother magazine; The Best Toys, Books, Videos &AMP;
Software for Kids, (Prima Publishing, $13); Families and Work
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Houck writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
