<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Snow days not so popular with Ohio school officials
 &HT;    (ATTENTION Ohio editors.)
 &HT;    By Jim Bebbington
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Local school officials can expect a chilly
reception if they go to the Ohio legislature seeking additional
snow days.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers who would have to approve any increase in the
number of calamity days granted school districts said Tuesday they
did not think an extension was likely.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio school districts are allotted five ``calamity days'' each
year. Several area districts, including Dayton, Trotwood-Madison,
Beavercreek and Tipp City, have missed seven days due to the recent
winter storms. Several others are also over the five-day limit,
including Vandalia-Butler, Kettering and Centerville with six.
</P>
<P>
   ``(An extension) would not be easy,'' said state Sen. Gene
Watts, R-Dublin. ``We would look at that very skeptically. We need
more school, not less.''
</P>
<P>
   Districts must have a contingency plan for how they will make up
the sixth to 10th calamity day if they exceed the five-day limit.
State lawmakers added that rule in the aftermath of ice storms and
a bitterly cold winter in 1995-96, when the legislature ended up
waiving minimum school year requirements to prevent classes in some
areas from extending into late June.
</P>
<P>
   Among big districts around Ohio, Cleveland and Akron have used
four days, Columbus has used three, and Cincinnati entered this
week having used two. Some school districts in northwestern Ohio
have used more than five calamity days, having lost time earlier to
fog.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers said urban districts especially have a difficult time
pleading for additional calamity days because it is assumed cities
have the resources to clear the streets after a storm.
</P>
<P>
   If there are no more storms, schools will have to make up their
days, legislators said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless something major pops, the answer is no,'' said state
Rep. Jim Buchy, R-Greenville.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton school officials said they have not talked about asking
for more days. They plan to add two days in June to make up for the
extra snow days, said district spokeswoman Jill Moberley.
</P>
<P>
   Tipp City Schools will not have to reschedule any days as long
as they do not miss any more because of the weather, said school
spokeswoman Kitty Lobo. The district had two extra class days built
into the schedule beyond the 178 required by state law.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Bebbington writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
