</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIRED-MAILMAN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sleepy mailcarrier has much to answer for in upcoming court
appearance
 &HT;    (ATTENTION: Ohio editors)
 &HT;    By Wes Hills
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Maybe rain or sleet can't stop postal workers _
but what if they're tired?
</P>
<P>
   A former mail carrier has been charged with keeping and opening
30,383 letters and packages, including 208 parcels _ and
authorities are holding it all as evidence until the case is
closed.
</P>
<P>
   James S. Wynn, 54, faces a maximum of five years in prison and a
$250,000 fine, is charged in U.S. District Court in Dayton in a
bill of information. Bills of information are filed when defendants
agree to waive their right to first have their cases heard by grand
juries and agree to enter a plea.
</P>
<P>
   Wynn is scheduled to appear Friday before U.S. District Judge
Walter H. Rice.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities were tight-lipped about the mail contents, and
postal officials would only say Wynn's route was in West Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   One source close to the case, however, said it appears Wynn was
tired more than anything else and figured he could deliver certain
mail later. Doug Ervin, a postal inspector, said he will be able to
say more about the case after Wynn's court appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Ervin did say that authorities found some Social Security checks
in the undelivered mail and the Social Security Administration has
been advised of the addresses on those checks.
</P>
<P>
   That, in turn, allowed the Social Security office to contact the
person ``directly and re-issue the checks to them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ervin said Wynn resigned ``shortly after he was confronted and
realized that the inspection service was aware of what he allegedly
had done.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the case is closed, Erwin said ``all efforts will be made
to deliver this mail to the rightful owners.''
</P>
<P>
   One source close to the probe said it appears Wynn primarily
didn't deliver junk mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Wynn) made sure the important stuff got delivered,'' the
source said. ``When he got behind on his route, he'd put the heavy
catalogs'' and other third-class mail in his home with the hope
``of getting to them later.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Erwin said he hopes the public understands that
wrongful conduct is involved in ``less than one-half of 1 percent''
of the mail delivery.
</P>
<P>
   When Wynn's case gets settled, however, is up in the air. His
Friday hearing may have to be postponed because his attorney is
preparing to resign from the case, according to Montgomery County
Prosecutor Matt Heck.
</P>
<P>
   Wynn selected assistant Montgomery County Prosecutor Carla Y.
Jones to represent him. But Heck said his assistants may not act as
a defense attorney in a local criminal case.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is absolutely not permitted by me,'' Heck said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Heck said Jones' father asked her to represent Wynn because he
was a friend of her family for several years. Heck said Jones took
the case without telling anyone in his office. But he said he did
tell federal prosecutors that she is a county prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is very apologetic,'' Heck said of Jones. ``She is
basically a young lawyer. She simply made a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Wes Hills writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
