<HEADER>
A1067 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-SOUP14-COX     01-13 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SOUP14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Soup is a good food, and a warming one too
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Chicken soup may be the ultimate winter comfort
food, not just for those with a cold or flu, but for those weary of
the sight of ice ruts and the whirring sound of slipping tires.
</P>
<P>
   But soup can be as stimulating as it is soothing. With
imaginative seasonings, a bowl of soup can be an invitation to play
Let's Pretend.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine exploring the exotic markets in Morocco. Fantasize about
the beaches of Cancun or the eternal springtime of Oaxaca or San
Miguel. Indulge dreams of trekking through the temples of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, turn your back on the snow piled high outside.
Put on a pot of soup, steam up the windows and pretend you are
somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   The quick-cooking soup pictured here uses the exotic flavors of
Moroccan cuisine to become a flavorful and filling meal in a bowl
that's ready in 15 to 20 minutes. The recipe is adapted from
Cooking to Beat the Clock by Sam Gugino (Chronicle, $16.95). Using
boneless skinless chicken thighs trimmed of fat really bumps up the
flavor. I wanted a dab of Harissa, the fiery Moroccan condiment
made from red peppers, to add excitement, although the recipe's
generous seasoning with cumin and ginger provides a flavorful base.
Look for Harissa at specialty stores specializing in Middle Eastern
foods.
</P>
<P>
   Because the emphasis is on speed, the author uses a food
processor to chop the onions. That's fine if you take care not to
overprocess the onion, which can quickly become a watery puree in
the machine.
</P>
<P>
   MOROCCAN CHICKEN SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 pound boneless skinless chicken thighs
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon hot paprika
</P>
<P>
   5 cups fat-free chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   2 medium zucchini
</P>
<P>
   cup couscous
</P>
<P>
   1 16-ounce can chickpeas, rinsed and drained
</P>
<P>
   salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   8 sprigs cilantro
</P>
<P>
   Harissa
</P>
<P>
   Put the oil in a deep, heavy skillet over medium-high heat. Use
scissors to trim away any pockets of fat and cut the chicken into
inch cubes. Add to the skillet, raise heat to high and stir once or
twice while browning.
</P>
<P>
   While the chicken browns, peel and quarter the onion and put in
a food processor. Pulse until just chopped. Add the onion, cumin,
ginger and paprika to the skillet. Stir and cook for 1 minute. Add
the stock to the skillet and stir with a wooden spoon, scraping any
bits from the bottom. (Note: The soup can be made ahead to this
point and kept warm before proceeding.) Cover the soup and bring to
a boil.
</P>
<P>
   While the soup heats, trim the zucchini and slice in half
lengthwise. Cut crosswise into inch wide half-moons. When the soup
comes to a boil, add the zucchini and the couscous. Stir and add
the drained chickpeas. Cover and let the soup return to a boil,
then lower the heat so the soup simmers for 4 minutes. Season with
salt and pepper to taste. (The amount of salt depends on the
saltiness of the broth used. Start with teaspoon). Chop the leaves
from the cilantro and stir into the soup. Cook for 1 minute and
serve.
</P>
<P>
   Or substitute teaspoon sweet paparika and teaspoon cayenne.
</P>
<P>
   Harissa is available in tubes in some specialty and Middle
Eastern food stores.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate nutritional analysis per serving: 425 calories, 11.9
g fat, 94 mg cholesterol, 1,218 mg sodium (amount will be lower if
chick peas are well rinsed).
</P>
<P>
   Ann Heller writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
