NYT-01-13-99 1038EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 10:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1068 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JANIS14-COX     01-13 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JANIS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mitrovich sings as herself, not Joplin
 &HT;    (ATTENTION: OHIO, TEXAS editors.)
 &HT;    By Chris Riemenschneider
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ There's a thin, awkward line between exploiting
dead rock legends and using their memories to create something
heartfelt, immediate and real. Andra Mitrovich felt relieved when
she learned that Big Brother and the Holding Company didn't want
her to cross that line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on an elevator with (Big Brother guitarist) Sam Andrew
after our rehearsal,'' the 31-year-old Austinite said last week,
remembering the night in December when she first joined the
legendary San Francisco band that helped launch Janis Joplin.
Mitrovich played Joplin in Zachary Scott Theatre's musical ``Love,
Janis.''
</P>
<P>
   She continued, ``Sam asked me, 'Andra, you didn't bring any
Janis garb, did you?' I said, 'No. To tell you the truth, I was
hoping to sing as Andra Mitrovich tonight and not Janis Joplin.' He
said, 'Good, that's exactly what we want.'''
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake about it, Mitrovich and the founding members of
Big Brother and the Holding Company _ Andrew, Dave Getz and Peter
Albin _ have an adoration for Janis that Melissa Etheridge herself
could never quell (Etheridge was rumored to be portraying the Texas
icon in one of two upcoming film biographies). But when the band
members get together with the Austin performer for a series of
Texas gigs this month, none of them are interested in reincarnating
Joplin's musical ghost.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she had a good night, she sang as good as anyone in pop
music _ simple fact,'' Andrew said of Joplin, who got her musical
start as a folkie when she was briefly a student at the University
of Texas. ``But we are musicians, too. These tunes are fun to play,
and we think we actually say something new when we play them now.''
</P>
<P>
   The thing to remember about Big Brother and the Holding Company,
as well as many of the songs they still perform, is that they were
around before Joplin joined and after she left. The singer, who
died of an accidental heroin overdose in 1970 at the age of 27, was
only with the group for about two years before she and Andrew left
to form the Kozmic Blues Band. Even when she was with Big Brother,
Janis often lent the limelight to the other members, as evident in
the recently released ``Live at Winterland '68'' CD.
</P>
<P>
   Mitrovich, meanwhile, was a singer who happened to look and
sound like Janis, which led to a great opportunity to play the
troubled rock queen at Zachary Scott Theater. She went on to win a
B. Iden Payne Award for her performance last year. If anything, the
award showed that Mitrovich was portraying Joplin _ not trying to
be her.
</P>
<P>
   The two singers do share odd similarities, though. Mitrovich's
birthday is a day after Joplin's (Jan. 19). Mitrovich also grew up
in a refinery-laden Texas coastal town, LaMarque, much like
Joplin's native Port Arthur. And, said Mitrovich, ``I wasn't liked
by anybody at my high school, either.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mitrovich is quick to point out, ``I'm not a fanatic. I
don't have all the recordings. I don't go to the museums and try
and steal feathers from her boa. . . . I grew up listening to her
music and admiring her persona, just like so many other people.''
</P>
<P>
   The key similarity Andrew sees between the two singers is their
singularity. ``Believe me (Andra) has a big, big personality,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew first came across Mitrovich when he attended the opening
of ``Love, Janis'' in Austin in 1996. The two met after the show
and, later, at several other Janis-related functions. But it wasn't
until this fall, when another young woman singing with the band
opted out, that Andrew contacted Mitrovich about singing.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Janis' shadow set aside, few probably would have
guessed that Big Brother and the Holding Company would still be
playing together, almost 35 years after it became the house band at
the Avalon Ballroom in San Francisco and helped kick off the city's
revolutionary psychedelic era. When Joplin's star began shining
brightly after the 1967 Monterey Pop Festival and the release of
the ``Cheap Thrills'' album, the band was hit hard by critics who
said its musicianship was amateurish and that Joplin could do
better without the band _ words she eventually believed. Andrew,
who also left the band then but soon rejoined, said he and Janis
made a ``big mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she would have been better off someday . . . but she
left too early, and so did I,'' he said. ``Full Tilt Boogie Band
was good and they were starting to build a solid friendship with
Janis when she died, but Janis never reached the same rapport with
another band that she reached with Big Brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Big Brother continues to tour and record semi-regularly.
Following the Texas tour, which includes a stop at Port Arthur's
Janis Joplin Birthday Bash on Saturday, Mitrovich will prepare for
a spring run of ``Love, Janis'' in Cleveland. The Rock and Roll
Hall of Fame Museum in Cleveland is opening a new Joplin exhibit to
coincide with the production. Mitrovich hopes to hook up with the
band there, and anywhere else she can.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really felt good about singing with the band when Peter
(Albin), their biggest skeptic, told me I worked well because I
don't fake Janis, I feel her, and I feel the music,'' she said.
``That's what it's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Riemenschneider writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
