</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VIKINGS-RANDLE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Versatility, effort define Vikings defensive tackle
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINTER PARK, Minn. _ Remember Keith Millard, the 1989 NFC
defensive player of the year? A ferocious, dominant defensive
lineman. A run-stopping, pass-rushing juggernaut. Well, Dennis
Green took over the Vikings in '92 and promptly traded him. It
seems there was a young, fearless terror who displayed the
potential to redefine the position and make everyone forget about
Millard.
</P>
<P>
   A decade later, Green is still right. Millard's name has hardly
been raised in these frigid parts since, primarily because John
Randle fulfilled Green's prophecy. Make that exceeded the coach's
expectations. Surpassed anyone's expectations.
</P>
<P>
   In the seasons since Millard was jettisoned, Randle has made the
Pro Bowl seven times. He has 86 sacks from '91-97 _ more than
anyone else. Keith who?
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of scared me at first,'' Randle said about the Millard
trade. ``I mean, I was supposed to replace Keith Millard, a guy who
did this and that. Coach Green told me not to be worried about all
that, (to) relax and play. Finally, I was able to just forget about
everything and just go out and play.''
</P>
<P>
   He's played the best defensive line of anyone. And Randle has
been so dominating because he plays all over the line. He rushes
the quarterback from the left side and the right and the middle. He
rushes from a down stance and from an upright position. He stops
the run and attacks on the pass.
</P>
<P>
   And Randle attributes his ability to play various positions to,
of all things, basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to emulate basketball players,'' he said, ``a guy like
Michael Jordan or like Charles Barkley. I get my versatility from
watching a guy like Jordan. I'm able to line up on both sides. I
got my spin move from Charles Barkley. When you watch him play,
he's more likely to push you, push you and then spin off you to get
to the basket. I got those moves from watching basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching Randle work during practice and games is to witness the
ultimate, tireless competitor, his teammates say. That's really
what seems to separate Randle from others who are as physically
gifted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy the game so much,'' he said. ``I just go out there and
just play as hard as I can. When I'm out there, I want to make the
most of it. I want to let everyone on the field know, `Hey I'm out
here, too.'''
</P>
<P>
   It's highly unlikely Randle goes unnoticed by anyone. Surely the
Falcons will doubleteam him during Sunday's NFC Championship game
at the Metrodome. His teammates notice how committed he is to
preparing himself and to performing at a high level.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see the kind of work he puts into it is amazing,''
defensive line mate Derrick Alexander said. ``I've learned to
appreciate it. It's uplifting to everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone except the opposition. Green Bay's Brett Favre said
earlier this season: ``John is the toughest player I play. On
artificial turf, he's unblockable.''
</P>
<P>
   In October, the NFL blocked one of Randle's pregame rituals that
he's done for years. Some called it petty, others called it
ridiculous, but the league, in a harshly written letter, fined
Randle $10,000 and told him he could no longer line his face with
black paint on game days. It violated the NFL Uniform and Equipment
Rules. ``Specifically, you used black paint to cover your face,''
the letter said, although paint on the face was neither on his
uniform or equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just tried to find a way to stop me,'' he said, knowing
that it wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing that can stop Randle is, well, no one's
sure. Maybe injury. He's hampered with a knee problem this week,
suffered in the Arizona win Sunday, but no one among the Vikings
believes he would miss a game that decides who represents the NFC
in the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah, I'm pretty sure John'll be there,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   Randle will start getting emotionally ready for Atlanta early
Sunday morning. ``My body is alive when I wake up on the day of a
game,'' he said. And he gets more excited as the day progresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if I play in Alaska or the middle of a desert,''
he said. ``Just give me 10 teammates and a chance to get to the
Super Bowl and I'll be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Randle, 31, had a tough but happy childhood in rural Hearne,
Texas. And it's a reason he's so relentless on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've chopped cotton, picked watermelons, built fences, worked
on an assembly line, worked in an oil field, built scaffolding,''
he said. ``You know what? Those jobs are harder than football. So,
I'll never take it easy in football.''
</P>
<P>
   THE JOHN RANDLE FILE
</P>
<P>
   _ Position: Defensive tackle.
</P>
<P>
   _ Size: 6 feet 1, 285.
</P>
<P>
   _ College: Texas A&AMP;I.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1998 stats: 42 tackles, 10.5 sacks
</P>
<P>
   _ Honors: Names to Pro Bowl team seven straight seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
