<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUHN-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    And that reminds me....
 &HT;    By Gary Nuhn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Notes, quotes &AMP; winter coats . . .
</P>
<P>
   Unlike politicians, Michael Jordan is apparently going to ignore
the polls. I say apparently because I hold out hope.
</P>
<P>
   Eight NFL head coaches have been fired or left their jobs, and
none of them was named Bruce Coslet. I think I saw that movie once:
Against All Odds.
</P>
<P>
   Nice game of Musical Chairs the boys are playing, too. Ray
Rhodes, fired in Philadelphia, takes over in Green Bay. Andy Reid,
the Green Bay quarterback coach, replaces Rhodes in Philadelphia.
One man's trash is another man's treasure, and trash-versa.
</P>
<P>
   Two days into 1999, we had a frontrunner for Classless Act of
the Year: After his Dolphins beat Buffalo, Miami coach Jimmy
Johnson ripped up a box of Flutie Flakes and flung the cereal
across the locker room floor.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't know, Bills quarterback Doug Flutie's son was born
with autism, and profits from Flutie Flakes go to help people with
the disorder. Really hated to see Jimmy get drilled by Denver in
the next round, 38-3. Denver should have spread some of his
hairspray on its floor.
</P>
<P>
   In the interest of full disclosure, I checked five names on my
Hall of Fame ballot: Nolan Ryan, George Brett, Tony Perez, Tommy
John and Jim Kaat. No Robin Yount. I didn't consider him
first-ballot worthy, although I would have voted for him next year
had he not made it.
</P>
<P>
   My Heisman ballot: 1. Ricky Williams of Texas; 2. Tim Couch of
Kentucky; 3. Donovan McNabb of Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   Since I've ripped Big Ten football _ deservedly _ these many
years, I must say now that the conference was the best in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The Buckeyes will miss David Boston more than Andy Katzenmoyer,
but they'll miss Joe Germaine more than either of them.
</P>
<P>
   If I'm the Browns, I trade that No. 1 pick and get a starter and
a No. 1 pick in return. Ricky Williams isn't going anywhere without
an offensive line and, as Jacksonville showed (with Mark Brunell),
expansion teams need mobile quarterbacks, of which Couch isn't one.
</P>
<P>
   Remember O.J. at Buffalo before they put together The Electric
Company?
</P>
<P>
   If I'm the Bengals, I'm looking real hard at offensive tackles
(BYU's John Tait, Georgia's Matt Stinchcomb or UCLA's Kris Farris).
Any or all of these guys might be an anchor who you put in the
lineup and then don't worry about for the next 12 years. The
Bengals blew it the last time this came up when they took Ki-Jana
Carter instead of tackle Tony Boselli.
</P>
<P>
   My four-team playoff after the bowl games would have been
Tennessee, Ohio State, Florida and Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's national championship the year after Peyton Manning
left reminds me of a duplicate in college basketball. After Oscar
Robertson left Cincinnati (1960), the Bearcats won the next two
national championships.
</P>
<P>
   Fox-TV's ace play-by-play announcer, Pat Summerall, has
officially come to a point where he is as lost as Robinson Crusoe.
My favorite of his 317 miscalls or no-calls this season came in
October. Terrell Davis blasted at the goal line against the Eagles.
Half his body was clearly in the end zone. The officials on both
sides raised their arms. The entire Denver offensive line raised
its arms. Davis jumped up and exulted.
</P>
<P>
   Summerall, after 15 to 20 seconds: ``Well, the extra-point team
is coming on the field, so I guess it was a touchdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat Summerall is always the last to know. For his benefit, I
close with this: Hey, Pat, you're in Minneapolis this Sunday. Get
on your bike.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Nuhn writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
