<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAESARAEAN-SUIT14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HEALTH: Woman claims Caesarean's expense made doctor push
vaginal birth despite risk
 &HT;    By Cara Tanamachi
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ For Michelle Ramirez, routine tasks like
mealtime have become daunting challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez's youngest son, who turns 2 in April, cannot swallow,
hold up his head, speak or crawl. He has severe brain damage and
doctors say he might never learn to walk.
</P>
<P>
   He's fed through a tube inserted into his belly every four
hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard,'' said Ramirez, 27, who lives in Austin. ``I pray
he'll learn to walk one day.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez filed a malpractice lawsuit against her doctor on Jan.
12, claiming that a vaginal childbirth, which caused her uterus to
rupture, led to her son's brain damage. Ramirez, like thousands of
women, had a Caesarean section with her first child 7 years ago. In
her lawsuit, she says she wasn't properly told of the dangers of
having a vaginal birth for her second child.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez's doctor, Melanie Collins, could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez's lawsuit is one of a growing number across the country
that claim cost-cutting pressures from the managed care insurance
industry are forcing hospitals and doctors to perform risky vaginal
births instead of Caesarean sections, which are often more
expensive procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifteen years ago, the wisdom was once a Caesarean section,
always a Caesarean section, but there's been a movement away from
that fueled in large part by economics,'' said Les Weisbrod, an
attorney representing Ramirez. ``It costs two to three times more
to have a Caesarean section than to have a vaginal birth. This
cost-cutting mentality has become so pervasive, it has become a
medical standard.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez, who has three children, was on Medicaid when she
underwent the birth of Isaac, her now 21-month-old son. Caesarean
sections cost on average about $6,000 for a hospital stay, versus
$1,800 for a vaginal birth, Weisbrod said.
</P>
<P>
   Called a VBAC for ``Vaginal Birth After Caesarean,'' the
procedure carries a risk because the scars from previous Caesareans
can increase the risk of uterine tears during birth, according to
Paul Fine, director of urogynecology at Baylor College of
Medicinein Houston. Such tears can rupture the placenta, blocking
the flow of blood and oxygen to the baby during birth, which can
lead to brain damage.
</P>
<P>
   About 15 years ago, new studies indicated that VBACs were not as
dangerous as once thought, which opened the door for their routine
use. Since then, the advice to have VBACs has become more common
and has led to a growing number of malpractice lawsuits, Fine said.
</P>
<P>
   Just how dangerous VBACs are is being debated among researchers,
with some experts saying such a risk of uterine tears is less than
1percent and others saying it is far greater.
</P>
<P>
   In Ramirez's lawsuit, filed by the Morgan and Weisbrod law firm
in Dallas, she claims her doctor did not move quickly enough to
perform a Caesarean, once it was clear Ramirez's uterus had
ruptured and the baby was in distress. She also says she was not
fully informed of the risk in having a vaginal birth after she had
had a Caesarean section for her first child.
</P>
<P>
   Isaac's father, Luis Vargas, said he hopes the lawsuit will
educate other potential parents about the risks involved in VBACs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want everybody to be informed, so the same thing doesn't
happen to them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cara Tanamachi writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: ctanamachi(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
