<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   &HT;    Norton utilities package goes a bit overboard
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After many a fanfare and rolling of the drums, the
computing public finally has Norton SystemWorks, a new package
apparently created because the venerable purveyor of utilities
succumbed to the siren call of introducing a product with a capital
letter in the middle of the name.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Norton Utilities, which have been recovering trashed
and damaged files for about as long as computers have been trashing
them, are here. Thrown in for good measure are a bunch of other
excellent utilities, such as Norton's AntiVirus, CleanSweep and
CrashGuard.
</P>
<P>
   If you install the entire program, you will have what amounts to
a silicon Chicken Little. You will be bombarded by colorful pop-up
messages warning you that WinDoctor has found errors in your
system. Rescue Disk will complain regularly that it needs to be
updated. LiveUpdate will pester you with urgent messages about
checking the Norton Web site for upgrades.
</P>
<P>
   Eudora Pro, my Internet mail program, never gives me any
trouble. But the first time I shut it down after installing
SystemWorks, CrashGuard leaped onto the screen, beating its hairy
chest and announcing it had saved me from disaster _ Eudora had
experienced 26 _ count 'em, 26 _ errors and was about to seize up.
</P>
<P>
   When I rebooted the computer for the first time after the
installation session, a Norton program came on and announced the
system hadn't been shut down correctly _ it had _ ran its own
version of Scandisk and found something on the order of 1,000
errors, most of which it corrected in less time than it takes to
tell you about it.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow this puts me in mind of those parking lot vampires who
disable your car when you aren't looking, then run up and
graciously offer to get you going again when it won't start.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I would never want to be without the Norton Utilities.
These are the best tools there are for recovering from accidental
or mistaken file and disk erasures and hard disk crashes. On the
other hand, I am not a computer hypochondriac; I don't want half a
dozen out-of-work neurologists, psychiatrists and proctologists up
to their elbows in my computer all day long, clucking and gasping
over the slightest blemish. Fortunately, there are ways of cutting
down on the communications.
</P>
<P>
   There is one problem in my system WinDoctor cannot, apparently,
solve _ a missing file needed by a Norton program already installed
on my computer. Evidently I'm going to have to uninstall this
program just to get Windoctor off my back about it.
</P>
<P>
   An interesting new part of Rescue Disk offers to create a more
elaborate and effective rescue setup on a 100-meg Zip disk if you
have an Iomega Zip drive. There's a second CD-ROM with the program
that throws in virtually everything else Norton publishes,
including Visual Page, a Web page creator; a basic edition of
WinFax; Norton's Mobile Essentials for laptop users; a utility
intended to bring you into the Year 2000 without disaster; and
something called ``Norton Secret Stuff.'' Hey, I can keep a secret.
</P>
<P>
   But just one suggestion. Why give up a title that stands forever
in anyone's top 10 software programs? If Peter Norton absolutely
had to give it a name with a capital letter in the middle, then why
not just plain NortonUtilities?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
