J.D. already had a barrel chest in elementary school. Maybe he'd
been held back a grade or two. But while the rest of us were still
little shavers, he was already shaving, probably twice a day, and
coming to school with a pack of Camels in his shirt pocket.
(Murray, Cox News Service) MOVED TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ Last spring, 57 percent of charter-school fourth
grade students passed all portions of the Texas Assessment of
Academic Skills. In Texas public schools, 77 percent passed. Among
seventh graders, 78 percent of public school students passed the
test compared to 59 percent of students in charters. In third
grade, 75 percent of students in public schools passed versus 63
percent in charter schools. Only in fifth grade did charter school
students beat public school students in the TAAS, and that margin
was only one percentage point. (Young, Waco Tribune-Herald). MOVED
TUESDAY.
