<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   &HT;    CDs detail every inch of national parks
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Remember the ``Brady Bunch'' episode when Bobby and
Cindy got lost in the Grand Canyon on a family vacation and had to
eat baked beans out of a flashlight with an Indian boy?
</P>
<P>
   A National Park Digital Guide could have saved them the hassle.
Maptech, a New Hampshire and Massachusetts-based company, sells the
guides on CD-ROM for $29.50. Regional CD-ROMs, which come in sets
of two discs and have maps for eight to 13 parks, sell for $69.50.
The complete set of 54 parks is $179.50.
</P>
<P>
   The discs include topographic maps, which show elevation, and
information about park wildlife and history. The maps are
printable.
</P>
<P>
   Latitude, longitude and elevation are shown on the screen
automatically as you move your cursor. The interface is similar to
Microsoft Windows and works on a PC. You use a mouse or trackball
to draw your path on the on-screen map. Your charted course can be
printed, measured for distance, and viewed by elevation and
profile.
</P>
<P>
   The program requires Windows 95, Windows 98 or Windows NT; a 486
CPU or higher; 2X CD-ROM; 8 megabytes of RAM; and a mouse or a
drawing equivalent.
</P>
<P>
   The map CD-ROMs, a 1998 winner of Popular Science's Best of
What's New award, are available at http://www.maptech.com or
1-800-627-7236.
</P>
<P>
   Cereal killing
</P>
<P>
   The good folks at Cheerios are looking for four kids, ages
several months to 10 years, to be featured on a parenting advice
Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The site, Growing Up With Cheerios, will offer child development
advice. The site also will include biographies of the four kids,
weekly progress reports and monthly articles written by child
development experts.
</P>
<P>
   Each kid chosen will get a $2,500 savings bond for his or her
college education and a year's supply of Cheerios, a popular
oat-based cereal.
</P>
<P>
   The kid search will be conducted online at the Cheerios site,
</P>
<P>
   http://www.cheerios.com. The site has information about the
Cheerios Kids program, a printable application form and
instructions for entering the search. Applications are due March 1.
The Growing Up With Cheerios site is to be launched in June.
</P>
<P>
   Save the tiger
</P>
<P>
   An Atlanta-area software company is helping an international
effort to save the Sumatran tigers in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   The members of the Sumatran Tiger Project are using satellite
image maps created with ERDAS IMAGINE geographic-imaging software.
Project members use the images to help field research teams map
Sumatran tiger habitats and identify threats.
</P>
<P>
   The Sumatran Tiger Project was started in 1995 by the Indonesian
Ministry of Forestry, the World Conservation Union, the Minnesota
Zoo and Taman Safari Indonesia to gather information on Sumatran
tiger ecology, population and threats. Members are developing
geographic imaging software that will let researchers analyze the
data collected during three years of field studies and use it to
develop conservation plans.
</P>
<P>
   ERDAS, a mapping software company, started helping with the
project in 1997. The company develops customizable software that is
used in more than 20,000 projects in 105 countries. The software is
used for oil, gas and mineral exploration; natural resources
management; urban and regional planning; environmental monitoring;
forestry; academia; engineering; telecommunications; utilities; and
map-making.
</P>
<P>
   Online people watching
</P>
<P>
   If you're like the old man who sits on the bench outside the
Hallmark shop people-watching, but you don't have time to hit the
mall, there's a Web site that still might quench that thirst.
</P>
<P>
   Look at http://www.metaspy.com/spy/warningtop.html or, for those
who don't really want a peek into the unfiltered mind of the
average Web surfer, try the Disney version,
http://www.metaspy.com/spy/filtered.html.
</P>
<P>
   Both sites offer an online chance to people-watch, to see what
folks look for when they are on the Web, as viewed through
MetaCrawler's search engine.
</P>
<P>
   A list of random searches is updated every 15 seconds. A recent
slice of online randomness included searches for ``Hefty trash
bags,'' ``IRS forms,'' ``model railroad layouts,'' ``Alan Jackson
calendar,'' ``Teletubbies'' and ``Westchester schools Web sites.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
