 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Thursday, January 14, 1999 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ Dayton Daily News columnist Mary McCarty tells
the REAL story about what happens to kids, parents and life as we
know it after a few snow days. (McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MURRAY-COLUMN _ J.D. Terry was the toughest kid I ever knew.
J.D. already had a barrel chest in elementary school. Maybe he'd
been held back a grade or two. But while the rest of us were still
little shavers, he was already shaving, probably twice a day, and
coming to school with a pack of Camels in his shirt pocket.
(Murray, Cox News Service) MOVED TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ Last spring, 57 percent of charter-school fourth
grade students passed all portions of the Texas Assessment of
Academic Skills. In Texas public schools, 77 percent passed. Among
seventh graders, 78 percent of public school students passed the
test compared to 59 percent of students in charters. In third
grade, 75 percent of students in public schools passed versus 63
percent in charter schools. Only in fifth grade did charter school
students beat public school students in the TAAS, and that margin
was only one percentage point. (Young, Waco Tribune-Herald). MOVED
TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Children and teen-agers should
be disciplined by their parents and teachers, not the government.
Little wonder that the Supreme Court was openly skeptical of the
argument that a Georgia school system should be held liable under
federal law for failing to stop a male student from sexually
harassing a female student. (Nethaway, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KELSO-COLUMN _ SNOOK, Texas _ Occasionally throughout history, a
visionary comes along who should be honored for his Herculean
efforts in swimming upstream against the tide of political
correctness. Such a man is Frank Sodolak, who is pretty darned sure
he invented chicken-fried bacon. (Kelso, Austin American-Statesman)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JEFFERSON-COLUMN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Much has been made of
the almost unanimous support among blacks for President Clinton.
The most pious critics suggest that such support is an acceptance
of lower moral standards and a disregard for the level of decency
and integrity set forth in the Constitution. I suggest that such
critics consider another possibility: government-sanctioned social
conditioning. (Jefferson, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
