<P>
   KIDS-AT-WORK _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The kids-at-work concept
is growing in popularity, labor experts say. Some companies have
found that employees _ who are spending more time at the office and
must juggle child-care arrangements _ are happier and more
productive when the children are cared for on-site. According to
the National Childcare Survey, 12 million children younger than 6,
as well as 17 million school-age youngsters, have their sole parent
or both parents in the work force. As a result, parents are
flocking to family-friendly employers. (Houck, Palm Beach ) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CAESAREAN-SUIT _ AUSTIN, Texas _ For Michelle Ramirez, routine
tasks like mealtime have become daunting challenges. Ramirez's
youngest son, who turns 2 in April, cannot swallow, hold up his
head, speak or crawl. He has severe brain damage and doctors say he
might never learn to walk. He's fed through a tube inserted into
his belly every four hours. ``It's hard,'' said Ramirez, 27, who
lives in Austin. ``I pray he'll learn to walk one day.'' Ramirez
filed a malpractice lawsuit against her doctor on Jan. 12, claiming
that a vaginal childbirth, which caused her uterus to rupture, led
to her son's brain damage. (Tanamachi, Austin American-Statesman)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ANIMAL-SCHOOL _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Your eighth-grade
science class probably wasn't like Branden Hursey's. Maybe there
was a fish tank or a gerbil or two. But did you have anything like
Pete the prairie dog, who burrows under the courtyard? Or Ferris
the emu, who sits atop 14 eggs which could mean as many as 14 baby
birds in the coming weeks? Or Floyd the iguana, found sunning
himself on the Bear Lakes Middle School roof Tuesday morning?
(Desmon, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NEWS-QUESTIONS _ Q&AMP;A on the news, in two takes. (Bessonnette,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) (l, a) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD
</P>
<P>
   COXNET-FOOD _ PYRAMID POWER: Everyone knows the basic four have
been out for a while and that little pyramid that appears on so
many food labels now is in. But just how much do you know about
that pyramid and how much do you or should you follow it? The
pyramid shows that the base of your diet should be primarily
vegetarian, with grains, fruits and vegetables. (Walker, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) (EDS: This is the CoxNet food page for the
week of Jan. 11. This layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-TEXMEX _ With Mexican food near the top of favorite ethnic
foods, cheesey enchiladas and fattening guacamole and chips is the
dietary downfall of many. But it can actually be healthy. With
assistance from a spa chef, we offer tricks for trimming the fat
out of tex-mex food. (Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH
COLOR PHOTO and LAYOUT.
</P>
