<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   &HT;    Gathering rallies Apple faithful
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ What a difference a year makes. At last January's
annual MacWorld convention in San Francisco, Apple Computer was
losing tens of millions of dollars and its share of the market had
fallen to 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   This year's convention, which ended Wednesday, came as Apple
Computer doubled its market share to 10 percent and had the No.
1-selling computer in the United States. And Apple posted its first
annual profit since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to the first MacWorld conference that nobody thinks
will be the last MacWorld conference,'' computer industry
journalist David Pogue said as he greeted conventioneers.
</P>
<P>
   While Apple Computer has had a great year, the company remains
challenged. For one, its $309 million in earnings last year came
mostly from cost cutting and not higher sales. Annual revenues in
fiscal 1997 were $6 billion, down sharply from the company's peak
of $11 billion in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Falling revenue represents both lower prices and fewer sales,
which declined to 2.763 million in 1998. That's down from 2.874
million in 1997 and far below the company's 5 million peak in the
early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Many observers believe Apple Computer can survive only as a
niche player. Others think the company needs a white knight, such
as Disney or Oracle, to prosper long term.
</P>
<P>
   ``Macs will never make up more than 10 percent of all desktop
machines,'' consultant Tim Bajarin told MacWorld conventioneers.
``Whether we like it or not, the desktop war is over.''
</P>
<P>
   But last week was a banner one for the Apple Computer optimists.
Consider the good news.
</P>
<P>
   Apple's iMac is the No. 1-selling computer, with 800,000-plus
units purchased since its August introduction.
</P>
<P>
   That success is luring both hardware and software developers
back to the Mac platform. Attendance at MacWorld was up 15 percent
to 420 exhibitors this year over last, according to the
convention's figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question of Apple's sheer survival has died down,'' Rob
Scheschareg, MacWorld's director, told the San Jose Mercury News.
``Now the question seems to be, `What's next?' There's a lot of
enthusiasm for innovation.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
