 ENTERTAINMENT No 416 - January 13, 1999  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY -- No. 416 -- Jan. 13, 1998 We are
offering the following articles for sale. Please contact us for
availability your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1. CUBA'S SALSA STARS Cuba's salsa stars are its first
capitalists and, Castro fears, its most potent opposition. Castro's
government insists that Cuba is a socialist society, but a small
number of musicians today have more - much more - than the rest of
the 11 million Cubans who live on the island. They are the first
professionals in almost four decades - since the tobacco and sugar
barons, the mafiosi and the American corporations were driven out -
to accumulate wealth, the first Cubans allowed to be independent
businessmen and rich capitalists, even if they are not allowed to
invest in their own country. This preferential treatment coincides
with the country's loss of Soviet support. ``There will be more
confrontations with officials as they become a profitable
sub-culture,'' an American record producer says. ``The state will
start looking for excuses to crack down on them because they
represent freedom.'' By Silvana Paternostro. From The New York
Times Magazine. Full-length (4,000 words) + edited article
available.
_______________________________________________________________2.
FILMS AND MORALS Should we censor apparently amoral films such as
``Pulp Fiction?'' Or are they challenging us to repudiate their
twisted morality? Who is to say which film treats drugs, or
violence or sex in a responsible way, and which invites us to rush
out of the cinema and head straight for trouble? By Nigel Cliff.
From Prospect magazine. 1,000 words. (Not available U.K.)
_______________________________________________________________3.
WRESTLING HAS A HOLD ON HOLLYWOOD Four years ago, Hollywood
rediscovered the Western. Last year, disaster movies were all the
rage and this year, World War II movies dominated the screen. Next
year, moviegoers might be grappling with .... wrestling! Strange as
it sounds, there are a whole host of wrestling projects out there
right now. There are sound economic reasons why Hollywood thinks
wrestling is ``in.'' By Zorianna Kit. From The Hollywood Reporter.
1,000 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________4.
LIV ULLMANN TALKS OF 'CONFESSIONS' AND BERGMAN Liv Ullmann calls
the experience of working again with Ingmar Bergman, for whom she
starred in nine films, ``like a circle, the ends coming around to
meet each other.'' The former actress, now a director, and the
retired director, now a screenwriter, have come up with 'Private
Confessions,'' inspired by an incident in Bergman's mother's life.
Interview by Betsy Sherman. BPI. 1,300 words + photo. 5. PATRICIA
ARQUETTE : ACTING TO BEAT OF A DIFFERENT DRUMMER Patricia Arquette
knows about peer pressure: not only are her father, grandfather and
siblings Rosanna, Alexis and David actors, but she is married to
superstar Nicolas Cage. But she's not intimidated, avoiding
mainstream movies to shape a distinctive career in independent
films, including Stephen Frears' ``The Hi-Lo Country.'' In this
interview Arquette talks about the new film, the experience of
working with director Frears, why she never felt competitive with
her siblings and why she doesn't worry that Cage's announced
intention to work steadily for the next five years or more may hurt
her own career. By Ian Spelling. 1,400 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 6.
STEVEN FREARS' 'COMPLICATED' WESTERN ``The Hi-Lo Country,'' a
Western, almost got made a few decades ago by American maverick
director Sam Peckinpah. Now it comes to the screen thanks to
British maverick director Stephen Frears, best known for such
non-Westerns as ``My Beautiful Launderette,'' and ``Dangerous
Liaisons.'' Frears and actors Billy Crudup, Woody Harrelson and
Patricia Arquette have concoted an admirable, imaginative addition
to the cowboy genre. By Joshua Mooney. BPI. 1,000 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
JOHN TRAVOLTA IN 'ACTION' There is a kind of performance possible
only to a movie star. It is a fascinating morphing process, tied to
the power of pop iconography. John Travolta, long on recognition as
a pop culture icon, short on recognition as an actor, has delivered
two such performances within the last 12 months. The first was in
``Primary Colors.'' The second, his extraordinary performance in
``A Civil Action,'' about a landmark toxic waste case. Much has
been written about Travolta - his comeback, his career trajectory,
his belief in Scientology. Little has been written about his
empathetic capacity and his ability to turn himself into one
character after another. By Jay Carr. From The Boston Globe. 2,100
words + photo.
</P>
