<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER BRIEFS:  
 DIGITALIZED JOHN HANCOCKS FOR E-MAIL  
 INVESTIGATING TIME DILATION  
 BUSINESS AS USUAL AT SHOPPING.COM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 (ATTN: Mich., Calif., Canada)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Other than the stamp, about the only thing a letter has over an
e-mail message is the idiosyncratic swirls of the sender's John
Hancock.
</P>
<P>
   This fact was not lost on H. Lee Browne, a venture capitalist
turned entrepreneur, who was determined to find a way to attach a
personal signature to an e-mail message. With his new service,
Signature-mail.com, visitors to his World Wide Web site can request
a form, which they use to fax Browne as many as 25 versions of
their penmanship. Minutes later, they receive their writing back in
digital form, for easy inclusion in e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening in e-mail is we all love it and think it's
great, but the fact is, it's eventually going to look a lot more
like paper mail,'' said Browne, who is offering the
signature-digitalization service free. ``We can't go on with it
looking all the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the inherent danger is that someone might take
somebody else's digital signature and use it inappropriately. But
Browne stressed the security of his company's computer system, and
the fact that, ``just like if I find your signature in a trash can,
I can't use it to legally bind a document.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing legally binding about this sort of
signature,'' he continued. ``This is definitely not
authentication.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Browne said, he had received expressions of interest from
banks and others about possible commercial applications of his
software.
</P>
<P>
   _ LISA NAPOLI &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Intel and Compaq Dispute One Year 2000 Bug Theory
</P>
<P>
   Moving to debunk theories of a supposed Year 2000-related bug
known as the Crouch-Echlin effect, Intel and Compaq Computer, two
of the computer world's heavyweights, said last week that their own
extensive tests had found no evidence of such a problem.
</P>
<P>
   The findings could dampen fears that were first stirred in 1997
by Internet postings from Jace Crouch, a history professor in
Michigan, and Michael Echlin, a Canadian programmer, who reported
that the clocks on some computers could jump randomly forward or
backward in time after the year 2000. The jumps occurred at the
instant the computers were turned on, but not on every occasion,
they said.
</P>
<P>
   The purported problem, also known as time dilation, received new
currency last summer after a manager at Compaq's Year 2000
Expertise Center in Albany, N.Y., said that testing there had
confirmed it. Time dilation was said to affect primarily older
personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   Echlin proposed that the problem could arise from design flaws
in how the basic input/output system, or BIOS, chip retrieved the
time and date from a computer's real-time clock, a battery-driven
chip that keeps track of time even when the computer is off. Most
software on stand-alone personal computers relies on the BIOS for
time and date.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts had consistently dismissed the time-dilation
reports, saying faulty components rather than design bugs were
undoubtedly responsible for the reported date jumps. They were
stunned, and big corporate computer users were worried, by the
seeming confirmation from Compaq's Albany unit, which had just been
acquired in Compaq's merger with Digital Equipment Corp. The Albany
center also said it would sell diagnostic and repair tools
developed by Echlin.
</P>
<P>
   As criticism filtered back to Compaq's headquarters in Houston,
both Compaq, the leading PC maker, and Intel, the leading PC-chip
producer, set out to methodically search for the Crouch-Echlin
effect.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's testing was especially extensive. And the company said
last week that although it could not completely rule out the
existence of time dilation, it had disproved all reported
hypotheses for how the anomaly could occur. The company also said
its tests included one machine provided by Echlin and had used his
diagnostic tools.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq, meanwhile, revised its Year 2000 site
(www.compaq.com/year2000/year2000-qa.html) to say it would no
longer sell the Echlin tools. But Echlin is not ready to concede.
He said that while he had not yet seen the new research, evidence
continued to trickle in that post-2000 time dilation occurs, albeit
rarely.
</P>
<P>
   _ BARNABY J. FEDER &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Executive Musical Chairs at Shopping.com, Again
</P>
<P>
   It sounded drastic _ the third management team in nine months.
But for Shopping.com, an Internet retailing company, it was more
like business as usual.
</P>
<P>
   The company said last week that Randall Read, an executive from
the packaging industry, would replace Shopping.com's chairman,
Frank Denny, who is becoming president and chief executive. Denny,
in turn, was replacing John Markley.
</P>
<P>
   According to Denny, Markley resigned to spend more time in the
family cabinet business. Markley had arrived in June to replace
Robert McNulty, who was president and chief executive before
leaving for undisclosed reasons.
</P>
<P>
   In this latest shuffle, Denny, Shopping.com's founder, will take
over day-to-day operations.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping.com, which sells housewares, sporting goods, computer
supplies, electronic gadgets and more, was initially backed by Bill
Gross, the financier who has ``incubated'' dozens of Internet
businesses through his company Idealab.
</P>
<P>
   Catching the wave of investor enthusiasm for electronic
commerce, Shopping.com's initial public offering in November 1997
was an instant success, starting at $9 a share and soon trading as
high as $39.
</P>
<P>
   But things soured. The Securities and Exchange Commission
suspended trading of Shopping.com shares for two weeks in March,
though trading resumed after the SEC found no wrongdoing by
executives of Shopping.com. But in September, an arbitration panel
of the National Association of Securities Dealers fined the
company's underwriter, Waldron &AMP; Co., on the grounds that it had
inflated Shopping.com's stock price.
</P>
<P>
   The company, based in Corona Del Mar, Calif., has had trouble
filling customer orders, and dozens of customers have filed
complaints with numerous consumer protection agencies. Denny
attributes these problems to an overly ambitious marketing campaign
that generated more sales than the company could handle. It grew
from $40,000 in daily sales in June to $300,000 a day by October.
After scaling back, the company now does about $100,000 in sales a
day.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping.com's shares, having dipped below $1 each last
September, closed Friday at $13.1875, up 68.75 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Denny said the company was now intent on rebuilding its daily
sales volume, though more gradually than before.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to build a power center on the Web, a sort of
CompUSA, Home Depot and Wal-Mart,'' Denny said. But first, given
the recent upheavals, he may be busy building a power center in the
executive suite.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAURIE J. FLYNN &QR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-01-10-99 1706EST &QL;
</P>
