<P>
   EDITORS, attention features, technology page editors:
</P>
<P>
   Here is a list of selected computer-related stories from the
past week from  &UR; The N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  and its partners.
</P>
<P>
   These stories are being repeated with a distinguishing ``CPT''
in the slugline and an ``a'' general news category code.
</P>
<P>
   Similar stories planned for Thursday's New York Times will be
listed on  &UR; BC-CIRCUITS-BUDGET-NYT &LR; , moving later this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN-AZR (Phoenix) - Let's begin this week with a few
notes, a few newsy tidbits and a few interesting Web sites: Ever
wonder why so many companies lend their names to things like
college football bowl games? A recent press release from Insight in
Tempe, Ariz., explained one reason: Web page hits. The press
release said hits (visits by computer users) to the computer
marketing company's Web site (www.insight.com) soared 917 percent
after the televised Insight.com Bowl in late December. By David
Hoye.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-CENTERPIECE-COX _ Weekly centerpiece on personal
technology, from products to trends to advancements. This week:
E-mail in the office.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY-COX _ Popular column about personal computing
written for the average user. This week: An up-to-date list for
what to look for when buying a PC. By Bill Husted.
</P>
<P>
   TECHTOOLS-COX _ Software reviews. This week: Norton SystemWorks
scours the computer, clucking and gasping over every blemish.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE-COX _ What's new on the Web. This week: Food Web
sites _ those that do the expected (provide terrific recipes) and
the unexpected (offer little touches that make good use of the
unique advantages offered by a computer and an Internet
connection). By Bill Husted.
</P>
<P>
   TECHMEDIA-COX _ What the tech magazines are writing about. This
week: Microprose's latest version of ``Civilization,'' one of the
most popular games on CD, ``Civilization II.'' By Bill Haddad.
</P>
<P>
   MAC-REPORT-COX _ News on Apple and its products. This week: The
annual MacWorld convention. By Bill Haddad.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-REPORT-COX _ Tech briefs on new products and developments.
This week: Maptech, a National Park Digital Guide.
</P>
<P>
   MAC-PERIPHERALS-HNS (Undated) _ As they say in the fashion
world, there are three rules to looking hot: accessorize,
accessorize and _ wait for it _ accessorize. That's the mantra at
this week's MacWorld Expo, where accessories for the curvy teal
green iMac dot the convention floor. By Matt Beer.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTERS-ULTRALIGHT-BOS (Undated) _ Come gather 'round and
listen to me while I sing the praises of the new ultralight
laptops. These new machines are laptops as they should be: superbly
light, sleek, and beautiful. Yet at the same time these
Windows-based machines are extremely fast, rivaling all but the
fastest desktops. They are capable, with ample memory banks and
hard drives. And most important, they are affordable. By Simpson
Garfinkle.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS (San Francisco) _ A couple of years ago,
Apple was nearly as hard-up as this town's street people. The
remarkable success of the stylish iMac has changed that. Apple
employees at the MacWorld trade show exude a quiet confidence
which, for the first time in years, carries with it not a trace of
desperation. By Hiawatha Bray.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTINGQ&AMP;A-SFCHRON (Undated) _ Computers questions and
answers. By David Einstein.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-BUG-NYT (Undated) _ As if all the panic over the
infamous Year 2000 computer glitch were not enough of a problem,
experts now reveal that the omission of a single equal sign has
created a time-related error in Microsoft Corp.'s Windows family of
operating systems that will next appear on April 1, 2001. Bu John
Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   CYBER-TRAVEL-$ADV17-NYT (Undated) _ Here are three independent
sites on the World Wide Web, each of which intends to be your main
or only stop for arranging travel. They all succeed, at least to
some extent; they also all fail, to some extent. They are all worth
a look. By L.R. Shannon.
</P>
<P>
   COMPAQ-SHOPPING.COM-BLOOM (Houston) _ Compaq Computer Corp., the
world's second-largest computer company, agreed to buy online
retailer Shopping.com for $220 million in cash in an effort to
expand the features of Compaq's AltaVista Internet site. By Molly
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-MILITARY-COX (Washington) _ At the first-ever National
Summit on Skills for the 21st Century, Vice President Al Gore on
Tuesday unveiled a sweeping agenda aimed at helping mid-career U.S.
workers make the transition into high-tech jobs. By Mary Beth
Regan.
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION-INTERNET-HNS (Albany) _ Hundreds of students here are
taking college courses without leaving home and earning degrees
from universities they have never seen. It's called distance
learning, and though it has been around for years in the form of
correspondence courses, the concept has exploded with the advent of
the Internet. Now the time and distance once necessary for a
four-year degree have vanished with the click of a computer mouse.
By Andrew Brownstein.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTERS-BUG-1999-NYT (Undated) _ The world apparently sailed
through the first days of 1999 with only scattered mistakes by
computers confused by the approaching Year 2000 _ an outcome that
added to growing optimism about the chances of avoiding widespread
disruptions 51 weeks from now. By Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-BRIEFS-NYT (Undated) _ Computer notes and news.
