<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 12:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1168 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-13 1815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRETEENS: WHERE SHOULD YOU DRAW THE LINE? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing; moved Jan. 7)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Did your preteen get invited to a New Year's Eve party? Not an
all-girl or
</P>
<P>
   all-boy sleepover, but a boy-girl dress-up party with music and
dancing and
</P>
<P>
   who knows what else? Or was there a party to which your child
didn't get
</P>
<P>
   invited?
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to the social life of the 10- to 12-year-old, no
parent has
</P>
<P>
   it easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The variability in kids this age is enormous,'' says child
psychiatrist
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Greenspan of George Washington University. At one end of
the scale are
</P>
<P>
   children with surging hormones and a budding curiosity about the
opposite sex.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end, children are oblivious.
</P>
<P>
   If she could choose how her child would be, preteen researcher
Margaret
</P>
<P>
   Sagarese would go for oblivious. ``The worst that happens is
hurt feelings and
</P>
<P>
   a new set of friends,'' she says. For the precocious child,
there can be dire
</P>
<P>
   consequences: The National Center for Health Statistics
estimates that 3.2 of
</P>
<P>
   every 1,000 girls aged 10 to 14 gets pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, when a child is oblivious, parents can
inadvertently be the
</P>
<P>
   cause of a problem. ``If you weren't popular in high school,
your buttons may
</P>
<P>
   get pushed,'' says Sagarese. ``You say things like, `All your
friends are
</P>
<P>
   going to the party, don't you want to go?' '' Sagarese is
co-author of ``The
</P>
<P>
   Roller Coaster Years'' (Broadway Books), a book on middle-school
children.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't high school, though, and at this age, not being
social in a
</P>
<P>
   boy-girl way is not a stigma or a popularity issue. Not only do
these parents
</P>
<P>
   end up pushing a child into situations prematurely, but they
also send a
</P>
<P>
   message that can have deleterious effects by the time he is in
high school:
</P>
<P>
   that you should do something just because everyone else is doing
it.
</P>
<P>
   If your child isn't invited to an event and doesn't care, or is
invited
</P>
<P>
   but doesn' want to go, Sagarese tells parents to back off and
not worry. If a
</P>
<P>
   child is upset she isn't included, trying to make her feel
better -- ``Who
</P>
<P>
   cares about that stupid party, anyway?'' -- will only make her
think you
</P>
<P>
   don't understand. Instead, validate her feelings -- ``It's hard
not to be
</P>
<P>
   included.'' If friendships begin to shift and a child is hurt,
be honest: ``It
</P>
<P>
   seems like your interests aren't the same anymore. She's
interested in boys,
</P>
<P>
   you're not. That happens sometimes to friends. It's hard, but
you can still
</P>
<P>
   have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   For the parent whose child is socially active, the concerns are
very
</P>
<P>
   different.
</P>
<P>
   ``To assume this is innocent is a mistake,'' says Joan Lipsitz,
founder of
</P>
<P>
   the Center for Early Adolescence at the University of North
Carolina and a
</P>
<P>
   middle-school consultant.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't a given that a 10- to 12-year-old who wants to spend
time with an
</P>
<P>
   opposite-sex peer is experiencing sexual feelings. ``More
typically, it's a
</P>
<P>
   kind of playacting. They're trying on what they see older kids
doing,'' says
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan, who is author of ``Playground Politics'' (Addison
Wesley).
</P>
<P>
   But it is likely this girl or boy is wondering, ``Am I lovable?
Am I
</P>
<P>
   attractive? Am I masculine/feminine?''
</P>
<P>
   Once they get a ``yes'' from one person, Sagarese says, they
tend to move
</P>
<P>
   on to someone else to test it out again. The child who is stuck
on one peer
</P>
<P>
   for weeks or months -- parents might call it a crush -- or who
pushes on a
</P>
<P>
   regular basis for activities that have a dating patina -- going
to the movies
</P>
<P>
   or the mall or buying him or her presents -- may be at risk for
unsafe
</P>
<P>
   behavior.
</P>
<P>
   It is not just an issue of age but also of judgment. ``They can
be so
</P>
<P>
   mindless,'' says John Serino, principal of the Belmonte Middle
School in
</P>
<P>
   Saugus, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   What keeps children safe, say Serino and others, is structure
and
</P>
<P>
   supervision. Parents can't be wimps about either. When we are,
we become what
</P>
<P>
   Serino calls ``enablers'': ``Every time you allow your kid to do
something
</P>
<P>
   with a mature social concept, you enable him to grow up too
fast. That's
</P>
<P>
   risky.''
</P>
<P>
   Serino believes this so strongly that he did away with dances at
his
</P>
<P>
   school, and only grudgingly allows an end-of-the-year social
from 6:30 to 8:30
</P>
<P>
   p.m. (anything later is too adultlike). He won't even allow a
local church to
</P>
<P>
   advertise dances at the school, even though the dances are only
for grades 6
</P>
<P>
   to 8.
</P>
<P>
   Sagarese wishes parents were as vigilant. ``When you just let
things happen
</P>
<P>
   because you don't know what to do or you're afraid of
embarrassing your child,
</P>
<P>
   even if kids aren't doing or thinking anything sexual, they are
getting a
</P>
<P>
   message that going down this path is what they should be doing.
You are
</P>
<P>
   saying, `This quasi-romantic, quasi-sexual path is for you. I
approve.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Make no mistake,'' she continues. ``It's a path that leads
someplace.
</P>
<P>
   If they're slow-dancing in fifth grade, don't kid yourself about
what happens
</P>
<P>
   in seventh.''
</P>
<P>
   Her research shows that what happens in seventh is oral sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids were raised knowing about AIDS, so they've seized
on oral sex
</P>
<P>
   as a compromise,'' she says. ``They see it as safe and casual.''
Although AIDS
</P>
<P>
   is unlikely to be an issue at age 10 or 11, it is not unheard
of, and she says
</P>
<P>
   HIV can be transmitted through oral sex if there's a sore in the
mouth such as
</P>
<P>
   the kind children develop from braces.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lipsitz and Sagarese agree it's hard to stop a child
who is intent
</P>
<P>
   on physical intimacy, vigilance can reduce the likelihood of
risky behavior
</P>
<P>
   (see accompanying box). One piece of good news Lipsitz offers is
that even if
</P>
<P>
   an 11-year-old does something like kiss, it doesn't mean this
will become a
</P>
<P>
   regular activity. ``Kids do a lot of things one time and then
not again for a
</P>
<P>
   very long time,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   So your 12-year-old daughter has invited two boys over and they
want to go
</P>
<P>
   to her room and close the door. What do you do?
</P>
<P>
   Be respectful but firm, says Greenspan. ``Ask, `What is it you
want to do
</P>
<P>
   that you need the door shut?' They want `privacy' or they want
to turn up the
</P>
<P>
   music really loud? `That's fine,' tell them. `You can do that
with the door
</P>
<P>
   open.' '' Your child will probably balk. Don't get into
negotiations; stand
</P>
<P>
   firm. Similarly, fifth- or sixth-graders may push to go to the
mall or movies
</P>
<P>
   to hang out. Make sure they have a plan for the mall, arrange to
meet them at
</P>
<P>
   a restaurant; at the movies, go along but give them breathing
space, say, by
</P>
<P>
   sitting six rows behind them. Just dropping them off at either
venue becomes
</P>
<P>
   the enabling behavior Serino talks about.
</P>
<P>
   At a party, Sagarese says supervision means being in and out of
the room,
</P>
<P>
   refilling snacks and drinks, but not standing guard. Before you
agree to host
</P>
<P>
   a party, spell this out to your child. Tell him, ``This is my
job as a
</P>
<P>
   parent.'' If he says friends won't like it, a good response is
``If they don't
</P>
<P>
   understand, they aren't good friends to have.''
</P>
<P>
   A parent's worst fantasy, of course, is walking in on something
</P>
<P>
   inappropriate. Ever hear of a game called Lemon? Sagarese says
it's popular
</P>
<P>
   among 11-year-olds in some parts of the country. Participants
write names of
</P>
<P>
   body parts on scraps of paper, then take turns picking the
papers at random
</P>
<P>
   and describing whether they would like to lick, touch, or just
look at the
</P>
<P>
   body part. She knows one parent who walked in on the game and
walked back out
</P>
<P>
   again, flabbergasted but paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kind of makes you long for `Spin the Bottle,' '' says
Sagarese.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what Serino would tell a parent in that situation to do:
``Say to
</P>
<P>
   the group, `This is not a game for kids your age,' or pull your
child aside
</P>
<P>
   and give him the option of stopping it before you do.'' Doing
anything less,
</P>
<P>
   he says, surrenders moral leadership.
</P>
<P>
   If you know for a fact, either from observation or overheard
conversations,
</P>
<P>
   that your child is sexually curious, ``I'd be having lots of
conversations,''
</P>
<P>
   says Sagarese. There are no magic words, but the main message to
get across is
</P>
<P>
   that sex is a wonderful thing, ``but you're too young for
anything but
</P>
<P>
   kissing.' '' Set up the idea that sex happens in stages;
otherwise, she
</P>
<P>
   says, kids go to intercourse at 14.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, shift your child's focus from sex to
personality traits:
</P>
<P>
   ``David makes you feel special, doesn't he? What is it about him
that you
</P>
<P>
   like so much?'' ``Is Jenny someone who could keep a secret?
Loyalty is a trait
</P>
<P>
   I admire in a person.''
</P>
<P>
   The more children this age do things in groups, the better, says
Lipsitz.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry if the group is lopsided, three girls and two boys
or even three
</P>
<P>
   and one. ``That's a pal group,'' she says. But consider it a red
flag if it's
</P>
<P>
   consistently two and two, especially if one ``couple'' stays the
same. ``That
</P>
<P>
   smacks of romantic overtones for somebody,'' she says, and it
can lead to
</P>
<P>
   experimentation.
</P>
<P>
   Sagarese says a parent's goal isn't to stop feelings but to
guide them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids need help to understand what their emotions are all about
and to act
</P>
<P>
   on them in appropriate ways. If you fall down doing that, what
they do at 10
</P>
<P>
   and 11 ends up as practice for what they will do at 13 and 14.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIPS FOR PARENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - In the lingo of preteens, ``going out'' means talking on the
phone and
</P>
<P>
   walking together to classes. ``Dating'' means going to the
movies or the mall.
</P>
<P>
   - Clues that your child is curious about sex: magazines she
reads; phone
</P>
<P>
   calls to peers of the opposite sex; conversations about the
opposite sex;
</P>
<P>
   interest in activities that look like dates.
</P>
<P>
   - Children with older siblings are more likely to engage the
opposite sex
</P>
<P>
   at a young age.
</P>
<P>
   - Keep socialization to age-mates. In these years, there are big
</P>
<P>
   developmental differences between children only two years apart.
Even hanging
</P>
<P>
   out with the friends of a slightly older sibling can expose a
10- to
</P>
<P>
   12-year-old to risky behavior.
</P>
<P>
   - Get together with parents of your children's friends. The more
consistent
</P>
<P>
   you all are in setting limits, the more likely it is that
parents, not
</P>
<P>
   children, will set behavior standards.
</P>
<P>
   - Don't be embarrassed or intimidated to call a child's parents
to ask
</P>
<P>
   about supervision at their house.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Barbara Meltz's e-mail address is meltz(at)globe.com. Her
columns are now on line at Boston.Com, keyword ``parenting.'' For
photocopies of past columns, send a self-addressed, stamped
envelope to Barbara F. Meltz, The Boston Globe, Box 2378, Boston,
MA 02107-2378. Please specify the column.)
</P>
</TEXT>
