<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Now, even more of America can tune in `The Truman Show'
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Truman Show'' (PG)
</P>
<P>
   Truman Burbank's life is so picture-postcard perfect, it doesn't
seem real. And it isn't. In director Peter Weir's comedy-drama, Jim
Carrey plays the unwitting star of a 12-hour documentary, unaware
that his life is constantly filmed, and that his picturesque
seaside village is actually the world's largest self-contained
sound stage. While the movie never finds a way to develop its plot
beyond easy social satire, the movie is a pleasure thanks to
supporting work from Laura Linney as Truman's ``wife'' (actually,
an actress), and especially from Ed Harris as the show's godlike
producer, and surrogate father for Truman. Grade: B +
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
