<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1204 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-MINIS14-COX     01-13 0393
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MINIS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini views of recently released movies
 &HT;    By Steve Murray and Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Dance With Me'' (PG) _ A guilty, quick-stepping pleasure.
Vanessa L. Williams plays a Houston dance instructor who hopes to
recapture dance competition glory with the help of a Cuban newcomer
(Latin music star Chayanne). Original it isn't, but ``Dance'' is
great fun. It's the first film that lets Williams show off her
knockout dancing, and in his first Hollywood flick, Chayanne goes
for Hollywood heartthrob status. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Henry Fool'' (R) _ More challenging but irritatingly oblique
foolishness from Hal Hartley. A nerdy, withdrawn garbageman (James
Urbaniak) is befriended by a grandiose, overbearing stranger
(Thomas Jay Ryan) with literary pretensions and a secret past.
Encouraged to write himself, the protege surpasses his mentor.
Hartley has wit and an eccentric vision. But his trademark monotone
style is emotionally deadening. The movie just goes on and on and
on.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C -
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``54'' (R) _ Buy the soundtrack, skip the flick. This
tidied-up, fictionalized look at New York's ground zero of '70s
excess presents Studio 54 as a home for an alternative family of
sweet-hearted bartenders and would-be singers. Ryan Phillippe plays
the Jersey kid who doesn't seem to realize the only reason he gets
attention is because he's a cute piece of meat. The movie doesn't
seem to realize it, either. The only live performance comes from
Mike Myers as a drugged-out Steve Rubell. Grade: C -
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Pi '' (R) _ Math prodigy Max (Sean Gulette) thinks he may
have cracked the code to all existence in a 216-digit code he
discovers. And it's a code a bunch of other people want in this
black-and-white, science fiction fever-dream. Made for only
$60,000, it's rich with young filmmaking vigor and ambition. Grade:
B +
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Wilde'' (R) _ Stephen Fry delivers a sympathetic, smart
performance as famed playwright Oscar Wilde, whose affair with
Alfred Lord Douglas (Jude Law) destroyed his life. The strong
supporting cast includes Vanessa Redgrave, but the film is
everything Wilde was not: conventional. Grade: C +
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray and Eleanor Ringel write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
