<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-RINGEL14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Off-screen couples show on-screen chemistry
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You'd think that after ``Shanghai Surprise,'' the picture he
made in 1986 with Wife No. 1, Madonna, Sean Penn would steer clear
of marital movie efforts. Yet he and Wife No. 2, Robin Wright Penn,
have acted together twice since tying the knot: first in ``She's So
Lovely,'' and now in ``Hurlyburly,'' which opens Friday. And
neither the marriage nor their careers seem in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Husband-and-wife teams appearing together is hardly a rarity in
Hollywood. Think of Mary Pickford and Douglas Fairbanks, Tom Cruise
and Nicole Kidman, Hume Cronyn and Jessica Tandy, Alec Baldwin and
Kim Basinger, Tony Curtis and Janet Leigh, Warren Beatty and
Annette Bening. And, of course, Bogart and Bacall.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the marriages survived. Not all the movies worked. But
if you want to check out the on-screen chemistry of some of
Hollywood's more famous wedded couples, here are a few ideas.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Paul Newman and Joanne Woodward
</P>
<P>
   How they met: Introduced by an agent while making the theatrical
rounds in New York. They got to know each other better when both
were cast in ``Picnic'' on Broadway. He had a three-line role; she
understudied the two female leads.
</P>
<P>
   Some movies they've acted in together: ``The Long Hot Summer,''
``Paris Blues,'' ``Winning,'' ``The Drowning Pool,'' ``Harry and
Son''
</P>
<P>
   The one to rent: ``Mr. &AMP; Mrs. Bridge'' (1990)
</P>
<P>
   Newman and Woodward play Walter and India Bridge, a well-bred,
white-bread couple living in Kansas City in the '30s and '40s. The
Bridges have measured out their lives in coffee spoons. Sterling
silver ones. The movie may be a bit slow but it shows the minutiae
of these well-cushioned, bestilled lives with excruciating
accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Richard Burton and Elizabeth
</P>
<P>
   Taylor
</P>
<P>
   How they met: Very publicly, in Rome, on the set of
``Cleopatra.'' Pre-Rome, he'd disparaged her, saying, ``I must don
my armor to play against Miss Tits.'' Obviously, his opinion
changed.
</P>
<P>
   Some movies they've acted in together: ``The Taming of the
Shrew,'' ``The Sandpiper,'' ``The Comedians,'' ``Under Milk Wood''
</P>
<P>
   The one to rent: ``Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?'' (1966)
</P>
<P>
   Mike Nichols made his directorial debut directing the fun couple
of the '60s as another fun couple of the '60s: George (Burton), the
bullied academician with the brutal tongue, and Martha (Taylor),
the blowzy harridan to whom he's married. George Segal and Sandy
Dennis are the young couple invited over for fun 'n' games (one is
Get the Guests). The movie nabbed 13 Oscar nominations, including
best actor and best actress for the stars (she won, he didn't).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dennis Quaid and Meg Ryan
</P>
<P>
   How they met: While filming ``Innerspace,'' a
comedy/fantasy/thriller directed by Joe Dante (``Gremlins'').
Actually, they had hardly any scenes together. As Ryan said in an
interview, ``There were very few minutes when he (Quaid) isn't five
inches tall and inside Martin Short's intestines.'' (See the movie;
you'll understand.)
</P>
<P>
   Some movies they've acted in together: ``Innerspace,'' ``Flesh
and Bone''
</P>
<P>
   The one to rent: ``D.O.A.'' (1988)
</P>
<P>
   Borrowing the premise (but little else) from a '50s film noir of
the same name, ``D.O.A.'' is definitely alive and kicking. Quaid
plays a college professor who's been poisoned by a slow-acting
toxin and spends his last days tracking down his killer. Ryan is a
fresh-faced freshman on his side. The directors are Rocky Morton
and Annabel Jankel, co-creators of Max Headroom.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Kenneth Branagh and Emma Thompson
</P>
<P>
   How they met: They were cast as a married couple in the BBC
miniseries ``Fortunes of War,'' which later aired on ``Masterpiece
Theatre.''
</P>
<P>
   Some movies they've acted in together: ``Henry V,'' ``Much Ado
About Nothing,'' ``Peter's Friends.''
</P>
<P>
   The one to rent: ``Dead Again'' (1991)
</P>
<P>
   Branagh is a cynical L.A. detective whose quest to help a
beautiful amnesiac (Thompson) ties him to a headline-grabbing
scandal from the '40s in which a celebrated concert pianist (also
Branagh) was sentenced to death for murdering his wife (Thompson
again). This reincarnation/mystery-thriller may be high-class hooey
at heart _ a New Age nonesuch decked out in Hitchcockian trappings.
But even at its thinnest _ and it can get pretty thin _ ``Dead
Again'' is always lively. Plus, Branagh's direction gives it a fine
theatrical charge.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
