<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Simmering stew is the perfect antidote to winter
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It is the dead of winter, and as chill winds and gray
gloom threaten to creep under the windowsill, the kitchen kicks
into high gear as the heart of the home. Add a pot of stew
simmering on the stove and high-octane warmth can chase away any
winter melancholy.
</P>
<P>
   This timeless mix of meats and vegetables, herbs and spices in a
savory gravy is a basic and elemental dish that has been prepared
for eons by people throughout the world. From the robust beef, lamb
and potato combinations favored in the British Isles to the spicy
blends of meats, raisins and chickpeas eaten in Morocco to the
delicate fish stews of the Mediterranean, most every country has
its signature stew.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, though, that stew is not a quick fix. Like the season,
it is a contemplative pursuit that requires time and thought and
instinct. Each ingredient must be nurtured, coaxed and adjusted so
it enhances the others and blends rather than overpowers.
</P>
<P>
   Stew is one dish that really does taste better after a day or
two. So make enough when you have the time; add a loaf of crusty
bread and maybe a salad and you are set for part of the week.
</P>
<P>
   A good way to learn what the Internet has to offer you in the
kitchen with that new computer you may have received over the
holidays is to search out new and different stew recipes. Not only
will you be amazed at the stunning variety, but as you link up with
other sites, you will get a geography lesson as well.
</P>
<P>
   During our search we found ourselves deep into the history,
culture and cuisine of Ireland, all the while being serenaded by
bagpipes over the speaker. Another click found us in a place called
Bizkaia, which is in the Basque country of Spain, and meeting a
most amazing indigenous stew recipe containing four or five meats,
dozens of vegetables including lettuce, and even eggs.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have the time for a virtual trip around the world,
make your first stop
http://soar.berkeley.edu/recipes/stews/indexall.html for tons of
just recipes ranging from an exotic lamb stew with chestnuts and
pomegranates, to the hearty stew favored by the citizens of County
Cork, to a robust Italian variation of beef stew that features
wine-braised beef served over creamy polenta. For some African
stews and other dishes that are at least as tantalizing to read
about as they are to prepare, call up
http://ivu.org/recipes/african.html.
</P>
<P>
   If you have the greatest stew-making implement of the 20th
century, the crockpot, call up
http://southernfood.miningco.com/library/cprec/bl424.htm for an
index of recipes that includes Basque, French, Mexican, Italian and
Native American stews along with standard American beef and lamb.
</P>
<P>
   Some lovely pasta stews with ingredients geared to seasonal
availability can be found at
http://wizard.ucr.edu:80/(tilde)phannema/recipes/pastafeb.htm.
Stunning Stews at
http://www.geocities.com/(tilde)recipelu/stew.html divides stews
into seafood, beef and veal. A list of hearty vegetarian stews can
be found at http://www.suma.co.uk/rec-stews.html. Epicurious adds
to the stew with a list of some elegant recipes from the pages of
Bon Appetit, House and Garden and Gourmet magazines at 
http://www1.epicurious.com/s97is.vts?action &QC; filtersearch&AMP;filter &QC; RSF.
hts&AMP;keyword &QC; stew.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, for tips, questions and information about pressure
cookers and crockpots, check out
http://homearts.com/gh/food/03stewf1.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Keep warm _ and happy stewing.
</P>
<P>
   BYTES &AMP; e-mail
</P>
<P>
   Diabetic help
</P>
<P>
   As a newly diagnosed diabetic, I am trying to locate recipes
that will afford some bulk in my diet and are also flavorful. Have
you done any research in this area? Craig Ratleff
</P>
<P>
   Take a look at
http://www.diabetic-lifestyle.com/jan98recipes.htm which is a
diabetic lifestyle on-line magazine with a tasty collection of
recipes plus menus, medical updates, entertaining, travel and
practical information to enhance life while managing diabetes on a
daily basis.
</P>
<P>
   And the chef recommends
</P>
<P>
   I am the chef at Emory Hospital and am always on the
</P>
<P>
   lookout for new sites. One site I have had some fun with
recently is http://www.cbt.net/dedwards/index.htm(Southern Cooking
Recipes). While it is not on the same scale as, say, SOAR, it is
interesting in the regional aspect. Check it out if you haven't
already.
</P>
<P>
   _David Marsh
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Lentil Kielbasa Stew
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings Preparation time: 15 minutes Cooking time: 1
hour, 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 slices bacon
</P>
<P>
   3 medium onions, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 quarts beef stock or bouillon
</P>
<P>
   2 cups dried lentils, rinsed
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped carrots
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   1 pinch thyme
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds kielbasa, sliced thin, divided
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   In a medium skillet, fry bacon and onions over medium heat.
Drain off and discard drippings. Remove bacon and crumble. In a
large stockpot, place the bacon, onions, beef stock, lentils,
carrots, bay leaf, thyme and 1 1/2 pounds kielbasa. Bring to a boil
and simmer for about 1 hour. Add remaining kielbasa and cook 10
minutes more. Season with salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 341 calories, 20 grams protein, 15 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 39), 33 grams carbohydrates, 32
milligrams cholesterol, 557 milligrams sodium, 11 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Tuscan White Bean Stew With Spinach and Radicchio
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 18 minutes Cooking time: 15
minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil, or olive oil spray
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 anchovy fillets, chopped (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1 pinch red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   5 ounces fresh spinach, chopped
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup shredded radicchio
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups cooked white beans, such as cannellini beans, drained
and rinsed
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces pasta, such as bow tie/farfalle, cooked
</P>
<P>
   Fresh oregano, chopped
</P>
<P>
   Fresh parsley, chopped
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in a large pan over medium-high heat. Stir in garlic,
anchovies and red pepper flakes; heat about 30 seconds. Add spinach
and saute about 30 seconds. Add broth and radicchio and saute for
about 30 seconds. Add the lemon juice and beans. Reduce heat to
medium-low and simmer for 6 to 10 minutes. Serve on hot pasta and
garnish with chopped oregano and parsley.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (without anchovies): 267 calories, 12 grams protein,
5 grams fat (percent calories from fat, 16), 44 grams
carbohydrates, 1 milligram cholesterol, 172 milligrams sodium, 6
grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Detail from: http://homearts.com/gh/food/03stewf1.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
