<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Candy cake gets quick response
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In November, Joann Brewer of Conyers (Ga.) asked if
anyone had a recipe from a magazine like one she lost for Texas
Pecan Candy Cake, a dessert she said her whole family liked.
</P>
<P>
   Soon three possibilities arrived _ one of them the same recipe
taken from a 1985 issue of Family Circle magazine. Jean Dollar of
Snellville (Ga.), who sent that one, has made the cake many times,
too, often when she makes fruitcakes during the holidays. She
agrees it's delicious, ``but very rich,'' and adds, ``the longer it
sits, the better it gets.'' Our tester likes it, too, and echoes
that it is best to wait the full two weeks for the flavors to
mellow in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Texas Pecan Candy Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 32 thin slices
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1 1/2 hours
</P>
<P>
   Refrigeration time: 2 weeks
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound candied red cherries, cut in quarters (1 1/3 cups)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound candied pineapple, coarsely chopped (1 cup)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound pitted dates, coarsely snipped (1 1/2 cups)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   4 1/3 cups coarsely chopped pecans (1 pound, shelled)
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces flaked coconut (about 1 1/4 cups)
</P>
<P>
   1 can (14 ounces) sweetened condensed milk
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 250 degrees. Grease and flour 9-by-3-inch tube
pan with removable bottom.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, combine cherries, pineapple and dates. Sprinkle
with flour; toss to coat well. Add pecans and coconut; toss to mix.
Add sweetened condensed milk; stir to mix well. Spoon evenly into
prepared pan, smoothing top.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for 1 1/2 hours. Cool in pan on rack. Remove from pan. Wrap
tightly in foil. Refrigerate at least 2 weeks so flavors can
mellow.
</P>
<P>
   Cake cuts best when cold. Slice very thin with serrated knife.
</P>
<P>
   Per slice: 207 calories, 3 grams protein, 12 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 53), 25 grams carbohydrates, 4 milligrams
cholesterol, 17 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Requests
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  S.L. Harrod (e-mail) is looking for a Vidalia onion casserole
that includes onions, butter and cheese.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tiffany Kramer (e-mail) would like a recipe for German
Chocolate Pie similar to one she had 25 years ago. Closer to a
brownie than a pie, it is chewy and not cakelike. It includes two
pie shells, cocoa, coconut, cornstarch and sweetened condensed
milk.
</P>
<P>
   Where to write
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests for recipes for this column should be sent
to Recipe Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Include a daytime telephone
number. E-mail: mlanghenry(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
