<HEADER>
A1217 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN     01-13 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When it comes to brews, everybody has a favorite
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``I must say, I am surprised at you.''
</P>
<P>
   A good knuckle-rapping should carry the weight of unbending
conviction, and Robert Manns' did. Manns was not merely aggrieved,
he was ``multiply aggrieved.''
</P>
<P>
   And he was not the only one, although he may have been the
wittiest.
</P>
<P>
   Manns, an Atlanta playwright, wondered if the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution's picks as Atlanta's 10 Best Beers last month
were a perverse joke. Not that he disagreed in every instance, but
where in the world, he wondered, was the Old Ivy Pale Ale made by
John Harvard's in Atlanta and Roswell (Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   And how could anyone, he asks, omit Sweetwater Festive Ale, a
seasonal sold in 1-liter bottles for $8. ``Ah, now that beer is so
fresh and so lightly spiced,'' Mann reports. ``It's a dark beer
without darkness in the taste.''
</P>
<P>
   Manns presents a formidable bill of particulars. But life is
full of choices, and you live with what you choose, right?
</P>
<P>
   It happens that a number of readers would have chosen very
differently, while others would have chosen in more or less the
same way. And, believe it or not, an enlightened few would have
chosen exactly as I did, beer for beer.
</P>
<P>
   That's the fun of picking 10-best lists. You can't be entirely
wrong, and there will always be someone who thinks you've hit the
nail on the head.
</P>
<P>
   No one so far has taken issue with the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution's choice of Percy's Pale Ale, brewed at
Percy's Fish House, as Best in Atlanta for 1998. But some thought
the Silent Screamer India Pale Ale at U.S. Border Brewery and
Cantina in Alpharetta (Ga.) was its equal, and others, like Manns,
were withholding judgment until they sampled it.
</P>
<P>
   Readers' responses to the Journal-Constitution's Top 10 list
showed, more than anything else, a surprising awareness of who's
been brewing what. More than one reader voiced the opinion that the
Seven Sisters Munchener at Phoenix Brewing Co. _ which made the
Journal-Constitution's Top 10 in 1997 but missed out (narrowly) in
1998 _ has been the most consistently excellent local beer since
the arrival of brewpubs.
</P>
<P>
   And it just might be.
</P>
<P>
   But a reader new to Atlanta, Debra Stacey, declared herself a
devotee of stouts _ Guinness in particular _ and said she was tired
of seeing brown ales wherever she went. Not just in brewpubs, but
in bottles as well. ``Newcastle's the worst,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   I don't blame you, Debra. An English-style brown ale is a dull
beer. That's why the American-style browns at Max Lager's and at
U.S. Border were on our Top 10 _ stand-up beers that are bold
variations on a tired theme.
</P>
<P>
   Many readers wrote or e-mailed saying they missed the Kickin'
Cactus India Pale Ale no longer on tap at U.S. Border. Strictly
speaking, the Kickin' Cactus might not have been a true IPA, but it
was a pale ale in every respect and a different one at that. Chris
Terenzi, the new brewer at U.S. Border, would be smart to replace
one of the two IPAs now on tap with a version of the Kickin'
Cactus. Both the Three Silo and the Silent Screamer are, after all,
the same beer, the only difference being a smidgen more hop
character in the latter.
</P>
<P>
   Others offered briefs for the medal-winning Iron Horse Stout and
the new India Pale Ale at Rock Bottom. ``I've been to most of the
local brewpubs,'' wrote Jim Davis of Atlanta, ``and I find the beer
at Rock Bottom closest to what I used to enjoy in Denver. The stout
is outstanding, and, since you seem to like IPAs, I recommend you
try the one there.''
</P>
<P>
   I like the Iron Horse, too, but have to disagree on the IPA. I
liked Clay Gentry's old one better, even if it wasn't as hoppy as I
might have wanted. The Bramling Cross hops _ which Gentry says lost
their freshness too quickly _ gave the beer a soft, lemon-grass
finish that was different from the citrusy or piney notes of many
American-style IPAs.
</P>
<P>
   One test of any Top 10 list is whether you would make the same
choices a month later. It hasn't been quite that long and the
regrets about having to omit this beer or that beer are the same,
but regrets are not recantations. These were fairly calloused
knuckles even before Robert Manns took his rod to them.
</P>
<P>
   Many readers wrote or e-mailed saying they missed the Kickin'
Cactus India Pale Ale no longer on tap at U.S. Border. Strictly
speaking, the Kickin' Cactus might not have been a true IPA, but it
was a pale ale in every respect and a different one at that.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
