</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-TEXMEX-RECIPES14-IstTAKE- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Resolved: Can't-resist-'em favorites aren't off-limits when
they're these flavorful, pared-down versions
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I wish I could tell you I found the perfect replacement for hot,
greasy, salty tortilla chips. Or that you can go ahead and eat
deep-fried chiles rellenos stuffed with half a cup of cheese and
still lose weight or be healthy.
</P>
<P>
   When I become a fairy godmother, I'll remember these wishes.
Promise. But until then, there are tasty alternatives that will
allow you to keep your resolutions and tantalize your Tex-Mex taste
buds, too.
</P>
<P>
   For quesadillas, try Rancho La Puerta chef Bill Wavrin's trick
and use chopped grilled veggies and a small amount of part-skim
mozzarella as the base. Then add just a teaspoon of a strongly
flavored crumbled cheese, such as blue cheese or feta, and cook in
a nonstick pan or a skillet lightly coated with vegetable spray.
</P>
<P>
   Soft tacos with grilled chicken cut in cubes and mixed with
cilantro are light and lean. For a crispy shell, Weight Watchers
suggests draping soft corn tortillas directly over the bars of your
oven rack and baking for 10 minutes at 400 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Think guacamole is out of the question? You won't when you try
the recipe below. Same goes for cheese dip and chips. We also have
lighter versions of cheese enchiladas, beans, chiles rellenos and
shredded beef tacos. Try these and we're sure a fiesta will fit in
your diet plan anytime.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Baked Tortilla Chips
</P>
<P>
   Makes 24 chips Preparation time: 5 minutes Cooking time: 5-7
minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cookbook author Paulette Mitchell, who taught two cooking
classes at Rancho La Puerta the week I was there, offers this
alternative to fried chips.
</P>
<P>
   4 7- or 8-inch flour tortillas
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Use kitchen scissors to cut each
tortilla into 6 wedges. Arrange in a single layer on an ungreased
baking sheet. Bake in the preheated oven until crisp, about 5-7
minutes. The chips will continue to crisp as they cool. The chips
can be made in advance and stored in an airtight container at room
temperature for a few days.
</P>
<P>
   Per chip: 19 calories, 1 gram protein, less than 1 gram fat
(percent calories from fat, 20), 3 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 28 milligrams sodium, less than 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Microwave `Baked' Chips
</P>
<P>
   Makes 72 chips Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: about 30 minutes (about 5-7 minutes per batch)
</P>
<P>
   Noted Mexican cookbook author Rick Bayless discovered the
microwave is perfect for creating low-fat chips. The time it takes
for the wedges to crisp will depend on how powerful your microwave
is. The thinner and fresher the corn tortilla, the better.
</P>
<P>
   12 corn tortillas
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable oil for brushing or misting
</P>
<P>
   Salt, preferably kosher or sea salt
</P>
<P>
   Lay the tortillas out on a cutting board, lightly spray, brush
or mist both sides with oil, then cut each tortilla into 6 wedges.
Lay the wedges out in a single layer on the bottom of the microwave
oven. Microwave on high for 1 1/2 minutes. Turn the tortilla wedges
over and microwave for another 1 1/2 minutes. Continue turning and
microwaving at 1 1/2-minute intervals, moving the wedges around if
some seem to be browning more than others, until they are crisp
(remember, as they cool, they'll crisp even more). Total
microwaving time is likely to be 5-7 minutes. Immediately toss the
chips with salt and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Per chip: 10 calories, less than 1 gram protein, less than 1
gram fat (percent calories from fat, 15), 2 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, less than 1 milligram sodium, less than 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Chile Con Queso Dip
</P>
<P>
   Makes 3 1/2 cups Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   I admit I was a skeptic when it came to a reduced-fat cheese
dip. But I tried this and I liked it. Take note that a serving is
1/4 cup. This comes from Cooking Light's Web site (http://www
</P>
<P>
   .cookinglight.com).
</P>
<P>
   1 14.5-ounce can diced tomatoes, undrained
</P>
<P>
   1 10-ounce can diced tomatoes and green chiles, undrained
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 8-ounce block fat-free cream cheese, softened
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chili powder
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces light processed cheese, cubed (such as Velveeta Light)
</P>
<P>
   Cilantro sprigs (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Drain tomatoes and tomatoes with chiles in a colander over a
bowl, reserving 1/3 cup liquid; set aside tomatoes and reserved
liquid.
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in a medium saucepan over medium heat. Add onion and
garlic; saute 4 minutes. Add cream cheese; cook until cheese melts,
stirring constantly. Add tomatoes, reserved liquid and chili
powder; bring to a boil. Add processed cheese; reduce heat and
simmer 3 minutes or until cheese melts, stirring constantly.
Garnish with cilantro, if desired. Serve warm with baked tortilla
chips.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 14 calories, 2 grams protein, less than 1 gram fat
(percent calories from fat, 22), 1 gram carbohydrates, 1 milligram
cholesterol, 100 milligrams sodium, less than 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Guiltless Guacamole Dip (below)
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 2 1/2 cups Preparation time: 25-30 minutes Cooking
time: 13 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Still want to indulge in this traditionally high-fat dip?
</P>
<P>
   Here the fat is cut in half when the avocados are combined with
other green veggies for a winning concoction by Bill Wavrin, chef
at Rancho La Puerta.
</P>
<P>
   Try it once and you'll see.
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup broccoli florets
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fresh or frozen peas
</P>
<P>
   1 medium avocado (about 8 ounces), peeled and seeded
</P>
<P>
   1 medium tomato, diced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 red onion, finely diced
</P>
<P>
   1 green onion, trimmed and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 jalapeno pepper, seeded and minced
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped fresh cilantro
</P>
<P>
   4 to 6 tablespoons fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   In a small saucepan, cook the broccoli in gently boiling water
for about 10 minutes, until soft.
</P>
<P>
   Add the peas and simmer for about 3 minutes longer.
</P>
<P>
   Drain and cool.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the broccoli and peas to a food processor; add the
avocado and process until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Scrape the mixture into a bowl. Add the tomato, red onion, green
onion, jalapeno, garlic and cilantro and season to taste with lime
juice and salt.
</P>
<P>
   Mix well and serve, or cover and refrigerate for up to 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Per tablespoon: 15 calories, less than 1 gram protein, 1 gram
fat (percent calories from fat, 56), 2 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 5 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Unfried Beans
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 5-7 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Usually, refried beans are not only fried, but fried in lard.
Here's an alternative from ``The American Medical Association's
Family Health Cookbook'' (Pocket Books, $30) that will satisfy
without clogging those arteries.
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons chili powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cumin
</P>
<P>
   2 cans (16 ounces each) pinto beans, rinsed and drained, or 3
1/2 cups cooked pinto beans
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup chopped red onion
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 pickled jalapeno peppers, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 to 6 tablespoons warm water
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Toast the chili powder and cumin in a small skillet over medium
heat, stirring, until fragrant, 1 to 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In a blender or the work bowl of a food processor, combine the
beans, onion, jalapeno(s) and toasted spices. Pulse to make a
coarse puree. With the motor running, add warm water to thin to a
spreadable consistency. Season with salt and pepper to taste. (You
can also mash the beans with the seasonings in a bowl, using a
potato masher.)
</P>
<P>
   Use immediately at room temperature as a sandwich spread or warm
the beans in a saucepan over low heat, stirring, until heated
through, about 5 minutes, and serve as a side dish.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 196 calories, 11 grams protein, 1 gram fat (percent
calories from fat, 5), 37 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 18
milligrams sodium, 12 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER/SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Chiles Rellenos
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 rellenos
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20-25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   The last one of these I had at a restaurant was stuffed with
ground beef and at least 1/2 cup of cheese, then deep-fried and
topped with even more cheese. This version shows that a little
cheese will actually go a long way _ and won't stay with you nearly
as long.
</P>
<P>
   4 Anaheim or poblano chiles (about 3/4 pound)
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces low-fat, low-sodium Monterey Jack cheese, cut into 4
long strips
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg white
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg
</P>
<P>
   1 garlic clove, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chopped fresh oregano
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons whole-wheat pastry flour
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Toast the chiles over an open flame until the skins are lightly
charred. Transfer to a paper or plastic bag and let rest for 10
minutes. (Alternately, roast the chiles in a baking pan in a
preheated 400 degree oven for 15 to 20 minutes, until the skins
begin to pull away from the peppers.)
</P>
<P>
   Remove the skin to just below the stem of each chile. Make a
2-inch slit lengthwise in each chile and remove the seeds.
Carefully insert one cheese strip in each chile. Using an electric
mixer set on medium-high speed, beat the egg white until doubled in
volume. Beat in the whole egg, garlic, oregano and salt until the
mixture again doubles in volume or reaches soft peaks. Sprinkle the
flour on a plate and dredge the chiles in the flour to coat all
sides.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
