<HEADER>
A1219 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-TEXMEX-RECIPES14     01-13 1524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-TEXMEX-RECIPES14-2ndTAKE- </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: all sides.
</P>
<P>
   Lightly spray a saute pan with canola or olive oil spray and
place over medium-high heat. Dip each chile into the egg batter,
then carefully place in the saute pan. Cook for about 1 1/2 minutes
on each side. Lightly spray a baking pan with canola or olive oil
spray. Transfer the chiles to the baking pan and bake for about 15
minutes, or until the cheese melts. Serve at once. _ From ``The
Rancho La Puerta Cookbook'' (Broadway Books, $20)
</P>
<P>
   Per relleno: 86 calories, 8 grams protein, 3 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 32), 7 grams carbohydrates, 84 milligrams
cholesterol, 460 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Shredded Beef Soft Tacos
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings Preparation time: 15 minutes Cooking time: 9
hours Standing time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   Prep the onions the night before, then put the meat and fixin's
in the crockpot before you leave for work. When you get home,
you'll have a wonderfully tender and flavorful filling for soft
tacos. Garnish with reduced-fat cheddar and light sour cream.
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds top sirloin steak or sirloin tip roast, all visible
fat removed
</P>
<P>
   3 cups chopped yellow onion (6 medium)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped green bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup dry red wine (regular or nonalcoholic)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup low-sodium ketchup
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   6 medium cloves garlic, minced, or 1 tablespoon bottled minced
garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons low-sodium beef bouillon granules
</P>
<P>
   2 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon liquid smoke
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cumin, divided
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon red hot pepper sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dark brown, light brown or granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   8 8-inch nonfat or low-fat flour tortillas
</P>
<P>
   Put meat in slow cooker. Add onions and bell pepper. In a medium
bowl, whisk together wine, ketchup, vinegar, garlic, bouillon
granules, bay leaves, liquid smoke, 1/2 teaspoon cumin, hot pepper
sauce and pepper. Pour wine mixture into slow cooker, cover tightly
and cook on low setting for 9 hours, or until meat is tender.
</P>
<P>
   Shred meat using two forks, and return it to slow cooker. Remove
and discard bay leaves. Add 1/2 teaspoon cumin and sugar and let
mixture stand for 1 hour to allow flavors to blend.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Wrap tortillas in aluminum foil and warm in oven for 6 to 8
minutes. Spoon meat mixture down center of a tortilla. If you want
to add garnishes, such as chopped tomatoes, salsa, shredded lettuce
or nonfat or low-fat cheese and sour cream, do it now. Roll and
repeat with remaining tortillas. Serve immediately. _ From ``The
New American Heart Association Cookbook'' (Times Books, $30)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 257 calories, 22 grams protein, 5 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 17), 31 grams carbohydrates, 53
milligrams cholesterol, 229 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Chicken Southwestern (above)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings Preparation time: 20-25 minutes Cooking time:
20-25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   While it may not be a classic on the Tex-Mex menu, we had to
include this because it is a flavorful, colorful way to enjoy
chicken. And if you are on a diet, you're probably looking for some
new way to enjoy chicken. Serve with corn tortillas and fresh
fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable oil spray
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups orange, red or yellow bell pepper strips or
combination (1 1/2 medium)
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons seeded and minced fresh jalapeno pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup diagonally sliced green onions (4 to 5 medium)
</P>
<P>
   6 boneless, skinless chicken breast halves (about 4 ounces
each), all visible fat removed
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 teaspoons chili powder, divided
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon pepper, divided
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vegetable oil, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 28-ounce can no-salt-added whole tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon grated lime zest
</P>
<P>
   Heat a large nonstick skillet over medium-high heat. Remove
skillet from heat and lightly spray with vegetable oil spray.
Return skillet to heat. Saute bell pepper and jalapeno for 4 to 5
minutes, stirring occasionally. Add green onions and saute for 1
minute. Transfer vegetables to a plate and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Rinse chicken and pat dry with paper towels. Put chicken, smooth
side up, between two sheets of plastic wrap. Using a tortilla press
or the smooth side of a meat mallet, flatten chicken to 1/2-inch
thickness.
</P>
<P>
   In a paper or plastic bag, combine flour, 1 1/2 teaspoons chili
powder, 1/4 teaspoon pepper and salt. Add chicken one piece at a
time and shake to coat with flour mixture. Shake off excess flour.
</P>
<P>
   In a large nonstick skillet, heat 1 teaspoon oil over
medium-high heat. Add half the chicken pieces and lightly brown on
both sides, 3 to 4 minutes per side. Transfer to plate containing
vegetables and repeat process with remaining oil and chicken. Set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   Add undrained tomatoes to skillet, breaking up whole tomatoes
with a wooden spoon. Stir in remaining 1 teaspoon chili powder and
1/4 teaspoon pepper. Reduce heat and simmer for 3 to 4 minutes. Add
lime zest, vegetables and chicken. Heat over medium heat for 5 to 6
minutes, or until heated through and chicken is no longer pink in
the center. _ From ``The New American Heart Association Cookbook''
(Times Books, $30)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 218 calories, 29 grams protein, 5 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 21), 14 grams carbohydrates, 72
milligrams cholesterol, 176 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Cheese Enchiladas (above)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 enchiladas Preparation time: 25-30 minutes Cooking time:
45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This comes from another health spa, the tony Canyon Ranch near
Tucson, Ariz. The enchiladas are small. One would make a nice
appetizer, or two a nice meal.
</P>
<P>
   Sauce:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons fat-free vegetable stock
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons diced pimentos
</P>
<P>
   1 14 1/2-ounce can undrained low-sodium canned diced tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons diced green chiles
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon white vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 garlic clove, pressed or minced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon chili powder
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   Dash hot pepper sauce
</P>
<P>
   Enchiladas:
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fat-free vegetable stock
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup canned diced green chiles
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chili powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1 cup peeled and diced tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces part-skim mozzarella cheese, grated (1 1/2 cups)
</P>
<P>
   6 corn tortillas, warmed
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce sharp cheddar cheese, grated ( 1/4 cup)
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   For the sauce: Cook the onion in the stock in a medium saucepan
over medium heat until soft, about 3 minutes. Add the pimentos,
tomatoes, green chiles, vinegar, garlic, chili powder, cumin and
hot pepper sauce and bring to a boil. Cover and simmer 10 minutes.
Allow to cool slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer about half the sauce to a blender container and blend
until smooth. Pour back into the remaining sauce and mix
thoroughly. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   For the enchiladas: Combine the onion and stock in a skillet and
cook over medium heat until the onion is soft and translucent,
about 3 minutes. Add the green chiles, chili powder, cumin and
tomatoes and cook for another 5 minutes. Remove from heat and cool
to room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Add the mozzarella cheese and mix well. Spoon 3 tablespoons of
the filling into each tortilla and roll it up. Spread 1/2 cup sauce
evenly in the bottom of a 9-inch square baking dish. Put the rolled
enchiladas on top of the sauce, folded side down, and cover with
the remaining sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle the grated cheese over the top and bake for about 20
minutes, or until heated through.
</P>
<P>
   Serve immediately. _ From ``Canyon Ranch Cooking''
(HarperCollins, $40)
</P>
<P>
   Per enchilada: 252 calories, 14 grams protein, 8 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 30), 35 grams carbohydrates, 21
milligrams cholesterol, 291 milligrams sodium, 7 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Baked Bananas
</P>
<P>
   With Cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5-10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 15-20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This is a nice, sweet way to end a meal. And it's great over
low-fat frozen yogurt.
</P>
<P>
   3 bananas, peeled and quartered horizontally
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon grated orange zest
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon grated lime zest
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup fresh orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup raisins or currants
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees. In a shallow baking dish just large
enough to hold them, arrange the bananas in a single layer. In a
small bowl, combine the zests, juices, currants or raisins, vanilla
and cinnamon and whisk to blend. Pour over the bananas and bake,
uncovered, for 15-20 minutes or until the bananas are lightly
browned and bubbling. Use a spatula to put 3 banana pieces in the
center of a dessert plate and spoon the sauce from the dish over
them.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 102 calories, 1 gram protein, less than 1 gram fat
(percent calories from fat, 4), 30 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 2 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
