u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-TEXMEX14-COX     01-13 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-TEXMEX14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The lighter side of Tex-Mex
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TECATE, Mexico _ It's my first day at Rancho La Puerta fitness
spa, and I've huffed my way up the mountain, pumped my way through
an upper body weightlifting routine and held the warrior yoga pose
for what seemed like eter-
</P>
<P>
   nity. And it's only noon.
</P>
<P>
   Bring on the cottage cheese lunch plate. I mean to get lean.
</P>
<P>
   Wait a minute. Is that a quesadilla they're putting on my plate?
</P>
<P>
   No, it couldn't be. Didn't the Center for Science in the Public
Interest in Washington say a few years back the average restaurant
quesadilla with all the toppings has the same amount of saturated
fat as three Quarter Pounders at McDonald's?
</P>
<P>
   Not when chef Bill Wavrin makes them. After all, each week he
oversees the preparation of three meals a day for 150 guests at
``the ranch,'' where the overall diet contains no more than 18
percent fat.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can't believe I'm talking about spa cuisine when I tell
them our most popular dishes are quesadillas and chiles rellenos,''
says Wavrin.
</P>
<P>
   If your New Year's resolution included eating healthy and losing
weight, you probably put Tex-Mex food on the ``red light'' list. No
more nachos nuked in the microwave. No more Friday lunches at the
cantina with the gang from work.
</P>
<P>
   But everyone knows today's deprivation is likely to be
tomorrow's binge. So we have a better plan. Go ahead and dine on
some favorites, such as guacamole and enchiladas, but use lighter
recipes that are loaded with flavor, not fat.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you can still go to your favorite Tex-Mex restaurant,
but remember to take your iron will with you. ``They are probably
one of the most troublesome types of restaurants for people to stay
in control,'' said Page Love, an Atlanta nutritionist and
spokeswoman for the Georgia Dietetic Association. ``It starts with
the chip basket, where often each chip has a gram of fat.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't be fooled by the taco salad. With a fried shell, ground
beef, sour cream, cheese and avocado, many come in at 1,000
calories. And above all, watch your portions. A beef burrito the
size of a brick can have 800 calories or more.
</P>
<P>
   The best bet for negotiating the local cantina is to go with
soft flour and corn tortillas and salsa as an appetizer instead of
fried chips, cheese dip and guacamole. And Love suggests staying
away from the fried items, such as chiles rellenos, and steering
toward fajitas or soft tacos without the sour cream and cheese.
</P>
<P>
   But for those who simply can't stop themselves when a basket of
fresh, hot chips is plopped before them, it may be a better idea to
satisfy your Tex-Mex taste buds at home for a while. Cut some flour
tortillas into wedges and bake until crispy, or put wedges of corn
tortillas in the microwave until crisp for a quick, healthy chip
fix. Dip into salsa, which is usually fat free, or try our recipes
for low-fat guacamole and cheese dip.
</P>
<P>
   The guacamole comes from Wavrin, who's fooled many a
sophisticated spa guest into thinking they are indulging when he
offers it at special events. Truth is, his version has about half
the fat of regular guacamole.
</P>
<P>
   Wavrin's trick for quesadillas is to use small amounts of
cheeses with strong flavors, such as feta and blue cheese, along
with part-skim mozzarella. Grilled vegetables and corn make good
fillers, too. Garnishes are salsa and cilantro. They are served in
wedges, usually as a side to soup. Three wedges, or the equivalent
of a whole tortilla folded over, come in at around 180 calories and
only 6 grams of fat.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of low-fat, largely vegetarian cooking didn't come
naturally to Wavrin. He grew up on a cattle ranch and was trained
as a chef in the classic butter-and-cream French tradition.
</P>
<P>
   But during his six years as La Puerta's chef, he's mastered a
number of dishes to satisfy the health-conscious guest with
discriminating taste. Many of the recipes are in the ``Rancho La
Puerta Cookbook'' (Broadway Books, $20).
</P>
<P>
   We found some great ideas from other sources, too, proving that
cookbook folks know the appeal of Tex-Mex cuisine. For the makings
of a Tex-Mex fiesta for a fraction of the fat, see the recipes
inside. There are slow-cooked shredded beef tacos, cheese
enchiladas and unbelievably light chiles rellenos, all sure to fit
in with most diet plans.
</P>
<P>
   Now if someone would just invent a low-cal margarita. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Reagan walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
