<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1287 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EURO-DIVISIONS-BOS &LR;      01-13 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EURO-DIVISIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE LAND OF THE EURO, THE FRENCH FUME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS _ What's in a name? Plenty when it comes to Europe's
new single currency.
</P>
<P>
   The euro, which on Jan. 1 became the currency for 11 European
Union countries, was hailed by officials here, the EU capital, as
the crowning achievement of a campaign for European integration.
</P>
<P>
   But the euro has also served to highlight the cultural and
linguistic differences across the continent that make problematic
the creation of a political and economic bloc to rival the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The French are angriest over the designation of the new economic
union as ``Euroland.'' They consider this use of an English word as
an insult, particularly because Britain is one of three countries
that chose not to participate in the euro launch. Greece wanted to
join but could not reduce its debt and inflation levels enough to
qualify, while the British, Swedes and Danes decided it was a
foolhardy surrender of sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   French purists are incensed by what they consider yet another
Anglicization, a process aided and abetted in this instance by the
European Union. If French is the language of diplomacy, English has
become the language of finance. This fact is especially galling to
the Gauls.
</P>
<P>
   Former French president Valery Giscard d'Estaing was among those
who vociferously denounced the term ``Euroland,'' first coined by
American bankers and adopted by European Union officials because
they think it sounds hip.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a horrible expression, an Anglo-Saxon expression of
denigration,'' opined the former president, in French.
</P>
<P>
   Herve Lavenir de Buffon, president of the International
Committee for French as a European Language, was even more
strident, suggesting that adopting Euroland was an act of ``cheap
Americanization and treason against Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   The august Academie Francaise formally ruled last week in Paris
that ``Euroland'' is a non-non. ``The Academy advises against the
use of `Euroland' because it is not the name of a sovereign state
or even a confederation, but simply the area of application of a
treaty,'' concluded the academy, which is the official guardian of
Gallic culture, in a communique. ``One never speaks of dollar-land
or sterling-land but of the dollar zone and the sterling zone.''
</P>
<P>
   The academy recommended calling the bloc the ``euro zone,''
pointing out that this is the term used by the Bank of France.
</P>
<P>
   But by joining the single currency, the Bank of France and the
10 other central banks in Euroland have become largely irrelevant.
Monetary policy for the bloc is set by the new European Central
Bank in Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
   Other French institutions, including leading newspapers such as
Liberation, have taken to adding an ``e'' to the end of Euroland to
make it look more like the spellings of Ireland and Finland, which
are Irlande and Finlande in French. But as some Eurocrats here
point out, ``lande'' in French means open, uncultivated land.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking privately over dinner at an impeccable French
restaurant called La Maison du Cygne here on the Grand Place, one
European Union official said he was reluctant to arm those opposed
to the single currency with such a propaganda coup as the word
Eurolande.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to be calling this the euro desert,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
