<SLUG> BC-HAZELNUTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HAZELNUT DESERVES A LITTLE RESPECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH FANTASIA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The flavor of hazelnuts seems to be in
everything, from coffee to ice cream, yet you could count America's
per-capita consumption of these little heart-shaped nuts on one
hand. Actually, on two fingers.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, for all its popularity, Americans only eat two
hazelnuts per person, per year, according to the Hazelnut Marketing
Board. Most of the hazelnut-flavored products on the market in
America are just that, flavored, not made from real nuts. It's a
situation growers like Peter McDonald would like to see change.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's farm is in Oregon's Willamette Valley, where 99
percent of the hazelnuts _ or, filberts, as some call them _ grown
in America are produced.
</P>
<P>
   ``The joke is that we grow filberts and sell hazelnuts,''
McDonald said, standing in a grove of hazelnut trees last summer.
``There really isn't a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the sun shines brightly, the floor of the grove is
bathed in shadow. About 30 feet above, the branches of the
multitrunked trees form a thick canopy. From eye level, you can't
tell that there are nuts up there, much less what type they are.
Much like a chestnut, the smaller hazelnut develops in a husk that
dries and splits when the nut is mature. The trees start producing
when they are 4 years old and will keep producing indefinitely,
McDonald said.
</P>
<P>
   The gray dirt below is as smooth as a ballroom dance floor and
devoid of litter, for good reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't pick the nuts, or shake them from the trees because
the branches are too fragile,'' McDonald said. To harvest, ``we
wait until they drop and vacuum them up.''
</P>
<P>
   Any divot larger than half an inch across will prevent a nut
from being harvested.
</P>
<P>
   ``The drop'' happens each year in late September or early
October and, in a good year, each acre of trees can produce about
two tons of nuts. The 1997 harvest is the largest to date, with
Oregon farmers producing more than 45,000 tons. Unfortunately, it's
a cyclical crop, large one year and low the next; 1998 brought a
harvest of only 15,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, from one-fifth to one-third of the hazelnuts grown in
America are exported to Europe, with Germans buying the largest
share. Unlike peanut-loving Americans, the average German eats
about 200 hazelnuts annually, McDonald said.
</P>
<P>
   So what is it that the Germans know that we don't? Well, there's
the medicinal folklore. Somewhere around the year 20, Dioscorides,
the first pharmacist, wrote in his ``De Materia Medica'' (``On
Medical Matters''), when pounded and eaten with honey, a filbert
will cure chronic coughing. And then there was the part about
mashing burnt filbert shells in suet and smearing the mixture on
bald heads to make hair come again.
</P>
<P>
   Today's consumers have even better reasons to use hazelnuts.
They contain fewer calories per ounce than either walnuts or pecans
and, although hazelnuts have nearly the same amount of total fat as
other nuts, they have a much higher ratio of unsaturated fat to
saturated fat. For instance, hazelnut oil is 88 percent unsaturated
fat and only 7.4 percent saturated fat, according to the Department
of Agriculture. Whereas peanut oil is 78 percent unsaturated fat
and 16 percent saturated fat. In fact, of the 15 oils listed by the
USDA, only canola oil contains less saturated fat than hazelnut
oil.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, one ounce of hazelnuts supplies 75 percent of the
recommended daily intake of vitamin E, 31 percent of the
recommended daily intake of vitamin B6 and 18 percent of the
recommended daily intake of folic acid.
</P>
<P>
   But even the best nutrition report card probably won't get
Americans to eat more hazelnuts. ``If we could only get them into a
cereal ...'' McDonald mused.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SAUTEED HALIBUT WITH HAZELNUT-LEMON SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   (Serves 4)
</P>
<P>
   FISH: 4 (6-ounce) halibut filets
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   SAUCE: 1/4 cup dry, white wine
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon finely chopped shallots
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces toasted, chopped hazelnuts
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons cold, unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped Italian parsley
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   FISH: Heat oven to 450. Dredge halibut filets in flour, shake
off excess. In a 10- to 12-inch, oven-proof, skillet, heat olive
oil. Season fish with salt and pepper. Saute on high heat for 2
minutes per side or until the fish is lightly browned on both
sides. Place pan in oven and bake for 6 minutes or until fish is
firm to the touch. Keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   SAUCE: Pour white wine into pan used to cook fish while pan is
still hot, scraping up any bits of flour that have stuck to the
pan. Add shallots, hazelnuts and lemon juice and reduce over high
heat until the liquid is slightly syrupy. Remove pan from heat and
whisk in butter, one piece at a time, parsley and lemon zest. Stir
until sauce is thickened. Serve over fish.
</P>
<P>
   _ From ``Hazelnuts &AMP; More,'' by Lucy Gerspacher (Graphic Arts
Center Publishing).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ORANGE-HAZELNUT OATMEAL COOKIES
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 48 cookies)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup butter, room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup shortening
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup brown sugar, packed
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons orange zest
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup orange juice
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups oatmeal
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped, toasted hazelnuts
</P>
<P>
   Place rack in center of oven and heat oven to 375. Lightly
grease cookie sheets. In a bowl, whisk flour, baking soda and salt.
In a large bowl, beat butter and sugars until smooth, about 2
minutes. Add eggs and vanilla and continue beating until light and
fluffy, about 2 more minutes. Add dry ingredients and orange juice
alternately in 3 additions. Fold in oatmeal and hazelnuts. Chill
dough for about 1 hour. Drop 1 1/2 tablespoons of dough, 2 inches
apart, on prepared cookie sheets. Flatten dough gently by hand.
Bake until golden, 12 minutes. Let cool on pan for several minutes.
Remove with metal spatula and cool on wire racks.
</P>
<P>
   _ From ``Hazelnuts &AMP; More,'' by Lucy Gerspacher (Graphic Arts
Center Publishing).
</P>
</TEXT>
