<HEADLINE>
MUSLIM RAGE IN SOUTH AFRICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ Five days after he was shot in the head by a
policeman's rubber bullet, Yusuf Jacobs, a recent convert to Islam,
Tuesday became to many Muslims here the first martyr in a deadly
confrontation between South African security forces and radicals
suspected of sowing domestic terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of angry Muslims marched in a long funeral procession
in Cape Town Tuesday, shouting inflammatory slogans _ ``One Police,
One Bullet'' _ and firing weapons. Addressing mourners gathered in
a township stadium, the radical leader Abdulsalaam Ibrahim issued a
battle cry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We say to the police and the military, `You have declared war
on innocent people.' We need to arm ourselves because they are
killing defenseless people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs, 22, was hit on Friday during a Muslim protest in Cape
Town against Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain, who was
visiting, and the recent US-British airstrikes in Iraq. The rally
was illegal, prompting police response. But Islamic militants vowed
to retaliate by ``making the country ungovernable'' if Jacobs died.
</P>
<P>
   It was not an idle threat. Cape Town was shaken by 1,137 violent
attacks last year, including more than 80 bombings. The new year
opened with a car exploding on the city's waterfront _ a tourist
center. Police suspect Ibrahim's group _ People Against Gangsterism
and Drugs (PAGAD) _ is behind the violence.
</P>
<P>
   The government, directed by Deputy President Thabo Mbeki,
Tuesday launched an ambitious initiative making the crisis in Cape
Town its top national security priority. Called Operation Good
Hope, the plan devotes $67,000 per month to increase national
intelligence and police structures in the city and its surrounding
suburbs and townships. Security officials have also asked President
Nelson Mandela to open a probe into Jacob's death in an effort to
defuse anger against the police.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government will act against anybody who either propagates
or attempts to instigate any acts of violence,'' said Sydney
Mufamadi, minister of safety and security.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, the crisis in Cape Town is a clash between the
police and a discontented minority. Western Cape Province has the
highest density of Muslims in South Africa, numbering about
500,000. Most are packed into the impoverished townships on the
outskirts of Cape Town. Illegal drugs _ prolific in those
neighborhoods for decades _ have fueled violence among
predominantly Muslim gangs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, in reaction to the rising criminal activity afflicting
the townships, civic leaders banded together and created PAGAD.
Initially, it was a secular response, a frustrated community's
attempt to take back its streets. The group enjoyed early support
among people who believed the police were standing idly by while
their children killed one another.
</P>
<P>
   But PAGAD soon turned into a vehicle for radical Islamic
elements, and their broadening target range of vigilante attacks
exposed the deep levels of political discontent and religious
ferment running through the Cape Muslim community. The group _ to
which Jacobs belonged _ started by bombing the homes of drug
dealers and killing gang leaders. Last year it turned against
Muslim businessmen, politicians, and mainstream clerics. The group
is suspected in the explosion of a Planet Hollywood restaurant in
August.
</P>
<P>
   ``PAGAD has organic roots in a community that over two decades
became destabilized through drug abuse and the resulting domino
effect of crime,'' said Shamil Jeppie, a University of Cape Town
historian. ``But that is a naive understanding of the problem.
There is a clash of visions about what Islam is and how it should
work within democratic law.''
</P>
<P>
   Active during the struggle to liberate South Africa from
apartheid, many Muslims have become disillusioned by democracy. The
new constitution ensured liberal freedoms anathema to Islam. The
Truth and Reconciliation Commission let murders buy their freedom,
they said, with half-truths. The police force, still manned by
old-guard apartheid officers, did not protect them.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result, marginal Muslim groups determined that the
struggle should continue,'' said Rashied Omar, imam of the
Claremont Main Road Mosque in a suburb of Cape Town. Groups like
PAGAD, and more recent offshoots, have taken up arms against
government officials and moderate Muslims alike.
</P>
<P>
   Internecine religious strife aside, the police and politicians
have given their critics cause. Law enforcement has a difficult
record to defend. There was not a single conviction tied to the
1,137 violent attacks last year. Police have yet to bring a case in
the Planet Hollywood blast. In a blatant mockery of their efficacy,
the city's largest police stations were hit by armed robbers last
week.
</P>
<P>
   In their defense, police officials say they believe the violence
is being carried out by a small cell of people, and that building a
case against them is extremely difficult.
</P>
<P>
   The Cape is also caught in a competitive game between two rigid
political rivals: the ruling African National Congress and its
apartheid foe, now called the New National Party. The Western Cape
is the only region governed at the provincial level by the NNP.
Mbeki wants it back, and underscored that point on Saturday at a
rally marking the 87th anniversary of the ANC. Celebrating in the
township of Athlone, a central turf in the Muslim conflict, the
deputy president urged people in the Cape to back his party in the
upcoming national elections in May.
</P>
<P>
   He also issued the call for a new police strategy in the Cape _
a move that, in an election year, looks political even if governed
by higher motives.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, false bomb threats forced evacuations in a shopping
mall, the central post office, and a restaurant Tuesday, and the
police are taking special precautions until the furor over Jacob's
death recedes. Members of the South African National Defense Forces
are patrolling Cape Town's waterfront undercover. Road blocks and
weapons searches have been set up at various points throughout the
city. And Operation Good Hope, devised in just days, is already
being implemented.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
