<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POVERTY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO TURNS TO WELFARE TO AID POOREST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ While the United States is dismantling welfare,
Mexico is building such benefits for its poorest families.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past 17 months, the administration of President Ernesto
Zedillo has quietly implemented a sweeping antipoverty initiative
that gives cash benefits directly to the poor.
</P>
<P>
   The welfare program _ dubbed ``Progresa,'' or ``Progress'' _ is
a dramatic and controversial departure in Mexican social policy,
which for decades has largely consisted of providing food and other
basic services through government-funded subsidies or price
controls.
</P>
<P>
   But those projects have mostly failed to stop the country's
growing poverty, which now affects around 40 percent of the
population despite years of economic growth and a half-decade of
free trade with the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``Giving cash benefits to the poor has been one of the most
difficult things to convince people of,'' said Santiago Levy, a
former Boston University economics professor who is now Mexico's
deputy finance minister and Progresa's chief architect. ``But we're
finding that the idea is more efficient and that the money is being
fairly well spent.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 2 million families have been enrolled in the program
since it began in August 1997. The administration hopes to double
that figure by 2000. And although this year's federal budget is the
most austere in modern history, Progresa's 1999 appropriation
increased 40 percent over 1998, to $800 million.
</P>
<P>
   Poverty is perhaps Mexico's most pressing and daunting problem
and can be found in nearly every corner of the country, from the
dusty shantytowns along the Rio Grande to the remote jungle
enclaves in the southern state of Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
   By most estimates, roughly 40 percent of the country's 97
million people live in poverty. That is more than the 29 percent
who lived in poverty a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Today, extreme poverty hounds 25 percent of the country's
residents, most experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Progresa is as controversial as it is radical. Critics of the
sudden shift to welfare say the plan serves only the most needy at
the expense of the moderate poor, reducing or ending subsidies and
discount prices on a variety of staple foods.
</P>
<P>
   To underscore their argument, Progresa opponents point to
tortillas, the nation's most important food product. Days after the
government lifted price controls on tortillas on Jan. 1, the cost
of a 2-pound stack rose from about 30 cents to as high as 50 cents.
On Wednesday, the government pressured tortilla makers to limit
prices to about 35 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Progresa critics offer other reasons why the idea does more harm
than good: it favors the rural poor over the urban poor; it does
not do enough to lift families out of poverty through job training;
and it is too small to have any real impact on the country's
widespread problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a philosophy driving this that says you can give cash
to the poor but you won't help them up the income ladder,'' said
Denise Dresser, a political scientist at Mexico's Autonomous
Technological Institute. ``It's a message that doesn't offer much
hope for the poor.''
</P>
<P>
   The shift to welfare underscores a change in the Zedillo
administration's emphasis to serving mostly rural poor, who make up
60 percent of Mexicans who live in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, under the old system, nearly 69 percent of
federal antipoverty funds went to low-income urban residents,
according to government budget documents. With the expansion of
Progresa this year, the administration expects that rural
communities will receive 76 percent of assistance dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Progresa identifies eligible families from interviews conducted
mostly in rural towns and villages. To qualify, a family has to
keep two promises: that their children will stay in school and that
they will get regular medical checkups. Every month, caseworkers
review class attendance sheets and clinical records.
</P>
<P>
   If the family complies, it receives an average cash benefit
every two months of about $50. The amount increases for every
additional year each child remains in school _ what officials refer
to as ``scholarships.''
</P>
<P>
   Another trait that distinguishes Progresa from other assistance
programs in Mexico is its emphasis on women: Only the mother can
receive the family's benefits because experts say they think she
would handle the money more responsibly than the father, and
scholarships are higher for girls who stay in school than they are
for boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a program that makes a pact with families who have
been the principal buffer against our volatile economic
situtation,'' said Jose Gomez Leon, a Harvard-trained economist who
is Progresa's director. ``And it does it by integrating assistance
with health and education.''
</P>
<P>
   By scrapping the old programs _ nearly all of which were created
by Zedillo's Institutional Revolutionary Party, which has
controlled presidential power in Mexico for the past 80 years _
Zedillo appears to be distinguishing himself from his predecessors,
especially Carlos Salinas.
</P>
<P>
   A free-market proponent who is credited with winning approval
for the North American Free Trade Agreement in 1993, Salinas
created his own public works and social investment project called
``Solidarity.'' By 1994, however, the initiative was riddled with
accusations of corruption and that its main beneficiaries were
local party bosses.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Solidarity) sent money to the community level, but that left
it open to influence by political leaders who ruined the program,''
said one top administration aide. ``What we want to do is bring the
benefits directly to the family level.''
</P>
<P>
   Early on, Progresa sparked fierce debates within the government
between those who favored a cash-based welfare system and those who
worried about the chaos that would follow if subsidies were
removed. Zedillo settled the dispute by siding with Levy and Gomez
and approving Progresa, which has received praise from
international organizations such as the World Bank and the
Inter-American Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Progresa reaches its goal of aiding 4 million families,
it remains unclear how long welfare will last here, too. Zedillo's
term ends in 2000, and no one guarantees that the next president
will keep the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge is for us to keep this progam from being
identified as a political operation,'' said Levy. ``If we can stick
by the rules and make sure the families are sticking with their
promises, then there will be no reason to change it. But it must
remain society's program.''
</P>
</TEXT>
