<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-BEARS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIGHTMARE ON WALL STREET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They said it could not possibly happen again.
</P>
<P>
   But in the first week after the calendar flipped to 1999, the
Dow Jones industrial average twice set new records, coming within
shouting distance of that once-implausible 10,000 mark and imbuing
investors with renewed hopes of the untold riches yet to be reaped.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow has not only bounced back from a 512-point, one-day dive
in August but has done so while one-third of the world has been
mired in recession. Americans are spending like there's no
tomorrow, and Wall Street is predicting the economy will continue
to expand. Nothing can stop it!
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an optimism in the air _ a feeling a new wave is
coming with the euro and the millennium and all the rest,'' said
Jeremy Siegel, a finance professor at the University of
Pennsylvania's Wharton School in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   It may be a new wave. Or it may, just suppose, be insanity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless the laws of nature have been repealed,'' said Barton
Biggs of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter in a 1999 outlook report,
``bust still follows boom, and bear markets follow bull markets.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth about the market's future no doubt lies between the
doomsday forecasts of bears, like Biggs, who have crawled out of
their Wall Street dens, and the mania that has infected
Internet-stock buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, as the Dow last week added 461 points _ 5 percent
_ in its march toward Friday's record close of 9,643.32, it was not
difficult to find market analysts and economists willing to
indulge, albeit briefly, in their worst nightmares about 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Although none would predict a market collapse while the United
States is still in the midst of its longest peacetime expansion
ever, they did reveal what keeps them awake at night. &QL; 
 &QL; 
A junky bull market &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 stock market index posted a snappy
26.7 percent gain last year. Peel back the surface, and the picture
is not so pretty: The 10 best-performing stocks in the index
produced a remarkable 41 percent of that gain.
</P>
<P>
   In healthier bull markets, ``the soldiers _ the broader market _
support the generals,'' explained Marshall Acuff, equity strategist
for Salomon Smith Barney. ``In 1998, the soldiers ran away from the
field and left the generals to fight the battle by themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the ``generals'' were technology giants: Microsoft
Corp., Dell Computer Corp., MCI WorldCom Inc., IBM Corp., Intel
Corp., Lucent Technologies Inc., Cisco Systems Inc., as well as
General Electric Corp., Wal-Mart Stores Inc., and Pfizer Inc. Of
the Top 10, all but four doubled last year. Dell's stock more than
tripled, and Lucent's nearly did.
</P>
<P>
   Blue chip companies propelled all markets last year. For
example, although the technology-heavy Nasdaq index rose 40 percent
last year, Acuff said, the average stock in Nasdaq was actually
down 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A market built on such a narrow foundation is what worries
analysts about 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a healthy thing,'' he said. ``The best-quality
bull markets are ones that rise on solid breadth.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Up and out &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The problem with the current market, analysts said, is the high
price of many stocks when compared to their per-share earnings.
</P>
<P>
   This ``price/earnings ratio'' has spiraled to record highs.
According to calculations by Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI, a Lexington
research firm, the P/E ratio is currently at a record 33.8 times
earnings _ up from 28 times earnings last fall. At its low in 1980,
the market's P/E was just 7 times earnings. That was at the end of
the 1970s bear market, the longest in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me nervous,'' said economist David Wyss at S&AMP;P DRI,
who wonders how today's lofty prices can be sustained.
</P>
<P>
   As troubling, he said, is the market's accelerated pace. After
the 1987 crash, it took two years to return to pre-crash levels.
After the August 1998 plunge, the recovery period was only four
months _ ``the world's shortest correction,'' he said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Internet intensity &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although analysts generally avoid using ``bubble'' to describe
the market overall, it is the first word on their lips to describe
Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The combined market value of publicly traded Internet stocks is
currently about $250 billion _ about the size of the Hong Kong
stock market. Yet most Internet companies did not turn a dime of
profit last year.
</P>
<P>
   Take Broadcast.com. The Dallas-based company's stock shot up
from 80 a share at mid-week to nearly 230 after its executives told
stock analysts about a plan to disseminate earnings conference
calls by public companies over the Internet. After Nasdaq officials
on Friday temporarily halted trading in the stock it settled at 197
1/2 at week's end.
</P>
<P>
   The most successful among the Internet-related companies _
America Online Inc. (145 a share); Amazon.com Inc. (160 1/4); and
Yahoo Inc. (343 5/8) _ have combined yearly sales of $3.5 billion.
But their aggregate value in the stock market is out of this world,
at 40 times sales, said Ned Riley, chief investment officer for
BankBoston Corp. Compare it, he said, to the S&AMP;P 500, which is
worth twice its yearly sales.
</P>
<P>
   This ``doesn't matter'' to investors, Riley said, ``because
there's another fool out there buying at a higher price, and this
speculative bubble keeps expanding and expanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts' unspoken fear: If the Internet bubble pops, it could
jeopardize the entire market in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The great profits debate &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Economist say markets rise for essentially two reasons: Low
interest rates or strong corporate profits. When interest rates are
low, money is cheap, encouraging companies to invest and consumers
to spend. Low bond yields also make investors eager to pour money
into stocks, further driving up share prices.
</P>
<P>
   But in forecasting the stock market in 1999, economists can't
seem to agree on whether corporate America will make more money
this year or less. In an annual survey of analysts forecasting the
new year, First Call Corp. said Wall Street expects 18.5 percent
growth in 1999 profits. No one believes this _ not even First Call,
which said 18.5 percent was ``on the optimistic side.''
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, profits last year grew just 3.2 percent. More
bleak were operating profits _ profits minus one-time gains and
losses. By the end of the third quarter of 1998, operating profits
had been in decline during most of the seven quarters, according to
Charles Clough, chief investment strategist for Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
As companies' profits fell, their debt swelled by $350 billion last
year _ much more than it did during the leveraged buyout boom of
1988, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Profits, Clough predicted, ``will go down well into the year
2000.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The wealth squelch &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The danger is that the consumer spending craze appears to be the
only engine keeping the economy going. Consumers are riding high,
and companies are obliging them: Two dozen new sport utility
vehicles were introduced last year in the United States, including
offerings by Mercedez Benz and BMW. Spending is being financed by
unprecedented gains in stock portfolios, which make consumers feel
rich, so rich that they have quit saving money: The savings rate
actually went into negative territory for part of last year for the
first time in decades.
</P>
<P>
   Although retailers report they had a good holiday shopping
season, the party may be over. Consumers ``are spending more than
what is sustainable,'' said Robert Brusca, chief economist in the
New York office of Nikko Securities Co.
</P>
<P>
   And what about the stock market? ``The image you get is of Wile
E. Coyote having stepped off a mesa but still smiling because he
hasn't looked down yet,'' Brusca said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The world is a mess &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   True, Asian stock markets are rallying. Hong Kong's market rose
6 percent last week; South Korea's, 11 percent; Indonesia's 10
percent. The cascading currency crises of the summer _ which
triggered Russia's economic collapse and the Dow's plunge in August
_ have abated.
</P>
<P>
   But the heart of Asia's economy, Japan, is still a mess. Its
financial system is sucking wind _ and carrying about $700 billion
in bad loans. Said Acuff, who traveled to Tokyo twice last month,
``people there ask you what can we do to make this better. There's
a loss of confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if Tokyo's whirlpool doesn't pull down the US market,
pessimists fear another international shock might. The prime
candidate: Brazil, which last week delayed payments of government
debt and is facing possible recession and currency devaluation.
</P>
<P>
   ``World growth is still slowing. Europe is probably getting
weaker, rather than stronger. Japan's not going anywhere and Latin
America's getting weaker,'' said Robert Mellman, senior economist
for J.P. Morgan in New York, who is also pessimistic about US
profits.
</P>
<P>
   So, why does the market keep going up? ``It's hard to know where
it's coming from.''
</P>
<P>
   But indulgence in such dark scenarios is futile, because they
could certainly prove to be wrong. The Dow and the S&AMP;P 500 in 1999
very well may post double-digit gains again _ for a fifth year in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   Stranger things have happened.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
