<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-BOTHA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY BOTHA? GOOD QUESTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Francois Botha knows most people would agree with
the opinion of Ron Stander's wife.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, Stander was a club fighter who somehow found himself
in the ring with Joe Frazier one night. After Frazier was done
beating Stander half to death, his wife was asked what she thought
of the mess her husband had become. She said, somehwat irked, ``I
told him you don't enter a Volkswagen in the Indianapolis 500.''
</P>
<P>
   Botha is considered the Volkswagen in Saturday's fistic race
with Mike Tyson at the MGM Grand Garden Arena, but this will be no
Indy 500. If the experts are correct, Botha-Tyson will be a
demolition derby, one in which the Volkswagen is widely expected to
collide head-on with a Ford Suburban.
</P>
<P>
   The former International Boxing Federation champion has done his
best to ignore such talk, but it is all around him. Wherever he
goes in Las Vegas, Botha hears that he is a 6-1 underdog but should
be 60-1. He hears how fearsome this latest incarnation of Tyson
appears after a 17-month layoff. He hears this is the unbeatable
Tyson again. The old Tyson. The intimidating Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   Botha hears all this and tries to ignore it, because what else
can he do when a $1.8 million payday lies just three nights and one
probable beating away?
</P>
<P>
   ``Tyson always had the intimidation factor,'' conceded Botha
(39-1, 24 KOs). ``So it's the opponent that counts. The guys he
fought like Frank Bruno and Bruce Seldon were scared. They lost the
fights before they got in the ring. I can't be intimidated.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he can't, but one sentence later Botha is saying, ``I
still think that Mike Tyson is the greatest heavyweight out there.
I have nothing to lose and everything to gain. If I lose, people
will say, `I told you so.' People don't expect anything of me.
People still see Tyson as the baddest man out there. That's going
to make my victory that much bigger. I'm not another Peter
McNeeley.''
</P>
<P>
   McNeeley, of course, lasted only 89 seconds with Tyson under
similar circumtances, so that's not saying much. Tyson was coming
off 3 1/2 years in prison that night and chose to fight a guy who
had never been in with anyone of note. This time he is coming off a
briefer exile for biting Evander Holyfield's ears and has chosen to
fight a former world champion, even if that championship was won
under a cloud because Botha tested positive for steroids after
winning a decision from Axel Schulz.
</P>
<P>
   Yet if one looks carefully at Botha's record, the victims list
is not much different from the one McNeeley carried with him into
this same Grand Garden Arena: Lee Gilbert, Tim Tomashek, David
Cherry, Willie Jake, Brian Sargent, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   The only difference is the presence of two-time heavyweight
champion Michael Moorer and Schulz on Botha's list, but he lost a
desultory decision to the former and won the IBF title from the
latter without winning the fight, which was ruled a no-contest
after the drug test. So if Botha is not another Volkswagen or
another McNeeley what is he? A Yugo?
</P>
<P>
   ``I made same huge mistakes that night against Moorer,'' Botha
insisted. ``I'm a more mature fighter now. Most of the public
thinks I'm another Peter McNeeley. They think, `This guy is another
sacrificial lamb.' But I believe strongly in myself. I really don't
care what Mike Tyson thinks.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a good, thing because here's what Tyson thinks of
Francois ``VW'' Botha, at the moment:
</P>
<P>
   Q. ``What do you expect Botha to do when you come right at
him?''
</P>
<P>
   A. ``Die.''
</P>
<P>
   Some might call that hyperbole. Others might think Tyson is
taking Botha a tad lightly. A few would conclude that Tyson simply
agrees with Mrs. Stander and chose to answer with a burst of
honesty.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, Botha clings to the one straw out there for
all opponents of the two-time heavyweight champion: Evander
Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did the same thing with Evander Holyfield,'' Botha said.
``He didn't have any respect for Evander Holyfield before their
first fight. After the fight, he asked to shake Holyfield's hand.
He'll respect me after Jan. 16. This is the kind of fight that most
heavyweights wait for. It can put you up where you belong.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I knock out Tyson, I will be the biggest thing in boxing. I
believe they bit off more than they can chew with Francois Botha.
No pun intended.''
</P>
<P>
   If they did, it's news to Tyson, his handlers, and local
bookmakers. In a world Botha believes is clamoring for the next
Great White Hope, he knows he is being seen as the Great White Nope
by the multitudes.
</P>
<P>
   Yet with three days to go, he still believes. With three days to
go, he is still unafraid. With three days to go, he still thinks he
is what the world wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``People all over are crying for a white heavyweight champion,''
Botha said. ``In fact, many black people have come up to me many
times offering their support. Blacks and whites are crying for a
white heavyweight.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night they may have good reason to, as Mrs. Ron Stander
well knows.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
