<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-JOBS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN TRAFFIC STOPS, POOR GO TO WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ It happens about any time of day at busy
intersections throughout this capital metropolis. Once the traffic
light turns red, the carnival begins.
</P>
<P>
   A man with a clown's exaggerated smile painted on his face
climbs a ladder and eats fire while his small children collect
pesos from waiting motorists.
</P>
<P>
   A woman in a white, soot-stained skirt sells straightened
doughnuts called ``churros.'' Young boys dart between cars offering
30-second windshield washings. The young and old peddle everything
from chewing gum to crayons to seat belts.
</P>
<P>
   It is a sign of the times in this cash- and job-strapped
economy, where millions of ordinary Mexicans must make ends meet
any way and anywhere they can.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is hard work and I know it's not good for my health, but
there's nothing else I can do,'' said Mario Fernandez, a
69-year-old fire-eater, who works an east-side street corner.
</P>
<P>
   On a good day, Fernandez said, he can make up to $10 in tips
from drivers, nearly triple the $3.40 daily minimum wage. But to
earn that, he repeatedly thrusts flaming gasoline-soaked swabs into
his mouth from 7 a.m. until sunset, six days a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drink lots of milk to coat my mouth and throat,'' he added,
in a hoarse voice.
</P>
<P>
   Years of economic growth have opened government-controlled
industries to private competition, fueled by capital from
multinational corporations and bullish investors.
</P>
<P>
   But much of the country's new wealth has yet to reach the
swollen ranks of the poor. And new price hikes on basics from
tortillas to electricity may worsen the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rapid population growth is one way of explaining Mexico's
poverty, but it's not the complete answer,'' said Yolanda Moreno,
an economic consultant in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a new welfare program by President Ernesto Zedillo,
millions of Mexicans are not covered, and must make ends meet with
unusual tasks.
</P>
<P>
   Some walk around dressed as ostriches or other outrageous
costumes to get a laugh and a peso out of spectators. Others spread
blankets on sidewalks and sell old shoes, used watches, and faded
magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel Rodriguez Cardoso and his family guard Monte Stanovoi
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with a damp red rag and a plastic bucket filled with soapy
water, the Rodriguez family earns about $140 a month washing and
protecting the cars that are parked on this affluent block.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes my wife washes dishes or sweeps over there,''
Rodriguez said, pointing to the Chinese Embassy on the corner.
``We're still enjoying the extra money we got during Christmas, so
we're not feeling the higher prices yet. But we will soon, I know
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 1323EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1300 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-13 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VEHICLE TO THE AMERICAN DREAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yellow school bus. Orange city bus. Bright beacons, great,
glowing chariots chugging me to class. Some people just cannot
understand how I could see buses in this light. Many writers are on
a scorched-bus campaign, rewriting school busing into one of the
greatest wastes and social evils of the last 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   The revisionists fool no one. They blame elitist, liberal
judges. They exhume 20-year-old polls to say, ``See, see, the
blacks didn't like busing either!'' These tactics give white
critics the license to torch busing without appearing to immolate
educational opportunity for African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   This week, busing was news again as Boston Mayor Thomas M.
Menino pledged five new neighborhood schools. The Globe said this
could signal the end of busing. Menino said he wanted parents to
have ``the choice of where to send their child to school. Parents
should make that decision. Not the politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   African-American parents know that buildings and ``choice'' mean
nothing when only five of the city's 75 elementary schools send
significant numbers of students to Latin. For Menino to go from
rhetoric to reality, he must remember what the revisionists
insidiously forget. The issue is not neighborhood schools. It is
the quality denied to black neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   I called my mother to ask her why she put me on a school bus in
the second grade in Milwaukee to go to a school a mile away from my
neighborhood school. In the fifth grade she put me in an
accelerated program, which meant that from that point through high
school graduation, I would take the city bus to schools between 4
and 8 miles away from home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't regret it at all,'' my mother, Doris Jackson, told me.
``I never gave it a second thought. Your little mouth was working
overtime. I knew you were not going to get what you needed in the
schools around here.''
</P>
<P>
   My mother did not use the buzz phrases of the '90s, like
``parent involvement,'' ``teacher-student ratios,'' or
``resources.'' She judged my neighborhood school with her eyes. The
school had served me fine in kindergarten and first grade in 1960
and 1961. I still feel the hug of first-grade teacher Ms.
Vanderkelen, who told me I did a great job even though my Marine
Corps hat fell off on stage during a Veterans Day program.
</P>
<P>
   But we lived in a neighborhood that went predominantly white to
predominantly African-American almost overnight. Parents could feel
resources and caring teachers leaving the local school with the
force of a gust blowing an umbrella inside out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing some of the teachers and hearing them talk, you could
tell that the quality was going way down,'' my mother said. ``You
could look around the school and see if the kids were at their
desks. If they were running around, going to the bathroom and not
going right back to class, that was not good.''
</P>
<P>
   From age 7 until 16, I spent one to two hours a day on the bus,
not to mention the sloshing, sliding, and freezing the half-mile to
and from the bus stop. Like my mother, I have absolutely no regret
except for watching how my neighborhood friends got the shaft
merely for staying close to home. Their textbooks were five to 10
years older than mine. I went on field trips to Madison and
Chicago, to farms, fish hatcheries, and pumpkin fields. My
neighborhood friends were lucky if they went to the city museum.
</P>
<P>
   Revisionists blame busing for a brain drain that harmed black
neighborhoods. That is laughable, since no one talks about brain
drains when white families send children to prep schools. The fact
is that black folks, whether my mother or the thousands of
African-American families who have used METCO in Boston to get
their children into suburban schools, are using any means necessary
to catch what was drained out of neighborhood schools.
</P>
<P>
   This was about more than books and teachers. It was about
exposure and confidence. I was friends with the sons of furriers as
well as factory workers. I had white and black bowling partners and
partners as who talked as much science fiction as sports. The
interracial friendships taught me about individual humanity in a
racist country. The vigorous debates with white teachers taught me
how to use the library to explore and explain my African-American
heritage.
</P>
<P>
   The bus carried me through neighborhoods that showed me in
subtle ways the inequities of the American Dream. I did not
understand redlining, but I did understand the lower prices for
chocolate milk and hit records. I gained so much independence that
by 17, I regularly took Greyhound to Chicago to see shows or up to
Green Bay to photograph the Packers.
</P>
<P>
   The ability to travel would come in handy in journalism. Busing
is not ideal. But until society treat schools equally, it has no
right to vilify it or any other way black parents secure a good
school. Until quality education comes back to the black
neighborhood, it makes the critics rather transparent. They hate
busing so because they know those yellow buses, those great,
glowing chariots, put a lot of black children like me on the road
to a golden life.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 1325EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1303 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-MANAGERS-BOS &LR;      01-13 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-MANAGERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PROSECUTORS' DRAW ON THE PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The last time Representative F. James Sensenbrenner
Jr. argued a case in court was a divorce matter in 1975. He also
questioned a witness in a 1989 impeachment trial of a federal
judge. But over the New Year's holiday, while the Wisconsin
Republican was home watching the Rose Bowl, he penned the opening
argument in what many consider the case of the century, the Senate
impeachment trial of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Sensenbrenner is one of 13 House ``managers'' who will act as
prosecutors in the impeachment trial. They are all white, all men,
and all lawyers, and all are among the most conservative members of
the House.
</P>
<P>
   While the 100 senators hold Clinton's fate in their hands, they
are not allowed to speak during the trial until the deliberations.
Thus, the managers will become the focus, as they make the final
effort to convince the Senate _ and a largely skeptical public _
that Clinton should be convicted and ousted from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But to the great frustration of the managers, they are preparing
for the case of their lives without a road map. ``It would be a lot
easier if we knew the rules,'' Sensenbrenner said in a telephone
interview last week, explaining that he still did not know whether
witnesses such as former White House intern Monica S. Lewinsky
would be allowed. The Senate trial compromise worked out Friday by
Senators Edward M. Kennedy of Massachusetts and Phil Gramm of Texas
leaves the question of witnesses up in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Sensenbrenner was handpicked by House Judiciary Committee
Chairman Henry Hyde to deliver the opening statement Thursday
because of his ``innate brilliance,'' Hyde said in a brief
interview minutes after he delivered the articles of impeachment to
the Senate last Thursday. It also helped, aides said, that
Sensenbrenner is the second-ranking member of the committee. Hyde
is slated to deliver introductory remarks before Sensenbrenner
begins, as well as one of two closing statements.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Bill McCollum of Florida has been tapped as one
the top managers, due to his even manner and his work as a judge
advocate general in the military, a job that McCollum said is
glamorized in the television series ``JAG.''
</P>
<P>
   McCollum said he dealt with all kinds of cases in the military,
but he said, ``You can never be prepared for a case like this.''
While the House team includes a number of former prosecutors and
staff lawyers, he said, ``We all know that the White House has . .
. the most high-power law firms in town, and we are obviously
working under some severe constraints.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats who served with the managers on the House Judiciary
Committee expressed doubts about their qualifications, saying many
will be perceived by the public as conservative ideologues.
Moreover, said Representative Martin T. Meehan, a Massachusetts
Democrat on the committee, ``None of them have tried a case in a
very long period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   But Paul McNulty, a spokesman for the House Judiciary Committee,
said the managers do not have to have backgrounds as star
prosecutors to perform well. ``Of the lawyers in this country, the
list of us who have done a really big case is rather small,''
McNulty said. He noted that Sensenbrenner and Representative George
Gekas of Pennsylvania have served as managers in impeachment trials
of federal judges, and that several other managers have been
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   While all 13 managers are expected to play a part in the trial,
it is clear that a handful, including Sensenbrenner, McCollum, and
Gekas, will be most prominent. In addition, Representative James
Rogan of California is scheduled to deliver one of the closing
arguments, and Representatives Asa Hutchinson of Arkansas, Lindsey
Graham of South Carolina, and Charles Canady of Florida are
expected to receive top roles.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson may be in the extraordinary position of arguing the
case before a jury of senators that includes his brother, Senator
Tim Hutchinson, also of Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, at least, one of the most qualified managers is
Representative Bob Barr of Georgia, who was the first member of
Congress to call for Clinton's impeachment. Barr, US attorney for
the northern district of Georgia from 1986 to 1990, successfully
prosecuted a former Republican congressman, Patrick Swindall of
Georgia, in 1989 on charges of lying to a grand jury. An aide said
that would make Barr especially well qualified to present the case
that Clinton lied before a grand jury, one of the two impeachment
articles being prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   But some Judiciary Committee officials, speaking privately, said
Barr may be given a low profile due to concerns that he is
perceived _ fairly or not _ as too much of an ideologue. Barr is
expected to be given a role in discussing the laws governing
perjury.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, one of the expected stars is Rogan, a telegenic
former Democrat who rose to prominence as a deputy district
attorney in Los Angeles by working in the ``hard-core gang murder
unit.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde himself is described by associates as more of a coach of
the team than the on-floor leader, but the committee chairman
picked himself for the final arguments of the trial. After Rogan
delivers a closing statement on the facts of the case, Hyde is
slated to wrap things up by making the case for Clinton's
conviction. While there had been some speculation that Hyde's
admission last year of adultery 30 years ago would make him a poor
choice for such a role, aides said this week that Hyde sees no such
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said last week that his job was ``a little depressing,''
but he felt a ``solemnity'' about it. ``All of us wish we could get
it over with,'' Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Baron, an attorney who acted as a House counsel in the 1989
impeachment trials of two federal judges, said he expected much of
the legal work to be done by lawyers for the Judiciary Committee.
Baron said he helped prepare the managers in the previous cases
deliver their statements and sometimes wrote a proposed set of
questions to interrogate witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``You brief them, you teach them, and your job is to make them
look good,'' Baron said, referring to the managers in an
impeachment trial. Unlike a regular case, in which one person might
take the lead in prosecution, Baron said, impeachment trials
usually are divided into small pieces with each manager handling a
specific part. Baron said managers who formerly were lawyers or
prosecutors often performed well, even if they had not argued a
case in many years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The experience of handling a witness is a major help,'' Baron
said. ``It is kind of like riding a bike. And as politicians, all
these guys are reasonably articulate and think on their feet. Some
of the political skills are not only helpful but really applicable
to their skills as managers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
