<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAINE'S IMPEACHMENT PERIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Maine -- Maine voters like their president and like
their two female Republican senators, and they don't want Clinton
ejected from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   So if Senators Olympia Snowe or Susan Collins vote with the
conservative Sun Belt senators who want Clinton impeached, they
risk forfeiting their seat representing a state that gives low
marks to partisan politicking.
</P>
<P>
   Snowe, like two other GOP moderates from New England, Rhode
Island's John Chafee and Vermont's Jim Jeffords, faces reelection
next year. Collins is not up till 2002. Both women are pro-choice
on abortion, hew to the political center, and take pains not to be
caught posturing on national issues while seeming to ignore
bread-and-butter concerns of this largely rural state.
</P>
<P>
   Snowe seems comfortably positioned for reelection, but that
would change dramatically if she votes to remove Clinton from
office, some local experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are satisfied that Snowe and Collins will do the right
thing'' and choose to censure Clinton rather than eject him from
office, said Dr. Chris Potholm, a government professor at Bowdoin.
``Maine assumes they will vote their conscience _ that the best
thing for Snowe and Collins is to say, `OK, the House had its fun,'
but not to vote to remove him.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Maine's voters are nearly evenly divided in thirds,
Republican, Democrat, and independent, said Potholm, ``Republicans
here succeed only by appealing to conservative Democrats.'' For
Snowe to cast her lot with southern and western Republicans baying
for Clinton's scalp, she'd fracture that coalition she needs to
hold her seat for a second term.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she does, it would be because she fears a right-wing
challenge in the primary,'' reasoned Potholm, author of ``An
Insider's Guide to Maine Politics.'' Snowe, whose husband is former
governor John McKernan, would seem to have little difficulty
disposing of a right-wing primary challenger.
</P>
<P>
   Snowe last year heeded the entreaty of Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott and at a key juncture abandoned the campaign finance
reform proposal of Senators John McCain, Republican of Arizona, and
Russ Feingold, Democrat of Wisconsin. ``If she does cave in to Lott
(on impeachment),'' concluded Potholm, ``She would anger the
suburban Democrats in the belt around Portland.''
</P>
<P>
   You've heard of bipartisan and post-partisan. Try this: Maine is
tripartisan. The two senators are Republican; the two congressmen
are Democrats (who voted against impeachment); Governor Angus King,
just reelected with 59 percent of the total vote in a four-way
race, is an independent; and both branches of the Legislature are
controlled by Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't get any more tripartisan than that. Maine expects its
senators to be independent and not hidebound partisans. Margaret
Chase Smith, a Republican who humbled the venomous Joe McCarthy,
and Edmund Muskie, a centrist acceptable to all factions of the
riven Democratic party of the late '60s, were role models for
George Mitchell and Bill Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   Snowe and Collins sit in the Mitchell and Cohen seats,
relinquished by both men. The irony is that Mitchell and Cohen, one
the former Democratic majority leader, the other a Republican who
became Clinton's highly regarded secretary of defense, are both
close to the embattled president, whose fate rests partly in the
hands of the two women who succeeded Clinton's allies.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton remains generally popular here. ``I think if the
president came here for a visit tomorrow, he'd be well-received,''
is the hunch of A. Jay Higgins, a political writer at the Bangor
Daily News. ``I don't sense that there's a great hue and cry for a
full impeachment proceeding against the president, as far as
Olympia's or Susan's constituents are concerned. The mood in Maine
is pretty much `enough, already!' like most other places.''
</P>
<P>
   When Patrick Murphy of Portland's Strategic Marketing Services
polled 400 Mainers last October, 71 percent wanted him to stay in
office, 25 were for impeachment. Sixty-five percent approved of
Clinton's job performance, and 71 percent disapproved of the
Republicans' handling of the impeachment drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton's ratings are high,'' said Murphy. ``Most people here
want the same thing as people in the rest of the country, excluding
the South. They want him censured, but not removed from office.''
</P>
<P>
   Maine's Democratic Party chairwoman, Gwethalyn Phillips, said,
``I'm hoping they (Snowe and Collins) will do the right thing, and
decide we don't need to hear Monica and company parading across the
stage one more time.'' But if Snowe votes to impeach, she added,
``There is an opening here.'' Phillips said she knows of at least
one Democratic office-holder who'll challenge Snowe next year, but
would say which. Potholm said he believes US Representative Tom
Allen ``will run if she looks vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   Governor King has said repeatedly he's not interested in going
to a talking shop in D.C., but his second term is up when Collins
has to run again, and his poll ratings are higher than hers. The
Democrat who just lost to King, Tom Connolly, got only 12 percent
of the vote and would pose little threat to Snowe. Nationally, the
GOP's impeachment drive has driven the party's image to record low
territory _ two of three voters disapprove. A vote by Snowe to
impeach would energize Democrats here like no other issue could.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
