<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SENATE'S BLOODIEST BATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO -- As they gathered in the old Senate chamber in
Washington for a private bipartisan caucus last week, one senator
rose and pointed to the door through which a congressman, Preston
Brooks of South Carolina, entered on what would be the red-and-gold
room's most dramatic and bloodiest day.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Dodd of Connecticut, now the senior Democrat on its
rules committee and thus a curator of its lore, argued that the
caning of Senator Charles Sumner of Massachusetts on May 22, 1856,
foreshadowed the firing on Fort Sumter on April 12, 1861.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever civility and comity remained in the Senate in the
late 1850s ended with that event,'' he said, arguing that when
decorum disappears, greater violence can follow. Dodd did not
exaggerate. In his two-volume biography of Sumner, Harvard
historian David Herbert Donald asserts that the Brooks attack ``may
be regarded as the first blow of the Civil War.''
</P>
<P>
   Educated at Boston Latin, Harvard College, and Harvard Law
School, Sumner was handsome, brilliant, and eloquent. Like many
heroes and martyrs, he was also vain, humorless, and insensitive.
He was slow to denounce the anti-Catholicism of the Know-Nothings
and slower to support women's suffrage.
</P>
<P>
   But he became a zealous advocate for the abolition of slavery
after the Massachusets Legislature elected him to the Senate in
1851. Sumner said he was ``in morals, not politics.'' He laced his
oratory with arcane classical allusions, but not with civility or
comity. Senator Andrew Pickens Butler of South Carolina, Sumner
said, ``has chosen a mistress to whom he has made his vows. . . . I
mean the harlot, slavery.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler was absent but his cousin, Brooks, sought revenge with
the chosen weapon of Southern chivalry, a horsewhip. ``But knowing
that the senator was my superior in strength, it occurred to me
that he might wrest it from my hand,'' Brooks said later. With the
Senate in recess, Sumner sat addressing letters. Brooks approached
him from behind, wielding an 11-ounce hardwood walking stick with a
gold head.
</P>
<P>
   He addressed Sumner, whom he had never met, and when the senator
turned around Brooks brought the cane down upon his skull. A geyser
of blood covered his face as Brooks landed more blows. The 6-foot-2
Sumner staggered to his feet, ripping his desk from the iron plates
bolting it to the floor. Brooks flailed away at his blinded victim,
shattering the stick while delivering what he called ``about 30
first-rate stripes.''
</P>
<P>
   After the five-minute attack, Sumner was stitched up and, during
a long convalescence, lionized by the antislavery forces and the
new Republican party. The abolitionist John Brown visited him to
view his bloodied coat.
</P>
<P>
   The blows that disabled Sumner also disabled the Senate, Dodd
told his colleagues last week. After the Civil War, Sumner's vanity
rose and his statesmanship vanished. In 1868, he welcomed the
impeachment trial of President Andrew Johnson, who, he said, ``has
triumphed in his wickedness'' and ``patronized massacre and
bloodshed and license to the Ku Klux Klan.''
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, the late political operative Lee Atwater once
told me, the birthplace of ``Bully Brooks'' was regarded as a
shrine. But Sumner's assailant died of a sudden fever at 36. After
his victim died in 1874 at 63, the Commonwealth published a
317-page memorial volume of the eulogies for Sumner, including a
53-stanza poem by John Greenleaf Whittier.
</P>
<P>
   Statues rose to him in Boston and Cambridge, but the muse of
history seldom stood as self-confidently as did Charles Sumner of
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   He was like ``a cat without smellers,'' his friend, Richard
Henry Dana Jr., said. ``He has none of the delicate tests that, as
he passes along, tell him what he touches.'' In 1965, historian
Samuel Eliot Morison wrote that Sumner was ``one of those
fortunately rare and rarely fortunate persons who are not only
thick-skinned themselves but assume that everyone else is.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
