<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BOY'S LIFE LOST, AND TOO FEW CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN MCNAMARA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He is no more than a collection of body parts _ a torso, a
thigh, a shoulder, a groin. Each piece of Eric Dawood is isolated
from the whole in the color photographs that are mounted on poster
board and exhibited on an easel in Courtroom 304.
</P>
<P>
   Circles of broken blood vessels mark the spots where the punches
landed. Strips of flayed skin hint at the sting of an electrical
cord. Blotches of red and purple flesh define the points of impact
where a heavy shoe smashed into the abdomen of a 6-year-old boy,
the places where Eric Dawood's intestines ruptured and his ribs
shattered.
</P>
<P>
   Three years after this child's broken body was lowered into a
grave, Juan E. Cruz is on trial in Suffolk Superior Court in Boston
for murder. Melissa Dawood, Juan's girlfriend and Eric's mother,
testified last week that she witnessed an assault that dragged on
for days but that she failed to intervene to save her son's life.
</P>
<P>
   In the time-honored tradition of criminal defendants, Cruz
contends she, not he, inflicted the fatal blows in the apartment
they shared on Quincy Street. A jury will determine criminal
responsibility; it's left to the rest of us to consider our own.
</P>
<P>
   In a week when political discourse has been dominated by the
governor's promise to cut the income tax and the mayor's commitment
to subsidize a baseball park, the murder of Eric Dawood barely
registered.
</P>
<P>
   There are no British au pairs or beauty pageant princesses to
elevate this case of fatal child abuse to a level of political
interest. There is only a dead boy, born impoverished to a mother
whose four other children had been taken away by the Department of
Social Services because of her chronic neglect, a mother whose
choice in men culminated in Cruz, a man with a history of drug
dealing and a prison term for armed bank robbery.
</P>
<P>
   The story is so familiar we assume we can fill in the blanks,
piece together the puzzle that was Eric Dawood's life with our
preconceptions about social dysfunction, substance abuse, and the
welfare state.
</P>
<P>
   But what easy answers can explain the ``exquisite pain'' and
``the profound suffering'' that a 40-pound kindergartner must have
endured on those awful days in January 1996 when, Dr. Eli Newberger
testified Tuesday, ``massive force'' must have been used against
the recumbent, naked body of Eric Dawood to produce his fatal
injuries?
</P>
<P>
   In a study issued this week, Columbia University's Center on
Addiction and Substance Abuse reported that the number of abused or
neglected children has more than doubled, from 1.4 million in 1986
to more than 3 million in 1997. Joseph A. Califano Jr., the
center's director and a former US secretary of Health, Education
and Welfare, noted that at a time of economic boom we are devoting
fewer and fewer resources to children most at risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this nation,'' he said, ``we take better care of condors
than of children.''
</P>
<P>
   It is no better in Massachusetts. In the last decade the state
has enacted a dozen laws to protect vulnerable children. We now
license foster homes, require more training of foster parents, and
limit to six the number of children permitted in a single foster
home. But still, six children in foster care died last year; 10
died the year before.
</P>
<P>
   And those numbers do not include children like Eric Dawood, dead
despite their family's supervision by the state's child protection
agency.
</P>
<P>
   At the State House this week, the no-longer-acting governor made
much of the state's robust economy, vowing to spend $1.2 billion in
the next three years to roll back the state's income tax rate from
5.95 to 5 percent. It is not a proposal that will distinguish his
tenure in the corner office.
</P>
<P>
   For almost a decade, the Department of Social Services has been
the last priority of the Weld-Cellucci administration. As caretaker
governor for 17 months, Cellucci continued his predecessor's
policies of benign neglect. He is faced with an opportunity to do
the right thing with a budget surplus this year that the
Massachusetts Taxpayers Association estimates will fall anywhere
between $300 million and $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   Spend it on our children.
</P>
<P>
   At the courthouse this week, jurors examined the autopsy
photographs of a little boy's torso, his thigh, his shoulder, his
groin. They took notes on the shape of his bruises, on the
discoloration of his skin. As if, in reassembling the pieces of the
puzzle that was once a child, they could make Eric Dawood whole
again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Eileen McNamara is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 1330EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
