<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CANNED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPECIAL RECIPE IS A SECRET BETWEEN YOU AND YOUR CAN OPENER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DEBORAH P. JACOBS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The vocabulary of fine dining experiences is varied and varying.
As trend follows trend and experts enthuse over different cuisines,
those of us observing from our kitchens pick up such words as
``fennel'' and ``focaccia.'' Almost without trying, we've learned
to rattle off terms like ``Cajun'' and ``fusion'' and
``reduction,'' and sometimes even back them up with their edible
incarnations. It's hard to remember when ``sun-dried tomato,''
``cilantro,'' and ``celeriac'' weren't part of the home cook's
everyday parlance.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely, however, do the words ``canned goods'' find their way
into the discourse. Compared with the elegance and occasional
mystery of such relative newcomers to the grocery store as mesclun
and portobellos, the contents of the tin or aluminum can might seem
passe, a relic of the colorless cooking of the '50s.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone uses canned goods, of course _ they just don't brag
about it. Usually they don't think beyond adding a can of chicken
broth for soup or building a pasta sauce with 28 ounces of peeled
tomatoes. But there are more imaginative ways to employ the humble
bean and sardine and their other canned relations. Many canned
goods have evolved to fit modern dietary and nutritional concerns,
coming in low-sodium and low-fat versions, while some _ such as
beans _ are virtually the equivalent of foods cooked from scratch.
Their convenience, versatility, and low cost are undeniable assets.
For a fraction of the cost of a pound of fresh fish, for example, a
can of tuna can be dressed up into a savory, satisfying sauce for
pasta. With the savvy addition of chili sauce or curry paste, red
kidney beans combine with bulgur for a quick vegetarian dish. Here,
then, a few recipes that no one _ not even someone who can
pronounce ``frisee'' _ would guess rely on a can opener.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
PASTA WITH TUNA-MINT SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Mary Taylor Simeti's recipe for pasta with
swordfish, in ``Pomp and Sustenance'' (Knopf, 1989).
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 large, very ripe tomatoes, peeled and chopped (or 1 cup
canned)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped parsley mixed with 1 tablespoon dried mint
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 can (6 ounces) tuna
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup water (liquid drained from tuna can be used)
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound pasta
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces mozzarella, diced
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Saute the whole garlic cloves in the olive oil until they are
pale golden. Add the tomatoes, all but a few tablespoons of the
parsley-mint mixture, and salt and pepper, and simmer for 5
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the garlic, then add the tuna and the water. Simmer for
about 15 to 20 minutes over a low flame.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, cook the pasta in abundant salted water, drain
it well, and put it in a large serving dish. Add the tuna sauce and
the mozzarella, mixing well so that the mozzarella melts in the
heat of the pasta. Garnish with parsley-mint mixture and serve
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 2.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
FISH WITH ARTICHOKES
</P>
<P>
   A sublimely tangy, easy-to-prepare dish. Adapted from Marcella
Hazan's ``More Classic Italian Cooking'' (Knopf, 1978).
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 pounds firm white fish (such as cod, scrod, or pollock)
</P>
<P>
   1 can (1 pound) artichokes in brine, drained and halved
(quartered if large)
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried or 1 to 2 teaspoons fresh rosemary
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 425 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In a baking dish large enough to hold the fish and artichokes,
mix together the lemon juice, oil, rosemary, salt, and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the fish into 3 or 4 chunks and place in the baking dish,
turning to coat well with the sauce. Push the fish to one side
while you stir the artichoke hearts into the sauce to coat them
well, then spread out the fish on the bottom of the dish and
arrange the artichokes over and around it. Bake, uncovered, till
the fish is done, about 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 3 to 4.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
SCALLOPED CLAMS
</P>
<P>
   From James Beard's ``New Fish Cookery'' (Little, Brown, 1976).
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cracker crumbs
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Paprika
</P>
<P>
   Cayenne
</P>
<P>
   Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 (6 1/2-ounce) cans minced clams
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons finely minced onion
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons finely minced parsley
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup cream
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter and mix it with the bread and cracker crumbs.
Add the salt and pepper to taste and a dash each of paprika,
cayenne, and Worcestershire. Set aside 1/3 cup of this mixture for
the top of the casserole.
</P>
<P>
   Add the rest of the mixture to the clams, onion, and parsley.
Pour into a well-buttered baking dish or 4 ramekins and top with
the remaining crumb mixture. Dot with additional butter and pour
the cream all over. Bake in a 375-degree oven for 20 to 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
BARBECUED BEANS AND BULGUR
</P>
<P>
   This savory one-pot dish can accommodate many personal tastes
and ingredients. Throw in any vegetables (such as cabbage) or
leftovers you have on hand.
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup chopped yellow onion
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped green pepper (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup medium-fine bulgur, uncooked
</P>
<P>
   2 cups liquid (water or tomato juice or both combined)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup bottled barbecue or chili sauce, or 1 to 2 tablespoons
curry paste, to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 can (16 to 19 ounces) dark red kidney beans, drained and
rinsed
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Parsley or cilantro, for garnish (optional)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a deep lidded skillet, heat the olive oil over medium heat.
Add the onion and green pepper, if using, and saute until the
vegetables are soft. (If you like, turn up the heat so the
vegetables get browned on the edges.) Stir in the bulgur and mix
well to coat with the oil and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Add the water or tomato juice, then stir in the barbecue sauce
or curry paste. Cover the pan, turn down the heat, and simmer until
the bulgur is tender, 15 to 20 minutes. Stir in the beans, then
taste and adjust the seasoning. Add a bit more liquid if the
mixture seems too dry.
</P>
<P>
   Cover and simmer till the beans are hot. Garnish with parsley or
cilantro, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
BEET AND CORIANDER PUREE
</P>
<P>
   This beautiful magenta puree is a perfect accompaniment for
roasted meat or poultry. Adapted from ``The New Basics Cookbook,''
by Julee Rosso and Sheila Lukins (Workman, 1989).
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds canned beets
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup diced onions
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground coriander
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cut the beets into 1-inch cubes.
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter in a large saucepan over low heat. Add the
onions, cover, and cook for 20 minutes. Then add the beets,
vinegar, sugar, coriander, and salt. Stir well and simmer,
uncovered, stirring frequently, for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the beet mixture, in batches, to a food processor and
process until very well mixed with no chunks of beet remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Return the puree to a saucepan and stir well over low heat until
heated through. (Or transfer to an ovenproof serving dish, cover
with aluminum foil, and heat in a preheated 350-degree oven until
steaming hot, for 25 minutes.)
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
SMOKED FISH PATE
</P>
<P>
   If you don't use the toasted almond garnish, try serving this
with sesame seed crackers.
</P>
<P>
   1 can (3 1/2 ounces) kippered snacks, drained, or 1 can (4 1/4
ounces) sardines, drained
</P>
<P>
   4 to 5 ounces cream cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon cream or milk
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 teaspoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 tablespoons minced onion or scallion
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Liquid smoke to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon toasted almonds (optional), for garnish
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With a fork, mash the kippers or sardines in a bowl until fairly
smooth. Add the cream cheese and mash together with the fish until
smooth, thinning as necessary with the cream or milk and the lemon
juice to get a spreadable consistency. Add the minced onion, a
small pinch of salt, and, if necessary, 1 or 2 drops of liquid
smoke. (Kippers are already smoked, so if you use them you may not
need to add any liquid smoke.) Mix together thoroughly and taste
for seasoning. (Add more liquid smoke very carefully; it is a very
powerful flavoring agent.) When the mixture is seasoned as you
like, mound in a small bowl. Sprinkle with optional toasted almonds
and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 1 cup.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
