<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NINETIES NOMENCLATURE, LOVE SCIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are a country drawn irresistibly toward the art of
trend-making, toward braiding together a few of the very many
strands, toward identifying new cultural thrusts and counterthrusts
that signify. Are we afraid our world, so fragmented, so
fast-paced, so stranger-than-fiction, will spin out of control? Are
we unable to deal with a deluge of the unique, the one-of-a-kind,
the purely original? It's lots of fun, of course, gathering up bits
of evidence of the national mood from TV and the movies and the
news, to piece together a corner of the ever-growing puzzle. But
trendifying is also satisfying on a much deeper level, as it feeds
a great hunger for a semblance of order amid all the electronically
enhanced chaos.
</P>
<P>
   And so the race for the definitive name for the Nineties is on,
as this curious 10-year story draws to a close. In the coming
months, expect reams of very smart trendifying, a bunch of clever
phrases, and a massive effort to be objective about a decade that
is still very much upon us. The February Vanity Fair begins the
festivities, with an impressive run at the Nineties in a long
article by David Kamp called ``The Tabloid Decade.'' Kamp says
that, just as previous decades had their crystallizing events (for
the '50s it was the House Un-American Activities hearings, for the
'60s it was J.F.K.'s assassination, for the '70s it was Nixon's
resignation, for the '80s it was the economic boom), the '90s will
find its moment in the O.J. Simpson trial, ``a prolonged Hollywood
Babylon spectacle that confirmed the prevailing national interest
in sex, death, celebrity, and televised car chases.''
</P>
<P>
   Kamp's Tabloid Decade has its official start in the 1991
porn-theater arrest of Pee-wee Herman, which got much more
attention than it ever deserved. Behind the fraudulent parental
concern about the fall of a children's icon, there was
``countrywide mirth at his humiliation,'' Kamp writes, a mirth that
next found its target in the Clarence Thomas hearings, which
presaged the Starr report ``in their public airing of humiliating
details.'' And then parade began, with Amy Fisher and Joey
Buttafuoco, Lorena and John Wayne Bobbitt, Tonya Harding and Jeff
Gillooly, Woody and Mia, the Menendez brothers, Heidi Fleiss,
Gennifer Flowers, Michael Jackson's child accuser . . . America
began its open love of ``going where the stink is,'' as Matt Drudge
puts it, a love that culminated seven years after Pee-wee Herman
with Ken Starr's document dump.
</P>
<P>
   Kamp pulls a lot of information together nicely, looking at the
minitrends within the miditrend (maxitrend should probably be saved
up for millennial guesswork), and talking to some well-chosen
observers, including director John Waters, whose movies ride on a
sort of tabloid joyousness. Waters points out that real tabloids
like the National Enquirer (``we hate you because you're famous''),
the Star (``we hate you because you're on TV''), and the Globe
(``we hate you because you're famous and have sex'') are losing out
in the Tabloid Decade. ``My sense is that they hate the Monica
story, because they've been robbed of it. They feel gyped. It
should be theirs, and it's everyone's.''
</P>
<P>
   Kamp is also responsible for the least interesting piece in VF,
the cover story on the forthcoming ``Star Wars'' sequel, which
bears the cumbersome title ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom
Menace.'' Just as Kamp is naming the decade before it's over, he is
turning the next chapter in George Lucas' sci-fi series into a
classic before it's even finished. The reason for the story is that
Lucas has let VF into his shroud of secrecy, for a few promotional
interviews, a bland photo spread by Annie Leibovitz, and an
exclusive preview of the text that will appear at the beginning of
the film, which begins ``A long time ago in a galaxy far, far away
. . . '' But there's not much here, beyond the hype.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I was struck by the coverlines on February's Life magazine,
which read ``The Science of Love: What researchers now know about
how we fall in love and why we stay in love.'' Now here I thought
love was marvelous and mysterious, but it turns out we are driven
to mate, marry, and remain monogamous thanks to ``a complex mix of
naturally occurring chemicals and hormones _ cupid's elixers, if
you will.'' (Do we have any choice?) The whole attraction thing
comes down to a pretty little cocktail made up of dopamine and
norepinephrine and phenylethylamine, and this potion brings on ``a
slight buzz'' like ``a very low dose of amphetamines,'' as well as
``almost irrational feelings.'' That means that within the next 10
years, according to one professor, we'll be able to treat marital
unbliss easily and painlessly, with ``brain chemical nasal sprays
to enhance love between a couple.'' Hey, wasn't that popular back
in the '70s?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
