<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1317 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-13 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE WAS NEVER GONE, BUT THE BARD IS BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He's everywhere. Up there on the silver screen, double-clutching
with Gwyneth Paltrow. He's got a play running over at the
Huntington Theatre, and another one at what a friend of mine
uncharitably calls the American Repertory Museum of Avant-Garde
Theater. I heard him on a radio show the other day. Not The Man
himself, but His representative here on earth, Yale professor
Harold Bloom.
</P>
<P>
   BBC listeners recently voted him the man of the millennium,
edging out tough competitors like Isaac Newton and Charles Darwin.
According to the search engine Yahoo!, he's got 15,323 web pages to
his credit. (Compare with 1,336 for ``Mamet, David.'') At this very
moment, Mongolia's minister of culture is commissioning a CD-ROM of
one of his plays.
</P>
<P>
   We speak, of course, of William Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   All you clever English majors who fantasize about writing the
next ``There's Something About Mary'' or ``South Park'' episode _
maybe it's time to ``banish hence these abject lowly dreams''
(``The Taming of the Shrew'') and aim a little higher. Writing for
the gronk culture is fine, if you want a nice car or to make a
little headway in the singles scene.
</P>
<P>
   But if you'd like to have a reputation that endures for four
centuries, you might adopt a style ``by spirits taught to write /
above a mortal pitch'' (Sonnet 86). In his book, ``Shakespeare: The
Invention of the Human,'' dewlapped acolyte Bloom makes a
persuasive argument for his subject's near-divinity. Shakespeare is
``a mortal god,'' quoth Bloom. ``Some authors are indeed dead, but
not William Shakespeare.''
</P>
<P>
   So, how fares Shakespeare in ``the flinty ribs of our
contemptuous city'' (``King John'')? Pretty well. I launched my
personal Shakespeare safari last week at the ART's production of
``The Merchant of Venice,'' which I did not expect to enjoy. So I
was disappointed, in a good way. The production was fine, edgy, and
excusably incoherent. Bloom himself waxes incoherent on
``Merchant'' in his book, but he's correct when he writes: ``The
Holocaust made and makes `The Merchant of Venice' unplayable, at
least in what appear to be its own terms.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Merchant'' was written as a comedy, but of course the travails
and ``trial'' of Shylock, powerfully rendered by Will LeBow in this
version, don't evoke any humor these days. The play ends with a
comic act disentangling two pairs of entangled lovers, but after
Shylock has been offered a choice between death and a forced
conversion to Christianity, the audience really doesn't feel like
laughing any more.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Midsummer Night's Dream'' at the Huntington reaches for less
and comes up with more. Much ink has been shed praising the
MacArthur-certified genius director Mary Zimmerman; her real genius
in this production of ``Dream'' is staying out of the way. Not a
bad idea, in a play Bloom deems ``flawless.'' The set is perfect,
and this ``Dream'' has the best-directed ending of any Shakespeare
play I've seen, which may say more about my theatergoing habits
than about Ms. Z's directorial acumen.
</P>
<P>
   Lastly, but not leastly, I took in Joseph Fiennes's over-the-top
performance in the movie ``Shakespeare in Love.'' It's a great role
in a great movie that will bring the Bard home to a larger audience
than a barrel full of Yale profs. Bloom has dumped all over
``Love,'' and trashes most recent popularizations of Shakespeare,
whether it be Kenneth Branagh's ``Hamlet,'' ``Henry IV,'' or ``Much
Ado About Nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   But for once the self-styled Bardolator is wrong. ``The purest
spring is not so free from mud,'' Shakespeare reminds us in ``Henry
VI,'' Part 2. Some impurities have curative properties, as
Bardophiles like Branagh and the writers of ``Love,'' Marc Norman
and Tom Stoppard, demonstrate while running Shakespeare through
their well-tempered typewriters.
</P>
<P>
   Will I wax so lyrical when the planned film version of ``A
Midsummer Night's Dream'' comes out, starring Kevin Kline as Bottom
(maybe), Michelle Pfeiffer as Titania (groan), and Calista
Flockhart (red alert!) as Helena? ``Opinion's but a fool,'' He
writes in Pericles. Maybe Flockhart &AMP; Co. will prove to be such
stuff as dreams are made on.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
