r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-JORDAN-HNS &LR;      01-13 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JORDAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHAEL JORDAN LEAVES BIG SHOES TO FILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Michael Jordan's re-retirement has forced us to
examine our attitude toward one of America's most prevalent
contemporary pastimes _ slapping his best highlights into a single
reel, backed by music you would throw your radio out the window to
avoid hearing ever again.
</P>
<P>
   The miserable pop tunes melded onto his incandescent moments
have brought all right-thinking people to their knees since the
news of his departure broke. He left us with memories for a
lifetime, and we responded with a jukebox full of slop that
wouldn't make the cut on Jock Jams XVIII.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well. He leaves the NBA to its own inadequate devices, and
he leaves our ears the same way.
</P>
<P>
   He did the right thing for him, of course. A glorified
half-season, his own agent routed by the forces of David Stern, his
favorite coach (Phil Jackson) gone and his least favorite executive
(Jerry Krause) still sitting in place, and above all, the prospect
of winning a cheapened championship to go with the six full-sized
ones he already has ... frankly, what's in it for him to stay?
</P>
<P>
   Ahh, but what of the rest of us? Much has been made that he does
not leave behind a logical inheritor to his crown the way Magic
Johnson and Larry Bird left theirs to him, or Julius Erving to
them. What has not been discussed is what the rest of us do about
his absence.
</P>
<P>
   There is much to be done, of course. First, we will have to
feign interest in the NBA while we endure the wholesale remaking of
the 29 rosters (well, the 28 that aren't the Bulls; they are, as we
all know, headed for Warriorville at top speed).
</P>
<P>
   We will have to pretend that 61 percent of a season is the same
as a full season, that we won't know who is on what team until the
playoffs start, and that we will still be interested when the
Finals end at the same time as baseball's All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   That, though, is the easy part. Whatever it is that Jordan has
done all these years, it has nothing to do with us, and we all
understand that.
</P>
<P>
   Here, though, is where the sledding gets difficult.
</P>
<P>
   We have to find new heroes upon whom to spread our post-Jordan
worship, and there really is nobody worthy of it.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal hasn't been to a Finals since 1995, and more
viscerally, his teams' records in the last series they have played
is an absurd 1-19. Thus, we remember him mostly as a guy who
couldn't win the big one, even when the big one has just been an
opening-round series.
</P>
<P>
   Hakeem Olajuwon is the best of a tiny group of non-Jordanians
who have rings in this decade, but he will turn 36 before the
season begins. The other big names the league sold with such
alacrity in this decade are also on the back nine, career-wise _
Charles Barkley (35), Joe Dumars (34), Patrick Ewing (36), Karl
Malone (35), Reggie Miller (33), Gary Payton (30), Scottie Pippen
(33), Glen Rice (31), Mitch Richmond (33), David Robinson (33),
Dennis Rodman (37) and John Stockton (36).
</P>
<P>
   Their replacements _ well, there won't be any, because the
league's big thinkers have determined that they set their own
financial trap by promoting the players above the teams, and while
this benefited Jordan, it also elevated lots of pretenders and even
non-contenders. Shoe companies have scaled seriously back on their
endorsers, and the owners, having won the lockout, are sure to want
to win the peace as well.
</P>
<P>
   We have to decide if it's worth the bother to punish the teams
by not attending the games or watching them on television. Oh, a
few of us operate on the lofty principle of a dollar lost for a
dollar wasted, but even baseball in its darkest times lost only
about 10 percent of its paying customers. Jordan's loss will mean
50 fewer sellouts this year (out of 725 games), and 82 thereafter
(out of 1,189), but crowds have always responded more to their own
teams' successes than another team's marquee. After all, Jordan at
his best could only be in one building at a time.
</P>
<P>
   We have to decide if we can see redemption in the Golden State
Warriors the day after Latrell Sprewell is traded.
</P>
<P>
   We have to decide if we can live with the spectre of Ahmad
Rashad wandering aimlessly with nobody to talk to.
</P>
<P>
   We have to decide if we will spend that extra $170 on a pair of
Air Potapenkos.
</P>
<P>
   We have to decide, more comprehensively, who will sell us our
next phone card, our next cereal box, our next pair of underwear,
our next ... well, our next everything. We have to decide who will
lead us into the next century when politics, commerce, wrestling,
Mark McGwire, animated television shows, the Internet and Sandra
Bullock tear-jerkers fail us.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, we have no answers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
