<HEADER>
A1320 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UTILITIES-Y2K-BOS &LR;      01-13 1600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UTILITIES-Y2K-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A Y2K DEADLINE NEARS, UTILITIES LACK GUARANTEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At a breakfast meeting in a Boston financial district office
tower recently, Boston Edison manager Jim Ashkar displayed a slide
spelling out the question on the minds of 100 business executives
who had turned out to hear him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will the lights stay on 1/1/2000?'' the slide read.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will they?'' called somebody from the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the $64,000 question!'' replied Ashkar, who
coordinates Boston Edison's efforts to ensure that the local power
grid will operate through the millennial date change _ and the
resulting computer software problem popularly known as the Y2K bug.
</P>
<P>
   The work by Boston Edison and other utilities to resolve the
issue is vital. As the North American Electric Reliability Council
warned last September: ``The electric industry's year 2000
preparedness is crucial to the operation of virtually every aspect
of the economies of the United States and Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   But like other utilities, Edison and its parent, BEC Energy,
will not promise that their distribution network will function 356
days from now. Rather, Edison will say that it is ``very optimistic
that there will be only minimal problems'' come Jan. 1, 2000. In a
$32 million race to prepare for the new century, 70 Edison
employees are reviewing codes for 300 computer systems. Their work
is scheduled to be completed by mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   That date, however, is later than the utility industry's
self-imposed June 30 deadline. Northeast Utilities, which serves
Western Massachusetts and most of Connecticut and New Hampshire,
says it also expects to miss the deadline, by a month.
</P>
<P>
   The US Department of Energy is keeping an eye on the deadline as
it tracks the industry's ability to keep the computerized switching
equipment at the heart of the nation's electric grid on line.
Edison and Northeast say their lagging schedules should not be
cause for concern.
</P>
<P>
   Yet they also say prudent customers should expect at least minor
problems or blackouts on New Year's Day 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who assumes it will be perfection has a
misperception,'' Ashkar said at his presentation, hosted Tuesday by
the World Affairs Council.
</P>
<P>
   Ashkar said Edison and other utilities cannot offer more
specific guidance, in part because of concerns over legal
liability. But given the stakes, that stance vexes public
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our members need to come away with some assurances and not
just fluffy statements,'' said Leon Jacobs, who heads the Y2K task
force of the National Association of Regulatory Utility
Commissioners in Washington. Dennis DiMarzio, chief operating
officer for the city of Boston, plans to meet soon with BEC Energy
and other providers of basic services to hear their specific Y2K
plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking for more assurance,'' DiMarzio said.
</P>
<P>
   It is an awkward position for monopoly power distributors,
unaccustomed to strict deadlines. Never mind the millennium, says
David Jacobs of Eastern Utility Associates in Boston, ``We can
never guarantee that the lights are even going to stay on
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Y2K bug'' refers to the difficulties expected to affect
computers programmed to use only the last two digits of the year to
keep track of dates. Whereas ``99'' indicates the current year,
some computers might interpret next year's ``00'' as 1900, and
malfunction or shut down.
</P>
<P>
   As the power industry's reliability council notes, much of the
country's basic infrastructure will be vulnerable unless systems
are reprogrammed. For New England's bulk-power distribution system,
those improvements are being monitored by New England's so-called
Indepedent System Operator, based in Holyoke. James Sinclair, the
group's spokesman, said the organization is comfortable with the
progress of its member utilities.
</P>
<P>
   So will the lights stay on?
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll have to ask the membership,'' Sinclair said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the wrong question,'' said Howard Gruenspecht, a staff
member of the US Energy Department who helps oversee the industry's
Y2K response. More immediately, he says, regulators must make sure
utilities that miss the June 30 target can explain why. Some spot
checks of lagging utilities are likely later this year, Gruenspecht
indicated.
</P>
<P>
   After receiving reports from the country's largest electric
utilities last September, the Energy Department said the industry
``needs to accelerate its efforts.'' An updated survey was released
Jan. 11, a report Gruenspecht said showed utilities are making
``reasonable'' progress.
</P>
<P>
   Handicapping the outlook for specific utility companies is
difficult. Trade groups will not discuss the progress of individual
members; except for Northeast Utilities, most local power
distributors declined to release filings describing their
performance. Boston Edison spokesman Michael Monahan said that
``There's so much minute detail it could be confusing.''
</P>
<P>
   But the reports were available from the state's Department of
Telecommunications and Energy, which had also requested them from
the utilities.
</P>
<P>
   These filings suggest a mixed picture of the progress being made
by New England's three largest utilities compared to other electric
distributors in the Northeast and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   In some areas, New England's big three _ Northeast Utilities,
Boston Edison, and New England Electric System _ seem to be ahead.
For example, by June 1, 1998, Boston Edison had finished counting
which systems it needed to check for Y2K problems, and had assessed
problems to see how they might be fixed, several months ahead of
most other utilities in the region.
</P>
<P>
   But the three lag in other categories. New England Electric and
Northeast do not plan to finish assessing their systems until Jan.
31 and March 31, 1999, respectively, well behind the average
completion date of Nov. 19, 1998 for the region.
</P>
<P>
   Also, as of Nov. 25, 1998, none of the three had finished
planning for special Y2K conditions like temporarily taking
malfunctioning power plants off line or recovering from blackouts.
Other utilities had already developed such plans and a few had
tested them.
</P>
<P>
   New England's biggest utilities do expect to have contingency
plans in place by the summer. Out of 40 systems it calls
``mission-critical,'' Boston Edison says only one system will not
be ready by the June 30 deadline. The company blames the delay on a
Montreal software maker that is providing upgrades to the system,
used to track the performance of Edison's energy distribution
network.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think it's that significant,'' Edison's Ashkar said.
</P>
<P>
   But software consultants working on Y2K remediation say they
worry about missed deadlines because final tests can take longer
than expected. ``You need as much time to test as possible,'' said
Tony Wray, a sales manager in New England for Nexus Unlimited Inc.,
a systems integrator in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Should remediation efforts fail, other power executives are
developing backup measures to reduce the strain on the region's
electric grid.
</P>
<P>
   One plan would put extra power plants into standby mode by Dec.
31. Another more costly option would be to suspend the exchange of
power between neighboring regions of the country, keeping each
region's grid independent and, theoretically, less vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Elacqua, a New York Power Pool engineer in Albany, N.Y.,
who oversees regional Y2K readiness, said he expects such efforts
will keep the bulk-power distribution system functioning. Besides,
he said, demand for electricity during a January holiday typically
runs at just 40 percent of New England's summertime peak of around
20,500 megawatts. That means plenty of power plants should be
available to provide backup generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm optimistic, but I'm also realistic,'' Elacqua said. ``I'm
not going to say that there won't be any local blackouts. But there
won't be any bulk-power system blackouts. We won't lose the whole
Eastern Seaboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be isolated pockets throughout the US,'' Elacqua
added. ``But hopefully it's nothing to worry about. We're
experienced at putting things back together once something
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, most of the lights will stay on?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' said Janet Gail Besser, chairwoman of the Massachusetts
Department of Telecommunications and Energy. The agency began
surveying the utility companies it oversees last spring, and Besser
says she is satisfied with their preparations.
</P>
<P>
   Typical is one filing from Northeast Utilities: ``NU has found
nothing that cannot be repaired or replaced and be made Year 2000
ready in time,'' it states. Northeast is also the region's largest
nuclear utility, owning most of the Millstone facility in
Waterford, Conn., and the Seabrook, N.H., reactor.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Northeast has spent about $11 million of the $30 million
it expects to pay to review codes and fix weaknesses. Spokeswoman
Debra Durbin said the company is not concerned that its scheduled
completion date lags the rest of the industry because the company's
July 31 goal was set several years ago. She said the date still
reflects ``prudent planning.''
</P>
<P>
   Durbin also mentioned a Northeast site on the World Wide Web
discussing questions the utility often gets, such as: Should
households buy portable electric generators? The company responds
that ``The leader of our Millennium Program team has no plans to
buy a generator for his home, because he does not expect to need
one.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is, however, an individual choice,'' the company adds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 1339EST &QL; 
