<HEADER>
A1323 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTERS-GOFISH-ART-     01-13 1512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-GOFISH-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING FISH ON LINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ross Paasche had bought books and sold stocks over the Internet.
But as a professional seafood buyer, he doubted many others in his
own industry were of a mind to go on line.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with holidays coming up and demand certain to build for
calamari, a seasonal tradition in many homes, he took a chance.
Before going home one evening last fall he posted a request for the
squid delicacy on an Internet site, GoFish.
</P>
<P>
   The number of calls he got the next day ``threw me for a loop,''
said Paasche, who works for Agar Supply Co. in Boston, a wholesale
distributor of meat, poultry and seafood. And one was a winner,
from a supplier known for quality who offered ``such a bargain,
such high quality, that I saved enough money to go up a level in
quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Shedding its low-tech reputation, New England's fisheries
industry is putting electronic commerce and information technology
to work to speed a globalization demanded by shortages in haddock,
cod, and other popular species.
</P>
<P>
   Deals once cut in a smoke-filled Boston Fish Pier auction room
are being replaced by a system that can deliver market quotes via
the Internet to laptop and desktop computers from Boston to Seattle
and Bangkok and Buenos Aires, many of those quotes open for all to
see, and at the blink-of-an-eye speeds these perishable products
require.
</P>
<P>
   When combined with better refrigeration and low-cost bulk air
transport, e-commerce is being seen as the next step in assuring
consumers of uniform quality, at prices that reflect actual market
conditions and reduce middleman charges.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, information technology is being seen as a
framework for specialty trading, by which consumers who will settle
for nothing else can track down hard-to-find products _ Alaska king
crab, for example, rarely sold in the East _ that they can buy on
line directly from the fisherman who caught it.
</P>
<P>
   The key word in all this is ``information,'' says Neal Workman,
43, who heads SeaFax Inc., the Portland, Maine, company that
introduced GoFish to the World Wide Web last August.
</P>
<P>
   ``The invisible hand of business is imperfect information,''
Workman said, paraphrasing Adam Smith. And the fish industry, in
which most of the work done is at sea or in distant ports, suffers
imperfect information more than most others.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet starts to make things a little tighter _ it
starts to take some of the shell game out of the business,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big story here,'' says Ken Coons, director of the
Boston-based New England Fisheries Development Association, ``is
the global flow of fish'' that has resulted from shortages of
traditional fish species in North America and Europe. Once unknown
species such as orange roughy, from the South Pacific, are now
common on American tables, and high-speed technology has arrived
just in time to deal with this trading revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Coons describes electronic trading of fish as ``an on-line
version of the farmer's market,'' and sees even greater use when _
as biologists hope _ limits imposed on fishermen to rebuild
depleted stocks have done their job and catches are so big that
``it will take a lot of mechanisms to get it all to market.''
</P>
<P>
   Workman learned the value of information as a commodity when he
set out, in 1987, as a bill collector who chased down delinquent
restaurant owners on behalf of Maine lobstermen.
</P>
<P>
   He soon found others also wanted to know who was not paying on
time, and began publishing semimonthly reports detailing what he
knew. Later, he began sending his reports by fax, a move that was
welcomed in a world where the value of time is measured in spoiled
inventories _ and which led to the name SeaFax.
</P>
<P>
   Workman moved into preparing full-scale credit reports for
clients on a case-by-case basis _ and then began compiling this
information into printed directories and, later, CD-ROM disks, also
sold by annual subscription. By last year, closely held SeaFax had
revenues of more than $5 million annually, Workman said, and the
Internet was his next frontier
</P>
<P>
   Others had beat SeaFax onto the Net. One, Fish Info Service
(www.sea-world.com), based in Tokyo, distributes price and market
data from around the world. The National Marine Fisheries Service
statistical service (www.st.nmfs.gov), does the same for US ports.
Another site is sponsored by the National Fisheries Institute
(www.seafoodlink.com). And the Massachusetts Department of Food and
Agriculture last month launched a site to serve state seafood
exporters (www.massfish.org).
</P>
<P>
   But GoFish (www.seafax.com/gofish) offered the first global
matchmaker service in which vetting of buyers by SeaFax's
credit-rating staff offered sellers some confidence they'd be paid.
</P>
<P>
   GoFish's other advantage, both Workman and his subscribers say,
is its ability to introduce buyers and sellers who might otherwise
have never met. ``All of a sudden you get six or seven different
offerings, and you can select from among them,'' said James R.
Faro, president of Sea Star Seafood Corp. of Holliston, which
processes and distributes seafood under its own Beacon Light brand
and various private labels in 38 states.
</P>
<P>
   John Fiorillo, editor of Seafood Business, a monthly trade
magazine, said it's too early to tell the ultimate impact of
on-line buying and selling, but pointed out that only a decade ago
the industry's open-outcry auction system was mostly replaced by
the fax machine. ``Nobody was sure what that (technology) would do,
and now it is the way they do business all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The 350 responses Workman got when he offered free access to
GoFish for 90 days convinced him that an on-line service could
succeed. Since that trial ended Nov. 1, he said, 95 dealers have
signed up for subscriptions that cost between $2,000 and $6,000 a
year, depending on use. Workman said GoFish had $150,000 in
revenues last year, and expects to reach $500,000 in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   GoFish so far doesn't give users an option to quote prices.
``They see what's there and then they get off line and haggle over
the price on the phone,'' Workman said.
</P>
<P>
   But a transactional site, where traders could do one-on-one
deals without picking up a telephone, is the second phase of his
business plan. A third phase would be an on-line auction, ``at a
certain time of day, that GoFish would conduct.'' Both would be
promoted as a package that would include SeaFax credit reports.
Sellers would pay GoFish a 1 percent commission, justified by the
credit information they get and time saved by selling on line,
Workman said. GoFish would keep half and rebate the rest to buyers
as an inducement to keep coming back.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-five percent of GoFish's traffic now is in frozen
seafood, which distributors thaw and cut into fillets for sale to
restaurants or grocery stores. Both upscale restaurants and big
supermarket chains are holding back, Workman said, although about
25 smaller grocery chains are members. He thinks larger
organizations will be convinced only if they can see prices on
line, something that sellers so far are reluctant to do.
</P>
<P>
   Workman thinks the US fresh fish market, composed of hundreds of
small boats that sell either through small distributors or at
localized auctions, is too volatile to make much use of GoFish.
</P>
<P>
   But John Sackton, a fisheries consultant in Lexington whose
market research company, Seafood Datasearch, developed the
Massachusetts Department of Food and Agriculture's Web site, sees
the fresh-fish marketplace differently.
</P>
<P>
   Sackton says the Internet's wide-open access is a good forum for
directly matching specialty sellers with buyers who want unusual
species or premium quality. ``On the West Coast there are now some
boats branding their catch by the boat's name, and restaurants are
featuring it that way,'' he said. ``The Internet has potential to
open up this kind of specialty niche.''
</P>
<P>
   Sackton says GoFish faces problems in an industry in which
buyer-seller relationships are important. ``Nobody likes to be
lumped in as just a commodity buyer or seller,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Paasche, at Agar Supply, said using GoFish helped him
establish new relationships. One was with the New Jersey supplier
who submitted the winning response in his first search for 5,000
pounds of frozen calimari.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was the quality good, Paasche said, but the money he
saved paid for his first-year subscription to GoFish. Since then
Paasche has both bought and sold haddock, shrimp, scallops, and
calamari, via GoFish, expanding his Rolodex along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think of GoFish as a dating service,'' Paasche said. ``I
won't turn back now. This thing exposes you to people all across
the country and around the world. Sometimes in this business you
get blinders on and don't see things you should.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 1340EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1327 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-STOCKS-ART-B     01-13 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-STOCKS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET STOCKS DEFYING WALL STREET'S GRAVITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON AND ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just eight days ago, shares in Internet-site developer CMGI Inc.
sold for $57.25 apiece; Tuesday they traded for more than twice
that, $130.75. Yahoo Inc., the search-engine company, has seen its
stock nearly double over the same period, to $402. And
Broadcast.com, an Internet radio and television provider, ended the
session at $223 a share, nearly three times what the stock fetched
at the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The surge in these and other Internet stocks during the past two
months has spawned a buying frenzy the likes of which Wall Street
has not seen in a generation. Even though investors stopped to
catch their breath Tuesday, prompting a selloff of some Internet
issues, the mania for stocks of companies connected to cyberspace
shows little sign of abating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's buying them,'' said Ken Pasternak, president of
the brokerage firm Knight Securities in Jersey City, N.J., which
handles stock orders for Internet trading companies. Everybody, he
said, ``down to taxicab drivers and housewives'' and anyone else
who has ``felt the empowerment of the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   By traditional standards, hardly any of the Internet companies
deserve to trade at the atmospheric prices they have reached in
recent days. Even some of the best-known Internet companies, like
on-line bookseller Amazon.com, do not expect to turn a profit any
time soon. Yet thanks to the run-up of its stock, the 4-year-old
company has a market value of $26 billion, six times the combined
value of its two main competitors, traditional booksellers Borders
Group Inc. and Barnes &AMP; Noble Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Lack of profits hardly seems to matter to Internet investors,
many of them trading on-line from home computers, far from the
advice of stock brokers. In their world, fundamental yardsticks
like revenue estimates take a back seat to the drive for quick
gains _ and the belief that companies making their mark in the
rapidly growing area of electronic commerce have bright futures,
whatever their bottom lines say now.
</P>
<P>
   So who has the nerve to buy the inflated shares of these
companies?
</P>
<P>
   James Payne for one. A computer science major at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, the 20-year-old Payne said
that so far this month he has made $10,000 trading in Internet
stocks and other issues. Each morning, he boots up a personal
computer loaded with software that tracks the Nasdaq stock
exchange, where most Internet issues are traded.
</P>
<P>
   Payne said he has ``absolutely not'' mastered the art of valuing
stocks over the long term and has no intention of doing so. But he
said he has grown adept at anticipating increases in individual
stocks at specific moments. ``This is about seeing a pattern and
stepping in front of it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Payne also has made mistakes. The worst, he said, came last
month when he went to the gym while still holding shares of
Amazon.com. By the time he returned, he had lost $1,000. Now he
tries to sell all his shares at the end of each two-hour trading
session before heading to his part-time job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know when this (Internet) bubble is going to burst,
and I don't want to be there when it does,'' Payne said.
</P>
<P>
   A friend, MIT senior Jeremy Roy, who also dabbles as a so-called
day trader, said he lost $500 last week when he stepped away from
his screen to use the restroom, but he has made it back and still
hopes to make big profits in technology trades.
</P>
<P>
   Investors like Payne and Roy have been stoking Internet stocks
since early December, analysts say, helping push the
technology-heavy Nasdaq market index to record levels this month.
According to BankBoston Corp., the combined total value of all
Internet stocks rose to about $275 billion on Monday _ or twice of
the size of Hong Kong's stock market.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq has gained 63 percent since a recent low last Oct. 8
of 1419.12. The index, after breaking another record Monday, lost
63.84 points Tuesday, closing at 2320.75, amid concerns that the
sector had become overheated. But even with Tuesday's declines,
many Internet stocks remain well above their levels of a few months
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Investment professionals appear hard pressed to make sense of it
all. Many believe the unbridled enthusiasm for Internet stocks may
screech to a halt and are avoiding them.
</P>
<P>
   Ned Riley, BankBoston Corp.'s chief investment officer, said he
is not buying any Internet stocks for the bank's $27 billion
portfolio. Riley said the stocks ``may be the greatest illusion
we've seen since David Copperfield made a 737 disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than buy these stocks, Riley said, the bank holds the
shares of profitable companies that make an identifiable product
related to the World Wide Web, such as Cisco Systems, Lucent
Technologies Inc. and Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   But Rob Adler, president of CCBN.com in Boston, an on-line
financial data provider, thinks the Internet the boom is far from
over. He offers a simple explanation for why it will continue:
supply and demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The supply (of Internet stocks) is grossly limited compared to
their place in the world,'' Adler said. ``The fact is that
everybody thinks that the Internet is going to open up a lot of new
electronic channels of commerce, and they want to have a piece of
that in their portfolios.''
</P>
<P>
   Others say the boom is being driven by the rise of small
investors, who are taking advantage of on-line trading services,
and are not shy about speculating in stocks they think are on the
way up.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we see particularly here in New York . . . is that
there's a huge amount of day trading going on, both by the firms
that specialize in that, as well as Internet-savvy people trading
the Internet stocks on the Internet from home,'' said Robert
Yevich, president of the Tucker Anthony Inc. retail brokerage firm.
</P>
<P>
   Amateur investment crazes have long been a staple of the
markets. Most recently, biotechnology stocks became notoriously
volatile as small investors tried to match their limited knowledge
of complex scientific developments against the chance of making
large profits.
</P>
<P>
   But never before the Internet run-up have lightning-fast
decisions by amateur investors had such an impact on industry
leaders, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet bubble is as big (a bubble) as I've ever seen,''
said Robert M. Whelan, a partner in the Boston office of Volpe
Brown Whelan &AMP; Co., an investment banking firm specializing in
technology companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
