<SLUG> BC-FUNDS-QUARTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETURNS SHINE, BUT DON'T SCRATCH TOO HARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mutual fund investors who stood steady during Wall Street's
fizzles last year can reward themselves with champagne. A sparkling
fourth-quarter rally in the stock market rescued fund shareholders
from a downturn that threatened to end
</P>
<P>
   the long party for investors.
</P>
<P>
   But to many financial professionals, the gains in 1998 _ tamer
than in recent years _ masked a market more troubled than it
appeared. The danger, some say, is that fund investors will equate
last year's respectable to spectacular returns, depending on where
you invested, with an unstoppable market.
</P>
<P>
   The average US diversified stock fund rose a solid 14.5 percent
in 1998, according to Lipper Inc., the fund tracking firm in
Summit, N.J. While below 1997's 24.6 rise and more in line with
recent historical averages, the bounty nonetheless reflected a
record fourth straight year of double-digit returns on Wall Street.
After slipping 15 percent in the third quarter, when the Dow
swooned, stock funds gained a stunning 22 percent over the last
three months.
</P>
<P>
   The surge made 1998 a cork-popper for funds invested in stocks
of the biggest companies as well as in technology and
telecommunications firms. It was also a banner year for funds that
mirror the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index, the market's most common
gauge. In fact, most domestic stock funds had double digit gains
last year, except for funds invested in small to mid-size
companies, natural resources, and real estate.
</P>
<P>
   But disquieting questions abound. One problem is that most of
the gains came from relatively few stocks, mainly the biggest
blue-chips and tech shares; most equity funds had to load up on
those issues to do well. That skewing could prove troubling to the
$5.4 trillion fund industry in a protracted downturn.
</P>
<P>
   S&AMP;P 500 index funds, including the well-known Vanguard 500,
mirrored their benchmark to bring home a stunning 28 percent return
in 1998, better than 9 out of 10 actively managed funds and any
other category of diversified stock fund. Propelled by a mania for
Internet-related shares, tech funds gained 51 percent.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, funds focused on small companies continued their
miserable streak, losing 0.3 percent despite big fourth-quarter
strides. Those invested in value, or relatively inexpensive, stocks
fell far behind funds in growth stocks, or companies with expanding
sales and profits.
</P>
<P>
   In another measure of the unevenness of 1998's gains, the Dow
Jones industrial average of 30 blue chip stocks, usually not far
behind the S&AMP;P 500, rose only 16.1 percent. And barely half the
issues in the S&AMP;P 500 gained last year, despite the barometer's
overall increase of 26.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Combined with the changes that have swept the nation's fund
industry this decade, the performance differences point to a
volatile cocktail for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   One key issue facing investors this year, according to Tony
Kreisel, manager of Putnam Investment's Growth &AMP; Income II fund, is
that the domestic stock market is now driven less by solid
fundamentals, such as strong earnings growth, and more by scads of
money waiting to be invested at any cost. Most cash idling in
conservative money market funds, including $11 billion yanked out
of stock funds in August as the market sank, is simply looking for
a new stock fund _ evidence that investors believe they will not be
disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   But ``the lesson of last year is that the market is not what it
seems to be,'' Kreisel said, noting the performance chasms dividing
individual fund categories. The differences, he said, revealed how
fewer issues accounted for the market's gains _ not a portent of a
smooth road ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Many strategists predict a decent but unspectacular year for
stocks but lower corporate earnings as well _ an inconsistency that
begs the question of how shares can rise when company profits
don't. Already many stocks are at record-high valuations, despite
dimmer earnings outlooks. Yet those points may be lost on fund
investors, who by and large will look at 1998's returns and pile
into popular equity funds to seek more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers will always buy past performance,'' said Bruce R.
Specka, president of the New England Funds, pointing out what
investors often forget: that the past does not predict the future.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the intoxication with the Internet _ a phenomenon
known to some as ``tulip.com'', a reference to the 17th century
Dutch mania for speculating in flowers that ended in a crash.
Already Internet fever among money managers and ordinary investors
alike shows some signs of infecting other shares, such as expensive
Microsoft and Intel _ a situation some observers say could presage
a blow-out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market has aspects of what some people would call a
bubble,'' said Prof. Richard E. Sylla, an economic historian at New
York University. ``It reminds me a bit of the late 1920s'' _ when
stocks were the wave of the future and faith in new technology was
high.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would advise an investor to build up cash, since stocks are
richly valued and subject to a downturn,'' Sylla said.
</P>
<P>
   Such a move would constitute a major shift for Americans. At the
beginning of 1990, 25 percent of all households owned around $1
trillion in mutual funds, with stock funds accounting for a quarter
of the total. Now the fund-owning population is nearly 40 percent,
and equity funds make up 56 percent of the industry's assets,
according to the Investment Company Institute, a trade group.
</P>
<P>
   Although investors grew a shade more conservative in 1998,
putting more net new cash into money market funds than stock funds,
they are back in force this January, traditionally a strong buying
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're seeing now is the belief that the market's
momentum continues,'' said Lipper chairman A. Michael Lipper. He
cautioned later: ``People are extrapolating present trends into the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, each of the past four years has seen investment
professionals ask a trenchant question: Can the returns continue?
</P>
<P>
   Each of those years has ended with good gains. And portfolio
managers who answered the question with a no and sought returns
outside the most popular US stocks often came up empty handed.
</P>
<P>
   For answers, some investors may look increasingly at European
stock funds, which gained 22.6 percent last year on optimism about
monetary integration. Others may point to international funds;
those avoiding emerging markets and most Asian countries, all
disasters last year, rose 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Still others may search outside the stock market. Seemingly
boring US Treasury bond funds, deemed a good bet in times of stock
market turmoil, rose 9.7 percent in 1998 _ a hefty gain that may be
telling investors a thing or two about temperance for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investment strategists take the view that the stock market is
the only game in town,'' Lipper said. ``Statistically, of course,
they're right, except when they're wrong. And as last year proved,
when they're wrong, they're wrong big.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
