<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-TV-JORDAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO AIR TIME HURTS NBC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The truth is in the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Without Michael Jordan, NBC's ratings dropped 22 percent for NBA
games.
</P>
<P>
   Without Michael Jordan, ratings on WGN, the Chicago affiliate
that carried Bulls games, dropped 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Without Michael Jordan, the NBA championship series lost as many
as 8 million viewers nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Higher ratings mean higher advertising revenue, and Jordan was
money, television money. Word of his retirement has caused industry
executives to wonder privately just how TV, particularly NBC, plans
to restore the value to a league already deflated by a protracted
lockout.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, NBC was downplaying the retirement of His Airness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have all been fortunate to have been part of one of the
most magical rides in sports history,'' NBC Sports chairman Dick
Ebersol said in a statement. ``Michael Jordan's retirement is not
completely unexpected, but we've been here before . . . While no
single player can replace the transcendent athlete of this decade,
it will be exciting to see what players and what `super teams' step
into the spotlight for the fans to embrace in the next era.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol is half-right. Back when NBC acquired rights to the NBA
in 1990, critics said the league didn't have a superstar to market
because Magic Johnson and Larry Bird were on the way out.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Michael.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the numbers from last year. The Bulls were on NBC eight
times during the regular season and pulled an average rating of
6.5, or about 5.7 million households. NBC showed 17 other games
during the season, which were seen by an average of 3.7 million
households. The lowest-rated Bulls game bettered the highest-rated
non-Bulls game.
</P>
<P>
   The real test was the playoffs. When Jordan was playing baseball
in the mid '90s, the NBA Finals between Houston and New York
averaged a 12.4 rating. The next year's championship series,
between Houston and Orlando, averaged a 13.9.
</P>
<P>
   When Jordan played in the Finals, he was able to attract
crossover fans and increase the ratings. In 1992 against Portland,
the rating was 14.2. It was 17.9 against Phoenix in 1993, 16.7 in
1996 against Seattle, and 16.8 in 1997 against Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Bulls-Jazz was no different. Game 5 alone pulled a
20.6 rating.
</P>
<P>
   NBC and Turner paid about $2.6 billion last year to televise NBA
games, and though the cable networks felt more pain during the
lockout, NBC will take the ultimate hit with the loss of Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   One reason Jordan became such an attraction was that NBC gave
his team prime-time exposure. The Sunday games that started at 5:30
p.m. usually featured the Bulls. With no Jordan, and probably no
Scottie Pippen and Dennis Rodman, the Bulls will be no better than
any other team undergoing a rebuilding year. Or decade.
</P>
<P>
   The question, then, is what team can replace the Bulls as a
prime time player. Never mind what player can replace Jordan; that
person probably hasn't been born yet.
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol remain hopeful that something or somebody will emerge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to reintroduce the new generation of stars in the
NBA,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 1344EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
