<HEADER>
A1333 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BULLS-COMMENT-BOS     01-13 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BULLS-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLS HAVE DECISIONS TO MAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We got a glimpse of the new Chicago Bulls last June 14, in Game
6 of the NBA Finals. Scottie Pippen was on the bench with a bad
back and Michael Jordan was getting a rare breather. The team
looked horrible.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Bulls know that their rebuilding can begin. Right now,
the team has only four players under contract for this season _ Ron
Harper, Toni Kukoc, Keith Booth, and Randy Brown. They had a
league-high 10 free agents, which are now down to nine. Some of
those _ Pippen, Luc Longley, Steve Kerr, maybe even Dennis Rodman _
may stay on the Bulls' cap while the team decides which way to go.
</P>
<P>
   There are two alternatives. The Bulls can use their cap money to
lure someone such as Antonio McDyess, whom vice president Jerry
Krause loves, then try to re-sign Pippen and Longley and win with
that group. The other is to take a big hit this season and get
ready for the summer, when they'd get a good draft pick and have
oodles of money to spend on a list of free agents that may include
Antoine Walker, Ray Allen, Shareef Abdur-Rahim, Glen Rice, and
Stephon Marbury.
</P>
<P>
   Krause said Monday that he would try to rebuild around Pippen
should Jordan retire. The Pippen story is an interesting one. He
has felt underpaid and, at times, underappreciated in his years in
Chicago. He has said he will never wear a Chicago uniform again,
cannot stand Krause, and seemed like a lock to go elsewhere until
the money limits were installed as part of the new Collective
Bargaining Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Would the Bulls make up for Pippen's years of lost wages and
reward him with what he wants, a five-year deal starting at $14
million? Don't count on it. Pippen is 33 and coming off back
surgery, and Chicago may feel that if it can't win without Jordan,
why spend the money on Pippen?
</P>
<P>
   No top-name free agent are likely to sign with the Bulls without
knowing that Pippen is there. McDyess, for instance, is being wooed
heavily by Houston, which also has only four players under
contract. But one of those is Hakeem Olajuwon.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was the top priority, and now the Bulls know about him.
Pippen should be the next stop, except that Chicago would lose its
cap room if it re-signed him right away. But if he did, Krause
could then try to re-sign Longley, Kerr, and others from the title
team and let it roll.
</P>
<P>
   But if Pippen goes elsewhere, or is signed by Chicago and traded
for bodies, then the Bulls go into the tank this season. Krause
will try to load up the roster with serviceable players in the
final years of their contracts or promising rookies. He will then
focus on the 1999 draft and try and rebuild through free agency.
Depending on how the roster is built, the Bulls could have $15
million-$20 million available, enough for two impact players to go
along with what should be a good draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman is a goner without Jordan. What's the point? Rodman, when
he decided to play, was valuable as the third wheel. He'll be no
more than a freak show without Jordan and Pippen and, frankly, it's
hard to see him toeing the line for Tim Floyd. Even the enormously
patient Phil Jackson struggled with Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   Longley and Kerr will have suitors and could find new homes.
Teams need centers, and Longley is one, if not a great one. The
Celtics, for instance, could offer their $1.7 million average
exception, but that likely isn't enough. And Longley might not want
to close out his career playing Pitino Ball. (Remember, though,
Longley was part of a trade, along with Pippen, that Pitino mulled
in June 1997.) Phoenix might take a pass at Longley, and it has
money to spend. Detroit is said to be eyeing Kerr for the same role
he had in Chicago, only this time to benefit Grant Hill.
</P>
<P>
   No one is shedding any tears for Krause. The Bulls of the '90s
are a lot like the Celtics of the '80s; there's is no shortage of
teams eager for payback when Chicago stops by. That's the price of
building a consistent winner, and Krause can only hope that he now
also has built a tradition in Chicago, although that may be hard
without Jordan in this day and age.
</P>
<P>
   Krause, of course, is the man who said organizations, not
players, win championships. His organization is about to be put to
the test, and many feel Krause has been salivating for the
opportunity to show that it can be done without No. 23. He drafted
Pippen, Horace Grant, and Kukoc, signed key free agents and made
big deals (Bill Cartwright for Charles Oakley) to get Chicago
rolling. But he always had Jordan. He doesn't have that luxury
anymore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 1345EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1336 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-13 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENEFITS AND BEYOND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Melissa Brisman gave birth to twins 10 months ago, the
Boston lawyer received a basket of toys, bibs, gift certificates,
and a baby book _ courtesy of her employer, Goodwin, Procter &AMP; Hoar
LLP.
</P>
<P>
   Brisman, a tax associate, did not have to go too far for
parenting advice or help, either. The reason? Her employer supplied
it as part of a benefits program for new moms and dads.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't all. Goodwin Procter offers an emergency child-care
center to employees such as Brisman, part-time hours and flexible
scheduling, and a savings program that allows employees to set
aside up to $5,000 in pretax wages for child care.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a Parent Exchange Program the law firm developed with
the help of Workplace Connections Inc., a Waltham, Mass. workplace
benefits firm, offers everything from home visits and counseling
for new parents to help choosing day-care centers or nannies who
best meet their needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``These services offer great peace of mind,'' said Brisman, 27,
who splits the responsibility for caring for her fraternal twins
with her husband, a medical resident at a Boston area hospital.
</P>
<P>
   As the demand for skilled employees increases, companies are
doing all they can to hold on to top talent, and that includes
offering more flexibility, more benefits and, yes, more gifts and
perks.
</P>
<P>
   ``In industries that are experiencing the effects of the tight
labor market, they are realizing that after salary, the other thing
that employees look at is the benefits package,'' said Grace
Pantano, president of Workplace Connections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Benefits can actually set companies apart in terms of
potential employees' choice of jobs,'' Pantano continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``People do have lives outside of work, and that is definitely
being recognized by employers more and more.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Kelly, director of human resources at Goodwin Procter,
agreed. ``Our Parents Exchange benefits are geared to keeping
people,'' she said. ``We believe they will help to alleviate some
of the push and pull, the struggle of work and family demands.''
</P>
<P>
   And few understand that struggle better than those who are
trying to balance family or personal needs with the goal of making
partner at a big, competitive law firm.
</P>
<P>
   Nancer Ballard, a senior partner at Goodwin Procter, discovered
as much when she began studying why some young women and men are
abandoning their legal careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The myth of the culture is you work hard and deny yourself,''
Ballard said in an interview with The Boston Globe last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``But a huge number of women are leaving law, including women
who have gotten past the glass ceiling, and even men are saying
that the prize might not be what they thought it would be,'' she
added.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, severe labor shortages in some industries and
increased competition for top-flight professionals and skilled
employees are forcing employers to pay closer attention.
</P>
<P>
   When Working Mother magazine began compiling information for its
1998 report on the best companies for mothers to work at, it
pinpointed a slew of exceptional benefits designed to help workers
cope with life's many stresses _ and keep them on the job.
</P>
<P>
   Some examples:
</P>
<P>
   Dayton Hudson, Hewlett-Packard, and Sequent Computer Systems all
offer subsidized public schools at worksites, says Working Mother.
Procter &AMP; Gamble offers insurance coverage for organ transplants,
and Glaxo Wellcome and Motorola give employees cash to help buy
houses or take courses.
</P>
<P>
   At Eli Lilly, profit-sharing added an extra 18 percent to
workers' salaries in 1997. And new parents at IBM Corp. can take
advantage of a three-year unpaid leave program. At Merck, by
contrast, new moms get six months off with a guaranteed return to
their previous job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies compete vigorously to get on the Working Mother 100
list because they want to be known as the most family-friendly
employer in their industry or profession,'' wrote Milton Moskowitz,
who compiled the magazine's list of top firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recruitment needs drive this competition and, of course,
companies want to retain the talented people who already enrich
their ranks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At Goodwin Procter, portions of the Parent Exchange Program are
purchased by the law firm and offered to employees free of charge.
</P>
<P>
   A simple list of available child-care centers that meet a
client's specifications costs the law firm $25, for example. The
cost of the entire package? About $1,000, according to Kelly,
Goodwin Procter's human resources director.
</P>
<P>
   Brisman says the program has sent her research information about
twins, parenting, and baby-proofing her home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The program will help you find day care and, if you want,''
she said, ``a counselor will actually go to the day-care center
with you, or they will give you the list and you can go alone.''
</P>
<P>
   (Questions, comments? Contact Diane Lewis at work(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
