<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1338 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOM-DRAG-RACER-ART-BO     01-13 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOM-DRAG-RACER-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HER LIFE IS AN EXCITING DRAG 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Jessica Willard was standing in front of the 30-foot
jet dragster race car called the ``Queen of Diamonds'' at the World
of Wheels show in Boston recently, flashing her smile and
describing the car to anyone who walked by.
</P>
<P>
   But don't for a minute assume that that the 5-foot-3-inch
Willard was serving as window dressing at the show.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Willard is the driver of that needle-nosed,
10,000-horsepower machine, the one who puts on a fire suit and
helmet and gets strapped into the seat to power the race car to
faster than 300 miles per hour in about five seconds. When she hits
the brakes, two parachutes behind the car inflate to help it stop.
</P>
<P>
   And even though the owners of the car did want to find a woman
driver for their team to liven up the marketing, Willard brought
not only her gender, but lots of experience, with her.
</P>
<P>
   Her father made sure of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made me take apart a motor and put it back together before
I drove a real race car,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Willard, a 22-year-old from Leominster, virtually grew up at
racetracks as her mother and father traveled to compete in races
every weekend. So it was only natural that when she got her
driver's license, she wanted do more than just tool around the
roads of central Massachusetts, where rotaries during rush hour
offer the most excitement.
</P>
<P>
   So she borrowed her mother's Chevy Lumina to start drag racing
in the trophy class _ for regular street cars _ and raced at 76
miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   She kept racing in that class, and moved up to an '84 Corvette
that she revved up to 85 miles an hour and in 1994 won the National
Hot Rod Association Sears/Craftsman Scholarship award and was named
the New England Dragway Rookie of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   By 1997 _ after Willard had taken apart that motor _ she had
moved up a class and was racing a Super Comp Baretta at speeds of
160 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   She went on the the University of New Hampshire, from which she
graduated last May with a degree in psychology, but her eye was
still on the racetrack. And the eyes of the Hanna race Team were on
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``We heard about her from someone at Lebanon Valley Dragway, and
met with her and her family and made the decision to add her to our
team,'' said Al Hanna, who with his son, Richard, run the Hanna
Motorsports team.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did she have the drive and ability, he said, but being
female was a plus. ``She adds to the marketability.'' In fact,
after naming the car ``Queen of Diamonds,'' he got a sponsorship
with the Bicycle Division of the US Playing Card Company.
</P>
<P>
   Hanna said that he and his son, both jet dragster racers, took
about a year to train Willard in the car that was like none other
she had driven.
</P>
<P>
   They took a rear-view mirror so she could see the smoke and
flames that flared out up to 30-feet long on the back of the car
when she fired up the engine. The flames are to both put on a show
and to burn off fuel and make the car lighter to race.
</P>
<P>
   The engine _ the kind in an F-5 fighter jet _ is so loud that
when Willard fired up the race car last Friday morning outside the
Bayside Expo, the state police thought an explosion had gone off
and came rushing to the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Hanna spent the next months training Willard how to hold onto
the butterfly-steering wheel and release the throttle when the
starting lights signal it's time to go. And he had some terse words
of advice for Willard in case her two main parachutes and the
reserve one didn't go off to make her brake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to her, `just drive your blank off, and if you don't
have parachutes, just keep driving.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I did it I went 60 feet and shut the car off,''
Willard said. ``It was so fast, before I even knew I was scared, I
was at that point.''
</P>
<P>
   But she obviously got in again and again, and is now the only
active female jet dragster racer in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Willard got her jet car license last June, and has since chalked
up several track records. Perhaps the most exceptional one was when
she covered the quarter-mile track at Englishtown (N.J.) Raceway
Park in 5.08 seconds at 305 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   In August, after she had been racing only six weeks, Willard won
jet car races at the New England Dragway in Epping, N.H., and at
the Jet Car Nationals in Englishtown, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``She beats the boys, she beats them all,'' Hanna said. ``She's
beating everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Willard, who has a boyfriend (and yes, he races), said she's
been the target of both good and bad attention as a woman in a
male-dominated sport. She just shrugs it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once in a while, after I race them they won't talk to me, but
that's kind of to be expected,'' she said. ``I don't think it's
because I'm a woman, either, I just think it's because our team is
very respected.''
</P>
<P>
   And the notice she gets isn't just from other racers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a lot of marriage proposals this year, most of them
yelling from the grandstand,'' Willard said, laughing. ``A few come
up and they offer their friends' for marriage, stuff like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Willard acknowledges that she had a less-than conventional
childhood that was centered around racetracks, first to watch her
parents drive, then to race herself.
</P>
<P>
   She and her brother, Nick, would play with toy cars, or play
catch on the side.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd stop the game when my dad was racing and go watch, then
go back to our games,'' Willard said. ``We used to color Easter
eggs there, and most of my major birthdays were at the racetrack.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In high school, she said, friends wondered why she took off
every weekeend. Even though she played on the field hockey and
softball teams, she couldn't practice on Saturdays because she was
traveling to racetracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't really get it,'' Willard said. ``But they were all
thrilled for me when I won the high school race. When I came back
on Monday they announced it over the intercom to the whole school,
and everybody was really excited for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Willard, who was a senior at the time, didn't get prize money
for the win, but was given $1,000 for her school. She donated half
to the school library, and half to the automotive trade department.
</P>
<P>
   Now that she's in her racing offseason, Willard is using her
psychology degree to work with a first-grader with Attention
Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder. And she spends about two to three
hours a day in the gym learning boxing ``as a hobby.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, she has thought about taking up skydiving,
flying, and would love to go up with the Blue Angels. As for a
career, Willard said she aspires to teach, but wants to stay in
drag racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to use drag racing as a tool, to get the kids'
attention,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That shouldn't be a problem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
