<HEADER>
A1341 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNION-PAST-$ADV17-COX     01-13 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNION-PAST-$ADV17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ONE YEAR LATER, A MIXED RECORD FOR STATE OF THE UNION AGENDA
 &HT;    With UNION. For release Sunday, Jan. 17.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As President Clinton prepares a list of proposals
for his State of the Union address Tuesday, many of his goals from
a year ago have not been accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Save Social Security first'' was the most memorable phrase
from the 1998 speech. The president vowed to reserve ``every
penny'' of the expected budget surplus until the Social Security
system was made stronger.
</P>
<P>
   With the treasury collecting its first surplus in three decades,
Clinton has declared his promise to be fulfilled. However, many
budget watchers have cried foul because the president and Congress
forged a plan to use $20 billion of the surplus funds for
``emergency'' spending.
</P>
<P>
   The record on other proposals in the 1998 speech is mixed:
</P>
<P>
   FULFILLED
</P>
<P>
   _ The ``largest funding increase in history'' for the National
Institutes of Health and the National Science Foundation. Congress
agreed and added even more for health research.
</P>
<P>
   _ Increased International Monetary Fund contributions, totalling
$18 billion, to help bail out ailing foreign economies.
</P>
<P>
   _ Expanding the North Atlantic Treaty Organization to include
Hungary, Poland and the Czech Republican to the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization. The Senate easily ratified the plan.
</P>
<P>
   _ An overhaul of the Internal Revenue Service. Congress
completed and the president signed a measure, initiated by the
Republicans and later embraced by Clinton, that pledges to make the
tax collecting agency more helpful and less dictatorial.
</P>
<P>
   RECEIVED PARTIAL ACTION
</P>
<P>
   _ ``An ambitious agenda to reduce the serious threat of weapons
of mass destruction.'' In a year of tension in this area, Clinton
ordered air strikes of suspected arsenals and arms factories in
Iraq, but U.S. officials acknowledged they could not determine how
much weapons production was affected. The strikes ended the United
Nations inspections role in Iraq, at least for the foreseeable
future.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, North Korea fired a ballistic missile test over
Japan. India shocked the world, including U.S. intelligence
agencies, by exploding a nuclear bomb, and Pakistan soon followed,
despite Clinton's efforts to dissuade its leaders.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``From Belfast to Korea to the Middle East, America will
continue to stand with those who stand for peace.'' Clinton
administration efforts helped produce the Good Friday agreement to
end the sectarian violence in Northern Ireland. But Clinton's
effort to broker an interim peace accord between the Israelis and
Palestinians unraveled soon after it was signed.
</P>
<P>
   _ 100,000 new teachers to help reduce class size in primary
schools. In a last-minute budget deal with Congress last October,
the president won $1.2 billion to hire about 30,000 new teachers
starting next fall.
</P>
<P>
   _ Environmental spending increases, including ``a far-reaching
effort'' to clean up rivers, lakes and coastlines as well as reduce
fossil fuel emissions. The White House asked for $1.1 billion in
increased funding, and Congress granted $714 million in last fall's
annual budget. A Clinton plan to grant tax cuts of $6 billion over
five years for the research and development of fuel-efficient homes
and cars did not pass.
</P>
<P>
   RECEIVED NO ACTION
</P>
<P>
   _ An increase in the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   _ National standardized testing for schools. The exams for 4th
and 8th graders, first promised in 1997, have yet to be designed.
</P>
<P>
   _ Construction money to build or remodel 5,000 schools.
</P>
<P>
   _ A consumer ``bill of rights'' for health care to give patients
more control in choosing doctors and treatment provided by
insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   _ Allowing people between the ages of 55 and 65 who have lost
their private health insurance to purchase Medicare coverage.
</P>
<P>
   _ Raising cigarette taxes by $1.50 a pack to discourage teen
smoking.
</P>
<P>
   _ Major new tax cuts and new federal spending for day care.
Without the tobacco tax increase to pay for it, this plan was
dropped. However, Clinton won $200 million in new funding for
after-school activities.
</P>
<P>
   _ Campaign finance reform. This perennial request died once
again in the Republican-led Congress.
</P>
<P>
   _ Special authority to negotiate international trade pacts.
Congress rejected the measure, a mainstay of the Clinton foreign
policy.
</P>
<P>
   _ Payment of overdue debt to the United Nations. Clinton vetoed
the $900 million bill because Congress attached a measure to ban
federal aid to agencies that lobby for abortion rights in foreign
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
