<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-201YEAST-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO GET RISE OUT OF LEAVENING  
 (ART ADV: PHOTO IS BEING SENT TO NYTNS CLIENTS)  
 (ADV: WITH 201INTRO, 201YEASTTIPS, 201BREADTIPS, 201 BREAKBOOKS AND
201YEAST-RECIPES, 201REVIEW) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY WALKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Fear not, fellow and sister foodies. Follow me into
battle. Today, we tackle the Yeast Beast, one of the most
beneficial yet somehow frightening denizens of the food world.
Otherwise-good cooks tremble and turn the cookbook page at the very
word yeast. Fear not! The Yeast Beast can be yours.
</P>
<P>
   The Yeast Beast, once tamed, makes a wonderful pet. The Yeast
Beast will perform tricks at your command, make your home smell
terrific and bring you the happy glow of successful baking.
</P>
<P>
   The Yeast Beast is alive. Seriously. Yeast is a one-cell plant,
identified as a living organism by Louis Pasteur in 1857. Like a
seed that needs to be planted, watered and warmed to grow, the
Yeast Beast sits in your cupboard (or, better yet, your freezer)
waiting for you to give it something warm, wet and edible. After
it's put to work, the Yeast Beast eats sugars and gives off carbon
dioxide and ethyl alcohol, gases that expand when trapped in a
gluten network.
</P>
<P>
   Gluten is strands of protein that form when wheat flour and
water are mixed together. As dough is kneaded, gluten strands stick
together in stretchy bands, and the yeast divides, grows, eats more
sugars and gives off more bubbles that blow up the gluten. Poof.
The Yeast Beast works, and the bread rises.
</P>
<P>
   Flours contain varying amounts of protein (and gluten), which is
why bakers learn to choose certain flours for certain jobs. In
general, high-protein flours are best for products that need lots
of gluten for strength and elasticity, such as bread, cream puffs,
puff pastry, pizza and pasta. Semolina is the first choice for most
pastas.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, low-protein flours, made from wheat grown in
the South and widely used there, make great cakes, quick breads,
muffins, pancakes, gravies, pie crusts and biscuits _ all of which
need tenderness and little gluten, leavened as they are by baking
powder and baking soda. (Brand names: Swansdown and Softasilk cake
flours; Shake &AMP; Blend and Wondra Instant Flours for gravies;
bleached Southern all-purpose flours such as White Lily, Martha
White, Gladiola and Red Band for pie crusts, quick breads, muffins,
biscuits).
</P>
<P>
   In ``CookWise,'' Shirley Corriher explains that national brands
of bleached all-purpose flour have a little too much protein for
the best pie crusts and not quite enough protein for outstanding
yeast breads. However, she says, ``unbleached'' all-purpose
national brands of flour are blended to contain more protein,
enough for the Yeast Beast to work well.
</P>
<P>
   Only wheat has the ability to form lots of gluten, which is why
white flour is often combined with rye, barley and all those other
grains to make bread. The bran in whole-wheat flour, the outer
layer of the grain of wheat, is sharp enough to cut gluten strands
and thus doesn't rise as much.
</P>
<P>
   Yeast, wheat flour, water: These are the basics of bread. Now
you need . . . technique.
</P>
<P>
   You can make bread dough in a bread machine set on the dough
cycle, in a heavy-duty mixer with a dough hook, in a food processor
or by hand.
</P>
<P>
   If you have any one of those machines, use it, by all means. A
bread machine makes a superior dough, and you can pull it out of
the machine to have the joy of shaping and baking without working
up a sweat while kneading. Instruction booklets for your appliances
should give details of how to adapt recipes; there are several
excellent cookbooks to consult, too.
</P>
<P>
   When you've made dough by hand, however, you will understand all
the nuances _ and all the confusing terms. In all recipes, it's
important to read through them first before starting to cook, but
in bread recipes, it's critical.
</P>
<P>
   The recipe for French Bread in 201YEAST-RECIPES describes all
the steps in detail, with a few flourishes from the person who gave
it to us a few years ago: Nancy Johnson, who developed this recipe
at home before she opened her highly successful bakery,
BreadCrafters, in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Along with kneading the dough and giving it rest periods,
Johnson slams the dough around to develop the gluten. It works. You
can slam, or you can knead continuously. With time, you, the
successful tamer of the Yeast Beast, will develop your own tricks.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's recipe describes the sequence of kneading: fold, push,
quarter-turn. But there really is no right or wrong way to knead.
What you want to do is manipulate the dough for some minutes until
you feel it begin to change right under your hands into a silky
ball. It's then ready to rise in a greased bowl, covered with your
best kitchen towel.
</P>
<P>
   Most recipes call for two rises, starting right after kneading,
until the dough ``has doubled in size.'' How do you tell when it
has doubled? If you know the volume of your bowl, you can tell when
it's risen from the 4-quart mark to the 8-quart mark. The first
rise generally takes an hour, after which the bread is deflated to
let the air out (it's always fun to sock your fist into the middle
of the mass). The bread is then shaped and left to rise a second
time, which usually takes half the time of the first rise, around
30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The ideal conditions that your Yeast Beasts need to give off gas
and rise are in a warm, draft-free place. The kitchen towel keeps
the crust from hardening. You don't want the crust to harden until
after it's in the oven. And for this recipe, you want to make a
crisp, crackly crust.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson achieves that by misting the oven with water to make
steam and with a baking stone, which is preheated to simulate the
brick-line ovens in which artisan breads are baked. (Yes! This is
an artisan bread!) Baking stones draw out moisture from the crust
as it cooks, making it crisp.
</P>
<P>
   Stones are flat slabs, often round because they are so excellent
for pizza crust. Look for them in kitchen and department stores.
The only thing you have to watch is that they don't go from hot to
cold quickly, which might crack them. Preheat stones in a hot oven
for about 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Loaves are slashed after they have fully risen and just before
going in the oven to release interior steam that will otherwise
blow out a side or end of the loaf. Use a single-edge razor blade
or a really sharp knife and cut quickly.
</P>
<P>
   When the bread goes into the oven, the gases give one last jump
after they hit the heated air inside. This is called ``oven
spring,'' and it's the last gasp of the Yeast Beast before it dies
in the heat, having given its all. This is why your oven must be
preheated _ to promote oven spring.
</P>
<P>
   How do you tell when the bread is done? For one thing, the crust
should be really brown, not just a little brown. Recipes tell you
that a thumped loaf sounds hollow, but until you develop an ear for
that sound, or if you're tone-deaf, use an instant-read
thermometer, to measure the interior temperature of the loaf. This
French bread is done when the internal temperature is 200 degrees;
most breads are done around 190 degrees. Take the loaf out, turn it
sideways onto a cooling rack and insert the thermometer's stem into
the bottom of the loaf. If it doesn't register high enough, return
it to the oven for a few more minutes.
</P>
<P>
   As you can see from Johnson's recipe variations, you can delay,
slow down or otherwise manipulate the Yeast Beast to work on your
schedule. You can also tell that between the rest periods and the
rising of the dough, there are many times that the dough is just
sitting there, doing its thing while you do something else around
the house, such as laundry.
</P>
<P>
   All the Yeast Beast needs is a little warmth, something to eat,
gluten protein to blow up like bubble gum, and your hands or a
machine, kneading it into silky submission. The Yeast Beast can be
cranky, yes, but work with it. Practice. One bite of your first
good loaf, and the Yeast Beast is yours for life. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
