<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-201REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET'S REVIEW BAKING BASICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 ByJUDY WALKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Brief points for baking success from ``The Arizona
Republic's'' Cooking 101 series: &QL; 
- Measure accurately for baking success. You need different
measuring cups for liquids and dry ingredients. Flat-topped
measuring cups are made to be filled to the top with dry stuff.
Liquid measures are usually glass, with more space at the top to
eliminate spills, and a pour spout. &QL; 
- To measure flour, stir the flour first. Gently spoon flour into
the (flat-topped) measuring cup while held over a sheet of waxed
paper or the flour canister. Do not tap it or shake it to level the
flour. Let the flour heap up. When the flour is over the top, use
the flat side of a knife or spatula to level off the top of the
cup. &QL; 
- Preheated ovens are critical in baking. Most ovens will preheat
in 10 to 20 minutes. &QL; 
- Whole wheat is heavier than white flour. You can substitute up to
half of the flour amount in an all-white-flour recipe with
whole-wheat flour. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
