<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
I LEFT MY BALLPARK IN SAN FRANCISCO 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Someday archaeologists will dig up heaps of old
newspapers and conclude that San Francisco was a city obsessed not
with sex, not with beauty or style, not with food or restaurants,
not even with itself, but with ballparks.
</P>
<P>
   It's very odd that politically correct San Francisco is obsessed
with stadiums rather than food, sex or world peace. It's like
discovering that Dallas is a city obsessed with social justice
rather than social climbing.
</P>
<P>
   The Stadiazoic period of San Francisco began in the early 1980s
when then-Giants owner Bob Lurie said Candlestick Park was no
longer adequate and started moping for a new ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   To appease Lurie, public officials drew up plans for ballparks
all along the shore of San Francisco, shared ballparks with
Oakland, ballparks near the airport, in Santa Clara and near dumps
in Milpitas.
</P>
<P>
   At one point a plan for a floating ballpark was floated.
</P>
<P>
   The area was littered with imaginary ballparks, while
journalists built entire careers writing about them. Politicians
threw away their political capital trying to get ballparks built.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after a brilliant campaign, the voters gave the Giants
their ballpark. What a jewel it will be when it's finished, and in
such a setting, with the Bay glistening on one side and brightly
hued traffic jams on the other.
</P>
<P>
   This week, San Francisco's ballpark obsession flared up again _
about the proposed 49ers stadium and shopping mall. Yes, that's
what our mayor wants, even though a stadium-mall in San Francisco
makes as much sense as a croquet lawn-vegetarian restaurant in
Muleshoe, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The headlines sounded like medical reports from Generalissimo
Francisco Franco's bedside. Depending on which newspaper you read,
the stadium-mall was still dead, or still alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The project is moving forward in the same fashion it has for
the last two months,'' a spokesman for the 49ers told the San
Francisco Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   And Generalissimo Francisco Franco has shown just as much
movement.
</P>
<P>
   All that matters for Mayor Willie Brown is that the stadium-mall
survive on the resuscitator, or at least stay alive as an idea,
until after the next election.
</P>
<P>
   Brown has put a lot of his prestige on the line for this
ungainly concept, combining The Gap and Wet Seal with beer-sodden
fans and tailgates outside a multiplex.
</P>
<P>
   If the stadium-mall completely, certifiably dies before the
election, what will Brown have? A lot of homeless people still on
the streets, a gold dome on a poorly computerized $300 million City
Hall and a flea market on Treasure Island.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody might even dare to run against him.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the 49ers have something to do with the intensity of
the current weirdness. The hard-core fans are basically a cult,
expecting nothing less than perfection.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers are religion, sports, family and politics rolled into
one sputtered-out offense.
</P>
<P>
   Talk-radio conversations and letters to the editor about the
Niners sound like debates about how many angels can run pass
patterns on the head of a pin _ as debated by pinheads.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder San Francisco is stuck on its nonexistent
stadium-mall, even though many people in this town avoid both
stadiums and malls as if they're on the same boycott list as
Starbucks and Coors.
</P>
<P>
   I guess I'm just a typical fan, one who watches most of the
games on television and doesn't plan to do a lot of shopping after
paying a couple of hundred bucks on tickets, parking, hot dogs and
beer.
</P>
<P>
   Let them play in Candlestick, as long as they play. Who cares
about luxury boxes and getting a Super Bowl? Those are for other
people, and not the kind of people who live in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, it doesn't look like the Niners will be in a Super Bowl
for a while. Not to argue theology with you.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
