<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 14:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1395 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSUMER-FREE-PHONES-     01-13 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-FREE-PHONES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHONE CALL IS FREE, ONCE YOU'VE LISTENED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Maryland company is offering consumers free calls to anywhere
in the United States _ if the caller is willing to listen to an
advertisement first.
</P>
<P>
   The concept is similar to radio or television. Listeners don't
pay for each song or news report they hear on the radio;
advertisers do. And advertisers will foot the bill for BroadPoint
Communications of Landover, Md., to offer callers two free minutes
of long-distance service for every 10- to 15-second ad they listen
to.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to completely refresh the telecommunications
industry and at the same time launch a new medium for
advertising,'' said Perry Kamel, president of BroadPoint, which is
rolling out the service nationally with DQE Inc., a Pennsylvania
energy services company.
</P>
<P>
   Broadpoint's FreeWay service is not for someone in a hurry, but
Kamel said a test in Pittsburgh last year found that callers with a
little extra time on their hands were happy to trade it for free
long-distance minutes. More than 10,000 people signed up for the
service during the Pittsburgh test.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty advertisers have bought into the concept, including
Blockbuster Entertainment, Acura, Rolex, the Wall Street Journal
and Sports Illustrated. Relying on questionnaires that FreeWay
members are required to fill out, advertisers are guaranteed that
their ads will reach their target market. The service even allows
callers who want more information after hearing an ad to connect
directly to the advertiser.
</P>
<P>
   Kamel, who previously was head of strategy at MCI WorldCom's
mass markets division, said advertisers pay BroadPoint between 6
cents and 24 cents for delivering each message to a customer. The
rate varies depending on how closely the caller fits the
advertiser's demographic requirements and whether the caller can
connect directly to the advertiser.
</P>
<P>
   BroadPoint buys long-distance time at discounted rates from one
of the nation's top three long-distance companies. Kamel declined
to say whether his long-distance supplier was AT&AMP;T, MCI WorldCom or
Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for AT&AMP;T, which relies on the traditional
pay-per-minute long-distance model, said the firm was following
BroadPoint's venture closely. ``We are watching this segment of
calling. However, I cannot speculate as to whether we will offer a
service such as this in the future,'' said Andy Boisseau.
</P>
<P>
   The only way currently to sign up for FreeWay is to go to
www.broadpoint.com and fill out an application and demographic
survey. Enrollment is free currently, but an email address and a
touch-tone phone are required.
</P>
<P>
   Broadpoint says the demographic information will not be provided
to unrelated third parties, although it will be used to link
advertisers and callers. Demographic questions focus on age,
educational background, work status, income, hobbies and other
interests.
</P>
<P>
   Once accepted, FreeWay members receive a card with instructions
on how to make a call. Callers dial a toll-free number to hook up
with Broadpoint, punch in their home phone number plus a four-digit
PIN number and dial the number they are calling.
</P>
<P>
   The first ad comes on immediately. At its conclusion, you can
then press the phone's star button to hear another ad and receive
another two minutes of calling time, or press the pound button to
connect the long-distance call you want to make. Kamel said the
Pittsburgh test indicated the typical caller listens to about seven
ads and builds up 14 minutes of calling time.
</P>
<P>
   With some advertisers, callers can also punch zero and be
connected directly to the advertiser. After you finish talking to
the advertiser, you can press the star button again and be returned
to FreeWay.
</P>
<P>
   If a caller doesn't use all of his minutes on a call, the
minutes cannot be banked and are lost. Callers are notified that
their time is about to expire 30 seconds before the end of the
call.
</P>
<P>
   FreeWay is currently restricted to US calls only, but Kamel said
he is working on expanding the calling area to include
international calls.
</P>
<P>
   Kamel said surveys of those who joined in Pittsburgh revealed a
membership that would be very attractive to advertisers. He said
most participants had children and an average household income of
$60,000.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for BroadPoint said there were enough varied
advertisers participating in FreeWay so no one would be rejected
for membership because they failed to meet certain demographic
criteria. But BroadPoint is cautioning that membership may be
delayed if response to the national rollout is bigger than
expected.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bruce Mohl covers consumer issues for The Boston Globe. His e-mail
address is mohl(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
