<SLUG> BC-BIRD-STAGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TONGUE OF THE BIRD' SOARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Fortunately enough, for a woman who spent several
years of her life being an angel, Ellen McLaughlin never has had a
fear of flying.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, one of McLaughlin's earliest and best memories is of
her first plane trip with her parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I went up, when I was a little girl, I really
did think that I would see the edge of the world from the plane,''
the playwright and actress recalls. ``And I remember distinctly
feeling that I was finally at home in the air, being up that high
and having that omniscient view was where, to a certain extent, I'd
always been. I've always been very comfortable in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Several decades after that first celestial odyssey, McLaughlin
is again reaching for new heights.
</P>
<P>
   This week will mark the opening of the Mark Taper Forum's
production of McLaughlin's psychological-adventure drama, ``Tongue
of a Bird,'' about a female search-and-rescue pilot's hunt for an
abducted 12-year-old girl.
</P>
<P>
   Playing through Feb. 7, it features a heaven-sent cast,
including Tony Award winner Cherry Jones, last seen in Los Angeles
in ``The Heiress,'' as the intrepid aviator, Maxine. The rest of
the all-female ensemble consists of Golden Globe winner Diane
Venora as the child's strong-willed mother, venerable Tony winner
Marian Seldes as Maxine's eccentric Polish grandmother,
Emmy-nominated Sharon Lawrence (``NYPD Blue'') as a spectral
presence and newcomer Ashley Johnson as the missing child.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tongue of a Bird'' was commissioned by the Taper and developed
as part of its 1995-96 New Work Festival. It premiered at Seattle's
Intiman Theatre in September 1997 and was subsequently produced at
the Almeida Theatre in London. It will open at the Joseph Papp
Public Theater in New York City in March.
</P>
<P>
   Taper resident director Lisa Peterson, who helmed the Seattle
production, will oversee the play here as well.
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin herself already is familiar to Taper audiences as an
actress, having created the eponymous role, so to speak, in
``Angels in America,'' Tony Kushner's two-part epic of AIDS,
Reaganism and premillennial angst. She and Stephen Spinella were
the only actors to be connected with ``Angels'' from its earliest
formative readings in San Francisco all the way through its Tony
Award- and Pulitzer Prize-winning Broadway run.
</P>
<P>
   Kushner is still one of McLaughlin's close friends and, she
says, the only person she trusts to cut her writing. And ``Angels''
remains a high point of her acting career. Imagine getting paid to
dip and soar across Broadway's Walter Kerr Theatre eight times a
week!
</P>
<P>
   ``I just loved it,'' she says. ``It's hard on the back, hard on
the body, but well worth it. I was totally happy up there, 35 feet
above the stage, I was zipping around, I was having the time of my
life. Because it did conform with all those dreams that you have,
you know, those ecstatic dreams of flying.''
</P>
<P>
   Play writing, however, is for McLaughlin an occupation that can
quickly bring you down to earth. Although she has written half a
dozen plays, which have been produced at such prestigious venues as
the Actor's Gang in Los Angeles, the Vineyard Theatre off-Broadway
and at the Humana Festival at the Actors Theatre of Louisville, it
remains for her a process full of storm and stress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's your heart and your soul that's like a little raw oyster
out there,'' she says. ``And when the reviews come in, they're
reviewing something essential about you as a human being. As an
actor you've still got a lot of armor because you're saying
somebody else's words, you're in somebody else's production, you've
been directed to do things by a director, you're standing on
somebody else's set. And you're basically in somebody else's
dream.''
</P>
<P>
   The emotional rigors of play writing are magnified if the work
enters deep within the airspace of your own psyche, as it has with
``Tongue of the Bird.'' McLaughlin says she can identify with
certain aspects of Maxine, who has a perfect record of finding
missing persons and always has been able to keep her own demons at
bay by throwing herself into her work.
</P>
<P>
   But, confronted with the increasingly desperate search for the
lost child, Maxine's own unresolved past baggage surfaces with a
vengeance, and a psychological crisis ensues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess that, to a certain extent, is what I experienced a few
years ago,'' McLaughlin says, ``that, yeah, I'm good at coping, but
after a certain point you want to do more than cope. You want to
sort of know who you are and confront your demons and get on with
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you get to a certain point in your life where you want to
do more than survive. And actually you want to do more than
succeed. And I think that that's what she (Maxine) gets to, that
she sort of wants to stand in her own body. She wants to land the
plane.''
</P>
<P>
   Cherry Jones, who has known McLaughlin for many years and,
ironically, inherited the role of the angel from her in ``Angels in
America,'' says she has ``never been so scared of a role'' as she
is of Maxine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Originally I was not going to do the New York run because I
already knew I'd be doing Los Angeles, and I just didn't think I
could do it (the play) that long, simply because I find it so
disturbing,'' Jones says. ``Even though there is a catharsis at the
end, it literally comes in the 59th minute of the 11th hour, and
the rest of the time it's pretty rough going for Maxine and for all
the other characters. They're in crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   In person, McLaughlin doesn't give the impression of someone
who's ever been on intimate terms with crisis or dire self-doubt.
Calm, steady-eyed and quietly witty, the Yale-educated child of
academic parents appears to always have had both feet planted on
terra firma.
</P>
<P>
   As an ``academic brat,'' she says, she grew up in many different
places, on the campuses of Stanford and Harvard universities and,
later, American University in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up to the sound of typewriters going all night long,
the most comforting sound in the world. And nobody does it anymore!
The clickety-click (of personal computer keyboards), it just isn't
the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet her childhood was difficult. Both of McLaughlin's parents
had contracted polio during the epidemic of 1955, before she was
born. Her father began using a wheelchair, and her mother went
temporarily deaf.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother also suffered from severe mental illness for one
10-year period, during which most doctors didn't think she was ever
going to improve, although McLaughlin says her father never doubted
his wife would pull through.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd have these doctors say, `You know, you really should
settle your affairs, your wife's not getting out of here.' And he'd
say, `I think she might. I think she'll be OK.' So it was a tough
childhood. Sort of zero through six for me were pretty bad years.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what kept her grounded during childhood, McLaughlin
hesitates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I was very grounded,'' she replies. ``I had a
psychic once tell me, `You know, you're not actually in your body
almost all the time. You're sort of located behind you'.''
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin says that ``Tongue of a Bird'' initially shaped up as
a lyrical rumination about women and flying in the form of an epic
poem or perhaps a novel. Its guiding spirit was Amelia Earhart, a
figure who has always interested the playwright, ``but not in a
conventional `she's my hero' way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just feel like I know her on some level,'' she explains.
``She was really only comfortable in the air. She was a
tremendously uncomfortable being on the ground, socially.
</P>
<P>
   ``And she wasn't a natural. When you realize that she was
actually nauseated every second that she was in the air _ she was
airsick, always, and she was afraid, it wasn't like this was some
easy thing for her _ the desire for that state of being had to be
deeply passionate and compelling.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, McLaughlin ruled out writing a biographical play
about Earheart. Instead, ``Tongue of a Bird'' invokes the vanished
pilot as a kind of icon of self-sufficiency and godlike detachment.
</P>
<P>
   While she's reluctant to generalize about gender, McLaughlin
thinks there may be a fundamental difference in the way men and
women perceive flying _ and in the way male and female aviators
have expressed those feelings in literature. For men, the
experience often is characterized in territorial terms, Man vs.
Nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``And for women, I find that oftentimes it ... has to do with
entering a kind of sublimity, being empowered by an element rather
than conquering an element. It is out-of-body and the confines of
the body, the confines of identity. When you're in the air, you're
not a person who belongs to a country, a family. You're stripped,
to a certain extent, of a kind of human identity. You transcend the
body and the confines of the body. And I think for women that's
different than it is for men.''
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin describes her talent as a ``cranky'' one, making it
difficult for her to feel comfortable ``writing on demand'' for
film and television, or acting in works she doesn't care for
deeply. She once spent two days working on a soap opera and found
the experience so humiliating and depressing that ``it took me
months to recover.''
</P>
<P>
   Though she describes play writing as ``like watching your baby
walk out into traffic every night,'' she seems dedicated to
fighting her fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Writing's scary for me,'' she says for more than the second
time. ``I used to be a painter, and I would fall in love with the
blank canvas. And as soon as you put a mark on it, you're marring
it to a certain extent, you're marring the perfection of that blank
canvas.
</P>
<P>
   ``And as soon as you write the beginning of the play, you're
already marring the perfection that exists somewhere inside you.
There is a perfect play, and it will not come out of you whole.'' &QL; 
ENDIT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
