<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1434 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-WORLD-0114-CO     01-13 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-WORLD-0114-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A WORLD WEARY OF MONICAGATE WATCHES THE CLINTON TRIAL,
RELUCTANTLY
 &HT;    With IMPEACH-CLINTON-0114.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ On the streets of the Russian capital, souvenir hawkers
peddle a unique version of the matrioshka, the traditional
pear-shaped, wooden nesting doll.
</P>
<P>
   In a twist on the folk craft, this version presents Bill
Clinton's face painted on the outer layer, which opens to reveal a
Monica Lewinsky, then a Ken Starr, then a Hillary Rodham Clinton,
and a Linda Tripp.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton-Lewinsky scandal still inspires hot-selling
novelties, but is it news?
</P>
<P>
   Not big news, judging from many of the major daily newspapers
and broadcasts from Tel Aviv to Tokyo. The world's media is
choosing not to play up the opening arguments Thursday in the first
impeachment trial of an American president in more than 130 years.
</P>
<P>
   After months of saturation coverage of the Clinton saga, the
world seems weary of a bewildering process that blends modern-day
media sensationalism and obscure legal wrangling between the U.S.
House of Representatives, the Senate and the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``We follow it only because we have a responsibility to do so,''
said Yelena Ovcharenko, foreign editor of ``Komsomolskaya Pravda''
newspaper in Moscow. ``We are tired of this and we would like to
turn the page.''
</P>
<P>
   With widespread predictions that a two-thirds vote is lacking in
the Senate to remove Clinton from office, many wonder just what the
point is of the trial and worry about a lasting effect on American
foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Israelis) don't understand how Americans don't realize that
their image is being destroyed in the world,'' said Judith Elizur,
a lecturer in political science at Hebrew University in Jerusalem.
``They're worried he won't be effective in Middle East peacemaking
if he is battered by this.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet even if Clinton were to be removed from office, the Mexico
City newspaper ``Reforma'' noted, he would be replaced by Vice
President Al Gore, ``whose political opinions are very similar to
those of his boss.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, much of the world's press say only America's reputation
and morale are at stake in the current saga, with limited
implications for the globe.
</P>
<P>
   In Central America, Guatemala's ``Prensa Libre'' called the
accusations against Clinton ``serious'' but noted there was little
chance he would be forced from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The loser is U.S. society in general because its president has
stained the dignity of his office and hurt moral values across the
country,'' the paper said.
</P>
<P>
   The venerable British Broadcasting Corp. promises live coverage
of portions of the Senate trial. But even the usually avid British
tabloids have taken a break from Monicagate.
</P>
<P>
   In part, this is because the London press has been captivated by
domestic turmoil in Prime Minister Tony Blair's government that has
led to some highly public resignations and finger-pointing. And for
sleaze, the British public got all it wanted from an expose written
by the ex-wife of Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, who she accused of
all sorts of infidelities and unacceptable behavior in great
detail.
</P>
<P>
   But sex doesn't sell in Beijing. The Starr Report was banned in
China as obscene. Most accounts of Clinton's troubles in China's
government-controlled newspapers and on television stick to the
least sensational facts that will tell the story. And they usually
spell out that a majority of Americans oppose Clinton's removal
from office.
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, newspapers Wednesday carried photos of President
Clinton dancing merrily with Amanda Fernandez, the wife of an
Argentine official at a state dinner for Argentina President Carlos
Menem.
</P>
<P>
   This prompted columnist Bronwen Maddox to admire the president's
toughness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like him or not,'' Maddox wrote in the London Times. ``You
have to admit that President Clinton is amazing. Judged on
resilience, he beats all other politicians in the United States
hands down.''
</P>
<P>
   In many parts of the world, political scandals involve murder
and brutality. Thus, many people don't quite understand what all
the fuss is about over mere sex.
</P>
<P>
   In Colombia, editorials centered on the start of peace talks
designed to end a long-time civil war in that country.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican papers played up Pope John Paul II's upcoming visit to
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil is coping with deep economic problems -- highlighted by
Wednesday's resignation of the head of the central bank and
devaluation of the real -- which dominates the country's news
pages.
</P>
<P>
   Its ``O Globo'' newspaper wrote recently about Clinton --
Hillary Clinton -- in a piece discussing her possible bid for a
U.S. Senate seat and Republican Elizabeth Dole's potential pursuit
of the presidency in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Interest from the world media will most likely increase should
witnesses appear in the Senate trial or new revelations surface.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, said Yuri Levada, director of the Russian Center for
Public Opinion and Market Research, ``We have our own important
problems to worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   If the world's consumers of news have had their fill of Bill
Clinton and former White House intern Monica Lewinsky, apparently
chocolate-lovers have not.
</P>
<P>
   In Ukraine, a candy manufacturer has been deluged with orders
for its new line of ``Monica'' chocolates, a triangular-shaped
confection with raisins and nuts. The box features a cartoon
illustration of Lewinsky addressing the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   The candymaker experienced an ``avalanche'' of orders it could
not meet, according to an article in the Russian newspaper
``Sevodnya.''
</P>
<P>
   Its promotional pitch: ``Monica is now available to all.''
</P>
<P>
   (Contributing to this report were Cox Newspapers' foreign
correspondents Joseph Albright and Marcia Kunstel in Beijing;
Shelley Emling in Miami; Susan Ferriss in Mexico City; Larry Kaplow
in Jerusalem; and Bert Roughton Jr. in London).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
