   &UR; SPORTS &LR;  (``s'' code)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JORDAN RETIREMENT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BKN-JORDAN-RDP (Chicago) _ One month short of his 36th birthday,
Michael Jordan, perhaps the best-known athlete in the world today,
announces his retirement from basketball. By Mike Wise.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-JORDAN-RHODEN-COLUMN (Chicago) _ William Rhoden, at the
scene of the Jordan retirement, examines what the star's departure
means on three levels: to the the league, to Chicago and the Bulls
and to the other teams.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-JORDAN-PLAYERS (Undated) _ Sure, every player now thinks
that his team can win the league championship now that Jordan is
retiring, but the players also think the world of him, too. By
Chris Broussard.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-JORDAN-KNICKS (Purchase, N.Y.) _ Looking back at Jordan with
fond or not-so-fond memories: Patrick Ewing, the Knicks' center who
considered Jordan his friend, or Jeff Van Gundy, the Knicks' coach
who felt Jordan did not respect him. By Selena Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   HIGHSCHOOL-SPORTS-II (New York) _ Special report: Second of
three articles on the decline of school sports in New York's public
schools. By Kirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-JETS (Hempstead, N.Y.) _ After a couple of days off, the
Jets' players return to the practice field as they prepare for
Sunday's AFC Championship game in Denver. Their biggest challenge
will be stopping Terrell Davis, the Broncos' runner who gained
2,000 yards this past season. By Gerald Eskenazi.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-FALCONS (Atlanta) _ The Atlanta Falcons' defensive backs
have a huge assignment on Sunday: trying to stop the most dynamic
receiving corps and passing game in the league. By Chuck Nobles.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-BRONCOS (Denver) _ John Elway, who finally won the Super
Bowl last season and is the city's most famous athlete, might be
playing his last game on Sunday. By Joe Drape.
</P>
<P>
   HKN-RANGERS-ISLANDERS (New York) _ Islanders at Rangers, 7:30
p.m. By Joe Lapointe.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CIRCUITS ('a coded') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CIR-BORDER-WAR (Undated) _ To bolster its effort to stop
lawbreakers from entering the country and to speed along the
law-abiding citizens who sometimes wait for hours to cross the
border with a truck or car, the government is enlisting the help of
technology. By Verne G. Kopytoff.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-BORDER-WAR-PASS (Undated) _ After a transcontinental flight
to the United States, most travelers want to grab their luggage and
go to bed, not wait in line at the airport. But wait they do. But
now, by using what looks like a automated teller machine, some
travelers can be on their way in a flash. By Verne G. Kopytoff.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-BORDER-WAR-DUST (Undated) _ New technology uses some kind of
swab on travelers' suitcase handles to sense traces of drugs or
explosives. By Verne G. Kopytoff.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-EMAIL-ROMANCE (Undated) _ From courtship to kiss-off, e-mail
now plays a role for many couples in how a romance progresses and
sometimes in how it ends, although the e-mail breakup is generally
considered bad form. By Katie Hafner.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ Feature on the new Pentium III
chip, with a look at whether most users need one. By Peter H.
Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-GEEK-NOTES (Undated) _ Computer notes and news. By Matt
Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-BUG-GAME (Undated) _ If, as Frank Zappa observed, writing
about music is like dancing about architecture, then video games
about movies are like synchronized swimming about opera. By J.C.
Herz.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-THEATER-WEBSITE (Undated) _ As William Shakespeare observed
in ``As You Like It,'' all the world's a stage _ but these days it
helps to have some idea of exactly where to find the good stuff.
The American Theater Web www.americantheaterweb.com) is helping to
do just that, providing links and listings for over 1,000 theaters
across the country in one convenient place. By J.D. Biersdorfer.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-PLASMA (Undated) _ For decades, flat-panel, hang-on-the-wall
televisions have been a staple of science fiction and viewers'
fantasies. And not too long ago, the only place anyone could
actually see one was at a World Fair or geeky science expo. But now
flat-panel plasma televisions are on sale at mainstream television
retailers nationwide. They are expensive _ $10,000 or more _
finicky and fragile. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-WRITERS (Undated) _ The Web has become a virtual Schwab's
drugstore for screenwriters, offering sites where they can post
their work and hope to be discovered. By Bonnie Rothman Morris.
</P>
<P>
   W/
</P>
<P>
   CIR-WRITERS-SITES (Undated) _ Sites for screenwriters.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-SCIENCE-EDUCATION (Undated) _ Natural history and
paleontology museums are exploring new ways to use the Internet to
complement exhibits and enhance science education. The results so
far have been promising for curators and visitors. By Beth
Schachter.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-RARE-BOOKS (Undated) _ Buying rare books on line. By
Michelle Slatella.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-ART-INFO (Undated) _ Art information and the Internet. By
Judith H. Dobrzynski.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-LAPTOP-TOUCHPADS (Undated) _ All you ever wanted to know
about laptop touchpads. By James Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-COMPUTER-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Shortcuts and aliases. By J.D
Biersdorfer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOUSE AND HOME (`coded l') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FOLK-ART (Undated) _ Among the sleek seals swimming through
Christie's New York with their fur coats, thin watches, Italian
loafers and winter tans, appeared John Gordon, wrapped in a wool
scarf, wearing suede bucks and an imitation beaver-skin coat _ like
a piece of folk Americana miscatalogued in a European sale. Gordon,
72, a preeminent folk Americana dealer who retired eight years ago,
was at the auction house to observe the installation of the 1,352
lots of his own collection, an important view of an unusual field,
being offered Friday and on Tuesday. By William L. Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GRAVES-TARGET (Undated) _ Move over, Martha Stewart and Jaclyn
Smith. Michael Graves, the former poster boy of postmodernist
architecture, is coming out with a line of kitchen accessories for
Target, the discount chain. By Phil Patton.
</P>
<P>
   W/
</P>
<P>
   GRAVES-DESIGNS (Undated) _ At last, there is reason to hope that
the Whitney Museum of American Art may be casting off its
reputation for trendiness. In what may be seen, fairly or not, as a
defining moment in the early tenure of the Whitney's new director,
Maxwell Anderson, the museum has rented its premises next Tuesday
evening for the unveiling of a new line of houseware accessories
and furniture designed by the noted American architect Michael
Graves. By Herbert Muschamp.
</P>
<P>
   HAMPTON-ANTIQUES (New York) _ Like extremely rare gilt side
chairs and exceptional Louis XV what's-its, the late decorator Mark
Hampton was a fixture at the Winter Antiques Show. Hampton, who
died at 58 of non-Hodgkin's lymphoma last July, was known for his
erudition as well as an A-list of clients that included George and
Barbara Bush, Anne Bass, Carter and Susan Burden and Pamela
Harriman. He left behind his wife, Duane, two daughters, Alexa, 30,
and Kate, 27, and hundreds of watercolors. By Patricia Leigh-Brown.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-BOOKS (Undated) _ ``Have you seen them?'' asked Carole
Baron, the president and publisher of Dell Publishing and Delacorte
Press. ``They're cute.'' Indeed they are. Cute was exactly the word
that came to mind when I first set eyes on the six little books
that will, beginning in February, be distributed on supermarket
shelves, tucked inside some 40 million 12- and 24-packs of Diet
Coke. Four inches by six inches, roughly 30 pages thick, these
excerpts of forthcoming works by best-selling authors are adorable.
By Karrie Jacobs.
</P>
<P>
   LIVINGROOM-POOL (Undated) _ Andrea Urban was in the kitchen
washing dishes when she heard something strange: ``Suddenly there
was this sound of splashing in the living room,'' she said, ``and I
thought, `Somebody's floating through the house.''' Then it
clicked. It was just her husband, Glen. He had shoved off on his
inaugural swim in the lap pool. By Joseph Giovannini.
</P>
<P>
   DOG-FRIEND (Undated) _ Hemingway is not my dog. He belongs to
the people I rent from, but they don't have the time to exercise
him. He's beautiful, all white with big black liquid eyes and a big
black nose. But he's a work dog; he needs a farm to run on, a herd
of sheep to tend. I started to walk him every morning because I
felt sorry for him, and now, as soon as he hears my coffee grinder,
he starts howling. By Anne Raver.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ Pushing heat into the cold corners
of the house. By Edward R. Lipinski.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &LR;  (``e'' code)
</P>
<P>
   POPLIFE (Undated) _ Pop critics choose the best of the small
independent recordings. By Neil Strauss.
</P>
<P>
   WINKLER-PROFILE (Undated) _ Interview with Irwin Winkler,
director of ``At First Sight'' By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-TALK (Undated) _ Weekly column on the book industry. By
Martin Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   HOLDEN-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Christopher Lehmann-Haupt reviews
``Four Corners of Night,'' by Craig Holden.
</P>
