<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANK-AMERICA-MINORITIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKAMERICA CHIEF VOWS MORE LENDING IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE RAINE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The chairman of BankAmerica Corp. is pledging at
least $70 billion over the next 10 years for loans to low- or
moderate-income communities and to minorities in California, saying
that the figure is ``a floor, not a ceiling.''
</P>
<P>
   During a trip designed to smooth concerns about the recent
takeover of the San Francisco bank by NationsBank of Charlotte,
N.C., the executive also pledged $20 million in philanthropic gifts
in the state this year, a 30 percent increase over 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Hugh McColl, the chairman and chief executive of the merged
corporation, said Tuesday that decisions about Bank of America
operations in California would be made there, not in Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   ``Attempting to run an organization this large by concentrating
all authority in one place is a recipe for disaster,'' McColl told
the Commonwealth Club in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The remarks responded to California critics that managers in
Charlotte do not understand the needs of California. Critics,
including some leading public officials, also have said the new
bank is not as responsive to cultural and ethnic diversity as the
former BankAmerica was.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most difficult view I have run into has been the suspicion
from day one that we are going to do the wrong thing instead of the
right thing,'' McColl said in a question-and-answer session. ``And
the view that nothing we have done before counts.''
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank acquired the venerable San Francisco bank last year
but took the Bank of America name. The combined corporation is now
based in Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the BankAmerica president for Northern California,
Barbara Desoer, presented one of the banks' first gifts of the
year: $5 million, over five years, to the University of California
at San Francisco for development of a new campus.
</P>
<P>
   The grant is equal to the largest donation ever made by Bank of
America, a $5 million gift in 1997 to support construction of the
Walt Disney Concert Hall in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   John Gamboa, executive director of the San Francisco-based
Greenlining Institute, a nonprofit advocacy center for low-income
and minority groups, said that his and other community
organizations ``would like more investments and fewer presents''
offered by the bank.
</P>
<P>
   He has unsuccessfully pressed McColl to be specific about how
much is available for community lending in California and said
``promises do not ring true.''
</P>
<P>
   McColl said diversity was at the core of the bank's strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have said many times that our company is an inclusive
meritocracy ... It means we care about results, we believe in the
power of diversity and we help all associates fulfill their
potential without regard to race, gender, sexual orientation,
culture, religion or any other non-relevant factor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McColl met with three San Francisco supervisors who have been
critical about the lack of specificity about community lending
plans. Supervisor Michael Yaki said later he was ``pleasantly
surprised'' by the meeting and that McColl wants to work with
political and community leaders to determine the proper course for
lending.
</P>
<P>
   Yaki, who earlier characterized the bank merger as akin to ``The
Invasion of the Body Snatchers,'' said he and McColl had agreed
``the past is past.''
</P>
</TEXT>
