   &UR; BRAZIL CRISIS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-RDP (Rio De Janeiro) _ The president of Brazil's central
bank resigns, the government moves to allow a faster depreciation
of the currency, and the currency, stocks and bonds fall sharply.
By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-HISTORY (Undated) _ A look at how Brazil got to this
point. By Diana-Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-IMPACT (Undated) _ A look at what a Brazilian devaluation
means for the rest of the world. By Michael M. Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-BONDS (Undated) _ Investors flee to what they view as
safety: The long Treasury bond is up nearly 2 points. By Jonathan
Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-U.S. (Washington) _ A look at the impact of the Brazilian
economic crisis in Washington. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-FLOW (Undated) _ Which institutions have the most to lose
in Brazil? Who has the big money there? What will they do with it?
What did the banks learn from the first Latin debt crisis _ and
then from the Asian and Russian crises? By Timothy J. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-MUTFUND (Undated) _ A look at the mutual funds that
invest in Brazil and other emerging markets. By Rick Oppel.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-LATIN (Mexico City) _ A look at the impact of the Brazil
crisis across Latin America. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-EUROPE (Frankfurt) _ A look at the impact of the Brazil
crisis in Europe. By Edmund Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER FINANCIAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SEC-LIVENT (Undated) _ The Securities and Exchange Commission
accuses Livent and its ousted founders of inflating the company's
earnings and engaging in a kickback conspiracy. In filing the
securities and accounting fraud charges, the commission says the
founders, Garth Drabinsky and Myron Gottlieb, engaged in a scheme
to siphon off approximately $4.6 million for themselves by
inflating invoices paid to vendors. By Melody Petersen and Benjamin
Weiser.
</P>
<P>
   LUCENT (Undated) _ Lucent's purchase of Ascend for about $20
billion in stock, announced Wednesday morning, will have a broad
impact on the market for Internet equipment. By Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   PUSH-CONFERENCE (New York) _ Executives from several dozen
blue-chip corporations will gather in New York Thursday with
hundreds of their counterparts at minority-owned companies for the
second annual economic conference organized by the Rev. Jesse
Jackson's advocacy initiative, the Wall Street Project. By Diana J.
Henriques.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-TRIAL (Washington) _ The questioning of Franklin
Fisher, the government's final witness at the Microsoft trial, is
expected to conclude today, followed by the cross-examination of
Richard Schmalensee, Microsoft's first witness. Separately, the
Justice Department plans to introduce further deposition testimony.
By Steven Lohr and Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   APPLE-EARNINGS (San Francisco) _ Apple will report earnings and
is expected to come in at 69 cents a share. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Wall Street activity. By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   COMPANIES (Undated) _ Company news.
</P>
<P>
   KEYRATES (Undated) _ Key interest rate numbers.
</P>
<P>
   BIZGLANCE (Undated) _ Major financial stories at a glance.
</P>
