<P>
   &UR; JORDAN RETIREMENT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BKN-JORDAN-RDP (Chicago) _ One month short of his 36th birthday,
Michael Jordan, perhaps the best-known athlete in the world today,
announces his retirement from basketball. By Mike Wise.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-JORDAN-RHODEN-COLUMN (Chicago) _ William Rhoden, at the
scene of the Jordan retirement, examines what the star's departure
means on three levels: to the the league, to Chicago and the Bulls
and to the other teams.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-JORDAN-PLAYERS (Undated) _ Sure, every player now thinks
that his team can win the league championship now that Jordan is
retiring, but the players also think the world of him, too. By
Chris Broussard.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-JORDAN-KNICKS (Purchase, N.Y.) _ Looking back at Jordan with
fond or not-so-fond memories: Patrick Ewing, the Knicks' center who
considered Jordan his friend, or Jeff Van Gundy, the Knicks' coach
who felt Jordan did not respect him. By Selena Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   HIGHSCHOOL-SPORTS-II (New York) _ Special report: Second of
three articles on the decline of school sports in New York's public
schools. By Kirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-JETS (Hempstead, N.Y.) _ After a couple of days off, the
Jets' players return to the practice field as they prepare for
Sunday's AFC Championship game in Denver. Their biggest challenge
will be stopping Terrell Davis, the Broncos' runner who gained
2,000 yards this past season. By Gerald Eskenazi.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-FALCONS (Atlanta) _ The Atlanta Falcons' defensive backs
have a huge assignment on Sunday: trying to stop the most dynamic
receiving corps and passing game in the league. By Chuck Nobles.
