<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1470 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISABLED-ADDICTS14-CO     01-13 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISABLED-ADDICTS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEW GUIDELINES OFFERED FOR DISABLED ALCOHOLICS AND ADDICTS
 &HT;    600&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A national panel of experts Wednesday released a
set of guidelines designed to help disabled substance abusers
achieve recoveries like those of John de Miranda and Hector del
Valle.
</P>
<P>
   De Miranda had a seizure disorder and drank excessively. He saw
no connection between them at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when I resolved the alcohol problem, the seizure problem
was resolved as well,'' de Miranda said. ``I have been seizure-free
for 25 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Del Valle, now 34, was 17 and drunk when he crashed his car into
two other cars and a brick wall, leaving himself paralyzed from the
chest down.
</P>
<P>
   After a grueling therapy session, he and other patients would
party to ``reward'' themselves with alcohol and drugs. He heard
visitors and medical personnel whisper things like, ``If I was in
their situation, I would do it too.''
</P>
<P>
   Today he thinks, ``Perhaps that is why it was so easy to have
family, friends, nurses and home health aides hold my straw to
snort a line of cocaine again, or roll my joints _ because they
only saw what I had lost.''
</P>
<P>
   After nine months of treatment and physical rehabilitation, he
landed a job in New Jersey with the National Council on Alcoholism,
using an expensively equipped van to drive himself and his
wheelchair to public appearances at which he warned against the
consequences of drunk driving.
</P>
<P>
   His brochure read, ``Drinking and Driving can Kill or Worse!''
It had a big picture of del Valle ``as if to say living in a
wheelchair is worse than death,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drove drunk or stoned for seven years after the initial
crash,'' del Valle recalled. With the encouragement of recovering
addicts and alcoholics in Narcotics Anonymous and Alcoholics
Anonymous, he spent the last three of those seven years trying
again and again to quit.
</P>
<P>
   He was turned down twice for in-patient treatment because the
programs lacked features such as assistance with using a toilet or
getting dressed. He missed some meetings in 10-step programs
because they were held in church attics or basements that could be
reached only by narrow stairs.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was he above using his disability to excuse his relapses.
``I thought that I couldn't recover because I was a disabled
individual, and was separate from people who were recovering
without a disability,'' del Valle said.
</P>
<P>
   But eventually he learned to deal with his disability and
substance abuse at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to grieve my disability as I had to grieve my
addiction,'' he said. ``I have to wake up every morning as an
addict and as a quadriplegic. But on Aug. 23, 1989, I came back,
and by the grace of my higher power I have not used a drug or drink
since.''
</P>
<P>
   He strongly endorsed ``Treatment Improvement Protocol 29,'' the
guidelines released Wednesday by the Center for Substance Abuse
Treatment, which is part of the federal Substance Abuse and Mental
Health Services Administration (SAMHSA).
</P>
<P>
   The 156-page reference book spells out ways to cope with this
frustrating tangle of symptoms. It was developed over four years by
a panel of researchers, clinicians, substance abuse program
directors and patient advocates.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to distribution through professional and disability
associations, it can be ordered by phone at two toll-free numbers
(1-800-729-6686, or TDD for the hearing-impaired at 1-800-487-4489)
and is to be posted for online access
(http://www.samhsa.gov/csat/csat.html).
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people with disabilities use substance in response to an
injury. Others may suffer injury as a result of using alcohol and
drugs,'' said Dr. H. Westley Clark, the center's director.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is data (indicating) that between 20 and 40 percent of
individuals in treatment for substance use disorders have a
coexisting disability, whether physical, cognitive or affective,''
Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   But many disabled substance abusers aren't being treated, said
Dennis Moore, who chaired the panel. Among the deaf, for example,
one researcher tallied seven hand signs for crack cocaine. ``Yet
there was no sign for abstinence,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, ``five million people with disabilities are
in need of chemical dependency treatment,'' said Moore. He
estimated that men and women with disabilities are about twice as
likely as others to abuse alcohol or drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The protocols tell professionals treating the disabled or
substance abusers about field-tested ways to:
</P>
<P>
   _ Eliminate barriers in attitudes, communications and
architecture.
</P>
<P>
   _ Identify and end discriminatory policies.
</P>
<P>
   _ Train staff to understand and accommodate special needs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Judge whether specialized treatment or use of existing
programs would be better for an individual.
</P>
<P>
   A shorter, simpler version for non-professionals will also be
developed, SAMHSA administrator Nelba (CQ) Chavez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disabilities too often contribute to isolation, chronic pain,
low self-esteem and poverty,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But an appropriate treatment plan can not only help someone
recover, but can help them obtain full-time, part-time or volunteer
work. This opens the door for people who have been stigmatized or
shut out of mainstream life,'' Chavez said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
