</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE-HEALTH &LR;  (`a' code)
</P>
<P>
   BREAST-CANCER (Undated) _ For women with a high risk of breast
cancer, a study being published Thursday Thursday in The New
England Journal of Medicine offers hope, but at a cruel price.
Removing both breasts while they are still healthy reduces the risk
of getting breast cancer by 90 percent, and the risk of dying from
the disease by 80 to 90 percent. The new study, by researchers at
the Mayo Clinic, is regarded as the most reliable work to date on
the surgery, known as bilateral prophylactic mastectomy. The
authors of the paper, however, cautioned that the findings should
not be used to pressure women into having their breasts removed. By
Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
