<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENTS SEEKING A `FLAKY' FUTURE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Rocky Mountain News)  
 
By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ When you're 20 years old, retirement seems like a long
way off. Joining the snowbirds in South Texas or being able to golf
every day isn't a big conversation starter on campus.
</P>
<P>
   But at an age when students are likely to be telling tales of
drinking vast quantities of beer, many of them are thinking ahead
to an early retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-one percent of college students reported that they plan to
retire between 40 and 50 years of age in a online poll by the
accounting firm KPMG Peat Marwick. Another 17 percent plan to
retire between the ages of 50 and 60.
</P>
<P>
   Career counselors weren't a bit surprised to hear that.
</P>
<P>
   Many college students and recent college graduates want to stop
their traditional career early in life and devote their time to a
hobby, focus on volunteer work or start their own business.
</P>
<P>
   Students are thinking of their life as a series of careers,
rather than a climb up one career ladder until retirement, said
Cheryl Matherly, director of career services at Rice University in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   One student told her she wanted to go to medical school and work
as a physician until the age of 40. After that, she'd like to join
a group of doctors doing relief work in Guatemala until the age of
60 and finally buy some land and open an antique store.
</P>
<P>
   Many others plan to teach after ``retirement'' or start their
own businesses, said Matherly, who teaches a career and life
options course for freshmen and sophomores. When these students
talk about retirement, it's not the traditional put up your feet
and watch television all day.
</P>
<P>
   Matherly was also struck by how important money is to the
students she talks to. They recognize that they can't satisfy their
other needs _ such as volunteering full-time _ until they have
enough money to support that career change.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Holdcroft, vice president of Career Management Resources in
Dallas, a company that sets up in-house career development programs
for corporations, said she also has found that recent graduates
increasingly are interested in making financial plans to ensure
they'll have the money they need to retire early.
</P>
<P>
   That's a change. Young people didn't usually focus on financial
planning for retirement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
INTERESTING WORK SOUGHT &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While students want to earn enough to retire sooner than their
parents, they're also keen to find interesting work, Matherly said.
They don't just want to find a high-paying job that isn't
satisfying until they can earn enough to quit and do what really
interests them.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Laird Jr., a senior at Texas A&AMP;M University in College
Station, Texas, has a clear career plan: He's studying civil
engineering and plans to get a job with a company that will let him
learn everything he can about construction. By the time he's in his
30s, Laird said, he wants to start his own construction company.
</P>
<P>
   Those first years will be tough, so the 21-year-old student
figures he won't be able to retire really early. Laird figures that
retiring at the age of 60 is more like it.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Milano, partner in charge of university relations for
KPMG Peat Marwick in Montvale, N.J., said that retirement age is
more realistic.
</P>
<P>
   Milano, a certified public accountant who admitted he likes to
see mountains of data before he will proclaim a trend, speculated
that students who are planning to retire in their 40s are doing
little more than wishful thinking.
</P>
<P>
   What would you say if you're asked if you want to work until
you're 70 years of age or quit when you're 50 and do something
really neat and cool like joining an over-50 football league?
Milano asked.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
LAYOFFS MAKE IMPRESSION &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Career counselors believe, however, that the tide is turning.
Every student today has seen someone close to them get downsized _
either a parent, relative or family friend _ and they have been
deeply affected by that devastating experience, said Holdcroft.
That's convinced students they can't just rely on an employer to
provide them with a lifetime career.
</P>
<P>
   That thinking leads students to consider a much wider variety of
options, including early retirement. It also has removed the stigma
that someone who quits a traditional 9 to 5 job somehow shows a
weak work ethic.
</P>
<P>
   Our fathers couldn't retire early from a traditional job for
fear of being labeled flaky, said Matherly, but younger workers
don't have that same constraint. Now, it's cool to think about
retiring early and doing something completely different.
</P>
<P>
   That said, they'd still like to know, ``Where's the beer?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
