<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1533 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-2     01-13 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHOOSH! THE NEXT PENTIUM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (af)  
 By PETER H. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Nick built his own personal computer from scratch in 1996,
it was the fastest machine in our house. He spent his life savings
for components, including a motherboard that contained an Intel
Pentium 166 microprocessor. He was 13 years old then. Now he is 16
and in high school, with the keys to my car, and he cannot believe
he ever thought a Pentium 166 was cool.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it was cool, for about three months, until it was
upstaged first by faster versions of the Pentium chip, then by the
Pentium with MMX and then by the Pentium II, all of which came in
steadily ascending chip speeds. Today, Nick regards his ancient
computer as decidedly lame, but marginally useful and occasionally
amusing _ sort of like his parents.
</P>
<P>
   The only difference, from his perspective, anyway, is that
parents start out old and get older, while computers start fresh
and new, only to descend into decrepitude at an abnormally
accelerated pace.
</P>
<P>
   And now it is happening again. The Intel Corp. is about to
introduce the Pentium III, a new generation of microprocessor for
consumer and business computers. Or, as Intel's marketing folks
call it, the Pentium !!!, with exclamation points replacing the
Roman numerals of the old Pentium II chip.
</P>
<P>
   Or are they three daggers? They must look that way to anyone who
bought a new Pentium II computer just in time for the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the chip ought to be called the Pentium ??? because
Intel will not divulge its performance specifications until later,
probably during Super Bowl commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Computer makers already have the Pentium III systems ready to be
shipped. They are waiting until Intel's marketing army is ready to
try to convince us, once again, that it is time to upgrade our PCs
and downgrade our bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, most PC owners question whether they are suckers
for buying into this constant game of rapid obsolescence. The
advance of computer technology has always occurred at a dizzying
speed, but the experience of computing seems to slog along at the
same old pace.
</P>
<P>
   We have been promised for years that as computers get more
powerful, they will become easier to use and more useful, allowing
us to do wonderful new things.
</P>
<P>
   For consumers, however, the most wonderful advances in recent
years have been the growth of the Internet and its main
applications, including the World Wide Web, E-mail and E-commerce.
When it comes to the Internet, a faster modem has probably had more
impact on our happiness than a faster processor.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some analysts are now suggesting that we are on the
cusp of a new, ``post PC'' era in which simple, relatively
inexpensive information appliances, not complex PCs with
fire-breathing microprocessors, will win the hearts of consumers.
</P>
<P>
   With the Pentium III, however, Intel is once again promising
that great things are just around the corner, including better
tools for using the Internet, and that people who do not adopt the
newest chip will miss out on exciting new computing experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, we've heard it all before. But there are technical and
economic reasons to be interested in the imminent arrival of the
Pentium IIIs, even if one has no plans to move up to the new chip.
</P>
<P>
   On the technical side, there are two principal things that
differentiate the Pentium III from the Pentium II. One is speed.
Intel is expected to offer two versions of the new chip at first,
one operating at 450 megahertz and one at the milestone level of
500 MHz.
</P>
<P>
   A version that is 600 MHz or faster is expected by the end of
the year. Chip speed alone is not a reliable measure of computer
performance, but all other things being equal, standard software
applications will run faster on a 500-MHz machine than on a 400-MHz
system.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The second and more intriguing difference is something called
the Katmai New Instructions, a set of some 70 new multimedia
instructions that programmers can use to create applications with
better audio and graphics. Katmai was the code name for the Pentium
III.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Intel added new instructions for its major PC
microprocessor line was two years ago, when it introduced the
Pentium MMX chip. MMX stands for multimedia extensions, and
software developers eventually took advantage of the new hooks to
develop software with better graphics and sound.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's rivals, including Advanced Micro Devices, Cyrix and IDT,
came up with their own version, called 3DNow, which greatly
improves the performance of 3-D graphics and has been very popular
with game designers.
</P>
<P>
   According to people who have worked with it, the Pentium III
chip with Katmai New Instructions pushes ahead of both MMX and
3DNow. Intel has been working with software developers for more
than a year in preparation for the Katmai introduction, so
announcements are likely to come from software makers about their
support for the new chip in coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In practical terms, consumers can expect new software that makes
richer use of video, sound, speech and 3-D graphics. Games will get
more realistic, with almost fluid motion, better video playback,
better sound quality and superior 3-D graphics.
</P>
<P>
   But there will also be improvements in streaming video and audio
over the Internet, speech recognition as a user interface, video
E-mail, DVD-based entertainment, video and sound editing, and other
multimedia applications that developers are keeping secret for now.
</P>
<P>
   Such enticements typically make people reach for their wallets.
Some do so warily because they know that to take full advantage of
a Pentium III machine, they will have to buy new software. Others
do so enthusiastically because they want to be the first one on the
block to have the new technology.
</P>
<P>
   Intel will probably reserve the Katmai instruction set
exclusively for its Pentium III chips for the next year, at least,
before extending it to the rest of the Intel product line. Doing so
will create a clear difference between the high end Pentium III and
the low end Celeron chips.
</P>
<P>
   With the introduction last week of 366-MHz and 400-MHz versions
of the Celeron, the performance gap between the cheaper Celersons
and the Pentium IIs is quite narrow.
</P>
<P>
   Intel officials would not disclose the pricing for its Pentium
III chips, and they are prohibiting PC makers from talking about
system prices before the Pentium III is formally launched, which
might not occur until late February. But analysts say Intel plans
to be aggressive in keeping Pentium III prices low because of
increasing pressure from companies like AMD.
</P>
<P>
   AMD, meanwhile, is preparing to announce in a few weeks its K6-3
Sharptooth microprocessor, which it will promote as a challenger to
the Pentium III. And later this year, AMD is scheduled to unveil
the K-7, a powerful and fast chip that AMD asserts will finally let
the company break free from its usual place a speed bump or two
behind Intel.
</P>
<P>
   Details of all these future chips are unknown, but one thing is
certain.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is going to be a price war,'' said Keith Diefendorff,
editor in chief of The Microprocessor Report, a newsletter
published in Sunnyvale, Calif. ``Intel's latest announcements have
some pretty impressive prices on the low end, much lower than what
they have done before. They are growing tired of AMD taking market
share and they are going to put up a fight. That's going to cause
AMD to cut their prices. It's great news for consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   People who just want to do word processing, E-mail and basic
Internet browsing will almost certainly be able to buy a very
capable low-end machine, with more power for less money. The cost
of Pentium II-based machines will come down as the chip is phased
out.
</P>
<P>
   Cautious PC owners can relax and wait to see whether the new
applications written specifically for the Pentium III are really
worth the cost of upgrading. And fanatic game players, who
perpetually lust after the fastest machine on the block, will soon
have a choice of several new high-end machines.
</P>
<P>
   The hard part for Nick will be deciding whether to spend his
momney on petroleum or silicon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
