<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1537 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-EMAIL-ROMANCE-ART     01-13 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-EMAIL-ROMANCE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURTSHIP TO KISS-OFF, E-MAIL IS CHANGING THE LANGUAGE OF LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By KATIE HAFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maud Lavin and Locke Bowman were each other's first loves,
college sweethearts who were together for three intense years then
went their separate ways. One day, twenty-two years and three
marriages later _ one for her, two for him _ Bowman was in New York
on business. He called Ms. Lavin and they met for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   As they made tentative steps back into each other's orbit,
e-mail flew back and forth constantly between his computer in
Chicago and hers in New York. Their messages _ some 200 in all _
were at once confessional and guarded, brutally honest and gently
solicitous. Three-and-a-half months after the first message, they
were married.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a story about anonymous passion, infused with
subtext that asks, ``What does he/she look like?'' and ``Will the
physical chemistry be there?'' It's not the real life version of
the movie ``You've Got Mail.'' This is about the role e-mail can
play in matters of the heart when you already know about that
strange thing your former, current, or prospective lover does with
his mouth, or that sometimes annoying way she flips her hair back
when she's nervous. It is about the revival of the epistolary
romance.
</P>
<P>
   Love by letter is nothing new, of course. During the Victorian
Era, when the post was delivered several times each day,
impassioned letters fairly flew from door to door. Even before
those days, no Jane Austen novel would have been complete without
repeated scenes at the writing desk. When the telephone became a
more convenient instrument of communication, the intensity of
conducting a love affair by letter tapered off.
</P>
<P>
   Now e-mail has returned to relationships the ability to
formulate feelings and desires by writing them down.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, e-mail represents an inverted version of the
role of the letter in courtship rites, said Steven Johnson,
co-founder of the online magazine Feed and author of ``Interface
Culture: How New Technology Transforms the Way We Create and
Communicate,'' (HarperCollins 1997) ``Letters gave you the
formality of actually putting it down on paper,'' he said. ``You
could express in full rich language the depth of your feelings.
E-mail prose is much more informal. It's half way between speech
and writing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lavin and Bowman, both 44, had already known each other
intimately.
</P>
<P>
   But when they rediscovered each other, divorce had made them
wary and frightened. Ms. Lavin credits e-mail with helping them
broach topics too awkward for the telephone, yet too urgent for
snail mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about everything,'' she said. ``It was like one long
pajama party.'' A running electronic dialogue, she said, also
helped speed things up. ``I think we would have gotten together
anyway, but it would have taken much more time.'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Conversations with a few couples among the many who have courted
_ or parted _ by e-mail suggest that people with an affinity for
words are those most likely to embrace the technology as a means of
propelling a relationship forward, or speeding its end.
</P>
<P>
   Alaina and David Sloo met at a computer industry press
conference in New York in 1993. Ms. Sloo, then an analyst in New
York, caught the eye of Sloo, then a user interface designer at a
Silicon Valley startup. They went out for coffee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought anyone who could describe the tables at the Royalton
as looking like turtles tucking themselves up under their shells
was a guy worth knowing,'' recalled Ms. Sloo. ``But it wasn't until
I got an e-mail message from him that I realized he had an
astonishing imagination and routinely turned the most mundane
things into pure fun with the turn of a phrase. And I promptly fell
in love.''
</P>
<P>
   For nearly a year, they lived on separate coasts, then Ms. Sloo
moved to California and they married in 1995. ``I think writing
makes a fun-loving, poetic soul visible much faster than speech,''
said Ms. Sloo.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sloo, 33, said she believed there can be lingering effects
when a relationship has been galvanized by e-mail. ``Sometimes I
wonder if one of the reasons we're so given to turning our grocery
list into a Gershwin rhyme or falling into fits of alliteration on
the sidewalk is that we built our relationship on the written word,
rather than the spoken word,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   M.P. Dunleavey, 33, a writer in New York, and her boyfriend,
Paul Budnitz, 31, an entrepreneur in Berkeley, Calif. had an
experience similar to that of the Sloos. After meeting at a party
in New York last February, they went on a date. Things went well.
Soon after, he left for a three-week trip to Hawaii. E-mail became
not just a means of frequent communication, but, for Ms. Dunleavey,
it was also a gauge of the seriousness of his intentions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely paid close attention to how he was e-mailing me,
how long his e-mails were, how often he sent them, how quickly he
responded to mine, etcetera,'' she said. ``You're trying to see how
interested this person is.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the spring and summer and into fall, although they were
visiting each other frequently, the e-mail flow remained constant.
``Sometimes it was just these cute little dumb remarks,'' said Ms.
Dunleavey. ``It was almost a way of reaching out and tousling
someone on the head. Once he sent me an e-mail that was my name,
Mary Pat, copied a hundred times. Then `I love you.'And that was
it.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But e-mail is no substitute for the real thing. Last week, Ms.
Dunleavey moved to California to be together with Budnitz. And now
that they are married, Ms. Lavin and Bowman seldom use e-mail to
communicate with each other. ``During the day we use the phone,''
said Ms. Lavin.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail is as much of a boon for cowards and cads as it is for
separated lovers. Polly Shulman, 35, a senior editor at Discover
Magazine in New York, noted the appeal of e-mail as something to
hide behind. When her boyfriend of a year confessed to her that he
had been having a clandestine romance _ with someone, it may bear
noting, that he had met electronically _ he preferred to conduct
the painful prelude to his breakup with Ms. Shulman over e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was ridiculous, because we lived seven blocks
apart. I thought: Why can't we do this in person?'' said Ms.
Shulman. ``He's a writer and feels like he has more access to who
he really is in writing, that he's revealing a truer aspect of
himself than by talking person to person.''
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks after the final split, Ms. Shulman received a box
from her former beau containing her possessions _ including someone
else's undergarment, which Ms. Shulman noticed was nothing close to
her size. She donated the lingerie to Goodwill, and fictionalized
the experience in a short story she published in the Village Voice.
She has not identified her former lover.
</P>
<P>
   Currently in a relationship with a colleague, Ms. Shulman avoids
e-mail, preferring instead to ``just stick my head over the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kaminer, 32, president of a public relations firm in New
York, has broken up via e-mail, and says he regrets it. After
months of a long-distance relationship with someone in London, he
recalls, he wanted to put an end to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put together a very terse e-mail and sent it over to him. It
said something like, `This is it. Bye-bye,' '' he said. ``It was
direct enough, and impersonal, and enough of a brushoff he wouldn't
get in touch with me again.''
</P>
<P>
   Or so Kaminer thought. Instead, the plan backfired. For months
afterward, he recounted, ``I'd get phone calls from him, drunk. The
e-mail brush-off seemed to set him off more than anything I could
have said on the phone. It set some bomb off in this guy's head.''
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, said Kaminer, ``It was obviously a total cop-out.
I wouldn't do it again unless I really really disliked the
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Ullman, author of ``Close to the Machine: Technophilia and
Its Discontents'' (City Lights 1997), is also a critic of the
technique. ``Breaking up is a dreadful thing to do by e-mail,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Ms. Ullman confessed to having done precisely that.
``Several times. With the same person,'' she added. ``There was no
other way to get in touch. The only alternative was a cell phone,
and he had said he was too busy to talk with me. What was I
supposed to do? Break up a meeting? So e-mail seemed the best
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, she said, e-mail is a medium famous for being sent in the
heat of the moment and she advised caution. ``I have a folder that
I call `letters for the drawer,' '' she said. ``I get it off my
chest but don't send it.'' Ms. Ullman's system isn't perfect.
``Sometimes I take it right out of `letters for the drawer' and
send it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail can also be a good way to clarify things at the start of
a brand new relationship, especially for someone as reserved as Jon
Coifman. After Coifman, 32, a senior program director at
Environmental Media Services in Washington, D.C., went out with
Lisa Magnino, 31, a public relations executive, he was unclear
where things stood. ``I wasn't sure if the first date had actually
been a date or something else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So the following morning, he sent an e-mail asking just that.
Ms. Magnino e-mailed back cheerily that a date it had been. But
whatever reassurance Coifman may have taken from that message (and
a sign, perhaps, that e-mail, alone, will never a successful
relationship make) paled when he picked up Ms. Magnino for a second
date the next week. ``She planted a big one on me as soon as she
opened the door,'' he recounted.
</P>
<P>
   Now Coifman and Ms. Magnino live together and work in the same
office building. They still use e-mail, but differently. ``Now we
fire crude little missives back and forth,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
