<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1544 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS14-TAKE     01-13 1742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS14-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Editors: RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO NEED IT
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes.)
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or E-mail
him at q&AMP;(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: Since Hustler magazine publisher Larry Flynt is back in the
news, can you refresh my memory: When and where was he shot, and
was the person who shot him ever caught?
</P>
<P>
   A: Flynt was shot by a sniper on March 6, 1978, near the
Gwinnett County Courthouse in Lawrenceville, Ga. Gene Reeves, an
attorney who helped defend Flynt against charges that he broke
Georgia's obscenity laws in Gwinnett County, also was wounded. On
the day of the shooting, Flynt and Reeves had eaten at a cafeteria
and as they walked back to court, they were struck by the sniper's
bullets. One pierced Flynt's spine and another cut through his
back, continuing through Reeves' arm and into his abdomen. The
trial was called off and the charges dropped. Flynt was left
paralyzed, but Reeves recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Six years later, Joseph Paul Franklin, a self-proclaimed white
supremacist, confessed while in an Illinois jail for murder to the
Flynt shooting and other shootings, including the wounding of civil
rights leader Vernon Jordan. Franklin said he shot Flynt because
the pornographer published sexually explicit pictures of an
interracial couple. Franklin was indicted in 1983 in Flynt's
shooting, but Gwinnett prosecutors never brought him to trial
because he already was facing stiffer penalties in other states.
</P>
<P>
   Q: During the NBA strike negotiations, I heard frequent
references to the ``Larry Bird rule'' or the ``Larry Bird
exception.'' What does that mean?
</P>
<P>
   A: That was the rule allowing a team to go over its salary cap
to sign one of its own players who became a free agent. It was so
named because Larry Bird with the Boston Celtics was one of the
first situations it came into play.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was said on a TV quiz show that there are eight time zones
in the United States, but we can count only seven. Can you clarify?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are only six time zones in the United States. From the
east: Eastern, Central, Mountain, Pacific, Alaska and
Hawaii-Aleutian. Three other North American times zones (heading
east) are: Atlantic, Newfoundland and Greenland. But Newfoundland
might not be considered a true time zone because it differs from
its neighboring time zones by only a half-hour.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who was the first secretary-general of the United Nations?
How many have there been since then, and will you list their names
and nationalities?
</P>
<P>
   A: Seven men have served as secretary-general: Trygve Lie of
Norway, 1946-53; Dag Hammarskjold of Sweden, 1953-61; U Thant of
Burma, 1961-71; Kurt Waldheim of Austria, 1972-81; Javier Perez de
Cuellar of Peru, 1982-91; Boutros Boutros-Ghali of Egypt, 1992-96;
and, since Jan. 1, 1997, Kofi Annan of Ghana.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Four men, educated and world travelers,were discussing the
origin of the expression ``a lion's share'' the other day, and each
had a different explanation. Can you clarify how it came about?
</P>
<P>
   A: A lion's share is the largest portion of anything, and
relates to the term ``leonine contract,'' which means a completely
one-sided agreement. According to the Facts on File Encyclopedia of
Word and Phrase Origins, the source of both is Aesop's fable about
the lion that hunted with several other animals, with the lion
claiming all the spoils of the hunt. One-quarter of the spoils he
claimed as king of beasts; a second quarter because he was braver
than any other animal; a third for his mate and cubs; ``and as for
the fourth, let him who will, dispute it with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Whatever happened to the characters on the Taster's Choice TV
commercials? It was sort of a love triangle. Now I don't see them
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   A: The spots fell apart, rather like the complicated
relationships they portrayed. But they kept many viewers enthralled
for a long time. The ad campaign, launched in 1990, had 13
episodes, the last of which was shown in July 1997. It started when
a divorced woman, whose name was never disclosed, knocked on the
door of a neighbor, a single (and suave) gentleman identified as
Michael. She had wanted to borrow some coffee, and he introduced
her to Taster's Choice.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, the woman's ex-husband, Andrew, came back into
her life, as did her grown son. Viewers were tantalized about how
it would turn out, but they won't ever know, because the
commercials ended without a climax. In the last one, the ex-husband
arrived to pick up the woman for a date. Michael was clearly
disturbed. The ex-husband was shown calling the next day to
apologize to the woman for creating the awkward scene. ``I'm sorry
about last night,'' he said. She interrupted with a mysterious
``I'm not.'' And that was the end.
</P>
<P>
   In print advertisements in October 1997, Taster's Choice invited
viewers/consumers to decide, through a poll, which man she should
pick. Michael won, but no later commercial ever dramatized the
choice.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If the Atlanta Falcons should go to the Super Bowl in 2000,
when it's scheduled for the Georgia Dome, would the game site have
to be moved to another city?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. So it would be considered a ``home game,'' even though
most people in the Dome would be corporate execs and others from
all over.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recall that years ago, when I was in school, stamps cost 3
cents, and they stayed at that price for the longest time. Do you
know exactly how long?
</P>
<P>
   A: The per-ounce rate was 2 cents on July 1, 1885, said Barry
Ziehl of the U.S. Postal Service. It rose to 3 cents on Nov. 3,
1917, but went back to 2 cents on July 1, 1919. Then on July 6,
1932, it went back up to 3 cents, and didn't rise again (to 4
cents) until Aug. 1, 1958. Ziehl said he couldn't speculate on why
the rate was lowered between 1919 and 1932.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It's often mentioned that Republican Rep. J.C. Watts of
Oklahoma is a former college football player. When was that? Did he
also play pro football? How old is he, and does he have a family?
</P>
<P>
   A: Indeed he did play pro ball _ in Canada. From 1981 to 1986,
Watts started for Ottawa and Toronto in the Canadian Football
League. Watts was voted the most valuable player of the Grey Cup
game _ the CFL's equivalent of the Super Bowl _ his rookie season,
said his spokeswoman, Tobi Edwards. Watts had been drafted by the
New York Jets as a running back, but he wanted to play the
quarterback position and went to Canada. Before his entrance into
elective office in 1990 as an Oklahoma State Corp. commissioner,
Watts was best known to many people as the University of Oklahoma
quarterback who led the Sooners to consecutive Big Eight
championships and Orange Bowl victories in 1979 and '80.
</P>
<P>
   J.C. (for Julius Caesar) Watts Jr. was born Nov. 18, 1957, in
Eufaula, Okla., the son of a Baptist minister and policeman who
also traded cattle. The junior Watts graduated from the University
of Oklahoma in 1981 with a B.A. in journalism. He won his seat in
Congress, representing Oklahoma's 4th District, in 1994, and was
re-elected in 1998 with 62 percent of the vote. He and his wife,
Frankie, have five children and live in Norman, Okla.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can we use our old 1-cent stamps along with remaining 32-cent
stamps for the new mailing rate, instead of buying the
undenominated supplement stamp that the post office is selling?
Like the new $20 bill, it looks like something somebody printed in
their cellar.
</P>
<P>
   A: You can use any combination of new or old stamps you like, so
long as they add up to 33 cents, said Postal Service spokeswoman
Sandra Harding in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the difference between Coca-Cola Co. and Coca-Cola
Enterprises?
</P>
<P>
   A: They're obviously closely entertwined. As explained in
Hoover's Handbook of American Business 1998, ``Guys in lab coats
and suits at the Coca-Cola Co. concoct the secret recipes and
blitz-market the brand, but Coca-Cola Enterprises does much of the
actual bottling and distribution of Coca-Cola products.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's the more official explanation, from CCE's Web site
(http://www.cokecce.com): ``Coca-Cola Enterprises is the world's
largest marketer, producer and distributor of products of the
Coca-Cola Co. We also distribute Dr Pepper and several other
beverage brands in selected territories. We are an independent,
public company traded on the New York Stock Exchange under the
stock symbol CCE.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Coca-Cola Co. (stock symbol KO) develops products,
produces the advertising and programs to support those products,
and sells syrup concentrate to Coca-Cola Enterprises and other
bottlers. As a bottler, we combine the product concentrate with
other ingredients to manufacture and package our beverages.
Coca-Cola Enterprises then uses its extensive sales and delivery
force to market and distribute products to retail customers and
consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have any information about a plagiarism case involving
authors Danielle Steel and Nora Roberts? What books were involved,
and what was the disposition of the case?
</P>
<P>
   A: Steel wasn't one of the parties. The copyright infringement
lawsuit that shook the world of romance writing down to its
throbbing heart was filed by Roberts in August 1997 against fellow
romance writer Janet Dailey. The suit was settled out of court last
year for an undisclosed sum.
</P>
<P>
   The case involved two of Dailey's books, ``Aspen Gold'' (1991)
and ``Notorious'' (1996), both of which contained ideas and
passages that she admitted were lifted from works by Roberts.
Dailey said the plagiarism occurred at a time when her husband was
undergoing cancer surgery and she was under great stress. When
asked about the incident last year, Dailey's husband, Bill, told
The Associated Press: ``That's all behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   The plagiarism first came to light when it was posted on the
Internet by readers who cited comparisons between paragraphs in
novels by both writers. Initial reports about the lawsuit said
Roberts was asking Dailey to make a donation to the Literacy
Volunteers of America in lieu of damages, but it wasn't disclosed
if that came to pass in the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   END TAKE 1
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
