<HEADER>
A1546 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-BUG-GAME-NYT &LR;      01-13 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-BUG-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYFUL ALCHEMY: A MOVIE BECOMES A GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If, as Frank Zappa observed, writing about music is like dancing
about architecture, then video games about movies are like
synchronized swimming about opera. The media have very little in
common except a flat screen.
</P>
<P>
   And the question is: How do you map a linear, noninteractive
story onto a free-ranging environment where the player decides what
comes next? How do you translate a film into a game without
compromising either?
</P>
<P>
   For Disney Interactive, which produced a version of ``A Bug's
Life'' for the Sony Playstation, it was a particularly tricky
prospect because the intended audience _ children 8 to 12 years old
_ has sky-high standards for video games. Having seen the movie,
they already know the story.
</P>
<P>
   A few months from now, they will have seen it over and over on
video. They don't want anything incongruous in a game, but they
demand something new. And they expect it to look great.
</P>
<P>
   Grafting the film's narrative into the structure of a game is an
exercise in streamlining. ``We went through the film very early
with the script and picked out what we thought were high points, or
beat points,'' said Dan Winters, the game's senior producer. ``We
came up with a five-part structure that allowed us to hit every
major beat point of the film and then design to those points.
During those stages, the player kind of re-enacted or walked in the
footsteps of Flik, the hero, which allowed us to incorporate a lot
of the action elements of the film.''
</P>
<P>
   Storyboards can be cut and pasted from a film. The dynamics of
game play cannot. It took Hollywood a long time to understand that,
which is why movie-based games have been among the most boring ever
released.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, the studios are beginning to realize that you can do
more than put your hero in the standard
running-jumping-and-shooting scenario that prompts jaded eye rolls
among second graders. You can make something original. And Disney
Interactive has done so, in a playful and elegant way.
</P>
<P>
   A Bug's Life incorporates the conventional running and jumping
and shooting. (No deadly projectiles. You hurl large berries at
enemy bugs, and they disappear or run away. This is, after all, a
Disney title.) But most of the game play revolves around collecting
things and using them strategically.
</P>
<P>
   The bug-scale universe is littered with useful objects to be
picked up and transformed. Giant seeds can be hauled around and
dropped. If you jump on them, they sprout. So if a ledge is too
high to climb, you can grow a mushroom, which functions as a
trampoline, and bounce up to the ledge.
</P>
<P>
   If it's too high for you to use a mushroom plant, then you run,
find another seed, grow it into an ivy plant next to the mushroom,
bounce onto the mushroom and leap onto the higher plateau of an ivy
leaf. Then you climb over the wall.
</P>
<P>
   There's a good deal of puzzle-solving in A Bug's Life, but
nothing is arcane (decipher the extraterrestrial runes; play the
ancient musical instrument). The problems mostly involve getting
from point A to point B when you're not strong or tall enough, or
tracking down things that are difficult to find. These are problems
that an 8-year-old can understand.
</P>
<P>
   There are different ways to solve these problems, and there are
different ways to win. You can win by making it through all 15
levels. Or you can win by uncovering everything that is hidden in
the game world _ digging up the buried treasure and unlocking all
the secret doors, covering every inch of virtual ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are very goal-oriented,'' Winters said. ``They
just want to get through the game and finish it and have the
accomplishment of getting through the game. Other people want to go
through and find every single little thing.''
</P>
<P>
   It depends on your definition of winning. In one case, it means
going as far as you can on a linear path from beginning to end. In
the other, it means drilling down from the game's surface through
all of its layers to the core. A video game, like a film, has an
axis of length. But it also has an axis of depth.
</P>
<P>
   That is the most fundamental difference between a cinematic
narrative and an interactive narrative. A film can be cut up,
rewound or fast-forwarded. You can skip around. You can slow it
down. You can notice different things at different times. But you
can't reveal something that was submerged and invisible. There's no
such thing as ``deeper.''
</P>
<P>
   A Bug's Life is a layer cake, in that sense. After every level
of the game, a video clip follows the narrative arc of the movie.
Strung together, the clips constitute a rough sketch of the story.
And if you race through the game, that is what you'll see.
</P>
<P>
   But if you really delve into the environment _ explore every
cranny, solve every puzzle, collect every floating icon and defeat
all the enemies _ a screen pops up, congratulates you and plays a
bonus clip. There are almost 20 minutes of film buried in the game,
and those moments are enhanced precisely because they are hidden
and inaccessible.
</P>
<P>
   If you could simply fast forward to them, it wouldn't be as much
fun. This way, they are like the elusive gold berries or the
propeller plants: objects to be sought, areas to unlock.
</P>
<P>
   Embedded in the game universe, these kernels of film sprout into
the roots and branches of the interactive narrative, just like the
other seeds lying around. They become part of the environment and
part of the player's story. Because in a video game, the
environment (italics)is(end italics) the story.
</P>
<P>
   The player moves through it, gazing around all the while. The
story of a video game is like the story of a theme park, minus
ticket lines and hydraulics.
</P>
<P>
   Video games are theme parks of the mind. And if there's one
thing that Disney knows how to build, it's theme parks: synthetic
environments that contain fragments of its films. Disney knows a
lot about making films into objects and creating a context for
those objects.
</P>
<P>
   The question of translating a linear story into an interactive
story is really a question of context. ``What is the envelope?'' is
the question that defines the design process. If the envelope is
linear and you put little interactive things into it, you get
something that looks like a game but feels like a snaggy,
interrupted movie.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated players ask themselves, ``Why can't I just watch the
movie straight through without the roadblocks and speed bumps?'' If
the envelope is the interactive environment, you get something that
looks like a movie and feels like a decent video game _ and meets
the exacting standards of an 8-year-old.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (A Bug's Life, developed by Disney Interactive and published by
Sony Playstation; $39.99; for ages 8 and up.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
