<HEADER>
A1547 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-T     01-13 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SWEET DECEIT: THE SECRET'S IN THE SAUCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the holidays over and the rich menus of pies and cakes and
cobblers gone, it is time to seek out a simpler, more deceptive way
of getting our sugar fix.
</P>
<P>
   I think it could be bread pudding.
</P>
<P>
   Bread pudding might be a regular thing at your house, but not at
mine. We are in denial at my home; we never admit having desserts.
We recently bought a birthday cake for our son-in-law and when he
was unable to claim it, we had to quickly eat away the evidence. It
was a two-layer cake, fully iced.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, we ate it while standing, and any nutritionist
worth their sodium will tell you calories don't count if consumed
in the upright position. It is an axiom, if not a constitutional
mandate.
</P>
<P>
   Bread pudding is not a fancy dessert. How damaging can it be
when it doesn't even have icing? It is easy to prepare and it is
truly a comfort food _ warm, good smelling and squishy in your
mouth.
</P>
<P>
   That might not be vital to a lot of people, but to those of us
who grew up thinking it was funny to squish Jell-O through our
teeth, a soothing texture is important.
</P>
<P>
   Also, bread pudding crosses tons of cultural lines. It can be
found in many French cookbooks; one Alsatian recipe I came across
was made with Bing cherries, a fruit-based liqueur and lemon zest.
</P>
<P>
   It is a western dish as well. Today's chuck-wagon cooks often
use leftover biscuits to soak in milk and eggs and sugar. Bread
pudding can be made easily in a Dutch oven.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, it's not too important how the pudding turns out
anyway because most of the cooks pour a whiskey sauce over it, and
the sauce would bring out a nice, delicate, wonderful taste in boot
leather.
</P>
<P>
   Bread pudding recipes are found in Mexican versions, Southern
versions, soul food versions and Cajun versions. I'm sure there are
more variations, but those were the only books I had.
</P>
<P>
   Raisins are generally one of the ingredients in a basic bread
pudding, although I've never cared for them. It has to do with that
texture thing. Some people use fruit cocktail, pecans, candied
orange and lemon peel.
</P>
<P>
   Cinnamon is prominent in many recipes, others use nutmeg, and a
few call for both.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone uses whiskey sauce. Rum is often substituted, and
the pudding is commonly topped with honey, sorghum, fruit glazes,
whipped cream or ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   The one thing I don't care for is tightly packed, dense bread
pudding. I don't want to slice my pudding from a brick; I want it
moist and creamy, the way pudding is supposed to be.
</P>
<P>
   And, in my opinion, it ought to be reasonably simple. I saw one
recipe for chocolate brioche-English toffee bread pudding, and
although it looked like a luscious dessert, it didn't look like
bread pudding. It was more like a chocolate block that oozed
caramel.
</P>
<P>
   And there was another recipe for ``bread and butter pudding
served with clotted cream and compote of apricots.'' I, and the
rest of the guys down at the feed store, don't eat things that are
clotted.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a reasonably simple recipe our family has enjoyed for
years. I'm not sure where it originated, and probably there have
been so many changes it no longer matters.
</P>
<P>
   Notice it has apples, and that makes it a fruit, not a dessert.
</P>
<P>
   APPLE BREAD PUDDING
</P>
<P>
   Yields 8
</P>
<P>
   8 thin slices stale, firm white bread
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons unsalted butter at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   6 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces frozen unsweetened apple-juice concentrate, defrosted
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup apple jelly
</P>
<P>
   4 Golden Delicious apples
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 pint vanilla ice cream, optional
</P>
<P>
   Butter one side of bread slices with 2 tablespoons of butter.
Cut each slice into quarters. Lightly butter a 6-cup baking dish
with 1 tablespoon of butter. Lay bread evenly in dish, overlapping
slices.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, whisk together eggs, granulated sugar and
cinnamon until well blended.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium saucepan, combine cream, apple juice and apple
jelly. Bring to simmer over moderate heat. Gradually whisk liquid
into eggs in a thin stream. Pour custard over bread and let stand,
pushing slices down once or twice, until bread is saturated, about
15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees. Place baking dish in a roasting pan
and add enough warm water to reach halfway up sides of dish. Bake
in center of oven for 45 to 50 minutes, until custard is set.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, quarter, core and peel apples. Cut each quarter into
two wedges. In a large skillet, melt remaining 2 tablespoons
butter. Add apples and saute over moderately high heat, tossing
occasionally until browned, about 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat broiler. Broil pudding about 4 inches from heat until
top is browned, 1-2 minutes. Dust with 1 teaspoon of the
confectioners' sugar, mound sauteed apples on top and sprinkle with
remaining 1 teaspoon confectioners' sugar. Serve warm or at room
temperature with a scoop of vanilla ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 418 calories, 23 grams fat, 48
grams carbohydrates, 7 grams protein, 220 milligrams cholesterol,
163 milligrams sodium, 49 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes on food for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Write to him at: Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101. E-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com. Web Site:
www.startext.net/interact/chapman.htm. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
