<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1550 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS14-TAKE     01-13 1661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS14-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDITORS: RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO NEED IT
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: Take two of 2.)
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I recall that Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.) started publicly calling
for President Clinton's impeachment almost immediately after the
president was elected for the first time. Can you refresh my memory
about the sequence of these events?
</P>
<P>
   A: Clinton was first elected president Nov. 3, 1992. He was
inaugurated Jan. 20, 1993. It was more than four years later _
March 1997 _ when Barr wrote a letter to Rep. Henry Hyde (R-Ill.),
chairman of the House Judiciary Committee, asking Hyde to consider
beginning an impeachment inquiry of Clinton and Vice President Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent item in Q&AMP;A said bottled waters have had the
fluoride filtered out. Is the same true for those of us using
faucet filters? I've had a PUR water filter for some time, and when
I bought it, I was told it doesn't filter out fluoride. I want the
fluoride for my children's benefit.
</P>
<P>
   A: You're in good shape using a PUR filter. ``None of our
products take out the fluoride in the water,'' Q&AMP;A was told by Judy
Smith of PUR and Recovery Engineering, which makes the PUR drinking
water system. The PUR filter does claim to remove lead and
chlorine, as well as Crypto (Cryptosporidium) and Giardia bacteria.
For more information about what the filter does and does not
remove, call PUR consumer service at 1-800-787-5463 or
1-800-845-7873.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, while fluoride is removed from most bottled waters,
not all are fluoride-free. Gleda James, president of Lithia Springs
Water Co. in Georgia, says her firm's mineral water contains
natural fluoride in the amount of 1.7 milligrams per liter. Doe
information: 770-944-3880.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I heard that ever since Elizabeth Dole became president of
the American Red Cross, contibutions have been down. Is this true?
Can you list the total annual contributions to the Red Cross from
the time she took over until now?
</P>
<P>
   A: Although contributions haven't gone up every year under Dole,
they've shown an increase of $181 million over the eight-year
period, according to the American Red Cross. Dole, who became
president of the Red Cross in February 1991, announced recently
that she would step down, prompting speculation that she would be a
Republican candidate for the White House in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The contributions over Dole's eight-year period added up to $3.4
billion, of which more than $650 million was earmarked for disaster
relief, said Red Cross spokesman Bill Maddox. The year-by-year
amounts: 1991, $386 million; 1992, $394.7 million; 1993, $535.6
million; 1994, $504.7 million; 1995, $465.6 million; 1996, $474.4
million; 1997, $493.4 million; 1998, $566.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   The American Red Cross is not a government organization, Maddox
pointed out, so it relies on contributions from the public,
businesses, corporations and foundations. During her tenure, Dole
initiated a complete redesign of the organization's fund-raising
practices and launched a new four-year fund-raising growth plan,
Maddox added.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We would like to write to Larry Flynt, who is so much in the
news lately for his project to expose what he calls the hypocrisy
of some members of Congress. What is the address?
</P>
<P>
   A: The publisher of Hustler magazine can be contacted at: L.F.P.
Inc., 8484 Wilshire Blvd., Suite 900, Beverly Hills, CA 90211.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the address for the Council of Conservative Citizens,
the organization that Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.) spoke to, igniting a
controversy because of its white supremacist views?
</P>
<P>
   A: Write: Council of Conservative Citizens, P.O. Box 221683, St.
Louis, MO 63122. While Barr admits having spoken to the group, he
disassociated himself from it after his appearance was publicized,
saying he initially wasn't aware of its extremist views. That point
was disputed by his critics, however, who maintain that the group's
reputation is well known.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Five women were just sworn in to statewide office in Arizona,
making it the first state to have an all-female elected line of
succession. What are their party affiliations?
</P>
<P>
   A: Gov. Jane Hull, Secretary of State Betsey Bayless, Treasurer
Caro-- Springer and Superintendent of Public Instruction Lisa
Graham Keegan are Republicans; Attorney General Janet Napolitano is
a Democrat. Arizona doesn't have a lieutenant governor.
</P>
<P>
   An interesting footnote: According to statistics compiled by the
Center for the American Woman and Politics at Rutgers University,
Arizona long has had one of the highest percentages in the nation
of women in state legislatures. This year's percentage: 36.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can I get tickets to Super Bowl XXXIV in Atlanta next
January? How much will they cost?
</P>
<P>
   A: A limited number of tickets is made available to the public
through a lottery. To enter the lottery for the 2000 game, send a
certified letter with your request between March 1 and June 1 to:
Super Bowl Ticket Lottery, National Football League, 280 Park Ave.,
New York, NY 10017. Names will be drawn at random for the
opportunity to purchase tickets. A National Football League
spokesman said he expected ``about 5,000'' to be available next
year. Tickets for the Jan. 31 game in Miami are $325 each; the cost
for Atlanta's Super Bowl hasn't yet been determined.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Often on ``Good Morning America,'' a group of people is shown
saying something like this: ``We are the teachers from the Atlanta
middle schools. Good morning, America!'' How can we do that?
</P>
<P>
   A: First, you need to be aware that a screening process is
involved, and potential subjects for ``GMA faces,'' as they're
called, are backed up for at least six months. But if you want to
try your luck, you need to contact the network's local affiliate,
said ABC publicist Dahlia Roemer in New York. If the local
affiliate determines by its screening that the proposed group is
suitable, if then forwards it to ``Good Morning America'' at ABC
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I haven't seen who will perform the national anthem at this
year's Super Bowl. Do you know?
</P>
<P>
   A: It will be sung by Cher.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent TV commercial for the Audi A6 showed a European city
square scene with a bride, a man on a bicycle, and a man and woman
embracing. The music, sung in a foreign language, was haunting.
Where was it filmed? Who performed the music, and what is the
language?
</P>
<P>
   A: The spot, part of a six-commercial campaign for Audi titled
``Heart,'' was filmed at the Royal Naval Academy in London, said
Joni Madison, head of broadcast production at the ad agency
McKinney &AMP; Silver in Raleigh. The music is a Bulgarian folk song
performed by Mystere de Voix Bulgares, the Bulgarian State Radio
and Television female choir. The particular number in question is
``Polegnala e Todora,'' a love song. The language, of course, is
Bulgarian.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've read several items suggesting that Ted Turner might run
for president. Is that true? I would vote for him because he's got
scads of money, so he couldn't be bought by any special-interest
group, and his wife is no wallflower, so maybe he wouldn't get into
any sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   A: Here's the official response from Turner Broadcasting
spokeswoman Caroline Harkleroad: ``We can confirm that in November,
The New Yorker magazine reported that Mr. Turner said he would like
to run for president. On several occasions in the past, he also has
talked about running, but he has never announced his candidacy. His
current focus is his work as vice chairman of Time Warner Inc. and
his dedication to the United Nations Foundation, the Turner
Foundation and other philanthropic endeavors.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What does ESPN stand for?
</P>
<P>
   A: It doesn't stand for anything any more. But when ESPN started
in 1979, it was the Entertainment and Sports Programming Network
(thus, ESPN). However, the full name was dropped in February 1985
when the company adopted a new corporate name, ESPN Inc., and a new
logo. Based in Bristol, Conn., ESPN is 80 percent owned by ABC
Inc., which is an indirect subsidiary of The Walt Disney Co. The
Hearst Corp. holds the remaining 20 percent interest in ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What powers does a president have to grant pardons? Must
other government leaders be consulted? Can pardons be challenged?
How common are they?
</P>
<P>
   A: The presidential power to pardon is absolute. As it has been
interpreted by the courts, the pardon power is one of the few
constitutional powers of the president that does not require the
agreement of Congress or allow for congressional interference.
</P>
<P>
   A challenge is possible, however. Such was the case when
attorney George Murphy brought an action against President Ford
seeking a judicial declaration that Ford's pardon of ex-President
Nixon was unconstitutional. Chief Judge Noel Fox of the U.S.
District Court for the Western District of Michigan validated the
pardon, but took the unusual step of lambasting Ford's decision.
``Evidence now available suggests a strong probability that the
Nixon administration was conducting a covert assault on American
liberty and an insurrection and rebellion against constitutional
government itself,'' Fox declared.
</P>
<P>
   Pardons are not uncommon. President Washington used his pardon
power to help quell the Whiskey Rebellion, and Presidents
Washington, John Adams, Madison, Lincoln, Andrew Johnson and Carter
all have granted amnesties, the latter extended to Vietnam-era
draft evaders. President Bush issued controversial pardons to
several key figures implicated in the Iran-contra scandal during
the Reagan administration, and Nixon pardoned labor leader Jimmy
Hoffa. President Truman pardoned more than 1,500 people who had
violated the Secret Service Act during World War II, and President
Reagan issued nearly 400 pardons during his two terms.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
