<HEADER>
A1560 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-TOUR-SPI &LR;      01-13 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TOUR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORM MACDONALD HAS NEW COMEDY ON ABC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Norm Macdonald, fired from NBC's ``Saturday
Night Live'' because Don Ohlmeyer didn't think he was funny, has
taken his game to ABC and a new half-hour comedy called ``The Norm
Show,'' premiering March 24.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why ABC, Macdonald said: ``I like ABC because it's the
American Broadcasting Company, and I think that's nice. `American,'
you know what I'm saying? Whereas NBC is `National,' but they don't
really say what nation. And then the other one (CBS) is a bunch of
freaking Colombians, aren't they?''
</P>
<P>
   (A note to the reader: Macdonald didn't exactly say
``freaking.'')
</P>
<P>
   Then he was asked, why not Fox?
</P>
<P>
   ``Fox I couldn't do because I'm three dimensional.''
</P>
<P>
   In his new show, Macdonald plays a hockey player turned social
worker, albeit an unorthodox one, who is kept in line by his
straight-arrow colleague, played by Laurie Metcalf (``Roseanne'').
The wisecracking native of Quebec said the ``climate of society,''
including the activities of the president of the United States,
paves the way for low-grade humor on television. Always ready with
an opinon, Macdonald added that, if the president's unconventional
use of tobacco products is a crime, ``then I'm (insert profanity
here) Dillinger.''
</P>
<P>
   From the profane, we move to propane, Hank Hill's line of work
on ``King of the Hill.'' More specifically to Chuck Mangione, known
by an older crowd for his 1977 megahit, ``Feels So Good,'' but
probably more familiar to a younger set for his recurring
``appearances'' on Fox's animated series.
</P>
<P>
   Mangione's sense of humor even extends to special engagements,
such as a favor this week to executive producer Greg Daniels, who
hosted about 50 TV critics on a tour of the ``King of the Hill''
studio _ actually a converted law office in an L.A. high rise. For
anyone wanting to know about the show's move from a successful
Sunday slot to a tender Tuesday posting, Daniels pointed to a small
room where Mangione stood alone, ready to play a few bars of
``Feels So Good'' for each visitor.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels' point: Despite a sharp drop in total viewers, ``King of
the Hill'' ratings remains strong in several desirable demographic
categories. A fact sheet of supporting evidence concludes with this
bit of sarcasm: Since the move to Tuesdays, ``Fox's entire Sunday
schedule is down 13 percent in the key adults 18-to-49 demo. That
shouldn't feel so good, but it does.''
</P>
<P>
   Were it not for a severe ankle injury, Jenna Elfman might be
more famous for her toe shoes than her tofu. Each summer for three
years in the late '80s, the tall star of ``Dharma and Greg''
studied in Seattle with the Pacific Northwest Ballet, intent on
becoming a great dancer.
</P>
<P>
   Elfman, who plays the peace-loving daughter of 1960s flower
children on her ABC sitcom, says there's a little motor inside her
that keeps her focused and driven. Though her career was redirected
by an injury, Elfman said, ``I don't feel that I can be stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to assess her talent as a ballet dancer on a scale from 1
to 10, Elfman said quickly and directly: ``Eight and a half.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
