<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1566 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIGSCREEN-TVS14-COX     01-13 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIGSCREEN-TVS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More and more people are moving up to larger TVs, but be warned:
It's not just a case of `the bigger, the better'
 &HT;    By Sandy Amann John
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ David Tillis is so happy with his big-screen
television with surround sound that he had the media room in his
new home specifically designed for the system. The house, now under
construction in north Fulton County, includes pre-wiring and spaces
in the walls for front and rear speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Tillis, a licensed professional counselor, and his family enjoy
watching videos on the 50-inch screen. When they move into the new
home next month, they'll switch from cable to satellite television
for a better picture.
</P>
<P>
   And Tillis is definitely planning to watch Super Bowl XXXIII on
his big-screen TV.
</P>
<P>
   With one of America's heaviest days of TV viewing on the horizon
_ Jan. 31 _ many people are upsizing their TV sets to a big-screen
model, or thinking about it. What should they know before buying?
</P>
<P>
   The Consumer Electronics Manufacturers Association considers any
television with a screen 30 inches or larger to be a big-screen
model. But for most customers, ``big screen'' means at least 40
inches across, said Marshall Bronson, manager of the HiFi Buys
store in Roswell (Ga.). The most popular size among buyers there is
about 50 inches.
</P>
<P>
   When shopping for a big-screen TV, you need to know where you're
going to place it and what you're going to watch on it. The
salesperson will ask you those kinds of questions to help you
select the size that best meets your needs, Bronson said.
</P>
<P>
   Prices start at about $1,500, with most people spending between
$2,000 and $2,500 for a big-screen set, Bronson said. Huge screens
_ 60 inches and bigger _ with high-end features cost much more, as
do more elaborate home theater systems.
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind that the larger the screen, the more it will
amplify flaws in the picture. On a big screen, the interlace lines
and individual pixels that make up the picture become more visible,
CEMA notes. To make them disappear, you'll need to sit farther from
the screen than with your smaller TV.
</P>
<P>
   So, before you head to the electronics store, measure the room
in which you plan to install the TV. For optimum viewing, CEMA
suggests the ``2.5'' guideline: You should sit 2.5 times as far
from the screen as the screen's diagonal measurement. With a
50-inch screen, for example, try to sit about 10 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   Another variable that could affect the screen size you want is
what the consumer electronics industry calls ``sources,'' or where
the picture being viewed comes from: cable, VCR, laser disc,
satellite, etc.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you blow the picture up to 50 inches, some sources don't
look so good,'' Bronson said.
</P>
<P>
   Cable television has a lower-quality picture than a laser disc,
for example. So if cable is your main source of viewing material, a
screen on the smaller end of the big-screen spectrum might be
better. Cable looks ``grainy'' on his screen, Tillis said.
</P>
<P>
   If you're dead set on a humongous screen, Bronson said, you
might want to change the source, by switching from cable to digital
satellite TV, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers also should keep in mind the coming advent of
high-definition television, or HDTV. For most people, a big-screen
set is a purchase that will last 10 years or longer. So it's
important, Bronson said, to buy a system that's flexible _ one that
can be upgraded for HDTV and that can accommodate options such as
digital video discs, or DVDs.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, upgrading for HDTV costs about $3,000, Bronson said,
but he expects that price to fall below $1,000 within two years.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the largest of today's big-screen sets are
rear-projection models, in which the picture is projected through
the screen via mirrors. Rear-projection sets are more easily
upgradable to HDTV, which is a major plus, but the screen is
delicate and can be damaged. If you have children or pets, consider
buying a protective screen, or look for a model with a built-in
protective screen. Airborne grease can also damage these screens,
Bronson said, so he recommends a protective screen if the set will
be near a kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   To get the highest-quality picture when selecting a big-screen
television, Bronson recommends that you focus on the
black-and-white elements, not the colors. Every manufacturer has
its own color standards, which makes the same picture look
different, although the colors can be adjusted; the blacks and
whites aren't adjustable, Bronson explained.
</P>
<P>
   If you plan to hook up a lot of other gear to your television,
make sure the set you select allows for easy switching among
sources. Another convenience feature to consider is a multibrand
remote control, which will allow you to operate your Sony VCR and
your Mitsubishi television, for example, from one hand.
</P>
<P>
   FOR MORE INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   More advice on selecting a television is available in ``The
Official Guide to Buying, Connecting and Using Consumer Electronics
Products'' at the Consumer Electronics Manufacturers Association
Web site, at http://www.cemacity.org/gazette/cebook/.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Amann John is a freelance writer for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   TV terms to know
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Direct-view TV: These television sets _ the kind most of us
grew up with _ house the picture tube, tuner and speakers within
the set.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Projection TV: Includes both a projector and a screen for
viewing the TV picture: It can be front projection (the projector
is in front and projects onto the screen, like a movie projector)
or rear projection, in which the projector is behind the screen and
uses mirrors to get the picture onto the screen.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Big-screen TV: The consumer electronics industry considers any
TV with a diagonal screen measurement of 30 inches or more to be a
big screen, at least for statistical purposes. Most consumers in
the market for a big screen want it to be at least 40 inches,
retailers say.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Wide-screen TV: The newest kind of TV features a rectangular
screen resembling the shape of a movie screen. These are also known
as 16:9 screens, because the ratio of width to height is 16 to 9.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  HDTV: High-definition TV, in which digital images result in a
TV picture that is amazingly clear and lifelike. Many stations now
air high-definition broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  DVD: Digital Versatile Disc, the latest video playback
technology. A DVD disc in a DVD player provides much better audio
and video quality than does a VCR, and offers viewers a variety of
options, such as subtitles and different viewing angles and screen
ratios.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Consumer Electronics Manufacturers Association
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
