A1575 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEIBOWITZ-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      01-13 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEIBOWITZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIKE BLEW CHANCE FOR SLAM DUNK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID LEIBOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Maybe we should all wear black _ warm-ups _
embroidered with the name Jordan. It's only fitting: He's quitting,
so it's time to mourn.
</P>
<P>
   Expect infinite paeans to His Airness, the man/god in the red
jersey numbered 23. Hacks nationwide will effuse about ``balletic
grace'' and ``competitive fire,'' about 10 scoring crowns and six
NBA championship rings. They will wail in prose over the loss of
Michael Jordan, our Christ in high tops.
</P>
<P>
   And they will be so very wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan quitting is exactly what sports needs, for he is a
perfect marker of all that ails sports: The athlete turned
pitchman, a soulless corporate shill; a human being reduced to a
logo; a name manipulated into a slogan.
</P>
<P>
   Be Like Mike, goes the commercial's catchline. Eat Wheaties;
slug Gatorade; munch McDonald's; wear Nikes, Oakley sunglasses and
Hanes underwear; bathe in Michael Jordan cologne; and use a
WorldCom cellular phone _ but have no social conscience whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
   The hacks look at Jordan on the court and see basketball
perfection. I look at Jordan in that other arena _ life _ and see
untold unfulfilled potential. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Husksters big losers &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You say he is not a role model, and I sadly nod in agreement _
exactly! But imagine if he had been? Imagine if Michael Jordan had
used all his influence to sell not sports drinks or hot dogs, but
something worth selling?
</P>
<P>
   Then the loss of him would be true tragedy. As it stands now,
the big loser is Madison Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Don't cry for the hucksters, though. There's always videotape:
Last year's jumper against the Jazz to clinch the Bulls' sixth
title; the night when, just out of retirement, Jordan dropped 55 on
the Knicks; the double-pumping buzzer-beater over Craig Ehlo to
knock the Cavaliers out of the 1989 playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Such presence on the court. Such a cipher in life.
</P>
<P>
   Think of what Jordan might have done to fight violence after the
murder of his father, James. Think of what a few well-placed words
might have meant, then think only of his silence.
</P>
<P>
   Think of Michael Eugene Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   He was 15 in 1989, a Maryland ninth-grader with a friend named
James Martin and a brand-new pair of Air Jordan basketball
sneakers. Thomas paid $115.50 for the shoes. He also paid with his
life.
</P>
<P>
   Martin strangled his pal. He left the body barefoot in the
woods.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas wasn't the first kid to die over sneakers stitched with
Jordan's number, but he may have been the first dead kid Jordan
learned about. For a 1990 story that detailed how endless hype had
made his Nikes part of gangbangers' uniforms, a ``Sports
Illustrated'' writer gave the superstar a press clipping. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Most Valuable Pitchman &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jordan looked like ``he might cry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone likes to be admired,'' he said, ``but when it comes
to kids actually killing each other . . . then you have to
re-evaluate things.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan again, a few dozen paragraphs later: ``I'd rather
eliminate the product (the shoes) than know drug dealers are
providing the funds that pay me.''
</P>
<P>
   It must have been some re-evaluation. In 1997, Michael Jordan
made $78 million _ about $50 million of it from endorsements.
Yesterday afternoon, Foot Locker was still selling Air Jordans.
</P>
<P>
   For $150 a pair.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not labelling Jordan an accomplice to murder, or blaming him
for a culture where welfare kids lust after sneakers priced higher
than a set of encyclopedias. But he did he benefit from it, then
abdicate what chance he had to help stop it.
</P>
<P>
   Such silence is not the stuff of heroes.
</P>
<P>
   So he will go now, and the mourning will commence. Sports Pundit
Nation has lost its meal ticket. The ad people have lost their Most
Valuable Pitchman. We will wait for the next Jordan, dribbling even
now in a far-off playground.
</P>
<P>
   I imagine that boy, and again I hear the commercial with its
catchline.
</P>
<P>
   Kid, I think, play like Mike. Don't be like Mike. &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Leibowitz can be reached at david.leibowitz(at)pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
