<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-IMPEACH (Washington) _ As the Senate prepares to begin
the second presidential impeachment trial in history, the White
House says President Clinton ``won't spend much time'' thinking
about it and will concentrate on government business. By GREG
McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-ARGUMENTS (Washington) _ With the real start of the
Clinton impeachment trial coming Thursday, we offer a guide to the
key questions and the arguments each side will make about them. By
DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-PROSECUTORS (Washington) _ The 13 House prosecutors who
will begin their impeachment case against President Clinton
Thursday include former U.S. attorneys, county prosecutors and a
judge. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-COLLECTIBLES (Washington) _ As the Senate trial of
President Clinton gets under way, political memorabilia collectors
are scouring for keepsakes. One sought-after item is the ticket
that will be handed out each day to members of the public viewing
the proceedings. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-EMAILS (Washington ) _ The Senate's computer system has
been nearly paralyzed as it tries to cope with a seven-fold
increase in the number of e-mails pouring into lawmakers' offices
on the subject of impeachment. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-CALIF-WELFARE (Washington) _ Supreme Court justices raise
serious questions about a 1996 California law that mandates lower
welfare benefits to newcomers than to more established residents.
By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   HORMEL-AMBASSADOR (Washington) _ A number of senators pledge to
support President Clinton's renewed nomination of gay rights
advocate James Hormel to be ambassador to Luxembourg. Sen. Paul
Wellstone, D-Minn., a leading Senate liberal, says he will fight to
bring it to the floor. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-LEGISLATURE (Austin, Texas) _ State budget writers propose
spending $91.7 billion over the next two years, three-fourths of it
on education. The budget plan, introduced by Sen. Bill Ratliff,
R-Mount Pleasant, and Rep. Rob Junell, D-San Angelo, does not
include money from the state's settlement with the tobacco
companies. By JOHN GONZALEZ.
</P>
<P>
   FOUR-DEAD (Richardson, Texas) _ The ex-husband of a woman shot
and killed her, her mother, her friend and then himself in an
upscale neighborhood of this Dallas suburb. The police say the
couple, who had divorced 15 years ago, had just ended a long court
fight. The woman's 12-year-old son from her current marriage
escaped through a window. By JIM HENDERSON.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-JORDAN-RETIRES (Chicago) _ Saying ``I've had a great time,''
Michael Jordan bids farewell to the game of pro basketball after an
unparalleled 13-year NBA career. By MICHAEL MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-FALLOUT (Chicago) _ At a time when the NBA is already
reeling from labor problems, the league loses its most talented and
popular star in Michael Jordan. A look at where the NBA goes from
here. By MICHAEL MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: BKN-SCENE, BKN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   BOX-TYSON (Las Vegas) _ Eighteen months after leaving the boxing
ring in disgrace, Mike Tyson returns to the sport that he once
dominated this week with a heavyweight fight against South Africa's
Francois Botha. By W.H. STICKNEY.
</P>
