<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1585 &Cx1f; tic-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-201YEAST-RECIPES-AZR &LR;      01-13 2090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-201YEAST-RECIPES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEAST RECIPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX -
</P>
<P>
   French Bread
</P>
<P>
   (From Nancy Johnson, BreadCrafters Bakery &AMP; Cafe)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons fresh or 1 1/2 teaspoons dry yeast
</P>
<P>
   11 1/2 to 12 ounces water (76 to 80 degrees)
</P>
<P>
   2 cups (9 ounces) unbleached bread flour
</P>
<P>
   2 cups (9 ounces) unbleached all-purpose flour, plus additional
flour for the work surface
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, dissolve yeast in 11 ounces of water. In a
separate bowl, mix flours together. (To measure flour, spoon flour
into a 1-cup measuring utensil, then, using the back of a straight
knife or a spatula, sweep the top to level.)
</P>
<P>
   Add 1 cup of flour to the water/yeast mixture and stir
vigorously. Continue adding flour by the 1/2 cup until the mixture
becomes too difficult to stir.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer mixture to a floured work surface and begin kneading
dough by folding it onto itself and then pushing away with the heel
of your hand. Give the dough a one-quarter turn and repeat the fold
and push sequence.
</P>
<P>
   If, after 2 to 3 minutes, dough seems stiff, flatten dough into
a circle and sprinkle with additional water.
</P>
<P>
   After kneading for a few minutes, pick up the dough piece by one
end and slap it down hard onto the work surface several times.
(This helps to develop the gluten in the dough and cuts down the
amount of kneading required.)
</P>
<P>
   1st Rest: Round the dough into a ball, cover lightly with
plastic wrap and let dough rest for 10 to 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   After the rest, flatten dough into a circle and sprinkle with
salt. Knead for 2 to 3 minutes, then repeat picking up dough and
slapping it onto the work surface.
</P>
<P>
   2nd Rest: Again, round the dough into a ball, cover, and let
rest 10 to 15 minutes. After 2nd rest, finish kneading until dough
is smooth and elastic.
</P>
<P>
   1st Rise: Round dough into a ball and place in a deep, narrow
glass or plastic container. Cover container with plastic wrap and
place dough in a draft-free location. Let dough rise until double
in bulk, checking after 60 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2nd Rise: When dough has doubled, deflate it by pressing down in
the center of the mass, then pulling in the outer edges. Turn ball
of dough over and re-cover to let rise a second time _ usually half
the time of the first rising.
</P>
<P>
   After second rise, transfer dough to a lightly floured work
surface and deflate by gently patting dough out with the palms of
the hand.
</P>
<P>
   Divide dough into 2 equal pieces, cover and let rest for 20
minutes before shaping.
</P>
<P>
   To shape: Take a piece of the dough and flatten it into a
circle. Fold the top 1/3 down so that the edge of the dough is in
the center of the circle. Seal the seam with the side of your hand.
Repeat with the bottom 1/3 of the circle and seal again. Fold the
top of the dough piece down to meet the bottom edge of the dough
and seal again with the side of your hand. Turn dough so that the
seam side is on the bottom and gently roll the piece back and forth
on the table, tapering the ends as you roll.
</P>
<P>
   If using a baking stone, place loaves seam-side down on a
lightly floured or cornmeal-dusted sheet of parchment paper that
has been placed on a rimless cookie sheet or on the bottom of an
overturned rimmed cookie sheet. If not using a stone, omit
parchment paper and place loaves directly on a floured or
cornmeal-dusted sheet pan, preferably a perforated pan.
</P>
<P>
   Cover loaves with a clean, damp kitchen towel and let rise in a
draft-free area until 1 1/2 times original size, or until a slight
indentation remains when dough is pressed with a fingertip.
</P>
<P>
   To bake: Turn oven to 450 degrees and place rack in center of
oven. If using a baking stone, place stone on middle rack and let
oven preheat for 30 to 45 minutes. Before baking loaves, slash the
top of each loaf with a sharp serrated knife or a razor blade. Hold
the knife or blade almost horizontal to the surface and cut under
the crust that has formed on the loaf.
</P>
<P>
   Using a spritzer bottle filled with water, quickly spray the
walls and floor of the oven, avoiding the oven light _ it may
break.
</P>
<P>
   If using a baking stone, slide the parchment paper with the
loaves directly onto the stone. If not using a stone, place the
sheet pan onto the middle rack of the oven. Spray again with the
water and quickly shut the door.
</P>
<P>
   Continue misting the oven with water every 2 to 3 minutes during
the first 10 minutes of baking.
</P>
<P>
   Bake until loaves are a rich, golden color and sound hollow when
tapped on the bottom, or until an internal temperature of 200
degrees is reached, about 18 to 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cool for at least 10 minutes before slicing.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 loaves, about 15 servings, or 10 to 12 rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Sponge method: Using the sponge method will give your bread more
character, as the grain has more time to develop flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Working from the same recipe as given above, take 2 cups of the
flour, 8 ounces of water and 1/2 the amount of yeast and place in a
glass or plastic container with enough room to allow the mixture at
least to triple in volume. Stir the flour, water and yeast together
vigorously until a thick, stringy batter known as a sponge forms.
</P>
<P>
   Cover the container with plastic wrap and let sit at room
temperature for 4 to 24 hours before using in the recipe.
</P>
<P>
   To continue with the recipe, scrape the sponge into a large
mixing bowl, add the remaining water and yeast and stir until
frothy. Add the remaining flour, 1/2 cup at a time, until the
mixture becomes too difficult to stir. Then transfer the dough to
your work surface and begin kneading procedure as directed above.
</P>
<P>
   Overnight-Rise method: Using only 1/2 to 3/4 of the amount of
yeast listed, follow the recipe above through the final kneading.
Then place dough into a glass or plastic container that has been
lightly oiled or sprayed. Turn dough ball over so that the surface
is lightly oiled. Cover tightly with plastic wrap and place in your
refrigerator overnight, or until doubled in bulk. Let dough return
to room temperature, about 2 hours, before proceeding with recipe
at the point of dividing the dough.
</P>
<P>
   Variations: Before slashing and baking the loaves, spritz the
surfaces with water and sprinkle the loaves with sesame seeds.
</P>
<P>
   When shaping the loaves, flatten the dough into the circle as
described, then sprinkle with your favorite fresh or dried herbs.
Shape as directed and you will have a swirl of herbs in your
loaves.
</P>
<P>
   Substitute 1/4 cup of whole-wheat flour for some of the
unbleached white flour in the recipe. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Approximate values per serving: 124 calories, trace fat, 0
cholesterol, 26 g carbohydrates, 314 mg sodium, 3 percent calories
from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Whole-Wheat Pizza Crust
</P>
<P>
   (From Peg Rhodes)
</P>
<P>
   1 package active dry yeast
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup warm water (110 to 115 degrees)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups whole-wheat flour
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups unbleached white flour plus 1/2 cup as needed
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Stir yeast and sugar into warm water in a small bowl. Cover and
let stand 5 to 10 minutes, or until yeast is foamy. In the large
bowl of a heavy-duty mixer, stir together 1 1/2 cups each of
whole-wheat and white flour and salt. Make a well in the center.
Pour in oil and dissolved yeast. Beat until dough starts to form a
ball. Remove from bowl and knead on a lightly floured board; add no
more than 1/2 cup white flour to the board if needed. Knead until
smooth and elastic.
</P>
<P>
   Spray inside of a large plastic bag with non-stick coating.
Place dough inside. Press the air out and coil the bag from the
dough all the way to the top. Knot the top. This allows the bag to
spread as the dough expands.
</P>
<P>
   Refrigerate overnight, or 4 to 6 hours. Press dough down if
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   To use: divide into 2 balls. Roll each into an 11-inch circle.
Place on oiled 12-inch pizza pans. Top as desired. Bake in
preheated 450-degree oven 20 minutes, or until bottom is browned.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 pizza crusts, 8 servings each.
</P>
<P>
   Variations: 1) Add 1/2 cup freshly grated Parmesan cheese to
flour mixture.
</P>
<P>
   2) Add 1 tablespoon minced fresh rosemary (or 1 teaspoon dried)
and 1 teaspoon chopped garlic
</P>
<P>
   3) Add 1/4 cup chopped green olives. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Approximate values per serving: 115 calories, 3 g fat, 0
cholesterol, 19 g carbohydrates, 74 mg sodium, 23 percent calories
from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mediterranean Focaccia
</P>
<P>
   (From ``Cooking Light'' magazine)
</P>
<P>
   5 1/4 cups all-purpose flour, divided
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried rosemary, crushed
</P>
<P>
   1 package quick-rise yeast
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups very warm water
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Cooking spray
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup pimento-stuffed olives, halved
</P>
<P>
   1 bottle (7 ounces) roasted red bell peppers, cut into 1/4-inch
strips
</P>
<P>
   Lightly spoon flour into dry measuring cups; level with a knife.
Combine 5 cups flour, cheese, and next 3 ingredients in a food
processor; pulse 2 times, or until blended. With processor on,
slowly add water and 2 tablespoons oil through food chute; process
until dough forms a ball.
</P>
<P>
   Turn dough out onto a lightly floured surface. Knead until
smooth and elastic (about 5 minutes), adding enough of remaining
flour, 1 tablespoon at a time, to prevent dough from sticking.
</P>
<P>
   Place dough in a large bowl coated with cooking spray, turning
to coat top. Cover and let rise in a warm place (85 degrees), free
from drafts, 10 minutes. (Dough will not double in bulk.)
</P>
<P>
   Punch dough down; turn out onto a lightly floured surface.
Divide dough into 12 equal portions, shaping each portion into a
4-inch circle. Place on 2 large baking sheets coated with cooking
spray and dusted with cornmeal. Cover and let rise 40 minutes or
until doubled in bulk.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 450 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Uncover dough. Gently brush dough with 2 teaspoons oil. Make
indentations in top of dough using the handle of a wooden spoon or
your fingertips. Sprinkle with 1/2 teaspoon salt and black pepper;
arrange olives and bell pepper strips as desired on each circle.
Bake at 450 degrees for 20 minutes or until golden. Remove from
baking sheets; cool on wire racks.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings. &QL; 
Approximate values per serving: 261 calories, 6 g fat, 4 mg
cholesterol, 43 g carbohydrates, 20 mg fiber, 8 g protein, 341 mg
sodium, 19 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Whole-Wheat Bread
</P>
<P>
   (From ``Cooking Light'' magazine)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 packages dry yeast (about 4 1/2 teaspoons)
</P>
<P>
   2 cups warm water
</P>
<P>
   3 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups whole-wheat flour, divided use
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   Cooking spray
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sunflower seed kernels
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon quick-cooking oats
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons stick margarine or butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   Dissolve sugar and yeast in warm water in a large bowl; let
stand 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Lightly spoon flours into dry measuring cups; level with a
knife. Stir all-purpose flour, 2 cups whole-wheat flour, vegetable
oil and salt into yeast mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Turn dough out onto a lightly floured surface. Knead until dough
is smooth and elastic (about 8 minutes), adding enough of the
remaining whole-wheat flour, 1 tablespoon at a time, to prevent
dough from sticking.
</P>
<P>
   Place dough in a large bowl coated with cooking spray, turning
to coat top. Cover and let rise in a warm place (85 degrees), free
from drafts, 45 minutes or until doubled in bulk. Punch dough down;
cover dough, and let rest 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Divide dough in half. Working with one portion at a time (cover
remaining dough to keep from drying), roll each portion into a 6-
by 4-inch rectangle on a lightly floured surface. Roll up each
rectangle tightly, starting with a long edge, pressing firmly to
eliminate air pockets; pinch seams and ends to seal. Place rolls,
seam side down, in 2 (8- by 4-inch) loaf pans coated with cooking
spray. Cover and let rise 30 minutes or until doubled in bulk.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Uncover dough. Combine sunflower seed kernels, oats and
margarine; brush over loaves. Bake at 350 degrees for 30 minutes or
until loaves sound hollow when tapped. Remove from pans; cool on
wire racks.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 24 servings (12 slices per loaf). &QL; 
 &QL; 
Approximate values per serving: 132 calories, 3 g fat, 0
cholesterol, 23 g carbohydrates, 22 mg fiber, 4 g protein, 202 mg
sodium, 23 percent calories from fat. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
