<SLUG> BC-201BREADTIPS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINGS BAKERS KNEAD TO KNOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY WALKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Tips for at-home bakers:
</P>
<P>
   - Accurate measurement is so important that it cannot be
overemphasized.
</P>
<P>
   - Use bottled or filtered water in bread recipes if your tap
water is hard.
</P>
<P>
   - Store whole-grain flours, nuts, seeds and other ingredients
that have oil in them in the freezer in airtight containers.
Otherwise, they'll go rancid, which doesn't take long in warm
desert-area pantries.
</P>
<P>
   - Use a pastry scraper (also called a dough scraper or case
knife) to scoop soft dough off the pastry board when you knead.
It's also extremely useful for cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   - If dough tries to spring back to its original shape when
kneading, rolling out for pizza crust or shaping into loaves, let
it rest, covered, for 10 or 15 minutes, so the gluten can relax.
</P>
<P>
   - Instead of ``lightly flouring'' the board before you turn out
dough to shape it, spray your kneading board with non-stick spray.
Spray your hands, too.
</P>
<P>
   - A 1-pound loaf of bread made with 3 cups of flour will bake up
much prettier in a medium-size loaf pan, 8{ by 4{ by 2{ inches,
instead of in a 9- by 5- by 3-inch loaf pan. The loaf will be domed
in the smaller pan, and flat in the larger one.
</P>
<P>
   - How do you tell when dough has risen enough? Press a finger
lightly into the dough. If the indentation remains, the dough has
risen enough. (In loaf pans, for best shape, the dough should be
risen slightly above the edge of the pan.)
</P>
<P>
   - Always preheat the oven, unless the recipe says not to.
</P>
<P>
   - In case your oven has hot spots, rotate and turn loaves during
baking onto different oven racks when you bake more than two
loaves.
</P>
<P>
   - When it comes out of the oven, let bread cool at least 20
minutes before slicing.
</P>
<P>
   - Let bread cool completely on a rack before wrapping for
storage.
</P>
<P>
   - Slice bread before freezing it, if you're going to use it for
breakfast toast. That way, you can remove one slice at a time.
</P>
<P>
   - Doughs can be frozen after the first rise, after they are
punched down. Let doughs thaw to room temperature, then shape and
let rise again before baking. Or bake the bread, then freeze it for
up to three months.
</P>
<P>
   - Specialty tools for bakers abound. Kitchen stores have lots of
things, from pans to dough scrapers to dough buckets marked inside
to let you know how much the dough has risen. More hard-to-locate
items, such as the French lame, a razor-sharp tool for slashing
loaves, are available through The Baker's Catalogue, 800-827-6836,
published by King Arthur Flour in Vermont. The catalog is also an
excellent resource for hundreds of items such as specialty flours,
salts, yeasts, and additives such as diastatic malt powder, a
natural ingredient used in professional bakeries. These people are
devoted to baking, and even produce a fantastic bimonthly
newsletter with recipes. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sources: King Arthur Flour, ``The All-New All-Purpose Joy of
Cooking.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
