<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1602 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRAVES-TARGET-ART-780     01-13 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAVES-TARGET-ART-780(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 FOR THE MALL RATS, A NEW PIPER 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also GRAVES-DESIGN) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By PHIL PATTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Move over, Martha Stewart and Jaclyn Smith. Costing less means
selling more. Or so Michael Graves hopes.
</P>
<P>
   The former poster boy of post-modern architecture is coming out
with a line of kitchen accessories for Target, the discount chain.
By Jan. 27, the first 150 items of the Graves Design Collection
will be on display at Target's 851 stores, priced from $3.99 for a
spatula called the Hipper Flipper to $40 for a toaster whose fluid
shape recalls a Bakelite radio (it's nicknamed ``Toast Modern'') to
an Indonesian-hardwood patio set for $499.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not blessing towels,'' Graves said dismissively of the
comparison with Martha Stewart and K-Mart. ``It is not licensing,
but designing.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the first samples arrived in Graves' own kitchen in
Princeton, N.J. Seeing the finished products for the first time,
the architect picked up a blue-handled garlic press and let his eye
trail over the rotund white electric can opener. A chubby peeler,
Graves said, was ``nice enough to take to bed.'' (A Graves bed with
Graves sheets, ideally, and Graves alarm clock nearby _ though beds
and sheets are not yet items Target has designs on.)
</P>
<P>
   With the Graves Collection, Target is bringing something new to
the giant discount stores on America's exurban strips: it wants to
make an architect's name into a house brand. The time seems right.
People accustomed to a beaming Martha Stewart face on K-Mart
placards are likelier to be ready for a high-design pitch at
Target, where customers have a higher average household income _
around $47,000 _ than in other discounters, and are more likely to
have college degrees. Target also enjoys a reputation for wit and
something like chic. Its ads mingle housewares and clothing: a
dollar and a half of paper clips made into a woman's shirt, a
pleated lampshade turned into a skirt. It is not only in Graves'
Princeton studio that the the company name is pronounced a la
francaise: tar-ZHAY.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Graves, 64, declared himself as proud of the products as of
anything he has ever done. Prouder, presumably, than of the
flamboyant Portland Building, the lavish headquarters for Humana in
Louisville, Ky., or the whimsical Walt Disney World hotel or the
intimate San Juan Capistrano Library.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the better part of the '80s and '90s, Graves was
considered at the cutting edge,'' said Reed Kroloff, the editor in
chief of Architecture magazine. ``But the cutting edge is very
fickle these days, and it's safe to say he is at the cutting edge
no longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, Graves' most singular area of triumph may lie
elsewhere. ``Whatever you think of his architecture,'' Kroloff
continued, ``there is no architect alive who has managed to cross
markets with such success, even in this age of hypermarketing.''
</P>
<P>
   He has designed high-end products for Steuben, Lenox,
Spinneybeck , Swid Powell and Vorwerk; has appeared in magazine
advertising for Dexter shoes and Miele appliances, and then
upgraded the Miele endorsement into a commission to design the
company's headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   In the popular mind, Graves is perhaps best known for his 1985
teakettle for the Italian Alessi company, with its famed bird
whistle: more than 1 million have been sold, at $150. Its U.S.
cousin, for Target, with its reverse-mounted handle and a whistle
like a Cracker Jack prize, set backwards so it also suggests a
pointing finger, will sell for $35.
</P>
<P>
   The two teakettles _ couture versus off-the-rack _ suggest the
difference in the decades: if the '80s were about simple
ostentation, the '90s have brought ostentatious simplicity. Nowhere
is the difference more evident than in the success of discounters
like Target. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Part of Dayton Hudson Corp. of Minneapolis, the number of Target
stores has grown more than tenfold, from 80 a decade ago. Sales,
which totaled $21 billion last year, are growing at about 13
percent a year, according to the company's figures. This year will
bring 65 or so new stores, many in the Northeast, joining recent
openings in College Point, Queens, and West Nyack, N.Y., a company
spokesman said.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving money is chic,'' said Kurt Barnard, who publishes
Barnard's Retail Trend Report, an industry newsletter. Even those
who can afford to pay more go to discounters _ a trend that Barnard
said will bloom as consumers shift their spending from clothing to
products for the home.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Target, which spends an estimated $500 million annually on
advertising and marketing, refused to reveal the size of its
investment in the Graves Collection, but its ambitions are clear:
the kickoff party next Wednesday will be held at the Whitney Museum
of American Art.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Whitney itself is not a site of triumph for Graves. In the
mid-1980s, he produced two ambitious expansion plans for the
museum. Neither was built, thanks largely to opposition from
architects and others who charged that the designs overwhelmed
Marcel Breuer's original modernist building.
</P>
<P>
   But Target planners said they were not conscious of any irony:
``We do not believe most of our guests will know him, but we think
they will recognize great design,'' said Ron Johnson, a vice
president and merchandising manager for home decor.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Company brands seem to be to the '90s what designer names were
for the '80s. Not knowing Graves may be an advantage.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Target is counting on the designs to catch the shopper's eye.
The Graves kitchen appliances and utensils share a palette of
colors _ blue handles and yellow and red knobs _ and a vocabulary
of forms based on an elongated egg shape: this is reassuring
off-the-shelf taste.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Target wants to sell Graves as a '90s brand like Bodum, whose
housewares the company introduced with great success in 1997, or
like Calphalon, whose cookware the stores will also soon begin
selling at prices 10 percent below those of Williams-Sonoma. The
company is locked in a battle with other chains called ``big box''
stores because they are housed in huge, windowless cinderblock
piles on the malls of America. Nabbing Graves accords with Target's
longterm strategy of seeking products its competitors don't have.
``A Target exclusive'' is a recurrent phrase in its catalogs.
Without this cachet the only thing to compete on is price _ and
even Target's roster of 851 stores cannot match Wal-Mart's 3,000
and K-Mart's 2,300. The casualties of such wars are all along the
strips: Bradlees and Caldor's are operating in Chapter 11; Janeway
is gone.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When it is suggested to the architect that Target customers may
even think Michael Graves is an invented figure like Betty Crocker,
he is unfazed.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The company's relationship with Graves began after Target
pitched in $6 million for the renovation of the Washington Monument
and asked him to do an elegant scaffolding. With his professed
admiration for ancient shapes, he conceived of the scaffold as a
second, larger obelisk, to keep the monument visible. It also made
Target's involvement more visible.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While working on it, Graves met Johnson of Target's home decor
division. ``We've been knocking you off for years,'' Graves recalls
Johnson saying, ``so why not go right to the source?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Afterwards, they went to a Target store, where Johnson asked for
advice. Graves offered to put yellow Post-It notes on all the
products whose design his office could improve. Johnson worried
there might not be enough Post-Its. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But what struck Graves most was an exquisite $18 glass vase that
he saw again a few days later on Madison Avenue for $180. ``That
told me something about the purchasing power of 850 stores,''
Graves recalled.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Graves products are manufactured by long-time Target
suppliers like Black &AMP; Decker and Miro and meet the down-to-earth
functional requirements of Middle America. Even the design language
_ they are being promoted as a ``family of objects'' _ suggests
family values, even family relations, made flesh: the pepper
grinder, for example, looks like the offspring of the blender.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started with the notion that most of the things in the
kitchen you touch,'' said Graves. ``When you pick up a spatula you
want to touch a cool handle and know that it will feel good. These
things are not so abstracted as modernist design objects where you
don't know which end to pick up.''
</P>
<P>
   About a year ago, Graves read a survey of architects and
designers talking about the perfect shape. Someone cited the egg.
The hemispheric shape ``is easy to recognize as something you want
to touch, whether on a teapot or spatula or garlic press,'' Graves
said. ``We also colored them similarly. There's the metaphor of
blue for cool on a handle versus red for, say, the whistle of the
teakettle.'' The same cues exist in the Alessi teakettle.
</P>
<P>
   The egg may even subliminally suggest nurture. This is a more
mellow, less grave Graves: the references to Thebes are left on the
patio _ in the outdoor furniture. The culture of inspiration here
seems to be mid-century Middle America Art Deco and moderne _
Dreyfuss toasters or mixers of the 1940s and 1950s. The handles
recall the enameled wooden utensils sold at Woolworth's half a
century ago.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Graves has lived with such items. ``I shopped at flea
markets and found multicolored plates and bone-handled flatware,''
he said. ``I had a half-moon shaped Sunbeam toaster with a little
light and chrome strips. All this was in my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The appliances reflect an era of informality and avoid all sense
of the weight of the precious and the collectible. They are to
Sunbeam mixers as the cartoon cars in ``Roger Rabbit'' are to the
real thing. The kettle looks like a Keystone Cop directing traffic;
its whistle sounds like a train's. If there is anything '90s about
the objects it is this: they seem made for kitchens increasingly
used as de facto family rooms.
</P>
<P>
   But there are problems. The kettle's egglike handle is awkward,
steam can lift the lid, and the removable whistle is almost too hot
to handle.
</P>
<P>
   Kroloff of Architecture magazine, said: ``Graves' designs have a
comfortable, timeless quality and widespread appeal. They look like
design.''
</P>
<P>
   But will they become collectibles for Everyshopper in Cordova,
Tenn., or Mason City, Iowa? To urge buyers on, Target has conceived
of a special teakettle billboard that will emit real steam. Look
for egg-shaped designer puffs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
