<HEADER>
A1606 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNABOMBER-FUND-HNS &LR;      01-13 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNABOMBER-FUND-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNABOMBER RELATIVES DONATE REWARD TO HELP CRIME VICTIMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: California, Connecticut, Illinois, Michigan, New Jersey, New
York, Tennessee and Utah)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAY JOCHNOWITZ  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _20In an effort to avoid a potentially huge tax
bill, David Kaczynski will establish a special fund for crime
victims with $535,000 of the $1 million he received for turning in
his brother, convicted Unabomber Theodore Kaczynski.
</P>
<P>
   David Kaczynzki of Schenectady, N.Y., unveiled the new ``Unabom
Survivors Fund'' on Monday. It will be managed by an Albany-based
charity that administers some $18 million for individuals,
businesses, foundations and other nonprofit organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The Unabom fund is designed to satisfy Internal Revenue Service
rules that would otherwise have required David Kaczynski to pay
about a third of the reward in income taxes _ along with gift taxes
each time he gave out donations of more than $20,000, lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   The fund, according to the foundation that will manage it, will
be tax-exempt and help victims of violent crimes committed by
paranoid schizophrenics, but only in the seven states in which the
Unabomber struck, and only over the years in which he was active _
1978 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
   If the money were used only for the Unabomber's victims, it
wouldn't be eligible for tax-exempt status, tax lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   The Community Foundation for the Capital Region, which will
manage the fund, will open applications to victims of criminal
paranoid schizophrenics in California, Connecticut, Illinois,
Michigan, New Jersey, Tennessee and Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Kaczynski said $465,850 of the $1 million federal reward will
pay his brother's legal fees and taxes on the taxable portion of
the reward.
</P>
<P>
   Kaczynski, a social worker, and his wife, Linda Patrik, a
philosophy professor at Union College in Schenectady, still face
legal bills of their own. They plan to pay them, they said Tuesday,
from an anticipated book or movie based on their life story.
</P>
<P>
   Anything left over, they said, will also go to victims, but, she
added without giving details, ``It's much less than you would
imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaczynski and Patrik in 1996 became suspicious that his
reclusive brother, living then in a Montana cabin, was the
Unabomber after his 35,000-word manifesto on the evils of
technology was published in The Washington Post. Through an
attorney, they approached the FBI about their suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   Theodore Kaczynski, whose bombing spree claimed three lives and
injured 29 others, is serving multiple life sentences.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a terrible tragedy,'' David Kaczynski said of
his brother's crimes. ``We're one step closer to having some
closure and resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Insisting they never wanted to profit personally from the
Unabomber's crimes, Kaczynski and Patrik last year worked with Sen.
Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-New York, to insert a provision in a
$500 million spending bill that would allow them to give the entire
$1 million reward to victims, tax free. ``We always wanted as much
money as possible to go to the victims,'' Patrik said.
</P>
<P>
   But their effort failed in the final days of last year's
congressional session.
</P>
<P>
   Patrik said she hoped the money would go in particular to the
families of those who died _ Thomas Mosser, a New Jersey public
relations executive, Gilbert Murray, a California timber industry
executive, and Hugh Scrutton, a California computer dealer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
