<SLUG> BC-CIR-BORDER-WAR-DUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELECTRONIC DOGS GUARD AIRPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By VERNE G. KOPYTOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It does not bark, wag its tail or scratch when sniffing for
drugs and explosives at the nation's airports and border crossings.
Rather, this device flashes a red light when it has detected
contraband and, on a display screen, tells what kind.
</P>
<P>
   Call them electronic dogs. These suitcase-size instruments are
increasingly being used to stop drug smugglers from entering the
country and terrorists from blowing up airplanes. They check for
prohibited materials without tiring, drooling or pawing at the
public.
</P>
<P>
   More properly called particle detectors or trace detectors,
these devices are perhaps best known from their use in airports.
They work on the principle that explosives, and the people who
handle them, leave traces of the stuff on much of what they come in
contact with.
</P>
<P>
   ``The word on the street was that canines were 100 times better
than the detectors,'' said Tony Fainberg, director of civilian
aviation policy for the Federal Aviation Administration. ``But now
we believe that the detectors are about equal, and in some cases,
better.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency's detectors, which are set to search only for
explosives, are located inside airport terminals next to the X-ray
machines. To use the devices, security guards usually wipe the
handle of carry-on luggage with a piece of cloth to pick up
microscopic particles.
</P>
<P>
   The cloth is then placed inside the detector and heated to make
the particles that were absorbed turn to vapor. Within seconds, the
instrument can tell whether that vapor contains any traces of a
dangerous substance.
</P>
<P>
   Some detectors rely on a different method to operate: security
guards use a tiny vacuum cleaner to suck the air around baggage.
</P>
<P>
   According to Fainberg, trace detectors are generally sensitive
enough to detect nitroglycerin on the luggage of passengers who are
taking it in medication for heart conditions. Alerts have also been
triggered by military and police personnel who work in demolition.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1997, the FAA has installed 327 trace detectors at the
nation's airports. Fainberg said that the goal was to have
detectors at every terminal.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for using this technology, he said, is that
explosives do not always show up on X-ray machines. He added that
while the FAA did still sometimes use dogs, the animals needed
frequent breaks, were not efficient in checking a large volume of
passengers and were considered by some to be intrusive.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the FAA has yet to find any actual bombs using the
detectors, said Rebecca Trexler, a spokeswoman for the agency.
Rather, she said the technology serves as a deterrent and is in
place just in case someone does try to smuggle explosives aboard a
plane.
</P>
<P>
   Other agencies like the Customs Service and the Coast Guard also
use particle detectors. But unlike the FAA agents, they search for
drugs as well as explosives, often by wiping steering wheels,
travel documents and door handles.
</P>
<P>
   Customs has had some modest success in detecting drugs with the
technology, according to Robert Armstrong, the agency's director of
research and development. However, he said that inspectors have yet
to find a bomb using a detector.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, no technology can guarantee that contraband will be
found discovered every time, Armstrong said. Smugglers often try to
circumvent detection, he said, by wearing rubber gloves, packing
drugs in plastic, and not letting the person who carries the load
ever touch it directly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is 100 percent,'' he said, and added that efforts at
evasion like wrapping illegal substances in thick plastic wrap
could make smugglers more vulnerable to other technologies, like
x-rays or send them searching for other routes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
