<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-EDUCATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS TRIMS SAILS ON SCHOOL REFORMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Lawmakers and lobbyists listening to Gov.
Gray Davis lately are finding that several education policies he
was promoting during last year's campaign somehow have vanished.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed policies were dropped or rewritten either because
of pressure from the powerful California Teachers Association, or
because of new laws signed during the campaign, a lack of money in
the state budget, or just common-sense advice from Davis' new
education advisers.
</P>
<P>
   During the campaign, Davis said school districts should
reimburse colleges and universities for the cost of teaching basic
English and math to incoming students. Those students, he reasoned,
should have learned the subjects before they entered college. That
plan has vanished.
</P>
<P>
   Contracts should be required between parents and teachers, the
campaigning Davis said, to encourage more interest from home. But
in his State of the State address, Davis said he would ``urge''
school districts to require the contracts, which all school boards
have the option of installing.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, during the campaign, pledged to force the lowest
performing 10 percent of schools to create a partnership with a
community college or university to improve instruction. Now, Davis
wants community colleges to issue report cards on failing schools
and create reading-development partnerships with elementary and
secondary schools.
</P>
<P>
   And Davis' campaign idea to require a certain amount of homework
from students _ so specific that kindergartners were to be given 15
minutes of homework a night _ has disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any reasonable person who becomes governor,'' said Kevin
Gordon, assistant executive director of the California School
Boards Association, ``looks at how pragmatic some of the ideas were
on the campaign trail, and also how they were received, and then
decides what to disregard and what to go with.''
</P>
<P>
   Generally, school lobbyists and Democratic lawmakers have
embraced Davis' comprehensive education package, which includes
increased teacher training, tougher graduation requirements, more
reading programs and more scrutiny of failing schools.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers have been impressed with the task force Davis
appointed, after taking office earlier this month, to look at
proposals to overhaul public education. They also are impressed
with the appointment of former state Sen. Gary Hart, an education
reformer for many years, as the new education secretary.
</P>
<P>
   The Davis administration said some of the reforms had been
delayed because of money problems. The state faces a $2.3 billion
deficit, which has forced Davis to cut back on his ambitious $3
billion program to buy new textbooks.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has called a special session of the Legislature to tackle
his education program. Davis spokesman Michael Bustamante said
voters should expect more from the new governor, including,
perhaps, some of the reforms that appeared to have vanished after
the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only about three minutes into the first quarter,''
Bustamante said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans worry that Davis is too quickly succumbing to
pressure from the California Teachers Association, a major Davis
campaign contributor, particularly when it comes to the ability of
school districts to fire teachers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail and even in his inaugural address, Davis
was tough on teachers, saying: ``They will get better, or they will
be encouraged to find another line of work.'' But in his State of
the State address, Davis said he wanted a system in which a teacher
was reviewed by a more experienced colleague.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the teacher receives an unfavorable review,'' Davis said,
``he or she will be given an opportunity to improve. But if there's
no improvement after an appropriate period of time, the results ...
will be conveyed to the local school board.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not enough for Assembly Republican Leader Rod Pacheco of
Riverside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned,'' Pacheco said, ``if you're talking about
broken promises, about his apparent retreat on accountability. He
said we are going to crack down on teachers and principals who are
incompetent.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Davis' campaign promises may have been jettisoned
because they just didn't seem logical.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that failing school districts should pay the California
State University system for educating incoming students with poor
English and math scores has two problems.
</P>
<P>
   It's the California State system, after all, that trains the
vast majority of California teachers. If they are producing
teachers who are producing failing students, then why should the
CSU system be reimbursed for their failures? And making failing
school districts pay more money from their already thin budgets
seems counter-productive.
</P>
<P>
   The Davis homework requirement, lawmakers say, may have suffered
from overkill. School districts constantly complain about state
mandates, preferring block-grant checks from Sacramento instead of
one-size-fits-all laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a certain point, we do need to draw the line between state
mandates and local control,'' said Assembly Education Committee
Chairwoman Kerry Mazzoni, D-San Rafael. ``I would really hesitate
to see the state micro-manage that much.''
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, Davis' proposed education reforms on the campaign
trail were already being discussed in the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail Davis demanded an end to ``social
promotion,'' the practice of advancing students a grade level even
though they are failing. There wasn't a single word about social
promotion in Davis' education-laden State of the State address.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps for good reason: Former Gov. Pete Wilson, a Republican,
signed a measure last year that requires students to meet minimum
academic requirements before they can move up to the next grade.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has not abandoned student accountability. The new governor
is proposing a rigorous state-mandated test in order to graduate
from high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has not shied away from student responsibility,'' Gordon
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gordon said he had noticed a subtle change in Davis'
rhetoric as soon as he was sworn in. Davis listed many proposals
during his inaugural address but offered this caveat up front:
``What matters is whether the idea is right or wrong _ and whether
it will work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
