<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1680 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOLK-ART-2TAKES-NYT     01-13 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOLK-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORK IN A FOLK HERO'S ROAD
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (bl) 
By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Among the sleek seals swimming through Christie's New
York last Thursday, with their fur coats, thin watches, Italian
loafers and winter tans, appeared John Gordon, wrapped in a wool
scarf, wearing suede bucks and an imitation beaver-skin coat _ like
a piece of folk Americana miscatalogd in a European sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fake,'' he said of his coat, as if to establish his
credibility quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, 72, a preeminent folk Americana dealer who retired eight
years ago, was at the auction house to observe the installation of
the 1,352 lots of his own collection, an important view of an
unusual field, being offered Thursday and on Tuesday. The estimate
for the sale is $1.3 million to $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon has been buying, selling and more than occasionally
keeping non-Native American, nonacademic American arts and crafts,
or folk Americana, for 50 years: whirligigs, rattles, rugs,
pottery, paintings, sculpture, furniture and other items.
</P>
<P>
   There are 38 weather vanes in the sale. ``In Europe's Catholic
countries, it's invariably a rooster,'' he said. ``Association with
Christ. The day the cock crowed. Here, name a subject, you've got
it in a weather vane: peacocks, locomotives. I've got a cow jumping
over the moon.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon has watched the market for folk Americana make the same
surprising leap from an eccentric, undervalued taste, restricted to
a few rich collectors like Henry duPont and Dr. Alfred Barnes, to a
star-powered, crowd-pleasing auction commodity. Gordon has sold
items to the Rockefellers and Andy Warhol. Since buying his first
piece, a $3 pie plate, as an art student in his 20s, he has set
records, including the $26,500 he paid in 1977 for a Shaker trestle
table, since resold.
</P>
<P>
   After a disastrous crash in the late 1980s, much like that for
contemporary art, the market for folk Americana has made a steady
march back to health, in part because of the interest in outsider
art, which is drawing new excitement to the field. Sotheby's
Americana sale Saturday and Sunday includes 57 lots of outsider
art. Gordon's collection has several examples, including two
drawings by Bill Traylor.
</P>
<P>
   More to the point, Gordon and his wife, Leah, have lived over
the years in a New York apartment and two houses in Massachusetts
with an expanding body of impressive bric-a-brac that now _ 10
truckloads later _ sits at Christie's. ``You're not going to find
my bed here, but they do have my chest of drawers,'' he said,
gesturing to a scrolled-foot, yellow-painted piece with a flowered
front. Not a problem. ``My wife hated it.''
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to believe that Gordon understands his visiting
privileges will end. He lifted an 18th-century Windsor chair off a
podium to sit on while talking, and offered a figured maple Queen
Anne as though he were at home and not in a room being set up for a
preview.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has nine spindles,'' he said of the Windsor's fanned back,
``which is scarce. It reflects the work of a master craftsman.
Normally, there are seven or less.'' Gordon settled in. ``The
American Windsor is a marvel of comfort.''
</P>
<P>
   He sat with a carved gray gull in his lap, its head nested back
on its wing as though Gordon had lulled it to sleep by stroking the
wood. He held the gull to his nose. ``It's camphor wood, so we know
the wood came from China,'' he said, holding it out. The air
suddenly smelled as though someone had opened a spice box. ``It was
made as a cap for a masthead, as luck for the sailors.''
</P>
<P>
   As a young collector, Gordon began dealing on the side. Later,
as a dealer, he began collecting on the side. Hattie Brunner, a
pioneer Pennsylvania Dutch folk Americana dealer and one of
Gordon's mentors, told him that being close to something was the
only way to learn about it. So Gordon told his wife that they would
keep what they liked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty-five years ago, you couldn't sell the stuff,'' he said.
``You couldn't mark it up more than 5 percent. Rather than quit the
business, I started selecting things for us to live with and to
enjoy.'' It improved Gordon's game.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon had witnessed the lesson as a young man, at the hand of
another mentor, Barnes. ``He began, in his house, associating
pieces from the Pennsylvania Dutch country with work by major
artists,'' Gordon said, ``placing dower chests under paintings by
Renoir. It proved art from any culture, any time, could have
value.'' Years later, Gordon repeated the experiment himself,
taking an Andy Warhol ``Marilyn'' painting on approval in exchange
for the balance on a bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hung it in my living room with an Edward Hicks,'' Gordon
said, referring to the artist discovered and made famous as folk
Americana. ``You know what? It held up.'' It hangs in Gordon's
newly empty bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Though now part of the canon of collecting, folk Americana has
been a hard sell and a subject of controversy. The largely
anonymous material has lived by its wits and its charm, the
suppositions of scholarship and the attributions of the market, not
by the sureties of dated signatures that verify other genres of
art.
</P>
<P>
   There are 21 attributions in the John Gordon collection, in
addition to many items described as probably or possibly by various
artists, schools or of various regions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can say who it's by, you can charge more for it,'' said
Jack Lindsey, curator of American decorative art at the
Philadelphia Museum of Art. Lindsey was asked by Christie's to
comment on the Pennsylvania Germanic pottery, a feature of Gordon's
collection. The ``fugitive nature of proof,'' he said, haunts the
category of folk Americana.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that, it has stayed popular with a public that responds
to both its nostalgia and its patriotism. Much of Gordon's force as
a dealer has been in mapping America as an uncollected, uncharted
country. As a collector, Gordon formed an idiosyncratic view of his
subject _ the subject itself was idiosyncratic: face vessels,
walking sticks, rummers, flags constructed from pop-tops. He
collected 18th-, 19th- and 20th-century examples, using his own eye
as much as provenance or scarcity.
</P>
<P>
   Paul D'Ambrosio, the chief curator of the New York State
Historical Association at Cooperstown, said he thought that range
was the strength of Gordon's vision. ``Very few people collect both
19th and 20th century,'' he said. ``There's a lot to be gained by
seeing the two together.''
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Pennington, editor of Maine Antique Digest, said the
broadness of the mixture worked against the collection's interest.
``There are some great things, some not great things in there,''
Pennington said. ``Any time you have a sale of a dealer's
collections, it's going to be a big mixed bag.''
</P>
<P>
   Have there been wild goose chases? Not to hear Gordon tell it.
There was the dower chest, one of five in the sale, that he bought
from a man named Smitty, a funeral director and postman in
Pennsylvania, who didn't easily let Gordon into his house and
thought the chest was French. Gordon recognized the stencils as the
work of Moses Eaton Jr., one of the most-renowned 19th-century New
England decorators.
</P>
<P>
   There was the weather vane he had to copy for the firemen to get
the rare original off the firehouse roof. There was the widow he
drank tea with until three in the morning to get her late husband's
pair of John Brewster Jr. paintings. ``I think she got tired,''
Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   In conversation, Gordon digresses like the county roads that
have revealed treasure for him. Where will the road take the
ex-collector next, now that America has been discovered and
consigned? ``Here's a secret,'' he said. ``I collect other things:
Japanese prints, School of Paris paintings, German Expressionist
prints.''
</P>
<P>
   Having an empty house might mean the chance to fill it. ``Who
knows if I won't see a piece and go nuts over it?'' Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 1653EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
