<HEADER>
A1700 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-THEATER-WEBSITES-     01-13 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-THEATER-WEBSITES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTING A SPOTLIGHT ON THEATERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As William Shakespeare observed in ``As You Like It,'' all the
world's a stage _ but these days it helps to have some idea of
exactly where to find the good stuff. The American Theater Web
(www.americantheaterweb.com) is helping to do just that, providing
links and listings in one convenient place for over 1,000 theaters
across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The site's eventual goal is to list as many Web sites from
American non-profit performing arts groups as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Web surfers in the mood for a little drama can search for
playhouses by either an alphabetical listing of theater names or by
city and state. For each entry on the site, there is a summary of
the theater company's work and productions, along with a link to
that theater's own Web site for more detailed information.
</P>
<P>
   The range of organizations found on the site is impressive _
everything from small community theaters in Utah to the famed Arena
Stage in Washington. Although the big commercial houses of Broadway
are not on the site, links to several dozen non-profit drama
companies in New York City are listed.
</P>
<P>
   The American Theater Web, which now averages 175 hits a day,
went on line last fall and has been growing steadily. The site's
creators are constantly on the lookout for new links, and one or
two theaters a week have been sending in the URLs for their home
pages for inclusion on the site.
</P>
<P>
   Using keywords, the American Theater Web site can be searched to
the surfer's own tastes. The site also has monthly groupings of
shows going up nationwide, and many theaters also list all their
productions for the current season. A message board for theater
professionals and other interested parties to exchange notes, ideas
and information is also a popular area of the site.
</P>
<P>
   The American Theater Web was created as a non-profit venture,
but its creator, Andrew Propst, said he was looking for a corporate
sponsor to help enhance it. ``Should this sponsorship be gained,''
he wrote by e-mail, ``the first expansion that we would like to
have take place is the creation of a server where smaller theaters
can place their Web pages.''
</P>
<P>
   Many smaller theaters use free Web space on America Online or
Geocities, but the Web addresses tend to get a bit unmemorable and
unwieldy. ``A URL of `http://americantheaterweb.com/publictheater,'
provided free of charge, we believe would be much more valuable for
the theater as it attempts to reach new audiences through the
Web,'' Propst said.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the site is offering to design Web pages, at no charge,
for a limited number of non-profit theaters that need them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the sponsorship search continues, the site is growing and
adding new features. In addition to more theaters submitting their
Web addresses for inclusion, the American Theater Web has a new
section called ``American Theater in the News'' devoted to feature
articles and reviews of productions from newspapers with online
sites, as well as stories of general interest to theatergoers.
</P>
<P>
   With this site, all the Web's a stage. And if by any chance your
appetite has now been whetted for a performance of ``As You Like
It,'' the site lists upcoming versions of the popular Elizabethan
comedy, including the Alabama Shakespeare's Festival's production
running from March 9 to July 25, 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
