<HEADER>
A1721 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRAVES-DESIGN-NYT &LR;      01-13 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAVES-DESIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAVES' PROGRESS FROM PAPER VISIONS TO GIANT TEAKETTLES 
</HEADLINE>
  (With GRAVES-TARGET) 
(js) 
 By HERBERT MUSCHAMP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At last, there is reason to hope that the Whitney Museum of
American Art may be casting off its reputation for trendiness. In
what may be seen, fairly or not, as a defining moment in the early
tenure of the Whitney's new director, Maxwell Anderson, the museum
has rented its premises next Tuesday evening for the unveiling of a
new line of houseware accessories and furniture designed for Target
stores by the American architect Michael Graves.
</P>
<P>
   Few architects today are less trendy than Graves. In the early
1980s, he was a trend beyond compare, an architect who designed
shopping bags for Bloomingdale's, a trophy cup for the style awards
presented by GQ magazine, a Fifth Avenue boutique for Diane Von
Furstenberg. Today, he is regarded by many as a stale trend:
yesterday's bag. And in these fast-paced times, a stale trend is
virtually ancient history.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Graves' appearance at the Whitney has the aura of an
archeological excavation. As the historically minded may recall,
Graves is the architect who designed an addition to the Whitney
Museum in 1985. The overbearing composition, a neo-classical
ziggurat that reduced Marcel Breuer's building to a black
cornerstone, roused wide public opposition, was twice revised and
was eventually abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   The outcry belied the conventional wisdom that controversy
boosts an artist's career. Though Graves has continued to prosper
as a builder, in the last 15 years his work has largely fallen off
the map of critical appreciation. This may be partly attributed to
a fickle press, which creates stars and then contrives to dim their
luster. But it's also true that his later work did not live up to
the promise of his early vision.
</P>
<P>
   The architect made his first reputation in the late 1970s with a
series of drawings on yellow tracing paper, which offered a
powerful new vision of urban America in the late 20th century. The
Fargo-Moorehead Cultural Center Bridge project, designed in 1977,
remains a powerful image of its time, although the design was never
executed.. But it also suggested that the post-modern movement was
creatively inspired, not the reactionary force it would become.
</P>
<P>
   It was with mounting disappointment, therefore, that some of
Graves' admirers acknowledged the awful truth disclosed by his
progression into full-scale building: the quality of his drawings
did not translate into architecture. Some fundamental talent for
space-making was glaringly absent and could not be concealed by the
swags, festoons, urns and other devices on which the architect
increasingly came to depend.
</P>
<P>
   Graves has written of his childhood encounters with Paul Cret's
neo-classical civic buildings in his native Midwest, and what
continues to be winning about his drawings is that they offer a
child's garden of classicism, immense, imposing buildings viewed
from the perspective of a child going off to explore the terrors
and wonders of the American downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Graves' drawings for the Portland Building, his first major
public commission, were wonderfully young-eyed, but when the
project was completed in 1982, it became painfully clear that this
quality had not survived the translation from drawing to building.
Nor was there any compensation in the imaginative use of space. The
result resembled some grotesque, architectural version of Alice
after she telescopes out into the giant of Wonderland.
</P>
<P>
   The Portland Building could be defended as a young architect's
learning experience, if an immensely conspicuous and expensive one.
But subsequent projects only confirmed that the strength of Graves'
vision relied on the essentially graphic virtues of architectural
drawings: the tentativeness of line, the atmospheric use of color
and, yes, even the background tone, at once sunny and mournful, of
the tracing paper.
</P>
<P>
   As Graves' celebrity ballooned, so did the extravagant claims he
made for his architecture. In one essay, he said he was restoring
the connection between mankind and landscape allegedly shattered by
the modern movement. Those traveling to La Jolla, Calif., can see
for themselves the absurdity of this notion. At the Salk Institute,
Louis I. Kahn, a modern architect, created one of the most sublime
landscapes in the world. A few miles up the road squats the
Aventine, a mixed-use development that Graves designed in 1985. The
buildings occupy the land with less sensitivity than the highway
that glides serenely past them.
</P>
<P>
   The pleasant surprise is that Graves' designs for Target stores
reverse the disenchantment with his architecture. At first, the
idea of them seemed like a bad memory. The '80s rise again! More
architect's baubles! But this resistance swiftly melts, because the
objects have such pleasingly cheap charm. They are not great design
on the level of work by Ettore Sottsass, Philippe Starck or Shiro
Kuramata. Nor are they uniformly elegant. But they do possess the
childish quality that has animated Graves' drawings.
</P>
<P>
   Enlargement of scale works to the designer's advantage here.
Graves' teakettle is large enough to boil lobsters in. His
two-slice toaster looks big enough to mix, knead and bake two small
loaves of bread. At a time when design is dominated by an
increasing trend toward miniaturization, these bloated objects are
comically perverse.
</P>
<P>
   The Target designs also illuminate an underlying philosophical
contradiction that has weakened many of Graves' buildings. Like
other post-modernists, he imagines himself a classicist, but the
infantile strain in his work places him firmly in the romantic
tradition. Deliberate regression, to use Robert Harbison's phrase,
is a hallmark of the romantic movement, and so is the craving for
novelty that the Target products are clearly designed to satisfy.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing unsound with being a romantic classicist _ it's
a style of distinguished historical pedigree. And the tension
between Graves' classical ambitions and his romantic sensibility
could be a source of strength if he allowed his sensibility freer
reign. As he evidently did in unearthing these playful artifacts
from within his richly fertile mind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
