<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1725 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAMPTON-ANTIQUES-ART-     01-13 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAMPTON-ANTIQUES-ART-1050(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 THE TORCHERE IS PASSED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By PATRICIA LEIGH BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like extremely rare gilt side chairs and exceptional
Louis XV what's-its, the late decorator Mark Hampton was a fixture
at the Winter Antiques Show. He could invariably be spotted at the
cavernous entrance to the Seventh Regiment Armory, one prestigious
client or another hanging on both his words and his pinstriped
Savile Row suits with twin vents.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, who died at 58 in July, was known for his erudition as
well as an A-list of clients that included George and Barbara Bush,
Anne Bass, Carter and Susan Burden and Pamela Harriman. He left
behind his wife, Duane, two daughters, Alexa, 27, and Kate, 30, and
hundreds of watercolors of interiors, including those of his own
design, some 40 of which will be on display in his stead at the
show, opening Friday. Later this month, there will be a tribute to
Hampton at Blair House, which he redecorated with Mario Buatta, and
a second show of watercolors will open at the New York School of
Interior Design on April 8.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton's passion for painting _ especially while on the
telephone _ was such that his beer would sometimes turn blue from
the paintbrush he dipped absent-mindedly in the wrong glass. He was
constantly sketching, and the walls of the family's Park Avenue
apartment are filled with archly rendered watercolors: Duane as
Venus on the half shell in workout clothes; Kate dancing
Astaire-style with her father, his bald spot in full bloom.
</P>
<P>
   This week, as the watercolors of idealized interiors were being
bubble-wrapped, Hampton's widow and daughters gathered on the
18th-century four-poster bed found for them by their friend the
duchess of Marlborough and remembered Hampton, periodically
resorting to balled-up Kleenex. Though their loss was still fresh,
the subject at hand was the news that Alexa, who worked with her
father from the time she was in high school, is taking over the
creative reins of Mark Hampton Inc. Although Duane technically owns
the firm and will be its ``figurehead,'' as she put it, Alexa will
forge its path.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an incredible legacy, and a great comfort to keep Daddy's
memory going,'' Ms. Hampton said, her gravelly voice betraying
tobacco. ``We've been doing this forever, but we've lost our
mentor.'' She paused. ``I realize I'll be judged by his standards,
possibly unfavorably.''
</P>
<P>
   His standards were legendary, even within the fussy sphere of
decorating. Two days before he died, Ms. Hampton visited him in the
hospital, carrying a legal pad, blueprints and drawings of
moldings. He corrected their shape in shaky scrawl and expressed
dismay that she'd brought a pencil instead of a pen.
</P>
<P>
   Though Ms. Hampton worked side by side with her father, she has
a delicate balancing act ahead, as she aims both to keep her
father's lifelong clients and to reposition the firm for a younger
generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alexa has been grooming herself,'' said Alan Tanksley, 39, a
Manhattan decorator and family friend, who worked at the firm in
the 1980s. ``She admired her father's passion and style and has
emulated that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, who was best known for an understated traditionalism,
was a native of Plainfield, Ind., but seemed a lifelong citizen of
style. He dated his own career from the moment when, at 13, he
precociously refinished the walnut shutters of his bedroom. In a
eulogy, his Michigan law school roommate, Charles Eisendraft,
recalled his shock at first entering their dorm room to ``a huge
splay of freshly cut rhododendron,'' three porphyry obelisks and
``little boxes all over the place, not one of them containing
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Like her father, who abandoned law school to study art history,
Ms. Hampton studied at the Institute of Fine Arts at New York
University (apres Spence and Brown). Her under-600-square-foot
apartment, substantially smaller than the family manse in
Southampton, was featured in Elle Decor in the fall. Her father
would sooner have lived with his back to the window than use bamboo
blinds from Manhattan Shade and Glass (``I couldn't afford
curtains''), and would never have displayed ``a Lucite cube I
begged Gracious Home to sell me.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of her strategy will be to go after the moneyed children of
her father's clients _ young people not so unlike herself, a young
woman who spent her 16th birthday with her father at the Prado.
Among her current projects are the downtown loft of Carter Burden
Jr. and his wife, Charmaine, and Belle Burden's apartment on the
Upper East Side. ``A lot of younger people love what our parents
had but maybe don't want to be so traditional,'' Ms. Hampton
explained. ``It took years for our parents to know what they
wanted. We have fewer layers, and we're less wedded to being
rigorously partial to one particular period.''
</P>
<P>
   With her friends, she is often ``an anti-decorator decorator,''
she said, adding: ``I sometimes tell them: `Don't do it _ buy it
later. How much money do you want to invest in a look when you're
only 27?' '' She seems to resist decorating the apartment of her
sister, Kate, an actress off-Broadway. ``She's insisting that the
particleboard has to stay,'' she said with brow-furrowing
disapproval.
</P>
<P>
   In the often catty world of decorating, where rumors sprout
whiskers, the entry of a younger Hampton into the business is being
greeted with some degree of skepticism, though many wish her luck.
``Is she going to Kennebunkport to plan the future of the Bush
empire?'' said a publicity agent in the decorating business, who
insisted on anonymity. ``You don't get there by reading history
books.''
</P>
<P>
   While her mother retains the links with the old guard _ jetting
off to visit long-term clients ``whose hands need to be held,'' in
Tanksley's words _ all three Hampton women (Kate works a day job in
the office) are keenly aware of Hampton's mystique, ``assessing how
to place themselves as a newly formed design entity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It's an emotionally tricky task. ``I have no interest in defying
his style,'' Alexa said of her father, whom she more than
fleetingly resembles. ``I think he was, and is, a genius.''
</P>
<P>
   At Hickory Chair, for whom Hampton designed a West Indian
rope-turned bed and other historically based furniture, Hampton
style will continue to be sold. His archive, said Jay Reardon, the
company's president, ``is like having a portfolio of mutual funds:
we'll keep reaching in and pulling out what's great.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But longtime Hampton watchers point out that decorating has its
own peculiar rules, ones that, in the stratosphere Hampton operated
in, are often dominated not just by a look but by winey lunches and
crystalline dinner repartee. ``If you're used to going to Mark
Hampton, have spent millions, and you buy a third house, do you go
back to the firm?'' asked Louise Grunwald, a family friend who took
her own business to Parish-Hadley and used to own an antiques shop
with Duane Hampton. ``I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hampton now faces her own blank canvas, brush in hand. For
now, she seems to have an ally in the economy. ``The timing is on
her side,'' said Arie L. Kopelman, chairman of the Winter Antiques
Show and president of Chanel, who became a client of Mark Hampton's
26 years ago. ``He was the rainmaker. But there are a lot of young
people out there with money.''
</P>
<P>
   In conversation, Ms. Hampton comes across as spunky, fiercely
determined and possessive of her father's memory. ``Mark was
certainly preparing her, but she's up against the entire design
world,'' said Paige Rense, editor in chief of Architectural Digest.
``Her problem is obvious: is she talented and strong enough to
handle the kind of clients he had, or will they turn to a brand
name? A personal relationship only goes so far, and chemistry is as
important as talent. My feeling is, she'll make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nan Kempner, a longtime client of Mark Hampton, who has hired
Ms. Hampton to ``freshen up the Kempner Hotel,'' as she called her
Park Avenue apartment, said: ``She has a lot of guts. She's not
just name alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton would probably approve of his daughter's direction. He
knew that many saw decorating as frivolous, but ``to transform the
bleak and the barren into welcoming places where one can live,'' he
wrote, ``seems to me an important and worthwhile goal in life.''
</P>
<P>
   The legacy Ms. Hampton inherits is present in the watercolors
now hanging, bittersweetly, in the Armory. In her father's hands,
life's moments were enchanted chapters to be illustrated. They
burst from the 51 leatherbound scrapbooks in the bedroom containing
family snapshots and triumphal newspaper clippings. Volume 52 waits
to be filled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
