<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shortcuts Save Steps
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are desktop shortcuts and alias files the same thing?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, but they are on different computer platforms. Shortcuts
and alias sit conveniently on a computer desktop. In Windows 95 and
98, they are called shortcuts; in Macintosh, aliases. Whatever you
call them, shortcuts and aliases serve as time-saving pointers to
frequently used documents, folders or even programs on your
computer and can be placed directly on your desktop, serve as time
savers that can be placed directly on your desktop, where they
offer quick, one-step access to frequently used documents, folders
and even programs.
</P>
<P>
   To make a shortcut in Windows 95 or 98, click on My Computer,
then go into the hard drive (probably drive C) and find the file,
program or folder that you want a shortcut for. Click on the item
with the right mouse button and drag it onto the desktop. A pop-up
menu will ask if you want to move it, copy it or create a shortcut.
Select shortcut, and a new icon with a small black arrow above the
item's name will appear on your desktop.
</P>
<P>
   If you are using a Macintosh with System 7.5 or later and want
to make an alias, click once on the icon for the item. Under the
File menu, select Make Alias (or press Command M on the keyboard).
The alias of the file will appear next to the original item. You
can drag the alias to wherever you would like it to be on your
desktop.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
postal mail to:
</P>
<P>
   Questions
</P>
<P>
   Circuits
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times
</P>
<P>
   229 W. 43rd St.
</P>
<P>
   New York, N.Y. 10036-3959
</P>
<P>
   or by e-mail to:
</P>
<P>
   Q&AMP;A(AT)nytimes.com.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
