<HEADER>
A1746 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-RARE-BOOKS-NYT &LR;      01-13 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-RARE-BOOKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOBBING FOR LITERARY PLUMS ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When my 9-year-old daughter brought home an arts and crafts book
called ``Confetti'' from the school library three months ago, she
must have had me confused with a different sort of mother, the kind
who likes to create perfect homemade decorations for a Halloween
party.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, we had the party all right _ I will not try to shock you
with the details of 15 children bobbing for apples, then running
crazily through the house with wet hair and pieces of fruit still
gripped in their teeth _ but we never once opened that book. Our
decorations consisted mainly of a set of orange plastic dishes
(circa 1967) purchased for $2 from a secondhand store in town.
Also, my husband taped a strip of black crepe paper to the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   So what became of the book? It was my recollection at the time,
and remains my testimony, that ``Confetti'' got mixed in with all
the cookbooks, phone directories and catalogs that crowd the
bookcase in the kitchen. I never thought about it again until one
day last week when my daughter Zoe came home looking sick. ``I lost
that book so the librarian says I have to pay for it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you look in the bookcase?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three times.'' I negotiated a deal with terms highly favorable
to me (a month of chores, to be specified later) to front her the
money to pay for the book, figuring that I had heard the last of
``Confetti.'' But the next day, the librarian phoned. ``The book is
out of print,'' she said. ``So we probably won't be able to replace
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't give up,'' I reassured her. ``I might be able to find a
copy.''
</P>
<P>
   Such an offer would have been hubris just a few years ago, when
the best way to find an out-of-print book was to ask a local
used-book store to query an unofficial network of other sellers. In
those dark days, it could take weeks to get a response, if you got
one at all. I have spent years trying to track down a copy of a
children's novel called ``Me and Caleb,'' picking over countless
stacks of remaindered library books in search of a piece of my
childhood.
</P>
<P>
   But recently, retrieving lost books has changed for the better.
I found out just how much better last month when I went to
www.bibliofind.com to search for ``Black-Eyed Susan,'' a novel I
read when I was 7. Armed with only the title, I searched the
database of more than 3,500 book dealers and 9 million titles.
Almost instantly the site supplied a list of books with the same
title.
</P>
<P>
   I recognized my ``Black-Eyed Susan'' as the one whose author was
Evelyn Trent Bachmann. The site said the book was published in 1968
and that a bookseller in Ames, Iowa, had a first edition in very
fine condition. After exchanging e-mail with the bookseller and
mailing $30, I received the package within a week. I ripped it open
and got my first glimpse of an old friend who had disappeared for
decades.
</P>
<P>
   I admit that I got a little out of control after that. I tracked
down a $9 copy of ``The Secret of the Crazy Quilt'' (a 1972 novel
about a girl who discovers dark family secrets _ trust me, it's
great), a $15 copy of ``Ballet Shoes'' (the 1937 classic about
three orphaned girls who go on stage) and, to ease my husband's
transition to the post-football season, a $2 paperback of
``Semi-Tough'' by Dan Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   So after assuring the librarian that I could find ``Confetti,''
I went to Bibliofind. But I found nothing. I filled out a ``book
wanted'' form; the site promised to keep looking for up to six
months.
</P>
<P>
   I next tried www.powells.com, maintained by a well-known
bookstore in Portland, Ore. Searching its inventory of more than 1
million new and used books, I could purchase copies of other books
by the authors of ``Confetti'' but not ``Confetti'' itself. At that
point, I decided I needed a metasearch engine. So I went to
www.bookfinder.com, a one-stop tool for simultaneously searching a
number of large, distinct databases that contain a total of more
than 10 million books. Still no ``Confetti.''
</P>
<P>
   I decided to take the unusual step of going to www.amazon.com to
place an order for the out-of-print book. The reason I hesitate to
do this is simple: I am cheap. I buy plenty of new books from
Amazon.com because its prices substantially beat my local
bookstore's. But Amazon.com tacks on a finder's fee for
out-of-print books, a cost that depends on how hard it is to track
down the title. Since Amazon.com relies on some of the same sources
as Bookfinder and Bibliofind, it's usually cheaper to do the
legwork yourself.
</P>
<P>
   But I was desperate. So I placed an order _ knowing that I would
have the option to cancel it if the copy that Amazon.com tracked
down seemed too pricey. The site told me it would take a week or
two to search.
</P>
<P>
   Some people are patient enough to wait that long. Me? Facing
visions of a disappointed school librarian, I phoned Amazon.com two
minutes later to ask the company's media-relations librarian, Dj
Alton, why I was having so much trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Alton explained that it was often easier to track down
out-of-print novels than niche-market books like ``Confetti,''
which might have had a smaller publication run. ``It's detective
work,'' he said. ``We'll try.''
</P>
<P>
   A week later, I still hadn't heard from Amazon. But you never
know where you'll find treasure. In the meantime, as I was trying
to compose a note to the librarian that sounded hopeful without
being unrealistic, my daughter came running in. In her hand, she
clutched a copy of the elusive ``Confetti.'' She said she had found
it in the bookcase in the kitchen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 1718EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0269 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1748 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-SCIENCE-EDUCATION     01-13 1253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SCIENCE-EDUCATION-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAR FROM THE MADDING CROWD, DINOSAURS AWAIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BETH SCHACHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a Tyrannosaurus rex shows up on your computer screen, your
spine doesn't tingle as it does when the giant beast dwarfs you at
a museum. On the other hand, when you read on line about how
dinosaur eggs were discovered in Patagonia, you are not likely to
be bashed in the shin by errant baby strollers.
</P>
<P>
   Natural history and paleontology museums are exploring new ways
to use the Internet to complement exhibits and enhance science
education. The results so far have been promising for curators and
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Museum scientists can use the Internet to offer new windows into
paleontology. Many museums have vast collections but limited space
for displaying their artifacts, and financial restrictions can also
limit the size and style of exhibits.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is also a good place to see specimens that are too
delicate to display openly and others that are barely visible to
the naked eye but are captivating when magnified.
</P>
<P>
   Museums are also beginning to experiment with the Internet as an
education tool that can attract children and adults who might
otherwise feel alienated from science. Science textbooks, even
those for college students, provide little insight into the real
working life of scientists, but online exhibits can easily present
such details.
</P>
<P>
   Paleontologists realize that many people find dinosaurs
fascinating and enjoy fossil hunting. Many museum-based educators
are responding to this interest by showing enthusiasts what is
involved in paleontology research. Taking advantage of the
Internet, they help people learn about the kinds of questions
paleontologists ask, the kinds of tools they use to look for
answers and the process in which new answers lead to new questions.
</P>
<P>
   Exploring a museum Web site does not replace the experience of
roaming through the actual galleries, but it can enhance the
on-site experience. Previewing a museum Web site before your actual
visit can help you identify the displays you want to visit. After
your visit, a look at the Web site may give you additional
information about the exhibits you saw firsthand.
</P>
<P>
   Such Web sites can whet one's appetite for information. Since
exploring the paleontology museum Web sites, I've made several
trips to the American Museum of Natural History in New York to gaze
at the myriad fossils. I got my first New York Public Library card
in order to explore paleontology more deeply, and I am midway
through two terrific books: ``Taking Wing: Archaeopteryx and the
Evolution of Bird Flight'' by Pat Shipman (Simon &AMP; Schuster, 1998)
and ``Wonderful Life: the Burgess Shale and the Nature of History''
by Stephen Jay Gould (W.W. Norton &AMP; Co., 1989).
</P>
<P>
   My virtual explorations of paleontology on the Internet led me
to many Web sites, including those described below.
</P>
<P>
   Among others, I toured the Royal Tyrrell Museum in Canada
(www.tyrrellmuseum.com), where I learned about museum-sponsored
digs for the general public. Now I'm saving my money to go on a
real fossil hunt. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA MUSEUM OF PALEONTOLOGY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.ucmp.berkeley.edu &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The richness of this online museum is not found in
state-of-the-art interactive features. The museum team elected to
keep dynamic features to a minimum until user-friendly software
became available and has begun adding fancier features only
recently.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the museum provides text _ sometimes with pictures, and
frequently with photographs of exceptional quality _ that tells a
lot about paleontologic research.
</P>
<P>
   The site, one of the first 50 on the Web, was started in 1993 by
some visionary graduate students _ Robert P. Guralnick, P.David
Polly and Allen G. Collins _ from the department of integrative
biology at the University of California at Berkeley. They
recognized early the Internet's potential for showing the outside
world the processes and thrills of scientific research. The site
now registers about a million hits per week.
</P>
<P>
   Readers enter the main hall, Paleontology Without Walls, through
one of three interlinked portals: Phylogeny presents the Family
Tree of Life, Geologic Time shows who shared the earth with whom
during each geologic era, and Evolutionary Thought describes the
work of major evolutionary biologists, paleontologists and
geologists. Brief essays tell the history that led to Charles
Darwin's theory of the origin of species and describe the
controversy that followed.
</P>
<P>
   The Family Tree of Life lets the reader meander through exhibits
of the domains of life, from microscopic bacteria to extinct
creatures like the quagga. One important side trip explains
cladistics, the technique used for figuring out how organisms, both
living and extinct, are related to one another.
</P>
<P>
   The site's Special Exhibits include Dinobuzz, which covers
current dinosaur research. It answers such questions as, How fast
did dinosaurs move? While Hollywood films like ``Jurassic Park''
may show dinosaurs running at a cheetah's pace, Dinobuzz presents
the real evidence. The distance between the fossil imprints of
dinosaur feet, along with the absence of tracks from their large
tails, help answer the question about dinosaur speed. The evidence
suggests that some of these beasts could lope along at 26 miles per
hour.
</P>
<P>
   The Special Exhibit on Vertebrate Flight shows how scientists
develop hypotheses, then look for evidence to support or to refute
them. Did the ancestors of birds first fly by gliding from the
treetops, or did they run fast along the ground and jump into the
air?
</P>
<P>
   The current wisdom now favors the ground-up idea rather than the
trees-down) hypothesis. As you read on, you learn how scientists
study flight in modern birds and look at fossil remains to learn
how bird flight evolved.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's director, David Lindberg, said the Web site was as
much an encyclopedia as a virtual museum. The museum staff is
currently designing interactive Internet-based programs for
teaching the process of paleontology in middle school and high
school. New programs will include both tours and interactive
laboratory research modules.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Scotchmoor, the museum's education and outreach director,
showed me the first research module, which is near completion. It
draws on a real field study in Montana that museum researchers are
conducting and will let students and their teachers study fossils
from the Cretaceous/Tertiary (or K/T) boundary, which marks the end
of the dinosaur era.
</P>
<P>
   Users will be able to take a virtual journey to the field to
collect specimens then return to a Berkeley laboratory to sort and
classify them. Using the interactive tools, students will learn how
to do things like distinguishing teeth from tiny bone fragments and
inspecting the teeth to determine their source.
</P>
<P>
   Students will record their findings in online journals, then
submit hypotheses about the ancient environment they are studying.
Each class can send a report to the museum and receive a response
from graduate students and faculty researchers.
</P>
<P>
   The modules are being created in a novel way by museum
scientists and graduate students in collaboration with middle
school and high school biology teachers. After seeing the
interactive research module, I left with the feeling that these
Internet pioneers were exploring exciting territory. They are
making the process of paleontology come alive. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN MUSEUM OF NATURAL HISTORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.amnh.org &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Deep within the Gobi Desert, Dr. Michael Novacek, a
paleontologist, had just completed an online interview with his
colleagues back home at the American Museum of Natural History in
Manhattan. Soon after, he got an e-mail message from a boy in New
Delhi asking whether he had found a velociraptor skeleton that day.
``Here we were, in one of the world's most deserted places,'' he
said recently. ``Suddenly I felt more in communication with the
population of the planet than I ever did in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Novacek, senior vice president and provost for science at the
American Museum of Natural History and co-leader of the museum's
Gobi Expedition, relishes the museum's role in turning cyberspace
into an interactive showcase for paleontology. For the past two
years, the museum has used the Internet to link the world to its
scientists on the Gobi fossil hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Paleontologists on the 1998 trip gave interviews that people
could hear through live Webcasts and submitted nightly e-mail
dispatches, which were immediately posted on the Web site. The
results reflected life on a dig. Some days were thrilling, while
others were hot, tiring and boring. The thrills came in many forms
_ new fossil discoveries as well as torrential hailstorms.
</P>
<P>
   A History in the Desert, written by the team's co-leader, Mark
A. Norell, accompanies the dispatches. This narrative describes the
Gobi locale, which contains the most extensive finds to date on
animals from the dinosaur age. Links to other sites point to
drawings of fossil animals found on this expedition.
</P>
<P>
   The daily Web dispatches from the Gobi expedition are only one
creative way in which the museum uses electronic media. Nancy
Hechinger, director of the museum's National Center for Science
Literacy, Education and Technology, noted that the museum's
Internet projects extended, rather than imitated, the features
provided at the museum.
</P>
<P>
   Another area, Dinosaur Discoveries in Patagonia, on the Web site
details another of the museum's famous expeditions. A team leader,
Luis M. Chiappe, provides clear narratives about the discovery in
1997 of dinosaur eggs containing embryos, skin and all in
Patagonia, a remote part of Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   To complement this text, the Web site contains pictures of the
fossils embedded in rock. As the viewer moves around the frame, the
fossil is highlighted against the rock background.
</P>
<P>
   The fossil skull exhibit allows an interactive approach. Here
you can compare the skull of a modern human with the skulls of
several close primate relatives. Moving the mouse within the frame
rotates each pair of skulls left or right, or up or down.
</P>
<P>
   A visit to the site's Fossil Halls display reveals another
example of effective electronic media. In the Hall of Vertebrate
Origins, users learn how scientists constructed the vertebrate
family tree.
</P>
<P>
   The page features a simple tree, called a cladogram. Take care
to let the program download, then move your mouse to the Expedition
Guide panel at the left. Click on the Vertebral Column and
Braincase, and you get a diagram and text explaining that the
backbone and braincase were the first features that distinguished
vertebrates from other animals.
</P>
<P>
   By bookmarking the Electronic Newspaper address found in the
site's Fossil Halls, you can easily return for more paleontology
news. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE HOOPER VIRTUAL NATURAL HISTORY MUSEUM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.wf.carleton.ca/Museum/lobby.html &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Tim Patterson, an associate professor of earth
science at Carleton University in Ottawa, started giving his
undergraduate students a choice: they could turn in traditional
term papers on topics in paleontology, or they could create
relevant Web pages. Each year, about half the class has opted for
the latter. These classroom assignments are now on the Web as the
Hooper Virtual Natural History Museum, produced largely by
third-year undergraduates majoring in geoscience.
</P>
<P>
   The museum was named to honor Dr. Ken Hooper, the first
paleontologist in the earth sciences department. Its virtual wings
range from The Mammalarium to Microfossils and Theoretical
Paleontology. Students have selected the topics for their
presentations, resulting in a pleasantly broad range of subjects in
each of the wings.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in the Flight wing, you will find The Flying
Dragons, the pterosaurs. You can choose to see an animation of the
beast in flight or go on to a page offering a range of information
about pterosaurs _ plus a fanciful depiction of a pterosaur
attempting to rescue Fay Wray and battling King Kong. Click on the
navigation icon at the bottom of the page, and you move from
fantasy back to reality.
</P>
<P>
   What follows is a well-crafted presentation about the pterosaur,
including information that is easy for nonscientists, including
children, to grasp. The author poses several questions: Did these
extinct flying lizards walk on two legs or on all four? Were they
warmblooded or not? He provides answers and identifies the
controversies that remain. Excellent illustrations, complete with
citations, are included.
</P>
<P>
   Other noteworthy presentations include Gastropoda: Snails
Throughout the Ages, in the Invertebrates wing; Burgess Shale:
Hidden Treasure in the Canadian Rockies, in the Fantastic Fossil
Finds wing; and Evolution and Creationism: An Objective Evaluation,
in the Evolution and Extinction wing.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson said the presentation quality improved each year. So
while each exhibit remains within a museum wing for a year, some
are moved to the Archives after that.
</P>
<P>
   With traditional homework assignments, only two people _ the
student author and the teacher _ read most term papers. Patterson
said that because his students had a way to share their work with a
broader audience via the Web site, many of them took greater care
with their projects. Moreover, public display of the work helps
students learn from one another.
</P>
<P>
   Even the best presentations on this site could benefit from
further editing and tweaking. Patterson said students continued to
modify their online exhibits and improve their homework on their
own time, well after the works are posted (and, of course, grades
are given).
</P>
<P>
   Although secondary students with passions for dinosaur hunting
often consider careers in paleontology, many do not know about the
necessary training. A tour through the Hooper Virtual Natural
History Museum offers an excellent view of the matters that concern
fossil hunters when they are not digging in the field.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
