<HEADER>
A1756 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-     01-13 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME CLINIC: GIVING HOT AIR A PUSH TOWARD COLD CORNERS
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo and graphic are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (bl) 
By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some homeowners get perturbed when they find that even though
they have a new furnace with a state-of-the-art heating system,
there is always one room in the house that is cold. Turning up the
thermostat will warm the room, but it may also make the rest of the
house too hot and create higher heating bills.
</P>
<P>
   What is the best way to bring heat into that cold room?
Unfortunately there is no easy answer because the chill may come
from a number of causes. First, it's important to examine the
heating system to make sure that heat is indeed being delivered to
the room. In extreme cases, it may be necessary to consult a
heating specialist who can evaluate your home heating system to
determine if it is operating efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   First, inspect the system yourself to see if there are any
obvious malfunctions. With a few simple adjustments, you may be
able to correct the problem and save yourself a consultation fee.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a forced-air system, look first at the air filter. A
dirty filter can restrict the flow of hot air from the furnace to
the delivery ducts. Many homeowners neglect to change air filters
at the beginning of the season. As a result, the system cannot
deliver heat efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   Inspect the heat outlet, or register, in the cold room. It is
usually in the floor near a wall. Feel to make sure that heat is
coming out. If not, it could be blocked. Unscrew the register cover
and look down with a flashlight. Remove any obstructions.
</P>
<P>
   If there is no blockage, examine the ducts that feed air into
the room. These usually have dampers that control the flow of air
through the duct. Make sure that they are in the open position. If
these measures do not restore the proper air flow, the problem
could be more serious, like faulty duct design. It is best to
consult with a heating specialist to see if this is the case.
</P>
<P>
   If hot air is coming out of the register, it is likely that it
is not flowing toward the center of the room. This can happen if a
piece of furniture is positioned over the register. The obvious
solution is to move the furniture. Another way to redirect the air
flowing from a register is by installing plastic deflectors. These
are available in a variety of shapes that allow you to control the
air-flow patterns in a room.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a steam-heating system with radiators, inspect the
room radiators to see if they are hot. Cold radiators may not be
leveled properly. A radiator that is perfectly level or pitched
away from the intake valve will trap water so steam cannot enter.
Raise one end with small wood blocks so the radiator slopes toward
the valve.
</P>
<P>
   Another cause of cold radiators is a blocked air vent. The air
vent is the small chrome-plated cylinder mounted on one end of the
radiator. It allows air to escape from the radiator so steam can
enter. If the vent is blocked, the radiator will never heat up.
Sometimes you can open a blocked vent port with a thin wire, but
it's best to install a new vent.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible to buy variable adjustment vents that allow you
to regulate the amount of air released and, consequently, the
amount of steam entering the radiator. If the radiator doesn't heat
up, simply turn the adjustment control on top of the vent to allow
more air to escape.
</P>
<P>
   Modern hot-water radiators are less problematic because they are
part of a closed system. Still, air can collect in the radiators
and keep the hot water out. These units have a purge valves that
allow you to release the tapped air. Purging the air from a hot
water radiator is not difficult. Hold a metal container under the
valve port and open the vent with a screwdriver. Keep the vent open
until all the air is released and water begins to flow, then close
the vent.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most efficient heating system will fail to keep a room
warm if cold air is allowed to enter through the gaps and cracks in
an old window. The best way to remedy this problem is by replacing
the old windows with new, energy- efficient ones. This is
expensive, and such an installation may not be possible in the
middle of winter. As a temporary seasonal fix, you can install
plastic indoor ''storm'' windows, available as kits at most home
centers. Tape the plastic sheet over the window then heat it with a
hair dryer to make it taut.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
