<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1766 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-LAPTOP-TOUCHPADS-     01-13 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-LAPTOP-TOUCHPADS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREADING ON THE MOUSE'S HEELS: THE OH-SO-SUBTLE TOUCH PAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By JAMES RYAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For many, the computer mouse is a marvel of ingenuity. But for
Dr. George E. Gerpheide, an engineer, it is an abomination. He set
out to build, if not a better mousetrap, then something to rid
society of the inelegant mouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed clunky,'' said Gerpheide, who is 46. ``What the
world needed was a pointing device that matched people's
expectations and looked like it belonged in the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   After two years and 19 unsuccessful prototypes built after hours
in the basement of his home, he hit upon the solution in 1988: an
electronic touch pad that would register the slightest twitch of a
finger and translate it into cursor movements on the monitor. He
picked the nickname ``cat'' for his rival to the mouse and founded
the Cirque Corp., where he is now chief executive, to market the
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Apple was the first to license Gerpheide's technology and take
it to market. It incorporated a touch pad 11/2 inches wide into its
Powerbook laptops in 1994, replacing the built-in trackball.
</P>
<P>
   Most laptop manufacturers, with the exception of IBM and
Toshiba, which employ a joystick, have adopted touch pads. Nearly
all of the laptop touch pad market is now divided between Alps
Electric, a Japanese company that licenses Gerpheide's technology,
and Synaptics, a competitor based in San Jose, Calif. (Apple
switched a few years ago to Synaptics technology.)
</P>
<P>
   Cirque, which makes Glide Point touch pads and is based in Salt
Lake City, made 70 percent of the touch pads sold as accessories
(primarily for use with desktops) in the first 11 months of 1998,
according to PC Data, a market research company.
</P>
<P>
   Touch pads range from the size of a pack of matches to that of a
small wallet. They rely on minute flows of electric current and how
those currents are modified by the human finger's effect on small
electric fields, so moisture or electromagnetic interference can
diminish performance. That was particularly true of early touch
pads.
</P>
<P>
   What touch-pad users do not have to worry about is peanut
butter, cookie crumbs or hair fouling any moving parts, as they can
in a mechanical mouse, which dates from the mid-60s. They also do
not need to make space on their desks for a mouse to roam in.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike touch screens and some touch pads called resistive, which
require pressure from a finger or stylus to function, one need not
actually touch the surface of a capacitive touch pad to make it
work. The finger can affect electric fields in the touch pad even
when it is merely near the surface.
</P>
<P>
   But if a business card or two is placed on top of a touch pad,
that extra insulation will keep it from registering the presence of
a finger running on the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Another advantage of newer models of touch pads is that they can
be trained to recognize handwritten commands. Synaptics sells a
model, popular in China, that enables users to use their fingertips
to enter Chinese characters into the computer. If used properly,
the touch pad is less likely to cause repetitive stress injuries
because touch-pad users do not have to grip or press anything.
</P>
<P>
   The finger movements required are subtle and relatively easy.
But Dr. John Kella, an ergonomics consultant to The New York Times,
said touch-pad users still needed to be careful. ``With any
tracking device, the user should take frequent breaks, flex and
move the muscles and joints,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gerpheide offered a few tips for using a touch pad: (a) The
lighter the touch, the better the touch pad works. (b) For a large
cursor movement, slide the finger; for a more precise movement,
hold the finger still and roll the tip from side to side. (c) A
double tap equals a double click of the mouse. To highlight and
drag an object, use a tap and a half: tap once, then lower the
finger and leave it down.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the advantages of touch pads, they have been slow to
catch on, especially among desktop users, who may have had bad
experiences with the first generation of touch pads, which were
less precise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're currently in our fifth generation, light-years ahead of
what you find on a notebook computer,'' Gerpheide said. It takes
roughly two years for the product cycle to catch up to new
touch-pad technology, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Other users are simply more comfortable with the more familiar
mouse, but Gerpheide is banking that the rapid evolution of
technology will change that.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the post-PC era, when you're talking about mobile
appliances,'' he said, ``the mouse is not suitable. Nobody wants a
mouse dangling from their Net-connected cell phone.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 1723EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0273 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1771 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-TALK-2TAKES-NYT     01-13 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING BOOKS: A PLACE FOR POETS, PERHAPS NOT FOR GIANTS
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Where have all the poets gone, long time passing; where have all
the poets gone, long time ago? It may not be that young girls pick
them, everyone, but several major publishing houses do.
</P>
<P>
   Poetry has become a consequential part of a few publishing
programs, and it's not just Jewel and Springsteen and Dylan and
Cobain either, but Robert Pinsky and Mark Strand and Deborah
Garrison and Frederick Seidel and Sharon Olds and others whose
names and work you may not know either, but whose art is more
literary than the songwriter poets.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is not one major poet who has the crossover
recognition in mainstream America that a Robert Frost or a Wallace
Stevens or a Marianne Moore had (although she might have been as
well known for being photographed in large hats and beautiful black
velvet at baseball games as for her poetry), with the possible
exception of the best-selling Maya Angelou, who is probably known
more for her memoirs than for her poetry.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with the proliferation of literary poetry, why is there
no one artist who bestrides this terrain? Perhaps because there is
no one American language. The Scotch and the Irish, for instance,
each have their own luxurious national languages. The United States
doesn't. It is too polyglot, too regional for that.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it always was, but even as recently as Wallace
Stevens, who died in 1955, the country paid little attention to its
powerful diversity, and the national language was white and male
and middle-class. Rap, for instance, might as well have come from
the far side of the moon.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Meneka, who is senior editor and in essence poetry editor
of Random House, said that there were ``a huge number of
multicultural threads, pulling together a bit now, maybe because of
the Internet, and maybe because of that we'll see a more national
picture in the world of poetry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If so,'' he continued, ``it remains to be seen who will emerge
as high-profile figures.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Galassi, the editor in chief at Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux
and himself an accomplished poet and translator of the poetry and
essays of the Italian writer Eugenio Montale, agrees that ``a lot
of Americans are interested in language, but there are regional and
ethnic idioms _ a lot of different consistencies, more of a grab
bag of different groups.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Meneka and Galassi see, if not exactly a great surge of
interest in poetry, certainly an increasing pursuit of it by
publishers and the public. Virginia Hamilton Adair, who was 83 and
blind when her first book, ``Ants on the Melon,'' was published two
years ago, and Deborah Garrison, author of ``A Working Girl Can't
Win'' (1998), both sold well for Random House. There are 20,000
copies of Ms. Garrison's book in print, a goodly number for poetry.
``We should be a pure purist about what poetry we publish,'' Meneka
said. ``We shouldn't worry about pegs. Nevertheless, a suitcase
carries better with a handle on it. `Working Girl' has a built-in
demographic _ the young working professional and her plights and
her life.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lack of a contemporary celebrity poet, the Alfred A.
Knopf publishing group last year still sold 250,000 books of
poetry, hardback and paperback, which was not bad for something so
many people apparently feel is intimidating if not actually
menacing in its mannered pithiness on the page. The figure is
slightly misleading since it includes Knopf's Everyman's Pocket
Poetry Series, which has 30 books in print ranging from Emily
Dickinson to an anthology of erotica.
</P>
<P>
   Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux and Random House publish serious poetry,
as of course do the university presses. Galassi, who is also
president of the Academy of American Poets, said that his house
``actually does make a little money out of publishing poetry, but
it's about the way we think of literature _ when people quote, what
do they quote most often but poetry. So it's not a byproduct of
what we do, not a side issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Farrar, Straus over the years has published T.S. Eliot and
Robert Lowell and Joseph Brodsky and Seamus Heaney, among its
poets. Last year the publishing house sold more than 100,000 copies
of Ted Hughes' ``Birthday Letters,'' although that large number
could probably be attributed mostly to the fact that the poems
discussed, for the first time, his doomed relationship with his
wife, the poet Sylvia Plath, whose suicide at the age of 30 turned
her into a feminist icon and him, for many, into a dark presence.
</P>
<P>
   HarperCollins paid seven figures to publish the songwriter
Jewel's best-selling ``A Night Without Armor,'' but then not every
poet comes to the calling with a mega-platinum disk in her agent's
pocket. Last year Crown published ``the complete poems and lyrics''
of Joni Mitchell. (Were they poems? Yes, mostly, whatever their
lasting quality, although both books raised the question of where
is the line between poems and lyrics.)
</P>
<P>
   However one looks at it, things are happening in poetry. Bill
Wadsworth, executive director of the Academy of American Poets,
said that membership had grown from 2,000 to 8,000 during the last
four years and that the organization now supported poetry prizes at
160 colleges and universities. It also awards the annual Tanning
Prize of $100,000 to the poet of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Slate, the online magazine, features a weekly poem selected by
Pinsky, America's poet laureate. Click the right ``here'' and you
can even hear Pinsky read the poem. There are even ``poetry
slams,'' which means that conventional poetry readings often have
been replaced by a performance art that combines poetry and rock
and, well, athletics. The performing poets are scored by judges in
the same way Olympic ice-skaters are scored.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   No one remembers seeing a newspaper want ad that said ``poet
wanted,'' so it's nearly impossible to make a living by simply
writing poetry. The usual advance for a poet is $10,000 to $15,000,
although $2,500 advances are not rare. Very occasionally, a poet
might receive a $25,000 advance. Ten thousand copies is an
excellent ego-building first printing; 20,000 borders on being
newsworthy.
</P>
<P>
   Most poets earn their living teaching. Frederick Seidel, whose
well- received ``Going East'' (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux) was
published last summer, writes screenplays. What makes him unusual
is that when he was young and was asked the eternal question what
do you want to be, he answered not fireman or forest ranger but
poet.
</P>
<P>
   Reading Ezra Pound's ``Cantos'' in ``my school library in St.
Louis stunned me,'' Seidel said. `` `What thou lovest most
remains.' Reading that lyric got to me; it was a moment. It's the
pleasure of rounding words, it's gripping, it's a transportation.
As a writer you go places, you aim, you aspire, you're
transported.''
</P>
<P>
   And for him there was, not unnaturally for a young man, hero
worship, not for a ball player but for a poet. At the time, Pound
was considered a crazy traitor to his country. ``He wrote those
poems while being held in a cage, imprisoned, the cage made of the
metal matting they used for airfield runways,'' Seidel said.
</P>
<P>
   He accounts for the increased interest in poetry, in part, by
the explosion in the number of creative writing classes at colleges
and universities: ``Years ago there were hardly any; now it's a big
part of a university's liberal arts program. That means there's
lots of poetry being written; doesn't mean good poetry, but more
poetry, and that's important. Poems are meant to be a pleasure.
They instruct by pleasing.''
</P>
<P>
   How will technology affect the popularity of poetry? Since
poetry by its nature tends to be terse, and its books generally
slim, perhaps there will be little need to cram your electronic
book with verse, but many people in publishing believe that the
ability to publish one's own book on demand means getting your
rhythms the very moment you want them, easily and cheaply, and that
will make poetry more popular. As will the ability to not only read
poetry on the Internet but hear it as well.
</P>
<P>
   Although the United States is not a language-oriented nation,
people still seem to feel a need to write poetry, as has every
schoolgirl and boy whose heart was broken. Poetry is the history of
emotion. It is imprinted on a page, and it has to stay put, always
available. Looked at that way, perhaps it doesn't need a superstar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 1729EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
