<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ARGUMENTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEY QUESTIONS IN BATTLE BETWEEN WHITE HOUSE AND GOP PROSECUTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the historic Senate impeachment trial gets under
way Thursday, President Clinton's legal team and House Republican
prosecutors will square off in a go-for-broke final weighing of the
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The 13-member House team led by Judiciary Chairman Henry Hyde
will attempt to prove that the president, sworn to uphold the
Constitution and enforce the laws, is guilty of the crimes of
perjury and obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, White House Counsel Charles Ruff, White House
special counsel Gregory Craig, and David Kendall, Clinton's private
lawyer, will unleash a scorched-earth attack on Independent Counsel
Kenneth Starr's findings of possible impeachment offenses by
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to arguing that the offenses alleged do not fall
under the Constitution's impeachment standard of ``high crimes and
misdemeanors,'' the Clinton lawyers will try to pick holes in the
Starr investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The first impeachment article approved by the House last month
charges Clinton with lying under oath during his Aug. 17, 1998,
federal grand jury appearance about his relationship with Monica
Lewinsky. While acknowledging ``inappropriate intimate contact''
with the former White House intern, Clinton stuck by his previous
denial that he ever had ``sexual relations'' with Lewinsky. That
denial came Jan. 17, 1998 in his deposition in the Paula Jones
sexual harassment lawsuit and was based on a definition of sexual
relations provided by Jones' lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The second article charges Clinton with obstructing justice by
taking steps to hide his affair with Lewinsky. It says Clinton
urged her to deny the affair in an affidavit to the Jones lawyers,
helped her find a job in exchange for her silence and assigned his
secretary Betty Currie to retrieve from Lewinsky the gifts he had
given her.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some key questions likely to come up:
</P>
<P>
   DID CLINTON LIE ABOUT HAVING `SEXUAL RELATIONS' WITH LEWINSKY?
</P>
<P>
   During his grand jury appearance, Clinton acknowledged
``inappropriate intimate contact'' with Lewinsky but claimed that
his deposition in the Jones case denying ``sexual relations'' was
technically correct and within the definition provided by Jones'
lawyers because he and Lewinsky never had sexual intercourse.
</P>
<P>
   The House prosecutors say Clinton was lying. The definition was
broad enough to cover any touching for sexual stimulation, they
contend, but Clinton in essence was saying he received such
stimulation from Lewinsky but never touched her himself. Lewinsky,
the House prosecutors note, testified Clinton touched her in a
sexual manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``While his treatment of Ms. Lewinsky was offensive, it is much
more offensive for the president to expect the Senate to believe
that ... his intimate contact with Ms. Lewinsky was so limited that
it did not fall within his narrow interpretation of a definition of
`sexual relations,''' the House prosecutors said in their Jan. 11
trial brief.
</P>
<P>
   The White House team is said to believe it can more easily
defend Clinton's grand jury testimony than his deposition in the
Jones case, in which Clinton said it was ``absolutely true'' that,
as his lawyer Robert Bennett put it, ``there was absolutely no sex
of any kind.''
</P>
<P>
   A White House trial memorandum released Wednesday says that on
discrepancies between Lewinsky and Clinton over when the
relationship began, whether he touched her sexually and the extent
to which they were alone: ``Should the will of the people be
overruled and the president ... removed from office because two
people have a different recollection of the details of a wrongful
relationship _ which the president has admitted?''
</P>
<P>
   DID CLINTON ENCOURAGE LEWINSKY TO SIGN A FALSE AFFIDAVIT?
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans cite a 2 a.m. phone call Dec. 17, 1997 from
Clinton to Lewinsky in which, they say, he asked her to lie about
their relationship. He informed her that her name had appeared on a
witness list submitted by the Jones lawyers. Lewinsky told the
grand jury that Clinton said, ``Well, maybe you can sign an
affidavit'' denying the relationship, and ``you can always say you
were coming to see Betty (Currie) or that you were bringing me
letters.'' Lewinsky signed the affidavit on Jan. 7, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   White House lawyers argue that Clinton suggested only that
Lewinsky might sign a ``truthful but limited'' affidavit. During
his grand jury testimony, Clinton said he never talked to Lewinsky
about her approach to the affidavit, but ``if she defined `sexual
relationship' in the way that I think most Americans do, meaning
intercourse, then she told the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   DID CLINTON GET CURRIE TO RETRIEVE HIS GIFTS TO LEWINSKY?
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors point to Dec. 28, 1997, the day Clinton met
Lewinsky for the last time. The Jones lawyers' subpoena that
Lewinsky received nine days earlier required her to produce ``each
and every gift'' from Clinton. After he gave her holiday presents
including a stuffed animal and chocolates, Lewinsky broached the
subject of what to do about all the gifts. She suggested that
perhaps Currie could take charge of them. Lewinsky recalled Clinton
saying, ``I don't know'' or ``let me think about that.'' Later that
day, Lewinsky said, Currie called her and drove by Lewinsky's
Watergate apartment, took the boxed-up gifts home and put them
under her bed.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lawyers argue that if he was so concerned about hiding
gifts, he would not have given Lewinsky new ones. They accuse Starr
of ignoring other Lewinsky statements reporting that when she
brought up the gifts, Clinton said nothing. In none of her
statements about the issue, they add, did Lewinsky say Clinton told
her to conceal the gifts.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers accuse Starr of ignoring Currie's recollection that
it was Lewinsky who called and asked her to pick them up.
</P>
<P>
   DID CLINTON SEEK A JOB FOR LEWINSKY TO BUY HER SILENCE?
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors say Lewinsky asked Clinton to help her find a
job in New York in July 1997, but the assistance she received from
the president and his friend Vernon Jordan intensified in December
1997 at the time her name appeared on the Jones lawyers' witness
list. Clinton met Lewinsky on Dec. 6, 1997, the same day he learned
her name was on the list. When she complained that Jordan, a
high-powered Washington lawyer, had done nothing to find her a job,
Clinton replied, ``I'll talk to him. I'll get on it.'' Lewinsky met
Jordan five days later. On Jan. 9, 1998 _ two days after Lewinsky
signed the affidavit _ Revlon Inc. offered her a job in New York.
After learning of the offer, Jordan left a message for Clinton with
Betty Currie: ``Mission accomplished.''
</P>
<P>
   White House lawyers contend that Lewinsky's job search was at
full throttle well before her name appeared on the Jones lawyers'
witness list. The White House team points to testimony from Revlon
executives that the company official who offered her a job had not
been told of Jordan's phone call to Revlon's chief executive on
Lewinsky's behalf the previous day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 1732EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0277 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1780 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-ART-INFO-NYT &LR;      01-13 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ART-INFO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ART INFORMATION AND THE INTERNET': AN ART BOOK FOR BROWSING THE
INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS.: Publication notes are at the end of review.) 
(js) 
 By JUDITH H. DOBRZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes you have to stare at a work of art for a while before
appreciating it. ``Art Information and the Internet: How to Find
It, How to Use It,'' a recently published book from Oryx Press, is
a case in point.
</P>
<P>
   Written by Lois Swan Jones, whose 1990 book, ``Art Information:
Research Methods and Resources'' (Kendall-Hunt), is a standard
reference for educators, students and museum staff members, the new
book is serious stuff, too. At first glance, it seems useful only
to the same audience of researchers. But take time to look deeper
and ``Art Information and the Internet'' turns into a $45 resource
that many casual culture lovers, as well as art professionals, can
appreciate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Art Information and the Internet'' is, in fact, a guide to
information on the Internet that you never knew you wanted _ but
will enjoy once you find it.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the sites under ``Museums and Libraries: Medieval and
Byzantine Collections'' on page 134. The Bodleian Library at Oxford
University (www.bodley.ox.ac.uk/welcome.html) lets you enter its
Map Case and call up a sampling of early maps: the London Docks of
1831 and America, circa 1800, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Pick ``early manuscripts'' and you can view several examples up
close. Or you can shop in the Bodleian Arcade, check in on the
Bodleian's Broadside Ballads Project, which is building a digitized
repertory of 30,000 ballads, or try the library's Toyota City
Imaging Project, which offers images from the John Johnson
Collection of auto ephemera.
</P>
<P>
   Have you ever been puzzled by classical paintings, unable to
tell Aphrodite from Demeter or Ares from Hades? ``Art Information
and the Internet'' has a section on mythology (page 170), and one
of the listed sites, Classical Myth
(web.uvic.ca/grs/bowman/myth/index.html), may help. Besides giving
a brief timeline of Greek history, it has images and texts for each
Olympian god. Another section, called ``Attributes in
iconography,'' gives the symbols associated with each god.
</P>
<P>
   Like most sites, Classical Myth has links of related sites. One
of the best is the Perseus project (www.perseus.tufts.edu), a
digital library of resources for studying the ancient world that
includes texts and translations, maps and art images from more than
70 museums. You can also, for example, take a walk around ancient
Athens (click on Starting Points, then on Sites and click on any
triangle to see a photograph from that vantage).
</P>
<P>
   Animals can also be artistic symbols, but the Internet
references in this category (page 175) will not help. The Butterfly
Site (www.mgfx.com/butterfly) is charming, however, with
illustrated information on the butterflies of every state and other
places, plus links to sites-in-the-making on hummingbirds, birds
and dragonflies. The Unicorn Web Page is in French
(perso.wanadoo.fr/bruno.faidutli/licornes/unicorn.html).
</P>
<P>
   The book's Chapter 10, on art historical periods, offers some
good sites. In one example, readers are directed to an ancient art
site maintained by the University of Wisconsin's art history
department. And if you backtrack to the department's main site
(www.wisc.edu/arth) and look under ``course materials'' for various
classes, not just ancient art, you will find Assyrian, Renaissance,
French and Asian art images. Better yet is the department's ``Find
an Image'' section, which lets you sample the work of an artist,
architect, period or site around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Chapter 10 lists many, many other museum, university and other
sites, covering early civilization up to the present.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a real aid to find information about contemporary
artists online since they are by definition less known. ``Art
Information on the Internet'' first sends readers to galleries,
then suggests ``Worldwide Books On Line'' (www.worldwide.com). But
you will find little to see here. Go to ``Artist Index'' and you
can browse the names of some 6,000 artists, with not much more than
a roster of books or their catalogs. Using the ``Extended Search''
option will bring up a description of the book, but no images.
</P>
<P>
   Another section of the book, ``Pronunciation,'' on page 145
looked promising, perhaps the key to finding out at last the
correct way to say Ingres or Caillebotte. Alas, no; it recommends a
CD-ROM. Still, the section does direct readers to a
French-English/English-French dictionary
(humanities.uchicago.edu/formsunrest/FR-ENG.html) that works for
single words, but not titles or phrases.
</P>
<P>
   And so ``Art Information on the Internet'' goes, reflecting the
spottiness of World Wide Web sites themselves. Some references are
very good; others quite pedestrian. The publisher promises,
however, to keep current. It posts updates to the book on its Web
site &UR;  &LR; (www.oryxpress.com/artupdate).
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ART INFORMATION AND THE INTERNET: HOW TO FIND IT, HOW TO USE
IT'
</P>
<P>
   By Lois Swan Jones. Oryx Press (Phoenix), $45.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
