<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1781 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-WELFARE-HNS &LR;      01-13 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-WELFARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES EXAMINE WELFARE BENEFITS IN CALIFORNIA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court, delving into the
constitutionality of welfare reform efforts, on Wednesday
considered if benefit restrictions that California imposes on new
residents violate the constitutional freedom to travel.
</P>
<P>
   At issue was whether the Constitution permits California to
require people to live in the state for a year before they can
collect higher welfare benefits than they would have received in
their previous residence. The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in
San Francisco, agreeing with poor Californians who challenged the
restriction, has ruled that the law violates the freedom to travel
by discouraging welfare recipients from entering California.
</P>
<P>
   An attorney for the the state disputed the 9th Circuit's ruling,
arguing that the one-year waiting period for full benefits is a
temporary delay that only remotely hinders travel. Theodore
Garelis, California's deputy attorney general, said the delay
passes constitutional muster because it is a rational way for the
state to achieve its legitimate goal of encouraging new residents
to get off welfare.
</P>
<P>
   But attorney Mark Rosenbaum, representing new Californians on
welfare, countered that the reduced benefits for incoming residents
discourage poor people from exercising their freedom to travel.
Because it encroaches on a constitutional right, the law is valid
only if the state can prove it is narrowly written to achieve a
compelling state interest, Rosenbaum told the justices.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Solicitor General Seth Waxman, the Clinton administration's
chief advocate before the high court, agreed that the California
law impinges on the freedom to travel but added the interference
might not be so severe as to violate the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Garelis and Rosenbaum, Waxman argued that the
welfare statute should be upheld if California can show the
one-year delay is substantially related to achieving the important
governmental objectives Congress spelled out in a 1996 welfare
reform statute.
</P>
<P>
   Those goals include giving states greater flexibility in
operating assistance programs for needy families and encouraging
self-reliance and family stability.
</P>
<P>
   The justices appeared as divided as the lawyers, with several
indicating that the law is a substantial encroachment on the
freedom to travel and others regarding it as a mere inconvenience.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg, questioning the law's validity,
said the court has held that the right of people to travel is
greater than the authority of states to enact laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can pick their states, but states cannot pick their
people,'' Ginsburg said. ``That is the genius of the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Anthony M. Kennedy disputed Garelis' contention that the
state's purpose in enacting the law was not to keep welfare
recipients out of the state. ``The whole purpose of this law was to
discourage migration,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing Kennedy, Justice John Paul Stevens asked Garelis how the
state could argue that the law was not chiefly intended to convince
indigent people to stay away from California. The state presumably
sets benefits for long-term residents based on its cost of living,
meaning that the statute effectively forces new residents to make
do with inadequate funds for an entire year, Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   Garelis responded that the welfare benefits do not reflect
California's cost of living. He said states have always provided
different welfare benefits and that the disparities have not raised
constitutional concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Justices Antonin Scalia and Sandra Day O'Connor, indicating
support for California, said the state law might impose a mere
hindrance on the freedom to travel and not raise significant
constitutional concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Scalia said states have many legitimate regulations that
discourage travel, such as those that assess higher licensing fees
on out of state residents. ``I would like to get Louisiana hunting
licenses at Louisiana-resident rates,'' added the justice, who
resides in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, picking up on Scalia's theme, said states have a
strong interest in charging higher rates for fishing licenses to
ensure that fish caught in the state are consumed in the state.
</P>
<P>
   But Rosenbaum answered that people who seek to change their
state of residence have greater rights than those who merely visit
a state to hunt or fish. The freedom to travel embodies ``a right
not to be discriminated against based on the length of residence,''
Rosenbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   That response led Scalia to poke a bit of fun at the Los Angeles
attorney's home state. ``I'm more interested in my right to travel
to California than I am in my right to live there,'' the justice
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
