<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAX LAW SQUEEZES NOT-SO-RICH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star   A story in BEGIN ITAL HERE The New York
Times END ITAL HERE on Sunday became the latest damning evidence of
how tax policy designed to soak the rich inevitably has harmful
unintended consequences for hard-working taxpayers trying to cope
with life's financial challenges.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The effort was headlined ``Funny, They Don't Look Like Fat
Cats,'' and its anecdotal focal point was the Klaassen family of
Marquette, Kan. David Klaassen and his wife, Margaret, have 13
children, including one 17-year-old son who has endured a long
fight with leukemia.
</P>
<P>
   Klaassen, a lawyer, made just under $90,000 in 1997 and paid
$5,989 in federal income taxes. A few weeks ago, Klaassen got a
notice from the Internal Revenue Service demanding $3,761 more in
taxes. The amount was due, the IRS said, under the alternative
minimum tax. It included a penalty because Klaassen was deemed to
have been aware he owed the AMT, as the tax is generally known.
</P>
<P>
   Klaassen acknowledges knowing of the potential AMT claim but
says the law wasn't intended to apply to somebody in his situation.
He has never, he said, invested in tax shelters or tax-free bonds
or other investments to avoid income taxes. The reason for his
relatively low tax liability is his 13 children and the medical
expenses incurred as a result of his son Aaron's leukemia fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``What kind of policy taxes you for spending money to save your
child's life?'' Klaassen asked.
</P>
<P>
   The kind so obsessed with squeezing the rich that it allows the
imposition of outrageous injustices on unintended victims. Over
time, however, governmental sclerosis renders a reasonable remedy
apparently impossible. Tax experts say both Congress and the
administration understand the unfairness of the law's current flaw
but can't agree on how to reform it in a way that best serves the
original intent.
</P>
<P>
   The AMT was born 30 years ago after a revelation that 155
wealthy Americans paid no income taxes. The alternative minimum tax
was devised to prevent the very rich from avoiding their fair share
of income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the story estimated, more than 2 million tax filers
will owe the AMT, and about half will have incomes from $30,000 to
$100,000. Paradoxically, many of the truly rich won't be among
those liable. Meanwhile, those subject to the AMT will expand over
the next decade by about 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   How did the AMT evolve into a source of tax oppression for
ordinary folk instead of a way to soak rich business owners and
investors? At the risk of oversimplification, here's what happened:
</P>
<P>
   When tax reform was undertaken in the mid-1980s, huge deficits
made it politically necessary to make it appear as though the
Treasury wouldn't lose revenue. One way to accomplish this was to
restrict AMT tax preferences. The effect of these restrictions has
spread to taxpayers of relatively ordinary means because the AMT
limits haven't been indexed to inflation. The total allowable
exemptions before the AMT kicks in, for instance, have been fixed
since 1993 at $45,000 for a married couple filing jointly.
</P>
<P>
   Klaassen is fighting, but most experts consider it a losing
fight because the law is clear. Thus, only Congress can undo the
injustice. Unfortunately, it seems in no hurry to do so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 1744EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1801 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIVINGROOM-POOL-ART-N     01-13 1246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVINGROOM-POOL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LAP POOL PUTS LIVING IN THE LIVING ROOM
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (DW) 
By JOSEPH GIOVANNINI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Andrea Urban was in the kitchen washing dishes when she heard
something strange. ``Suddenly there was this sound of splashing in
the living room,'' she said, ``and I thought, `Somebody's floating
through the house.''' Then it clicked. It was her husband, Glen. He
had shoved off on his inaugural swim in the lap pool.
</P>
<P>
   Most houses lead from front living room to back family room in a
gradient from formal to informal. At the Urbans new addition in
rural Massachusetts, however, Sheila Kennedy and Frano Violich of
the Boston architectural firm of Kennedy &AMP; Violich plunge visitors
into the life of the house: they have put the living back in the
living room.
</P>
<P>
   The architects radicalized the plan by placing front-and-center
the activity areas (including the pool) that are usually relegated
to the back rooms, basement and yard. Perhaps the Urbans are more
affluent than most, but the new configuration reflects changes in
the way many Americans live. By taking pool, exercise area, office
and an art gallery out of the margins and placing them center
stage, the architects are catching up with everyday reality.
</P>
<P>
   In the very wide world of conventional four-bedroom, three-bath
houses, the coexistence of gallery, office, pool, gym, music room
and living room under a big top represents no less than a big bang
in thinking about the home.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing about the poker-faced facade of the house extension,
completed last summer, would strike anyone heading up the driveway
as conspicuously revolutionary: the classical proportions overcome
the avant-gardism implied by the unpainted zinc shingle cladding.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the front door, a 48-foot-long lap pool plies its way
past the furniture and continues into a windowed extension
cantilevered into the garden. A gracefully arched plywood ramp
swans over the pool on its path to a home office tucked into an
upper corner of the living room; an exercise space with a ballet
barre lies beyond the pool.
</P>
<P>
   The walls, under a faceted 17-foot ceiling, serve as a gallery
for the Urbans' art collection. The Urbans haven't gotten around to
buying sofas, but the piano is in place, already the centerpiece of
their musical soirees.
</P>
<P>
   The architects have mixed seemingly irreconcilable functions _ a
pool and a gallery _ in a new domestic landscape that collects
rather than separates the couple on their daily routines. This is a
big house in which husband and wife are not lost to each other.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, the Urbans found themselves empty nesting in
the traditional-style house they had built in 1970. The house no
longer suited their needs _ but not because they needed something
smaller once their two children had left. Their art collection,
which they started as a young couple, had expanded to bursting, and
they needed much more wall area, with space for long sight lines.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Urban, a dancer also devoted to yoga, needed an exercise
area. Urban, a business professor, consultant and an amateur
sculptor, wanted an all-year lap pool. Urban also wanted a
technically sophisticated office.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of them wished to feel exiled from the house, and from
each other, in compartmentalized rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The Urbans are active in the arts, and they treated the shaping
of their new addition as an artistic process. Even though they had
designed the old house, with double-height living room and gabled
ceiling, they hired architects for the new addition.
</P>
<P>
   The project revealed a subtext of two people moving into a
different phase of life. ``It was important that the addition not
simply reflect the old house but the challenges we were growing
into,'' Urban said. ``It had to be about what we were becoming and
would become. We wanted to make another step forward in our
development and creative outlook.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Urbans, remodeling their house was, in a sense, a way of
remodeling their lives. The design process became a metaphor for
two people in transition. They were molting into a larger shell.
``It was clear they didn't want the usual loft or a big box,''
Violich said.
</P>
<P>
   What intrigued the architects most, and finally broke open the
floor plan, was the Urbans' notion that their pool didn't have to
be set outside the main living spaces: it was the wild card that
dislodged the usual relationships in the layout and acted as a
magnet for additional functions the Urbans wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frano and I were interested in bringing the pool into the
gallery, because we saw it could have a double life,'' said Ms.
Kennedy, who is also an associate professor at the Harvard Graduate
School of Design. ``We thought the pool would also be a water piece
_ an art piece _ with surfaces that reflect light.'' They saw that
the pool would function as a wall _ ``because you couldn't walk
across it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So the architects performed surgery on the original house,
opening its side to draw out a narrow isthmus of space (now the
site of the piano) that connects to the addition. The architects
shaped the overall geometry by inverting the gable so that, from
the outside, the roof line takes on the topography of an angular
hill. A frosted glass trough in the new roof, at the center of the
addition, acts as a skylight over the pool and anchors the roof
planes that fly up to a band of clerestory windows around the
perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   The outside of the house changes character several times _
intimate around the back courtyard and monumental on the side where
the lap pool bursts through the wall. Inside, the roof looks like
an umbrella blown inside out by a gust of wind.
</P>
<P>
   While the addition roughly doubles the size of the house, it
nearly quadruples the wall space for paintings, from 600 square
feet to 2,200 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   To maximize wall space, the architects invented what they call
``near furniture'' _ small built-in pieces that incorporate
cabinets, air grills and lighting elements. The largest piece of
near furniture is in Urban's home office. As the bridge over the
pool descends into the office area, one side metamorphoses into
cabinets and desktop.
</P>
<P>
   The pool acts as a reflecting pond or, perhaps, a conceptual
water installation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pool changes the color of the light, and the play of the
light on the ripples reflects on the walls and makes the whole
space feel more alive,'' Mrs. Urban said. ``It changes all the
time, the natural light mixing with the artificial light, and all
of it reacting with the surfaces of the painting. We get surprising
moments.''
</P>
<P>
   To handle the dampness, the architects designed a glass pavilion
around the pool, with disappearing sliding doors that contain the
humidity when the pool is heated in the winter. The roof of the
pavilion contains a system of air ducts.
</P>
<P>
   Multiplying the functions in the space alters the experience of
viewing the paintings.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the pool that changes the experience most radically.
``You can see the artwork when you're in the water _ as though
you're swimming in a museum,'' Mrs. Urban said. ``And the water
reflects light on the art. I like that overlay. With the water by
my side, I feel its tranquillity as I'm looking at a work of art. I
enjoy just knowing it's there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 1746EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
