<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0283 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1805 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURT-CALIF-WELFARE-H     01-13 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-CALIF-WELFARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT SHOWS IT'S SKEPTICAL ABOUT CALIFORNIA WELFARE LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Several U.S. Supreme Court justices on Wednesday
indicated they were skeptical about a 1997 California law that
would confer lower welfare benefits to newcomers than to more
established residents.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg said the law may violate the
constitutionally protected right to travel by setting up financial
roadblocks to migrating welfare recipients.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the genius of the United States,'' she said. ``People
can pick their states, and states can't pick their people.''
</P>
<P>
   After Congress passed its 1996 welfare reform law, California,
like 14 other states, redesigned its welfare system to pay new
residents who sign up for aid only as much as they would have
received in their former states. Newcomers could receive full
California benefits after one year of residency.
</P>
<P>
   California's welfare program is among the most generous, ranking
sixth among all 50 states in terms of individual welfare benefits.
</P>
<P>
   This means that the vast majority of newcomers would receive
less money than established residents. For example, California
would pay an established family of four $673 per month, but if that
family had recently arrived from Mississippi, for example, it would
receive $144 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Congress allowed the two-tier system to prevent states with
higher benefits from becoming ``welfare magnets'' that would
attract migrating poor people. If welfare migration were to happen,
lawmakers feared that states might engage in a ``race to the
bottom'' to lower their benefits and make themselves less
attractive.
</P>
<P>
   ``This law blatantly treats new residents differently from other
residents and prevents citizens from freely choosing the state in
which they wish to live,'' Mark Rosenbaum, attorney for a group of
welfare recipients, told the justices Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbaum's clients, a woman and a family, sued the state in
1997 because they would have received lower welfare benefits under
the new law.
</P>
<P>
   The family, listed under the fictitious name the Roes, moved to
Long Beach, Calif., from Oklahoma qualified to $307 per month under
the new law compared to the in-state resident benefit of $565.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, Anna Doe, moved to Los Angeles from Washington, D.C.,
when she was six months pregnant was slated to receive $330 per
month under the new law, compared to an in-state resident benefit
of $456.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. district judge ruled on April 1, 1997 that the new law
was unconstitutional. The court said the law penalized migration
between states in violation of the equal protection clause of the
14th Amendment. The next year, the 9th Circuit Court of Appeals in
a unanimous decision agreed.
</P>
<P>
   The high court's decision, which is expected by July, could
force California to restructure its welfare program, the nation's
largest with about 2.6 million recipients and a $6 billion budget.
The decision also could impact other states that have enacted
similar laws under the 1996 welfare reform law passed by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   During Wednesday's arguments before the high court, Justice
Sandra Day O'Connor pressed California Deputy Attorney General
Theodore Garelis to show why his state's law does not infringe on a
person's right to move to California.
</P>
<P>
   Garelis answered that while the law may ``impede'' migration to
California, it certainly does not prevent freedom of travel.
``People move for a host of reasons, with welfare benefits being
only one,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the law does not ``hurt'' newcomers because they
do receive benefits and those payments increase to California
levels after a year. ``In the end, they're no worse off than if
they had stayed in their original state,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A skeptical O'Connor replied: ``You'd be hard-pressed to tell a
family who must live on welfare that getting $300 a month instead
of $600 a month is not painful. This has grave consequences for
that family.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Ginsburg asked Garelis why California chose to reduce
welfare benefits of newcomers, while not lowering their
unemployment benefits or adjusting their taxes to the level of
their old states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there something special about welfare benefits that
distinguishes them from other kinds of benefits?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Garelis said the state felt lowering welfare benefits was ``the
best way to save money.''
</P>
<P>
   Justices Stephen G. Breyer, Anthony M. Kennedy and John Paul
Stevens also appeared skeptical about the California law.
</P>
<P>
   The only justice to show sympathy to Garelis was Antonin Scalia,
who noted that states often treat new residents or travelers
differently than established residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every state that I know of charges higher tuition in their
universities for out-of-state residents and doesn't give the
in-state tuition until they live in the state at least a year,'' he
said. He added that states also charge different fees for hunting
and fishing for non-residents.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration asked the court to send the case back
to lower courts to decide if the statute fully conforms to 1996
welfare law passed by Congress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
