<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CLINTON _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's lawyers file
a brief of more than 100 pages in preparation for opening arguments
Thursday in the Senate impeachment trial. (Deans, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   OTHER IMPEACHMENT SIDEBARS
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-JURORS _ WASHINGTON _ Breakdown on various blocs among
the senators and who viewers should watch for: Northeast GOP
moderates targeted by Dems (Collins, Chaffee, Jeffords, Snowe) GOP
pragmatists (Lott, McConnell); hardliners, Senators facing
elections (and likely to keep a low profile), etc. (Foskett,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-BARR _ WAHINGTON _ Bob Barr's job as a House manager is
to persuade Senators to see the merits of the case against
President Clinton. But, in the weeks before the trial, Barr has
gone out of his way to insult these jurors, questioning both their
attention spans and backbone. (Carr, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-WORLD _ MOSCOW _ As opening arguments begin today(Jan.
14) in the Senate trial of American President Bill Clinton, is the
world still paying attention? Or are they growing more weary of
this saga than the American public? Developing. (Foreign staff, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TV _ You say you're tired of the Clinton scandal. You
can't stand to watch a second more. But watch you will. Ratings are
up across the board on CNN, MSNBC, Fox News Channel and more for
Clinton coverage. (Jubera, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TVBOX _ Where to watch it, and what you'll see. (Jubera,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CHABOT _ WASHINGTON _ When Ohio's Rep. Steve Chabot made
his living as a lawyer, he was the legal equivalent of the family
doctor. Advertised in the Yellow Pages, Chabot's one-man law office
handled cases across the legal spectrum from criminal defense to
divorce court. It was a mix of work Chabot categorizes under the
heading of ``whatever came in the door.'' But now, Chabot's legal
profile is about to rise. Just weeks into his third term in
Congress, this former elementary school teacher is part of the team
of prosecutors that on Thursday will begin presenting a case for
removing President Clinton from office. (Montgomery, Dayton Daily
News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DISABLED-ADDICTS _ WASHINGTON _ Drunks and addicts can become
disabled. Disabled people can abuse alcohol or drugs. On Wednesday,
a federal panel of physicians and other professionals releases a
new ``treatment protocol'' _ advice to their peers on successful
methods of treating someone with this particularly frustrating
combination of symptoms. Recovering substance abusers who are
disabled will be there to comment. (Mollison, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Cox photos for this story will be placed in the National folder
on the Cox server.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ Continuing spot coverage of the federal
antitrust trial against Microsoft Corp. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   FLYNT-TALKS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ It's easy to forget, I suppose, but
Larry Flynt is a former Daytonian, worked here for six years and
started the publication here that became Hustler magazine. In an
interview Wednesday, Flynt recalled his days in Dayton and
explained his motivation in investigating the pasts of prominent
Republicans. Asked if he feels more legitimate now, Flynt said no,
he's still a smut peddler. (Beyerlein, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   GINGRICH-DISTRICT _ATLANTA _Two non-residents of the 6th
Congressional District jump into the race to replace Newt Gingrich.
(Visser, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-D0LE-PRESIDENCY _ CONCORD, N.H. _ Years after other
potential GOP presidential candidates began campaigning in this
bellwether state, two noncampaigners have jumped way ahead of the
pack. In results that confirm speculation that noncandidate
Elizabeth Dole could provide the most serious challenge to
noncandidate George W. Bush, a Manchester TV station poll gives
Dole a slight edge among New Hampshire Republicans, but within the
margin of error. Bush and Dole both have said they are undecided on
a presidential candidacy. Dole got a bump in the polls last week
after she resigned as president of the American Red Cross.
Political leaders here expect them both to run. (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   CLEAN-MARSH (developing) _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The federal
government helped craft Florida's $763 million Everglades cleanup
plan, but five years later the project still lacks a federal
permit. Now the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency is offering a
permit, but it has all kinds of strings that South Florida water
managers and the sugar industry object to. Among them: super-strict
rules on how much polluting phosphorus the cleansed water may
contain. The feds say they'll relax the rules if research later
shows that the Everglades can take more phosphorus, but the growers
say they smell a trap. Meanwhile, environmental groups say the
strict rules are needed to keep the state and sugar from colluding
on a ``cleanup'' that leaves the Everglades polluted. Sugar growers
will urge the water managers today to either reject the permit or
seek big changes. (King, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   PRAYERONAIR _ ATLANTA _Supporters of Conyers, Ga., visionary
Nancy Fowler are taking to the airways to get the whole world
praying for peace. In a monthly international telecast, backed
largely by Martin Folse, president of HTV of Houma, La., a free,
hour-long program now will be part of a daytime television lineup.
Fowler claim to have spoken to the Virgin Mary and thousands of
people have attended rallies at her farm.(Scott, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SMOKE-MONEY (developing) _ Lawyers who represented Florida in
its successful lawsuit against tobacco money are meeting in Orlando
to decide how much of their fees to give to the Lawton and Rhea
Chiles Center for Healthy Mothers and Babies, and other charities.
Lawton Chiles, who died last month, pushed for the lawsuit while
governor of Florida. (Hiaasen, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   NEW-BISHOP _ PALM BEACH GARDENS, Fla. _ Anthony J. O'Connell
becomes the third bishop of the Diocese of Palm Beach today in
investiture services at the cathedral. Gushee spends time with him
in Knoxville, Tenn., on his last weekend in that diocese and writes
a profile, laced with color and comments from the parishioners
there. (Gushee, Palm Beach Post). 74. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) general news and (l) Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   GA-BUDGET _ATLANTA _Governor Barnes proposes $13.3 billion
spending plan for FY 2000, that includes $760 million in new
spending (a 5.6 percent increase). Highlights include: $12.9M for
alternative schools; $48.6M for new prisons; $17.3M for juvenile
justice improvements and $83M for the first phase of a property tax
cut. (Mantius, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WELFARE _ An Ohio Senator is taking Bob Taft to task over his
inaugural example of a welfare reform success story. Taft
highlighted the succes of a Dayton woman, Shannon Stavis, who went
from welfare to work with training at Miami Jacobs College. State
Sen. Fingerhut says under GOP sponsored welfare reform Stavis could
not have gotten her benefits while going to schools. (Jasper,
Dayton Daily News). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   SEXOFFENDER _ Accused sex offender in court on charges of raping
a girl younger than 13. ART: mug shot. (Springfield Daily News).
12.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-DRUG-MOVIE _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ While the students at
Lake Worth High School were being held to a strict ``Zero
Tolerance'' anti-drug policy last week, Palm Beach County's film
commission was unwittingly helping a low-budget film crew shoot a
comic drug deal in one of the school's bathrooms. ``Dave's Day
Out'' begins when Dave buys some marijuana in the bathroom. (Hayes,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TIRED-MAILMAN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Maybe rain or sleet can't stop
postal workers _ but what if they're tired? A former mail carrier
has been charged with keeping and opening 30,383 letters and
packages, including 208 parcels _ and authorities are holding it
all as evidence until the case is closed. James S. Wynn, 54, faces
a maximum of five years in prison and a $250,000 fine, is charged
in U.S. District Court in Dayton in a bill of information. (Hills,
Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-SCHOOL-SNOWDAYS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Local school officials can
expect a chilly reception if they go to the Ohio legislature
seeking additional snow days. Some lawmakers who would have to
approve any increase in the number of calamity days granted school
districts said they did not think an extension was likely.
(Bebbington, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   STATE LEGISLATIVE NEWS
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-BUDGET _ State spending would creep above the $90 billion
mark for 200-2001, under a budget plan proposed by legislative
leaders. The Legislative Budget Board spending plan, widely
considered the blueprint for the state budget, would increase
spending 3.8 percent overall and 6 percent in general fund
expenditures, which are those funded by taxes. (E;izondo, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
