<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1816 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TVSURFER-COLUMN14-COX     01-13 0436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVSURFER-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Actor portrays King with emotional power
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Clifton Powell says he was about 12 and
oblivious to the civil rights movement when he came home one night
in 1968 and found his father crying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew something big had happened, cause my dad never cried.
He said, 'Dr. King has just been killed.' I was deeply into sports
and almost a teenager, and the civil rights movement just hadn't
registered on me. It didn't affect my life.
</P>
<P>
   ``But from that day, I started my education in the civil rights
movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Powell is a part of that education for a new generation.
He's playin the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. in the ``The Wonderful
World of Disney'' TV movie ``Selma, Lord, Selma'' (7 p.m. Sunday on
ABC).
</P>
<P>
   Powell, who starred in the short-lived Fox series ``South
Central,'' trimmed his moustache to match King's and studied old
footage to learn his speaking voice. ``I tried to get tapes of him
away from the crowd, just sitting with the SCLC or in the back room
meetings,'' he says during an interview at an ABC party for the
nation's TV critics meeting here. ``I wanted to capture his natural
voice, when he wasn't doing a sermon.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie, filmed in Atlanta, Griffin, Ga., and Selma, Ala., in
Setpember and airing on the eve of King Day, also stars Yolanda
King, the late minister's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``She plays a schoolteacher,'' Powell says. ``For one of my
sermons, she was sitting in the back of the church just listening.
After we finished I went to her and we both started crying. It was
so emotional.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more emotional, Powell says, was re-enacting the march on
the Edmund Pettis Bridge and Bloody Sunday, milestones in the
movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just can't imagine how Dr. King and those people faced any
of that. The feeling of walking up to those policemen and knowing
they're not going to really hit us is a lot more of a relief than
walking up there and knowing that you're going to get beat down. I
don't think I could have done it.''
</P>
<P>
   SEEN AND HEARD
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's impeachment on TNT
</P>
<P>
   At noon Sunday, Turner Classic Movies will air the 1942 film
``Tennessee Johnson.'' It chronicles President Andrew Johnson's
impeachment hearings some 130 years ago. Van Heflin plays Johnson
with Lionel Barrymore portraying Sen. Thad Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   _Contributing: Bob Longino and news services
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
