<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0290 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1817 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOG-FRIEND-NYT &LR;      01-13 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOG-FRIEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME COLUMN: ADOPTED UNAWARES IN RED HOOK 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ANNE RAVER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RED HOOK, N.Y. _ We never talked to each other until the big
yellow dog showed up, lying like a sphinx under the goal posts of
the soccer field. ``Come over here, honey,'' Charlie Mae called,
only I didn't know her name then. To me, she was the jaunty woman
who walked the track every morning in a colorful headdress, a loose
skirt that came to her calves and red tights with Reeboks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come over here, girl,'' she said in a velvety voice. ``Aren't
you a pretty girl? Who could've dumped you?''
</P>
<P>
   Hemingway, the Great Pyrenees who drags me to the park every
morning, hardly gave the stray a second glance. It was Monday, and
two days' worth of picnickers had left a wealth of chicken bones in
the grass. His big black nose was working the ground like a metal
detector.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at those big ears,'' I said as we stared at the dog. One
ear stood up, the other flopped. She had a broad head and a big
pink nose, and squinty eyes. She looked like Miss Piggy. Mostly
Labrador, with some pit bull mixed in. Or maybe Akita.
</P>
<P>
   A little man in a hooded sweatshirt, who never said a word as he
did his morning crunches and knee bends with the discipline and
silence of a Buddhist monk, now walked onto the field with a Rite
Aid bag full of scraps, dumped them on the ground and spoke to the
dog in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Now Hemingway was interested. The crunch of bones between
another dog's jaws was riveting.
</P>
<P>
   Hemingway is not my dog. He belongs to the people I rent from,
but they don't have the time to exercise him. He's beautiful, all
white with big black liquid eyes and a big black nose. But he's a
work dog; he needs a farm to run on, a herd of sheep to tend. I
started to walk him every morning because I felt sorry for him, and
now, as soon as he hears my coffee grinder, he starts howling.
</P>
<P>
   Now he was watching this upstart eat pork chop bones as I and
the others tried to cajole her closer. She'd wag her whole body,
drawing her black lips back from her long white teeth in a worried
little crocodile smile. But she wouldn't budge.
</P>
<P>
   The man in the sweatshirt, who told us he was from Puerto Rico
and had just moved to Red Hook Houses, said he had seen a family
dump her here. ``They went to Florida,'' was all he said.
</P>
<P>
   It went on like that for a couple of weeks, as people brought
food and talked about who among us could adopt her (no one), or if
we knew anybody who could.
</P>
<P>
   One day a big Buick drove up on the grass, and a woman got out
with her own bag of scraps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honey,'' one of our band called out, ``that dog already had
two breakfasts!'' We felt a little proprietary by this time, almost
hostile, as the woman defiantly plopped some pancakes onto the
grass. It was obvious that this dog was not going to starve. But
winter was coming. And we worried about wild dogs, like the pit
bulls turned out of Red Hook Houses when the Housing Authority
ordered tenants to give up their dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen guys sic their pit bulls on her,'' a man had told me
one day as Hemingway and I left the park. ``She sleeps in that
empty lot over there.'' This man parks his van at the edge of the
field every morning and lets his three cocker spaniels run about as
he drinks his coffee. We'd never exchanged more than a nod before,
but there was something lovable about this big yellow dog with the
soft ears and gentle independence.
</P>
<P>
   One day at last, the dog (we called her Red for Red Hook)
trotted up to Hemingway and playfully bit his neck. Then she bowed,
rump up, paws down, inviting him to play. And the two of them
gamboled down the field as I let the leash out as far as I could,
while they leapt and gnawed and growled at each other. Once in a
while, Red would tug at the leash, as if to say, ``Let him off this
thing so we can have some real fun.''
</P>
<P>
   So Hemingway became the love object, and I started trying to
lead Red home, using Hemmie as bait. I also asked around to see if
anyone wanted a dog. I even rang some doorbells to show her off.
One friend fell in love with her, but then the friend's arthritis
flared up.
</P>
<P>
   By now, Red was loping after us as we walked down the streets.
But she would veer off when Hemingway and I got to our corner. I
tried to lure her through the front gate with chicken scraps, but
she would have none of it. So one morning I tried the Tom Sawyer
routine, feigning no interest in anyone helping to whitewash the
fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on, Hemingway,'' I said, without a backward glance as I
left all the doors open to the backyard. It didn't work the first
time. But on the second try, I heard paws trotting down the
hallway. She bounded through the back door to leap on her lover
boy, and I slammed it shut.
</P>
<P>
   From then on, Red was ours, like it or not. I tried to give her
to an artist down the street whose little boy fell in love with
Red, but within half an hour she was at our gate. I took her back,
but she slipped away again in the pouring rain and sat by the front
door, barking, until we let her in.
</P>
<P>
   So now there are two dogs at our house on Dikeman Street. One
afternoon the neighborhood children married them in the backyard.
Hemingway wore a bow tie, Red a little skirt made of a shawl. The
two play-fight for hours on the deck, then flop down for a snooze,
head to head.
</P>
<P>
   I've remembered the comfort of dogs. They were my constant
companions when I was a child. As a young woman, I had a dog,
Molly, who knew me in some uncanny way. She was my spirit dog. I
think you get only one of those in your life, but I guess I'm ready
to love some others. I'd been waiting for that life in the country,
when I could work at home and let my dogs use a dog door.
</P>
<P>
   But two big dogs adopted me in the middle of my real life. It
isn't convenient. I don't have a lot of time. But living with me is
better than being mauled by a pit bull. And Hemingway is so much
calmer now, he reminds me of a man with slippers.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the weather is cold, they spend their nights with me,
and I love to hear them breathing as I drift off, peaceful and safe
with my pack.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
