<SLUG> BC-TV-MACDONALD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORM MACDONALD ISN'T IN IT FOR THE APPLAUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ You get the feeling that Norm Macdonald
requires adult supervision, but that you wouldn't want the job.
</P>
<P>
   He's surely left behind a string of sputtering, red-faced
relatives, teachers, neighbors, bureaucrats, bosses and _ this we
know for sure _ network TV executives.
</P>
<P>
   Macdonald will listen, but with a crooked half smile that tells
you he thinks you're crazy, and then do exactly as he damn well
pleases.
</P>
<P>
   Don Ohlmeyer, a very large suit at NBC, tried to get Macdonald
to knuckle under and finally fired him, a year ago, from ``Saturday
Night Live.'' Ohlmeyer didn't like Macdonald's ``Weekend Update.''
Macdonald apparently didn't care what Ohlmeyer liked or didn't
like.
</P>
<P>
   So now Macdonald is rewarded with his own ABC prime-time comedy
series, ``The Norm Show,'' scheduled to premiere in March. He'll
play a social worker who _ surprise! _ can't abide rules and
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I can fail upward all the way,'' Macdonald says of his
capacity to parlay apparent screwups into career advances.
</P>
<P>
   Getting fired made Macdonald instantly infamous, and a bit of a
hero, because of suspicions that Macdonald's O.J. Simpson jokes
were the real burrs for Ohlmeyer, a longtime friend and supporter
of Simpson's.
</P>
<P>
   ``This publicity did help me,'' Macdonald told critics during an
ABC interview session this week, ``because all publicity is good
publicity, as Hitler said.''
</P>
<P>
   But wasn't a network pink slip upsetting? Didn't Macdonald fear,
however fleetingly, that he'd somehow scuttled a career that began
in the stand-up comedy dens of eastern Canada?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I mean, I don't want to be maudlin or anything,'' he
said, ``but my dad, when I was a young boy, told me that, you know,
life would not always be easy, and God knows he had hard times. And
he said that in times of trouble, you should drink a lot of
whiskey.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, Macdonald slouched back in his chair, hands on his
knees, and waited for the silence to be broken by laughter. It took
a long five-count.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Macdonald eventually added, he has nothing against
Ohlmeyer, NBC's soon-to-depart West Coast president. He doubts that
his firing was due to ``the O.J. thing'' and agrees that his
``Weekend Update'' segments weren't ``an audience-pleasing, warm
kind of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I did jokes that I knew weren't going to get big reactions,''
Macdonald said. ``I think he just, his thing to me was always like,
`Hey, Jay (Leno) goes out there every night and kills with his
monologues, and they applaud constantly, and you don't, even though
you only have to do it one night a week.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So I saw his point, you know. But I wasn't trying to please
the audience. So I can understand from a businessman that why the
f_ would you want some dude not trying to please the audience?''
</P>
<P>
   Radical thought, but isn't pleasing the audience the point of
show business?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I just try to, like, please my buddies and myself,''
Macdonald said. ``I know that you can do certain jokes, like I know
on `Update' oftentimes people would offer jokes to me, the idea
being like, you know, Newt Gingrich being a Nazi or something.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I knew that the audience would applaud that, but I never
thought Newt Gingrich was a Nazi. I hate doing jokes where people
applaud, you know? Because they're not laughing, you know what I
mean?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the thing. I loved Johnny Carson when he would do a
joke and when the joke didn't work, he would backtrack. That was
always very funny. Like he'd go, `Ahhh, I guess that one ...'
That's my Carson impression. And it seemed like everybody tried to
do that afterward. In other words, you'd do the joke, then if it
doesn't work, you're embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling always was, I like the f_ joke. And so if the
audience doesn't laugh, that doesn't mean (set ital)I'm(end ital)
wrong. It means (set ital)they're(end ital) wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   In that case, the audience couldn't possibly have been more
wrong about ``Dirty Work,'' a feature film Macdonald co-wrote and
starred in last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the audience not laugh, it didn't even get within
chuckle distance of the theaters where ``Dirty Work'' was playing.
</P>
<P>
   So of course Macdonald was asked about that particular exercise
in cinematic futility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they put the movie out in the summer against
blockbusters,'' he said. ``Some people have told me that's the
reason.
</P>
<P>
   He paused a beat and added, ``Some people say that the film is
just f_ horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   But then, that would be their fault.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
