<SLUG> BC-KINGHOLIDAY-SERVICE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KING'S FAMILY WANTS HOLIDAY TO BE ABOUT HELPING OTHERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSAMY BROWN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Independence Day, families watch fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   Thanksgiving is a turkey and football gorgefest.
</P>
<P>
   But what to do on Martin Luther King Jr.'s birthday, an American
holiday so new that there aren't widespread traditions?
</P>
<P>
   During his life, King led the movement for civil rights for
African-Americans and equality for all. So his family wants the
holiday honoring him to be more than a day off from work or school.
They are promoting the annual event as a national day of service,
on which people do hands-on things to help others.
</P>
<P>
   ``People working together and getting to know each other, that's
improving the quality of relationships among people. People working
together learn to respect each other,'' Coretta Scott King, 71, the
Baptist minister's widow, said in a telephone interview. ``To
improve race relations starts with relationships among people. We
have to work at it. It's not going to happen by itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin Luther King Jr. was born Jan. 15, 1929, in Atlanta and
assassinated on April 4, 1968, in Memphis, Tenn., where he was
leading a strike of sanitation workers. President Reagan in 1983
signed papers making the third Monday in January a holiday for
remembering King and honoring his legacy. The nation's first
observance of King Day was in January 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Coretta Scott King suggests that Americans take an hour or two
to read to an elderly person or go grocery shopping for invalids.
Schools need painting and voters need registering, she said last
week.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site for the Martin Luther King Jr. Center for
Nonviolent Social Change (www.thekingcenter.com) suggests that
people donate books about King, civil rights and black history to
prisons, nursing homes or halfway houses. Planting a tree and
flying the U.S. flag are two additional ways to honor what King
stood for.
</P>
<P>
   Dexter King, 37, one of King's four children, said the holiday
should not be thought of as only for blacks, but as a celebration
of America's diversity and pledge to equality among people.
</P>
<P>
   King's message is universal, his son said, and the civil-rights
movement was subsequently used as a basis for the anti-Vietnam War
effort, the women's movement and the gay-rights movement in this
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `I am challenging America to be its best self, to
live up to the statement in the Constitution that all men are
created equal.' He said we have an obligation to live up to the
commitment that we've made to ourselves,'' said Dexter King,
president of the King Center in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Although much has changed since the 1960s, there's still work to
be done to achieve the goal of becoming a ``harmonious society,''
Coretta Scott King said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rosa Parks didn't organize a committee,'' she said, referring
to the seamstress who inspired the 1955 Montgomery, Ala., bus
boycott by refusing to give up her bus seat to a white rider, as
was required. ``If she had, we might still be arguing about how to
get things done. One person can make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
