<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE VENERABLE CBS NEWSMAGAZINE JOINS A CROWDED FIELD _ AND RAISES
EYEBROWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Word is that Don Hewitt, patriarch and
longtime producer of ``60 Minutes,'' is still miffed over this ``60
Minutes II,'' which made its debut Tuesday night. Hewitt's
aggravation, in fact, is receiving sound-bite treatment courtesy of
``60 Minutes II'' Executive Producer Jeff Fager, who is sharing the
story about arriving his first day and finding a note from Hewitt
attached to his door.
</P>
<P>
   It read: ``It's 6 a.m. I'm here. Where the &AMP;% are you?''
</P>
<P>
   Notes Fager: ``I think Don was still very nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, who isn't? Though the CBS brass insist that Hewitt has
given his blessing, ``60 Minutes'' veteran correspondent Mike
Wallace has repeatedly expressed that he thinks it's a lousy idea
for the highly distinguished newsmagazine to birth an offspring and
fall in line with the lesser shows such as ``Dateline NBC.''
</P>
<P>
   I can see the competitive, cranky Wallace growling something
about the selling of journalistic souls and jeopardizing
credibility and integrity just to turn a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Me? I simply find it gutsy for a network to dive headfirst into
a pool that's already being sucked bone-dry.
</P>
<P>
   Joining ``60 Minutes II'' next month will be a third edition of
ABC's ``20/20,'' plus a prime-time hour tentatively titled ``ABC
News Thursday.'' This will bring to 15 the number of hours on the
networks and cable, which is far more than any human should be
expected to digest, unless, of course, such viewing is used as a
torture tactic.
</P>
<P>
   The ratings, most of them heading south this year, seem to bear
out saturation levels. But the networks insist that viewers aren't
losing interest in the newsmags but in the ratings-challenged
sitcoms that are lead-ins. And besides, overall viewing on network
TV is down, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly, the largest audience exodus has been from ``Dateline
NBC,'' the format's leader with five installments a week.
Viewership is down for all except the Wednesday edition.
</P>
<P>
   Is it time to stop the newsmag madness? Those running the
networks think not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saying that there are too many newsmagazines was the same as
saying that there were too many talk shows before Ricki Lake
entered the group,'' says Susanne Daniels, president of
entertainment at The WB. ``What \Rcreators\S did so well with Ricki
Lake was take a new twist on an old talk format. That can be done
with newsmagazines. There's always room for that in television.''
</P>
<P>
   The scary thought is that at least three networks seem to be
moving inexorably toward a daily prime-time news hour, which would
merely combine an evening news-style wrap-up of the day's events
with the usual shopworn stories and consumer scare-tactic pieces.
Like when a ``Dateline'' story on trucking called America's
highways ``a trucker's killing fields!''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has spent much time watching newsmagazines knows how
unoriginal the stories are. Good investigative reporting takes time
_ something your average magazine show doesn't have.
</P>
<P>
   The growing problem, though, is that because they compete in the
entertainment milieu, these shows must acquire certain aspects of
entertainment programming. They have ``stars'' (Jane Pauley and
Stone Phillips, Diane Sawyer and Hugh Downs, Barbara Walters and
Sam Donaldson, Katie Couric and Maria Shriver), titillation in the
form of hidden cameras, and hype in the form of enticing on-air
promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Many segments are merely re-examinations of earlier stories or
pieces plucked out of some print magazine or newspaper, often
tabloidy in nature.
</P>
<P>
   One producer who didn't want his name or affiliation used said
that network executives even request minute-by-minute ratings on
newsmagazines, so it is known not only which stories entice
viewers, but also which aspects of those stories get their hearts
racing.
</P>
<P>
   As for ``60 Minutes II,'' well, it's here for the same reasons
that NBC has stuck ``Dateline'' under a copy machine. Newsmagazines
have in the past been extremely profitable, earning dependable
Nielsen ratings in almost any prime-time hour.
</P>
<P>
   NBC has learned _ and this was Hewitt's point early on _ that
it's easier to stick in a ``Dateline'' than to find another
``Seinfeld'' or ``ER,'' which is costing the network a small
fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Moonves, president of CBS Television, argued vigorously
for ``60 Minutes II'' on the notion that finding dramas hasn't been
the problem _ getting people to watch them has.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why newsmagazines are easy picks,'' he says. ``They
cost half the amount of money. And it's easy to sell. Look at NBC.
``Trinity'' goes off the air and they put ``Dateline'' in there.
Nice fix. Easy fix. You know it's a solid performer. Problem
solved.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Moonves would rather not see a TV universe filled
with newsmagazines, ``New dramas are difficult to launch. Our two
highest-rated new shows are ``L.A. Doctors'' and ``Martial Law.''
Neither one of them is knocking down the world yet.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to say whether ``60 Minutes II'' will, either.
Correspondents Bob Simon and Dan Rather'' are familiar faces.
Charlie Rose is the acerbic late-night host with a reputation for
being a disarming questioner; Vicki Mabrey and Carol Marin are
lesser-known, but are considered smart reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``60 Minutes II'' plans to follow the same ``60 Minutes''
format: three stories, an occasional commentary, letters segments,
and the familiar ticking clock.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting with TV critics over the weekend, Moonves tried his best
to separate ``60 Minutes II'' from what producer Dick Wolf ``(Law &AMP;
Order)'' calls cookie-cutter television and ``the enemy of
dramas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there should be a balance between comedy, between
news, between movies,'' he said. ``And have they overdone it, some
of our competitors? Possibly.'' But not CBS, even though a ``48
Hours'' offspring is also rumored.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to duplicate the best traditions, the
highest-quality storytelling, the highest- quality interviewing,
the best stories, week in and week out,'' says Fager. ``And we'll
do that with an A-team of broadcast journalists both on and off the
air. I don't see how anyone can object to that.''
</P>
<P>
   The only objection so far has been to one of the show's
commentators, comedian Jimmy Tingle. Fager calls him ``sharp'' and
``opinionated.''
</P>
<P>
   He's more than that. A comic on a ``60 Minutes'' franchise is
yet another example of how news and entertainment have become
basically one and the same.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
