<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Jan. 14, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Treacherous traveling conditions Thursday will prevail from
southern New England across the central Appalachians to the eastern
Ohio Valley, where a combination of snow, sleet and freezing rain
will fall. A series of disturbances will cause mild, moist air to
rise as it encounters a mound of Arctic air centered over eastern
Canada. Periods of snow will occur though midday from northern Ohio
to southern New England. The cold air will gradually be eroded
causing the snow to mix with sleet and freezing rain later in the
day. Milder air from the ocean will cause the mixed precipitation
to eventually change to rain near the coast. Sleet and freezing
rain will be persistent in the central Appalachians resulting in an
accumulation of ice, some of which will cling to trees and power
lines. Farther south, rain will dampen most areas near the Middle
Atlantic Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds and showers will be scattered ahead of a cold front as it
moves through the Southeastern States. A few stronger thunderstorms
will develop near the Gulf Coast as increasingly humid air moves
north ahead of the front. Clouds and cool breezes will linger
behind the front in the lower Mississippi Valley. Farther west,
partly to mostly sunny skies will develop over the southern Plains
although it will be cooler than recently.
</P>
<P>
   A front in the Dakotas will separate cold air and snow showers
over the Great Lakes and northern Mississippi Valley from much
milder air and gusty winds in the northern Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Rain will accompany a front in the Pacific Northwest. Meanwhile,
the Southwestern States will remain dry.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Understanding Ice
</P>
<P>
   An icy mixture will fall in much of the Northeast on Thursday.
Nearly all winter precipitation starts as snow 10 to 20 thousand
feet above the ground. The type of precipitation that reaches the
ground is determined during the last 5,000 feet of descent.
Sometimes a warm layer aloft will melt the snowflake before
reaching the ground. If a shallow layer of subfreezing air is
present at the surface, the raindrop freezes on contact, producing
the glaze condition called freezing rain. A deeper layer of cold
air will cause the drop to freeze into a pellet of ice known as
sleet.
</P>
</TEXT>
