<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SACKS-TILES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLAY FEAT: DESIGNER IS TILE STYLE GURU
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GAILE ROBINSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Name a linoleum designer. How about an artist known for
cabinets, faucets or floors? No? It's understandable. In those
trades, most of the creative people labor in obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   The tile industry, though, has a star. Her name is Ann Sacks,
and she is bringing her exquisite tiles to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   After the International Home Builders Show closes Jan. 17, the
Ann Sacks Tile &AMP; Stone store and showroom will open to the public
in Dallas' Design District. In an enclave of brick fortresses
hiding their precious contents from public view, Sacks'
glass-walled space is as open and enticing as a chest full of
jewels. It stands out.
</P>
<P>
   Her work always does. Sacks manipulates tile as fashion
designer, architect, engineer and archaeologist. She includes
stone, metals and glass in her mosaic palette.
</P>
<P>
   Sacks makes narrow, heavily textured tiles to border walls,
reminiscent of boucle trim on a Chanel jacket. On a floor of huge,
matte-glazed tiles, she embeds brilliant little pieces of glass
that look like jeweled buttons on gray velvet.
</P>
<P>
   She shakes free of the traditional 4-inch-square boundaries. Her
tiles are large, larger _ and minuscule. They are rectangular like
shoe boxes, or interlocking odd shapes resembling an M.C. Escher
background. They are thick, thin, heavily textured or as slick and
reflective as a mirror. They are glazed with the intense hues of
semiprecious stones or mottled with a multitude of earth colors.
</P>
<P>
   Sacks tiles entire rooms. She makes border tiles that look like
baseboards and then turns them upside down, places them at the top
of the wall and turns them into crown molding.
</P>
<P>
   She buys old terra-cotta tiles from houses and barns that are
being demolished in France. The barn tiles _ flat terra-cotta
rectangles that have a concave surface _ were used inside the barn
roofs. The six-sided kitchen tiles have seen decades of wear and
wine spills and are all the more beautiful for their nicks and
stains.
</P>
<P>
   ``They come here covered with mold, dirt and pieces of mortar,
and you can see the history in them,'' Sacks says reverently.
</P>
<P>
   She saves stones from ancient buildings in Israel. The crude
limestone blocks with their rough-hewn surfaces are carefully
numbered, registered and shipped to Sacks. She calls the
centuries-old building blocks her biblical stones and sells them
for $48 a square foot. She is dunned an additional export tax
because they are antiquities.
</P>
<P>
   A more affordable limestone look can be found on the back wall
of the Sacks showroom. What looks like Texas Hill Country limestone
isn't natural at all. The synthetic material is called Jacques
Rocks, and it can be put up right over Sheetrock without any other
supporting subsurface. It sells for $7 a square foot.
</P>
<P>
   The price range in the various lines is extreme, from a few
dollars to $250 a square foot. When faced with a tight budget,
Sacks recommends using more tile in a lower price range. She likes
to see rooms covered in tile, at least one entire wall and the
floor. She covered her kitchen in rectangular white tiles that are
priced at $4 a square foot. The more tile, the more stunning the
effect, she maintains.
</P>
<P>
   Sacks took a winding course to find her calling, even though the
big sign, the neon light of awareness, presented itself to her in a
Mexican shower stall when she was 13.
</P>
<P>
   She was on a family vacation at a resort in Mexico, and the bath
area was covered in Talavera tiles. The blue, green and gold colors
and hand-painted organic design fused to her memory. It was an
epiphany.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can still remember walking into that shower,'' Sacks says as
she closes her eyes to conjure up the vision that has stayed with
her for years.
</P>
<P>
   At 13, epiphanies, hormonal surges and the stress of family
vacations can be confusing. Whatever the reason, Sacks finished her
education with a degree in English literature and a fall-back
position in education. She accumulated a husband, children and
experience as a teacher and social worker.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, just when her life seemed on a predictable trajectory,
Talavera tiles made another appearance, this time in a Portland
gift shop. They had been backed with felt and were displayed next
to the cash register, to encourage an impulse buy. It worked. Sacks
bought them all and ordered more.
</P>
<P>
   She began importing large terra-cotta tiles and brilliant
Talaveras from Mexico. She tiled entire rooms in her house. She
covered her tables, then began tiling her husband's office. She
became the source for Mexican tiles in the Pacific Northwest. Her
home was her showroom. Soon she was manufacturing tiles of her own
design.
</P>
<P>
   She quizzed a few designers. ``If I could do with tile what you
can get with Formica, would you be interested?'' The answer was an
emphatic ``yes.'' That was all she needed to jump-start her custom
collection.
</P>
<P>
   At first, her name would appear in small print buried in the
resource list within the glossy magazines. If a bathroom or kitchen
was so extraordinary that a reader was compelled to wade through
the interminable where-to-buy section, her name inevitably
appeared.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few years, the name Ann Sacks Tile &AMP; Stone began
appearing under the photos, like that of a furniture designer. She
had a signature, a look. She was a name.
</P>
<P>
   The giant Kohler company, makers of sinks, tubs and fixtures,
bought her business in 1989. There are now eight showrooms, with
the one in Dallas and one other opening in '99. The company employs
more than 100 people, 30 of whom are artists, in seven states.
</P>
<P>
   Rizzoli, publisher of fine art books, recognizes her special
place in the design pantheon and is releasing a book about Ann
Sacks and her tiles this spring.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to see her work, though, is to visit her store. You
can't miss it. It's the shining beacon of color and light one block
south of Stemmons Freeway on Oak Lawn Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
