<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0296 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1840 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSEUM-NEWDIRECTOR-2n     01-13 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSEUM-NEWDIRECTOR-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
FORT WORTH, Texas: that are available. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   And that's going to be serendipitous because of what comes
available or can be made to come available. So, here, I am not
focused on identifying gaps in the collection, which is very
different from Melbourne. In Melbourne, the collection was much
larger, and we did look for gaps that could be feasibly filled.
</P>
<P>
   Here, if we go for 20 years without buying a piece of European
sculpture, that's fine. If nothing is good enough, you wait until
the outstanding thing comes along. And, if there are wonderful
things in Asian art, 20 things in the next 10 years, then let's get
all 20 of them.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about blockbuster shows?
</P>
<P>
   A: Actually, that's a term I don't like. Because it has acquired
all sorts of bad connotations, and I think rightly so. What I like
to do is present good exhibitions, some of which will be big, which
the press will call ``blockbusters,'' and some of which will be
small and just as good and won't be called blockbusters.
</P>
<P>
   The aim always is to do the very finest exhibition of that
artist or subject or period that can be done at a certain time. ...
My experience has been that, if you focus on that core issue of
quality, the rest of the problems directors are forced to worry
about _ attendance, financial liability and so on _ do, in a way,
take care of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   If you put people in front of really great art and explain what
is important, by and large you get a really positive response. You
can put wonderful works together but, if they're from an exotic
culture and you don't explain them, people may be perplexed and
walk away feeling that they've had a great experience but it really
didn't mean anything to them.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about the idea that really great works don't need that
verbal support?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, there's an enormous amount of art historical knowledge
that art professionals bring to an exhibition that we all take for
granted. But it is a specialist's knowledge that most people don't
have. So it's not condescending in any way to say that people need
and want to be told what is interesting about the object in front
of them.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And that does justice to the object and the culture that
created it, as well. What about other exhibitions coming up, apart
from ``Matisse and Picasso''? I know there's an Egyptian faience
show.
</P>
<P>
   A: The schedule that was in place when I arrived had ``Matisse
and Picasso'' and faience the first half of the year, and the
permanent collection the second half. It might as well stay that
way, and it certainly won't worry me if it does.
</P>
<P>
   Most exhibitions of real substance that are already curated
somewhere else take more than a year to put together. So I'm not
about to scramble to find things to fill the gap. Because we don't
need to: The permanent collection is an important priority. So my
plans are focused on the years after 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So is there anything planned for the millennium?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are lots of things milling around. But it's too soon to
say. I'm not being coy. It's just too soon.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about working in the Unites States? When you still were
in Melbourne and we talked on the phone, you said you were looking
forward to working here because of some positive differences.
</P>
<P>
   A: It's very different. The private foundation support of a
museum like this and _ on a very straightforward level, the
relative lack of bureaucracy and unnecessary paperwork _ is a
delightful change from a public institution.
</P>
<P>
   Here, all the focus is on actually achieving the result.
Everything is determined by wanting to acquire the best work of
art, by wanting to put together the best possible exhibition. The
very senior people are focused on achieving the core mission of the
institution, and are very happy to talk about how to make it
happen.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Speaking of here, how do you find Fort Worth?
</P>
<P>
   A: People told me I would find Fort Worth very hospitable and
welcoming, and that's been absolutely true. My family and I have
been overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Any difficulty at all adjusting?
</P>
<P>
   A: Practically speaking, it's still a bit chaotic at home. And,
you know, you get used to a certain kind of espresso coffee. The
hardest thing about coming here has been getting a strong cup of
coffee that isn't a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What would be the most fun thing you've done since you got
here?
</P>
<P>
   A: I haven't asked myself that in quite those terms. But my
greatest sense of anticipation was to go through the vaults and
discover all the things I didn't know about or hadn't seen in
person before. Some of the antiquities. Some of the Old Masters.
And some of the pieces where it's not clear who the artist is _
famous ones like the La Tour ``Saint Sebastian.'' That has been
very exciting.
</P>
<P>
   (Janet Tyson is art critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. You
can call her at (817) 390-7679, or e-mail:
vizart(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
