<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1841 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSEUM-NEWDIRECTOR-96     01-13 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSEUM-NEWDIRECTOR-960(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW KIMBELL DIRECTOR TIMOTHY POTTS TALKS IN WIDE-RANGING INTERVIEW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JANET TYSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Oxford graduate, archaeologist, art
historian, husband and father, former art critic and financier,
semi-frustrated espresso drinker and new director of the Kimbell
Art Museum, Timothy Potts, 40, has been a busy man since his
arrival in Fort Worth in November.
</P>
<P>
   He's still settling into his new job as head of a small,
relatively new, privately operated museum _ quite a change from
Australia's big old public National Gallery of Victoria, which he
directed for three years. But, as this first interview with him
indicates, Potts has a clear appreciation of what the Kimbell is
and can be.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: You've arrived at the Kimbell in the midst of
preparation for ``Matisse and Picasso.'' But what are some of the
other things you're addressing daily and weekly for now?
</P>
<P>
   ANSWER: Well, there are things that go under the heading of
management: security arrangements, planning on how we'll rehang the
permanent collection during ``Matisse and Picasso.''
</P>
<P>
   But I said when I came here that I wanted to take time to get to
know the institution. I spent the time before Christmas getting to
know the staff. With the new year, I'll be talking with them about
issues and, in four or five months, I'll be coming out with a clear
plan for what I want to do.
</P>
<P>
   Still, certain things already are jelling in my mind.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Such as?
</P>
<P>
   A: One is getting the collection, which is small and of high
quality, fully cataloged and in the form of digitized images, and
getting it online. There's no reason why it can't all be online.
Other museums are doing this, but they have 10- or 15-year
timetables, because they've got hundreds of thousands of objects.
We have a few hundred objects and can achieve that in a much
shorter space of time.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about the idea of a new, hard-copy publication of works,
as well?
</P>
<P>
   A: Publications is another area we are looking at. ``In Pursuit
of Quality'' came out in 1987, and we've continued to collect so
much that there is a lot of new material. But each decade, any
institution needs to stand back and rethink what visitors want to
know and the best way of presenting it to them. ... But I'm still
for the handbook. So we will be doing a new edition.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Have you thought about using the property across the street
that the foundation acquired last year?
</P>
<P>
   A: We haven't set a timetable for a decision on use of the new
site. In due course, we'll consider how we might use it to enhance
our current facilities. But anything we consider will be based on a
commitment to preserving and making optimum use of the Kimbell's
collections and its world-renowned Louis Kahn building.
</P>
<P>
   Q: This may be a bit soon to ask, but have you found a favorite
piece of art yet in the collection?
</P>
<P>
   A: (laughs) It's hard to avoid that question, isn't it? It's
funny, the only time you ever stop and think about it is when
you're asked by someone doing an article. But here is what might be
a cryptic response and a long-winded one.
</P>
<P>
   The sense in which you have favorites changes, I have found.
It's not a favorite in the sense of a collector who might want to
have that picture at home or over the mantelpiece. It is what is
uppermost in your mind. It's the work you're most interested in at
the moment. And the work you're most interested in often is
something you find fascinating because you know very little about
it.
</P>
<P>
   Often it's what you've most recently acquired. Because I'm new
here, my favorite work is the latest surprise in the vaults. That's
the sort of stage I'm at. You ask me this question a year from now,
and I'll give you a very different answer.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about the antiquities collection here? With your
background in antiquities and archaeological research, do you think
more things will be coming into that collection?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, the antiquities are not the most distinguished
collection in the Kimbell. There are a handful of good pieces, and
there's certainly scope for improvement. And I bring some expertise
in that area. So there's that possibility.
</P>
<P>
   But it's never been my practice to focus the collections of the
institution on what I know about or am most interested in. What you
enjoy the most is building a collection as a collection and not
just an assemblage of objects, looking at the balance and overall
direction of it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you address the balance of the Kimbell's collection or
its direction?
</P>
<P>
   A: Let me answer that in general terms, because the Kimbell has
never been a comprehensive collection. Nor should it be. During the
decades it's been collecting, there have been artists and
categories of art where the sort of quality you want just wasn't
available. So the Kimbell has tried to collect across a broad range
of areas ... and go for absolutely the supreme objects that are
available.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
