u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-N     01-13 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
  
 PARTISAN POLITICS LEADS TO ABUSE OF IMPEACHMENT CLAUSES  (EDITOR'S
NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the Casper
(Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First Amendment
commentary. His e-mail address is levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY    
 c. 1999 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The impeachment process which has entangled President Clinton
and the Congress is full of quirks and oddities that point to the
fierce partisanship that is driving this spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has been sworn in as jurors for the president's
impeachment trial. However, three newly elected senators will have
the privilege of voting twice on the impeachment of the president _
they were representatives in the 105th Congress. The double-vote is
comparable to the member of a grand jury voting to indict a person
and then in a trial voting on his guilt or innocence. They have
become both accusers and jury. This is one reason that the 106th
Congress should have begun the process all over again from the
start and dropped the articles of impeachment as passed by the U.S.
House in the 105th Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the three new senators voted to impeach Clinton when they
were in the House: Jim Bunning, R-Ky., and Michael Crapo, R-Idaho.
The other freshman senator, Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., voted against
impeachment. To be fair _ if the Senate were actually seeking
fairness, these senators should not be allowed to vote on whether
the president is guilty of the articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   If only 97 members of the Senate can vote, it would take 65
votes to bring the president down. It would still require 12
Democrats to vote guilty on one of the two articles of impeachment
_ nevertheless, the process would preserve some notion of fairness.
</P>
<P>
   When President Nixon was facing possible impeachment, the
Democratic-controlled House Judiciary Committee appointed an
impeachment inquiry staff to define the nature of an impeachable
offense. The staff, which ironically included attorney Hillary
Rodham before she was married to Bill Clinton, placed impeachable
offenses for a president at a high threshold _ as envisioned by the
framers of the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The staff submitted a memo to the committee that stated in part:
</P>
<P>
   `Because impeachment of a President is a grave step for the
nation, it is to be predicated only upon conduct seriously
incompatible with either the constitutional form and principles of
our government or the proper performance of constitutional duties
of the presidential office.` To be impeached, a president must have
acted to subvert the structure of our democracy.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear that some of Nixon's actions surpassed the threshold
of impeachable offenses and were, indeed, `seriously incompatible
with the constitutional form and principles of our government.` The
break-in at the Democratic National Committee headquarters as an
act of political espionage and subsequent attempts to cover up this
and other covert activities did jeopardize our democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee in the 105th Congress, however,
sought no standard for an impeachable offense. They flew into
impeachment by the seat of their partisan pants. The
Republican-controlled committee knew an impeachable offense when
they saw one _ whether they could define it or not.
</P>
<P>
   During the Constitutional Convention in 1787, James Madison
spoke to the issue of impeaching a president. According to his
notes on the convention, Madison said that impeachment should be
used when a president embezzles money or oppresses the people or
`might betray his trust to foreign powers.`
</P>
<P>
   In `The Federalist Papers,` No. 65, Alexander Hamilton explained
and defended the Constitution's provisions on impeachment. He
considered impeachment appropriate when a president violates the
public trust or damages society. Nothing less.
</P>
<P>
   The framers of the Constitution were worried about Congress
abusing its impeachment powers, so they set the impeachment
standard for presidents at a high level. The standard they set for
the impeachment of a president is much higher than the two articles
of impeachment facing Clinton. The real culprit here is partisan
politics.
</P>
<P>
   When former special prosecutors Archibald Cox and Leon Jaworski
conducted their investigations of then-President Nixon, they
avoided partisan politics. And when they presented the House
Judiciary Committee with their report, they simply provided the
results of their investigations. They did not lobby for
impeachment. In stark contrast, special prosecutor Kenneth Starr,
whose office leaked grand jury testimony that was damaging to the
president, was a shameless advocate of impeachment when he
testified before the judiciary committee. His actions caused
Starr's ethics adviser Sam Dash to resign in protest.
</P>
<P>
   The standard for the impeachment of judges is not as high as the
constitutional standard set for the impeachment of presidents. The
impeachment clause in the Constitution that pertains to judges
states that judges `shall hold their offices during good behavior.`
The constitutional standard for the impeachment of a president is
`treason, bribery, or other high crimes and misdemeanors.`
</P>
<P>
   There is good reason for the difference. Judges are appointed,
but presidents hold office after winning a national election, after
a majority of American citizens across the country have voted for
the candidate. Only the gravest betrayal on the part of a president
can be an excuse to nullify an election.
</P>
<P>
   Judges can be and have been removed for committing perjury. Even
if Clinton committed perjury in his testimony to the grand jury
about sex with Monica Lewinsky, that action alone does not
jeopardize our nation. Lying about a sexual liaison does not
violate the public trust. The affair itself violated a marital
trust --- important to the family, but not a national crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The high standard of impeachment for a president does not put a
president above the law, as some claim. If, indeed, Clinton lied,
he can be prosecuted when his term of office is over.
</P>
<P>
   Critics claim that Paula Jones did not receive justice because
of Clinton's alleged false testimony. Nonsense. Jones had her day
in court. Judge Susan Webber Wright dismissed her lawsuit, saying
that even if her allegations were true, there weren't grounds to
sue. The judge also ruled that Clinton's testimony in regard to
Monica Lewinsky was irrelevant to the Jones lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   If the Senate convicts Clinton on either of the two articles of
impeachment, Congress will have toppled a president by the abuse of
its powers. And Americans will have a lot more to worry about than
sex in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-01-12-99 1713EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 1809EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
