<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0299 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1843 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-COLLECTIBLES-     01-13 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-COLLECTIBLES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS TRIAL BEGINS, COLLECTORS SCOUR FOR A PIECE OF HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the Senate trial of President Clinton gets under
way Thursday, memorabilia collectors are scouring for keepsakes in
the first impeachment trial of a president in 131 years.
</P>
<P>
   Serious collectors already are bombarding dealers with requests
to purchase the tickets that will be handed out each day to members
of the public viewing the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got about 20 people who want to buy them, but I have
nobody who has offered them for sale,'' lamented Nelson Whitman,
owner of Capitol Coin &AMP; Stamp Co. in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, 50 seats in the 596-seat Senate gallery will
be made available each day to members of the public.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said that depending upon the length of the trial, the
tickets might be worth $50 to $100 to collectors. A shorter trial
likely would increase the value of the Clinton tickets because
fewer would be in circulation.
</P>
<P>
   A ticket to the only other impeachment trial of a president,
that of Andrew Johnson in 1868, sells for around $250.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Ross, a Washington attorney and president of the Clinton
Political Item Collectors club, is anticipating a small number of
Clinton tickets making it to the collectibles marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are going to be the sleepers,'' Ross predicted. ``A lot
of the Senate offices have asked people to hand them back at the
end of the day. One Senate office even requests a driver's license
in collateral.''
</P>
<P>
   Collectors in search of impeachment paraphernalia are sticklers
for nuance and oddities. For example, Ross noted that the Clinton
trial tickets are more true to the impeachment process than are the
Johnson tickets.
</P>
<P>
   The Johnson-era tickets admitted an individual to witness from
the Senate gallery the ``Impeachment of the President,'' which is
technically incorrect, since the Constitution requires the House to
vote articles of impeachment, then for the Senate to act as a court
to consider the charges. (The Senate acquitted Johnson by one vote
in 1868.)
</P>
<P>
   But the modern tickets admit a person to view ``The Impeachment
Trial of the President of the United States,'' which is the
appropriate phase for the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Collectors are hoping that unique items associated with the
impeachment in the House and the trial in the Senate eventually
appear on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Levine, of Presidential Coin &AMP; Antique Co. in Alexandria,
Va., said that the pens used by senators to sign an oath book last
week officially opening the impeachment trial will be much sought
after.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they won't be of any value unless they are accompanied by
an authenticating letter from a senator saying they were used to
sign the book,'' Levine said.
</P>
<P>
   John Loring, a Chicago attorney and political memorabilia
enthusiast, said aficionados are on the lookout for items such as
signed note cards used by senators during the trial or copies of
the Congressional Record, the daily transcription of congressional
activity, signed by major players like House Judiciary Committee
Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., or Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott,
R-Miss.
</P>
<P>
   Several lawmakers have recognized the historic dimensions of the
impeachment activity and have begun their own collections.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James E. Rogan, R-Calif., an avid collector who also is one
of the prosecutors in the Clinton trial, has copies of the badges
House Judiciary Committee staff wore during the panel's proceedings
last month that resulted in the approval of articles of
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   And Rep. Tom Davis, R-Va., had Hyde and former House Speaker
Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., sign a copy of the impeachment resolution
approved by the House that charged Clinton with obstruction of
justice and lying under oath.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Virgil H. Goode Jr., D-Va., a charter member of the Clinton
Political Item Collectors club, said he plans to ask Hyde and Rep.
Ray LaHood, R-Ill., who presided over the House when Clinton was
impeached on Dec. 19, to sign a copy of the Congressional Record
for that day.
</P>
<P>
   Goode was one of five Democrats who crossed party lines to vote
for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The case against Clinton has sparked tremendous sales of novelty
items, which may be valuable in years to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our huge seller has been the Starr Report on toilet paper.
We've sold about 6,000 rolls of that,'' said Daniel Kennedy, a
sales clerk at Political Americana in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Another item racking up large sales is a bumper sticker that
says, ``Get Off His Back.'' Kennedy said that David Kendall, the
president's lawyer, has ordered a batch of 50.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 1811EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
