<P>
   Collectors are hoping that unique items associated with the
impeachment in the House and the trial in the Senate eventually
appear on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Levine, of Presidential Coin &AMP; Antique Co. in Alexandria,
Va., said that the pens used by senators to sign an oath book last
week officially opening the impeachment trial will be much sought
after.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they won't be of any value unless they are accompanied by
an authenticating letter from a senator saying they were used to
sign the book,'' Levine said.
</P>
<P>
   John Loring, a Chicago attorney and political memorabilia
enthusiast, said aficionados are on the lookout for items such as
signed note cards used by senators during the trial or copies of
the Congressional Record, the daily transcription of congressional
activity, signed by major players like House Judiciary Committee
Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., or Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott,
R-Miss.
</P>
<P>
   Several lawmakers have recognized the historic dimensions of the
impeachment activity and have begun their own collections.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James E. Rogan, R-Calif., an avid collector who also is one
of the prosecutors in the Clinton trial, has copies of the badges
House Judiciary Committee staff wore during the panel's proceedings
last month that resulted in the approval of articles of
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   And Rep. Tom Davis, R-Va., had Hyde and former House Speaker
Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., sign a copy of the impeachment resolution
approved by the House that charged Clinton with obstruction of
justice and lying under oath.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Virgil H. Goode Jr., D-Va., a charter member of the Clinton
Political Item Collectors club, said he plans to ask Hyde and Rep.
Ray LaHood, R-Ill., who presided over the House when Clinton was
impeached on Dec. 19, to sign a copy of the Congressional Record
for that day.
</P>
<P>
   Goode was one of five Democrats who crossed party lines to vote
for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The case against Clinton has sparked tremendous sales of novelty
items, which may be valuable in years to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our huge seller has been the Starr Report on toilet paper.
We've sold about 6,000 rolls of that,'' said Daniel Kennedy, a
sales clerk at Political Americana in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Another item racking up large sales is a bumper sticker that
says, ``Get Off His Back.'' Kennedy said that David Kendall, the
president's lawyer, has ordered a batch of 50.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
