<SLUG> BC-OLY-SALT-LAKE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOC EXEMPTS SALT LAKE PANEL FROM SCANDAL CENSURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though the International Olympic Committee is expected to ask as
many as a dozen of its members to resign next week, it will take no
action against the Salt Lake Organizing Committee, which gave cash
and gifts to IOC voters in an apparent attempt to land the 2002
Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   Since SLOC's top two officials stepped down last week, ``there
is no action to be taken,'' IOC executive board member Jacques
Rogge of Belgium said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who were in the bid are no more,'' said Rogge, a
member of the special six-man panel investigating the worst scandal
in modern Olympic history. ``They took the actions they thought
were needed.''
</P>
<P>
   SLOC president Frank Joklik and senior vice president Dave
Johnson both quit under pressure, and their successors are expected
to be named within a month.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC, which has never expelled a member in its 105 years, is
likely to urge nearly a tenth of its roster of 115 to step down in
the wake of payoffs that included up to $70,000 in cash, college
tuition, jobs, free medical services, and expensive souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC is also looking into charges that Sydney officials were
approached for payoffs during their bid to host the 2000 Summer
Games. ``We have a mandate to look into any possible form of
corruption,'' said Rogge. ``It is not limited to Salt Lake City.''
</P>
<P>
   Although several people with Olympic ties _ most notably former
IOC member Robert Helmick of the United States _ have demanded that
IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch resign after accepting gift
shotguns from the Salt Lake organizers, IOC board members said that
would not happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Samaranch is not voting and he is not a corrupt man,
absolutely not,'' said Rogge. ``Why should someone resign at a
moment of crisis? We need leadership. We do not need resignations.
It would be ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   The IOC's inquiry panel, which says it has gathered the evidence
it needs, will make a report in Lausanne, Switzerland, Jan. 24 to
the 11-member executive board, which is expected to push for
resignations. If the members do not comply, the full IOC can vote
to expel them at its meeting in Seoul in June.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
