<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0304 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1861 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BO     01-13 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BEST OF HIS ERA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is hard now to remember life before Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Young people have no frame of reference. If you are playing
basketball at the college or high school level, you cannot remember
a time when there was no Air Jordan, no Nike Swoosh, no ``Space
Jam,'' no David Falk.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to believe there was a time when the only bald players
were the ones losing hair. There was a time when ballhandlers did
not carry the ball on every drive to the basket. There was a time
when shorts were really short.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was not always the best basketball player who ever lived,
but only because he is not older than the sport. The pre-Michael
arguments pitted Bill Russell vs. Wilt Chamberlain, then Larry Bird
vs. Magic Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, Bird shook his head and said, ``People always
want to talk about the greatest ever. Now it's Michael, and before
that, it was me or Magic. Well, I can tell you who it is. Look it
up. It's Russell and Chamberlain. Russell won 11 championships in
13 years. Chamberlain averaged 50 points a game for a whole
season.''
</P>
<P>
   It sounded logical at the time, but that was before Michael
began his run of championships, a run that certainly rivaled
Russell's, given the increase in the number of teams over the last
30 years.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Michael made that final shot against Utah last June,
it was almost impossible to find a sports fan who contested his
place atop the hardwood. Check the numbers. Count championships,
scoring titles, All-Defensive team selections, performances in the
clutch . . . Jordan is the best ever. There is no more argument.
</P>
<P>
   Now that he is officially retired, we are left to assess his
place in American sports history. We know he's the best basketball
player. Where do we place him in the pantheon of national sports
legends?
</P>
<P>
   You have your list. I have mine. And Jordan's head is chiseled
on my Sports Mount Rushmore alongside those of Babe Ruth, Jackie
Robinson, and Muhammad Ali.
</P>
<P>
   Let's be clear that this is for American athletes only. We
cannot possibly measure the global significance of Pele or sundry
Olympians of the modern era.
</P>
<P>
   But in the US of A in this century, one can make a strong case
for Jordan alongside Babe, Jackie, and Ali.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth forever will be No. 1 because he played in an era when
baseball was the only real professional game and he single-handedly
kept the sport afloat after the Black Sox Scandal of 1919. The
Bambino was a kid magnet, bigger than the president when that was
considered a formidable achievement. Folklore holds that Japanese
soldiers cursed the name of Babe Ruth when attacking US forces
during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Because of changing times and infinite entertainment
opportunities, no single game or figure can become larger than the
Babe was in the 1920s and '30s. It's the same logic that tells us
today's TV ratings can never top those of the days when there were
only three networks. The Babe was baseball when baseball was the
only game and everybody was a baseball fan. Case closed.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson belongs because he had the ability, the fire, and the
indomitable spirit to make America understand that athletes of
color belonged on the professional playing fields. It's hideous to
think of professional sports without black athletes, and Jackie's
The Man because he was the ideal candidate to blaze the trail.
</P>
<P>
   Ali was the perfect star when television took over sports
because he looked great, sounded great, and backed up his boasts.
He had the courage to stand his ground at the expense of his crown
when he became a conscientious objector during the Vietnam era, and
he fought long enough to convert all but a few detractors. He was
our first truly global sports star.
</P>
<P>
   And now there is Michael. He had none of Ruth's wild appetites
(unless we consider his compulsion for gambling). He was
consistently apolitical, sharing none of the controversy and social
consciousness that marked Robinson and Ali. He was the superstar of
the New World Order, famous around the world, infinitely wealthy,
loved by those who knew him and millions who didn't. He used his
fame to sell himself and wholesome products but ducked
controversial issues better than man-to-man defenses. He was
colorless and spotless, a man with no opinions and no peers when it
came to getting the job done in the final seconds of a championship
game. He could step on a movie set with no preparation and still be
a star.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth, Robinson, and Ali were unable to retire on top. They
performed in different eras when athletes were beholden to
promoters, owners, and those who used them up, then spit them out.
Jordan did everything on his own terms, retiring at the top of his
game, after a perfect game to win a final championship. Michael
made the system work for him, and he worked it better than any
other athlete in the history of sport. Like Ruth, he was a true
celebrity, an American icon on a par with Frank Sinatra and Elvis
Presley. We get only a few of those per century.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
