<HEADLINE>
CARROLL TO COACH FOR ANOTHER YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Pete Carroll no longer is twisting in the wind.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation that Carroll might be forced out as Patriots coach _
replete with rumors that Jacksonville offensive coordinator Chris
Palmer or Jets defensive coordinator Bill Belichick would be coming
aboard _ has been tempered for at least another year.
</P>
<P>
   Vice president of player personnel Bobby Grier, often blaming
himself for personnel decisions and draft choices, said in a
teleconference Wednesday that Carroll's job was never in jeopardy
but that the team had to go through its normal evaluation process,
an annual occurrence.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we went through the process, I don't think his job was in
jeopardy,'' said Grier. ``We had to go through the evaluation to
get things on the right track.''
</P>
<P>
   There were still strong rumors of Palmer's possible return to
New England circulating along the Eastern Seaboard, though Grier's
comments appeared to debunk them.
</P>
<P>
   Grier divulged that, as reported, the evaluation of the coach
and the team involved interviews with players and coaches in the
wake of a 9-7 season that ended with a first-round playoff loss at
Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   He vowed to make personnel changes, which could mean a dip into
free agency for a top-flight offensive lineman.
</P>
<P>
   Though Grier said, ``Let's not point the finger at the offensive
line coach,'' for the Patriots' problems running the ball, Paul
Boudreau was fired from that post Tuesday. With him went receivers
coach Steve Walters.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll is currently evaluating other assistants, and other
changes could be in the works.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus was that the millions spent on linemen Bruce
Armstrong, Max Lane, and Todd Rucci didn't work out, although
statistics show that Drew Bledsoe would have passed for more than
4,000 yards had he remained healthy, an indication that the
quarterback was protected well; and that the featured back, Robert
Edwards, ran for almost 1,200 yards and averaged 3.8 per carry,
generally a sign the running game was at least decent.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not good enough for Carroll or Grier.
</P>
<P>
   Coupling that with the feeling that the linemen drafted two
years ago haven't progressed enough to take over as starters, Grier
thought the running game needed to go in a different direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we went through and talked to people, what was
disappointing to everyone was that we didn't fulfill our goal,''
siad Grier. ``We're disappointed in the performance not only of the
head coach but the performance of the players, and we're trying to
make some corrections. We're not satisfied with the run game, the
offensive line, and the running backs. We'd like to make changes as
far as personnel goes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we don't want to do is point fingers at the line coach.
There are a lot of things beyond that. We haven't run the ball
effectively in three years. We had a great running back in Curtis
Martin. We have a young running back who is still developing. We
were not happy in the development of some of the young players. We
have a couple of young players in (Damon) Denson and (Ed) Ellis who
will progress and become players for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Grier also questioned the makeup of the team in terms of age and
the methods used to discipline players. He said Carroll's West
Coast/San Francisco style works with veteran teams, but the two
have discussed ways to alter that approach based on the fact that
the Patriots are a young team.
</P>
<P>
   He said he probably would change the mix of the team and
supplement the younger players with older ones if necessary _
exactly the recipe Parcells employed here.
</P>
<P>
   Grier said that could be accomplished through free agency,
pointing to players like Henry Thomas, Zefross Moss, Willie Clay,
Shawn Jefferson, and Mark Wheeler as veterans who came in and
filled such roles. Translated, that may mean don't hold your breath
awaiting free agents such as Antonio Freeman and J.J. Stokes.
</P>
<P>
   He envisions upgrades at offensive line, linebacker, cornerback,
and quarterback, where Scott Zolak's days may be numbered.
</P>
<P>
   Grier seemed taken aback when asked which of Carroll's qualities
persuaded the Patriots to keep him. The personnel boss said Carroll
was ``hardworking,'' did a good job keeping the team together
through massive injuries, and kept the offense current on NFL
innovations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal of this organization is reaching the Super Bowl.
Everything else falls short,'' said Grier. ``There are things we've
discussed concerning game management and personnel development and
some other things that we'd like to improve in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pete's a young coach and he's learning as he goes. I happened
to listen to (San Francisco coach) Steve Mariucci at his (contract
extension) press conference, and there are things he mentioned
about clock management and things he needs to improve on. Young
coaches have to do some work in that area.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his recent drafts, Grier said, ``I'll accept all and full
responsibility. I won't pass that off on anybody. I'm being
evaluated like everybody else in organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Grier was questioned about his interviews of players such as
Armstrong, Bledsoe, and Ted Johnson after the season, and he said
the players' response to Carroll was mostly positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things we talked about are things I won't betray
confidences,'' he said. ``There were a lot of positive things
said.''
</P>
<P>
   Grier said he wasn't in any way trying to let the players make
the decision on Carroll but wanted their viewpoints on what changes
were necessary, just as he wanted such input from the coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I interviewed everyone,'' said Grier. ``It's not unlike what I
did last year and what we'll do again. There's accountability that
all of us need to feel. I'm disappointed at some of (the players).
There's accountability that the players have to accept, too.''
</P>
<P>
   That will include attending the offseason conditioning program.
Grier said the number of participants in Parcells's offseason
program often was inflated, but he added that there have been too
many players who didn't care enough. He said he's met with Carroll
and strength coach Johnny Parker to discuss ways to get more
players with the program but he was not specific about new
strategies.
</P>
<P>
   As for the negative comments by some players at the end of the
season, Grier said, ``There's a concern. A lot of negative things
were said in the heat of battle. We have emotional young players. A
week after, when interviewing those same players, you got a
different response from them and a different perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   In summary, said Grier, ``I'm probably the most disappointed guy
in this organization other than the general public.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
