<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PROSECUTORS WARM UP FOR THURSDAY'S PERFORMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House prosecutors on Wednesday rehearsed the
arguments they will make Thursday when the Senate hears why they
believe President Clinton should be convicted in his impeachment
trial.
</P>
<P>
   The 13 House prosecutors practiced their oral arguments in the
Senate chamber, which was closed to the public for the warm-up. The
actual session, which starts at 1 p.m. EST Thursday, will be open.
</P>
<P>
   All members of the House team are Republicans, white and male
and their ranks include former U.S. attorneys, county prosecutors
and a judge.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors have a total of 24 hours over three days to make
their case. Here's what to look for Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry J. Hyde, R-Ill., chairman of the House Judiciary
Committee and a former trial lawyer, will make the opening
statement. Also delivering remarks will be Rep. James
Sensenbrenner, Jr., R-Wis.
</P>
<P>
   Sensenbrenner said he is a ``compulsive nonprocrastinator'' who
spent last weekend rewriting, cutting and pasting his opening
statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not done by staff, it is not done by a ghost writer,
it is done by Jim Sensenbrenner and no one else,'' he said. ``This
is the biggest speech I will ever give.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James E. Rogan of California, a former Los Angeles County
prosecutor, will argue that Clinton committed perjury before a
federal grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Calm and deliberate, Rogan, 41, was appointed in 1990 By
Republican Gov. George Deukmejian to the bench, making him
California's youngest judge at age 33. He once won a drunken
driving case by pouring out 10 beers in front of jurors to visually
illustrate how much a defendant had consumed.
</P>
<P>
   Rogan is a born-again Christian and former high school dropout,
who never knew his biological father and whose mother was a
convicted felon and welfare recipient. Raised by his grandparents,
he attended community college and eventually got a law degree from
the University of California at Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ed Bryant, 50, a former U.S. attorney in Tennessee, brings
a measured, deliberate style to his work. His assignment is to
deliver a chronology of events, starting with Clinton's oath of
office.
</P>
<P>
   When he was a federal prosecutor, Bryant prosecuted a member of
his state's congressional delegation, Democratic Rep. Harold E.
Ford, on charges of bank fraud, mail fraud and tax fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant resigned from the Justice Department after his superiors
supported Ford's request for a new jury. Ford was eventually
acquitted, but Bryant later used his high-profile role in the Ford
case to win his seat in Congress. As a federal prosecutor, he had
one of the highest conviction rates of any U.S. attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark., who will focus on the obstruction
of justice charge, said he has worked to make his presentation
concise ``because I don't want to bore the Senate with a lot of
details.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said when he goes home to the apartment he shares with
his brother, Sen. Tim Hutchinson, R-Ark., a juror in the
impeachment trial, ``We don't talk about the facts of the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Asa Hutchinson, who was nominated in 1982 by President Reagan to
be the U.S. attorney for the Western District of Arkansas, will be
prosecuting his second Clinton. He once prosecuted and convicted
the president's brother, Roger, on drug charges while the president
was governor of the state.
</P>
</TEXT>
