<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: NEUWIRTH RETURNS TO `CHICAGO'; KABUKI DANCE; B.B.
KING &AMP; BOBBY BLAND; `ON THE 20TH CENTURY' IN CONN.; RUSSIA'S EIFMAN
BALLET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., N.J., N.Y.)  (js) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HELLO, AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On two days' notice, Bebe Neuwirth returns Thursday
night to her Tony Award-winning role as the hard-as-nails Velma
Kelly in ``Chicago'' at the Shubert Theater. Until Jan. 26 Ms.
Neuwirth will replace Ute Lemper, who has been battling the flu and
laryngitis for two weeks and has been advised by doctors to take a
rest.
</P>
<P>
   IMAGES IN DANCE
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On a night at the theater, the business people wanted
to see performances that reflected their lives. And the warriors
wanted to see tales of their own adventures. So as Kabuki developed
as popular theater during Japan's Edo period (1603-1868), two
genres of dance drama evolved: the sewamono, based on domestic
matters, and the jidaimono, derived from historic events. At 8 p.m.
on Feb. 12 and 13, the Japan Society, at 333 E. 47th St.will
present three of Japan's most distinguished actors _ Nakamura
Shijaku, Nakamura Kannojo and Nakamura Kyozo _ in a typical program
consisting of each type of Kabuki dance.
</P>
<P>
   WHOSE BLUES?
</P>
<P>
   His name is Riley B. King, but the world knows him as B.B. King.
At 73, after more than 50 albums and eight Grammy Awards, he is
still brightening lives by singing and playing the blues. Although
he may be many people's favorite blues singer, he says his favorite
is Bobby (Blue) Bland. The two will perform at 8 p.m. on Saturday
at the New Jersey Performing Arts Center in Newark.
</P>
<P>
   COMING ATTRACTIONS
</P>
<P>
   A musical that won five Tony Awards, including best book and
score, after opening on Broadway in 1978 will begin the 1999 season
at the Goodspeed Opera House in East Haddam, Conn. ``On the 20th
Century,'' with book and lyrics by Betty Comden and Adolph Green
and music by Cy Coleman, will run from April 9 to July 3. The
Goodspeed's other productions will be ``No, No, Nanette'' (July 9
to Oct. 2) and ``Glimmerglass'' (Oct. 8 to Dec. 19).
</P>
<P>
   SECOND SIGHT
</P>
<P>
   It's an encore for the Eifman Ballet of St. Petersburg, Russia,
which earned accolades when it introduced itself to New York in a
weeklong engagement last spring. On Tuesday, the company, led by
the choreographer Boris Eifman, is returning to City Center, for
two weeks, through Jan. 31. Its program includes not only ``Red
Giselle'' and ``Tchaikovsky,'' which created a stir last year, but
also three American premieres: ``The Karamazovs,'' set to
Rachmaninoff, Wagner and Mussorgsky; ``Requiem,'' set to Mozart,
and ``My Jerusalem,'' set to techno-rock, Rachmaninoff, Mozart and
religious music.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
