<SLUG> BC-NY-PHILHARMONIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR CALIFORNIANS, MUSICAL VISITORS ARE WORTH THE WAIT
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Calif., Ill.) (bl) 
By DAVID MERMELSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The New York Philharmonic has not exactly been a
stranger to points beyond Manhattan in recent years. During Kurt
Masur's seven and a half years as its music director, the orchestra
has twice traveled to Latin America and to Asia, and to Europe four
times. But until now Masur and the Philharmonic had not made their
way across the United States together.
</P>
<P>
   Before it began its current seven-city tour, the orchestra had
not traveled in the United States since 1990, when Zubin Mehta was
conducting. And it had not appeared on the West Coast since 1986.
So the journey, which concludes Friday night in Boston after taking
the Philharmonic from West Coast to East, has included stops in
cities it had not visited in more than a decade, including Los
Angeles, San Francisco and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, its appearances have caused something of a
stir. So why did the Philharmonic wait this long? ``It's a matter
of money,'' Masur said during the orchestra's stop here. ``We need
support to make these tours. It's a partnership to decide where to
go next.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the Philharmonic's partner is Citibank. For nearly
20 years it has underwritten most of the Philharmonic's tours,
although this is the first time Citibank has paid for an American
trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a terrific relationship with Citibank, but they like
to show their flag around the globe,'' said Deborah Borda, the
Philharmonic's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   For those attending these concerts, the long wait seemed worth
it. ``The music really reached my soul,'' said Sylvia Dillon, a
longtime Southern California resident, after the orchestra's
appearance on Saturday at Royce Hall here. The program consisted of
two powerful Fifth Symphonies, Beethoven's and Shostakovich's.
</P>
<P>
   The reception in the sold-out 1,838-seat hall was nothing short
of ecstatic. Stacy Peralta, who accompanied his wife and 8-year-old
son to the concert, said they had ``a terrific time,'' adding,
``These people must be lit up for years.''
</P>
<P>
   The music critic of The Los Angeles Times, Mark Swed, wrote: ``I
have never heard this orchestra sound better. I have seldom heard
any orchestra sound better.''
</P>
<P>
   The previous night, similar enthusiasm greeted the Philharmonic
at the Orange County Performing Arts Center in Costa Mesa, where
the program included two tone poems by Richard Strauss.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't improve on this,'' said Paul Darbee, who attended
that concert. ``It sets the standard.'' Darbee and his wife, Ricki,
who have lived in Orange County since 1969, come from Ohio, where
they heard the famously autocratic conductor George Szell lead the
Cleveland Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Masur would be fiercer,'' said Ms. Darbee. ``In
fact, he's pretty sprightly. I like the way he connects with his
audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Because this is an American tour, the Philharmonic is connecting
with audiences in an unusual way. Most of the orchestra's 107
members were born in the United States, so for many the trip has
personal resonance.
</P>
<P>
   The Royce Hall performance summoned fond memories for the
violinist Glenn Dicterow, a Los Angeles native who has spent nearly
19 years as the Philharmonic's concertmaster. ``It's practically
home turf for me,'' said Dicterow, who made his professional debut
at Royce when he was 14 and served as concertmaster of the Los
Angeles Philharmonic before moving to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Though Masur's own roots are in Germany, he acknowledged that
there was something special about this tour. ``Maybe they are a
little bit proud of their orchestra,'' he said of the audiences,
trying to explain the extra effort his players have brought to the
concerts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Touring with them here, you find out that they have families
all over the country,'' he said. ``Very often I meet the family.
For me, that's a wonderful feeling, another connection to the
musicians and their backgrounds.'' And in such connections, ``there
is a trust that makes the music making more joyful,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There were some complaints along the way, mostly from critics
lamenting the absence of American music. ``For an American
orchestra to tour its own country without offering at least one
American piece,'' wrote Alan Ulrich of The San Francisco Examiner,
``is little short of disgraceful.'' In San Francisco Masur and the
Philharmonic played Tchaikovsky in addition to Beethoven,
Shostakovich and Strauss.
</P>
<P>
   The day before, in The Orange County Register, Timothy Mangan
wrote, ``It would have been good, in this orchestra's first visit
to these parts since 1986, to hear some of the American music it
has been unearthing in the past few seasons at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Masur disagreed. ``Why play American music in America?'' he
asked. ``We always take some American music when we play outside
the country. Why does there need to be nationalism inside the
country?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think American orchestras should always play American
music. And after all, you cannot very often hear Shostakovich the
way the New York Philharmonic plays it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
