<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON COMPUTERS AND GADGETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. Opens Hotline For Year 2000 Queries &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With fewer than 365 shopping days left until the possible onset
of a millenium bug, the federal government has sprung into action
and created ... a telephone hotline.
</P>
<P>
   Started last week, the new Year 2000 help line (1-888-USA-4-Y2K)
has recorded answers to common questions and also 25 operators
standing by from 9 a.m. to 8 p.m. Eastern time, Monday through
Friday. The idea is to help allay concerns, answer questions and
promote preparedness for citizens concerned about the possible
impact of widespread computer glitches in the banking, government,
utilities, telecommunications and airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The year 2000 problem is an artifact of computer programmers'
decisions in years past to enter years only as two-digits; when the
clock rolls over from 99 to 00, some computers are expected to shut
down.
</P>
<P>
   In a press conference announcing the phone service last week,
President Clinton's Year 2000 czar, John Koskinen, said all signs
were looking up, noting ``at this point in time we do not think
there is any basis for concern about the basic infrastructure in
the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Forget infrastructure. What about my toaster oven? ``One of the
things we'll get a lot of is questions about specific pieces of
equipment and household appliances,'' said Jack Gribben,
spokesperson for President's Council on Year 2000 Conversion.
``We'll provide people with whatever information we can, but they
really need to contact the manufacturer.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A &UR;  &LR; Really Big Scanner Still Comes Up Short &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Stanford University research team plans to use cutting-edge
technology to scan 3D images of the some of the greatest works of
art in Florence, Rome and the Vatican. But it seems the team could
benefit from the use of some old-fashioned technology, namely a
tape measure.
</P>
<P>
   The project's goal is to create three-dimensional images of all
of Michelangelo's statues for academic use although, according to
David F. Salisbury, a Stanford spokesman, there could also be
commercial applications for the scanning technology.
</P>
<P>
   The team had a scanner specially constructed that uses a video
camera and laser beams to capture and digitize the images. The
scanner, including the gantry on which it sits, is 20 feet high, a
size designed specifically to permit it to scan ``David,'' the
largest of Michelangelo's sculptures.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Stanford researchers arrived in Florence they
discovered that the scanner came up short. While art history books
commonly list ``David'' as standing 20 feet tall (14 feet of statue
and 6 feet of pedestal), the statue actually is 23 feet tall (17
feet of statue and 6 feet of pedestal). The researchers were forced
to make some modifications to their scanner, according to
Salisbury. ``It's a nontrivial problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the only challenge. The researchers also will have to
contend with the difficulties of accurately depicting the surface
colors of the sculptures, and of handling the huge file sizes of
these scans of works in museums in Florence, Rome and the Vatican.
Once they have scanned a sculpture, the researchers will apply
advanced algorithms to convert the digital data into a 3-D model,
the university said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DVD Player for Notebooks But What a Battery Hog &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A new ultra-thin notebook from Compaq Computer includes a DVD
player, which could be a neat addition for mobile movie buffs, just
so long as they don't plan to watch Titanic. The reason is that the
DVD player eats a great deal of battery life, cutting roughly an
hour from the average useful battery life of 2{ to 3 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The new Compaq Presario 1920 is scheduled to go on sale later
this month. Roughly an inch thick and weighing just five pounds,
the notebook computer has 64 megabytes of RAM, a 6.4-gigabyte hard
drive and a Pentium II processor, the exact speed of which has not
been announced. The company also has not yet set a price.
</P>
<P>
   The computer is yet another tribute to the capacity of the
electronics industry to cleverly shrink gadgets and functions into
mobile form. Greg Memo, Compaq vice president for the Presario
Mobile Division, said it was a particular challenge to fit the DVD
into an ultrathin notebook because the device consumes a great deal
of resources when running. ``It's a very intense application,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Certain technological advances could help, such as improving
battery life. Alternatively, someone might consider cutting two
hours out of Titanic. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Want Your Own Talk Show? You Can, On the Net &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It only seems as though everyone and her grandmother has a radio
talk show. Soon, however, everybody might. The catch is, the shows
won't take place on the radio, but on the Net.
</P>
<P>
   A Silicon Valley company, TalkNetRadio.com, plans to provide
Internet users with the technology to start their own talk shows,
on any topic under the sun (minus hard-core pornography and hate).
In other words, users who want a half an hour of ``airtime'' to
pontificate on baking, chat about the state of dental hygiene, or
invite listeners to share their thoughts on the wild world of the
Azalia soon will have a format.
</P>
<P>
   The way the technology works is that the talk show hosts will
speak into a microphone from their home computer. The computer will
digitize the sound, send it over the Internet to TalkNetRadio.com
in Santa Clara, Calif., which in turn will make it available for
listeners to download in real-time. The listeners in turn can
e-mail their responses back to the talk show host.
</P>
<P>
   TalkNetRadio.com has begun registering aspiring online talk show
hosts on its Web site. In the third quarter this year, it will
start offering the service, which involves sending the hosts a
marketing kit, and Web page and banner ad templates to promote
their talk show, said the company's chief, Ted Ganchiff.
</P>
<P>
   The service is free, with a big caveat. Ganchiff said the
audiences could be no larger than 30 people, to keep the company's
bandwith costs low, making these radio shows more like
tele-conferences via the Net. Also, people who want to use their
shows to promote products, or for business purposes, will have to
pay an, as of yet undetermined, fee. This is where the company
plans to make its money.
</P>
<P>
   The concept behind TalkNetRadio comes as commercial radio
streamed via the Net is increasingly popular. A recent study by
Arbitron found that 6 percent of Americans have listened to the
radio on line and that figure is growing. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Follow the Soaps On Line By Checking With a PDA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One downside of always being on the go is that it's tough to
follow the latest murder plots, marital affairs, or the sudden
appearance of an evil twin. No, not the normal doings in your
office, we're talking about fans of television soap operas who
really want to keep track of each episode's events. Now, they can
do so through their handheld computers.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia TriStar Interactive is starting a new Soap City Daily
Dose newsletter that downloads automatically to a Palm Pilot or
Windows CE device. Columbia joins roughly 70 companies, including
the likes of The New York Times, USA Today and Excite that provide
content to AvantGo Inc. in San Mateo, Calif. AvantGo then makes the
information accessible via a Palm Pilot or Windows CE device.
</P>
<P>
   Subscribers plug their mobile device into the Internet and
receive automatic updates of their choice, said David Rice,
director of content development for AvantGo.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Soap Opera site, who finds it really necessary to
have instant and mobile access to developments on major soap
operas? ``A lot of college students are hooked on soaps and a lot
of college students have'' handheld computers or personal digital
assistants, said Lynda Keeler, general manager of Columbia TriStar
Interactive. ``They can be in class and get their favorite
updates.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's Instant Replay At a Mouse Click &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to technology fresh out of Silicon Valley, it has just
become even easier to go stark raving mad at officials who blow
crucial calls during football games.
</P>
<P>
   At least, that is one possible use for Replay TV technology,
which offers television viewers a way to replay, pause and record
television programs in real time. The device, created by Palo
Alto-based Replay Networks Inc., is a box that goes on top or next
to the TV set. Inside, it's essentially a digital videocassette
recorder with the brains of a computer that translates analogue
television signals into digital data and then records them on a
self-contained hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to permitting real-time replay, the set-top box can
be programmed to automatically search and record programs on
specific topics, or certain actors. As a result, viewers can create
directories such as the ``ER file,'' that will record and store all
ER showings, said Anthony Wood, chief excutive of Replay. Woods
said the recorder would also continue to record an ongoing show
even while the user replayed part of the program that just
transpired.
</P>
<P>
   The technology, which should be commercially available in March
for around $700, won ``best of show'' honors last weekend at the
Consumer Electronics Show in Las Vegas. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Overseas Internet Users Protest High Access Cost &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Internet users in Brazil said on Wednesday that they would stage
a cybers strike: They pledged to refuse to log on to the Internet
for the day to protest the high-cost of Net access.
</P>
<P>
   The cyber strikers in Brazil join brethren who have engaged in
so-called ``Internet strikes'' in Germany, France, Spain, the Czech
Republic, China and Poland. Often organized by students and
academics, the strikes are meant to protest high access charges
that can lead to hundreds of dollars in monthly Internet bills.
</P>
<P>
   In Brazil, supporters claimed as many as 500,000 of 2.2 million
Internet would participate in the boycott, the Associated Press
reported. The boycott was organized through an e-mail chain letter,
according to Antonio Tavares, head of an Internet provider
association.
</P>
<P>
   In most countries the protests are aimed not at the service
providers, but at the national telecommunication companies, which
are sometimes state-owned monopolies that dictate the telephone
access charges.
</P>
<P>
   In China, protesters there said they would boycott the Internet
every Sunday this month. There the monthly cost of basic access
runs $30 to $43, which is more than a quarter of the average
monthly income, according to The Guangzhou Daily newspaper.
</P>
</TEXT>
