<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINKLER-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRWIN WINKLER: FILM PRODUCER ON THE SIDE OF UGLY DUCKLINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ It was 1966, and Irwin Winkler, an aspiring film
producer, had come to Hollywood from New York with a project for
Julie Christie. Winkler went to the offices of MGM and saw its
president, Robert O'Brien, who agreed to make the movie with one
proviso: he wanted to replace Julie Christie with Elvis Presley.
</P>
<P>
   Winkler replied, with some understatement, ``Well, that would be
a big rewrite.''
</P>
<P>
   Winkler, whose newest film, ``At First Sight,'' which he also
directed, opens Friday, said the other day: ``So we rewrote it for
Elvis Presley. It made me wary of Hollywood ways, and with that as
a start I said, OK, anything is going to happen now.''
</P>
<P>
   And it did.
</P>
<P>
   From his first film, ``Double Trouble'' (yes, with Elvis),
Winkler and his business partner, Robert Chartoff, moved on to
produce some of the best and most provocative films of the 1970s
and '80s, including John Boorman's ``Point Blank'' (1967), Sydney
Pollack's ``They Shoot Horses, Don't They'' (1969), John Avildsen's
``Rocky'' (1976) and the four other ``Rocky'' movies, Martin
Scorsese's ``New York, New York'' (1977) and ``Raging Bull'' (1980)
as well as ``The Right Stuff'' (1983), directed by Philip Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   On his own, Winkler produced such films as Costa Gavras'
``Betrayed'' (1988) and ``Music Box'' (1989) as well as Scorsese's
``Goodfellas'' (1990).
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Brooklyn-born Winkler, now 65, has also turned
to directing, making such films as ``Guilty by Suspicion'' (1991),
``Night and the City'' (1992) and ``The Net'' (1995). In his newest
film, loosely based on a nonfictional account by the physician
Oliver Sacks, Val Kilmer plays a blind man who briefly recovers,
then loses his sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``What appealed to me was that the real character, a blind
masseur named Shirl Jennings of Atlanta, had this operation to
regain his sight and then had a horrible problem in understanding
what sight brings you,'' Winkler said. ``To me it seemed like a
very courageous story.''
</P>
<P>
   Winkler has produced more than 40 movies over the last four
decades, making him one of the most prolific and successful
producers in Hollywood. The five ``Rocky'' films, which have
grossed more than $1 billion combined around the world, have made
him quite wealthy: he and Chartoff share the copyright with United
Artists.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Winkler has mixed feelings about present-day Hollywood. What
altered Hollywood irrevocably, he said, was the notorious 1980 film
``Heaven's Gate,'' Michael Cimino's drama about immigrant settlers
in 19th-century Wyoming. The film's excesses and cost overruns
nearly ruined its producers, United Artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the studios suddenly realized that one film can bring them
down,'' Winkler said. ``They said they would not let one filmmaker
or actor control their destiny. They basically took the
individuality away from the filmmakers, the directors, the
producers. They changed the product. They exercised a lot more
control.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well that was good in the days of Darryl Zanuck and Harry Cohn
and the other moguls,'' he added. ``Those guys loved movies and
they had no other businesses so they had to make money on their
movies. But now it was in the hands of corporate managers: people
who didn't have any great love for movies but a great love for the
bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   A result, said Winkler, was movie-making by committee, with
various executives giving filmmakers notes, sometimes conflicting,
about how to proceed with their films.
</P>
<P>
   He doubts that studios today would make such downbeat films as
``They Shoot Horses, Don't They,'' ``Raging Bull,'' ``Goodfellas''
and even the Cinderella fable ``Rocky.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even back then, `Rocky' was the most difficult film to make,''
said Winkler in the study of his elegant Beverly Hills home. ``You
sat in the office of United Artists and told them you've got a
story about a broken-down fighter in Philadelphia who meets this
ugly duckling, and they'd say: `Philadelphia? No one wants to go to
Philadelphia. And what do you mean, ugly duckling, you've got two
ugly people?' They said: `Who wants to see a movie about two ugly
people who kiss on screen? And you want to star a guy named
Sylvester Stallone? You're crazy.''' ( Winkler and Chartoff had to
mortgage their homes to complete the film).
</P>
<P>
   Winkler grew up in Coney Island, attended New York University
and after a brief, unhappy stint as an agent at the William Morris
agency arrived in Hollywood in 1966 and started producing movies.
Winkler and his wife, Margo, have three sons, two of them film
directors. His successful partnership with Chartoff lasted until
1983.
</P>
<P>
   Chartoff has since produced several films and has become
involved in charity work, but Winkler remains restless. His other
forthcoming producing projects include an adaptation of the book
``Lush Life,'' about Billy Strayhorn, Duke Ellington's co-writer
and arranger; ``Spite House,'' about Robert Garwood, the Vietnam
soldier convicted of collaborating with the enemy, and ``Winds of
Change,'' about the life of a doctor from the 1950s to the present.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the films Winkler produced there were, of course,
financial disappointments, the worst being ``The Right Stuff,''
based on Tom Wolfe's book about the nation's first astronauts. Even
16 years later, he said, its box office failure rankles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the best films I was ever involved with,'' Winkler
said. ``It got Academy Award nominations, the cover of Newsweek,
eight pages in Time, great reviews. And nobody went to see it. I'll
never know why. It was a wonderful film, and there was no audience
for it. And it still hurts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
