<HEADLINE>
SENATE FACES A FLOOD OF CYBER MESSAGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate's computer system has been nearly
paralyzed by a seven-fold increase in the amount of electronic mail
pouring into lawmakers' offices ahead of Thursday's impeachment
trial.
</P>
<P>
   On a typical day, about 70,000 e-mail messages are sent to
various Senate offices. But since late December, the Senate has
received an average of 500,000 e-mails daily. This deluge is
expected to continue, slowing Senate computer systems as long as
the trial of President Clinton lasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen it this bad,'' Joseph Keenan, an employee in
the Senate press gallery, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Staff members in the office of Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., faced a
queue of 7,000 e-mails after one recent weekend _ mostly on the
subject of impeachment. Levin's office normally receives less than
200 e-mails over a weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The onslaught of messages has kept many people outside the
Capitol from reaching Senate offices through the Internet and has
delayed e-mails sent to and from Senate offices. Some Senate
employees complained that e-mails they've sent never arrived at
their destination.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Lackey, press secretary to Sen. Olympia J. Snowe, R-Maine,
said he received an e-mail on Jan. 8 from a Maine congressman's
office. The message was dated Dec. 29.
</P>
<P>
   Senate employees experience little delay communicating with one
another on the Senate's internal e-mail system, but even an e-mail
sent to the House side of the Capitol is routed through the same
computer server that connects the Senate with the public and other
government agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, received 10,000 impeachment
related e-mails over New Year's weekend and is continuing to
receive thousands of e-mails and phone calls each day. Before
impeachment became an issue in the Senate, Hutchison received an
average of 700 e-mails a day.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, hasn't had the any trouble because his
office doesn't have an e-mail address. Kathy Dempsey, Gramm's
deputy press secretary, said Gramm has held off because other
offices have been frustrated with e-mail delays.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Iraq and other big items, the system was overrun,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Various issues have caused Senate computer systems to bog down
for a day or two, but the system has never been slowed for weeks as
it has with the impeachment issue.
</P>
<P>
   The number of e-mails is so great that many Senate offices are
having trouble logging them into pro- or anti-Clinton categories.
John Brennan, Levin's press secretary, said the e-mails ``are all
over the place'' with opinions on whether Clinton should be removed
from office and whether the Senate should conduct a full trial.
</P>
<P>
   Senate staff members have been advised to use the telephone or
fax machine if they want to communicate with people in government
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Senate technicians increased computer capacity by 50 percent
last year and are currently trying to add more capacity, but they
said the computer delays are expected to continue until the amount
of e-mail slows.
</P>
<P>
   While the number of e-mails has dramatically increased, a few
Senate press secretaries said they hadn't seen an increase in the
overall number of phone calls and letters received by their
offices, but they said the subject matter has mostly been on
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, as the House was debating whether to impeach Clinton
on charges of perjury and obstruction of justice, that chamber also
was deluged with e-mails, hampering computer systems at times. The
House received more than 1 million e-mails daily during the
impeachment debate compared to an average of 80,000.
</P>
<P>
   House Administration Chairman Bill Thomas, R-Calif., is
overseeing a $2.8 million computer upgrade that had already been
planned before House computers were deluged with
impeachment-related e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent letter to colleagues, Thomas said more than 11
million people logged into the House's Internet site
(www.house.gov) during a three-day period. The House Internet site
normally receives 10 million to 11 million visits per month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
