<HEADLINE>
STUDY CASTS NEW LIGHT ON WHO PAYS FOR HEALTH INSURANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a study that could diminish the power of businesses to sway
national health care policy, researchers have found that private
employers pick up far less of the nation's health insurance tab
than previously assumed.
</P>
<P>
   Less than half of Americans _ about 43 percent _ have health
insurance that is paid for, in part or in full, by private sector
companies, according to a study in the current New England Journal
of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The conventional notion has been that employers subsidize health
insurance for 60 percent of Americans. But the figure is far lower
when researchers, using data from a 1997 US Census Bureau current
population survey, subtract government workers, retirees, and
workers who pay 100 percent of their insurance premiums.
</P>
<P>
   The implication, according to study authors, is that business's
influence over such issues as managed care reform or mental health
coverage far outweighs its actual contribution to health care
spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have operated under the assertion that employers pay
for everything, and therefore they should get their say,'' said
study coauthor Dr. Steffanie J. Woolhandler, associate professor at
Harvard Medical School. ``This study makes it clear that businesses
are paying for only a minority of the bill, and that they shouldn't
be calling the shots.''
</P>
<P>
   The study's authors include Woolhandler; Drs. David Himmelstein
and David H. Bor, associate professors of Harvard Medical School;
and Dr. Olveen Carrasquillo, assistant professor at Columbia
University's College of Physicians and Surgeons. All four authors
are members of Physicians for a National Health Program, an
organization that advocates universal health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Business groups bristled at the authors' conclusion that private
sector payors should have less influence over health policy,
particularly in Massachusetts, where 50.3 percent of residents have
insurance subsidized by private employers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Health care is the most expensive overhead item facing
employers today,'' said John Gould, president of the Associated
Industries of Massachusetts, an organization that represents 5,000
businesses in the state and has argued against excessive regulation
of the state's managed care industry. ``If I were paying the bill
for 43 percent of Americans, I would feel my right to comment would
have validity.''
</P>
<P>
   The study was better received within academic circles. John
McDonough, a Brandeis University health policy researcher and
former state representative, said the study brought up legitimate
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good hit,'' McDonough said. ``It will be surprising to a lot
of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the study's findings: 9 million Americans have access to
employer-sponsored health insurance but must pay 100 percent of
their premiums. Also, individual, out-of-pocket spending accounted
for 26 percent of total health care spending, outstripping spending
by private sector employers, who contribute just 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of the nation's health care tab is picked up by
taxpayers, through government programs such as Medicare and
Medicaid, as well as insurance coverage for military personnel,
veterans, and government employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think people need to think differently about who pays for
health care,'' said Woolhandler.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
