<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Thursday, Jan. 14. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-RDP (Rio de Janeiro, Brazil) _ With its authority being
challenged by adversaries at home and its economic policies being
questioned by increasingly nervous investors abroad, the Brazilian
government devalues the nation's currency, allowing it to fall by
more than eight percent, an action that came after the surprise
resignation of the president of the Central Bank and a week of
precipitous declines in the stock market. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic and sidebars.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-U.S. (Washington) _ A look at the impact of the Brazilian
economic crisis in Washington. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-LEGAL (Washington) _ An analysis of the briefing papers
and the arguments on the impeachment charges being presented by the
two sides. By Jill Abramson. Graphic.
</P>
<P>
   With: IMPEACH-RDP (Washington) _ Final pre-argument briefing
papers from the House and the White House are released on the eve
of the opening of the Senate trial into the impeachment of
President Clinton. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   BREAST-CANCER (Undated) _ For women with a high risk of breast
cancer, a study being published Thursday in The New England Journal
of Medicine offers hope, but at a cruel price. Removing both
breasts while they are still healthy reduces the risk of getting
breast cancer by 90 percent, and the risk of dying from the disease
by 80 percent to 90 percent. The new study, by researchers at the
Mayo Clinic, is regarded as the most reliable work to date on the
surgery, known as bilateral prophylactic mastectomy. The authors of
the paper, however, cautioned that the findings should not be used
to pressure women into having their breasts removed. By Denise
Grady. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS (Washington) _ Supreme Court hears arguments on a
challenge to a California law setting lower level of welfare
benefits for new residents of the state, a practice many states
want to emulate. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO (Mexico City) _ Developments in Raul Salinas murder case.
By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   LABOR-RICO (Undated) _ RICO suit is filed against big
manufacturers including Tommy Hilfinger and Gap, claiming that they
knew about conditions in Saipan, a U.S. territory, where, the
groups filing the suit say, Chinese are promised a trip to the
United States but end up as indentured workers. By Steven
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Reefers:
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-SECURITY (Washington) _ For the first time since
President Clinton put Social Security's long-term financial
problems at the top of the national agenda, key members of both
parties are seriously examining compromise proposals that could be
acceptable both to Democrats who want to keep the retirement system
intact and to Republicans pushing for a shift to private investment
accounts. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   LOTT-TIES (Jackson, Miss.) _ If, as Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott insists, he has no firsthand knowledge of Council of
Conservative Citizens, which calls itself pro-white, it comes as
news to a lot of folks back home, including his Uncle Arnie. It
would be difficult for any conservative politician here _ Democrat
or Republican _ to remain ignorant of the Council of Conservative
Citizens. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   STATE-LOTTERIES (Columbia, S.C.) _ Of the 13 states that remain
without a lottery, four of them in the South appear poised to enact
one this year, in the face of longstanding conservative opposition
to state-sanctioned organized gambling. Resistance to the lottery
is crumbling in Alabama, South Carolina, North Carolina and
Tennessee. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   SEC-LIVENT (Undated) _ The founders of Livent Inc., the Broadway
theater company known for such lavish productions as ``Ragtime''
and ``Kiss of the Spider Woman,'' were indicted on charges they
inflated corporate earnings and took $4.6 million in kickbacks. In
addition, the Securities and Exchange Commission accused Garth
Drabinsky and Myron Gottlieb in a lawsuit of siphoning off money
for themselves by inflating invoices paid to vendors. By Melody
Petersen.
</P>
</TEXT>
