<HEADLINE>
BIPARTISANSHIP IS ELUSIVE COMMODITY IN CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Jan. 17)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``Bipartisan'' is the word senators are using as
they stride before television cameras to describe the way they and
their colleagues are conducting the impeachment trial of Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Each senator, having been sworn to impartiality by Chief Justice
William Rehnquist, promises to weigh the evidence as it is
presented and then, without consideration for party politics, to
vote for or against the two articles of impeachment passed by the
House.
</P>
<P>
   But the routine often is nothing more than a charade to please
the folks back home who want their elected representatives to work
together for the good of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Most senators know how they will vote on impeachment. But they
desperately want to avoid the appearance of narrow partisanship
that tarnished the House proceedings in which debate exploded with
ideological rhetoric and in which Republicans on the Judiciary
Committee voted against Clinton while Democrats voted for him.
</P>
<P>
   Some senators undoubtedly hope that when they get down to a
final judgment on Clinton's fate, polarization really will give way
to bipartisanship. That is what happened a quarter century ago when
the House Judiciary Committee approved articles of impeachment
against Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republicans joined Democrats in voting to impeach the
president. But that is where the process ended because Nixon,
having been informed by congressional leaders that he would be
found guilty in the Senate, resigned rather than suffer the ordeal
of a trial.
</P>
<P>
   It was the quest for an aura of bipartisanship that led the
Senate on Jan. 8 to vote 100 to 0 for the compromise on trial
procedures proposed by conservative Republican Phil Gramm of Texas
and liberal Democrat Edward Kennedy of Massachusetts. That
remarkable tally permitted the Senate to draw a sharp contrast
between itself and the House.
</P>
<P>
   But bipartisanship is an elusive commodity in an institution
such as the Senate, which is made up of members elected on party
platforms.
</P>
<P>
   That is why many observers contend that Clinton's Republican
prosecutors cannot garner the 67 votes _ two thirds of the Senate _
required by the Constitution to convict the president. That is why
a number of senators in both parties have suggested that in the
final analysis Congress should censure the president rather than
let him off without an official congressional reprimand.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, that may be the most important feat of
bipartisanship in the tragedy of the Clinton presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Although bipartisanship often is difficult to attain on Capitol
Hill, it can be crucial in determining the course of the republic.
</P>
<P>
   When George Bush prepared to dispatch American combat forces to
turn back Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1991, he sought a
congressional resolution of support from a Democratic-controlled
Congress. Many senators, especially Democrats, were wary of America
becoming mired in another Vietnam. Some compared Bush's plan to the
1964 Gulf of Tonkin Resolution, which passed Congress and granted
Lyndon Johnson authority to project America into the deadly morass
in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, Bush got his bipartisan resolution. By a vote of
52 to 42, the Senate approved the declaration. It fared even better
in the House, where the vote was 250 to 83. Bush already had
authority as commander-in-chief to send troops into combat, but he
felt more secure doing so once Congress had pledged its support.
</P>
<P>
   When the building blocks of America's enlightened post-World War
II foreign policy were put in place during Harry Truman's
presidency, their acceptance and approval in Congress depended on
the bipartisan leadership exerted by Michigan Republican Arthur
Vandenberg, who headed the Senate Foreign Relations Committee in
the Republican-dominated 80th Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Vandenberg, who had been a leading isolationist before the war,
became an invaluable partner in the initiatives taken by Truman to
help establish the United Nations, win congressional support for
the Marshall Plan and aid to Greece and Turkey, and break the
Soviet Union's blockade on occupied Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Sen. Everett Dirksen of Illinois played a somewhat
similar role in helping Lyndon Johnson push the 1964 Civil Rights
Act through the Senate. Johnson desperately needed GOP votes to
break the southern-imposed filibuster that prevented passage of the
measure that opened public accommodations to blacks.
</P>
<P>
   In the decades immediately preceding that struggle, Republican
conservatives had joined their southern colleagues consistently to
bottle up civil rights legislation. So Johnson knew that the only
way he could break the filibuster, masterminded by Georgia's astute
Sen. Richard Russell, was to win the support of Dirksen, the Senate
Republican leader.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of such Senate Democratic leaders as Hubert
Humphrey of Minnesota and Mike Mansfield of Montana, Johnson
finally persuaded Dirksen to join the civil rights battle. Once
that happened, the pending civil rights bill, which had originated
in the House, passed the Senate and became law.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1950s, when Johnson was Senate majority leader and
his mentor, Sam Rayburn of Texas, was speaker of the House, they
provided immeasurable support to Republican President Dwight D.
Eisenhower on important legislative issues, especially those
involving America's commitments abroad.
</P>
<P>
   In the impeachment trial of Clinton, we can only hope that the
Senate will return to the bipartisanship it exhibited on Jan. 8
rather than emulate the narrow partisanship demonstrated by the
House.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
