<SLUG> BC-SPEAKERS-NEWRULES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE TRYING TO RECLAIM FURNITURE, KEEPSAKES FROM FORMER SPEAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In their heyday, they were the kings of Capitol
Hill, but former House speakers are finding that retirement isn't
what it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   First they lost their taxpayer-financed offices. Now the
institution they once headed is trying to reclaim desks, chairs,
rugs and a host of other keepsakes _ including some priceless
artifacts _ that the former lawmakers took with them when they left
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Legendary Speaker Sam Rayburn, who dominated the House for
nearly two decades until his retirement in 1961, returned to Texas
with a treasure trove that included a 2,500-year-old Grecian urn
valued at nearly $3 million, a crystal chandelier, the original
marble speaker's rostrum and a fireplace mantel that came to the
Capitol from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the disputed items are more mundane. Former Speaker Jim
Wright of Fort Worth recreated his Capitol office at Texas
Christian University with a credenza, a small table, a couch and a
display case that had been government property.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want to take it back, they can,'' Wright said. ``I
don't lay personal claim to any of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Speaker Tom Foley of Washington state, who now serves as
ambassador to Japan, has also agreed to turn over any disputed
items.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the House clerk's office have opened negotiations
with the custodians of relics claimed by Speakers Thomas P. ``Tip''
O'Neill of Massachusetts, Carl Albert of Oklahoma and John
McCormack of Massachusetts, all of whom have died.
</P>
<P>
   An aide to former Speaker Newt Gingrich, who resigned in
November, said the Georgia Republican has no plans to recreate his
Washington office with furnishings from the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some things that he's allowed to take, maybe a gift
that someone gave him,'' spokesman Mike Shields said. ``But as far
as keeping the furniture, definitely not. I don't know what he
would do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rayburn's collection is on display at the Sam Rayburn Library
and Museum in Bonham, which is fighting to keep it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish it had come up when Mr. Rayburn was alive,'' said H.G.
Delaney, the museum director. ``He had the ability to use language
that would take wallpaper off. He wouldn't be exactly pleased, I
don't think.''
</P>
<P>
   The search for missing Capitol furnishings began shortly after
Republicans took control of the House in 1995, ending 40 years of
Democratic dominance. Trying to fulfill their promise of better
management, GOP leaders ordered an inventory that revealed some
glaring gaps in the property lists.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute also highlights the changing culture of Congress. In
Rayburn's day, speakers ran the House with unquestioned authority.
Tradition and practice also gave them the right to take their
office furnishings and other mementos when they left office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these items should never have been taken from the
Capitol,'' said one official involved in the reclamation effort.
``It was a different era. We want to make this as painless as
possible for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress eliminated another retirement benefit in 1993 by ending
the practice of giving former speakers lifetime government offices
and staff. The bill gave the living speakers five years, until
Sept. 30, 1998, to make other arrangements. Wright moved to TCU,
which is also the repository for the correspondence and other
documents from his 34-year congressional career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is as near to being a replica as TCU was able to create,
given the shape of the room,'' the Fort Worth Democrat said.
</P>
<P>
   Wright, who came to Congress in 1955 when Rayburn was still in
power, said speakers were expected to make their papers and
memorabilia available to the public after leaving office. O'Neill
recreated his office at Boston College, which has sent the chair
that O'Neill used on the speaker's podium back to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was done was done with the full consent and knowledge of
everyone involved,'' Wright said. ``If the rules have changed,
OK.''
</P>
<P>
   The guardians of Rayburn's legacy are a bit more reluctant to
surrender the showcase items in their museum. Delaney said the
Grecian urn was a gift to Rayburn from the Greek government.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Mr. Rayburn wanted here was a replica of the speaker's
office,'' Delaney said. ``Those people are saying that he should
have had permission from the Congress. Back in those days, he would
not have had any trouble getting permission.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
