<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ACQUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRO ACQUITTAL: MISDEMEANORS DON'T MERIT REMOVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House no-surprises strategy for defending
the president aims to risk nothing that would sway the majority of
Americans against Bill Clinton or change the judgment of senators
who now appear unlikely to convict him and remove him from office.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the constitutional and factual arguments prepared for
the Senate trial and detailed in the 130-page trial brief released
Wednesday look very similar to the ones the president's lawyers
made in the impeachment case in the House. They are that:
</P>
<P>
   --While the president, in an effort to conceal his affair and
avoid embarrassment, misled his family, staff, and the nation about
his relationship with White House intern Monica S. Lewinsky, he did
not intend to commit perjury or obstruct justice.
</P>
<P>
   --There is no evidence to support the allegations the president
lied under oath, and innocent explanations _ faulty memory among
them _ explain why the president's federal grand jury testimony
sometimes appears at odds with Lewinsky's.
</P>
<P>
   --No matter how badly the president behaved, his wrongdoing
falls short of the constitutional standard of high crimes and
misdemeanors that would merit removing him from office and
overturning the will of voters who elected him in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We plan to present, on behalf of the president, a vigorous,
successful, and complete defense,'' said Clinton lawyer Gregory
Craig. ``We are optimistic, we are confident, that the senators. .
.will conclude that the articles do not justify or warrant
conviction or removal from office.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House plan to keep the trial short, argue the facts
agressively, and paint the charges as inventions of an overzealous
prosecution could be put at risk, however, if the Senate votes to
allow witnesses or new evidence in the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Witnesses are not in the president's interest,'' said Susan
Low Bloch, a law professor at Georgetown University Law Center.
``Not because they will be so damaging _ some could be quite
sympathetic to him. But because the longer the trial goes, the
harder it will be to predict the outcome. The risk for the White
House is that a prolonged trial that ties up the country will put
pressure on the president to resign.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week's Senate agreement to get the trial under way Thursday
and require votes later on witnesses or new evidence gave the White
House some relief. James Kennedy, a spokesman for the White House
counsel's office, said a speedy trial built on the existing record
is in the ``best interest of the country to get this behind us.
</P>
<P>
   For the White House, the trickiest witness would be Lewinsky,
whose sworn statements before independent counsel Kenneth W.
Starr's grand jury have been used by lawyers both for and against
the president. Lewinsky's testimony on the nature of her physical
relationship with the president contradicts his and raised a
perjury charge against him.
</P>
<P>
   On the obstruction of justice charge, Lewinsky's testimony
appears to support Clinton's contention that he did not ask her to
lie about their affair in her affadavit in the Jones case and did
not provide her a job in exchange for her concealing it.
</P>
<P>
   Yet any help Lewinsky could provide the president is more than
offset by the unpredictability of what she might say and how she
would behave while being questioned in the well of the Senate,
legal experts say. Kennedy signaled the White House's caution with
Lewinsky when he denied a published report that Clinton lawyers
were prepared to challenge her credibility as a witness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Allowing a vivid narrative of what actually took place between
Lewinsky and Clinton, getting into a `he said, she said' debate on
the Senate floor, is not what the president's defenders want,''
said Jamin Raskin, a law professor at American University. ``It
could end up in a humiliating and not very positive outcome for the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Martin Meehan, a Massachusetts Democrat on the
House Judiciary Committee, said it would be a ``disaster'' if the
Senate trial turned into a highly explicit discussion of ``where
the president touched her and whether he meant to gratify her.''
The risk for the White House, Meehan said, is ``eventually the
American people will get angry about the president and his tawdry
affair.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, White House lawyers hope to stick to their game plan.
First, they will pound away on the constitutional argument that the
president's alleged wrongdoing does not meet the high standard of
proof of an impeachable offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is ridiculous, and a dangerous precedent, to think of
removing the president from office because of this sexual
misconduct,'' said Cass Sunstein, a law professor at the University
of Chicago and one of 200 constitutional scholars who signed a
letter advising the House against impeachment. ``The president's
offenses may be legitimate for putting him in jail, but they are
not a legitimate basis for removing him.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Ruff, the White House counsel, is expected to argue in
the trial that the president, whose private and personal conduct he
described to the House Judiciary Committee as ``morally
reprehensible,'' did not abuse his high office, endanger the
nation, or impair his ability to lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to have committed an impeachable offense,'' Ruff told
the committee, ``the president must have acted to subvert our
system of government. That did not happen.''
</P>
<P>
   On another constitutional point, White House lawyers will assert
that the articles, as written, are legally flawed because the are,
at the same time, too complex and too vague. Because the articles
are not specific enough, the senators might not agree on what they
are addressing with votes to convict or acquit.
</P>
<P>
   The second phase of the White House case will be arguing for
acquittal on the specific charges of perjury and obstruction of
justice. In the House, the president's legal team did not assault
the facts of the independent counsel's voluminous report and got
criticized for being too passive. The Senate trial will be
different, Kennedy predicts, as White House lawyers aggressively
challenge evidence as misleading, contradictory, and erroneous in
the `one-sided and prejudicial'' Starr record.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can challenge the facts, and we can argue them,'' Kennedy
said.
</P>
<P>
   On the perjury charge, the White House lawyers will argue the
president never intended to lie to the grand jury and did, in fact,
admit to an improper relationship with Lewinsky. But, they say,
Clinton chose his words carefully because he did not want to reveal
the affair and did not believe the intimate activity with Lewinsky
fit the definition of sexual relations provided by US District
Judge Susan Webber Wright in Paula Jones's civil case.
</P>
<P>
   They also will maintain a perjury charge can't be based on
Clinton and Lewinsky's differing versions about their sexual
contact or on ``such insignificant matters'' as the president
``misremembering'' when he began an affair with Lewinsky or him
``understating'' how frequently they met, according to the legal
brief.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may judge he crossed the line,'' Craig said to the House
Judiciary Committee, describing Clinton's grand jury testimony as
at times ``evasive, incomplete, misleading, even maddening.'' ``But
there is no testimony, no proof, that President Clinton knew he was
wrong and intentionally lied.''
</P>
<P>
   On the obstruction of justice charge, White House lawyers will
tell the Senate that no one who appeared before the Starr grand
jury, including Lewinsky, White House secretary Betty Currie, or
lawyer Vernon E. Jordan Jr., testified that Clinton told them to
lie under oath, instructed them to conceal or retrieve gifts from
Lewinsky, or demanded that Lewinsky be found a job. They will note
the Lewinsky job search started before she was called as a witness
in the Jones case, and that Clinton was giving Lewinsky gifts at
the same time he is alleged to have suggested Lewinsky get rid of
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning, this inherent contradiction has puzzled
investigations,'' the trial brief said. ``If there was a plot to
conceal these gifts, why did the president give Ms. Lewinsky
several more gifts at the very moment the concelament plan was
lalegedly hatched?''
</P>
<P>
   In the House, Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde of
Illinois dismissed much of the president's defense as ``legal
hairsplitting and semantic gymnastics.'' But Bloch, the Georgetown
law professor, said she believes the House managers, who will act
as prosecutors in the trial, will have a hard time proving
obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``My impression is there is no testimony from anyone that nails
the president on it, and on the contrary, there is material that
exonerates him,'' Bloch said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Meehan, Lewinsky's volunteered statement to the
grand jury that ``no one ever told me to lie'' is significant.
``That speaks volumes to the president's innocence on the
obstruction of justice charge.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the White House lawyers are expected to challenge the
relevancy and fairness of any attempts by the House managers to
depose Kathleen Willey and other women who gave testimony about
Clinton in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are irrelevant. It's too late in the day to attach on
other alleged affairs,'' Raskin said. ``The public won't accept it,
and the Senate would have to squint pretty hard to allow it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
