<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON HOPEFUL SENATE WILL DO `THE RIGHT THING' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton said Wednesday he was hopeful
that the Senate would do ``the right thing'' and acquit him of all
charges as House prosecutors prepared to make their case Thursday
in only the second presidential impeachment trial in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking his silence of the last few weeks on the issue, Clinton
declined to comment directly on the perjury and obstruction of
justice charges against him, saying he will leave it to his lawyers
to make the case for why the 42nd president should not be removed
from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing for me is to spend as little time thinking
about that as possible,'' Clinton told reporters, on the eve of the
Senate convening to hear oral arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton added that he plans to focus on other important issues
as his trial unfolds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the brief speaks for itself, and the statements
which have been made by hundreds of constitutional experts and
others ... that this matter was not the subject of impeachment,''
he said. ``I trust that the right thing will be done. And I think,
in the meanwhile, I need to work on the business of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made the comments shortly after White House lawyers
delivered to the Senate a 130-page brief rebutting point-by-point
the charges as outlined in the two articles of impeachment that the
House approved along party lines last month.
</P>
<P>
   In its brief, Clinton's defense team stuck to its contention
that the case against the president stems from an extramarital
sexual affair that under normal circumstances would have been kept
private and includes charges that are unconstitutionally vague and
ought to be dismissed outright.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers argued that the Senate ``has an obligation to turn
away an unwise and unwarranted misuse of the awesome power of
impeachment,'' which they insisted the nation's founding fathers
intended should be used only ``in the gravest circumstances, when
the stability of our system of government hung in the balance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Senate removes this president for a wrongful
relationship he hoped to keep private, for what will the House ask
the Senate to remove the next president, and the next?'' they
continued. They also contended that the House impeachment
proceedings were too `` partisan'' and ``unfair'' to even warrant a
trial in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Removing the president on these facts would substantially
alter the delicate constitutional balance and move us closer to a
quasi-parliamentary system in which the president is elected by the
choice of the people, but continues in office only at the pleasure
of Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   They also called on the senators to consider ``the will and
interests of the people'' in their deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not simply the president, but the vote of the American
people rendered in schools, church halls and other civic centers
all across the land 26 months ago, that is hanging in the
balance,'' they wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate filing with the Senate, the 13-member House
prosecution team, which is made up of Republicans, issued a short
response to the White House defense argument that the case is
essentially about a private sexual affair. The prosecution team
insisted that Clinton should be removed from office, not for the
affair he had with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky, but
for lying under oath about it and trying to cover it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of the articles of impeachment warrant the conviction,
removal from office and disqualification from holding further
office of President William Jefferson Clinton,'' the prosecution
team wrote.
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors also delivered to the Senate much of the
evidence and other supporting documentation that independent
counsel Kenneth Starr sent to them last September when he filed his
report outlining impeachable offenses against the president.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks to reporters, Clinton stressed that he intends to
continue with his plans to deliver the State of the Union address
next Tuesday, despite the fact that it will take place on the same
day his lawyers are scheduled to begin their oral presentation on
the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opinion is that I should be doing my job for the country,
and other people should be handling the defense and dealing with
this issue. And that's what I intend to do,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   He also indicated that he does not plan to mention the
impeachment proceedings during his address because most Americans
have heard ``quite extensively'' about it already.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they would like it if somebody up here were putting
their interests first ... and I think that's what they expect me to
do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A number of senators have urged him to postpone the annual
speech to a joint session of Congress and the nation, saying it
would be ``awkward'' for it to take place on the same day his
lawyers present their case against impeachment. In an effort to
avoid a conflict with the trial, some senators have also urged
their leaders to postpone the opening of Clinton's defense
presentation by one day to allow the State of the Union address to
take place Jan. 19, as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   But an aide to Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said
Republicans were not prepared ``at this point'' to interrupt the
trial schedule.
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors will begin their opening arguments at Thursday
afternoon, marking only the second time that a presidential
impeachment trial has taken place in the Senate. The last time was
in 1868 when President Andrew Johnson was acquitted of charges
against him by one vote.
</P>
<P>
   A two-thirds vote will be needed to convict Clinton and oust him
from office. But few senators have indicated that House prosecutors
will be able to persuade 67 of them to vote for conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Still, following a tour of the Senate chamber Wednesday, the
prosecutors said the case for removal can be made successfully if
senators give careful consideration to the facts and the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our case is very solid if people will listen,'' said
Rep. James Sensenbrenner, R-Wis., who will take part in the opening
statements Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., also said
that senators will be better informed once they get the ``full
picture'' of what Clinton did from the prosecution's
``comprehensive presentation.''
</P>
<P>
   In preparation for the opening arguments, two long, curved
tables were set up on the floor of the Senate on Wednesday. Each
table can accommodate up to 15 people from each side.
</P>
<P>
   The House prosecutors will have 24 hours over the next three
days to present their case. Clinton's lawyers will get the same
amount of time next week to present their defense.
</P>
<P>
   Senate officials Wednesday issued rules of conduct for the 100
senators, who were sworn in as jurors last week. They are expected
to attend all sessions and to refrain from extraneous reading at
their seats. The senators, accustomed to speaking their minds
whenever they want, will also be required to remain seated and
silent until conclusion of the arguments. They then will be
required to submit questions in writing through Chief Justice
William Rehnquist, who is presiding over the trial.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
