<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1896 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-microsoft14-cox     01-13 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-microsoft14-cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WITNESS: MICROSOFT LACKS MONOPOLY POWER
 &HT;    Moving in (f) financial and (w) Washington queues
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In opening its defense Wednesday against antitrust
charges, Microsoft Corp. called as its first witness an economist
who held that the software giant's Windows operating system did not
give it monopoly power over personal computer desktops.
</P>
<P>
   The view taken by Massachusetts Institute of Technology
economics professor Richard Schmalansee appeared to astound David
Boies, the government's lead attorney, as he began what promises to
be a lengthy cross-examination.
</P>
<P>
   In bringing the landmark case, the government asserted that
Microsoft has illegally wielded its monopoly power by seeking to
extend its hold to the Internet while crushing its rivals.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft's underlying power _ which is not illegal and
which is based on the fact that Windows runs on more than 90
percent of newly shipped personal computers _ had not been an issue
until Schmalansee took the stand.
</P>
<P>
   The witness, dean of MIT's Sloan School of Management, insisted
that Microsoft does not have a monopoly because its operating
system dominance is threatened by companies that could produce
rival technologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't agree that (Windows) is a relevant market,''
Schmalansee told Boies. ``It makes no sense analytically. There are
developers out there writing for other platforms.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmalansee argued that such operating systems as Linux and
Beos, both of which run, along with Windows, on Intel-based
machines, were waiting in the wings as potential competitors, ready
to pounce on Microsoft's most valued turf. Even hand-held units,
such as those that run the Palm system, are ``competitors to
Windows,'' Schmalansee said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you really mean to tell the judge that this hand-held
system is now a serious competitor to Windows?'' Boies asked
Schmalansee in an incredulous tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``My answer is no,''' Schmalansee replied, seemingly backing off
a bit. ``But it is the germ of a potential competitor. To rule it
out is to have a constricted view of the fluidity of this
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   In filing 328 pages of testimony, Schmalansee wrote on page 250:
``Whatever one believes about Microsoft's power in the 'market' for
PC operating systems, the Windows desktop is surely not a relevant
market _ any more than the exterior of a Coke can is a 'market.' It
is only one of many effective channels of software distribution and
promotion.''
</P>
<P>
   The concept of a ``relevant market'' is central to all antitrust
law. Unless the courts find that such a market in fact exists, a
finding that any company wields monopoly power, let alone abuses
that power by seeking to dominate other markets, cannot be made.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department and 19 states allege that Microsoft holds
a monopoly in the operating system for personal computers that it
has preserved and attempted to extend illegally.
</P>
<P>
   Dismissing Schmalansee's views, Boies said outside the
courtroom: ``It's like they used to say at the top in the former
Soviet Union that they were a democracy. They are not around
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmalansee took the stand after U.S. District Court Judge
Thomas Penfield
</P>
<P>
   Jackson denied a motion by Microsoft to dismiss antitrust
charges at the mid-point of the trial, now in its 11th week.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, the ruling means that the government can now put on
its case. Since Jackson insisted that all testimony be submitted in
advance in written form, the Microsoft trial has taken place in
reserve, with nearly all the time being taken up by
cross-examination of hostile witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 1848EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0328 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1899 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-microsoft14-cox     01-13 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-microsoft14-cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WITNESS: MICROSOFT LACKS MONOPOLY POWER
 &HT;    Moving in (f) financial and (w) Washington queues
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In opening its defense Wednesday against antitrust
charges, Microsoft Corp. called as its first witness an economist
who held that the software giant's Windows operating system did not
give it monopoly power over personal computer desktops.
</P>
<P>
   The view taken by Massachusetts Institute of Technology
economics professor Richard Schmalansee appeared to astound David
Boies, the government's lead attorney, as he began what promises to
be a lengthy cross-examination.
</P>
<P>
   In bringing the landmark case, the government asserted that
Microsoft has illegally wielded its monopoly power by seeking to
extend its hold to the Internet while crushing its rivals.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft's underlying power _ which is not illegal and
which is based on the fact that Windows runs on more than 90
percent of newly shipped personal computers _ had not been an issue
until Schmalansee took the stand.
</P>
<P>
   The witness, dean of MIT's Sloan School of Management, insisted
that Microsoft does not have a monopoly because its operating
system dominance is threatened by companies that could produce
rival technologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't agree that (Windows) is a relevant market,''
Schmalansee told Boies. ``It makes no sense analytically. There are
developers out there writing for other platforms.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmalansee argued that such operating systems as Linux and
Beos, both of which run, along with Windows, on Intel-based
machines, were waiting in the wings as potential competitors, ready
to pounce on Microsoft's most valued turf. Even hand-held units,
such as those that run the Palm system, are ``competitors to
Windows,'' Schmalansee said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you really mean to tell the judge that this hand-held
system is now a serious competitor to Windows?'' Boies asked
Schmalansee in an incredulous tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``My answer is no,''' Schmalansee replied, seemingly backing off
a bit. ``But it is the germ of a potential competitor. To rule it
out is to have a constricted view of the fluidity of this
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   In filing 328 pages of testimony, Schmalansee wrote on page 250:
``Whatever one believes about Microsoft's power in the 'market' for
PC operating systems, the Windows desktop is surely not a relevant
market _ any more than the exterior of a Coke can is a 'market.' It
is only one of many effective channels of software distribution and
promotion.''
</P>
<P>
   The concept of a ``relevant market'' is central to all antitrust
law. Unless the courts find that such a market in fact exists, a
finding that any company wields monopoly power, let alone abuses
that power by seeking to dominate other markets, cannot be made.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department and 19 states allege that Microsoft holds
a monopoly in the operating system for personal computers that it
has preserved and attempted to extend illegally.
</P>
<P>
   Dismissing Schmalansee's views, Boies said outside the
courtroom: ``It's like they used to say at the top in the former
Soviet Union that they were a democracy. They are not around
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmalansee took the stand after U.S. District Court Judge
Thomas Penfield
</P>
<P>
   Jackson denied a motion by Microsoft to dismiss antitrust
charges at the mid-point of the trial, now in its 11th week.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, the ruling means that the government can now put on
its case. Since Jackson insisted that all testimony be submitted in
advance in written form, the Microsoft trial has taken place in
reserve, with nearly all the time being taken up by
cross-examination of hostile witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
