<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1906 &Cx1f; tic-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR &LR;      01-13 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Thursday, Jan. 14. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
SOLDIER-OF-MISFORTUNE (Phoenix) - It was only a matter time before
the so-called ``Soldier of Misfortune,'' Bobby Joe Keesee, would
strike again. After all, the former Korean War hero was out of
prison again. In between terms, Keesee had stolen a plane while
stationed at Fort Huachuca and flown to Cuba, hijacked a plane in
Thailand and flew to North Vietnam during the war, killed a U.S.
diplomat in northern Mexico in a foiled ransom attempt and, more
recently, been involved in financial scams. So, when Lake Havasu
City boatman Harry Christensen placed an ad on the internet trying
to sale his airplane and Keesee arranged a test flight, you figure
that something would happen. It did. Christensen apparently was
killed by Keesee during the flight to Albuquerque. Keesee and his
wife have been arrested, but Christensen's body still hasn't been
found. By MARK SHAFFER. Story will move in the ``A' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CLINTON-AZNOTES (Phoenix) - The crisp morning air nips at the
children's cheeks, making them ruddy. But the kids running about
the Kyrene de Los Cerritos playground aren't bothered by it at all.
A mother takes in the scene from the playground gate and marvels at
the innocent faces. But already, the presidential scandal is taking
its toll. ``Look at them. They don't have a care in the world,''
says Roberta, who has a daughter in kindergarten. ``But the other
night, my daughter asked if her daddy would cheat on us like
President Clinton did on his family. I didn't even know she knew
what cheating was.''
</P>
<P>
   By JULIE AMPARANO. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
LEGAL-OBSESSION (Phoenix) - Years ago, the Span family of Phoenix
was known as a group of gritty strivers who invested their hopes
and sweat in the future of Phoenix. Now, in the halls of Maricopa
County Superior Court, they are known for their strange obsession
with suing the city, alleging cover-ups and conspiracy related to
the condemning of their property in 1988. Their lives revolve
around their court cases. They have filed tens of thousands of
papers in court. They spend their days preparing filings and
meeting court deadlines. In between, they crash from exhaustion.
They are even suffering from what one lawyer calls `legal abuse
syndrome.'' By VICTORIA HARKER. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
201YEAST (Phoenix) - Fear not, fellow and sister foodies. Follow me
into battle. Today, we tackle the Yeast Beast, one of the most
beneficial yet somehow frightening denizens of the food world.
Otherwise-good cooks tremble and turn the cookbook page at the very
word yeast. Fear not! The Yeast Beast can be yours. With PHOTO and
</P>
<P>
   201INTRO, 201YEASTTIPS, 201BREADTIPS, 201 BREAKBOOKS AND
201YEAST-RECIPES, 201REVIEW. By JUDY WALKER. Stories moved in the
``D'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
NOTARO-COLUMN (Phoenix) - As I looked at the letter in my hand from
the city of Phoenix that I received several weeks ago, my blood
began to bubble. It explained that a complaint had been filed
against my front yard, claiming that it contained an inordinate
amount of trash and overgrown weeds. On a hunch, I sought out all
of my neighbors and discovered, not to my surprise, that we had all
received the same letter on the same day. There could be only one
culprit, I decided. It had to be the Neighborhood Nemesis, or, as
he likes to call himself, the president of the neighborhood
association _ a man who doesn't even have a yard, only a small
strip of grass as wide as my thigh. By LAURI NOTARO. Story moved in
the ``L'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
LEIBOWITZ-COLUMN (Phoenix) - Maybe we should all wear black _
warm-ups _ embroidered with the name Jordan. It's only fitting:
He's quitting, so it's time to mourn.
</P>
<P>
   Expect infinite paeans to His Airness, the man/god in the red
jersey numbered 23. But Jordan quitting is exactly what sports
needs, for he is a perfect marker of all that ails sports: The
athlete turned pitchman, a soulless corporate shill; a human being
reduced to a logo; a name manipulated into a slogan. By DAVID
LEIBOWITZ. Story moved in the ``S'' and ``K'' categories.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
AUTO-REVIEW (Phoenix) - For stylists decided to play the retro card
with the (mostly) new 1999 Mustang, celebrating the 35th
anniversary of the original pony car with a nod to the past.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ford engineers were refining this old-style muscle
car into a thoroughly modern automobile, making it tighter, quicker
and generally more fun to be with. By BOB GOLFEN. Story will move
in the ``L'' category. EMBARGOED FOR SATURDAY, JAN. 16. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
