<HEADER>
A1916 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON-NYT &LR;      01-13 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE PURSUES STRATEGY OF CONCILIATION TOWARD SENATE
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-LEGAL, IMPEACH-HOUSE,
IMPEACH-SCENE.) 
(nk) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton said Wednesday that he intended
to spend as little time as possible thinking about his impeachment
trial, choosing instead to do the work of the people, who he says
have already heard more than enough about impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   As the Senate begins its trial in earnest on Thursday with
opening statements from House prosecutors, Clinton's aides say he
remains relatively uninvolved in his defense against charges that
could end his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he has kept up a full public schedule and spent time
preparing for the State of the Union address next week _ acting, in
short, as if some other president were on trial.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, asked by a reporter at a social engagement last month
how it felt to be impeached, responded, ``Not bad.'' The president
expressed confidence that future historians would consider his
impeachment only a minor blot on his legacy.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief session with reporters before a meeting Wednesday
with labor leaders, Clinton said, ``The important thing for me is
to spend as little time thinking about that as possible and as much
time working on the issues we're here to discuss as possible. They
have their job to do in the Senate, and I have mine, and I intend
to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The appearance of presidential detachment is one prong of a
White House strategy that has emerged in recent days as the Senate
opens the first impeachment trial of a president in 131 years.
</P>
<P>
   After a year of employing a combination of delay and defiance in
response to the investigations of Kenneth W. Starr, the independent
counsel, and the House Judiciary Committee, the White House has
adopted a markedly more conciliatory tone toward the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The president and his advisers hope that the bipartisanship
shown in the 100-to-0 vote on trial procedures last week will
survive as the trial continues over the next several weeks. To that
end, White House officials are careful to offer only praise for
Senate leaders, so as not to appear to be meddling with the
president's jury.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was asked whether he thought the charges of perjury and
obstruction of justice against him were warranted. He replied, ``My
opinion is not important here. My opinion is that I should be doing
my job for the country and other people should be handling the
defense and dealing with this issue, and that's what I intend to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton strives to present an image of unconcern about the
proceeding unfolding in the Senate, his lawyers and aides are
approaching the members of his jury with a deference they did not
show his inquisitors in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're treating the Senate with more gravity, absolutely,''
said Paul Begala, senior adviser to the president, ``because they
are approaching this just as the framers of the Constitution would
have wanted, by setting aside partisanship, proposing a process
that allows us a fair chance to state our case.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the White House has not announced how it intends to
present its case over three days next week, officials are
considering adding some new faces to the now-familiar legal team
that argued the president's brief before the House.
</P>
<P>
   The group will be led by Charles F.C. Ruff, the White House
counsel, Gregory B. Craig, coordinator of the president's
impeachment defense, and David E. Kendall, Clinton's chief private
lawyer. But officials are considering using several younger, less
combative members of the defense team to present a gentler face to
the Senate. These lawyers include Nicole K. Seligman, a partner of
Kendall, and Lanny A. Breuer and Cheryl D. Mills of the White House
counsel's office.
</P>
<P>
   But the deferential treatment of the Senate does not extend to
the House and its prosecution team, known as impeachment managers.
White House officials continue a campaign of vitriol against House
Republicans, who engineered last month's vote on two articles of
impeachment along near-party lines.
</P>
<P>
   In a trial brief filed with the Senate Wednesday, Clinton's
lawyers describe last month's House vote as ``an unwise and
unwarranted misuse of the awesome power of impeachment'' that
threatened the country's democratic institutions.
</P>
<P>
   The brief accuses the House of ignoring the will of the people
and seeking to subvert the result of two national elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``In weighing the evidence and assessing the facts, we ask that
Senators consider not only the intent of the framers but also the
will and interests of the people,'' the president's lawyers write.
``It is the citizens of these United States who will be affected by
and stand in judgment of this process. It is not simply the
president _ but the vote the American people rendered in schools,
church halls and other civic centers all across the land 26 months
ago _ that is hanging in the balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lockhart, the president's press secretary, described the
House prosecutors' trial brief as reading like a ``cheap mystery
novel'' and called the entire process that led to the president's
impeachment on Dec. 19 ``illegitimate.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart's remarks were part of a continuing strategy to paint
the charges against the president as the politically-inspired work
of a rogue independent counsel and a Republican-dominated House.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you read their document,'' Lockhart said of the House
summary of its case against the president, ``you start to
understand the weakness of their case. People who have strong
factual case argue the facts. If you don't have the facts, you
employ plots and subplots and sinister mysteries.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Lockhart continued, ``I think the Senators have
distinguished themselves as able to act in a bipartisan way to
date, clearly distinguishing them from House. There's no big
mystery about our strategy here. As long as they continue their
bipartisanship, we'll treat them accordingly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
