<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSTANG TURNS INTO A STUD  
 (ADV: EMBARGOED FOR SATURDAY, JAN. 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB GOLFEN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Ford stylists decided to play the retro card with the
(mostly) new 1999 Mustang, celebrating the 35th anniversary of the
original pony car with a nod to the past.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ford engineers were refining this old-style muscle
car into a thoroughly modern automobile, making it tighter, quicker
and generally more fun to be with.
</P>
<P>
   All I have to say is: sheesh, 35 years? Why, it was only
yesterday that my buddies and I were careening around the
neighborhood in a slightly used '66 Mustang convertible complete
with a 289 V-8 and the coveted pony interior.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe not yesterday. Maybe it was a long time ago that
Ford took the chassis of its compact Falcon and created a new kind
of funmobile. Unveiled midyear, the 1964{ Mustang was cheerful and
youth-oriented, an all-American that combined the aura of a sports
car with the practicality of a small, inexpensive four-seater.
</P>
<P>
   Quickly, Mustang also became Ford's imagemaker and perennial
performance machine. And, aside from a mid-'70s detour as the
crumby, downsized Mustang II, it has stayed the course.
</P>
<P>
   To recapture the look and style of the original, the designers
took the existing body and adorned it with sharper character lines,
fake hood and side scoops (that's (begin ital) so (end ital) '60s),
taillights that mimic the three-bar lights of the original 1964{, a
Mustang emblem that resembles the one in the original grille, and a
'60s-looking 35th anniversary badge stuck on the front fenders.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's a new look for Mustang, the beveled edges, rounded
flanks and glowering headlights bringing it crisply up to date. And
compared with the archaic suspension and handling of our '66 model,
the new Mustang brings the breed into focus as a car that performs
as good as it looks.
</P>
<P>
   That includes upgraded power for the overhead-cam, 4.6-liter V-8
in the GT test car. This smooth, sophisticated mill, which replaced
the raucous 5-liter pushrod V-8 that faded away a couple years ago,
has been boosted to 260 horsepower, 35 more than last year.
</P>
<P>
   If you're not in the power game, Mustang also comes with an
upgraded 3.8-liter V-6 that's been kicked up 40 horsepower to 190.
This is how most Mustangs will be equipped, because enough power is
still there, and the price tag is about $4,000 less than a
comparable V-8.
</P>
<P>
   The enhanced V-8 brings Mustang GT's acceleration more into line
with archrival Chevrolet Camaro Z-28. The extra oomph is noticeable
especially from a standstill, when the Mustang hunkers down and
takes off with a hot-rod roar. Most satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   Typical of an overhead-cam engine, it lacks the massive low-end
torque of pushrod models, but soars mightily into the upper rev
range, picking up power as it climbs.
</P>
<P>
   If you require more, there's the limited-edition Mustang SVT,
with 320 horsepower stuffed under the hood, thanks to reworked
cylinder heads with a total of 32 valves instead of 16, and some
intake- and exhaust-system redesign.
</P>
<P>
   If that's (begin ital) still (end ital) not enough, wait until
April, when the new Cobra is due. The engine's the same as the SVT,
but the Cobra will boast Mustang's first-ever independent rear
suspension for better handling and overall finesse.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, the Mustang GT's handling feels more supple and better
controlled than last year's. Credit goes to many incremental
suspension refinements, including about an inch-longer spring
travel to smooth the road, and quicker steering with a smaller
turning radius to straighten out curves.
</P>
<P>
   Our tester was outfitted with 16-inch performance tires;
17-inchers are available. In curves and quick maneuvers, the
Mustang remains poised and controllable, feeling nicely balanced.
</P>
<P>
   A quick run along a twisting desert road was a romp, though in
some tight turns at speed, the Mustang tends to feel heavy.
Advanced traction control keeps everything nicely tucked in, and
the four-wheel disc brakes are highly effective.
</P>
<P>
   The body of the convertible has been strengthened with box-rail
extensions to fight body flex and shake, and new motor mounts for
the V-8 to increase stiffness.
</P>
<P>
   Shakes, rattles and heaves are a lot less noticeable in the new
Mustang than in any of its predecessors. That '66 convertible shook
like a wet dog over rough surfaces, and later models weren't much
better.
</P>
<P>
   The hydraulic top works nicely, but the boot cover for the
folded top is a fussy affair that's destined to remain in the
trunk. Top down, cruising is pure hedonistic delight.
</P>
<P>
   The engine roar is another issue. The drone of the sporty
exhaust system becomes tiresome and intrusive, especially coupled
to an automatic transmission, as was our test car (five-speed stick
is available).
</P>
<P>
   The interior is nice, if plain, with decent space for front-seat
occupants. The driver's seat seems to have more legroom, which it
desperately needed. Passengers in the rear need to be considerably
smaller than adult scale _ a standard complaint with Mustang
convertibles.
</P>
<P>
   The trunk is small and shallow, another Mustang tradition.
</P>
<P>
   The '99 Mustang is well-priced across the board, with V-6 coupes
starting at just over $16,000 and lavishly equipped GT convertibles
like our tester just over $27,000.
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot of style for the money. Especially now that it has
the performance to match. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Ford Mustang GT convertible &QL; 
- Vehicle type: &QL; 
Four-passenger, two-door convertible, rear-wheel drive. &QL; 
- Base price: &QL; 
$24,870. &QL; 
- Price as tested: &QL; 
$27,005. &QL; 
- Engine: &QL; 
4.6-liter V-8, 260 horsepower at 5,250 rpm, 302 pound-feet of
torque at 4,000 rpm. &QL; 
- Transmission: &QL; 
Four-speed automatic. &QL; 
- Wheelbase: &QL; 
101.3 inches. &QL; 
- EPA fuel economy: &QL; 
17 city, 24 highway. &QL; 
- Highs: &QL; 
Engine power. Good handling. Nice styling. &QL; 
- Lows:  &QL; 
Tight back seat. Fake scoops. Engine drone. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 1901EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
