<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1922 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON14-COX     01-13 1310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ON EVE OF SENATE TRIAL, CLINTON SAYS HE'S FOCUSING ON HIS JOB
 &HT;    730&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On the eve of opening arguments in the Senate trial
that threatens his office, President Clinton broke weeks of silence
on the matter to say he has largely delegated his fate to his legal
staff while he carries on with the job of running the country.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrating the point, Clinton's 11-person legal team filed a
130-page brief countering the charges against him, as House
prosecutors filed their own five-page brief reiterating the
allegations. Neither filing broke significant new ground.
</P>
<P>
   A key unresolved matter in the Senate trial is whether to allow
witnesses, but the House Judiciary Committee contacted Monica
Lewinsky's lawyers to see if she would be available for an
interview, said committee spokesman Paul J. McNulty. He said
lawyers for the former White House intern declined to make her
available.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Committee is duty-bound to gather all relevant evidence
and to be thoroughly prepared to present its case in the Senate,''
McNulty said. ``Implicit in the House's right to request witnesses
is the responsibility of the managers to determine who those
witnesses will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Separately, CNN reported that two of the 13 House ``managers''
met this week with Kathleen Willey, a potential witness in the
trial.
</P>
<P>
   The managers were interested in discussing alleged efforts by
the president's supporters to suppress Willey's claim that Clinton
fondled her in a room off the Oval Office, CNN said, citing sources
who were present at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   As trial preparations continued, the president spent the day at
work on issues ranging from his upcoming State of the Union address
to the latest economic meltdown, this time in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   ''My opinion is that I should be doing my job for the country,
and other people should be handling the defense and dealing with
this issue,'' Clinton said after a reporter asked him about his
views on the Senate impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   ''The important thing for me is to spend as little time thinking
about that as possible,'' Clinton said. ''I need to work on the
business of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   With the capital poised for arguments to begin in the first
Senate trial of a president in 130 years, Clinton plans to pay
little attention to the televised proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he's got a packed schedule Thursday, beginning with a
meeting likely to focus on Iraq with his national security adviser,
Samuel Berger, a morning event in nearby Alexandria, Va., to
spotlight administration efforts to put more police on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   As House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., kicks
off the prosecution's opening arguments at 1 p.m. EST before the
Senate, with Chief Justice of the United States William H.
Rehnquist wielding the gavel, Clinton is scheduled to be in an Oval
Office meeting with senior aides _ ostensibly, at least, to work on
the State of the Union address he plans to give before Congress
next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is scheduled to leave town late Thursday for an
overnight trip to New York, where he'll go to Wall Street to
discuss ideas for making capitalism work better for the nation's
poor.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton virtually ruled out the prospect that he might address
his personal predicament as part of his State of the Union speech.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the American people have heard about that quite
extensively over the last year,'' Clinton said. ''I think they
would like it if somebody up here would put their interests first,
their business first, and I think that's what they expect me to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Clinton, ''We have to deal with the problems of America,
the challenges of America, the opportunities of America, and that's
what I intend to do in the State of the Union speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made the remarks in response to reporters' questions
during a brief photo opportunity at the opening of a meeting with
labor leaders in the Cabinet Room.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time he has fielded press inquiries on the
subject of his impeachment since a press conference in Jerusalem in
mid-December, a week before the House voted to impeach him for
perjury and obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted of either charge by a two-thirds majority in the
Senate, an outcome that appeared remote as of Wednesday, Clinton
would be required to leave office immediately and turn his
administration over to Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The Senate was closed on Wednesday as its chamber was readied
for opening arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Television monitors were installed for the first time ever near
the richly paneled walls at the rear of the chamber, and a single
television camera was set up on the chamber's floor, another first.
</P>
<P>
   The 13 House members elected to act as floor managers for the
trial will have up to 24 hours to make their case, a process
expected to stretch out over Thursday, Friday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Monday, Clinton's defense team _ a battery of 11
lawyers from the White House counsel's office and the private law
firm of Williams &AMP; Connolly _ would have an equal period of time to
rebut the charges and mount their defense.
</P>
<P>
   The arguments, from both sides, would be limited to the evidence
contained in the 7,000-page report the House presented to the
Senate to support its allegations that Clinton committed perjury
and obstruction of justice in connection with the Monica Lewinsky
sex-and-deception scandal that first surfaced a year ago this
month.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the legal brief filed by Clinton's lawyers nor the brief
filed Wednesday by House prosecutors broke major new ground.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lawyers amplified and detailed their contention that
none of the House charges rises to the level of ''high crimes and
misdemeanors'' the Constitution regards as impeachable offenses,
and that he is not guilty of the alleged charges in any event.
</P>
<P>
   The House brief claims precisely the opposite, stating
emphatically that ''each and every allegation in Articles I and II
is true and that Articles I and II properly state impeachable
offenses.''
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the White House argument that the charges should be
dismissed after the scheduled arguments, the House brief contends
that the Constitution does not provide for dismissal, only for a
vote on whether to convict.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lawyers insisted that the standard for conviction
should be evidence that is convincing ''beyond reasonable doubt,''
the highest standard applicable under conventional criminal trials.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, however, is not bound by such conventions. Indeed,
the Senate may vote to remove Clinton from office even if he is
found guilty of no specific crime, provided that a two-thirds
majority votes that he is guilty of one or more of the articles of
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   As they have before, Clinton's lawyers made the case that the
allegations before the Senate do not justify removing the president
from office.
</P>
<P>
   ''The gravity of what is at stake _ the democratic choice of the
people _ and the solemnity of the proceedings dictate that a
decision to remove the President from office should follow only
from the most serious of circumstances and should be done in
conformity with Constitutional standards and in the interest of the
Nation and its people,'' Clinton's lawyers argued.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Articles of Impeachment that have been exhibited to the
Senate fall far short of what the Founding Fathers had in mind when
they placed in the hands of the Congress the power to impeach and
remove a President from office,'' they said.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Carr and Ken Foskett of the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
