<HEADER>
A1928 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-LEGISLATURE-HNS     01-13 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-LEGISLATURE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUDGET PLAN TO MAKE BUSH'S TAX CUTS HARDER TO ACHIEVE, LAWMAKER
SAYS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush's tax-relief promises will
be hard to fulfill, a key lawmaker said Wednesday after unveiling a
$91 billion state spending plan that boosts appropriations for
schools and public safety but leaves less money for tax cuts than
Bush desired.
</P>
<P>
   Without touching Texas' initial tobacco-settlement paycheck of
$1.7 billion, and without allocating the $2.5 billion in left-over
revenues from the 1998-99 spending cycle, the 2000-01 budget would
continue most services at current levels yet boost funding for
schools, public safety and human services by $3.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed budget is 3.8 percent bigger than that of the
current biennium, which ends Aug. 31. At $91 billion, it's
equivalent to the annual spending of some nations _ such as
Australia and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to the current spending cycle, which will end with a
rare surplus, the new Texas proposal would increase spending on
education by $2.5 billion; add $428 million for public safety, and
$465 million for health and human services.
</P>
<P>
   Those big-ticket items are among Bush's spending priorities, but
he also campaigned for re-election with a pledge to push for $2.7
billion in sales and franchise tax reductions. Although Bush has
adjusted his outlook in recent weeks as new revenue projections
were released, he has remained hopeful that some degree of relief
was achievable
</P>
<P>
   But Senate Finance Committee Chairman Bill Ratliff, R-Mt.
Pleasant, renewed his own cautionary stance that there won't be
enough ``discretionary'' money to meet Bush's goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be difficult,'' Ratliff said. He explained that the
estimated $2.5 billion in discretionary money would have to cover
any tax cuts; new initiatives for public schools and universities;
and a proposed enhancement of Child Protective Services, along with
any other ``wish-list'' items that lawmakers present.
</P>
<P>
   House Appropriations Committee Chairman Rob Junell, D-San
Angelo, who filed the plan as House Bill 1 on Wednesday, joined his
Senate counterpart in urging members to carefully weigh the
spending options. He said the House could present its final plan to
the Senate by late March.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not enough money to do everything that every
politician has promised they would do to the extent they
promised,'' Junell said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in addition to the increases for education and public
safety, there could be significantly greater expenditures for debt
service; teacher and other state-employee benefits; and capital
expenses. And many existing programs could get more money based on
increasing population projections and changes in federal mandates.
</P>
<P>
   But, Junell said, ``we didn't take it upon ourself to start new
programs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't make any effort to try to address the spending of
any ... discretionary, new revenue,'' said Ratliff, who emphasized
that the top priority is to improve schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``It properly reflects our priorities ... that 85 percent of the
$3.3 billion (new revenue) has to do with either public or higher
education,'' Ratliff said.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the bigger budget increases:
</P>
<P>
   _ Public schools would gain $1.6 billion to fully fund the
Foundation School Program, which is the state's primary education
fund, buy textbooks, raise the guaranteed yield and fund facilities
obligations.
</P>
<P>
   _ About $428 million for health and human services would cover
increased state Medicaid costs; help needy nursing-home clients and
compensate for rising caseloads in foster care and adoptions.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Teacher Retirement System would see $296 million to
address rising retirement costs and health insurance premiums. An
additional $76 million was set aside for a 2001 projected deficit
for the TRS-Care system of health care for retired teachers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Higher education would collect $233 million to accommodate
enrollment growth in junior colleges and health-related
institutions, and to help with debt service and insurance costs.
</P>
<P>
   _ The mammoth criminal justice system would get a $229 million
increase to improve supervision of adults and juveniles. About $148
million of the sum would be targeted to accommodate prison
population growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is simply to maintain current levels of programs,''
Ratliff said. ``If you add those up, that's virtually $3 billion of
the $3.3 billion (new revenue,) which is 90 percent of the
increase,'' Ratliff said.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco proceeds, part of a $17-billion settlement pact
reached last year, were earmarked months ago for various state
institutions, health and anti-smoking programs, but they must be
formally appropriated by lawmakers before distribution.
</P>
<P>
   If left unchanged by the Legislature, the distribution would
include $400 million for higher education; $200 million for a
smoking reduction pilot program; $100 million for the University of
Texas M.D. Anderson Cancer Center Endowment; and $25 million each
for the UT Medical Branch at Galveston Endowment and the UT Health
Science Center at Houston Endowment.
</P>
<P>
   Interest income from the various endowments would be available
to operate programs, but Ratliff and Junell said the endowments
should be off-limits to lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Legislature, in its wisdom, should choose to spend that
tobacco money as opposed to putting it into endowments and
permanent funds for the future, then I suppose you could lump it in
as discretionary (money). We are going to strongly encourage the
Legislature not to do that,'' Ratliff said.
</P>
<P>
   He explained that it would be hard, in two years, to wean
agencies off higher funding levels if they got a huge infusion of
tobacco money.
</P>
<P>
   Junell cautioned that because the settlements recouped Medicaid
costs, about 40 percent of it might have to be returned to the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
