<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0347 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1932 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CELTICS-BUYBACK-BOS &LR;      01-13 0505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELTICS-BUYBACK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELTICS OWNER OFFERS TO BUY BACK STOCK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boston Celtics owner Paul Gaston offered to increase his stake
in the team's ownership Wednesday, driving stock in the limited
partnership to a 52-week high of 17 1/2, before it settled back to
close at 16 1/2, up 2 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   Gaston's closely held Castle Creek Partners LP is offering to
buy up as many as 430,000 shares of the publicly held Boston
Celtics LP in a cash tender offer set to expire March 1. The offer
for the units, about 16 percent of those outstanding, is $17 per
unit.
</P>
<P>
   The offer spurred a high level of trading in the team's shares,
with 60,400 units traded. The three-month daily average has been
16,400.
</P>
<P>
   Castle Creek, which is privately owned and controlled almost
entirely by Gaston and his family, currently owns 120,000 shares of
the publicly traded portion of the Celtics ownership. If the tender
offer is realized in full, Castle Creek would own 24 percent of the
publicly traded stock.
</P>
<P>
   Castle Creek owns about 52 percent of the Boston Celtics, with
the publicly traded shares of the Boston Celtics LP controls about
48 percent of the NBA franchise _ the only publicly traded
ownership in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Gaston's move signals his expectation that the stock will
increase in value, despite the National Basketball Association's
recent labor strife and the retirement Wednesday of the league's
star attraction, Michael Jordan, team officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``First and foremost, the Gaston family believes in this entity,
and consolidating their ownership of the entity is always important
to them,'' said Richard Pond, executive vice president, chief
operating officer and chief financial officer of the Boston Celtics
LP.
</P>
<P>
   Pond said the team also is interested in cutting the high cost
of serving some 80,000 unit holders. Because many people have
bought shares as souvenirs more than investments, most investors
hold less than 100 shares. The administrative costs related to
serving them is high, Pond said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The assumption is that by consolidating about 20 percent of
the stock, we'll reduce the number of shareholders,'' Pond said.
</P>
<P>
   The tender offer has nothing to do with either the six-month
lockout of NBA players, the most disruptive labor dispute in the
history of the league that was finally settled last week, Pond
asserted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that this was planned before that was done,''
he said. ``If we made this decision before it was done, it would
have looked like we were doing something based on information we
had that the public did not have.''
</P>
<P>
   Stock in the Boston Celtics LP has increased by about 60 percent
since the end of the lockout. It jumped 4 1/8 to 14 5/8 on day the
players and owners struck an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The 52-week low was 7 5/16 on October 14, while the negotiations
were underway for two months and showing little hope of yielding an
agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
