<SLUG> BC-CHINA-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG STOCK MARKET TUMBLES AMID CHINA DEBT JITTERS
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Fears of a debt crisis in China swept through Hong
Kong on Wednesday, punishing the stock market and stirring fresh
anxiety in a city that seemed to be recovering from Asia's economic
distress.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's benchmark Hang Seng index fell 437.79 points, or
more than 4 percent, to 10,273.77. The indexes here of
China-related stocks was hit even harder _ plunging 12 percent as
investors abandoned Hong Kong-listed companies with ties to Beijing
or to China's provincial governments.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first big reversal of Hong Kong's market since stocks
began rallying last September on hopes that the Asian crisis was
abating. ``People are freaking out because China stocks are
basically the only way Hong Kong made money in the last year,''
said Simon Ogus, director of Asian economics at Warburg Dillon Read
here. ``This is a reality shock for Hong Kong, just to show them
how difficult life is going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The fears about China began on Sunday, when the government in
Beijing refused to bail out foreign creditors of its second-largest
investment trust company. China said it would place the debt-ridden
Guangdong International Trust &AMP; Investment Corp., or Gitic, in
bankruptcy, and the foreign creditors would have to take their
places in line to try to recover their loans.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Chinese officials told foreign creditors of another
troubled state company, Guangdong Enterprises Holdings, that it had
debts of $2.9 billion. That figure was larger than expected and
prompted skittish investors to ask whether other China-related
companies had huge, hidden debts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more things that come out about Chinese companies, the
more people want to run,'' said an executive at an international
bank with loans outstanding to Gitic.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese officials have warned that several more investment trust
companies may follow Gitic into insolvency. Some investors fear
that the financial crisis may spread to mainland Chinese companies
that are publicly listed on the Hong Kong market. These ``red
chips'' were once the equivalent of Wednesday's Internet stocks _
soaring to gravity-defying heights before the onset of Asian crisis
in mid-1997.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a report by Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. estimates that the red
chips may have an aggregate debt exceeding $12 billion. Standard &AMP;
Poor's and other agencies have cut their ratings on the debt of
Guangdong Enterprises and other red chips as their balance sheets
have become precarious.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the debt trouble, many analysts reiterated that the
problems at two companies in Guangdong did not foretell a broader
crisis in the Chinese economy or banking system. Nor, they add, did
it mean that foreign banks would suddenly stop lending to Chinese
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may make it tougher for spiffy, coastal Chinese outfits
to get loans,'' Ogus said. ``But as far as Beijing is concerned,
it's not a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   As investors digest the news from China, they are finding that
not all companies are the same in the eyes of Beijing. Gitic and
Guangdong Enterprises are both ultimately owned by the Guangdong
province government and have the same purpose: to raise capital for
the authorities there.
</P>
<P>
   Yet while Beijing peremptorily shut down and liquidated Gitic
and infuriated the company's creditors, it has gone to pains to
assure creditors of Guangdong Enterprises that it will keep the
company afloat by injecting cash and assets. The government also
retained Goldman, Sachs to devise a plan to clean up the company's
finances, install new managers and sharpen its focus.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the different approaches might have to do with the
different authorities involved: As a financial company, Gitic is
regulated by China's central bank. As a diversified conglomerate,
Guangdong Enterprises is controlled by officials in the provincial
capital, Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
   But the difference may also have to do with jurisdiction:
Guangdong Enterprises is listed in Hong Kong, where creditors have
rights, while Gitic is based in Guangzhou, where bankruptcy law is
untested and where foreign banks have made loans based on winks and
nods from Chinese officials.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Guangdong Enterprises owns some valuable assets, while
Gitic is a more speculative venture. Chinese Prime Minister Zhu
Rongji plans to phase out investment trusts as part of an overhaul
of the nation's financial system.
</P>
<P>
   ``In large part, this is a public relations matter on the part
of the Chinese government,'' said T.K. Chang, a partner in the Hong
Kong office of the law firm Coudert Brothers, which is representing
South Korean creditors of Gitic.
</P>
<P>
   Chang is among many lawyers here who are taking refresher
courses on Chinese bankruptcy law to monitor the Gitic proceeding.
He said he expected the process to last about six months. But he
expressed worries that if the bankruptcy court liquidated Gitic's
assets, particularly its real estate, too quickly, it might end up
holding a fire sale that would shrink the return for creditors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bankruptcy will give quite an indication of how China
plans to handle these issues in the future,'' Chang said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
