<SLUG> BC-MA-TOBACCO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE MOVES TO PROTECT CHILDREN FROM TOBACCO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS AND HILARY SARGENT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In what anti-smoking leaders say is a groundbreaking
move that will serve as a national model, Attorney General Scott
Harshbarger Wednesday issued a set of tough marketing and
advertising regulations aimed at curbing the tobacco industry's
targeting of children.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger said his new rules, which are slated to take effect
August 1, will stop much of the industry's use of advertising and
sale strategies that are aimed at hooking young smokers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to end the deceptive tactics used to market, sell and
distribute tobacco products to our children, and do whatever we
reasonably can do to stop illegal access to tobacco by minors,''
Harshbarger said.
</P>
<P>
   But the 11 regulations that the attorney general issued under
the state's consumer protection statute must withstand a likely
legal challenge from the tobacco industry before they can take
effect. Harshbarger's move -- any outcome from a court challenge --
will provide a litmus test nationally as to whether consumer
protection statutes can be used in the battle against smoking.
</P>
<P>
   An industry spokesman, Scott Williams, Wednesday sharply
criticized Harshbarger, accusing him of ``grandstanding.'' He said
the recent national settlement that the attorney general signed
already placed restrictions for deceptive marketing to teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harshbarger has tried to make a career of beating up on the
tobacco industry... and this is more public posturing by a
politician who prefers rhetoric over results,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said the industry would study the regulations before
making a decision whether to challenge them with a court case.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Harshbarger's move, which began almost a year ago when he
announced he would hold a series of hearings on his proposed
regulations, has once again put him on the cutting edge of tobacco
control issues.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-smoking leaders Wednesday said his use of the state's
consumer protection statute that allows him to promulgate such
regulations will pave the way for other attorneys general to follow
his lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very comprehensive,'' said Edward L. Sweda, Jr.,
senior attorney with the Tobacco Control Resource Center at
Northeastern University School of Law. ``Other attorneys general
across the country can look at these as a model.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released by his office, Harshbarger, who is
leaving office next week after a failed bid for governor last fall,
said the rules will deal a major blow to what he said is the
industry's attempt to addict young people to nicotine and thus
assure a future market.
</P>
<P>
   ``These landmark rules will be one more step toward denying Big
Tobacco new customers in Massachusetts,'' said Harshbarger. ``When
the 1999 school year starts, our children will no longer be
bombarded with highly visible enticements that are designed to make
tobacco products seem attractive and cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the regulations will regulate sales and ban tobacco
billboards and store ads at retail outlets near schools. They will
ban outward-facing tobacco ads in retail establishments within
1,000 feet of the state's elementary and middle schools, parks and
playgrounds. Stores selling tobacco products within this 1,000 foot
parameter will be restricted to displaying one black and white
sign, no larger than 576 square inches that states ``Tobacco
products sold here.''
</P>
<P>
   Other restrictions include requiring warning labels on cigars
packs; locks on cigarette vending machines; bans on the
distribution of unpackaged or repackaged cigarettes; prohibit
advertising tobacco products in enclosed stadiums; and outlaw
mail-order distribution of tobacco products without age
verification.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
