<HEADER>
A1936 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARRON-CARNEGIE-HALL-$     01-13 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARRON-CARNEGIE-HALL-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VISIONARY'S DREAM FULFILLED, NOW AS MEMORIAL  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 17)
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Give a determined evolution a little time, and it can look like
a revolution. ``She completely transformed the institution,'' the
once revolutionary composer and conductor Pierre Boulez said last
week of Judith Arron, who was no one's idea of a revolutionary, and
her achievement at Carnegie Hall.
</P>
<P>
   True, change was already in the wind when Ms. Arron arrived as
general manager and artistic director in 1986. Her first major task
was to oversee the renovation of the hall and related construction,
which had been initiated long before.
</P>
<P>
   But she became executive director in 1988 and played a more
central role in planning for the hall's extensive centenary
celebration in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Now a dream of her own has come to fruition with the recent
announcement of plans for a small but versatile third performance
stage in the historic Carnegie building, replacing a movie theater
under the main auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Arron died last month, at 56, after a long battle with
cancer, and the announcement brought added news: although the new
hall will be named for Arthur and Judy Zankel, its prime donors,
the performance space itself will be called the Judith Arron
Auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Carnegie Hall will present a memorial service for
Ms. Arron on Tuesday afternoon. Although fiercely partisan on
behalf of Carnegie and a tough competitor in booking artists, she
was widely loved in the world of music for her personal warmth as
well as her thorough professionalism, and those expected to speak
in tribute to her include the violinist Isaac Stern, who is the
president of Carnegie Hall, and Sanford I. Weill, the chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Arron also conceived a wide-ranging series of events related
to the millennium, some of them just announced. But whatever
transformation she worked at the hall may best be symbolized not so
much by the big public events surrounding renovation, construction
or landmark celebrations as by her novel artistic ventures,
especially a series of professional training workshops, operating
largely out of public view.
</P>
<P>
   The prototype was the Robert Shaw Choral Workshop, developed in
1990 by a conductor with vast experience in training choral singers
and conductors. The current edition of that annual series _ alas,
without Shaw, who is ailing _ culminates in a concert Sunday
afternoon, with works of Verdi, Szymanowski and Poulenc conducted
by Charles Dutoit.
</P>
<P>
   Other workshops have been developed by Stern (chamber music),
Boulez (contemporary music and orchestral conducting), Georg Solti
(orchestral performance), Marilyn Horne (vocal performance),
Luciano Berio (composition), Jorma Panula (orchestral conducting),
Alfred Brendel (piano performance of Beethoven) and, for next
season, Daniel Barenboim (orchestral conducting and piano
performance).
</P>
<P>
   If Ms. Arron had done nothing more than enlist some of the
world's finest musicians and let them work their will, she might
have done well enough. But to hear Boulez tell it, she did much
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had real artistic vision,'' he said. ``She had the ideas.
Instead of saying, `What can you do for us?,' she said, `Here's
what I have in mind,' and I appreciated that very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Arron elaborated on the workshop idea in a series of
``Perspectives,'' broader collaborations with artists, beginning
this season with the conductor Dennis Russell Davies and Brendel,
and continuing next season with Barenboim, Boulez and the pianist
Maurizio Pollini. She set up a composer's chair, which Ellen Taaffe
Zwilich, the current occupant, cedes next season to Boulez. Ms.
Arron expanded the hall's educational activities and, in 1992,
installed the Carnegie Hall Jazz Band.
</P>
<P>
   Together, these multifarious initiatives represented a shift in
the balance from merely renting out the hall toward carving out a
genuinely creative role in the presentation and packaging of
concerts and related events. That shift was even more pronounced in
the smaller Weill Recital Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Some such activities had taken place before, of course, and Ms.
Arron's best efforts did not entirely eliminate humdrum events even
from Carnegie's own presentations. Yet her programming showed a
fresh imagination and a serious effort to create meaningful themes
and connections.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had an idea behind it, a continuing idea that Carnegie Hall
had never had before,'' Stern said.
</P>
<P>
   Those who hired her may, in fact, have got more than they
bargained for. Before going to Carnegie Hall in 1986, Ms. Arron was
the manager of the Cincinnati Symphony and Cincinnati May Festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``She learned faster than anyone could have believed,'' Stern
said. ``She came to the big city from a small town and learned
incessantly on the job. She developed a personal connection with
the world's artists and with the big backers in this city, and she
established an atmosphere of collegiality that I, as a professional
traveler, have never seen in any other hall.''
</P>
<P>
   What especially struck one critic, whose dealings with Ms. Arron
were limited, was her unfailing grace in the face of adversity.
Only those who were close to her had any idea what she was going
through physically or personally.
</P>
<P>
   Professionally, she faced an interesting little test in 1995,
when a layer of concrete was found under the renovated stage floor
despite Carnegie's heated denials over a decade that any such thing
existed. Ms. Arron handled the matter deftly, overseeing removal of
the concrete in the summer and, in the fall, immediately inviting
representatives of the music press to her office to reveal and
explain the incident candidly.
</P>
<P>
   For this writer, Ms. Arron defined the word ``aplomb.'' And
that, to judge from many who knew her better, may have been the
least of it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
