<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-HIGHSCHOOL-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHAEL JORDAN, LANEY ALUM, SURPRISES HIS HIGH SCHOOL COACHES
AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BKN-JORDAN-RDP, BKN-JORDAN-RHODEN-COLUMN,
BKN-JORDAN-PLAYERS, BKN-JORDAN-KNICKS) 
(DW) 
 By BRIAN HENDRICKSON NYT Regional Newspapers c.1999 N.Y. Times News
Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, N.C. _ Pender High School coach Ron Coley often got
a funny feeling while watching Michael Jordan play with the Chicago
Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   When he looked at the man who was, many believe, the best
basketball player of all time, he would still see the wiry kid he
coached as an assistant coach at Laney High School.
</P>
<P>
   It's strange, Coley said to have such close contact with
immortality. But in many ways, Coley still saw in Jordan that kid
he knew at Laney.
</P>
<P>
   A kid with an unparalleled work ethic who wanted to get better -
and did. A kid who loved basketball.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to think he's walking away from the game and retiring
for good this time, Coley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our loss, the fans,'' he said. ``I'm really surprised
because Michael really loved to play. I'm surprised he'd do it
because of that love.''
</P>
<P>
   Coley could see Jordan budding into a star even in his high
school days. Jordan set the school record for points scored in one
game with 44, and he led the team to a 19-4 record his senior year.
</P>
<P>
   His high school career ended on a sour note. Jordan fouled out
trying to help Laney defeat New Hanover in his last high school
game, which they lost 56-52. But Jordan's career soon surpassed
anything Coley could have ever dreamed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd thought he'd be an excellent NBA guard, but not an icon,''
Coley said.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan keeps in touch with his old coaches, Coley said. He wrote
a letter of recommendation for Coley when he was being considered
for the Pender job four years ago. ``He joked about Pender being
the enemy,'' Coley said.
</P>
<P>
   When Coley got the job, Jordan donated shoes to the team, and
has every year since.
</P>
<P>
   Laney head coach Fred Lynch, an assistant at Laney, gets shoes
and sweats for the basketball team every year, a deal the school
has benefited from since Jordan signed an endorsement contract with
Nike in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The gym at Laney now bears Jordan's name.
</P>
<P>
   Like Coley, Lynch keeps in touch with Jordan from time to time.
He said Jordan's achievements have given the school a constant
source of pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the people at the school, they're proud to have a person
like him to be associated with the school,'' Lynch said.
</P>
<P>
   Coley says we haven't seen the last of Michael Jordan on the
basketball court. Basketball will never cease to be part of
Jordan's life, Coley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be at Chapel Hill playing pickup because he loves the
game,'' Coley said.
</P>
<P>
   (Brian Hendrickson is a staff writer for the Morning Star in
Wilmington, N.C. This story was distributed by The N.Y. Times News
Service.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
