A1946 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILSON-MUSIC-REVIEW-A     01-13 0461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILSON-MUSIC-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CABARET REVIEW :  REINVENTING THE SPELL OF A MASTER
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By BEN RATLIFF     
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The slightly distant self-consciousness that can
envelop Cassandra Wilson in a concert hall was gone when she
performed at the Blue Note on Tuesday, her first nightclub
appearance in New York in four years. Instead, Ms. Wilson was
almost giddy, and in a confident cabaret-style performance with a
six-piece band, she nailed every step.
</P>
<P>
   It was an encouraging return: 13 months ago she presented a run
of concerts at Alice Tully Hall that dabbled with the idea of Miles
Davis as performer, composer and embodiment of a dark, elemental
tenderness. It was ambitious but chaotic, and she didn't quite make
her case.
</P>
<P>
   Since then she has finished a Miles Davis-themed record to be
released in March, done some touring, and tightened the concept for
each song in her repertory to the point where they're stylized and
shining. She included some of her older songs in the set, but the
Miles Davis songs easily stood out; they've come a great distance.
</P>
<P>
   She and her musical director, the bassist Lonnie Plaxico, don't
set out to replicate works from Davis' canon at all; there aren't
even any horns in the band. They take only the principal melody
within a piece of Davis' music, and create the rest on their own.
They're looking to suggest the spell he could cast with his
inward-gazing economy of notes. The group plays textural music,
with two guitars strumming flamenco chords and picking out ambient
effects that shimmer in pockets of silence. The show is inscribed
with all kinds of jazz connotations, but in the end it's elegant,
dreamy pop.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Never Broken,'' she sang the seesawing line of ``ESP,''
written by Wayne Shorter for the mid-'60s Davis band, stretching it
out over a slinky vamp. Davis' ``Seven Steps to Heaven,'' for which
Ms. Wilson has written lyrics, began with the rhythm played in
snare-drum rolls. After a few choruses the drummer Marcus Baylor
switched to swinging on the ride cymbal while Ms. Wilson plunged
into scat singing, delivering long, smoky tones.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wilson practiced some Betty Carter-style on-the-spot band
control: she dragged out a vowel sound and looked at her pianist,
Jason Moran, who knew to extend the trill he was playing until she
let go of the word. In one of the evening's few solos Moran gave
the music a thrilling edge, staying deep in the rhythm and punching
dark chords in thorny bursts. Shortly thereafter Ms. Wilson cut off
the song, quickening the senses of those who had been lulled by its
groove.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
