<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1947 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      01-13 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHERIFF JOE WINS, EVEN WHEN HE LOSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Sheriff Joe Arpaio is cheerful. He's relaxed. I'm
asking him about an $8.25 million settlement that Maricopa County
will pay the family of a man killed in his jail, and yet Joe's
happy. As he should be.
</P>
<P>
   He won.
</P>
<P>
   On May 31, 1996, police hauled 33-year-old Scott Norberg into
the Madison Street Jail. Within a few hours, Norberg suffered a
horrifying death at the hands of Joe's guards.
</P>
<P>
   All his family gets for this is money.
</P>
<P>
   No apology. No admission of guilt.
</P>
<P>
   The people responsible for Norberg's death haven't lost their
jobs and neither has their boss.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement, which was announced last week, will be paid by
insurance companies. Nowhere in it does the sheriff's department
accept blame for what happened to Norberg.
</P>
<P>
   For the cuts and bruises on his body. For the 21 pairs of
stun-gun burns. For the final, frantic moments of a man strapped to
a chair, his mouth and neck wrapped in a towel, gasping for air.
</P>
<P>
   After the settlement was worked out, Arpaio issued a statement
that read in part, ``I am relieved that this tentative agreement
contains no admissions of fault or liability on behalf of our
officers. . . Nor does the agreement require any changes in jail
policy.''
</P>
<P>
   He should be pleased.
</P>
<P>
   He gets to give away someone else's money and keep his own
reputation.
</P>
<P>
   When first asked about the Norberg deal, Arpaio says he can't
comment because it hasn't been finalized. Then he talks anyway.
</P>
<P>
   He always does.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (Norberg's family) said it was never about money. So why
do they agree to settle?'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Then, softening his tone and his language, he adds, ``I don't
want to make derogatory statments against the family. I feel for
them, in a way. But, I know my officers tried to do the right
thing. I can't try this case in the media, but I still have to
protect my organization. As you know, throughout this whole ordeal,
I did support my officers. And I will, unless somebody comes up
with new information. And there isn't any.''
</P>
<P>
   Arpaio is asked if he would have accepted a deal in which the
Norbergs received no money, but his office admitted wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never. Never,'' he says. ``I would want to go to a jury. I
would want to go to a court of law where we could bring out the
true facts, not the hype in the media that you've been hearing.
That would be the opportunity to put our case before a judge and
jury and let them decide. So, no, I would never have agreed to
that.''
</P>
<P>
   He can say that, now.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't have to discuss the fact that Norberg hadn't been
convicted of any crime. He doesn't have to prove Norberg was as
confrontational as his officers claim. He doesn't have to explain
missing evidence.
</P>
<P>
   A trial would have forced his office to do all those things.
</P>
<P>
   But Norberg's father says his family couldn't bear the stress of
pursuing the lawsuit anymore. Scott Norberg has two sons. Their
family didn't want them to endure a trial. They knew would have
been ugly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of things we know about their son that would
have come out in that trial,'' Arpaio says. `` But I still feel
sorry for the mother and father.''
</P>
<P>
   There is an ongoing criminal investigation into Norberg's death.
Some officers may yet be charged. As for the big cash settlement,
though, the sheriff says, ``I have no control over this money. The
insurance company made that decision.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he believes paying a settlement is not the same as
admitting guilt. And he's right.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things happen,'' he says. ``It's unfortunate. But it's
amazing what my officers have done with the lack of personnel and
the overcrowding. I'd have to say we have the best jail system in
the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how it is if the deal stands.
</P>
<P>
   The Norbergs make $8.25 million. Arpaio makes a killing. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 1930EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
