<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOUR-DEAD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS MAN KILLS 3, SELF IN CHILD SUPPORT CASE, POLICE SAY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional ending) 
 
By JIM HENDERSON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHARDSON, Texas _ A man who owed $38,000 in overdue child
support shot and killed his ex-wife, her mother and a family friend
early Wednesday, then took his own life.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-year-old son of the ex-wife was in the house at the time
but escaped through an upstairs window when the shooting began.
</P>
<P>
   Police identified the victims as Janette Jeffers, 41; her
mother, Margaret Compton, 67, of Midland; and her friend, Mary
Roland, 63, also of Midland.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect was identified as Allen Dale Price, 48, of Gorman,
which is about 140 miles west of this Dallas-area city of 87,000
people. He and Jeffers had been divorced for about 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Michael Hauver said Compton and Roland had been visiting
Jeffers and were preparing to return to Midland when Price arrived
at the house shortly before 6 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were carrying stuff out to their car when he approached
them and started shooting,'' Hauver said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the women was shot in the driveway of the two-story brick
house and the other was found lying in the garage.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffers apparently was inside and called 911 after hearing the
gunshots. She was on the phone with the dispatcher when she was
shot. On a police tape of the call, a woman can be heard screaming,
followed by a shotgun blast. Price then turned the shotgun on
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs, Jeffers' son heard the shots and his mother's screams
and climbed through a window onto a second-story balcony and leaped
to the ground, police said. He was standing in the front yard when
officers arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Price and one of the women died at the scene. Two of the women
were taken to hospitals, where they died a short time later.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of the quiet cul-de-sac where the Jefferses live were
jolted by the early morning gunfire. Ben Harvey said he heard two
gunshots that sounded like they came from outside the house. ``Then
the house alarm went off and then several other gunshots after
that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffers' husband was in California on business, police said, and
her college-age daughter, who is also Price's daughter, was not at
home.
</P>
<P>
   The Jefferses moved to the Dallas suburb from Midland about a
year ago, police said. Hauver said the motive was believed to be an
October order from a Midland judge that required Price to pay
$38,030 in back child support and interest for the couple's
daughter, Jennifer, who attends the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Price was ordered to pay $500 per month starting last November
to clear the debt, but did not do so. He originally was supposed to
have paid $250 per month starting in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Hauver said the 12-year-old told of Price causing ``a history of
some problems like theft of mail and tire-slashing,'' but nothing
recently. The officer added that the boy was a poor source because
his parents tried to shield him from the problems.
</P>
<P>
   Price was stopped by Richardson police Jan. 3 after he ran a red
light. He was driving a rented car and had a 12-gauge pump shotgun
in the back seat. Sgt. Steve Upchurch said a check with the rental
company revealed that the car was overdue and officers were asked
to impound it.
</P>
<P>
   The car had been rented in November, police said, but because of
a paperwork mix-up, the rental company could not confirm that it
had been stolen, so Price was released.
</P>
<P>
   Possession of the shotgun is not illegal, but because Price had
no transportation, it also was impounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't have a guy just walking around the streets with a
shotgun,'' Upchurch said.
</P>
<P>
   Price came to the police station two days later and retrieved
the weapon. It was the same gun used in Wednesday's shooting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Police also believe Price was at the Jeffers home early Tuesday
morning. Jeffers had just left for work when a man entered the
house through the garage.
</P>
<P>
   The man was confronted by Mary Roland, who screamed and ordered
him to leave. She and Compton called police, but the man was gone
when they arrived. Roland could not identify the man.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had never met Allen Price, so she would not have known if
it was him,'' Hauver said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
