<HEADER>
A1963 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-PERU-FUJIMORI-ART-1     01-13 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-PERU-FUJIMORI-ART-1115(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH POLLS AND ECONOMY AGAINST HIM, FUJIMORI PONDERS A THIRD TERM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Resending to add photo note. No other changes.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to photo clients. Locator map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORPACANCHA, Peru _ Claudencia Martin Gustavo cheered when
President Alberto K. Fujimori, defying the thin mountain air in
this remote village 12,000 feet above sea level, took two women
into his arms and twirled them in a vigorous Indian folk dance.
</P>
<P>
   He cheered as the president passed out pink blouses and beige
pants to local llama and alpaca herders. And he cheered again when
the Peruvian leader, already in campaign mode, donned a rather
unpresidential poncho, and talked about bringing telephones and
electricity to this settlement of 1,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   But Gustavo said he doubted he would vote a third time for
Fujimori next year because ``we don't have enough food and our
incomes are not enough for our families.''
</P>
<P>
   A deepening recession caused by stormy weather and the Asian
economic crisis has swung Peru's political mood against the
president who has dominated this country for nearly a decade. Once
widely popular for rescuing Peru from the abyss of terrorism,
cocaine trafficking and hyperinflation, Fujimori is struggling to
recapture his old magic that has brought him two election
victories. Whether he can regain it will determine if he will run
again next year.
</P>
<P>
   The son of Japanese immigrants, Fujimori bolted out of nowhere
as an independent populist to win the presidency in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   But he governed as a tough-minded, free-market conservative.
Faced with a spreading wave of terrorism, he unleashed the military
and intelligence services and quickly captured the most important
rebel leaders. He even ordered the air force to shoot down planes
loaded with Peruvian coca paste destined for Colombia leading to a
rapid decline in trafficking and coca cultivation.
</P>
<P>
   His ``Fuji-shock,'' treatment yielded a wave of privatizations
of inefficient state enterprises and attracted foreign capital.
</P>
<P>
   And with crucial military support, he replaced the Congress and
Supreme Court in 1992, with like-minded officials. His actions drew
heavy criticism from the United States and human rights activists,
but the terrorists lost ground and Fujimori won re-election
overwhelmingly in 1995 over former United Nations Secretary-General
Javier Perez de Cuellar.
</P>
<P>
   But now the 60-year-old president's support in the polls, which
has risen and fallen in the past, has dwindled to about 35 percent,
and has hardly budged over the last four months.
</P>
<P>
   His popularity has declined even after he successfully
negotiated a peace treaty with Ecuador late last year, forcing him
to replace his prime minister and shuffle his Cabinet last week. A
frightening crime wave in Lima early last year abated after
Fujimori ordered Peru's intelligence services to infiltrate street
gangs and arrest their leaders, but even that has not helped his
standing.
</P>
<P>
   While he has not signaled his political intentions, his
supporters say he is privately gearing up to run again. But some
analysts say that if his polls do not improve in the next six to
eight months, Fujimori may decide to forego the election.
</P>
<P>
   His standing has deteriorated mainly owing to a recession that
resulted first from El Nino, which caused major flood damage and
pushed important varieties of fish from Peru's shoreline, causing
hardship for the country's substantial fishmeal industry.
</P>
<P>
   A decline in commodities prices brought on by the Asian crisis,
especially for Peru's copper and tin, has reduced economic growth.
Indeed, the once white-hot Peruvian economy that registered
double-digit growth rates in the early 1990's stalled to zero
growth in the last quarter. The unemployment and underemployment
rate has risen in recent months from 40 percent to 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people are hungry, unemployed and tired of Fujimori,''
said Javier Valle Riestra, who served as prime minister for two
months last year. ``He can only make it to re-election by fraud and
blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori has been buffeted by widespread criticism that he
manipulated the courts and electoral tribunals to sidestep a
constitutional ban on a third term. Fujimori's claims that his 1992
``self-coup'' improved the justice system has been tarnished in
recent months by scandals, including two judges recently filmed
taking bribes from drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   And a new book about Vladimiro Montesinos, Fujimori's unofficial
chief of intelligence, describes the president as a virtual
prisoner of a sinister, power-hungry spy. The book has become an
instant best-seller sold at newsstands around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori cannot be counted out, however. The Ministry of the
Presidency controls 40 percent of the national budget, and it is
already turning on a pork-barrel spigot for bridges and roads. And
the opposition remains splintered. The strongest possible
opposition candidate, Alberto Andrade, was recently re-elected
mayor of Lima, but his organization is weak in the provinces.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, opinion polls and political analysts suggest that
the brief surge Fujimori received in 1997 by the rescue operation
of 71 hostages held by terrorists in the Japanese ambassador's
residence has faded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say re-election is possible, but very difficult,''
said Alfredo Torres, a leading Lima poll taker. ``The question is
whether the recuperation of the Peruvian and world economy will
come fast enough.''
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, Fujimori predicted that his new Cabinet
would help his government recover much of its luster. He said he
would be able to crank up economic growth by better the 5 percent
this year _ far higher than the consensus 2 percent of independent
economists _ unless neighboring Brazil suffers a complete economic
meltdown. Things will be better, he said, if for no other reason
than there will be not be an El Nino this year.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori made many promises, as he doodled on a piece of paper
in a wood-paneled office in the government palace. He pledged to
further reduce Peru's coca-growing area _ already cut by more than
half in three years thanks partly to eradication _ by an additional
20 to 30 percent this year. He predicted that the new treaty with
Ecuador would lead to yearly savings of $400 million in military
spending. And he promised to hunt down the handful of rebels left
in the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before there was terrorism, now there is stability,'' Fujimori
said, as if practicing a campaign speech. ``Before we had economic
chaos, now we have order. Before we were isolated internationally,
now we have friends again. Before we had conflict with Ecuador, now
we live in peace.''
</P>
<P>
   He refused to rule out a re-election bid, adding, ``I don't have
to decide yet.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   But for the last two years, Fujimori and his allies who form a
majority in Congress have been acting as if the Peruvian leader
intends to run in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The 1993 Peruvian Constitution prohibits the president from
running for a third consecutive term. But in August 1996,
Fujimori's supporters in Congress passed a law that granted him an
exception, arguing that his first term did not count since it began
before the new constitution was written.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the opposition appealed to the seven-member
Constitutional Tribunal, saying the exemption was unconstitutional.
Three of the judges agreed, three abstained, and the head
constitutional judge upheld the 3-0 decision against Fujimori. In
May 1997, Congress dismissed the three judges who opposed their law
on the ground that they had exceeded their authority, opening the
way for a third Fujimori campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition mounted a signature drive to petition Congress to
hold a national referendum on the issue of a third term.
</P>
<P>
   By July 1998, it had collected enough signatures to hold a
referendum. But the Congress ruled that two-thirds of its members
would have to clear the way for any referendum, and Fujimori's
majority blocked it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do not trust civilian, democratic institutions,'' said
Lourdes Flores Nano, an opposition congresswoman. ``The polls say
he can't win, but if the group at the head of the army insists on
Fujimori the possibility of fraud is very high.''
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori denied that he had manipulated the system and said
Congress was doing its democratic duty. ``I think we have a very
open, democratic system, even with its imperfections,'' he said.
``Before Peru had a democracy, but one that didn't function in the
face of terrorism and narcoterrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   He underscored how much Peru has changed on his trip to
Corpacancha. He would not have dared come to this Andean village 85
miles northeast of Lima without an army battalion when he first
took office in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, young Shining Path terrorists played soccer with
the skulls of their victims in these Andean highlands. As part of
their effort to terrorize the peasantry into submission, they
rounded up local leaders in village squares and then ordered their
relatives to stone them to death at gunpoint. The army was in
retreat until the security forces arrested the top terrorist
leaders in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   But this Sunday, Fujimori dropped by this settlement in a
helicopter with only a light escort of bodyguards to enjoy a
mountainside picnic, pass out gifts and dole out promises of new
roads, tourism projects and credits to expand their llama, alpaca
and sheep production.
</P>
<P>
   As the peasants swelled around him, tussling him as they
received their gifts, he cried out: ``Order! Order! This country
needs order, no?''
</P>
<P>
   The peasants dutifully obeyed, like recruits following a drill
sergeant, as the chaos gave way to three neat lines.
</P>
<P>
   In appreciation for the presidential gifts, the peasants gave
Fujimori a sheep with the Peruvian flag tied around its neck and a
hunk of barbecued alpaca to go with the French wine and Polish
vodka he brought along on the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Fujimori assembled the reporters traveling with him, and
via satellite telephone, gave a nationally broadcast news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``This government gets results,'' Fujimori told his people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
