<HEADER>
A1972 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-LEGAL-ART-2TA     01-13 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LEGAL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TRIAL BRIEFS: SAME EVENTS, DIFFERENT EXPLANATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-CLINTON, IMPEACH-HOUSE,
IMPEACH-SCENE.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(fe) 
 By JILL ABRAMSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In their trial briefs, the president's defense team
and the House prosecutors present their Senate jury with a legal
version of ``Rashomon,'' in which the main characters recall the
same events differently.
</P>
<P>
   The House managers, who submitted their brief on Monday, weave
an elaborate narrative in which the president is a corrupt
protagonist, orchestrating a scheme to hide evidence of an illicit
relationship from the lawyers for Paula Jones. In their version of
Clinton's actions, the president is a conspirator who influences
Monica Lewinsky to falsely deny their affair in a sworn affidavit.
He then uses his loyal secretary to conceal gifts he and Ms.
Lewinsky exchanged and to cover up their relationship, and he
attempts to find the former intern a job to insure her silence in
the Jones case. Finally, he lies about it all before a federal
grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``When viewed as a unified whole,'' the brief of the House
managers concludes, the evidence ``overwhlemingly supports'' two
articles of impeachment against President Clinton for perjury and
obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   The 130-page trial memorandum submitted on Wednesday by the
president's lawyers paints an altogether different picture of the
same events. The defense brief portrays a president beset by his
enemies, threatened by a politically motivated civil lawsuit and an
independent counsel bent on finding wrongdoing by the president
after years of fruitlessly investigating the Whitewater real estate
deal in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Far from committing perjury or obstructing justice, the
president's lawyers argue, he was simply attempting to conceal an
illicit affair and hide his own embarrassing behavior from his
family and closest aides. When he appeared before a federal grand
jury, however, the president told the truth, the lawyers say,
admitting to an ``inappropriate, intimate'' relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The briefs differ markedly in style as well as substance. What
is most striking about the House brief is its almost novelistic
structure, which lays out a highly detailed story alleging perjury
and obstruction of justice with chronological chapters and
subheadings such as ``Ms. Lewinsky's First Visit'' and ``Need For
The Cover Story.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's brief is filled with legal citations and
arguments that the charges against Clinton do not rise to the level
of impeachable offenses. ``The articles of impeachment that have
been exhibited to the Senate fall far short of what the Founding
Fathers had in mind when they placed in the hands of Congress the
power to impeach and remove a president from office,'' his lawyers
argue. But their brief too has some provocative subchapters,
including a section titled ``The Whitewater Investigative
Dead-End'' that contends the independent counsel's investigation of
Clinton and Ms. Lewinsky was ``wholly unrelated'' to its original
mandate.
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, the two briefs are indicators of two very
different trial strategies. The House managers want a longer trial
with the testimony of witnesses. Proving that the facts square with
the emphatic allegations in their brief, which in places goes
beyond even the impeachment referral of the independent counsel
Kenneth Starr, would almost certainly require the testimony of
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Although the defense brief disputes the facts in the Starr
referral, it trivializes the actual charges against the president,
minimizes the seriousness of the evidence against him and
criticizes the very structure of the impeachment articles,
whichunconstitutionally contain multiple offenses, the brief
contends. If they were counts in an indictment ``would not survive
a motion to dismiss,'' it contends. The president's lawyers want a
short trial with no witnesses, and they want it decided on the
basis that the case against Clinton is not serious enough to
warrant removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   The House brief, to a far lesser extent than the president's,
does not split the case into two parts, dividing it by the separate
perjury and obstruction charges. The House brief argues that it is
necessary to view the case as a whole and not by pieces.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is essential to avoid considering each event in
isolation,'' the House managers maintain. ``Events and words that
may seem innocent or even exculpatory in a vacuum may well take on
a sinister, or even a criminal, connotation when observed in the
context of the whole plot.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's brief, by contrast, dissects each article, piece
by piece. On perjury, the president's lawyers argue that the House
case rests on ``such insignificant matters as misremembering the
precise months on which certain inappropriate physical contact
started'' and ``understanding as `occasional' his infrequent
inappropriate physical and telephone contacts with Ms. Lewinsky
over a period of many months.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In his grand jury testimony, the president's prepared statement
said his relationship with Ms. Lewinsky spanned 1996 and 1997,
while she said it began in late 1995. She described 11 sexual
encounters with the president and 17 telephone conversations that
involved sexual banter.
</P>
<P>
   Because the president admitted to an ongoing physical
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky in his grand jury statement, the
president's lawyers dismiss discrepancies between his testimony and
Ms. Lewinsky's over the number and dates of their encounters,
saying that ``these squabbles are utterly immaterial.''
</P>
<P>
   As to clashes in their testimony over the nature of their sexual
contact, the president's lawyers repeat their prior insistence that
President Clinton believed oral sex did not fall within the
definition of sexual relations in the Jones case and that other
intimiate touching alleged by Ms. Lewinsky ``comes down to an oath
against an oath.''
</P>
<P>
   This argument of course, could undermine Ms. Lewinsky's
credibility when it comes to the second article of impeachment, for
obstruction of justice. Here the president's brief relies on Ms.
Lewinsky's testimony that no one ever told her to lie and that she
was never promised a job for her silence.
</P>
<P>
   The House managers' brief argues that no one would have ever
stated those aims so boldly to Ms. Lewinsky. The brief also argues
that the president's conversations with Ms. Lewinsky about her
affidavit in the Jones case and efforts to find her a job after she
appeared on the Jones witness list strongly suggest an unlawful
scheme to shape her testimony. The president's lawyers counter that
efforts to help Ms. Lewinsky find employment began long before she
became embroiled in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   The briefs also clash sharply on the proper standards and
precedents for the impeachment of federal officeholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senate's own precedents establish beyond doubt that
perjury warrants conviction and removal,'' the House managers
maintain, pointing out that the 1980's the Senate convicted and
removed three federal judges for committing perjury.
</P>
<P>
   The president's brief cites other precedents, noting, for
instance, a proposed article of impeachment against President Nixon
that was rejected by the House Judiciary Committee involved private
wrongdoing and the filing of a fraudulent tax return. The brief
also reaches back to 1792, when Congress investigated Treasury
Secretary Alexander Hamilton for taking payments from a swindler, a
private matter that was deemed unworthy of removing Hamilton from
office.
</P>
<P>
   The House managers, however, soundly reject the notion that the
president's dealings with Ms. Lewinsky and his testimony about it
are a private matter. ``This case is not about sex or private
conduct,'' their brief states. ``It is about multiple obstructions
of justice, perjury, false and misleading statements, and witness
tampering -- all committed or orchestrated by the president of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, despite the more than 50 pages of detailed narrative in
the House managers brief, the president's lawyers argue that the
charges against him are unfairly vague.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
