<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1974 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATE-LOTTERIES-ART-2     01-13 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATE-LOTTERIES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTTERIES GAIN MOMENTUM IN THE BIBLE BELT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., N.C., S.C., Tenn.)   (ART ADV: Graphic and locator map are being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ Lottery fever hit South Carolina Wednesday, and
it had nothing to do with the size of the Powerball jackpot. The
state's 114th governor, James H. Hodges, used his inauguration
ceremonies to begin lobbying for ambitious educational improvements
that he maintains can only be paid for through a statewide lottery.
</P>
<P>
   He may not have to lobby very hard. Convinced that Hodges'
victory in November served as a referendum on the lottery,
legislative leaders are predicting that lawmakers will approve a
measure this session to allow a public vote on the issue. Many of
those lawmakers remain personally opposed to the lottery, but have
said the election made it clear that South Carolinians want to join
the legal numbers racket.
</P>
<P>
   As legislative sessions open around the country, South Carolina
is one of four Southern states where the Bible Belt's once zealous
opposition to legalized gambling is being overwhelmed by the dire
need to improve public schools. Six of the 13 states that do not
have lotteries are in the South, but political experts predict that
South Carolina, Alabama, North Carolina and Tennessee could all
adopt lotteries in the next few years. Most of those states would
have to amend their constitutions to make the lottery legal,
meaning that legislatures would have to pass measures _ sometimes
by two-thirds majorities _ in order to place a referendum before
voters.
</P>
<P>
   As in South Carolina, resistance to the lottery is crumbling in
Alabama, where Don Siegelman will be sworn in as governor on Monday
after waging a campaign in which he spoke about virtually nothing
else. In his election-night victory speech, Siegelman defied
lottery opponents in the legislature ``to stand in the way of the
will of the people.'' To reinforce that point, he will be sworn in
on Monday by former Gov. Zell Miller of Georgia, who left office
this week with record approval ratings after bringing
lottery-funded college scholarships and pre-kindergarten programs
to his state.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-lottery momentum in South Carolina and Alabama has
spread to the neighboring states of North Carolina and Tennessee,
where political leaders fear the loss of potential tax revenue
across state lines. Ever since Georgia began its lottery in 1993,
leaders in adjacent states have watched helplessly as their
citizens drove across that state's border to spend millions of
dollars on lottery tickets. As long as their citizens are going to
gamble, the politicians figure, the proceeds might as well benefit
their schools. That reasoning has created a domino effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the surrounding states have lotteries or anticipate
getting them, so it seems like the Tennessee voters should have a
chance to vote on it,'' said state Sen. Ward Crutchfield, a
Chattanooga Democrat who serves as majority leader. ``People are
pouring into Kentucky and Georgia to play it and I'm tired of
supporting other states' education systems.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee is one of three states, along with Hawaii and Utah,
that do not have any form of legalized gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Both Hodges and Siegelman are Democrats who used their lottery
proposals to oust Republican incumbents in deeply conservative
states, and their victories sent a clear message to legislators
across the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've seen two incumbent Republican governors in the South
defeated by that issue, so people are scrambling to get on the
right side of it,'' said Q. Whitfield Ayres, a pollster in Atlanta.
``When the people speak, politicians listen and people in
neighboring states spoke loudly and convincingly on the lottery.''
</P>
<P>
   Hodges opposed the lottery while a state legislator, but changed
his views while campaigning for governor, saying he had shifted
after studying the success of Georgia's program. In the last five
years, that lottery has paid for college scholarships for 319,000
students and for pre-kindergarten classes for 246,000 4-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   At Wednesday's inaugural on the Capitol steps, Hodges reinforced
the imagery of his education agenda by asking his 5-year-old son,
Luke, and the other members of Luke's kindergarten class to lead
the Pledge of Allegiance. Each of the children wore inaugural
sweatshirts saying: ``It's All About Our Schools.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything else, all our hopes and dreams for economic
prosperity, preserving our precious natural resources, appreciation
for diversity in the decades to come, everything else depends on a
first-rate program of public education,'' Hodges said. ``That is
why I am asking all South Carolinians today to join me in launching
a children's crusade, a 21st century crusade of textbooks and
computers and parents and teachers, allied against the enemies of
ignorance and indifference.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Because the Hodges administration is committed to
improving education without tax increases, we must adopt a
statewide lottery with all the revenues targeted for specific
educational needs.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As a political device, the lottery has been a silver bullet for
Southern Democrats because it has allowed them to propose
significant spending on education without tax increases that
alienate conservative voters. Their Republican opponents typically
have been forced to oppose the lottery in order to maintain the
backing of Christian conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   But after the elections of Hodges and Siegelman, Republican
lawmakers are relaxing their opposition. ``I'm not an advocate of
the lottery but I realize that the public has spoken,'' said Al B.
Robinson, a Republican state representative from Easley, S.C., who
has voted against a lottery referendum in the past but said he will
vote for one this year.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker of the Republican-controlled House, David H.
Wilkins, said in an interview that he opposes the lottery but
believes it will win the two-thirds majority needed to be placed on
the ballot as a referendum in 2000. ``I think it's going to be
close but my sense is it will probably pass,'' he said. An analysis
in Wednesday's editions of The State, Columbia's newspaper,
projected that 87 House members would support a lottery referendum,
four more than are needed for passage.
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina, the lottery's odds have improved because
Democrats won back control of the state House of Representatives in
November. Previous speakers from both parties have blocked lottery
bills in the House, but the likely new Speaker, Jim Black of
Charlotte, has said he would allow a vote on the lottery even
though he opposes it. Gov. James B. Hunt Jr. also has personal
reservations, but supports letting the voters decide.
</P>
<P>
   Polls in each of the states have found that large majorities
support the lottery. A poll taken last July for The Charlotte
Observer found that 68 percent of North Carolinians and 73 percent
of South Carolinians favored a lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Lottery opponents will continue to argue that lotteries prey on
the poor, encourage gambling addiction, open the door to other
forms of gambling, and leave government dependent on unreliable
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats have used lotteries very effectively as a
political crowbar,'' said Tom Grey, director of the National
Coalition Against Gambling Expansion. ``They've been able to play
one state against the other states, but there's not a debate over
whether this is good public policy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
