<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1977 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-INDIA-SPI &LR;      01-13 1514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-INDIA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIA FILM INDUSTRY IS REELING, BUT HOPEFUL FOR COMEBACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOMBAY, India _ The word is out in international film circles
that the once mighty Indian cinema _ the largest, most prolific,
perhaps most colorful and distinctive in the world _ is, for the
first time in its history, in deep trouble.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 30 years and more, Bollywood _ as this Bombay-based
industry calls itself _ has been the one great holdout to the
Hollywoodization of the planet: a vibrant national cinema cranking
out an average of 800 films a year to a devoted domestic
theater-going audience of more than 14 million per day.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1998, it was hard to pick up a serious film journal
without reading at least one portent of Bollywood doom. Even the
usually upbeat International Film Guide, the bible of world cinema
statistics, reported the Indian cinema had hit ``the lowest ebb in
its 67-year talkie history.''
</P>
<P>
   Variety's India correspondent, Uma da Cunha, reported that
throughout the past year, Indian audiences have kept away from
movie theaters in droves. In 1998, ``nothing seemed to work.
Comedies, tragedies, musicals, fantasies, even big-budget,
star-laden bonanzas _ thumbs down greeted the lot.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, liberalized trade policies resulted in more
Hollywood films being released in India than ever before _ more
than 150 in 1998 _ and many thrived. One of Bombay's
English-language dailies noted sadly that ``India's movie event of
1998 was called `Titanic.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, despite these faltering vital signs, Indian filmmakers
themselves seem determined that their cinema will not wither and
die. One noted Bombay producer recently vowed to CNN: ``Anyone
expecting another Hong Kong (whose film industry all but collapsed
last year) here is likely to be disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   My own quick trip through Bollywood found an industry that was
reeling from its worst year ever, and struggling to figure out just
what its problem is, but also amazingly confident of its paramount
place in India's cultural life and certain that its vast audience
can and will be lured back.
</P>
<P>
   This optimism was buoyed by the fact that December finally
produced the 1998 Bombay movie year's first two bona fide
box-office hits _ the romantic comedies, ``Kuch Kuch Hota Hain''
and ``Bade Miya Chlote Miyan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can hear the collective sigh of relief reverberating
around Bollywood,'' India's Cineblitz Magazine observed.
</P>
<P>
   At Film City, the sprawling, government-owned studio in the
northern suburbs, a spokesman said that ``an even more positive
life sign'' is that the box-office depression has not depressed
production. ``At the moment, our sound stages are full. Some 679
films were produced in India last year _ down a bit from the past
few years _ but not drastically. The new year is likely to see as
many or more.''
</P>
<P>
   This is partly, he said, because the new Hindu-nationalist
government in Delhi has helped the industry get funding, for the
first time, from the nation's big commercial banks. And partly
because ``every Bombay yuppie who makes a killing still wants to
invest it in a movie.'' (The same could be said of the Bombay
underworld, which reportedly finances 5 percent of the industry
with ``black money.'')
</P>
<P>
   Almost everyone here disputes or pooh-poohs the evidence of
Hollywood's increasing market share in India. Movie analyst (or
film-wallah, as he's known) S.V. Singh said, ``Yes, the Regal
(Bombay's top Raj-era movie palace) is playing `X-Files,' and
Hollywood rules most of the downtown cinemas. But that's still only
eight out of 250 theaters in the city. And, with the exception of
`Titanic,' no Hollywood blockbuster has ever appeared on the list
of India's top five grossing hits.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh believes the statistics also don't take into account how
important the film industry is to India, the crucial role
Hindi-language films play in uniting the numerous linguistic,
ethnic and religious factions that make up the subcontinent and
giving India a common identity. ``It may be our most vital
industry. We can no more afford to let it die than you can let
Boeing or General Motors die.''
</P>
<P>
   The statistics also don't take into account how deeply ingrained
movie culture is in India _ the strength of its star system, for
instance. How photos of Indian movie idols seem to adorn every shop
window in every town and village. Indeed, the first thing a visitor
to India invariably notices are the gigantic movie billboards on
every corner.
</P>
<P>
   India is not only the most movie-mad nation on Earth, it's also
the most knowledgeable about its own movie heritage. Any taxi
driver picked at random can probably give you a detailed tour of
the movie-star homes in Juhu Beach and Malabar Hill _ Bombay's
Malibu and Beverly Hills. And every Bombay schoolboy knows the
names, dates and filmography of India's movie pioneers.
</P>
<P>
   Film historian Arthur Knight has noted that India embraced
movies before most European countries. In fact, the first public
screenings in Bombay (by the Lumiere Brothers, at the Watson Hotel)
were as early as 1896, and Bombay had its equivalent of the
nickelodeon at ``about the same time as New York.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1911, Bombay impresario D.P. Phalke _ the father of Indian
cinema _ directed India's first feature film, ``Rajah
Harishandra,'' taken from the Hindu epic, ``The Mahabharata.'' The
film was such a big hit that it single-handedly established a
booming silent film industry in India that, by 1929, was turning
out well over 100 features a year.
</P>
<P>
   The advent of sound, of course, posed special problems in a
country with 18 official languages and more than 1,000 recognized
dialects, and India's film industry soon fragmented into a dozen or
more regional cinemas: Bengali-language films in Calcutta,
Tamil-language films in Madras, Hindi (nominally the national
language) films in Bombay.
</P>
<P>
   And, while the rest of the regional cinemas were feeding
regional tastes and nourishing obscure art-film movements _
Calcutta's Satyajit Ray, for instance _ Bombay, with the most money
and best facilities, wisely decided to concentrate on the kind of
big-star, big-budget musical escapism that could cross India's many
cultural barriers to become the ``All-India film.''
</P>
<P>
   By the mid '50s, the Bombay musical had evolved into what is now
known as the masala (collection of spices) movie: a gaudy, usually
mindless, three-hour formula film that mixes music (often dozens of
songs), stars (all gorgeous), innocent young love (with no sexual
contact, even kissing), stylized action sequences (no blood) and a
happy ending.
</P>
<P>
   In isolation from the rest of the movie world, a unique
masala-movie culture developed: a cinema driven by a fierce star
system (with the biggest stars so in demand that they may be making
10 movies at once), a powerful synergy with the music industry (in
India, movie music is pop music), and such an insatiable demand
from the Indian masses _ and overseas Indian communities around the
world _ that as many as 1,000 films might be cranked out in a good
year.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly why that audience has turned off to masala films so
suddenly and so completely is hard to understand, especially since
the industry seemed to weather the advent of television and video
in the late '80s so well. But the consensus of the film-wallahs is
that the Indian film audience is simply more sophisticated than it
used to be, and the old masala formula has worn thin.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in Showtime, one of Bombay's dozen or so slick,
English-language movie magazines, critic Ashok Banker charges
``Hindi films have lost their flavor, their taste. They've become a
bastardized form that is neither commercially viable nor
artistically successful.'' He demands that Bollywood emulate
Hollywood by abandoning its reliance on masala musicals and
producing films in distinct, American-style genres. ``Comedies.
Love stories. Action. Historicals. Horror. Suspense. Family
socials.''
</P>
<P>
   Others _ and not just conservative Hindu groups (see the
accompanying story on the movie ``Fire'') _ are less sure of this
American direction, and already see signs of an adverse social
impact from the lessening of censorship and import quotas in the
'90s: the ``wet sari'' scene that now seems to be in every movie,
the increasingly brutal and violent gangster sagas that play off
the mythology of the Bombay underworld, the recent vogue for
splatter-movie horror.
</P>
<P>
   Mira Nair, India's best known expat-filmmaker (``Salaam
Bombay!,'' ``Kama Sutra''), built her career in western art houses,
but she too feels that copying successful Hollywood formulas would
be a disastrous course for the Bombay industry. In an interview
last year, she said, ``I don't make masala movies, and don't much
patronize them. But I recognize that they're indigenously Indian.
If the genre goes, let's just hope that whatever replaces it will
be as positive and popular, and as reflective of India's culture _
not America's.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
