<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1979 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-INDIA-FIRE-SPI &LR;      01-13 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-INDIA-FIRE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FIRE' FUROR SPOTLIGHTS INDIAN DILEMMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   No event of recent years has underscored the divisions facing
India's vast but troubled film industry as dramatically as the
turbulent opening last month of the appropriately named
Canadian-Indian movie, ``Fire.''
</P>
<P>
   The film, which played at the 1997 Seattle International Film
Festival, is an intelligent and moving family drama about a
neglected new bride who moves into a large traditional Indian
family and gradually falls in love with _ and has an affair with _
her equally neglected mother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly a lesbian movie, it's more a parable about how male
insensitivity and an intransigent, male-dominated, Hindu society
drive the two women together _ less from a suppressed sexual
longing as an emotional starvation, a need for a fulfilling human
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Since I had met the director, Deepa Mehta, knew the film well
and had championed it in several reviews (before it went on to win
14 international awards), I made it a point while I was in India to
follow how it was received by its target audience.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, as the first film with even a modest lesbian
love scene to pass India's strict censor board, it was a media
event even before it opened, providing an occasion for India's
various gay-rights and feminist groups to debate the issues it
raised. (``With the release of `Fire,' female relationships come
into full and fiery focus,'' said the Times of India, in a
full-page Op-Ed piece.)
</P>
<P>
   It was also a box-office smash. The morning of the film's Bombay
opening, I went down to the New Empire Theater, a Raj-era movie
palace, and found that the queue for the first two matinee showings
(one in Hindi, one in English) stretched around the theater and
five blocks down the street.
</P>
<P>
   Chatting with young people in the queue, it was apparent that
some had showed up in hopes of seeing an explicit sex film (which
``Fire'' definitely is not), but most were there for higher
purposes. A 20-year-old student from nearby Bombay University told
me, ``You can't imagine what a rarity it is to have a socially
relevant Indian movie playing in one of the big Bombay movie
houses. It's truly an event.''
</P>
<P>
   Near the front of the line were maybe a dozen protesters _
members, it turned out, of the Shiv Sena: the most radical,
far-right party in the Hindu Nationalist coalition that has
governed India since last February, and the party that currently
runs India's huge Maharashtra Province.
</P>
<P>
   The Shiv Sena leader, Balasaheb Thackeray, has publicly praised
Adolf Hitler, and has enthusiastically supported the violent Hindu
extremist attacks on Muslims, Sikhs and Christians in India that
have claimed well over 1,000 lives in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   The Shiv Sena has set itself up as the fundamentalist Hindu
equivalent of America's Christian Coalition. Without having seen
``Fire,'' they denounced it as ``disgusting,'' ``social AIDS'' and
even ``an attack on Hindu culture.'' ``This movie will corrupt
young minds,'' one demonstrator chanted. ``Lesbianism is not part
of Indian culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the demonstration was peaceful and mostly ignored. The
film played to large crowds for over a week without incident. But
when I returned to Bombay a week later, the first thing that
greeted me at Sahar Airport was a TV broadcast showing scenes of a
Shiv Sena mob ``in the process of destroying the New Empire
Theater.''
</P>
<P>
   A goon squad of some 200 men and women rampaged through the
theater, assaulted moviegoers in the queue, smashed windows and
ripped down the ``Fire'' posters. By the time I got there, the New
Empire (an art-deco landmark which underwent a restoration only
last year) was a ruin, the police had cordoned off the area and the
exhibition of ``Fire'' was history.
</P>
<P>
   The film was scheduled to open the next day at the Regal Theater
in New Delhi and the Shiv Sena announced that if it did this scene
would be repeated. Apparently, this opening was particularly
offensive to them because the Regal Theater was a sacred site to
Hindu supremacy: the spot where, 49 years ago, Gandhi's assassins _
ex-members of the Shiv Sena's parent organization, the RSS _ met on
the fateful morning of the murder in January 1948.
</P>
<P>
   I flew to New Delhi that morning. This time, I watched about a
dozen Shiv Sena activists _ including three women with canes _
threaten the terrified manager, disperse the line of moviegoers,
smash the glass in the ticket booth and display windows, and force
their way into the theater, chanting slogans, smashing the food
counter and terrorizing patrons. Outside, other Shiv Sena tore up
the film's posters and billboards, and set them ablaze in a
bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   Only one of the Shiv Sena was arrested. A Regal Theater
spokesman quickly backed down from the theater's initial stance and
said that the film would be withdrawn.The next day, Manohar Joshi,
the chief minister of Maharashtra Province not only condoned the
attack on the two theaters, he ``congratulated'' the Shiv Sena on
its ``achievement'' (according to accounts in several
English-language papers).
</P>
<P>
   By that evening, the small counterattack had begun. Director
Mehta flew in from her home in Toronto to defend the film. Numerous
Indian artists came forward to denounce the attacks. Shabana Azmi,
the older of the film's two stars _ a member of Parliament and
arguably India's most-respected actress _ publicly wore a black arm
band. India's foremost gay-rights activist, Ashok Rao Kawai, asked,
``If they (the Shiv Sena) think (lesbianism) doesn't happen in
Indian society, what do they think is going on in those sculptures
in Khajuraho and Konark?''
</P>
<P>
   Later that week, the film opened in Calcutta _ traditionally
India's most intellectually tolerant city and much less of a
fundamentalist Hindu stronghold. This time, both police and
moviegoers at the Chaplin Theater fought off the Shiv Sena mob and
kept ``Fire'' open. And finally and belatedly, India's Prime
Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee _ himself a member of the
Hindu-Nationalist RSS _ condemned the violence.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it soon became clear that repression had won the day. A
goon squad attack on the father of Nandita Das, the younger of the
``Fire'' stars, and on several of the celebrities who had expressed
support of the film, quickly silenced the outrage of the artistic
community. The theater owners in Bombay and Delhi refused to reopen
the picture, even when the Indian supreme court guaranteed
protection. The national censor board announced that it intended to
reassess its approval of ``Fire.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
