u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLTEC-CRANE-GOODRICH     01-13 0480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLTEC-CRANE-GOODRICH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRANE EXPECTED TO ABANDON OPPOSITION TO MERGER OF COLTEC AND
GOODRICH 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
 - NYT  
 (ATTN: Conn., N.C., Ohio)   By   SHARON R. KING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Following the dismissal of Crane Co.'s lawsuit to block Coltec
Industries from merging with B.F. Goodrich, analysts and investors
said Wednesday that they did not expect Crane to pursue a hostile
bid.
</P>
<P>
   In part because such a bid would be more costly, ``most people
viewed this as unlikely to go hostile,'' said Tom Burnett, an
analyst with Merger Insight, a research firm. ``We're expecting
they might appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Crane's lawsuit contended that Coltec, a maker of aircraft
braking systems, broke a 1995 promise to notify Crane of any offers
to buy it when Coltec agreed in November to be acquired by Goodrich
for about $1.6 billion in stock and assuming $610 million of debt.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also sought to void anti-takeover provisions that are
part of the proposed deal so that Crane, which makes aerospace and
industrial products, could present its bid for Coltec, worth about
$1.8 billion, excluding debt.
</P>
<P>
   But on Tuesday, U.S. District Judge Barbara S. Jones in White
Plains disagreed with Crane's interpretation of its agreement with
Coltec, ruling that ``Coltec was not required to notify Crane of
B.F. Goodrich's bid.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge was expected to issue a written decision within a few
days, her deputy said.
</P>
<P>
   Investors showed little reaction to Crane's legal defeat as
shares of all three companies fell modestly Wednesday. Shares of
Crane, which is based in Stamford, Conn., slipped 37.5 cents to
$29.50. Those of Coltec, based in Charlotte, N.C., fell 57.42 cents
to $18.92, while those of Goodrich, based in Richfield, Ohio, fell
70.3 cents to $34.92.
</P>
<P>
   Crane said it would wait until the judge issued her written
decision before deciding what to do, but the company also has said
that it is only interested in acquiring Coltec through a
stock-for-stock transaction, known as a pooling of interests.
Generally, companies must be on friendly terms for that type of
acquisition to work.
</P>
<P>
   Accounting for the acquisition as a purchase would be more
expensive. Accounting rules governing those transactions require
that any amount paid in excess of the asset values be written off
over time, causing a reduction in earnings.
</P>
<P>
   An anti-takeover provision, known as a lock-up agreement, that
is part of the Coltec-Goodrich deal makes it prohibitively
expensive for a third party to acquire Coltec.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, who believed that Crane would see immediate benefit
to earnings through the combination of its aerospace anti-skid
devices with Coltec's braking systems, would likely balk if that
meant lowered earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one's going to tolerate dilution on this,'' said Wendy
Caplan, a principal at ING Baring Furman Selz who follows Crane.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
