<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1981 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-INDIA-VIDEO-SPI &LR;      01-13 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-INDIA-VIDEO-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIA AND HOLLYWOOD: FOR HALF A CENTURY, A LOVE-HATE RELATIONSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the past 50 years, no two countries have had a stranger
cinematic relationship than India and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Since independence, India has _ until very recently _ used
strict quota laws to keep most of Hollywood's products out, while
building its own native industry into a powerhouse, the world's
largest-volume producer.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, except for an occasional art film, the United States
has shown no interest in importing any of the thousands of films
India has made in these decades, under the theory they're so inane
and foreign to our sensibilities that even film festivals won't
play them.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, India has happily allowed Hollywood (and other foreign
film) companies to shoot in India, financed by ``frozen'' rupees:
profits of expatriate companies that, under India's strict currency
restrictions, can't be taken out of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Since all the big Hollywood studios had frozen rupees to burn,
and since India held such fascination for western audiences (think
of ``Gunga Din'' or ``The Lives of a Bengal Lancer'') and since
shooting in India was relatively easy (half the population speaks
English, after all, and the government is quite helpful), Hollywood
leaped at the offer.
</P>
<P>
   So more foreign films have been shot on location in India than
any other Asian country. Indeed, virtually every aspect of its
diverse geography _ from the Himalayas to the deserts of Rajasthan
to the jungles of Tamil Nadu _ has been immortalized by Hollywood.
The director Mark Robson said it best: ``India is Hollywood's
biggest backlot.''
</P>
<P>
   This vast filmography of shot-in-India films includes B-movies
(``Monsoon''), kids' movies (``Tarzan Goes to India''),
documentaries (Louis Malle's four-hour ``Phantom India''), art
movies (more than a dozen Merchant-Ivory dramas), epic TV
miniseries (``The Jewel in the Crown,'' ``The Far Pavilions'') and
a star vehicle from every major studio.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, many of the Hollywood-India star vehicles are not
yet available on video, including Robson's 1963 ``Nine Hours to
Rama,'' the 1953 Tyrone Power epic, ``King of the Khyber Rifles,''
Alan Ladd's 1953 ``Thunder in the East'' and the 1955 Lana
Turner-Richard Burton romantic adventure, ``The Rains of
Ranchipur.''
</P>
<P>
   Here, however, is a rundown on some of the most memorable
filmed-in-India epics that you might find at your local video
store:
</P>
<P>
   ``Elephant Boy'' (1937) _ Robert Flaherty, America's greatest
documentary filmmaker, co-directed (with Zoltan Korda) this
Raj-era, British film version of a Rudyard Kipling story that made
a star out of Sabu, a stable boy discovered while working for the
Maharaja of Mysore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kim'' (1950) _ The most authentic of Hollywood's many Kipling
adaptations was this rousing, colorful MGM version of the author's
masterpiece, filmed in numerous remote Indian locations by director
Victor Saville and starring Dean Stockwell and (in one of his most
unusual performances) Errol Flynn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bhowani Junction'' (1956) _ The story _ about the plight of
Anglo-Indians at the time of independence _ clearly got away from
director George Cukor, but the film (shot mostly in Pakistan) is
still an extraordinary, eye-filling epic, and, as the half-caste
heroine, Ava Gardner was never more radiant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Journey to the Lost City'' (1960)/``The River'' (1951) _ Two
India films by two European masters: the first a compilation of two
exotic adventures shot by Germany's Fritz Lang in Rajasthan; the
second Jean Renoir's classic coming-of-age drama about two British
children growing up in Bengal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maya'' (1966) _ John Berry _ the blacklisted, film noir
director who fled America in the '50s _ showed a surprising feel
for the many moods of India in this children's movie about the son
(Jay North) of a hunter (Clint Walker) who teams up with an Indian
boy (Sajid Khan) to deliver a white elephant to a holy city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gandhi'' (1982) _ Few films have captured the sheer scope and
many contradictions of India quite as dramatically as this
still-stunning biography, which features an eerily perfect
performance by Ben Kingsley as India's Great Soul, Mohandas K.
Gandhi. The film won an Oscar for best picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heat and Dust'' (1983) _ The Merchant-Ivory team has made no
less than 17 films in India with blocked rupees (``Bombay Talkie,''
``The Guru,'' etc.) but this adaptation of Ruth Prawer Jhabvala's
novel _ following two parallel stories, 60 years apart _ is the
most exquisitely enigmatic of them all.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Passage to India'' (1984) _ India-phile David Lean tried for
years to a mount a film about the making of the Taj Mahal, but had
to settle instead for this lavish, mostly successful adaption of
E.M. Forster's novel, shot in and around Bangalore.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Deceivers'' (1988) _ Pierce Brosnan plays William Sleeman,
the British officer who stamped out the infamous thuggee cult
(ritual murderers who strangled travelers to appease the goddess
Kali) in this exciting, underrated Nicholas Meyer-directed
historical adventure.
</P>
<P>
   ``City of Joy'' (1992) _ Roland Joffe had so many hassles
mounting this evocative film version of Dominique Lapierre's novel
_ about the consciousness-raising of an American doctor in a
Calcutta slum _ that Hollywood producers are likely to be very shy
about venturing into India again for many years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
