<TEXT>
<P>
   (pr) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Thursday, Jan. 14. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-RDP (Rio de Janeiro, Brazil) _ With its authority being
challenged by adversaries at home and its economic policies being
questioned by increasingly nervous investors abroad, the Brazilian
government devalues the nation's currency, allowing it to fall by
more than eight percent, an action that came after the surprise
resignation of the president of the Central Bank and a week of
precipitous declines in the stock market. By Larry Rohter. (We plan
to move the story by 9 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic and sidebars inside.
</P>
<P>
   Paired with the lead story, both under a two-column hed:
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-U.S. (Washington) _ A look at the impact of the Brazilian
economic crisis in Washington. By David E. Sanger. (Scheduled to
move by 9 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
