<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1994 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOOT-THEATER-REVIEW-N     01-13 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOOT-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LOOT': FROM KIDDING OPERA TO REWRITING IT
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Production notes at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By WILBORN HAMPTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Perhaps the most disturbing thing about the plays of
Joe Orton is that what was first seen as outrageous farce a scant
30 years ago sounds today more like satirical social commentary. If
audiences and critics of the 1960's were shocked by Orton, he knew
what he was doing. ``People think I write fantasy, but I don't,''
Orton is quoted as saying by John Lahr, his biographer. ``Some
things may be exaggerated or distorted, but they're realistic
figures. . . . There's nothing incredible about it.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Loot,'' which is being revived by the Jean Cocteau
Repertory, Orton mixes a bank robbery with a funeral, pits a
murderous nurse against a fascist Scotland Yard detective and
creates a dazzling comedy that builds to a hilarious ending and
cuts very close to the all-too-human bone.
</P>
<P>
   As the lights come up on the McLeavy sitting room, a coffin
occupies center stage, bearing the mortal remains of Mrs. McLeavy.
As McLeavy waits for the hearse to arrive from the funeral home,
Fay, the nurse who has been attending the deceased, enters wearing
her house slippers and asks the mourning widower, ``Have you
considered a second marriage yet?''
</P>
<P>
   All the rules suddenly are out the window. There will be no
discussion of what Orton called ``teacup things'' here.
</P>
<P>
   As the title indicates, the play is about money and what people
will do to get it. As it turns out, the McLeavys' son, Hal, and his
lover, Dennis, who is also the undertaker, have just knocked over a
bank, and they must find a place to hide the loot before the
arrival of Truscott, the detective who is posing as an official
from the water board. There is the coffin. But what to do with Mrs.
McLeavy? What follows shouldn't happen to a dog.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a curiously hesitant beginning, the Cocteau production,
under Scott Shattuck's direction, hits full stride in the second
act and delivers the laughs in the play's zany denouement. Unlike
classic farce, which requires a buildup of circumstance before the
humor begins to accumulate, an Orton play starts out at a full
guffaw gallop, even with throwaway lines. (When the nurse places an
embroidered sampler on the coffin, she observes: ``The Ten
Commandments. She was a great believer in some of them.'')
</P>
<P>
   If the pace is tentative in the opening scenes, it gets a burst
of energy with the entrance of Truscott, ably played throughout by
Craig Smith, in a deerstalker and chewing on a pipe, like Sherlock
Holmes on speed. Part of the problem may be that some other cast
members are concentrating more on their attempts at English accents
than on their characters, and end up struggling with both.
</P>
<P>
   Tracey Atkins, for example, never seems completely comfortable
as Fay, the nurse who is seven times a widow at 28. Tim Deak's
performance as Hal, the thief who is disadvantaged by being unable
to lie, is hit and miss: funny in some scenes, less so in others.
Charles Parnell is generally on target as Dennis, the oversexed
undertaker, and Harris Berlinsky gives a low-key reading of
McLeavy.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `LOOT'
</P>
<P>
   By Joe Orton; directed by Scott Shattuck; sets by Robert Joel
Schwartz; costumes by Susan L. Soetaert; lighting by Jonathan R.
Polgar. Presented by the Jean Cocteau Repertory, Robert Hupp and
Shattuck, artistic directors. At the Bouwerie Lane Theater, 330
Bowery, in Manhattan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Harris Berlinsky (McLeavy), Tracey Atkins (Fay), Tim Deak
(Hal), Charles Parnell (Dennis), Craig Smith (Truscott) and Jason
Crowl (Meadows). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
