<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Profile illuminates Sun's rise to technology's big leagues
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Technology topics have dominated the covers of
business magazines in the past year and, based on the latest ones,
there's little reason to think this fascination will change in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   The latest Business Week (Jan. 18) profiles Sun Microsystems,
which among other things plays a leading role in the government's
case against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   By outpacing its rivals, the magazine says, ``Sun has finally
reached the big leagues of the computer industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes (Jan. 25), meanwhile, tells how Intel Chairman Andrew
Grove converted the advice of a Harvard Business School professor,
Clayton Christensen, into the sales strategy that captured 35
percent of the low-cost computer market.
</P>
<P>
   Christensen's message was that a small company with a good
product can use a ``stealth attack'' to take business away from the
big guys.
</P>
<P>
   A turn of the cycle
</P>
<P>
   Cyclical stocks, which are sensitive to the economy, aren't
supposed to perform well when the economy slows, as it is doing
now.
</P>
<P>
   But Individual Investor (February) points out that not all
cyclicals are alike _ which is a plus for bargain-hunting
investors.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the well-known ``deep cyclicals'' that make heavy
equipment and industrial commodities such as aluminum _ and also
depend on improving business _ there are ``soft cyclicals.''
</P>
<P>
   Among them are ``non-industrial'' stocks such as airlines,
hotels and retailers that serve consumers who have already taken
care of essentials, and have extra cash for travel, luxury and
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Moms manage the money
</P>
<P>
   It may still be a man's world in many respects, but women hold
the purse strings, Working Mother (February) reports.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of the nearly 1,000 working mothers questioned by the
magazine said they manage the finances and spending for their
families.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, 42 percent rarely, or never, fight with their
spouses about money, which the magazine attributes to the
``management and diplomatic skills'' of working moms.
</P>
<P>
   Worth mentioning ...
</P>
<P>
   _ Real estate investment trusts had a bad year in 1998, with
total returns falling more than 15 percent. But Georgia-based REITs
outperformed the industry by declining only 2.8 percent on average,
reflecting the region's economic strength, Georgia Trend (January)
reports.
</P>
<P>
   _ The attention lavished on the new European currency, the euro,
has obscured an even bigger currency development, says The
Economist (Jan. 15) _ namely the dollar's decline against the
Japanese yen, which, if it continues, ``could have serious
consequences for the world economy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
