</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-DEVALUE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia companies try to hang on as nation restructures
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia companies have a lot at stake as Brazil tries
to restructure its economy.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth, Coca-Cola, Southern Co. and AGCO Corp. are among the
companies that have significant investments or operations in what
has been considered South America's most promising economy. Delta
Air Lines has launched business-oriented nonstop daily service to
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil is the No. 7 destination for Georgia exports, and metro
Atlanta business boosters increasingly have been touting that
nation as a prime potential market, given the economic uncertainty
in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Trade delegations have been traveling back and forth for years.
Georgia Tech this week is hosting 45 students from the executive
M.B.A. program at the Universidade Federal de Pernambuco.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia State University economist Donald Ratajczak said
Wednesday's crisis will certainly cut costs for U.S. companies
doing business in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   But he also said the dollar value of U.S. investments there is
depreciating, and companies are likely to wait and reassess the
depths of the Brazilian recession before making any new moves.
``Nobody is going to do anything until it stabilizes,'' Ratajczak
said.
</P>
<P>
   David Orr, an economist at North Carolina-based First Union
Corp., said the crisis ``could have a $40 billion economic impact
on U.S. corporations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's huge and it could slow U.S. profit growth substantially
in 1999,'' Orr said.
</P>
<P>
   Ratajczak said the Brazilian economy will now shrink by between
4 and 5 percent this year, instead of the 1 percent that had been
widely forecast.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get a recession of that magnitiude, why would you
want to invest?'' Ratajczak asked. ``The issue is not Southern
Company and Delta. It's Chase Manhattan Bank and Bank of America,''
he said. ``These guys could lose so much money that they stop
making loans in the U.S. Then we've got real problems.''
</P>
<P>
   It did not appear Georgia companies were taking precipitous
actions in response to Wednesday's events:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``We are monitoring the situation in Brazil as we do on an
ongoing basis with economies around the world,'' said Delta
spokesman John Kennedy. Last year, the Atlanta-based carrier
launched nonstop service between Atlanta and Brazil. Daily flights
go to Sao Paulo, then Rio de Janeiro and return to Hartsfield
International Airport. Most of the passengers are executives.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kevin Doyle, a spokesman for BellSouth, said the company sees
no change of strategic direction for its Brazilian operations.
``Our business in Brazil was a long-term investment and that is
what it remains,'' Doyle said. The company is providing wireless
service in two regions of Brazil, paying well over $1 billion for
the two licenses and spending hundreds of millions more to build
the networks needed.
</P>
<P>
   A faltering economy could threaten the business, at least in the
short run. But Brazil also has a sizeable segment of affluent
residents that are BellSouth's prime custromers. A recession could
even make it cheaper for BellSouth to expand its investments there.
</P>
<P>
   _ Brazil is the sixth-largest market for Atlanta-based
Coca-Cola, providing 3.9 percent of its profit in 1997, according
to Sanford C. Bernstein analyst William Pecoriello. Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter analyst Andrew Conway estimated Coke sales dropped 3
percent in Brazil in the fourth quarter and could continue to slide
in 1999. Coca-Cola declined comment. But Embotelladora Andina SA,
Chile's largest Coca-Cola bottler, said Wednesday that sales slowed
in the last three months of 1998, in part because of a 12 percent
to 13 percent decline in shipments to Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last January, Southern Co. acquired a 3.6 percent stake in
Companhia Energetica de Minas Gerais for $247 million. The utility,
known as Cemig, has 4.3 million customers, more than all of
Southern's U.S. utilities combined.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Pershing, senior vice president at Southern Energy Inc.,
the company's international unit, said Southern had anticipated a
``creeping devaluation'' of Brazil's currency during 1999 and had
already factored that into its economic projections. ``This made it
happen faster,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Southern spokesman Chuck Griffin said Brazil ``is still the key
country we're looking at in South America'' for more investments.
</P>
<P>
   Southern said last month it would shift its strategic focus in
the region to Brazil. The company plans Tuesday to announce a
``significant'' onetime charge to 1998 earnings to reflect a
decline in value of $400 million investments in Chilean and
Argentine utilities.
</P>
<P>
   _ AGCO, the Duluth-based farm equipment manufacturer, has also
shifted operations from Argentina to Brazil. The company, which is
cutting jobs and expenses in response to a global economic slump,
is the leading tractor supplier in both countries. AGCO announced
last month it would sell an Argentine plant and consolidate
operations in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Michael Kannell and Bloomberg News contributed to
this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
