A2011 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LUCENT14-COX     01-13 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUCENT14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Acquisition of Ascend a key move for Lucent
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When giant AT&AMP;T was dismembered in 1984, the big news was the
freedom for the regional phone companies to grow independently.
Tucked away within Ma Bell were the huge manufacturing operation
and Bell labs, the think tank that came up with product ideas and
technology improvements.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion in telephone technology, now augmented by the boom
in Internet communication, threatened to bypass the product
development forces tucked within the vastness of AT&AMP;T. Limited to
satisfying the needs and demands of AT&AMP;T, that manufacturing would
have a hard time keeping up with the fast-changing
telecommunications market, let alone lead it.
</P>
<P>
   That is one reason it made sense for AT&AMP;T to spin off the
production machine, now known as Lucent Technologies, freeing it to
grow with the vast telecommunications market and meet a wider
variety of needs.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent, based in Murray Hill, N.J., took a big step in its
growth strategy Wednesday with its $19.7 billion purchase of Ascend
Communications Inc. of Alameda, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The move is expected to make Lucent a more formidable player in
telecommunications technology.
</P>
<P>
   The spinoff of Lucent, completed two years ago, has seen it grow
rapidly and become a darling of Wall Street. But what Lucent has
discovered is that to keep turning out new products and services
fast enough to meet needs, it had to buy into new talent, skills
and expertise.
</P>
<P>
   And that is why Lucent made the deal. In one motion, it became
an even bigger and more vibrant player in new technologies.
Moreover, it might even alter the tide of technological change
occurring around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Rich McGinn, chairman and chief executive of Lucent, said the
deal gives Lucent a ``broader and more powerful portfolio'' on
developing the next generation of networks for delivering phone
calls, handling data transfer and providing video services.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts expressed general approval of the
acquisition but with reservations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lucent needs the gear and the credibility in the market that
Ascend can bring them,'' said Bob Bellman, analyst with Brooktrail
Research in Natick, Mass. ``But I don't know if they can pull it
off. Lucent is such a big company; it may just eat up Ascend and
not produce very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucent, whose local hub is in Norcross, employs more than 6,800
people and leads the world in the manufacture of fiber-optic cable.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent has gotten more business from the regional telephone
companies in recent years, freed from AT&AMP;T, which the regional
companies saw as a looming competitor in the local phone business.
Now they can place orders and big deals to Lucent without feeling
that they strengthen AT&AMP;T and undermine themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Ascend is only 10 years old and a major player in the production
of ATM equipment and services. Lucent has been one of its important
customers. Now Lucent and Ascend can grow together, merging their
talents, facilities and market savvy to produce new products in
several areas.
</P>
<P>
   On its own, Lucent has had success in producing such items as
digital processing chips that enhance personal computers to do such
things as videoconferencing. It has also put together systems for
unified messaging, which integrates e-mail, telefaxing and voice
mail.
</P>
<P>
   Together with Ascend, a bigger and better Lucent can be expected
to push hard to be a leader in the new technology of bringing
greater bandwidth to personal computers. Achieving greater
bandwidth is like replacing a 1-inch water line with a 4-inch line.
</P>
<P>
   It creates a faster and bigger volume flow. In the computer,
increased bandwidth enables PC to load information faster and make
greater use of services such as video.
</P>
<P>
   Much anticipated are advancements in DSL and even faster
technology to create large bandwidth networks to deliver larger and
faster streams of data to personal computers through telephone
lines. This is an objective of many players in telecommunications
and a competition for which Lucent is now better armed.
</P>
<P>
   In this broader area, a bigger and enhanced Lucent can count on
the talents of Bell Labs, one of the country's most successful
enterprises in research and development.
</P>
<P>
   The new Lucent is now in the middle of the competition between
cable and telephone technology, with the $200 billion telephone
industry struggling hard to keep up with the cable industry in
providing better service to homes and offices.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
