<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PORTMAN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Father, son developer team accused of sexual harassment
 &HT;    By Sallye Salter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Architect-developer John C. Portman Jr., and his son,
Jeffrey Portman, are accused of sexual harassment in two federal
lawsuits filed by former employees. Their firm, AMC Inc., which
operates the downtown trade mart complex, is also named in the
suits by the former women executives. The alleged harassment, much
of it in public, ``reflected a corporate culture of sexual
harassment of female employees at AMC,'' according to the court
filings.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs are Stacey Schoppenhorst, a former buyer services
director, and Masa Kisner, who AMC employed as director of buyer
relations and as director of international development. The women
couldn't be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The suits, filed at different times last year in U.S. District
Court in Atlanta, don't ask for a specific amount of damages.
Schoppenhorst filed suit against AMC and both Portmans. Kisner's
suit names Jeffrey Portman and AMC.
</P>
<P>
   Christina S. Meador, attorney for the Portmans and AMC, denied
the allegations Wednesday. ``Discovery has barely started. We
intend to defend vigorously, and I think in the long run that we
will be vindicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Robert Marx, who represents both plaintiffs, said
Wednesday, ``We are litigating aggressively. We will be taking
depositions of current or former employees that will bear out the
allegations of the complaints.''
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the filing of the cases, sexual harassment charges were
filed with the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission. The EEOC
gave both plaintiffs right-to-sue letters, according to Marx. Such
a letter is required as a prerequisite before filing a federal
sexual harassment lawsuit, but it doesn't constitute an endorsement
of complaints.
</P>
<P>
   In court filings, the Portmans contended that some allegations
by Schoppenhorst are barred by a statute of limitations on
complaints to the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Court documents filed recently indicated a settlement conference
was held last week in the Schoppenhorst case, and stated that
settlement is a possibility after the discovery process.
</P>
<P>
   Schoppenhorst, who was hired in August 1997, alleged that at a
trade show she was required to attend prior to her employment,
Jeffrey Portman, AMC's executive vice president of sales and
marketing, ``rubbed his hand against'' her breast. From that time
until March 1998, the suit said, ``John Portman and Jeffrey Portman
sexually harassed Ms. Schoppenhorst on a frequent basis.''
</P>
<P>
   The harassment included, the suit said, ``unwelcome remarks''
about Schoppenhorst's appearance and inquiries about her
relationship with her husband, Michael Schoppenhorst, then AMC's
director of trade shows. Michael Schoppenhorst is still employee by
AMC. She was fired in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also alleges that Schoppenhorst was subject to
``repeated physical assaults.'' For example, the suit alleged that
at a trade show in January 1998, John Portman, AMC's chairman and
chief executive, grabbed Schoppenhorst and ``forcefully'' gave her
an open-mouthed kiss in the presence of her husband. ``On numerous
other occasions'' and ``on a regular basis'' Portman ``hugged and
kissed'' her, the suit alleged.
</P>
<P>
   In his response to the suit, Jeffrey Portman said ``certain
conduct and actions were encouraged by and consented to'' by
Schoppenhorst.
</P>
<P>
   Schoppenhorst's suit alleged she was fired after complaining to
AMC's human resource manager and the company's counsel. AMC
responded in court filings that Schoppenhorst was fired for ``lying
to her supervisor and for her history of poor performance.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit by Kisner, who was hired by AMC in June 1995, alleged
that between May and December 1997, Jeffrey Portman sexually
harassed Kisner ``on a frequent basis'' through inquiries about her
personal life, allusions to his sexual activities and explicit
sexual remarks.
</P>
<P>
   During a business trip to Tokyo, he ``physically assaulted''
Kisner, ``tore her stockings,'' resulting in her having to change
before she could attend a meeting, the suit said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Portman denied any of his actions ``constituted sexual
harassment or improper conduct'' and contended ``such conduct or
actions were encouraged by and consented to'' by Kisner, according
to court filings.
</P>
<P>
   Kisner said that the company retaliated to her complaints by
making false statements that she had credit problems. She resigned
in February 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
