<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2021 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LABOR-SWEATSHOPS-NYT &LR;      01-13 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABOR-SWEATSHOPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWSUIT SEEKS $1 BILLION IN DAMAGES FROM COMPANIES OVER OPERATION
OF SWEATSHOPS
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Previously budgeted as LABOR-RICO) 
 (sw) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Apparel workers and human rights groups on Wednesday
filed the biggest legal challenge ever against sweatshops on
American soil, accusing Tommy Hilfiger, Sears, Wal-Mart and other
prominent companies of conspiring to place thousands of workers in
involuntary servitude and otherwise mistreat them to hold down
production costs.
</P>
<P>
   The class-action litigation asserts that 18 well-known American
retailers and apparel companies engaged in a racketeering
conspriracy with factory owners in the Northern Marianas Islands,
an American commonwealth near the Philippines, to deprive the
15,000 apparel workers there of basic rights.
</P>
<P>
   The action, actually three related lawsuits, seeks more than $1
billion in damages and is based on work by private investigators,
testimony from apparel workers and reports from the U.S.
Departments of Labor and Interior, which have enforcement powers in
the islands.
</P>
<P>
   It is the most sweeping lawsuit against sweatshops, seeking the
largest amount of money and involving a potential class of 50,000
workers and former workers and an unusually large number of
defendants. Together, the lawsuits describe a grim picture in the
Marianas: the workers, predominantly young women from China, the
Philippines, Bangladesh and Thailand, often must work 12 hours a
day, seven days a week _ and sometimes for free if they fall behind
on their quotas.
</P>
<P>
   These workers, the lawsuits assert, often live seven to a room
in dreary barracks that are surrounded by inward-facing barbed
wire. The lawsuits state that some companies, eager to make sure
that workers remain productive, have forced pregnant workers to
have abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Many workers in China pay $2,000 to $7,000 to recruiters who
boast about ideal conditions in the Marianas, the suit contends,
but when they arrive they find factories where foremen often limit
the number of bathroom breaks and exits are sometimes locked,
creating dangers in case of fire. Frequently, workers who complain
are dismissed or deported.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade, the apparel industry in Saipan, the
largest island in the Marianas, has boomed as Chinese entrepreneurs
built factories to benefit not just from the right to ship goods to
the United States without duties or quotas, but also from cheap
labor. The minimum wage in the Marianas is $3.05, far lower than
the $5.15 federal minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saipan is America's worst sweatshop,''Albert Meyerhoff, one of
the lead lawyers, said on Wednesday at a Manhattan news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Several industry officials denied that apparel makers conspired
to deny workers their rights. These officials said that apparel
makers have strained to improve working conditions in recent years
and have often stopped doing business with factories that break the
law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The islands are not the draconian slave camp that the big-time
law firm instigators apparently claim they are,''said Jack
Abramoff, a Washington lobbyist who has long represented the
Marianas.
</P>
<P>
   Apparel industry experts said the lawsuits were a public
relations blow to an industry eager to shed its sweatshop-tinged
image. In the lawsuits, prestigious companies like Tommy Hilfiger,
The Gap, Nordstrom, J. Crew and The Limited have for the first time
been named in a civil racketeering lawsuit that essentially accuses
them of conspiring to prey on workers and place them in peonage.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits are different in scope from previous anti-sweatshop
litigation _usually small-scale actions seeking tens of thousands
of dollars in back pay. The new litigation involves a major law
firm experienced in class-action litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Meyerhoff's firm, Milberg Weiss Bershad Hynes &AMP; Lerach of Los
Angeles, recently negotiated a $1.2 billion settlement with Swiss
banks to reimburse Holocaust victims.
</P>
<P>
   More than $1 billion in apparel is shipped each year from the
Marianas to the United States, and by having production done there,
apparel companies save more than $200 million in duties.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs are non-union apparel workers in Saipan, human
rights groups, including Global Exchange and Sweatshop Watch, and
the Union of Needletrades, Industrial and Textile Employees, which
is eager to protect American jobs from unfair competition, although
the driving force behind the lawsuit is a group of law firms.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for several defendants said on Wednesday that they had
not yet seen the lawsuits. In a statement, The Gap Inc. said it ``
does not tolerate this type of conduct in the factories where we do
business.''
</P>
<P>
   A statement from Wal-Mart, the nation's largest retailer, said
it does not do business with manufacturers in Saipan and has a
``zero-tolerance position with regard to illegal or unethical
working conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for Sears, J. Crew and The Limited declined comment.
Officials with Tommy Hilfiger and Nordstrom said that they have
strict fair labor policies.
</P>
<P>
   One of the lawsuits, filed in Federal District Court in Los
Angeles, asserts that the factories, apparel companies and
retailers violated the Racketeering Influence Corrupt Organization
Act and also violated international human rights laws.
</P>
<P>
   A second lawsuit was filed in state court in San Francisco and
charges that the companies engaged in unfair business practices and
misleading advertising by not adhering to their codes of conduct.
</P>
<P>
   The third lawsuit was filed in Federal District Court in the
Marianas and charges violations of wage and hours law and of the
Marianas local laws.
</P>
<P>
   To win the conspiracy lawsuit, the lawyers must prove that the
defendants associated in a criminal enterprise that engaged in a
pattern of illegal acts like involuntary servitude and theft of
services. The plaintiffs must also show that the defendants
participated in or aided the conspiracy or received substantial
benefits from it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
