<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-HOUSE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
13 HOUSE PROSECUTORS WILL FOLLOW TIGHLTY SCRIPTED GAME PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-LEGAL, IMPEACH-CLINTON,
IMPEACH-SCENE.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic on the Senate seating plan is being sent to NYT
photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When the 13 Republican Congressmen appointed to
prosecute President Clinton appear before the Senate on Thursday to
begin presenting their case, they will follow a batting order and
game plan that reflect the delicate protocol of seniority, their
individual strengths and an egalitarian effort to give each of them
a turn in the spotlight of history.
</P>
<P>
   The first and last words will go to Rep. Henry J. Hyde of
Illinois, the 74-year-old chairman of the House Judiciary
Committee. The second speech will be given by Rep. F. James
Sensenbrenner Jr. of Wisconsin, who has been in Congress and on the
Judiciary Committee longer than any of the 13 prosecutors except
Hyde.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles T. Canady of Florida, who was selected to anchor a
presentation on what constitutes an impeachable offense, held a
hearing on that question last fall in his capacity as chairman of
the House's constitution subcommittee. And three of the four
prosecutors chosen to lay out the actual evidence against Clinton
have extensive trial experience.
</P>
<P>
   But other prosecutors have no special aptitude for the roles
they are set to play, other than their willingness to play them.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an excellent question,'' Rep. George W. Gekas of
Pennsylvania said Wednesday as he pondered why his assigned task
was a legal discussion of obstruction of justice and perjury, the
charges in the articles of impeachment against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no excellent response,'' he continued. ``I guess the
best answer _ and it's contrived _ is that all 13 of us could have
handled any part of the case.''
</P>
<P>
   The 13 prosecutors, all members of the House Judiciary Committee
that held extensive hearings about Clinton's impeachment, are also
all lawyers, with a vast and varied array of experience between
them.
</P>
<P>
   While some sent drug dealers or murderers to prison, others
defended corporations against civil suits. Four worked as military
lawyers, three as federal prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   But many have not tried a case in years, even decades.
Sensenbrenner, for example, went almost directly from law school
into the Wisconsin State Assembly in 1969; the last time he made a
courtroom argument was in a divorce case in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   As he walked into the Senate chamber Wednesday to size up the
surroundings for the comments that he is scheduled to give
Wednesday, he acknowledged, ``It's the biggest speech I'll ever
give.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Sensenbrenner, most of the 13 prosecutors came to the
Senate chamber around 1 p.m. Wednesday to get a feel for the arena
in which they will fight an irrefutably uphill battle for Clinton's
expulsion from office. They wanted to see how the furniture was
arranged, where they would be sitting or standing at different
moments and how the easels and audio-visual technology they might
be using worked.
</P>
<P>
   At other times Wednesday, prosecutors holed up in their
individual offices, rehearsing their portions of the team's full
presentation for their staffs and making sure their comments fit
within time constraints. Each prosecutor is being given about an
hour or less; a few, however, will speak more than once.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde will briefly introduce the group when the Senate convenes
at 1 p.m. Thursday, then Sensenbrenner will deliver the formal
opening argument for their case.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors expect there will also be time Thursday for at least
three of the four congressmen to give presentations on the evidence
against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   They are Reps. Ed Bryant, a former federal prosecutor in
Tennessee, who will give an overview of all the evidence; Asa
Hutchinson, a former federal prosecutor in Arkansas, who will
discuss the facts related to obstruction of justice; and James E.
Rogan, a former deputy district attorney in Los Angeles, who will
discuss the basis for the perjury charge.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill McCollum of Florida will give a summation of the
evidence either late Thursday, when the Senate is expected to
remain in session until at least 7 p.m., or when the Senate
convenes again at 1 p.m. Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Barr of Georgia had been slated for McCollom's role
until early this week, when Barr shifted to an arguably less
prominent part. Officials working with the prosecution team said
the change did not reflect the fact that Barr's past was the
subject of a news conference held by magazine publisher Larry Flynt
on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Barr will be among the next four presenters, who will focus on
laws concerning perjury and obstruction of justice and argue that
the president broke them. The other presenters in this group are
Reps. Gekas, Steve Chabot of Ohio and Chris Cannon of Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are probably four or five places I could have fit,''
said Cannon, formerly a lawyer for the Interior Department.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Reps. Canady, Graham and Steve Buyer of Indiana will
discuss the history of and constitutional guidelines for
impeachment. Their presentation could conclude Friday or roll over
into Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Canady said he specifically requested his role, because he had
begun researching the topic extensively last May. But he said late
Tuesday that he was still writing his remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of in a frenzy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rogan and, finally, Hyde are currently scheduled to give the
closing arguments, which should come Saturday afternoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
