<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2031 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-BUDGET-COX     01-13 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-BUDGET-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    76th Texas Legislature makes plans to spend billions
 &HT;    By Juan B. Elizondo Jr.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The Legislature's leading budget writers laid
out plans Wednesday for the state to spend more than $91 billion
over the next two years, a 3.8 percent increase over the current
budget.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Rob Junell, D-San Angelo, and Sen. Bill Ratliff, R-Mount
Pleasant, said they believe the proposed budget is responsible and
addresses the state's basic needs. It would increase spending by
$3.3 billion and also leave $2.5 billion for lawmakers to determine
how to spend.
</P>
<P>
   The $91.7 billion budget does not include $1.8 billion expected
to be spent on anti-smoking, health and education efforts. That
money will come from the state's lawsuit settlement with the
nation's tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   Junell said budget writers felt it was appropriate to keep those
dollars, officially part of the state's general fund, separate so
that it is clear how they are spent. Much of the money could end up
in permanent endowments to support health and education programs,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The chairmen's budget, prepared by the Legislative Budget Board,
is the traditional starting point for the state budget process.
Gov. George W. Bush later this month will lay out his spending
proposals. The 10-member budget board is made up of the lieutenant
governor, the House speaker and the chairmen of eight key
legislative committees, including Finance and Appropriations.
</P>
<P>
   As they have for months, Junell and Ratliff continued to warn
that money left for lawmakers to decide how to spend won't cover
everyone's wish list.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not enough money to do everything that every
politician has promised to do to the extent they promised to do
it,'' said Junell, who's expected to be renamed chairman of the
House Appropriations Committee. ``We're going to continue to be
vigilant. Just because there is some money that could be used
doesn't mean that we should not continue to scrub these budgets.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether there will be enough money to pay for proposals
Gov. George W. Bush laid out during his re-election campaign,
Ratliff said, ``It will be tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, Bush proposed $3.6 billion in new education
spending, eliminating the state's main business tax for small
companies and a limited sales tax break. All of that could be
accommodated if spending were lowered for other programs or taxes
were raised.
</P>
<P>
   The governor has not proposed either move. Instead, he has said
everyone's spending plans will have to be adjusted.
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff's and Junell's proposed budget already is $3.3 billion
more than the $88.4 billion expected to be spent by Aug. 31, the
end of the current two-year budget cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff said all of the $3.3 billion increase is related to
growth in current obligations, like public education, prisons,
health care and public employees' retirement and insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't take it on ourselves to start new programs. We
didn't take it on ourselves to make some changes in general
revenues,'' Junell added. General revenue is the part of the budget
funded with tax money and fees and that the Legislature controls.
The total budget includes federal money that must be spent as
Congress dictates and fees earmarked for certain projects, like
road work.
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff said 85 percent of the proposed spending increase is due
to growth in education obligations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of the $3.3 billion, $2.8 billion has to do with either public
(education) or higher education. I think that properly reflects the
priorities of the people of the state and of the legislators. I
think it is appropriate,'' said Ratliff, who is expected to be
renamed chairman of the Senate Finance Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Hawkins, the governor's chief budget writer, said some of
Bush's campaign proposal could change, though others might remain
as outlined during his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the state budget is the primary job lawmakers face
every two years, the budget process in recent sessions has been
largely ignored. That's because spending once considered excessive
has been trimmed and few major fights have erupted.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the most controversial part of the budget has been
so-called riders that put limits on how state money is spent. For
example, in 1997 Ratliff added a rider preventing state money from
being invested in companies associated with musical groups that use
violent or sexist lyrics. The courts have ruled that provision
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Ratliff says he wants to get rid of most of the
riders except the most basic dealing with employees' expenses and
travel.
</P>
<P>
   Extra money in state coffers this year could spur extra
attention to the budget debate. Last year, former Comptroller John
Sharp estimated the state would have $6.3 billion more than
expected for spending in the 2000-2001 budget years, which begin
Sept. 1. Newly elected Comptroller Carole Keeton Rylander lowered
that figure to $5.6 billion last week.
</P>
<P>
   But Ratliff said many people, and perhaps some lawmakers, have
mistaken the extra money as $5.6 billion in discretionary dollars.
He's warned since before November elections that growth will
consume much of it, as the proposed budget shows.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, lines are long for a piece of the $2.5 billion left
over, and extra attention is likely to be paid to how the total
$5.6 billion and the tobacco money is used.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
