<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2033 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APPLE-EARNINGS-NYT &LR;      01-13 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLE COMPUTER REPORTS 5TH CONSECUTIVE PROFITABLE QUARTER 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A resurgent Apple Computer Inc. on Wednesday
reported its fifth consecutive profitable quarter. Excluding a
one-time gain, Apple earnings exceeded Wall Street estimates by
more than 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Apple's unit sales grew by 49 percent in the quarter,
year-over-year, several times the average for the personal computer
industry. Apple sold 519,000 of its translucent teal iMac's in the
quarter, fewer than the most optimistic analysts' forecasts, but a
huge number for any single computer model by any other measure.
Apple also had strong sales of its G3 Macintosh machines, aimed
primarily at professionals, even as these beige boxes are phased
out for a new line.
</P>
<P>
   Apple reported its financial results after the close of the
market. Apple shares closed at $46.50, up 37.5 cents, in Nasdaq
trading.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Kunstler, an analyst with J.P. Morgan, said Apple
delivered better than expected earnings in spite of revenues that
fell at the low end of estimates. ``I think investors are going to
look at that and be pretty pleased, especially since it wasn't like
Apple priced its product to fleece customers,'' he said. ``The
prices are pretty competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   For its fiscal 1999 first quarter, which ended Dec. 26, Apple
earned $152 million, or 95 cents a diluted share, more than three
times the $47 million, or 33 cents a share, earned in the
comparable quarter a year ago. Revenues rose 8 percent, to $1.71
billion, from $1.58 billion in the first quarter of the fiscal year
1998.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent quarter included a $29 million after-tax gain
from the sale of 2.9 million shares of ARM Holdings P.L.C. Without
this nonrecurring item, Apple's earnings for the quarter would have
been $123 million, or 78 cents a diluted share. Analysts had
expected Apple to earn 70 cents a share, according to the First
Call Corp., which tracks earnings estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Apple said its gross profit margin was 28.2 percent, up from
22.4 percent in the prior year. International sales accounted for
47 percent of the quarter's sales.
</P>
<P>
   One major contributor to the improved profit margins was strong
sales of System 8.5, the latest version of the Macintosh operating
system, Steven P. Jobs, Apple's co-founder and interim chief
executive, said in a telephone interview. ``People forget that we
own one of only two high-volume operating systems in the world, and
last quarter we came out with a new release and sold a lot of
them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Apple also is operating at a higher level of efficiency than in
the past, Jobs said, noting that the company ended the quarter with
just $25 million in inventory, equivalent to about two days' worth
of product. Dell Computer Corp., generally considered the
industry's leader in lean operations, typically has seven days of
inventory, and some PC manufacturers have two to three times that.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs said that despite Apple's return to sustained earnings and
revenue growth he intended to keep costs low, with no plans to
return research and development spending to the company's historic
levels. ``I'm a big believer that what you get out of R &AMP; D is not
dependent on what you spend but on focus and leadership,'' he said.
``We're not looking to spend lots more on that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 2047EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0400 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2040 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT14-1STLEDE-C     01-13 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT14-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WITNESS: MICROSOFT LACKS MONOPOLY POWER
 &HT;    Eds: corrects spelling of ``reverse'' in final graf.
 &HT;    Moving in (f) financial and (w) Washington queues
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In opening its defense Wednesday against antitrust
charges, Microsoft Corp. called as its first witness an economist
who held that the software giant's Windows operating system did not
give it monopoly power over personal computer desktops.
</P>
<P>
   The view taken by Massachusetts Institute of Technology
economics professor Richard Schmalansee appeared to astound David
Boies, the government's lead attorney, as he began what promises to
be a lengthy cross-examination.
</P>
<P>
   In bringing the landmark case, the government asserted that
Microsoft has illegally wielded its monopoly power by seeking to
extend its hold to the Internet while crushing its rivals.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft's underlying power _ which is not illegal and
which is based on the fact that Windows runs on more than 90
percent of newly shipped personal computers _ had not been an issue
until Schmalansee took the stand.
</P>
<P>
   The witness, dean of MIT's Sloan School of Management, insisted
that Microsoft does not have a monopoly because its operating
system dominance is threatened by companies that could produce
rival technologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't agree that (Windows) is a relevant market,''
Schmalansee told Boies. ``It makes no sense analytically. There are
developers out there writing for other platforms.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmalansee argued that such operating systems as Linux and
Beos, both of which run, along with Windows, on Intel-based
machines, were waiting in the wings as potential competitors, ready
to pounce on Microsoft's most valued turf. Even hand-held units,
such as those that run the Palm system, are ``competitors to
Windows,'' Schmalansee said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you really mean to tell the judge that this hand-held
system is now a serious competitor to Windows?'' Boies asked
Schmalansee in an incredulous tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``My answer is no,''' Schmalansee replied, seemingly backing off
a bit. ``But it is the germ of a potential competitor. To rule it
out is to have a constricted view of the fluidity of this
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   In filing 328 pages of testimony, Schmalansee wrote on page 250:
``Whatever one believes about Microsoft's power in the 'market' for
PC operating systems, the Windows desktop is surely not a relevant
market _ any more than the exterior of a Coke can is a 'market.' It
is only one of many effective channels of software distribution and
promotion.''
</P>
<P>
   The concept of a ``relevant market'' is central to all antitrust
law. Unless the courts find that such a market in fact exists, a
finding that any company wields monopoly power, let alone abuses
that power by seeking to dominate other markets, cannot be made.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department and 19 states allege that Microsoft holds
a monopoly in the operating system for personal computers that it
has preserved and attempted to extend illegally.
</P>
<P>
   Dismissing Schmalansee's views, Boies said outside the
courtroom: ``It's like they used to say at the top in the former
Soviet Union that they were a democracy. They are not around
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmalansee took the stand after U.S. District Court Judge
Thomas Penfield
</P>
<P>
   Jackson denied a motion by Microsoft to dismiss antitrust
charges at the mid-point of the trial, now in its 11th week.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, the ruling means that the government can now put on
its case. Since Jackson insisted that all testimony be submitted in
advance in written form, the Microsoft trial has taken place in
reverse, with nearly all the time being taken up by
cross-examination of hostile witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 2054EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0401 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2041 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT14-1STLEDE-C     01-13 0638
