<HEADER>
A2044 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LUCENT-ASCEND-907&AMP;ADD     01-13 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUCENT-ASCEND-907&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUCENT ACQUIRES ASCEND IN $20 BILLION DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada)  (rk) 
 By BARNABY J. FEDER c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In announcing its $20 billion acquisition of Ascend
Communications Inc. on Wednesday, Lucent Technologies Inc. called
it the ``largest technology merger ever'' and ``a leap rather than
a step,'' but there was an unmistakable whiff of ho-hum in the air.
</P>
<P>
   The high-technology marriage is a stock swap of .825 share of
Lucent for each share of Ascend, a 19 percent premium over Ascend's
market value when trading ended on Tuesday. The deal would have
been dramatic had it occurred a year ago, but by the time it was
done it seemed inevitable and perhaps even overdue to many analysts
and customers.
</P>
<P>
   With all the subtlety of a hurricane, the rapidly spreading
network of computers that makes up the Internet has been bearing
down on the traditional telecommunications routing and switching
equipment market. The regional Bell companies and other traditional
phone companies are competing with upstarts and their own big
corporate customers to build networks, both wired and wireless,
that handle voice, video and data services.
</P>
<P>
   To exploit the advantages it inherited as the leading supplier
in the traditional telecommunications market, Lucent, the former
manufacturing arm of AT&AMP;T, clearly needed to become a gorilla in
Internet equipment. The most straightforward way to get there
quickly was to buy a major Internet player.
</P>
<P>
   Ascend, the second-largest independent Internet supplier after
the far larger and fiercely independent Cisco Systems, was the
obvious candidate, especially after Lucent's longtime Canadian
rival, Northern Telecom Ltd., snapped up another Internet equipment
maker, Bay Networks Inc., for $7 billion last June.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel pretty good about having gone first,'' said John A.
Roth, the chief executive of Northern Telecom, noting that Bay
Networks brought $2.5 billion in sales and a large engineering
group to his company at what looks like a bargain price compared
with what Lucent is paying for Ascend, which had $1.6 billion in
sales last year.
</P>
<P>
   Roth said Northern Telecom, which operates under the Nortel
Networks brand name, was already well down the path of absorbing
Bay. In a separate announcement, Northern Telecom said Wednesday
that it was moving toward Bay's model of contracting out production
and would cut 8,000 jobs, or 10 percent of its work force, from its
other operations. It is the second round of job cuts in four months
at Northern Telecom, which laid off 3,500 employees in September.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts think Ascend is a far more valuable asset than
Bay, so the Lucent deal is a case of better late than never.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives Lucent a great technological boost,' said Robert
Rich, a telecommunications specialist at Yankee Group, a technology
research company in Boston. ``If you are looking for one-stop
shopping, Lucent will have more arrows in its quiver than anyone
else.''
</P>
<P>
   That new range of products and services will be available by the
end of April if the deal closes as rapidly as Lucent and Ascend
hope. But just how potent it will be is up in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent sees the world as speeding toward what it calls a
``network of networks.'' In such a world, there are huge profits to
be made in being able to knit together old and new switching and
routing technologies. Others, led by Cisco, see all communications
merging into the Internet and most of the profits going to those
with the best equipment to hasten the process.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent comes at the world from the perspective of the old-line
phone companies. For Cisco and others, the newer ``enterprise''
market of corporations and new service providers has been the
jumping off point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time may be on Cisco's side, but the question is how long it
will take,'' Rich said. ``The public networks owned by the phone
companies are still very profitable, well known, and well
managed.'' In addition, he noted, investing to adapt them may often
provide better returns than building new ones.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts see Lucent as saddled with a slow-moving corporate
culture inherited from AT&AMP;T, which could clash with that of Ascend,
which was founded in 1989 and is based in Alameda, Calif., just
across San Francisco Bay from Silicon Valley. Mory Ejabat, Ascend's
chief executive and president, is committed to stay only through
the transition, and analysts wonder how many other executives will
also leave.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, some analysts question Lucent's projection that the
deal will not hurt earnings in the current fiscal year, which ends
Sept. 30, and will raise them by up to 4 percent in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a real risk they won't sell as much as they think they
will because a lot of their current products compete head to
head,'' said Steven D. Levy, who follows the industry for Lehman
Brothers. Levy estimated that 45 percent of the products
overlapped, so some customers might switch products without
increasing the company's overall sales.
</P>
<P>
   Some competitors were also unimpressed, at least publicly. Larry
Lang, vice president for service provider networks at Cisco,
derided the deal as a defensive one that will end up helping his
company take more business from both Lucent and Ascend.
</P>
<P>
   Investors seem to be taking a wait-and-see attitude. Shares of
Lucent fell $3.625 Wednesday, to $104.25, not a remarkable move on
the day when the stock market was down and arbitragers who had
expected the deal were cashing in. Ascend rose $5.375, to $80.3125,
and was the most actively traded stock on Nasdaq.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I think it will go up as people digest this,'' said Alex Cena,
who follows the industry for Salomon Smith Barney. ``The phone
companies will now be able to split their business between Lucent
and Cisco, which is exactly what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   The real payoff for Lucent may come down the line in overseas
markets. The buyout of Ascend makes it a more potent competitor for
foreign rivals like Ericsson of Sweden, Alcatel of France and
Siemens AG of Germany at a time when Lucent is already making
inroads in the overseas markets those companies grew to dominate
during the decades Lucent was confined to supplying the domestic
market.
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans are not sitting still. Ericsson said Wednesday
that it would start reselling computer switches for phone and
Internet companies made by Juniper Networks Inc., a closely-held
start-up in Palo Alto, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   And investors clearly expect one of the European companies to
buy Newbridge Networks Corp., a Canadian company that like Ascend
has been selling a switch that can handle data, voice and video on
phone lines with asynchronous transfer-mode technology. Newbridge's
shares jumped to $39 Wednesday before easing off and closing at
$36.1875, a 9.7 percent gain.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent, Cisco and other American equipment companies are facing
a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity in many overseas markets as
governments divest the telephone companies they once owned and
allow competitors to take root. Indeed, even analysts skeptical
about the value of the Ascend deal were pleased by Lucent's
announcement Wednesday that it had also bought 12.2 percent of
Amper SA, a Spanish equipment maker and installer, for $49 million.
</P>
<P>
   That deal could help Lucent become a major supplier to Amper's
primary owner, Telefonica, Spain's largest telephone company.
Telefonica also has a stake in the potentially huge Brazilian
market, which could open doors there for Lucent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
