<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taft bids to improve Ohio Lottery profits, hopes new hire
Mitchell Brown will help
 &HT;    By Debra Jasper
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ As he announced the new executive director of the
Ohio Lottery Commission and three other new members of his cabinet
Wednesday, Gov. Bob Taft said he wants his administration to manage
the lottery more efficiently and make it more viable.
</P>
<P>
   Taft said lottery profits have been stagnant for some time and
he's concerned about the impact declining sales could have on
schools. He said he wants Mitchell Brown, his newly named executive
director, to examine the lottery's operations and make
recommendations in the coming months for improvements.
</P>
<P>
   Taft said he doesn't want to see children or those with gambling
problems encouraged to play the lottery, but said some kind of new
marketing campaign may be needed. Taft declined to give specifics
of what, if any, new lotto games he'd like to see in Ohio, saying
``I'm not an expert on gaming.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, of Columbus, was director of the Department of Public
Safety in the Voinovich Administration. In that position, he
oversaw the work of 3,367 employees and budget of $844 million. His
responsibilities included oversight of the Bureau of Motor
Vehicles, the Ohio State Highway Patrol, and the Emergency
Management Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Taft said he has about 10 more cabinet positions to fill,
depending on whether he consolidates some departments. The other
three cabinet members named Wednesday are: Lee Johnson, of
Carefree, Ariz., director of the Department of Development; Joan
Lawrence, of Galena, director of the Department of Aging; and Major
General John Smith, of Columbus, adjutant general.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson retired in October 1998, as president of Limited
Distribution Services, a subsidiary of The Limited Inc. He also has
more than 15 years of senior management experience in the consumer
products and pharmaceutical industries industries , with Beatrice
Companies and Warner Lambert Company.
</P>
<P>
   He currently resides in Carefree, Ariz., and will be relocating
to Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   While employed in Columbus, Johnson served as chair of the Board
of Directors of Port Columbus International Airport; and served as
chair of the Columbus Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Taft said he got to know Johnson when Johnson worked at the
Chamber.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is one of the most experienced business executives anywhere
in the country,'' Taft said.
</P>
<P>
   During Johnson's tenure as chair of the Columbus Chamber, the
area was designated Small Business Development Region of the Year,
with $25 million in increased sales and 755 new jobs. In addition,
the Chamber helped attract $108 million in new investment to the
Columbus area, bringing in 1,279 new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson will take office in mid-February.
</P>
<P>
   Taft said Lawrence, who has been a state legislator for 16
years, is a registered nurse who will be a ``strong advocate for
Ohio seniors.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence was the primary sponsor of Ohio's welfare reform
legislation, and is a member of the legislature's Welfare Oversight
Council monitoring the implementation of welfare reform at the
county level. She also chairs the Human Services Subcommittee of
the House Finance and Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Major General John Smith currently commands the Ohio Air
National Guard, including more than 5,000 Air National Guard
members in 11 units. He is a command pilot with more than 4,000
flight hours, and flew combat missions over the Republic of Vietnam
in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
