<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES HEAR ARGUMENTS ON WELFARE POLICY AND RIGHT TO TRAVEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The debate before the Supreme Court on Wednesday
was over welfare policy _ whether states can have a lower level of
benefits for newcomers than for longtime residents _ but the deeper
issue was the meaning of citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   California was asking the court to permit it to do what Congress
authorized in the 1996 welfare law: hold newcomers, for their first
year of residency, to the welfare benefits they would have received
in their home state, often hundreds of dollars a month lower.
</P>
<P>
   California's deputy attorney general, Theodore Garelis,
complained that the state's search for ``flexibility'' in its
welfare policy had been ``stymied and hampered'' by lower court
rulings, which have invoked the constitutional right to travel to
block the state program from taking effect.
</P>
<P>
   At the most, Garelis said, the right to travel was affected only
``incidentally and remotely'' by a ``carefully crafted'' state law
that amounts to ``just a benefit-setting adjustment for one year.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg objected. The whole point of the
court's precedents on the right to travel was that new residents
and longtime residents were entitled to equal treatment, she said,
adding: ``That is the genius of the United States. People can pick
their states, but the states can't pick their people.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the hour-long argument, the court appeared deeply
engaged by this case, which brings today's moderate-to-conservative
justices face to face with one of the liberal Warren Court's more
expansive constitutional doctrines. Significant as the case is for
national welfare policy, it could also be an important indicator of
the court's current approach to constitutional interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution does not mention a right to travel, but
decisions in the 1960s derived it from the guarantee of equal
protection. In a 1969 case, Shapiro vs. Thompson, the court invoked
the right to travel to strike down state laws that barred newcomers
from receiving welfare benefits during their first year of
residency. Several briefs filed in the case on Wednesday, including
one signed by New York and 15 other states on California's behalf,
asked the court to overrule Shapiro vs. Thompson as an
illegitimately created ``fundamental right.''
</P>
<P>
   Justices expressed little interest in accepting that invitation,
with the possible exception of Justice Antonin Scalia, who appeared
intent on trivializing the issue with several references to his
ambition to take a vacation in Louisiana and invoke the right to
travel in order to get a hunting and fishing license at in-state
rates.
</P>
<P>
   When Mark D. Rosenbaum, an American Civil Liberties Union lawyer
representing the successful challengers to the California law,
pointed out that the right to travel applied to residents, not
tourists, Scalia professed not to understand the distinction.
</P>
<P>
   Garelis, the state's lawyer, told the court that California's
approach did not run afoul of Shapiro vs. Thompson because, by
reducing but not refusing benefits, ``we're not trying to deter
travel in any way, shape or form.'' He said the state was ``merely
neutralizing one factor that someone might care to consider when
moving to California.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand that,'' Justice Stephen G. Breyer objected.
He said the only difference between cutting off benefits, which the
Shapiro case prohibited, and reducing benefits ``is that you're
more generous, but not really much more generous.'' He asked why
California's approach would be constitutional simply ``because
you're trying to save a little less money.''
</P>
<P>
   If California were allowed to put the policy into effect, it
would save something under one-half of one percent of its annual
welfare expenditure.
</P>
<P>
   The case, Anderson vs. Roe, No. 98-97, is complicated by the
fact that, while the California law dates to 1992, Congress
subsequently authorized temporary two-tier welfare benefits as part
of its major reworking of federal welfare policy in 1996. Fifteen
other states also provide lower benefits for newcomers, although
most of the laws have been blocked by federal or state judges. The
California law was struck down twice, before and after the federal
law took effect, by the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in San
Francisco.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Although the constitutionality of the federal law was not
directly before the Supreme Court on Wednesday, it had a role in
the argument, prompting the solicitor general, Seth P. Waxman to
offer an argument in defense of the theory behind the federal law.
Justice Anthony M. Kennedy asked Garelis whether ``Congress can
somehow permit what otherwise would not be allowed'' under the
right to travel.
</P>
<P>
   The state's lawyer replied that the existence of the federal law
minimized what would otherwise be a concern about conflicting
policies that could ``balkanize the various states.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How is the concern minimized if Congress says go ahead and
balkanize?'' Justice David H. Souter asked. If the state's purpose
was the illegitimate one of interfering with the right to travel,
he continued, ``is there anything Congress can do to take the
poison out of that purpose?''
</P>
<P>
   Souter answered his own question. ``I would have thought not,''
he said, adding pointedly to Garelis: ``We're playing with words.''
</P>
<P>
   Waxman did not fare much better in his part of the argument,
which did not necessarily endorse California's approach. The court
appeared impatient with the solicitor general's nuanced position,
which his 10 minutes of allotted time left him little chance to
articulate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where else does Congress have the right to authorize a state
to discriminate among its citizens?'' Souter demanded. Ginsburg
told the solicitor general she was ``really astonished'' by his
argument that the case involved simply a ``transitional choice of
law'' during a newcomer's first year of residency. The American Bar
Association called this argument ``mysterious'' in a brief
attacking the administration position.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbaum, legal director of the American Civil Liberties Union
of Southern California, offered a spirited defense of his lower
court victory. The law was ``antithetical to the core values of our
federal system of dual sovereignty,'' he said, adding that the
principle that ``citizens are free to vote with their feet and to
act on whatever their needs and tastes are'' was a ``notion that
absolutely saturates'' the court's cases explaining the shared
federal-state system.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of the two named plaintiffs in Rosenbaum's class action
lawsuit, identified only as Brenda Roe and Anna Doe, were welfare
recipients when they moved to California from Oklahoma and
Washington, D.C. Ms. Doe had a job, and Ms. Roe's husband was
employed but lost his job when he stayed home to care for her
during a complicated pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   California officials told Ms. Roe she would get Oklahoma's
benefit of $307 a month instead of California's $565. Ms. Doe was
limited to the $330 a month provided by Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In other court business on Wednesday, the court ruled, 9-0, that
the Constitution's guarantee of due process does not require the
police, after seizing items from a home during an authorized
search, to inform the owner how to regain the property. Rather, the
police must simply notify the owner that the property has been
taken, ``so the owner can pursue available remedies for its
return,'' Kennedy said in his opinion for the court in West Covina
vs. Perkins, No. 97-1230. The decision overturned a ruling by the
9th Circuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
