<HEADLINE>
EXPERT ANGLERS TO SHARE KNOWLEDGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ Private boaters favor downriggers when
trolling because angling lines can be set at the specific depth in
the water column where game fish have been located.
</P>
<P>
   The baited line is clipped to the downrigger's wire cable, and a
lead ball submerges the setup.
</P>
<P>
   A problem occurs, however, when big game _ especially mako
sharks in Southern California, but also billfish, tuna, wahoo and
dorado _ swim forward after getting hooked instead of away from the
boat, as they do an estimated 90 percent of the time. The fishing
line can get tangled in the cable and, snap, the fish of a lifetime
is lost in the blink of an eye.
</P>
<P>
   Solution:
</P>
<P>
   Crimp 100 feet of 100-pound monofilament line to the cable. Clip
the lead ball and fishing line onto the monofilament and lower it
down. Now when the mako swims forward after biting the bait, the
lighter-strength and smaller-diameter fishing line _ often 30-pound
test _ knifes through the downrigger line.
</P>
<P>
   ``You lose your downrigger ball and you save your fish,'' said
George Poveromo, a marine-angling authority from Parkland, Fla.,
who offered the lesson. ``To most fishermen, catching that fish far
exceeds the expense of buying another downrigger ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The tried-and-true technique ``is something that very few people
know about,'' claimed Poveromo, 40, senior editor for Salt Water
Sportsman magazine.
</P>
<P>
   He and a crew of national and regional experts will be offering
a slew of such ``secrets'' Saturday in Long Beach during the only
West Coast stop of the Salt Water Sportsman National Seminar
Series, billed as the world's most comprehensive ocean-angling
educational tour.
</P>
<P>
   Just remember to keep some extra downrigger sinkers in the boat.
</P>
<P>
   Don't know how to crimp on line, you say. The seminar textbook
devotes an entire chapter to the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Geared to private boaters, the program recommends tackle and
tactics for anglers who don't rely on party-boat captains to find
the fish and deckhands to work the rigs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up to you to come up with the most productive technique
to find and land fish,'' explained seminar host Poveromo. ``And if
you know there are fish out there and they aren't biting, you have
to be able to switch to another technique to catch them. The
seminar helps improve your knowledge of those tricks.''
</P>
<P>
   Anglers who patronize party boats exclusively can also benefit
from the seminar, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   In a picky bite, for example, increase your chances of getting
hit by scaling down the size of the leader and hook and getting
less terminal tackle in the water _ which appears less conspicuous
to the fish. ``You may spend more time fighting the fish and that
may increase the chances of losing fish, but wouldn't you rather
take that gamble by increasing your chances of getting hooked up?''
said Poveromo.
</P>
<P>
   The program will also profile such specifics as fluorocarbon
leaders, which are significantly more expensive than traditional
line but are promoted as being less visible to fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope that participants would walk away knowing several
different techniques that will help them catch their favorite game
fish,'' Poveromo said.
</P>
<P>
   Since its inception in 1988, the series has produced some 60,000
``graduates.'' To better saturate the topic, several experts appear
on stage at the same time to address each species or tactic and
demonstrate technique.
</P>
<P>
   Poveromo will be joined by television fishing-series host Spider
Andresen and several area speakers, including big-game author and
shark and tuna guru Fred Archer, inshore and offshore light-tackle
authority Greg Stotesbury, tuna and marlin hunter Randy Wood, and
calico-bass and artificial-lure tactician Barry Brightenburg. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
IF YOU'RE GOING &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Salt Water Sportsman National Seminar Series makes a layover
Saturday at the Carpenter Performing Arts Center at Cal State Long
Beach, 6200 Atherton St. in Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The six-hour program begins at 9 a.m. and concludes at 4 p.m.,
with a one-hour lunch break at noon.
</P>
<P>
   Cost is $40. Tickets are available atthe door or in advance by
calling (800) 448-7360. Doors open at 8 a.m.; telephone-ordered
tickets can be picked up then.
</P>
<P>
   Each ``student'' receives a 106-page course textbook and a
chance to win door prizes, including an angling trip to the Bahamas
and an outboard fishing boat.
</P>
</TEXT>
