<HEADLINE>
MARINE RESERVES GET MORE ATTENTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ While the state Fish and Game Commission has put
the proposal to ban fishing along portions of the Northern Channel
Islands on the back burner, it has adopted a strict time line to
take action on the greater issue of creating more marine reserves
throughout California.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an issue that is receiving a lot of attention, not
only in California but worldwide, and the commission believes that
it needs to be aired and discussed,'' said Bob Treanor, executive
director of the five-member commission's staff. ``The commissioners
need to gain information from scientists who are working on this
issue, from the public and from the fishing community.''
</P>
<P>
   Treanor this week detailed the commission's plans.
</P>
<P>
   The commission decided Feb. 6 during its monthly meeting to
delay voting on the fishing-ban proposal until it receives a state
report on marine reserves that is part of the Ocean Initiative
ordered in 1997 by then-Gov. Pete Wilson to study the health of
saltwater environments, Treanor said.
</P>
<P>
   The report is expected to be completed by a task force of the
state Resources Agency _ which oversees the Department of Fish and
Game among others _ ``within the next couple of months,'' he said.
The report will look at reserves and refuges to establish a
standardized definition of each.
</P>
<P>
   The commission believes it will be able to use the data and work
with the DFG and Resources Agency task force to draft, by year's
end, a statewide policy on how to consider requests for adopting
marine reserves, commonly known as ``no take'' or ``no harvest''
zones that are off-limits to fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Within that time frame, the commission expects to identify 5 to
20 percent of the shoreline around the five islands in the Channel
Islands National Park for possible protection as marine reserves,
said the commission's executive director. Initiators of the
fishing-ban proposal recommend that no less than 20 percent of the
islands' shoreline be protected out to 1 nautical mile to replenish
dwindling fish stocks; they also want San Nicolas Island _ situated
outside of the national park _ to be included in a ban.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's two-member Marine Subcommittee will monitor the
progress of the Resources Agency's report and apprise the
commission at each of its monthly meetings, the next of which is
Feb. 4-5 in Sacramento. If the subcommittee determines there is
lack of progress in releasing their report, it will ask the
commission to reconsider the Channel Islands' ban issue directly,
Treanor said.
</P>
<P>
   Whichever route the commission follows, proponents and
detractors of fishing bans will have their chance to be heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we progress, there will be a specific agenda item
soliciting public input,'' said Treanor. He expects a draft of the
policy addressing future marine-reserve proposals to be issued by
the commission in late summer or fall and that public comment will
be heard on the item in October or November.
</P>
<P>
   While a fishing ban can be put in place within 90 to 120 days of
a Fish and Game Commission approval, Treanor said it is not likely
that any no-take zones will be established in the Channel Islands
National Park in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Also at last week's meeting, the commission discussed the
possibility of creating, within 60 days, a scientific panel and a
separate group consisting of sport anglers, commercial harvesters
and divers and other recreationists to provide the Marine
Subcommittee information, issues and criteria for consideration in
drafting the policy.
</P>
<P>
   The Channel Islands fishing-ban proposal has become a heated
issue between anglers and environmentalists _ and between anglers
themselves. Recreation fishers argue they should not be lumped into
a ban when statistics show the overwhelming majority of state
fishing takes come from commercial harvesting; commercial anglers
claim they are victims of a proposal that was largely brought about
by recreational anglers concerned about the exploitation of finned
species through sport-fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the Channel Islands National Park _ one of
the proposal's two initiators _ are pleased with the direction the
Fish and Game Commission is taking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that there has been a major change in direction since
last spring, when we first discussed it formally with the
commission,'' said Gary Davis, the national park's senior
biologist. ``It seems now that their focus is how, not if marine
reserves should be part of the management scheme for the Channel
Islands and all of California. I hear the commissioners saying we
need to think globally and act locally, and the Channel Islands are
the place to act locally.''
</P>
<P>
   Commercial anglers are concerned with the commission's new
direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``A commercial guy's first response is that he doesn't want to
be precluded from fishing any waters, but if the science suggests
the resource is going to benefit from such a ban he'd be all for
it,'' said Santa Barbara's Kevin Crisp, president of the Sea Urchin
Harvesters' Association of California. ``But the burden of proof is
on the science, and it hasn't been there. The reality is that there
isn't hardly any research on marine reserves.''
</P>
<P>
   Detractors have argued that California's existing 104
marine-protected areas are too small, too infrequently monitored
and lacking substantial amounts of fish to execute conclusive
studies, and many biologists _ Davis included _ agree.
</P>
<P>
   But Fish and Game Commission members have grown frustrated with
requests for more research and want to consider other options to
tackle overfishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Study is no longer an idea, and there is no state money for
studies,'' said commissioner Frank Boren. ``We need to try
something, and if the no-take zone is the only thing to try, then
we have two choices _ try it or ignore the problem.''! &UR; end! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
