<SLUG> BC-WARNER-WEB-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARNER BROS. PARTNERS WITH FORTUNECITY ON WEB SITE FOR FANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif. -- Warner Bros. announced Wednesday a major
cyberspace expansion, launching an ACMEcity.com site named after
the mythical company of its ``Road Runner'' cartoons.
</P>
<P>
   The site, a joint venture of Warner Bros. and Internet design
specialist FortuneCity, will allow users to create their own Web
pages using images and audio clips from Warner cartoons, TV shows
like ``Friends'' and music acts like Depeche Mode. ACMEcity has 14
community sites grouped into film, TV, music and comics-animation
but plans to add 50 more within its first year.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Butt, an analyst with Jupiter Communications, said the
approach is a logical way for Warner Bros. to exploit its fan base.
</P>
<P>
   ``We encourage companies to take this approach, because it makes
your fans into your allies,'' he added. ``It creates a ton of
goodwill since you're allowing your fan base to grow and prosper
rather than just sending the message that you want to milk the last
penny out of the relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   The companies sealed the deal with studio parent Time Warner
Inc. making an investment into FortuneCity and agreeing to supply
an impressive $100 million of marketing support during the next
five years. They said the partnership will develop hundreds of
sites within ACMEcity with content reviewed for
``community-zoning'' compliance.
</P>
<P>
   Warner, which made the announcement a day after rival The Walt
Disney Co. launched its ambitious Go Network ``portal'' service,
has high hopes for the service. ``The collaborative result will be
the largest entertainment-oriented community on the Internet,
creating a protected environment that is safe for families and
advertisers alike,'' said Jim Moloshok, president of Warner Bros.
Online.
</P>
<P>
   Work on the project began four months ago with the arrival of a
dozen FortuneCity employees in Burbank.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than going around saying you can't use this and
threatening to sue, the idea is to let the fans use what they
want,'' said Richard Jones, co-vice chairman of 2-year-old
FortuneCity. ``So, instead of clamping down, you're releasing their
creativity and the benefits are massive.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
