<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-RDP-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON TRIAL'S EVE, REPUBLICANS SECRETLY DISCUSS CALLING WITNESSES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH-LEGAL, IMPEACH-CLINTON, IMPEACH-HOUSE,
IMPEACH-SCENE.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic on the key players in the Senate trial is being
sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A small group of Senate Republicans has met
secretly with the House impeachment prosecutors to establish
standards for calling witnesses, even as the prosecutors have
approached Monica Lewinsky and Kathleen Willey to see if they would
testify in the Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   The question of calling witnesses to testify before the Senate
has badly divided Democrats and Republicans as they set procedures
for the trial. After a rare bipartisan meeting last Friday, all 100
senators agreed to vote on whether to call witnesses later in the
month, after hearing opening arguments from the House managers and
the White House beginning on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the agreement, Sens. Trent Lott, the majority
leader and Tom Daschle, the minority leader, announced that a
bipartisan group of four senators would meet to try to hash out how
the Senate would deal with the witness issue at a later date. But
that group fell apart almost immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Lott then quietly went ahead on his own and appointed three
Senate Republicans who have said publicly that they favor calling
witnesses _ Jon Kyl of Arizona, Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania and
Jeff Sessions of Alabama _ to work with Rep. Henry J. Hyde of
Illinois, the lead manager, and his aides. They were assigned to
devise criteria for witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats were belatedly invited to a meeting of the new
group on Monday, but Daschle rejected the offer. ``Senator
Daschle's position is that we voted on an unanimous bipartisan
level to put off the question of witnesses, so it would not be in
keeping with that agreement to start a discussion about whether to
call witnesses,'' said Ranit Schmelzer, a spokeswoman for Daschle.
</P>
<P>
   The White House spurned a similar offer from the Republican
senators after the Senate Democrats said no.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans insisted Wednesday that their discussions
with the House managers were aimed at continuing the bipartisan
spirit borne out of Friday's meeting in the Old Senate Chamber.
``We conveyed the sense of the Republican caucus, and the joint
caucus, that a large number of witnesses were not going to be
permitted,'' Specter said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Specter said the senators were careful not to advise the House
managers on which witnesses to call. But Specter said that
witnesses who could help resolve conflicting testimony or who were
``important in tenor and tone'' stood the best chance of winning
majority support.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the House managers confirmed that meetings had
taken place, but said that senators had benefited more than the
House managers from the talks.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of opening arguments in the trial, the maneuvering
over witnesses coincided with an implicit threat in the White House
legal brief filed Wednesday, in which Clinton's lawyers argued that
any witnesses would require a lengthy full discovery process and
perhaps the calling of additional witnesses by the defense team.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and the White House have balked at any suggestion that
senators need to hear from witnesses like Ms. Lewinsky, partly
because of the fear that the trial would spin out of control with
unpredictable testimony and a desire to wrap up the proceedings
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   But evidence of the House managers' adamant intention to try to
persuade at least 51 senators to approve deposing a list of
witnesses surfaced again Wednesday. Hyde's aides disclosed that Ms.
Lewinsky's lawyer, Plato Cacheris, had refused a request from one
of the House managers to set up an informal meeting with the former
White House intern to question her and gauge her credibility.
``Implicit in the House's rights to request witnesses is the
responsibility of the managers to determine who those witnesses
will be,'' said Paul J. McNulty, a spokesman for the House
Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans paraded out of an afternoon meeting Wednesday
insisting that over the next few weeks, they could do legislative
business in the mornings and the impeachment trial in the
afternoons.
</P>
<P>
   When asked how the usually deliberative Senate could pull off
such a feat, Sen. Connie Mack of Florida, a member of the
Republican leadership, borrowed an explanation often attributed to
Clinton's ability to juggle several complicated subjects
simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a phrase we didn't use very often around here,'' Mack
said. ``It is compartmentalization.''
</P>
<P>
   But Senate Democrats voiced fears that a lengthy trial with many
witnesses would hinder regular Senate business. ``The key question
is the number of witnesses,'' said Sen. Joseph I. Lieberman,
D-Conn. ``If there are not too many witnesses, it won't take too
long to depose them. My guess is that we're done by sometime early
to mid-February.''
</P>
<P>
   But if many witnesses are called, Lieberman said, the trial
could extend into March.
</P>
<P>
   A main goal of the House managers will to be persuade at least
51 senators to approve deposing a list of witnesses, and after
their depositions are taken, allow them to testify in the actual
trial.
</P>
<P>
   The House managers have talked about summoning about six
witnesses, including Ms. Lewinsky, Betty Currie, the president's
secretary, and John Podesta, the White House chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, two of the managers, Reps. Asa Hutchinson of Arkansas
and Lindsey Graham of South Carolina, met with Kathleen Willey, a
former White House volunteer, and her lawyer, Dan Gecker, to
discuss the possibility of her appearing as a witness, said a
Republican aide and another person familiar with the case.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers, meeting in the office of a third manager, Rep.
James E. Rogan of California, spoke about an allegation that
Clinton groped Ms. Willey, but they focused mainly on whether Ms.
Willey was pressured to change her story. The House prosecutors are
interested in Ms. Willey's case to bolster the obstruction of
justice charge.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the managers' case is the charge that Clinton
offered a cleverly worded lie about his relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky and then schemed to cover up the affair.
</P>
<P>
   The House managers filed their trial brief on Monday, a 105-page
document that provides a road map of their case. The managers are
seeking to persuade senators that a chain of events, read in its
entirety, demonstrates a compelling argument for the president's
ouster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we'll come in with a long list of witnesses,''
Hyde said Wednesday night on ABC News' ``Nightline.'' ``It is my
expectation and request to our managers that they not call a
witness unless the witness has something substantive to
contribute.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said the managers were walking a fine line in their
presentation to senators. ``I hope we don't bore them,'' he said,
``but the more detailed information we give them, the less they
want to call witnesses.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
