<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGSNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUC SNUB LEAVES KINGS SORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Los Angeles Kings coach Larry Robinson didn't mince words.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the All-Star snub of left wing Luc Robitaille,
Robinson admitted to extreme disappointment Wednesday at the
omission of the NHL's third-leading goal scorer from the North
American roster that will face the World team on Jan. 24 in Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very surprised,'' said Robinson, whose team plays the
Calgary Flames at 7:30 tonight at the Forum. ``I was more surprised
when I saw who's on. I'm not saying (Montreal's) Mark Recchi is not
a great hockey player. But he's having a horse(bleep) year. The
All-Star Game is not about what you did. It's about what you're
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille has 22 goals and 40 points this season, along with a
plus-4 defensive rating. Recchi, with eight goals and 29 points and
a minus-10 rating, is the only Canadien in the game. The only King
chosen was defenseman Rob Blake.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't give me the line that every team has to be
represented,'' Robinson said. ``In that case, why weren't we
represented last year? I think it's unfair. (General Manager Dave
Taylor) and I have been saying all along we don't get any respect
on the West Coast. Blakey's winning of the Norris Trophy (last
season) was the first recognition we've gotten out here in a long,
long, long time. It's the forgotten land.''
</P>
<P>
   Departed friend: Robinson was in a reflective mood Wednesday,
the day after former Montreal Canadiens teammate Doug Wickenheiser
died after a long battle with cancer at 37. Robinson was in his
ninth season when the Canadiens selected Wickenheiser first overall
in the 1980 draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was between Wick and Denis Savard as to who Montreal would
pick first overall,'' Robinson recalled. ``Wick came to Montreal
and Denis went on to set a million records in Chicago. It was
always a sore spot in Montreal because Wick never had the impact
Denis did.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very sad day. Life's not fair sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray pained: Glen Murray's right knee was feeling good - maybe
too good. Now, it's not feeling very good at all.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor called Murray ``an impatient patient,'' and that
impatience has caught up with the Kings' best all-around winger,
who has experienced pain and swelling in his right knee in recent
days, forcing him to curtail workouts. Murray tore the medial
collateral ligament in his knee 12 days ago and is expected to miss
at least another six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was feeling great,'' said Murray, the Kings' second-leading
scorer. ``But the last couple of days have been awful. I worked out
too hard, riding the bike and lifting weights. It was stupid. I've
got to lay off it. I was feeling great, I wasn't feeling sore when
I was working out. I thought I'd be back in a couple of weeks. I
thought wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray said he does not think his current setback will delay his
return to the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Loose pucks: Defenseman Doug Bodger is expected back in the
lineup tonight after missing six games with a cervical strain after
being blind-sided two weeks ago by Dallas Drake of Phoenix. ...
Jamie Storr, who has a bruised left hand, is expected to start in
goal tonight, with Stephane Fiset as the backup. Fiset experienced
soreness in his groin following Monday's 4-0 loss at San Jose, but
the Kings are downplaying the seriousness of the situation, even
though their No. 1 goalie has battled groin injuries all season.
... Winger Russ Courtnall, who suffered a broken foot when struck
by a puck eight weeks ago, remains a couple of weeks from returning
to the lineup. Courtnall admitted the rehabilitation routine is
wearing thin. ``I can lift weights and ride the bike with
anybody,'' he said. Courtnall is scheduled to be X-rayed today. ...
Minor-league goalie Ryan Bach, sidelined six weeks with an
abdominal strain, is about a week from returning to action for Long
Beach and worked out with the Kings on Wednesday because the Ice
Dogs are on the road.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
