</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS IN BOTH PARTIES WEIGH COMPROMISE PLANS TO REVAMP SOCIAL
SECURITY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD W. STEVENSON c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the first time since President Clinton put
Social Security's financial problems at the top of the national
agenda, key members of both parties are seriously examining
compromise proposals that could be acceptable both to Democrats who
want to keep the retirement system intact and to Republicans
pushing for a shift to private investment accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals center on investment accounts that would
supplement Social Security rather than replace part of it. In the
versions that are getting the most attention, the accounts would be
voluntary but would carry incentives, in the form of matching
government contributions or tax breaks, to encourage people to
save.
</P>
<P>
   Such plans would also have to include some combination of tax
increases and benefit cuts to deal with Social Security's looming
financial shortfall, although some would seek to solve most of the
problem by allowing the government to invest Social Security's
excess cash in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals would basically leave the current Social Security
system intact, in an effort to make the outcome palatable to
liberals, while giving supporters of individualized investment a
limited form of the private accounts they are seeking.
</P>
<P>
   The effort to find a middle ground is at an early stage, and
neither the White House nor the Republican leadership is openly
supporting any particular compromise. Many of the ideas are in
sketchy form, and the degree of support they attract could depend
in great degree on arcane details.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials have discussed one variant of the
voluntary account approach with House Democrats, who say they are
open to the idea. A moderate Democrat in the House who has worked
across the aisle on a number of contentious issues, Rep. Benjamin
L. Cardin of Maryland, said he is drafting a similar plan and has
gotten encouraging responses from Republicans with whom he has
consulted.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Sperling, the White House economic adviser, declined to
discuss details of the plans the administration is weighing. But he
said Wednesday that Clinton would work closely with members of
Congress in the next few months so he can develop ``a strong sense
of where the basis for support and ultimately bipartisan consensus
can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some of the strongest backers of private investment
accounts said they are open to a deal built around voluntary
accounts, although they cautioned that much would depend on the
details.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most we can hope for as reformers is a very small
incremental set of changes, given the political environment we're
in,'' said Rep. Mark Sanford, a Republican from South Carolina who
is an aggressive advocate of private accounts. ``With that in mind
I look more favorably on the idea of tax-incentivized savings.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. William V. Roth Jr., the Delaware Republican who is
chairman of the Finance Committee, is pushing another approach
built around individual accounts into which the government would
make contributions for the next five years using half of the
federal budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Under Roth's approach, the accounts would not technically be
part of the Social Security system. But Roth said his plan provides
``a means of moving ahead on a matter that has a direct relation to
Social Security,'' and seems to be similar to ideas being
considered by the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hopeful that we're seeing the beginning of a consensus
that could be very helpful,'' Roth said.
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans, however, said they would continue to push for
a fundamental overhaul of Social Security under which mandatory
private accounts would be financed out of the 12.4 percent payroll
tax assessed on workers and their employers.
</P>
<P>
   Members of both parties said the real question is whether both
sides will determine that they are better off reaching a deal now
on Social Security rather than leaving the issue on the table for
use as a political weapon in the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has made clear he favors seeking higher
investment returns in some way to help cover a financial gap that
will leave Social Security unable to pay all beneficiaries fully
starting in 2032. So far he has deflected pressure from Republicans
who want him to put a specific plan on the table.
</P>
<P>
   But his advisers have broached a number of possibilities in
recent weeks, including a plan under which retirement accounts
would be set up outside of Social Security as a way of reassuring
liberal Democrats that reform need not involve dismantling the
guaranteed benefit system.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, contributions by workers would be matched by the
government in the same way that employers match contributions to
401(k) plans, and could be set up to give the greatest incentives
to low and moderate income workers.
</P>
<P>
   Cardin's plan would establish voluntary accounts within the
Social Security system. The government would give a tax rebate or
make a direct payment into accounts to workers up to a certain
income level, probably about $40,000, Cardin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
