<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE WAS BETTER THAN ADVERTISED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's an observation you probably haven't digested before:
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan was underrated.
</P>
<P>
   We'll pause while a loved one unleashes the Heimlich on you and
your morning bagel. All clear? Good, those sesame seeds can be
murder.
</P>
<P>
   Back to business. Jordan ... underrated? Whew.
</P>
<P>
   But this is serious. Not to mention first-glance preposterous.
After all, aren't even the most pedestrian hoop citizens convinced
that MJ could take God to the rack without the aid of a pick?
Absolutely.
</P>
<P>
   And isn't ESPN beaming out separate Jordan highlight loops,
categorically filed as ``Right-handed Poster Dunks,'' ``Two-Handed
Face Jams'' and ``Dirty Daggers Jabbed Into The Hearts Of Teams
Located In Cities Whose Names Begin With The Letter C''? Yeah,
that's hour one. Hour two is ``Cold-Blooded, Series-Ending
Jumpers.''
</P>
<P>
   Columnists spent much of Tuesday clawing toward poetic salvation
to define Jordan's status as the greatest basketball player in the
history of basketball players.
</P>
<P>
   We're wondering if they really were aware of what they had been
witnessing.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was so much more than cobra-strike dunks and
double-clutch smooches off the glass.
</P>
<P>
   He was the superstar who made Bulls fans believe his coach, Phil
Jackson, was a New Age genius who could walk on bong water.
</P>
<P>
   He was the visiting icon who inspired fans to boo the home team.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was the defender who stalked the opposing squad's
offensive sharpie and sent him to the hoosegow without chance of
parole.
</P>
<P>
   He was the Bull who would set a bitterly effective and nearly
legal screen, using his mitts to discreetly hold up the opponent
with a subtlety that could make Tony Boselli weep.
</P>
<P>
   He was the offensive rebounder handing out ulcers when a
teammate prepared to launch a free throw that had the potential to
chip paint off the rim.
</P>
<P>
   Could the man pass? Well, Jordan could drop a dime on the
offensively challenged Dennis Rodman and get an answer on the first
ring.
</P>
<P>
   Competitive? Looking like a casting mistake from George Romero's
``Dawn Of The Dead,'' he starred in ``One Flu Over The Delta
Center'' during the NBA Finals of 1997. After providing the
game-clinching jump shot, he had to be carried to the bench by
Scottie Pippen, who was more than glad to finally return the favor.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was the one who coaxed six championships from teams that
weren't afforded the requisite luxuries of point guard and center.
The alleged point guards were John Paxson and Ron Harper, two solid
Chicago heroes who couldn't create a shot for Jordan in a Nintendo
scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   The centers were Bill Cartwright and Luc Longley. Don't ask.
</P>
<P>
   Fundamentally sound? His footwork was worth a measure of
hyperbole that includes references to Gregory Hines and an alley
cat.
</P>
<P>
   Visibility? Thanks to Jordan, little kids know Ahmad Rashad is
more than just the real-life husband of Claire Huxtable.
</P>
<P>
   He may not have been the best shooter, or passer, or dunker or
rebounder in NBA history. But he could be all of those including
the best perimeter defender of all-time on the very next play.
</P>
<P>
   Will there ever be another Michael Jordan? Yeah. Plays for Penn
in the Ivy League. Check it out; Michael Jordan. That's as close as
it'll get.
</P>
<P>
   I once asked Michael Jordan, the retired one, if he could guard
himself. Wow. Deep.
</P>
<P>
   His response was a look that exposed me as someone who was
stark, raving mad.
</P>
<P>
   See, above and beyond everything else that defined basketball
player Michael Jordan, he also was painfully wise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
