<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2072 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-BARR14-COX     01-13 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-BARR14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barr's part in history
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ From his desk, Rep. Bob Barr gazes at an etching on
the wall that depicts a scene from the last impeachment trial of a
president 131 years ago, and heaves a deep sigh.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, when Barr stumbled across the Harper's Weekly image
from the 1868 trial of President Andrew Johnson, he hardly could
have imagined that one day hewould take part in the trial of a
president.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Republican is one of 13 House impeachment managers
who will present the case against President Clinton beginning
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``My eyes are frequently drawn to that picture,'' said Barr, who
notes that the etching has been hanging in his office since he came
to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am about to participate in only the second impeachment trial
in our history,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly brings the weight of history down on my
shoulders, and I think ahead 130 years from now, will people look
at the pictures that will be taken of our presentations and wonder
what it was like? Hopefully they will look back on history and
agree that we did a very credible and appropriate job.''
</P>
<P>
   The House Republican leadership appears to approve of Barr's job
so far. On the eve of the impeachment hearings, Majority Whip Tom
DeLay (R-Texas) rewarded Barr by naming him one of several dozen
assistant whips to help him gather votes to pass legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am deeply honored that Tom DeLay, one of the most effective
and courageous legislators in Congress, has chosen to appoint me,''
said Barr.
</P>
<P>
   But as Barr helps prepare the House case that attempts to prove
Clinton committed perjury and obstructed justice in concealing an
affair with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky, he finds his
own conduct being questioned.
</P>
<P>
   Barr has angered more than one senator with his sharp criticism
of the Senate for its reluctance to call witnesses to support the
House managers' case. At one point, he suggested that ``a senator's
attention span is probably less than an average juror's, so we'll
need to simplify, simplify, simplify.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came Hustler magazine publisher Larry Flynt with his
rapid-fire accusations that Barr is a hypocritical critic of the
president because the legislator invoked a state law similar to the
Fifth Amendment in refusing to answer questions on whether he had
an affair with Jerilyn Ann Dobbin, who is now his wife, while he
was married to his second wife, Gail Vogel Barr.
</P>
<P>
   Flynt also said Barr paid $300 for Gail Barr to have an abortion
in 1983 when they were still married, despite Barr's strongly held
views against abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Barr will not answer specific questions about whether he had an
affair with Dobbin before marrying her. However, he said, ``as an
officer of the court for over 20 years, I have never perjured
myself.'' As for the abortion, he says only that he never
``suggested, urged, forced, or encouraged anyone to have an
abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barr is not going underground in the wake of these
accusations; in fact, he appeared on CNN three times on Tuesday
night to deny Flynt's charges.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the controversy seems to have energized him. The
only pause he has taken since the Flynt episode was a trip to the
National Gallery on Monday afternoon to reflect on the expansive
panoramas of Albert Bierstadt.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can look and just sort of be drawn into them,'' Barr said.
``I think you get a good sense for the majesty of our country.''
</P>
<P>
   Given his reverence for nation, why is Barr so determined to
oust this president?
</P>
<P>
   ``Love for our country, for our Constitution and for our system
of holding public officials being accountable for their misdeeds in
office and abusing the public trust,'' said Barr, who successfully
prosecuted former Rep. Patrick Swindall, a fellow Georgia
Republican, for lying under oath to a grand jury in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Still the question persists: Why would Barr criticize Clinton
for his personal conduct when he knew there might be questions
asked about his own conduct?
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern with the president is not his own personal
behavior,'' Barr said. ``My concern with the president is his abuse
of office, obstruction of justice, perjury in his capacity of
president, (and) working to deny one of our citizens her day in
court.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has nothing to do with his personal behavior. It has
nothing to do with anyone's personal behavior. It has to do with
his capacity as president.''
</P>
<P>
   Barr sees the charges by Flynt as politically motivated, an
effort to deflect attention away from the White House by sullying
the reputation of a hard-working congressman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very distressing that this sort of thing goes on, but
that's the administration we are dealing with. One has to move on,
press on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Barr's role during the Senate trial will include crafting a
summary of legal precedents concerning perjury and obstruction of
justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be armed with plenty of precedents,'' the congressman
said. For example, Barr said, he has found precedent to bolster his
argument that a person, such as Lewinsky, does not have to be
directly asked to lie in order to obstruct justice.
</P>
<P>
   Barr believes that case law will support his notion that the
president used Lewinsky to obstruct justice even though Lewinsky
has testified under oath that no one ever asked her to lie and no
one ever promised her a job in exchange for silence about her
affair with the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to get too bogged down in detail that we lose
the forest from the trees,'' Barr said. ``But we want to show there
is legal and factual basis to convict the president of perjury and
obstruction of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican senators say they are not surprised by Barr's
criticisms. ``He's a very bright guy with a lot of experience in
trial law,'' said Sen. Orrin Hatch (R-Utah). ``He can't be ignored
but on the other hand he's got to make his case to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Coverdell (R-Ga.) noted it is Barr's nature to be
aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   And that is how Barr sees it, too. He has to go after those who
go after him, such as Flynt.
</P>
<P>
   ``One always has to put up with charges in the political arena
whenever you attempt to hold a public official accountable,'' he
said. ``Whether it's a member of Congress or a county commissioner,
one has to look at the (source) of those sort of attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   One way to tell if the attacks are inappropriate is to look at
the history of those involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I have a history,'' he said, ``a history of pursuing
misconduct whether it's Republican, Democrat, black or white.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
