<HEADER>
A2073 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-JURORS14-COX     01-13 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-JURORS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    100 jurors unite to judge Clinton
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ They are unlike any jury in U.S. justice.
Ninety-one men and nine women, 55 Republicans and 45 Democrats.
Together the 100 members of the Senate will decide the fate of
President Clinton in the only presidential impeachment trial of
this century.
</P>
<P>
   Sworn to do ``impartial justice,'' the men and women of the
Senate nonetheless arrive at their rendezvous with history with a
complicated overlay of competing political ambitions and personal
biases.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, each will have only one vote in determining whether
Clinton should be impeached, but there are a few dozen senators to
pay close attention to as the trial gets under way Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Majority Leader Trent Lott
</P>
<P>
   Famous among his colleagues for his obsession with smooth
scheduling, Mississippi Republican Lott has the trial's most
difficult balancing act.
</P>
<P>
   Under normal Senate rules, the majority party can block
legislation, or filibuster, with only 40 votes. Under impeachment
trial rules, however, any motion is adopted by simple majority.
</P>
<P>
   Holding together 51 senators on procedural votes will be Lott's
toughest challenge. Democrats need only six Republicans to say
they've had enough of the trial and move to adjourn the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Byrd
</P>
<P>
   Byrd, the 81-year-old former Democratic majority leader and
author of a four-volume history of the Senate, is entering his 40th
year in the Senate. The West Virginian is keenly respected in both
parties both because of his longevity and his intimate knowledge of
Senate history and tradition. It was Byrd who set the tone last
week when Democrats and Republicans brokered a bipartisan beginning
to the trial, exhorting his colleagues to lance ``this boil in an
honorable and orderly way.''
</P>
<P>
   Look for Byrd to make many of the procedural motions on how the
trial should be conducted. It will be difficult for most other
senators to vote the other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever he has to, he rises to the occasion,'' said Sen. Pete
Domenici (R-N.M.). ``He does so without partisanship. He cares
about the Senate more than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   The Northeast moderates
</P>
<P>
   A handful of Republican moderates from the Northeast may hold
the key to how hard the Senate pushes to impeach Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In this group, the players to watch are Sens. John Chafee, whose
home state of Rhode Island is among the most Democratic in the
country; Jim Jeffords (R-Vt.), who said this week he wants the
trial to end ``as soon as possible''; and Sen. Olympia Snowe
(R-Maine), who was part of a bipartisan group of senators searching
for trial ground rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (Chafee) starts getting antsy about the length of the
trial, he'll make it known it could have an impact on other
moderates from the Northeast,'' said Ed Gillespie, a Republican
strategist.
</P>
<P>
   Two others would normally vote with the Northeast moderates on
most issues, but so far have taken a tough line against the
president: Susan Collins (R-Maine), who was one of Clinton's
harshest critics during the Senate campaign finance hearings, and
Arlen Specter (R-Pa.), a former federal prosecutor and member of
the Senate Judiciary Committee who has demanded a full-scale Senate
trial.
</P>
<P>
   The Western senators
</P>
<P>
   While Republican moderates from the Northeast form the smallest
grouping within the Senate Republican Party, conservatives from the
West and South form the heart and, in most respects, its governing
soul.
</P>
<P>
   This group of conservative ideologues objected most strongly to
the bipartisan proposal floated and then abandoned by Lott to hold
an abbreviated trial.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Don Nickles (R-Okla.), the majority whip, is at the center
of this band of Western, conservative senators. Nickles is one of
the Senate's most outspoken critics of Clinton and draws his
political support from many conservative organizations that have
called for Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Other strong conservatives include Sen. James Inhofe (R-Okla.),
Sen. Phil Gramm (R-Texas), Sen. Sam Brownback (R-Kan.), Sen. Larry
Craig (R-Idaho), Sen. Conrad Burns (R-Mont.) and Sen. Chuck Hagel
(R-Neb.).
</P>
<P>
   Although these conservatives do not dictate the will of the
Republican conference, ``you can move away from them on either
side, but not too far away and not too fast,'' said Gillespie.
</P>
<P>
   The Class of 2000
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the year of the Republican revolution, voters in
Democratic-leaning states swept into office a handful of young
conservatives who are now up for re-election in 2000. They will be
under political pressure to moderate their rhetoric in the
impeachment debate.
</P>
<P>
   Most notable in this group is Sen. Rick Santorum (R-Pa.), who
led the Senate fight against late-term abortions and who has been a
scathing Clinton critic. Lately, however, Santorum has been much
more circumspect about his comments on Clinton and impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the most passionate reflection of the class of '94,''
said Kyle McSlarrow, former chief of staff to Sen. Paul Coverdell
(R-Ga.) and a former aide to senator Bob Dole. ``As Santorum goes,
so goes that class.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Republican senators up for re-election in 2000 who come
from Democratic-leaning states include Sen. Rod Grams (R-Minn.) and
Sen. Spencer Abraham (R-Mich.).
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, there are no Democrats who believe the
president's misconduct rises to the level of impeachment, according
to Sen. Tom Daschle (D-S.D.), the minority leader. Several
Democrats, however, have nonetheless been publicly critical of
Clinton and would be among the first to support a strong motion of
censure.
</P>
<P>
   These include Sens. Daniel Patrick Moynihan (D-N.Y.), Joseph
Lieberman (D-Conn.) and Bob Graham (D-Fla.). Lieberman was the
first Senate Democrat to condemn Clinton on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most politically vulnerable Democrat is Sen. Charles
Robb (D-Va.), who is up for re-election in 2000 and will face a
stiff Republican challenge from a state with strong conservative
leanings. Robb may be forced to toughen his position on the
president in the same way that Santorum and others are forced to
soften theirs.
</P>
<P>
   The president's strongest Democratic defenders are Sens. Richard
Durbin (D-Ill.), Bob Torricelli (D-N.J.) and Edward Kennedy
(D-Mass.).
</P>
<P>
   The deal-makers
</P>
<P>
   Should the Senate begin to negotiate an early end to the trial
or work out the terms of a censure agreement, look for Sen. Ted
Stevens (R-Alaska), Appropriations Committee Chairman, and Sen.
Orrin Hatch (R-Utah), chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee,
to play key roles.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Biden (D-Del.), who has spoken repeatedly of the
need for bipartisanship in the Senate trial, will be one of the key
Democratic players in any compromise, along with Sen. Carl Levin
(D-Mich.) and Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   Any deal also will have to enjoy the blessings of Lott and
Daschle.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
