u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TV14-COX     01-13 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TV14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Deliberations have appeal of wreck you rubberneck
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You'll watch.
</P>
<P>
   You say you won't, but chances are you will. You've told
pollsters you think there shouldn't even be an impeachment trial
(84 percent, Time/CNN poll), that you want the trial to end
immediately (59 percent), that events in Congress are out of
control (74 percent).
</P>
<P>
   But you'll watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know from listening to traffic reports the thing that
slows traffic down is rubbernecking; you're in a hurry, yet you see
this incredible sight and can't help but turn your neck that way,''
Bill Moody, news vice president at Fox News Channel, says of the
contradiction between public fatigue with the Clinton story and the
story's high viewership levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all on the highway of impeachment; we're on Im-
peachment Road. Even though our spiritual souls are sickened by
this stuff, we are oddly and grotesquely interested in it.''
</P>
<P>
   You'll watch. You've watched all along. In 1998, live stories
and specials on CNN that dealt with the Clinton scandal averaged
three times more viewers than usually watched CNN. The network's
two highest-rated programs last year were scandal-related:
Clinton's Aug. 17 address to the nation after his grand jury
testimony (5.4 million households, 10th most watched event ever on
CNN, excluding 1991's Gulf War coverage) and Clinton's Dec. 19
address after Congress voted to impeach him (5.3 million
households).
</P>
<P>
   CNBC's prime time ratings rose 75 percent in 1998, mostly
powered by the all-Clinton scandal coverage on ``Hardball with
Chris Mathews,'' whose '98 viewership more than doubled.
</P>
<P>
   All this despite a Pew Research Center poll that found only 36
percent of you have followed the Clinton/Lewinsky investigation
closely _ 3 percent fewer than followed stories of ``unseasonable
weather.''
</P>
<P>
   And the more distasteful it gets, the more you dislike it and
the more you watch. Porn publisher Larry Flynt's appearance Monday
on CNBC's ``Rivera Live'' was the highest-rated ``Rivera'' (1.2
million households) since coverage of O.J. Simpson's civil trial
verdict almost two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   You have your limits, however: On Dec. 19, CBS was the only
network not to televise the first House of Representatives vote to
impeach a president in 130 years. Instead, CBS televised a pro
football game, and got the day's highest ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody's sure how many of you will watch this story's endgame,
beginning this afternoon; despite the Senate trial's historic
tonnage, its decorum could make it less visually dramatic than
other high-profile trials and hearings (Simpson, Anita Hill). Much
depends on whether witnesses are called, which ones, and whether TV
can show the deliberations, which it is now prohibited from doing
(the networks have petitioned the Senate to amend that rule).
</P>
<P>
   ``Levels will be very high, but it's hard to say how high,'' CNN
spokesman Howard Polskin says. ``We're in such unknown territory.
''
</P>
<P>
   ``Watching evidence being presented to 100 impartial jurors and
one chief justice is not the same as a pie-throwing contest,'' says
Moody, adding, ``But it's wrong to compare shock values; there have
been other hearings, but there has never been this. Maybe that
helps explain the apparent contradiction (between the public's
Clinton scandal weariness and high viewership).
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, (people) are tired of the thong and the cigar and seedy
parts of this drama. But they are also Americans with a sense of
their own country's history being written, and they can be live
spectators.''
</P>
<P>
   You'll watch.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
