 &HT;    Where to watch for impeachment trial coverage
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The drill for TV coverage is virtually the same for
today's Senate impeachment trial as it was for the House
impeachment hearings.
</P>
<P>
   The all-news networks, as well as C-SPAN II and at least one
local PBS station, plan continuous, gavel-to-gavel coverage. The
broadcast networks plan to air the trial's opening statement, cut
away afterward to regular programming, then break in as events
warrant today and the days that follow. All plans are subject to
change in the trial's schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Here is today's scheduled rundown:
</P>
<P>
   _ CNN: Continuous coverage
</P>
<P>
   _ C-SPAN II: Continuous coverage
</P>
<P>
   _ MSNBC: Continuous coverage
</P>
<P>
   _ WPBA and WGTV (public TV): Continuous coverage
</P>
<P>
   _ Fox News: Continuous coverage
</P>
<P>
   _ Court TV: Coverage 1-9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ ABC: Trial's 1 p.m. start, then rejoin as events warrant.
</P>
<P>
   _ CBS: Trial's 1 p.m. start, then rejoin as events warrant.
</P>
<P>
   _ NBC: Trial's 1 p.m. start, then rejoin as events warrant.
</P>
