<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2079 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     01-13 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEAGUE IS LEFT GASPING FOR AIR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   That sucking sound you hear is all of the Air being drained out
of the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   A league that recently celebrated its 50th birthday with a
series of parties suddenly feels much older. It feels older than
Chick Hearn. It feels paralyzed. Its mind is seriously confused,
unable to remember where it's been and absolutely petrified about
where it's going.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan left opponents with those kind of feelings
throughout his career, so it's poignant that his decision to retire
now leaves the entire league gasping.
</P>
<P>
   This was going to happen eventually, so the NBA certainly can't
say it didn't have time to prepare. Every one of Jordan's road
games last season was billboarded as potentially his last visit to
(fill in the city).
</P>
<P>
   NBC promoted every ``last'' Jordan moment there was down the
stretch a season ago his last regular season game, his last playoff
game against Indiana, his last game in Chicago, his last game with
Spike Lee courtside, on down to his last penetrating, insightful
interview with Ahmad Rashad.
</P>
<P>
   Now that MJ-Day is here, the NBA will have to take stock of
what's left and find a way to move on. It's not going to enjoy the
trip.
</P>
<P>
   Take Jordan away from the game and seriously study the league's
growth and you come away numb by exactly what he has meant to the
league, not to mention television and sneakers.
</P>
<P>
   During the 50th anniversary celebrations, the league got warm
and fuzzy about the league's early years, the 950s and 1960s, when
first George Mikan and then the Celtics were the headliners. It was
safe to do, in large part because there were few people around who
actually remembers those eras.
</P>
<P>
   For example: In 1969, the year the Celtics won their 11th title
in a 13-year span, the league's average attendance was 6,484 per
game.
</P>
<P>
   Think about that. The Celtics were as dominant in basketball as
the Yankees in baseball and the Canadiens in hockey. Their
opponents at the time featured Hall of Famers like Jerry West, Wilt
Chamberlain, Elgin Baylor, Earl Monroe, Oscar Robertson, Jerry
Lucas, Willis Reed, Walt Frazier, Lenny Wilkens and Nate Thurmond.
</P>
<P>
   And the average was 6,484. There are WNBA teams which consider
6,484 a bad crowd.
</P>
<P>
   NBA box office grew slowly the next seven years as it expanded
to 18 teams, then hit a plateau of around 10,000 a game in the late
'70s. Then, in the 1979-80 season, Larry Bird and Magic Johnson
arrived from the college ranks, put a smile on the game and gave
the sport its first real burst of energy since the Celtic era.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers and Celtics won eight of nine NBA titles between
1979-80 and 1987-88, and their battles are treasured as the most
memorable and aesthetic in league history. This was the NBA at its
absolute best.
</P>
<P>
   But here's what is so odd: while Bird and Magic are credited as
the league's saviors, they did not impact league-wide attendance.
The league's average per game stayed flat from 1975-76 to 1983-84.
The high during those nine years was 11,017 in Magic and Bird's
rookie year. The low was 10,021 in 1980-81.
</P>
<P>
   The league really did not gather its momentum until the late
'80s after Bird and Magic had won their last titles when Jordan
fully emerged as the best player the game has ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, the year he won his first scoring title, the league
average went up to 12,795 per game. In 1988, the first year the
Bulls and Jordan had a winning season, it jumped to 13,419.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, the league average attendance for 25 clubs passed
15,000 (15,088), and it hasn't looked back since. The league has
drawn 21 million fans each of the last three seasons, an average of
more than 17,000 per game, all coinciding with the second of
Jordan's pair of three-peats.
</P>
<P>
   All this doesn't even begin to detail what Jordan has meant as a
TV vehicle, either. The NBA's Nielsen ratings during the '90s
dominate the all-time list. The Magic/Bird-to-Jordan era spotlights
one revealing note: The league didn't televise every game of its
finals live until 1981.
</P>
<P>
   The league is not going to drown without Jordan as its captain.
The league has grown to 29 cities, and most of them are sound. Only
four of 29 teams last season averaged under 14,000 fans a game
Dallas, Golden State, Denver and our erstwhile Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   The new labor agreement David Stern just stuffed down the
union's throat will not leave any player feeling like a pauper, but
it will cap salaries and potentially engender warm feelings from
fans fed up with athlete earnings.
</P>
<P>
   But just as clearly, there is no one to replace Jordan in any
respect. There's no one out there capable of leading his team to
six NBA titles, no one capable of drawing fans to a television set,
no one who can move as smoothly both on- and off-court.
</P>
<P>
   Grant Hill? Great person. Capable of leading his team to a
title. On-court dynamic? He doesn't have one.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant? Great kid. Anxious to fill any shoes Jordan or
anyone else leaves behind. He may be the only player capable of
having the same on-court dynamic. Drawback? He's 20. It took Jordan
five years in the league to become the player that people remember
today, and he was 26.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal? He's capable of being a leader; after all, he
grew up the son of a Marine. But Shaq is having too much fun to get
serious about what it means to be a Magic- or Jordan-like figure.
Jordan played golf to relax. Shaq raps and acts. He's a cross-over
stud, but that doesn't play when the games begin.
</P>
<P>
   The scarier thing is to look at the names of prominent NBA
players now and find an easy connection to the league in the late
'70s, pre-Bird and Magic.
</P>
<P>
   The league title those seasons rotated around to a handful of
non-descript teams, like Golden State (1975), Portland (1977),
Washington (1978) and Seattle (1979). At the same time, the league
was flush with prominent characters who would have fit in a Hunter
S. Thompson novella free spirit Bill Walton, Marvin ``Bad News''
Barnes, Artis Gilmore, David Thompson, World B. Free, Spencer
Haywood and Connie Hawkins. Tales of NBA life in the late '70s
focused as much on drug use as they did basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Well, 1999 sans-Jordan has a similar look. Charles Barkley,
Patrick Ewing and Karl Malone are graybeards. Shawn Kemp, Kevin
Garnett and Juwan Howard represent those rich before their time.
Chris Webber, Allen Iverson and Latrell Sprewell provide elements
darker than those of the class of '79.
</P>
<P>
   And there's more paternity in the NBA than there is fraternity.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA will move on without him, but please forgive the league
if it chokes back the tears every week or so in the process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
