<SLUG> BC-GINGRICH-DISTRICT14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    6th District race draws candidates from other areas
 &HT;    By Steve Visser
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The race to replace Newt Gingrich drew two more
candidates Wednesday, neither of whom live in the 6th Congressional
District.
</P>
<P>
   Christina Jeffrey, 51, can claim a close affiliation with the
district that covers much of the north Atlanta suburbs. She teaches
at Kennesaw State University, although she went on unpaid leave
this week to campaign. She lives in Bartow County.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Clennon King Jr., 78, who also paid $4,101 to qualify,
hails from Dougherty County in South Georgia. In 1976, the
African-American minister applied for membership in
then-President-elect Jimmy Carter's segregated church, Plains
Baptist. A split in the congregation resulted.
</P>
<P>
   King has just moved back to Albany from Miami where he lived for
years, according to a friend, Lois Jones. King asked her to take
calls for him at her home, Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a Georgia boy ...but he's been in Miami a good while,''
Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   The only residency requirement in a congressional race is that
the candidate be an inhabitant of the state when elected.
</P>
<P>
   Today is the last day to become a candidate in the nonpartisan
race. Johnny Isakson of Marietta, who is also the state school
board chairman, and Leigh Baier of Vinings qualified for the race
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Other potential candidates are John Frank Collins, a Republican
who lost the race for labor commissioner last year; Bruce Hatfield,
a Republican; Bruce Doublestein, a Gwinnett County GOP leader;
Democrat Tony Center; and Democrat Gary ``Bats'' Pelphrey, who lost
to Gingrich in November.
</P>
<P>
   The election will be held Feb. 23, but the last day for voters
to register is Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
