<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2083 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      01-13 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS FALL IN RESPONSE TO BRAZIL'S CURRENCY DEVALUATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: BRAZIL-RDP, BRAZIL-IMPACT, BRAZIL-HISTORY BRAZIL-BONDS,
BRAZIL-U.S., BRAZIL-LATIN) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ World stock markets shuddered on Wednesday in
response to another dose of emerging market turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's plan to effectively devalue its currency initially
deflated the confidence of stock investors in the United States and
abroad. But after a sharp selloff in the first half-hour of
trading, American stock prices rebounded steadily throughout the
day.
</P>
<P>
   As the morning light seeped into the canyons of Wall Street,
indications were that stocks would take a huge hit. Some market
analysts predicted losses of up to 400 points off the Dow Jones
industrial average. In early trading, the prices of financial
futures dropped as far as regulators allowed, and when equity
trading started at 9:30 a.m. everything appeared bleak. The Dow
dropped more than 250 points, or nearly 3 percent, in the first 30
minutes, and the Nasdaq composite index fell 114 points, almost 5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as quickly as it came, the calamity was past. Recalling
that previous plunges spurred by foreign currency crises _ in Asia
in 1997 and in Russia last summer _ turned out to be significant
buying opportunities in U.S. stocks, investors dove in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once again, the mentality is to buy the dips,'' said Byron
Wien, chief U.S. investment strategist at Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter. ``When it looked like this was not the beginning of a bear
market, people saw that Yahoo was down 70 points and decided to
take advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreign markets did not fare as well. European markets, which
fell sharply as Brazil unveiled its plan to loosen the trading
range for its currency, the real, were closed by the time the
Brazilian Congress adopted reform measures that to American
investors looked promising.
</P>
<P>
   While investors in the United States shunned shares of auto
makers, heavy equipment companies and banks that have business
links to Brazil, they snapped up stocks like Intel, Microsoft and
Sun Microsystems, whose earnings are not expected to be disrupted.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average finished the day down 125.12
points, or 1.3 percent, at 9351.10. Other American indexes recorded
smaller losses, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up more
than 8 points at one point. It finished the day down 5.11 at
1234.40.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think U.S. investors saw Brazil's actions as inevitable, and
now that it's behind us we can move forward,'' Wien said. ``Markets
have a funny way of reacting positively to reality once they think
it through.''
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo, which ended the day down 34, at 368, has no operations in
Brazil, but the stocks of companies that do finished mostly lower
on Wednesday. Shares of Ford, General Motors and DaimlerChrysler
each fell by about 2 percent, while Caterpillar, the equipment
maker, International Paper and Coca-Cola shares also fell.
</P>
<P>
   Banking stocks suffered even more, as investors' recalled that
the last Latin American debt crisis caused longlasting problems for
money-center banks. J.P. Morgan's shares fell by 5 percent,
Citigroup declined 6 percent and American Express slumped nearly 4
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, investment analysts and portfolio managers said that
while they expect neither an extended nor a deep downturn from
Brazil's crisis, much uncertainty remains about that country's
fiscal plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is not the last adjustment that we will see to
the currency regime in Brazil,'' said Thomas Haslett, chief
investment officer for emerging market equities at Putnam
Investments, the mutual fund company. He noted, though, that
foreign companies doing business there have had plenty of warning
to hedge against a currency decline.
</P>
<P>
   Less certain is the spillover effect that Brazil's problems will
have on other markets in Latin America, Europe and the Far East.
Stock markets in those regions fell sharply on Wednesday, although
they could stabilize on Thursday in light of Wednesday's rebound in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM CAN START HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's Bovespa stock market index fell 5 percent, with shares
of the 12 companies created by the breakup of Telebras, the giant
telecommunications concern, being among the market's biggest
losers. Four of the largest Telebras spinoffs operate with pricing
discretion that could offer them some protection from the inflation
that is now expected to rise in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's Bolsa index fell 4.6 percent, and the Argentina general
index tumbled 10 percent. Investors are likely to be closely
watching Argentina and Mexico, two of the region's other largest
economies, for signs of weakness in light of Brazil's problems.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the uncertainty, Latin America is going to have a
higher cost of capital,'' said Haslett. ``A relatively small amount
of support should be able to carry Argentina through 1999.'' And
Mexico should benefit from a continued strong economy in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, stock prices fell sharply, 3 percent in Britain and 4
percent in Germany. The region's economy has already suffered from
slowing exports to Asia and Eastern Europe, and could feel a
further pinch from Brazil's trouble. Volkswagen, for example, is
among the biggest car producers in Brazil. Spanish banks have also
lent heavily in Brazil, which led investors to push Spanish stock
prices down nearly 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices also fell in Asia, although those losses came well
before Brazil unveiled its currency plans. Hong Kong stock prices
fell by 4 percent, while Japan ended slightly higher on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Asian currency crisis of 1997 or last year's economic
emergency in Russia, the current situation in Brazil carries more
importance for American investors. Brazil dominates the economies
of South America, accounting for 40 percent of the continent's
output. And investors can watch the effects of the crisis unfold in
real time.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Asian currency crisis began in the summer of 1997,
financial analysts have postulated that Brazil _ which like
Thailand, Indonesia and other emerging market countries had pegged
the value of its currency to the American dollar _ might come under
pressure to devalue the real.
</P>
<P>
   That concern was tempered somewhat by the International Monetary
Fund's move in November to put together a ``precautionary'' loan
package totaling $41 billion. The IMF has been criticized for
responding too slowly in Asia and for attaching overly harsh
austerity conditions to its loans there.
</P>
<P>
   Now Brazil could benefit from what has been learned elsewhere.
``There is a very strong possibility that this will be one of the
turning points,'' said David Herro, manager of the Oakmark
International fund, a $800 million fund that has about 9 percent of
its assets invested in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the fund had hedged most of its holdings against
losses caused by currency declines and that he was adding to some
of those positions during the day's weakness.
</P>
<P>
   Herro also dismissed parallels between Brazil's woes and last
year's turmoil in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brazil is free-market oriented and is run by some smart
people,'' Herro said. ``And unlike Mexico's crisis in 1994, Brazil
has no problem with short-term debt or its currency reserves.''
</P>
<P>
   When emerging markets recover from currency problems, they tend
to do so quickly. Witness some of the Asian emerging markets, which
soared last year after falling sharply in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM CAN END HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the reaction of American investors, the crisis in
Brazil appeared to be over almost before it started. Some stocks
rose from Wednesday's opening bell: Ascend Communications, for
example, gained 5] to 80 5/16 after Lucent Technologies agreed to
buy the company for $19.7 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Intel fell at the opening even though the company
reported fourth-quarter earnings late Tuesday that beat analysts'
estimates. Investors soon decided that the drop was unwarranted and
sent the shares up 3 7/16 to 139.
</P>
<P>
   Investors bid up several other technology stocks as well. Sun
Microsystems gained 3 7/16 to 96 13/16, and traded as high as 104{.
Microsoft, which started its defense in the ongoing federal
antitrust trial after losing a bid to get the charges dismissed,
rose 1| to 143 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   Technology shares closely related to the Internet finished
generally lower. Amazon.com fell 15] to 148; America Online lost 7~
to 145}; and E Trade dipped 8 1/16 to 92~.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
