<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.S.-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE CLASHES OVER NORTHERN IRAQ; U.S. WON'T RULE OUT PRE-EMPTIVE
STRIKES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IRAQ-U.N.) 
(ART ADV: Map-graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ American and Iraqi forces clashed in northern Iraq
for a third consecutive day Wednesday as Iraq's Vice President
vowed to defy American and British control of its skies ``with all
of our capabilities, regardless of the cost.''
</P>
<P>
   In what has become a pattern of cat-and-mouse confrontations,
American jets based in Turkey attacked five anti-aircraft and
surface-to-air-missile batteries in the northern no-flight zone
created by the United States and its allies in 1991 to protect
Iraq's Kurdish population, officials at the Pentagon said.
</P>
<P>
   For now administration and Pentagon officials said they would
continue to exchange fire with the Iraqi air defenses, but they did
not rule out launching more aggressive, pre-emptive strikes by the
United States and Britain against Iraqi forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a credible and robust threat of force in the region if
we determine that that needs to be used,'' the president's press
secretary, Joe Lockhart, said at the White House Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Islamic holy month of Ramadan, which administration
officials have acknowledged was a factor in the timing of last
month's American and British raids on Iraq, ends this weekend with
the arrival of the new moon.
</P>
<P>
   There are indications that Iraqi forces are deliberately drawing
fire, one defense official said, in an attempt to find weaknesses
in American tactics that could allow Iraq to shoot down an American
or British jet.
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday's skirmishes, Pentagon officials said, Iraqi forces
fired at least one surface-to-air missile, but the missile failed
to hit any of the aircraft patrolling the no-flight zone in Iraq.
American and British officials said their jets returned safely to
their base in Incirlik, Turkey, even though Iraq claimed to have
shot down an ``enemy aircraft,'' as it has in previous exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   Four American F-15E fighter jets then attacked two Soviet-era
surface-to-air missile sites near Mosul, the city in northern Iraq
that has been the center of a flurry of skirmishes over the last
two weeks. The officials said guided bombs dropped by those jets
scored ``direct hits.''
</P>
<P>
   In the same area, F-16 fighters and EA-6B electronic-jamming
jets fired three radar-seeking missiles at anti-aircraft sites,
also near Mosul, but the officials said it was not clear whether
those strikes had hit.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq has tested the enforcement of the zones before, but never
in such a sustained way. Iraq's vice president, Taha Yassin
Ramadan, kept up Iraq's increasingly strident defiance Wednesday,
saying the zones violate Iraqi sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue to confront this violation with all of our
capabilities, regardless of the cost,'' he declared.
</P>
<P>
   There is a cost to the United States, too. Each of the
radar-seeking missiles fired by the F-16s and EA-6B's costs about
$200,000, and those jets have already fired off nearly a dozen
missiles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
