<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Message from Conyers' makes television debut
 &HT;    By Peter Scott
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Supporters of Conyers, Ga., visionary Nancy Fowler are
taking to the airways to get the whole world praying for peace.
</P>
<P>
   In a satellite telecast beamed worldwide by HTV of Houma, La.,
an hourlong program called ``Message from Conyers'' made its debut
on Wednesday. The new program will air at 1 p.m. on the 13th of
each month.
</P>
<P>
   More than 20 million viewers, primarily in Latin American
countries, are expected to watch the monthly broadcast from the
15-year-old station, Fowler supporters said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Folse, president of HTV and a primary backer of the
program, said he launched the broadcast in response to an appeal by
Fowler. When Fowler delivered what she called her last public
message on Oct. 13, she asked pilgrims worldwide to pray the rosary
for peace. The event drew about 80,000 people to her Conyers farm,
about 35 miles east of downtown Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in the cause,'' Folse said at a Wednesday news
conference to announce the new show. ``We volunteered the resource,
and we are not making any money on this. We may break even.''
</P>
<P>
   Fowler did not attend Wednesday's news conference because she
was ill, said George Collins, one of her spokespersons. But Dr.
Ricardo Castanon and visionary Katya Rivas did attend.
</P>
<P>
   Castanon, a Bolivian neuropsychologist who was an atheist
skeptic of Fowler's claims, says he and others have proved her
claims exist, and they have submitted papers to the Vatican for
approval.
</P>
<P>
   Rivas, who says she now receives messages from the Virgin Mary,
urged all to ``live the life of the Spirit.'' Through an
interpreter, she said the world should know that ``the Father is
full of love, and do not fear me. How much do I love you? I have
sacrificed my son,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's program included about 20 minutes of prayers and an
interview that included Fowler and others associated with the
visions she said she began receiving in the early 1990s. Fowler
discussed a 1993 vision of Chinese soldiers occupying American
soil. She told her interviewer that the vision disturbs her because
she has since learned that Taiwan and China have bid for the
greatest economic influence in the Panama Canal, which the United
States will relinquish Dec. 31. She said the Chinese also have
bragged about their ability to take out American global
surveillance satellites.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
