<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2096 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-SALINAS-ART-2T     01-13 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-SALINAS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW EVIDENCE EMERGES AS MURDER VERDICT ON RAUL SALINAS IS
IMMINENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(fe) 
 By JULIA PRESTON with CRAIG PYES c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The gunman, undeterred by the bright daylight of a
Mexico City morning, strode up to the sedan parked on a bustling
street and fired one bullet from an automatic pistol, shattering
the driver's window and killing Jose Francisco Ruiz Massieu, one of
Mexico's most prominent politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Within months of the assassination, on Sept. 28, 1994, the
investigation turned into a crucial test of Mexico's justice
system. Prosecutors appointed by a new president arrested the
eldest brother of a former president, Carlos Salinas de Gortari,
and charged him as the mastermind of the murder. Never before had a
close relative of a figure as powerful as a former president faced
prosecution for so grave a crime.
</P>
<P>
   But after four years, the sensational trial of the brother, Raul
Salinas de Gortari, has taken so many bizarre turns that it has
done little to dispel the notion that Mexico's high and mighty
enjoy exceptional impunity.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the judge set to rule, a compelling new piece of
evidence implicating Raul Salinas that was never presented in court
has emerged. It is a tape recording of the very first police
interrogation of Jorge Rodriguez Gonzalez, who assembled the
assassination team and is serving 37 years in jail as an accomplice
to murder.
</P>
<P>
   The hourlong recording is significant because it appears to be
free of the manipulation and coercion by the police and prosecutors
that so fouled other evidence in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez Gonzalez, 48, was the first witness to give the police
a broad depiction of how the murder was planned and carried out.
Although much of what he says about the Salinas family is hearsay,
he gave a surprisingly fluid account 36 hours after the shooting in
which he described the plot in details only an insider could
possess _ most of which were confirmed in later investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez Gonzalez affirmed repeatedly that it was Raul Salinas
who gave orders ``to eliminate'' Ruiz Massieu, a fast-rising
politician who was the secretary general of Mexico's dominant
political party and had once been married to the Salinases' sister,
Adriana.
</P>
<P>
   And in allegations that were never followed up, Rodriguez
Gonzalez insists _ five times _ that Raul Salinas Lozano, the
father of Raul, Carlos and Adriana, who was once a power in Mexican
politics, also knew of and approved the murder of Ruiz Massieu, his
former son-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   The tape was provided to The New York Times by a person who has
worked closely with Mexican officials in a number of crime
investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Luis Ramos Rivera, a deputy attorney general who has
struggled for two years to stitch back together a homicide case
left in tatters by the two special prosecutors before him, said he
had not known about the tape. Why it never reached his hands is
unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``This without a doubt is very important evidence,'' Ramos
Rivera said. ``The testimony was given only hours after the
killing, by a participant who knew all the details of the homicide
and makes no effort to hide his own role. It shows that the name of
Raul Salinas de Gortari was mentioned from the very first moments
of the investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense lawyer for Salinas, Eduardo Luengo Creel, said today
that he could not comment on the new tape because he is required to
remain silent in these final days of the trial, as the judge weighs
his verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Instead he referred to comments he made in the past about a
different tape of Rodriguez Gonzalez that emerged in April 1997.
Luengo said he believes that tape was fabricated by the second
special prosecutor, Pablo Chapa Bezanilla, out of desperation
because he believed his case against Salinas was collapsing.
</P>
<P>
   Luengo has argued that Rodriguez Gonzalez and his brother,
Fernando, an accomplice, agreed beforehand they would blame the
Salinas family if they were caught. But the defense has never
explained what motive the Rodriguez Gonzalez brothers may have had.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, Raul Salinas de Gortari has maintained that
he is not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   He appeared, haggard and despondent, at the final hearing in his
trial on Dec. 9 in a courtroom at the grim Almoloya penitentiary,
where he has been confined since his arrest on Feb. 28, 1995.
Flanked by his nieces Claudia and Daniela Ruiz Massieu, the
daughters of the man whose murder he is accused of ordering, Raul
Salinas broke into tears as he asserted his innocence once again.
</P>
<P>
   ``My imprisonment in Almoloya responds more to a political
decision than a legal one,'' Salinas said. ``Public lynching and
fabricated accusations are some of the many weapons that have been
used against our family, aside from bullets.''
</P>
<P>
   Salinas Lozano, who is 81 and severely ill with emphysema, did
not respond to requests for comment on Wednesday. Salinas Lozano
has indignantly denied any part in the murder of a man he says was
a friend and family member. None of the prosecutors uncovered
sufficient evidence to call him for questioning in the case.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed last week in a Mexico City prison, Jorge Rodriguez
Gonzalez recognized his voice on the tape. He said the questioning
took place on the evening of Sept. 29, 1994, the day after the
assassination, at a federal police headquarters in Matamoros, where
he lived and where he retreated after the killing. The location and
time are confirmed by statements on the tape.
</P>
<P>
   After Rodriguez Gonzalez's interrogation in Matamoros, he was
flown to Mexico City for questioning by detectives working for the
special prosecutor chosen by President Salinas to handle the murder
case. He testified later that the detectives beat him until they
broke one of his ribs to force him to eliminate any mention of Raul
Salinas from his testimony. The April 1997 tape discovered by Ramos
Rivera registered his agonized responses under that torture.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Rodriguez Gonzalez gave his first official deposition for
the court record after about 12 hours of harsh interrogation by the
Mexico City detectives. In contrast to the version he gave earlier
in Matamoros, where he mentioned Raul Salinas 11 times, he did not
refer even once to Salinas.
</P>
<P>
   President Carlos Salinas appointed the first special prosecutor,
who stands accused in Mexico of brutalizing several witnesses to
cover up Raul Salinas' role. A cruel paradox is that he was the
victim's own brother, Mario Ruiz Massieu, then a deputy attorney
general.
</P>
<P>
   He resigned from the case after two months and after President
Salinas stepped down. He fled from Mexico in March 1995, but was
arrested in the United States. He vehemently denies that he tried
to protect Raul Salinas and has defeated four attempts by Mexico to
extradite him. He remains under house arrest in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   One mystery is where and how the decision was made to withhold
the first tape from Ramos Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   An American official who insisted on anonymity said a copy of
this tape was obtained by the United States Drug Enforcement
Administration over a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   It should have set off alarm bells. Attorney General Janet Reno
had pledged to Salinas' successor, President Ernesto Zedillo, that
the United States would cooperate fully with Mexico's efforts to
extradite and prosecute Mario Ruiz Massieu in order to help solve
the killing of Jose Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   But D.E.A. officials now deny that they know anything about the
tape. Van D. Quarles, a spokesman for the agency, said it ``does
not know of the existence of the tape, much less what's on it and
who's on it.''
</P>
<P>
   The tape can no longer be entered as evidence because the trial
is effectively over. Under the rigid procedures of Mexican justice,
the judge, Ricardo Ojeda Bohorquez, has until Jan. 22 to study the
trial record and issue his verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Rodriguez Gonzalez said on the tape that he was led into
the assassination by his brother Fernando, 52, who has been
convicted as the organizer of the plot. Trial records show that
Fernando instructed the gunman how to recognize his victim and
arranged the ambush as Ruiz Massieu emerged from a Mexico City
hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Rodriguez Gonzalez acknowledged on the tape that he helped
his brother to find the assassin, a ranch hand from Tamaulipas
state. Jorge stood lookout as the killer, Daniel Aguilar Trevino,
shot Ruiz Massieu.
</P>
<P>
   On the tape, Rodriguez Gonzalez said he learned from his brother
that Raul Salinas de Gortari and his father were behind the
killing.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did [Fernando) tell you about the operation?'' asked the
police interrogator, as buzzers and police radios hummed in the
background.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just said that they gave orders from above that there was
going to be an operation,'' Rodriguez Gonzalez replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``What operation?''
</P>
<P>
   ``They were going to eliminate a person who they did not want to
have around,'' Rodriguez Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who gave the orders from above?''
</P>
<P>
   ``As I understand it, what I heard there, was that Raul Salinas
de Gortari and his father were the ones who handled that,''
Rodriguez Gonzalez replied.
</P>
<P>
   A while later the interrogator asks, ``Why were they going to
kill him?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Because those were the instructions of Raul Salinas de Gortari
and his father,'' Rodriguez Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   Later he explains tha his brother told him that Raul Salinas
promised to find government jobs for the murder conspirators. He
also says his brother told him after the killing that Raul Salinas
and his father were ``irritated'' by early reports that Ruiz
Massieu had been only wounded, not killed.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Rodriguez Gonzalez said that Fernando heard that Raul
Salinas had pledged to find a way to free the gunman, Aguilar, who
was captured moments after the shooting by a bank security guard.
Jorge Rodriguez Gonzalez also said Fernando even hinted at a
motive.
</P>
<P>
   ``He left the sister of Raul Salinas; he left her for the reason
that he was a homosexual,'' saidJorge Rodriguez Gonzalez referring
to Jose Francisco Ruiz Massieu.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that why they want to kill him, because he was a
homosexual?'' an interrogator asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what problem they have inside the family, but the
father gave instructions,'' Rodriguez Gonzalez answered.
</P>
<P>
   Last week at the prison, Jorge Rodriguez Gonzalez became
distraught and gave confused responses after hearing the tape. He
said that the police in Matamoros had beaten him before the
questioning began, an accusation he had not raised previously in
court. Then he said that the tape must have been fabricated because
he said he would not have implicated himself as he did on the
recording. After first admitting to his role in murder plot, he has
recently begun to assert that he had nothing to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That tape is 90 percent manipulated,'' Rodriguez Gonzalez
said, trying to steady his trembling hands. ``The one part that is
true is that I was told that Raul Salinas de Gortari was behind the
assassination.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything he knew about Salinas' role he heard from his brother
Fernando, who in turn heard it from his boss, an ambitious
congressman from Tamaulipas named Manuel Munoz Rocha. The
prosecution alleges that Raul Salinas offered to lend Munoz Rocha
the political clout of a presidential sibling if he would ``take
care'' of Ruiz Massieu.
</P>
<P>
   Munoz Rocha, who is wanted for murder, disappeared one day after
the assassination.
</P>
<P>
   However, numerous details from Rodriguez Gonzalez's statements
were subsequently confirmed by documentary evidence. For example,
Jorge recounts that after the murder Fernando received a cellular
phone call from Munoz Rocha, who informed him that Ruiz Massieu was
dead, adding that he had called Raul Salinas at home to tell him
the news.
</P>
<P>
   Munoz Rocha, according to Rodriguez Gonzalez, ``even said they
told him that [Raul Salinas) was asleep, and he said, well, `Wake
up, brother, because it's done, it's over.'''
</P>
<P>
   Phone records presented in court show that Munoz Rocha made
several attempts to reach Raul Salinas' home on the day of the
murder. Later one of Salinas' bodyguards testified that he received
a phone call that day from Munoz Rocha but advised him that Salinas
was asleep.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos Rivera, the current prosecutor, acknowledged that his case
against Raul Salinas is far from airtight. ``We inherited a case
that was full of incredible errors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most serious, in his view, were committed by the
second prosecutor, Chapa. After the first prosecutor was accused of
trying to suppress the role of Raul Salinas, Chapa reversed course,
making huge secret payments court documents showed to induce
several witnesses to implicate Raul Salinas, including $500,000 to
Fernando Rodriguez Gonzalez. He fell in league with a clairvoyant
and with a former mistress of Salinas. Hoping to frame Salinas and
collect a reward that Chapa himself offered, the two women planted
a body on a ranch belonging to Raul Salinas, but the autopsy
results quickly exposed the scheme. Chapa fled to Spain, but when
he was arrested there, he agreed to return to Mexico for trial on
charges related to the illegal burial.
</P>
<P>
   The former prosecutor was acquitted of every charge.
</P>
</TEXT>
