<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2102 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-BUDGET14-COX     01-13 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-BUDGET14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tax cut, transit initiative drive Barnes' first budget
 &HT;    By Peter Mantius
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Gov. Roy Barnes set about fulfilling campaign promises
Wednesday with an $83 million property tax cut, new outside audits
of state agencies and a fresh approach to transportation planning
included in his $13.3 million state budget proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The spending plan, which covers the year beginning July 1, is
$760 million bigger than the current budget. It gives major boosts
to day care, alternative schools, law enforcement pay and the state
crime lab.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have managed to keep up with the demands of being the
fastest growing state in the South... without raising a single tax
or fee, while providing for a tax cut,'' Barnes told a joint
session of the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The tax cut doubles the homestead exemption on homes and farms
to $4,000 of assessed value. During the next seven years, Barnes
plans to raise the exemption to $20,000 in assessed value _ or
$50,000 in market value _ saving property owners $630 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many young couples struggling to qualify for their first
home, and for many elderly couples on fixed incomes who are
fighting tooth and nail to stay in their homes, this tax cut will
help lift the burden and fulfill the dream of home-ownership,''
Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   The tax-cut plan has bipartisan support, though legislators are
curious to see how Barnes plans to ensure that local governments
are reimbursed for lost revenue.
</P>
<P>
   A homeowner whose property is assessed at the state average,
$31,418, would receive a $506 annual tax cut when the Barnes plan
is in full effect.
</P>
<P>
   The governor repeatedly touched on the theme that Georgia must
begin to deal with the negative effects of its rapid growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I was born, a train ran from my hometown of Mableton to
this state Capitol every hour,'' Barnes said. ``But we pulled up
our rail lines for more and faster (highway) lanes, which are
slowing us down, snarling our growth and polluting our air.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor wants to spend $1 million to create the Georgia
Urban Transportation Management Authority to find new solutions to
traffic, sprawl and smog _ and commuter rail is likely to figure
prominently.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Tom Murphy, for one, is ready to listen. ``I've
changed my mind on rail transport,'' said Murphy, a Bremen
Democrat, who said he foresees Atlanta's MARTA commuter rail lines
extending out 40 to 50 miles within the next decade. ``We may have
to force people to do what they don't want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes promised details on the mechanics of his new
transportation authority in coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of Barnes' economic development program, the
$13.6 million Yamacraw Project, is an initiative to promote Georgia
as a mecca for the design of computer microchip systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we want to do is produce the graduates, attract the
companies and market the products that make the information
superhighway work,'' Barnes said. ``We want to make the nuts and
bolts _ the silicon chips and semiconductors.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes has also recommended issuing $220 million in bonds to
expand the Georgia World Congress Center, although that project
would be funded in his amended budget for fiscal 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The new governor's overall spending plan was well received by
the legislators who've been asked to adopt it.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Larry Walker (D-Perry) said the property
tax cut was long overdue. House Appropriations Chairman Terry
Coleman (D-Eastman) said he didn't see many sticking points likely
to trigger fierce opposition.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Bob Irvin (R-Atlanta) praised the
Democratic governor for seeking independent audits of major state
agencies. Republicans have pushed that idea for years, and Guy
Millner, Barnes' opponent in the governor's race, suggested it in
his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes' announcement that he wants to spend $4 million on the
audits drew the loudest applause during his speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the real news of this budget,'' Irvin said. ``It
makes all the difference in the world to have outside auditors
instead of the state auditor. They have more freedom, less
pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes also proposed establishing a special office of consumer
advocacy for insurance, a plan that is likely to come under attack.
One insurance lobbyist said it was a bad idea he and others would
oppose.
</P>
<P>
   The continuing decline in state welfare rolls gives Barnes $40
million to play with. He proposed using $30 million to expand state
child care programs to allow 14,706 additional children to be
served. The remainder of the savings also will be reinvested in
human services programs.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin endorsed that approach. ``I've always said the purpose of
welfare reform is not to save money, it's to save lives,'' the
legislator said.
</P>
<P>
   The Barnes budget includes $252 million for pay raises. Teachers
and college professors would get 4 percent raises, while other
state employees will get an average of 3 percent. Former Gov. Zell
Miller had given teachers four consecutive years of 6 percent
raises to raise their pay to the highest in the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said his boost is sufficient to keep Georgia in first
place.
</P>
<P>
   The new governor also wants to nearly double state funds for
alternative schools, which provide a special place for disruptive
students. He would add $12.9 million to increase funding to $24.6
million.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes is asking for large increases in after-school programs
for children in grades 4 through 8 and in reading programs for
younger students.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to use $48.6 million to open new prisons and to staff
existing facilities, along with $86.1 million in state and federal
funds in his supplemental budget for 2,200 new prison beds. A $17.3
million increase in juvenile justice spending will help the state
make the improvements ordered last year by the U.S. Department of
Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes wants to raise the starting salaries for correctional
officers from $18,880 up to $22,000 and for state troopers from
$24,000 up to $26,000. He also proposes hiring 40 new troopers,
bringing the force to 929.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes recommended $6.4 million in new spending for the state
crime lab, which he called ``nothing short of a disaster.'' The new
money would fund 85 new positions, equipment and related expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
