<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 The Wizard Can Boost Performance  &HT;       
 By David Einstein  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  How often should you use the Maintenance Wizard in
Windows 98? And is it really necessary to use it at all?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  The Maintenance Wizard is a tool that lets you
schedule three ``tune-up'' programs to run automatically when
you're away from your computer: Disk Cleanup, which deletes
unnecessary files, including temporary files; ScanDisk, which
checks and repairs minor problems on your hard drive; and Disk
Defragmenter, which organizes the data on the drive so that it can
be retrieved efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   Of those programs, the only one that really helps increase
performance is the disk defragmenter. Over time, your disk can
become fragmented, meaning information about programs gets
scattered around the disk rather than all being in one location.
This can impair performance.
</P>
<P>
   Whether and how often you should run the Disk Defragmenter
depends on how heavily you use your PC. If all you do is surf the
Web, exchange e-mail and write letters, you may never have to
bother defragmenting. If, on the other hand, you are constantly
adding and deleting programs from your computer, you should
defragment every month or so.
</P>
<P>
   You can run any of the maintenance programs directly from the
System Tools folder in the Programs/Accessories menu. The advantage
of the Maintenance Wizard is that it lets you schedule them to run
at a time when you won't need the PC. That's especially important
for Disk Defragmenter, because defragmenting a large hard drive can
take several hours.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for an inexpensive lot on which to build a
retirement home, and have found some affordable mountain land.
Though the site has nearby power lines, there are no plans for
telephone service in the near future. The land agent I am dealing
with assures me that many people now have Internet connections via
radio frequency (rf), and that telephone service is not necessary
for either voice or Internet access. I thought this technology was
still experimental. Can you enlighten me on this technology? Is it
affordable and reliable?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sounds like you're talking about fixed wireless service over
a cellular phone system. In some rural areas, phone companies will
set up cellular base sites to provide service to residents, rather
than wiring the area for regular phones. The way it works is you
have a send-receive device on the side of your house, which
communicates with the cellular base unit via radio waves.
</P>
<P>
   Such systems can provide Internet access at up to 28.8 kbps, for
about what you'd pay over a regular phone line. But before you buy
the land, get the name of the phone company from the land agent and
check out the service to make sure it's practical and affordable.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm shopping for a new PC. I'm an average user _ word
processing, genealogy software, some work with databases and the
Internet _ but no games. How much RAM should I have at a minimum?
And what feature or features enhance the speed with which one moves
about on the Internet?
</P>
<P>
   A: Most new home computers come with either 32 or 64 megabytes
of RAM memory. For your requirements, 32 megs should be sufficient,
but memory is so cheap now that you should look for a system with
64. That way, you'll have plenty of RAM for whatever memory-hungry
programs may come along in the next couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   The speed at which you can surf the Web depends mostly on the
speed of your Internet connection. New PCs all come with 56 kbps
modems. The phone company is rapidly rolling out ADSL service,
which ups the speed to 356 kbps. And in some communities you can
get cable-modem service, which gives you more than 1 megabyte per
second.
</P>
<P>
   Internet performance _ especially with graphics-intensive Web
sites _ also can be enhanced by a faster chip in your PC and by
increased memory. In other words, the better the PC, the better the
Internet experience.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; TIP OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  Want to keep up with the impeachment trial? The Internet is the
perfect place, offering live Webcasts as well as a wealth of video
and audio clips, news and analysis. To enjoy audio and video you'll
need a software player _ either the RealPlayer from RealNetworks
 &LR; (www.real.com),  &LR; or the Windows Media Player from Microsoft
 &LR; (www.microsoft.com).  &LR; Both can be downloaded for free. For a good
rundown of impeachment coverage on the Net, go to  &LR; www.real.com &LR; 
 &LR; /realguide/special/impeach/.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about computing? E-mail it to  &LR; computers(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
