<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCOLL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 McColl Takes His Assurances to Los Angeles  &HT;       
 By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Los Angeles
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
After two tense days in San Francisco, BankAmerica Chief Executive
Officer Hugh McColl brought his California road show to the kinder,
gentler confines of Los Angeles yesterday, assuring business and
community leaders his takeover of the old BankAmerica is good for
the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not bring my company to California with the idea of
taking anything away from California,'' the North Carolina banker
said in a speech before Town Hall Los Angeles, a public forum
similar to San Francisco's Commonwealth Club where McColl spoke
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   McColl, whose NationsBank bought San Francisco's BofA three
months ago and took its name, was on the third day of a four-day
swing through California aimed at winning over critics of the
takeover.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco earlier this week, McColl was grilled by Mayor
Willie Brown and San Francisco supervisors over such matters as his
refusal to make the sort of itemized lending pledges that have been
customary for California's big financial institutions. In the end,
though, his vows to step up the flow of loans and donations in the
state earned praise from Brown and several San Francisco
supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, in Los Angeles, McColl barely had to work up a
sweat. The passions aroused in San Francisco by the takeover of the
state's most important financial institution are largely absent in
Southern California, where the old BofA wasn't a hometown bank and
people have already seen their big local banks and thrifts _
including Home Savings, Great Western and First Interstate _
acquired by outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``There just hasn't been much of a reaction,'' said Ezunial
Burts, president of the Los Angeles Area Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   In his Town Hall speech, McColl hit the same notes he has
sounded throughout his California tour, portraying the new BofA as
a progressive employer and responsible corporate citizen.
</P>
<P>
   He promised to increase services in black, Asian American and
Latino communities. He announced $2.5 million in gifts to fund
literacy programs in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, McColl announced a $5 million gift over five
years to help develop a Mission Bay campus for the University of
California at San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   McColl yesterday also highlighted bank programs aimed at
improving opportunities for women employees, including an expansion
of the bank's councils on diversity.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of MCCOLL14 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  After his speech, McColl didn't have to field the tough questions
he faced at the Commonwealth Club about the resignations of senior
female executives of the old BofA or his treatment of former BofA
chief executive David Coulter.
</P>
<P>
   The only unexpected moment came when Town Hall president
Adrienne Medawar muffed her introduction, declaring she wanted to
``spank'' McColl. She quickly corrected herself, explaining she
wanted to ``thank'' him for appearing.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some in the audience said they will reserve judgment
until they see how the new BofA performs. ``That was wonderful
talk,'' said Tony Espinoza, director of the United Latino Fund, a
local charity supported by BofA. `We'll have to see whether they
walk the walk.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of MCCOLL14 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
