<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-DIRECTOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRIPPEN, REPUBLICAN WHO WORKED FOR REAGAN, TO HEAD CONGRESSIONAL
BUDGET OFFICE  
(RK)
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT PEAR c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Dan Crippen, who worked for President Reagan and
for Howard Baker Jr., the Senate majority leader in the early
1980's, was chosen Wednesday to be director of the Congressional
Budget Office, a powerful agency with an influential voice in
debates on economic and social policy.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Domenici, R-N.M., who is chairman of the Senate Budget
Committee, announced the selection, after getting agreement from
the Senate Republican leader, Trent Lott of Mississippi, and the
chairman of the House Budget Committee, John Kasich, R-Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Crippen, 46, is more clearly identified with a political party
than any of his predecessors. But he is expected to continue the
agency's tradition as an independent, nonpartisan source of
information.
</P>
<P>
   The Budget Office estimates the cost of every significant bill
that goes to the floor of the House or the Senate; makes
projections of federal spending and tax revenues, and forecasts how
the economy will perform. The Congressional Budget Office can, in
effect, kill legislative proposals if it estimates that they will
significantly increase the deficit or reduce the surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Crippen worked on economic and domestic policy on Capitol Hill
and at the White House. He went to the White House with Baker in
1987, when Baker became chief of staff for Reagan. Since leaving
the White House in February 1989, Crippen has been a Washington
lobbyist. His current clients include Ford Motor Co., General
Electric, Merrill Lynch and Baxter Healthcare Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Duberstein, former deputy chief of staff in the Reagan
White House, described Crippen as ``a pragmatic conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Crippen would be the fifth director of the Budget Office.
Democratic members of Congress say they see him as a mainstream
Republican, but worry that he does not have as much formal training
in economic theory as his predecessors. He received a bachelor's
degree from the University of South Dakota and a Ph.D. in public
administration and economics from Ohio State University in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   The Budget Office director serves a four-year term and is
jointly appointed by the speaker of the House and the president pro
tem of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans chose the agency's current director, June O'Neill,
but House Republican leaders harshly criticized her last June. In a
letter, they said that the Budget Office had been ``consistently
wrong'' and had repeatedly understated economic growth and
overstated budget deficits.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting with Crippen this week, Lott made clear that he saw
plenty of room for improvements. Some conservative Republicans have
complained that the agency is dominated by what they see as the
old-fashioned liberal views of career civil servants in senior
positions.
</P>
<P>
   Professor William H. Oakland, who advised Crippen on his
doctoral dissertation, described him as ``a low-key but tenacious
guy'' and said he was ``one of my favorite students in 35 years of
teaching.'' In an interview, Oakland said: ``Dan's training in
economic theory is not as rigorous as that of some people with a
Ph.D. in economics, but he has more training in areas directly
germane to the operation of government, like budgeting, management
and the legislative process.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1989 to 1996, Crippen was senior vice president of the
Duberstein Group, a consulting firm. Since 1996, Crippen has been a
principal in Washington Counsel, a law and lobbying firm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 2134EST &QL; 
