<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 AMD Profitable Again, But Lower Than Expected  &HT;       
 By Dan Fost 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Advanced Micro Devices reported its second straight profitable
quarter yesterday, but the results fell short of analysts'
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The Sunnyvale chipmaker suffered from declining prices for its
chips and a manufacturing stumble, at the same time its archrival
Intel Corp. was firing on all cylinders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a disappointing quarter,'' said John Lazlo, an analyst
with PaineWebber in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth quarter, ended December 27, AMD posted record
quarterly revenues of $788.8 million, but net income of $22.3
million (15 cents per share) missed analysts' estimates of 19 cents
per share, as reported in a First Call Corp. survey.
</P>
<P>
   In the year-ago quarter, AMD lost $12.3 million (9 cents) on
$613.2 million in revenues.
</P>
<P>
   AMD also reported record revenues for the year of $2.54 billion,
with a net loss of $104 million (72 cents per share). In the
previous year, AMD lost $21.1 million (15 cents) on $2.4 billion in
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   AMD's earnings report came the day after its arch-rival Intel
Corp. reported a smashingly successful quarter, including record
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Even though AMD made some inroads this past year, particularly
in selling chips for inexpensive computers, Intel has fought back
successfully. Intel maintains a vast lead over second place AMD in
the sale of microprocessors, the brains of personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   AMD's gains, as well as new products rolling out now and over
the next few months, had Jerry Sanders _ the company's founder,
chairman and chief executive _ as optimistic as always.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be able to increase ... revenues and average selling
price while maintaining the last quarter's record volume levels,''
Sanders told analysts in a conference call. ``We are increasingly
confident of our ability to broaden our market and our customer
base.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts thought AMD would have done better, given signs of a
possible rebound in the semiconductor industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``In December, we heard anecdotal news about better PC sales,
and automatically assumed AMD would benefit as would Intel,'' said
PaineWebber's Lazlo. ``AMD had production glitches so it couldn't
manufacture as many 400 MHz chips as it expected, and its average
selling prices eroded 13 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the company lost about $5 million in its
nonmicroprocessor products, although it had expected those items to
turn the corner into profitability.
</P>
<P>
   AMD made its announcement after the close of trading. Although
its stock rose 13 cents to $31.63 yesterday, it fell to $27.63 in
after hours trading.
</P>
<P>
   The company said that, in the months ahead, it plans to release
new chips to compete with Intel in every segment, including laptop
computers, high performance desktops and corporate servers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always an uphill battle,'' said Robert McCormack Jr., a
general partner with Integral Capital Partners in Menlo Park.
``You've got to stay up with Intel. Intel is doing a great job of
bracketing them on the low end.''
</P>
<P>
   AMD's K6-2 chips were squeezed by Intel's Pentium II on the high
end and Intel's Celeron chips on the low end. Intel showed strong
sales of both chips in its fourth quarter report Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 2135EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0439 </DOCNO>
