r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APPLE-SFCHRON &LR;      01-13 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Apple Reports 5th Straight Profitable Quarter  &HT;       
 By Jon Swartz 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Apple Computer, cashing in on insatiable demand for its new
space-age iMac computer, yesterday posted its fifth straight
quarterly profit.
</P>
<P>
   The Cupertino company said first-quarter profits more than
tripled, to $152 million (95 cents per share) from $47 million (33
cents) in the same quarter a year ago. The earnings exceeded
analysts' predictions of 69 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Discounting a $29 million gain from Apple's sale of 2.9 million
shares of ARM Holdings Plc, the company earned $123 million (78
cents).
</P>
<P>
   Equally significant, Apple reported its first year-to-year gain
in sales since late 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unit growth year-over-year was three to four times higher than
the industry average,'' Apple interim chief executive Steve Jobs
said in a statement. ``Apple ended the quarter with only two days
of inventory, besting industry-leading Dell's seven days of
inventory.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnings were at their highest level since the company returned
to profitability. For the fourth quarter of 1998, previously
Apple's highest earning quarter under Jobs' renewed leadership, the
company netted $106 million.
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by 519,000 unit shipments of the curvy, translucent iMac
to consumers and first-time PC buyers, Apple registered $1.71
billion in sales, up 8 percent from $1.58 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   Industry observers expect the trend to continue this year with
the release of new, speedy, top-of-the-line models called the Power
Mac G3 desktop computers. A laptop version of the iMac is expected
this spring, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The iMac is really helping them out, and I'm sure the
turnaround will continue with the new models,'' said Tom
Rhinelander, an analyst at Forrester Research in Cambridge, Mass.
``It's a very good showing for a company that looked down and on
the ropes a year ago. Amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Apple had returned to the black largely because
of severe cost cutting and the elimination of unprofitable
divisions and products. But the company had not created compelling
new products for consumers and businesses, and its sales were below
par.
</P>
<P>
   Apple's strong quarterly results for the three-month period
ended Dec. 25, 1998, reflect the runaway success of the iMacs _ the
hot-selling model that now comes in grape, blueberry, strawberry,
tangerine and lime. An estimated 800,000 units have been sold since
the iMac hit computer store shelves in August.
</P>
<P>
   More important, the sales figures indicate an increase in market
share for Apple, a key factor for software companies who are
considering writing programs for the Macintosh system.
</P>
<P>
   Apple's share of the worldwide PC market has improved to 5
percent from 3 percent a year ago, according to ZD Market
Intelligence of La Jolla.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the company's fiscal recovery has fueled a stock
price rebound. Yesterday it climbed 38 cents, to a 52-week high of
$46.50.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the good tidings, however, some remain skeptical that Apple
can sustain an upturn into the long-term future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apple's at a peak right now,'' said CIBC Oppenheimer's James
Poyner Jr. ``They are likely to see a plateauing of iMac shipments
going forward and that is going to make the stock a lot less
interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also caution that the $1,199 iMac could be vulnerable
to lower-priced personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their problems are not over,'' Rhinelander cautioned. ``But
they are much stronger than they've been in years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
