<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0440 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2113 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ESCROW-SFCHRON &LR;      01-13 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESCROW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Escrow services in demand as Net auction sites proliferate  &HT;       
 By Jamie Beckett 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Internet auctions can be a great way to buy or sell goods. Or they
be a tricky game of chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Say you're selling your prized Beanie Baby collection. You find
a buyer who will pay your price. Now for the hard part: Who makes
the first move? The buyer wants you to send the Beanie Babies
before she'll pay. But you want your money first.
</P>
<P>
   Online escrow services hope to end that game of chicken. Just as
real-estate escrow services help protect property buyers and
sellers, online escrow aims to be a buffer between buyer and
seller. Both systems work much the same way. In exchange for a
percentage of the transaction _ generally about 5 percent for the
online services _ the escrow company acts as impartial third party
that holds funds until the transaction is complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the Internet, there's no way to tell who you're dealing
with,'' said Bob Hanlon of Pleasanton, who buys and sells older PC
equipment online via auctions and classified ads. After getting
stiffed a few times, he started insisting on using escrow services.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm the seller, I typically tell buyers to use an escrow
service unless they want to prepay,'' Hanlon said.
</P>
<P>
   Some 5 million transactions take place monthly via online
auctions, classified ads or newsgroups, according to analysts'
estimates. The majority are transactions between individuals _
usually strangers. Completing a sale requires a considerable amount
of trust, and lots of things can go wrong: Goods may not live up to
their description. They may be lost or broken in transit.
</P>
<P>
   It's a situation ripe for misunderstandings, mistakes and even
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't know each other and don't necessarily want to
trust the other party,'' said Sherman Kwok, founder of i-Escrow,
one of three major online escrow services. ``Because we're an
impartial third party and hold the funds, both the buyer and seller
feel they won't get ripped off.``
</P>
<P>
   Kwok started i-Escrow in early 1997 after he tried to sell his
old NeXT computer online. Finding a buyer wasn't the problem.
Agreeing on a price went smoothly enough. But closing the deal was
another thing altogether.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of ESCROW14 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``The buyer said, `Why don't you send &LR;   &LR; the machine, and I'll
send you the money?' I said, `I don't know you. Why don't you send
me the money, and then I'll send you the computer?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Kwok and his buyer couldn't agree. He wound up keeping the
computer and using it to start his business. The San Mateo company
now counts more than 20,000 customers, and its services are offered
on eBay, Yahoo auctions and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   I-Escrow is the newest entry to what is still a tiny market. One
of the first companies in the business was TradeSafe, founded by
Bruce Todesco, a former special assistant attorney general in Rhode
Island and amateur musician. Todesco started up TradeSafe of
Providence, R.I., in 1995 after he tried to buy four-track tape
recorders online. He made offers on two and got e-mails from the
sellers accepting his orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was when the whole problem of `I'll send you the goods
after I receive the check' and `I'll send you the the check after I
receive the goods''' occurred, he said. He looked for an escrow
service and didn't find one, so he started his own.
</P>
<P>
   Trade-direct of Tampa, Fla., was founded about the same time
Todesco was trying to get TradeSafe off the ground. Also offering
escrow services: Online auctioneer Auction Universe
( &LR; www.auctionuniverse.com &LR; ), which provides escrow for a $19.95
yearly subscription fee.
</P>
<P>
   All of the escrow companies are privately held, and none would
release sales information. But analysts expect the market to grow
considerably as the online auction market booms.
</P>
<P>
   ``As people put up more and more goods (on auction sites), this
is an important service to be able to offer. People are putting
cars up for auction now, so an escrow service comes in handy,''
said Fiona Swerdlow, a digital-commerce analyst at Jupiter
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   The escrow services generally work this way: The buyer and
seller agree to a deal. Either buyer or the seller can hire the
escrow service via e-mail. Terms of the deal are transmitted to
both parties to make sure they agree. Then the buyer pays the
escrow service using any legal payment means besides cash. (One
advantage escrow services provide is that they allow credit card
transactions, which most individual sellers cannot offer.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of ESCROW14 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The escrow service notifies the seller that payment has been
received. The seller sends the item, using a method that is
trackable, such as UPS, Federal Express or registered mail. After
the buyer receives the item and determines that it is satisfactory,
she notifies the escrow service to release payment to the seller.
The escrow service cuts a check for the seller after deducting a
service fee.
</P>
<P>
   If the item isn't what the buyer ordered _ a Beanie Baby arrives
without the tag that makes it more valuable, for instance _ the
buyer notifies the escrow service. Then the buyer packs it up and
returns it, using a trackable method. When the seller receives it,
he notifies the escrow service and it refunds the buyer's money.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like buying insurance for your house or car,'' said
Mark Dodd, founder of AuctionWatch, an auction monitoring site.
Only it may be even more crucial on the Internet, Dodd said,
because people can easily forge or change identities.
</P>
<P>
   Clay Monroe of Seattle sells reconditioned PCs over the
Internet. These days, he rarely does business with buyers who won't
use an escrow service. He learned the hard way, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I sold a Mac to a guy in Colorado,'' he said. ``He wanted
it COD (cash on delivery). I don't do COD, and I suggested using an
escrow service. Instead, we spent a week e-mailing. I was afraid
I'd lose the sale, so I sent it. The idiot writes a bad check.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for Monroe, it was only a $60 loss.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 3 of ESCROW14 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
