<HEADER>
A2117 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-TYSON-ADVANCE14-C     01-13 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-ADVANCE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New-look Tyson still full of old rage
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ The image-makers have been hard at work.
</P>
<P>
   They give us photo ops of Mike Tyson distributing toys and
turkeys, hoping to steer attention away from the pending sentencing
hearing for assaulting two motorists in Maryland. They create slick
TV ads showing a dedicated Tyson doing his pushups, running at
sunrise and eating his cereal, as if he were an aspiring Olympian
from Mayberry, not the troubled celebrity from the Bronx who this
week spewed profanity on live satellite TV interviews meant to pump
pay-per-view sales.
</P>
<P>
   The new promoter, the new manager and trainer and security guard
and camp members _ they all paint pictures of a hard-working,
humble Mike Tyson. Then they see the spin obliterated in an
obscenity-laced session with a small group of media
representatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I lost to (Evander) Holyfield,'' Tyson said. ``I bit his
... ear. He's a good fighter, but he's not Mike Tyson. He and
Lennox Lewis are outstanding fighters, but they're not Mike Tyson.
They can't sell out Madison Square Garden. I can sell out Madison
Square Garden (doing anything). I'm the champion even when I'm not
champion. When they're the champion, I'm the ... king. They talk
about me like I'm a God. Muhammad Ali set the stage. But there's
never been a fighter as big as Mike Tyson. Look at the gate
receipts.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who count receipts apparently are keeping the numbers
secret from Tyson. Only 6,000 tickets had been sold as of early
Wednesday for his first fight in 19 months, Saturday against
Francois Botha at the MGM Grand, and signals from pay-per-view
operators are mixed. Conversely, Holyfield-Lewis, two months away,
is nearly sold out.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson has an undisputed place in boxing's financial record book.
He has been a part of seven of the top 10 all-time grossing fights.
A large segment of the population remains fascinated by a man who
won the heavyweight title when he was 20, then saw his personal
life deteriorate _ and take his ring wits with it, culminating with
two bites of Holyfield's ears in June 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact remains that when Tyson enters the ring against
Botha, he will represent someone who lost his last two fights, both
to Holyfield, hasn't competed in 19 months, because of license
revocation), hasn't won in 28 months, since a TKO over Bruce
Seldon, and is nearly 11 years removed from his perceived peak, the
91-second destruction of Michael Spinks. Further, he has done
little recently to prove he has rehabilitated himself out of the
ring. The public cursing sessions have become prevalent enough that
his advisers finally told him Wednesday to cool it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They put a muzzle on me,'' Tyson said at Wedneday's final news
conference. ``I can't really say what I want to say today because
of what I said on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   But he already had said plenty:
</P>
<P>
   _ On himself: ``My credibility is shot. If the sleaziest tramp
in the history of the world says, 'Mike Tyson grabbed my (rear),'
people would believe her because Mike Tyson is (expletive).''
</P>
<P>
   _ On God: ``If there's a God, how could there be slavery? But
you want to believe in God because you don't want to be a savage.
But if there's a God, there's a heaven. If there's a heaven, you'll
be judged, and some people will burn in hell. We're all creatures
of contradiction. I was really screwed up before. That was just a
few days ago.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On his upbringing: ``I was the scourge of Brooklyn. I was the
scourge of every part of society. I've been at the bottom, I came
up, fell again, and I'm coming back. Mike is gonna be Mike. You can
keep your tennis shoe deals, your little toy deals. I'll curse.
I'll be crass and obnoxious.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On his comeback: ``I'm not supposed to be here. I was supposed
to be finished after (ex-wife) Robin Givens, after jail (for rape),
after being thorazined-out wait a minute, what's that stuff they
gave me? lithium. Most of the guys I fought are in oblivion now.
They're fighting to pay their crack dealer.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On psychiatrists who examined him before he was re-licensed by
Nevada: ``There's no way those docs were sane. They love to torture
some people's minds. They would've been great Nazis.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On what he expects Botha to do when Tyson goes at him:
``Die.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't all negative. Tyson gushed about an I.R.A. account,
now worth $200,000, he only recently discovered former mentor Cus
D'Amato started for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was living crazy, I spent $200,000 on belts and
underwear or champagne for girls in nightclubs,'' he said. ``I said
to my wife, 'You think Don (King) or Rory (Holloway) set this up
for me? No (expletive) way.' Cus must've known I would screw up my
money. I never thought anybody would love my black (rear).''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson, who owes the IRS $12 million in back taxes, said he wants
to fight four more times in 1999 and then might retire. He has
other 10-rounders penciled in for April and July. Showtime then
will try to make a third Holyfield-Tyson fight, although
Holyfield's possible retirement and probable financial demands make
that bout improbable.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's enthusiasm for competing also has been questioned.
Trainer Tommy Brooks insists that the former champion has been
focused in camp, that he ``hasn't missed a day in the gym.''
</P>
<P>
   But Brooks also said, ``I look at it like this: Where else can a
kid from the ghetto with no education make this money? Maybe he
doesn't want to fight any more. But can you picture him flipping
burgers or slinging trash cans? Once you're used to living a
certain lifestyle, you want to stay with it.''
</P>
<P>
   On firing King and co-managers Holloway and John Horne and
moving his camp from Las Vegas to Phoenix, Tyson said, ``I needed a
fresh start. This is a new version of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   The rewrites sound familiar.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
