<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2125 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SCENE-NYT &LR;      01-13 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE EVE OF THE TRIAL, AN UNEASY QUIETUDE SLIPS OVER THE CAPITOL
</HEADLINE>
   (See also IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-LEGAL, IMPEACH-CLINTON,
IMPEACH-HOUSE.) 
(nk) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The debating chamber doors were masked Wednesday to
prevent early peeking at the bar of the Senate where tables for
contending lawyers had been set up along with other trappings for
the opening arguments in the trial of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senate has invited us over to look at their digs and tell
us where the men's room is,'' Rep. F. James Sensenbrenner Jr.,
R-Wis., declared genially, rounding a corridor as one of the House
prosecutors who visited for a private tour of the courtroom setting
where they will try to banish Clinton from the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the trial, the Capitol was suffused in uneasy
quietude. Officials were vetting history books in the Senate
library for some final ceremonial details, reading from President
Andrew Johnson's 1868 impeachment trial, an ordeal that prompted
one agonized participant, Sen. Edmund G. Ross of Kansas, to write
this wish for the nation: ``It is to be hoped that its like may
never return.''
</P>
<P>
   But its like has returned, and many of the figures involved are
turning for comfort to history in search of assurances that the
right thing can be done.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., has been carrying about
his dog-eared copy of The Federalist Papers, savoring just how
forward-looking Alexander Hamilton could be as a founding father.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most extraordinary things are being written about what
this new office of president will be,'' the senator read aloud in a
corridor citation of Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   While Republicans insist that the Clinton trial is not about
sex, Moynihan has magic-marked and gladly reads aloud Hamilton's
near satirical, now prescient reference to warnings that Americans
studying their presidents might some day have ``to blush at the
unveiled mysteries of a future seraglio.''
</P>
<P>
   Donald A. Ritchie, the Senate's associate historian, finds
comfort in the pungent narrative of a Washington newspaper
correspondent, Francis A. Richardson, who covered the Johnson
impeachment and found it ``more intense and thrilling'' even than
the Civil War with its many ``lulls'' at the battleground.
</P>
<P>
   ``No story as to what the Executive or Legislature might or
would do was too wild to receive credence,'' Richardson wrote in a
1902 memoir.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington has become so fruitful in gossip and scandal, and
intrigue, political and otherwise, that in contrast the ordinary
debates can but prove exceeding dry reading,'' he recalled for The
Historical Society of Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Television crews, jumpily waiting in the Capitol for the
Thursday excitement, suddenly dashed outside at midday to film a
man in a pink bunny suit. He was one of a group of protesters who
set fire to bales of hay at the base of the West Staircase as
members of the group People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals.
Cell phones crackled with news producers' reports of a nonhistoric
incident, and the crews retreated inside for news of higher crimes
and misdemeanors.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Senate, there were mere scraps of scattershot
interviews to be heard. ``He's going to be missed,'' Sen. Olympia
J. Snowe, R-Maine, said sadly, speaking not of the president but of
Michael Jordan and his retirement from basketball.
</P>
<P>
   In his history of the Johnson trial, Ross, looking back a
generation later, described ``the tumult and demoralization of the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The streets of Washington and the corridors of the Capitol
were thronged from day to day,'' Ross said of gaslight-era crowd
scenes that television has considerably thinned.
</P>
<P>
   Now there are modern electronic weapons detectors at the Capitol
entrances; in 1868, vigilant guards demanded a reporter unwrap his
pad and writing materials to convince them ``it did not contain an
infernal machine.'' Back then, reporters gambled thousands of
dollars on the trial outcome, Richardson recalled; nowadays, daily
polling dulls any gambler's instinct.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was wonderful how, up to the last moment, the friends of
the Executive and the adherents of Congress were both confident as
to the result,'' Richardson wrote. It was as if he anticipated the
modern ``spin teams'' of vying political factions that, historic
dignity or not, are expected to be in garrulous reach somewhere
about the Capitol within minutes of the opening arguments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The news nowadays won't keep a minute,'' Richardson said in
turn-of-the-century despair at the tyranny of the telegraph. On the
eve of the arguments over Clinton, the search for something new was
all about the details: Are the trial counsels' tables really
kidney-shaped, as some sources said? Or, from the readings of
history might they better yet be spleen-shaped?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a moment when rumor and rancor were not in the air,''
recalled Richardson the last time. ``Not a moment when hearts did
not tremble for the Republic.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross found the Johnson trial ``sublimely and intensely
dramatic.'' He aptly laid out the impeachment stakes for Clinton
now, as much as for Johnson then: Either to be acquitted or ``to go
the balance of his life's journey with the brand of infamy on his
back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
