<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2131 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-JORDAN-HAWKS14-CO     01-13 0459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JORDAN-HAWKS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta Hawks feelings mixed on Jordan's exit
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There was no fun in the locker room Wednesday, no
wisecracks, none of the jock humor that Hawks president Stan Kasten
once noted can be the cruelest in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Wrapped in towels, with knees and backs getting iced, players
who often had been beaten with impunity by Michael Jordan stared at
his image on a 46-inch TV screen, listening to his goodbye to
basketball on ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   When Vancouver forward Shareef Abdur-Rahim's young voice broke
the silence, it was to ask, half-seriously, ``Do you think he's
gonna play hockey and then come back again?''
</P>
<P>
   A voice said no. ``No more comebacks.'' That was Steve Smith of
the Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   For all that Jordan meant to the game over 13 seasons, this was
all about respect. NBA veterans and rookies eager to start the
season played pick-up games right up to noon in Georgia Tech's
arena, then raced for the big locker room the Hawks will use for
their split home schedule again this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll miss him,'' Mookie Blaylock of the Hawks said. ``But I
won't miss guarding him or him guarding me.''
</P>
<P>
   That was always a mismatch, but Blaylock never turned away from
the assignment. You had to play Jordan with the hand the game
dealt. If that was unfair, well, so were Jordan's talent and
consuming drive to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played against him four times,'' said Abdur-Rahim, who is
from Marietta. ``The last game, they blew us out. I scored 16 in
about half the game. It was a bad loss.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was a chance to learn from a master, he said. ``I learned
a lot by watching him. I don't mean so much in how to do things on
the court but how he was. He taught me that you don't really reach
the peak of your powers until you are 30 or 31, because so much of
this game is mental. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``As he went on, he got smarter, his knowledge of the game
expanded, his ability to deal mentally with his opponent got
stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   For a young, talented man of 22, two NBA seasons under his belt
and on ``loan'' to a Canadian team one more season before free
agency, this is heady stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Abdur-Rahim, who left the University of California after
compiling a 3.5 GPA his freshman year, said that, thanks to Jordan,
he expects to have his best seasons at 30 and beyond. ``He makes
you think that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is, he was the best I ever saw,'' free agent Ivano
Newbill said. ``You admired him and respected him. But now that
he's gone, it opens the doors to the championship for everybody
else. We'll miss him, but it's nice to have the opportunity for
everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
