<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0449 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2132 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-JORDAN14-COX     01-13 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JORDAN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jordan's last shot: Retirement
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Hours before making official his retirement from the
game he mastered, Michael Jordan executed a move he said will
typify his life away from the NBA: He took his kids to school.
</P>
<P>
   That done, Jordan headed Wednesday to the United Center _ the
edifice his otherworldly play financed and filled to capacity every
time he played _ to break the news that the league would have to go
on without him. He had another life to live, and it's time to get
to it.
</P>
<P>
   A city, and much of a nation, mourned. David Falk, his agent and
adviser, was one who wept.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said, ``I told my wife (Juanita) on the way over here
that I felt like was getting married.''
</P>
<P>
   He actually was divorcing himself from the game that brought him
millions of dollars and millions of fans, the game he elevated to
unprecedented heights, the game that cannot afford to lose him. He
conquered all of the challenges basketball presented and ultimately
set unreachable standards.
</P>
<P>
   And in the end, it came down to this: Michael Jordan realized he
could not top Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time, I'm at peace,'' said Jordan, who ``retired'' in
October 1993 to pursue a baseball career only to rejoin the Bulls
after 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his first retirement, when he would not ``shut the door''
on a comeback, Jordan said he was 99.9 percent certain that he had
played his final game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've accomplished everything I could accomplish
individually,'' said Jordan, who turns 36 next month. ``This is the
perfect time to walk away from the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan scripted an ending that the most mushy of novelists
wouldn't dare write: He won the 1997-98 NBA Championship for the
Bulls in June when, in Game 6 in Utah, he stripped Karl Malone of
the ball and hit the title-clinching jump shot.
</P>
<P>
   That shot wrapped up a 45-point effort that rates as the last
page of a
</P>
<P>
   lavish portolio: six championships, five NBA most valuable
player awards, six NBA Finals MVPs, three all-star game MVPs, one
defensive player of the year award, 10 scoring titles . . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael always represent a standard of excellence,'' Bulls
owner Jerry Reinsdorf said. ``This is a day I hoped would never
come. It's a tough day for the Bulls, the NBA, the city of Chicago,
millions of fans around the world. It's hard to imagine the game
played without him.''
</P>
<P>
   It was becoming hard for Jordan, too. He said he was physically
capable of playing a 14th season _ except for a severed tendon in
his right index finger, suffered while trying to cut a cigar in the
Bahamas last week. But mentally, he said, he was depleted.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is difficult because I'm giving up something I truly,
truly love. . . . I'm sad leaving, but I'm happy that life goes on
to another stage.''
</P>
<P>
   That stage, he said, will include fulfilling endorsement
obligations, getting more active in his vast business dealings and,
most importantly, being a more hands-on parent. Juanita Jordan
said, ``My life won't change at all. But I see Michael doing more
car-pooling.''
</P>
<P>
   That's challenge enough, according to Jordan. ``People have said
I won't have any challenges away from the game. Being a parent is
very challenging,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm basically just going to take it easy. . . . I'll live
vicariously through my kids, if they play the game of basketball. .
. . In the next step, there are a lot of different components. I
enjoy taking my kids to school and picking them up. Things that
seem so simple, I never got the opportunity to enjoy.''
</P>
<P>
   And for that reason, NBA commissioner David Stern said he
embraced Jordan's resignation. Jordan's reign had to end sometime.
``I get to say thank you for 29 teams and hundreds of millions of
fans,'' Stern said at the United Center. ``It's a great day because
the greatest player, ever, gets the opportunity to retire with the
grace that described your play.''
</P>
<P>
   To many people Wednesday, the scene was reminiscent of Jordan's
first ``retirement'' more than five years ago. That was at the
Berto Center in nearby Dearfield, Ill. This one took place at the
United Center, at midcourt of the playing floor. There was a
surreal feel to it, as Jordan sat at the makeshift stage,
resplendent in a dark suit, white shirt and elegant tie. He was
flanked by wife Juanita and Stern, with Reinsdorf at the send.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of media representatives from around the world were
present. So were several teammates from last year, although not
Scottie Pippen, whom Jordan met Monday night to tell him the news.
</P>
<P>
   The news is bad not only for the Bulls but also the NBA, which
needs Jordan's stately presence and appeal as it attempts to
recover from a six-month labor dispute that has disenchanted fans.
But saving the league was not Jordan's responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way to survive without Michael Jordan is to live without
him,'' Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   Out of the NBA spotlight, Jordan hopes his life will gain some
sense of normalcy, but he's not counting on it. No matter where he
goes, he expects to be beseiged by adoring fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot about my lifestyle I truly don't like,'' he said
without naming specifics. ``But I learned to deal with it. . . .
Hopefully, (the popularity) will subside some. . . . But I don't
think I can go into seclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Reinsdorf presented Jordan with his final championship ring and
re-unveiled his retired jersey No. 23, which was first put up in
the rafters in 1995 but wqas taken down at Jordan's request when he
came back.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no comeback likely this time, as Jordan leaves
behind a league in flux.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game,'' he said, ``is a lot bigger than Michael Jordan.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
