<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0450 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2136 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-DOLE-PRESIDENCY1     01-13 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-DOLE-PRESIDENCY14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Strong appeal for Dole as GOP candidate
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ Some potential GOP presidential candidates have
been campaigning for years in this bellwether state, but two
noncandidates have jumped way ahead of the pack _ George W. Bush
and Elizabeth Dole.
</P>
<P>
   In a presidential election cycle when Republican voters could
face a long list of candidates running to the right (including Pat
Buchanan and Dan Quayle), Dole is shaping up as Bush's major
challenger for the middle ground. In addition to competing for
votes, though, Dole and Bush would be competing for money,
volunteers and staffers aligned with the moderate wing of the
Republican Party. In that fight, momentum counts for a lot, and
right now, Dole has it.
</P>
<P>
   Now the folks who immerse themselves in New Hampshire primary
politics are watching to see if Dole is more than a passing
sensation. ``Those names have a lot of political equity here in the
state,'' pollster Kelly Myers of Portsmouth said of Bush and Dole.
The Bush or Dole name has been on every GOP ticket since the 1976
race when Bob Dole was Gerald Ford's running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Myers' poll, conducted for a Manchester TV station, puts Dole
and Bush way out front, each with about a third of the vote, and a
pack of other candidates with less than 7 percent each. Dole won
support from 31 percent of the 576 respondents contacted Jan. 8-11
for the WMUR poll, which has a margin of error of 4.1 percentage
points. Bush got 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the numbers dropped precipitously. Arizona Sen. John
McCain was third at 7 percent. Steve Forbes was at 5 percent, New
Hampshire Sen. Bob Smith was at 4 percent, Dan Quayle and Pat
Buchanan were at 3 percent, Lamar Alexander was at 2 percent and
John Kasich was at 1 percent. Tom Rath, a Concord lawyer and head
of the Alexander effort in New Hampshire, said the poll merely
captured the novelty of a possible Elizabeth Dole candidacy. She
resigned from the Red Cross last week, a move that touched off
speculation that she would run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week was all Elizabeth, all the time,'' Rath said. He
said Bush's popularity comes from his name, made famous by his job
as Texas governor and his father's former job as president.
</P>
<P>
   While Dole was garnering publicity, Bush had good things to say
about her as a contender and said her decision on whether to run
would have no bearing on his plans.
</P>
<P>
   Though the poll numbers come more than a year before New
Hampshire's first-in-the-nation primary, they come in a key state
that has a history of picking winners. Only twice since 1952 has
the winner of the GOP primary here failed to get the GOP
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a firestorm,'' New Hampshire GOP Chairman Steve
Duprey said of Dole's sudden rise.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire's Republican House Speaker Donna Sytek, who has
been taking a hard look at Bush, said she is now ``excited about
the prospect'' of Dole jumping in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd sure like to talk to those two people before I make a
decision,'' said Sytek, an Alexander backer in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Duprey, who will remain neutral in the primary, said Republicans
``are looking for new voices and new faces.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'll tell you what we are looking for more than anything
else, and that is a winner. I think people are excited by the
prospect of Elizabeth Dole,'' he said, noting that she is
well-known here through her speeches on husband Bob Dole's behalf
in 1996. ``The same is true, to a lesser degree, with Governor
Bush, who was up here campaigning for his dad all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   And while Bush supporters here are awaiting word on whether he
will run, Dole's potential candidacy is being championed here this
week by Earl Cox, a South Carolinian who has been running a draft
Dole movement for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   A similar Cox effort to get Colin Powell to run in 1996 failed.
</P>
<P>
   Cox is a former top official at the federal departments of
labor, agriculture and commerce in the Nixon, Ford and Reagan
administrations.
</P>
<P>
   For Cox, here to huddle with New Hampshire GOP officials,
victory _ interpreted as Dole getting in the race _ is near.
</P>
<P>
   Her resume _ devoid of any races for elected office _ is a plus,
Cox said. If she runs, Dole would be attempting to become the first
president since Dwight Eisenhower to win the White House without
ever holding elected office.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we have many good candidates that are running on the
Republican ticket, I believe that Elizabeth Dole would come into
the political arena with no baggage whatsoever,'' he said. ``When
the closets are opened up by reporters there will be no skeletons
jumping out.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to her Red Cross post, Dole served as secretary of
transportation in the Reagan administration, and secretary of labor
in the Bush administration.
</P>
<P>
   Though pleased that he is finding Republicans receptive to a
Dole candidacy, Cox is going out of his way not to say anything
negative about Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he is a gentleman and I think he has a lot to offer,
and I think it would be a good idea for George Bush to add his name
to the ballot,'' Cox said. ``It's not that Elizabeth Dole is better
than Governor Bush or any of the other candidates, but it just so
happens she reflects my personal views.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In 30-plus years in the political arena, with the exception of
Ronald Reagan, I have never, ever seen the enthusiasm for a
potential candidate as I have for Elizabeth Dole,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Though intrigued by her possible candidacy, several top
Republicans here say privately her best hope is to wind up as the
GOP's vice presidential candidate. Despite the latest poll,
insiders see Bush as a prohibitive _ if early _ favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Dole also could face a gender hurdle, according to a longtime
GOP activist here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if she is really strong enough to be president,''
said the activist, a woman. ``She is sort, and I like her, really a
Southern belle-style type of woman.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what anybody says,'' she added. ``You are still
going to have difficulty getting a women elected as president. I
think she make it better as a vice president than she can as
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
