u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAZIL-RDP-1STLD-WRIT     01-13 1282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-RDP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL DEVALUES CURRENCY; STOCKS PLUNGE BUT LATER RECOVER
SOMEWHAT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs to add first name for President Fernando Henrique Cardoso,
12th graf. Moves up graf to create new 4th graf to improve context.
Adds new 5th graf for more detail on market reaction. Adds new 7th
and 8th grafs to relate to Mexican crisis.)  (See also: BRAZIL-IMPACT, BRAZIL-HISTORY BRAZIL-BONDS, BRAZIL-U.S.,
BRAZIL-LATIN, MARKET) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(pr) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ Challenged by adversaries at home and
nervous investors abroad, the Brazilian government devalued the
nation's currency on Wednesday, allowing it to fall by more than 8
percent and triggering turbulence in financial markets around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   The action came after the surprise resignation of the president
of the central bank and a week of precipitous declines in the stock
market. In the first 12 minutes of trading on Wednesday, the key
Bovespa index dropped a stunning 10 percent, setting off an
automatic shutdown of trading. After the market reopened, shares
recovered somewhat, ending the day down 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty here revived investors' fears that Brazil's
renewed difficulties could create problems in neighboring
countries, undermine the International Monetary Fund's rescue
efforts or even lead to currency realignments throughout the
developing world.
</P>
<P>
   Since Russia's devaluation and partial debt default in August,
foreign investors and Government officials have expressed concern
that Brazil could also implode and drag the rest of Latin America
down with it, especially its partners in the Mercosur trading bloc,
notably Argentina. Brazil, the eighth-largest economy in the world,
is the locomotive for Latin American economies, which now absorb
one-fifth of United States exports.
</P>
<P>
   Stock markets in Europe dropped 3 to 5 percent on Wednesday and
elsewhere in Latin America by as much as 10 percent on the Brazil
news. In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 125.12
points. although broader indexes cut their losses as the session
wound down. United States Treasury bonds, long regarded as a haven
for investors at times of trouble, surged in value.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big question now is one of the credibility of the
government,'' said Edmar Bacha, a former government official, who
is now president of BBA Securities. ``The first impression of the
markets is: `Here we go; it's Mexico in December 1994 all over
again. They've opened the door, and there will be a flood.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bacha alluded to Mexico's decision late in 1994 to stop
defending its currency, the peso, as it was running out of dollars
amid a worsening imbalance in its foreign trade accounts. The peso
_ which was allowed to float at market value _ plunged, unnerving
foreign investors and pushing Mexico into a deep and painful
financial and economic crisis requiring an American-led bailout.
</P>
<P>
   While Brazil has not followed Mexico's path, it has resisted
suggestions that it devalue. So investors viewed the sharp drop in
the Brazilian currency, the real, on Wednesday as an ominous sign
that this devaluation could lead to a similar pattern. The
devaluation eases pressure on the Brazilian Government to spend its
reserves and keep interest rates high to defend the currency's
value. The Government described the action as a way to restore
consumer confidence and credibility among investors.
</P>
<P>
   Francisco Lopes, the newly designated president of the central
bank, opted for what Paulo Mallman, chief economist of Bic Banco in
Sao Paulo, called ``high-risk surgery.'' Since 1994, one key to
Brazil's economic growth and reduced inflation rate has been a
rigidly controlled and carefully calibrated exchange policy for the
nation's currency, the real. That will now be discarded in favor of
a more flexible approach, but one that is less predictable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The central bank should not be concerned with eventual
corrections in the real exchange rate,'' Lopes said on Wednesday at
a news conference in Brasilia. ``We believe that the real rate of
exchange is a phenomenon that should be determined by market forces
and should not be an objective of the central bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopes ruled out a maxi-devaluation, like the one in Mexico,
however, saying that would merely generate greater inflation,
traditionally the principal bugaboo of the Brazilian economy. He
estimated that Brazil had $45 billion in reserves and said the
government was willing to use both that money and interest rate
policy to defend what it considered a reasonable exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
   The new central bank head predicted that ``the maximum nominal
devaluation this year should remain between 12 and 15 percent.''
That would be approximately double the target of roughly 7 percent
that President Fernando Henrique Cardoso and his team set _ and
largely adhered to _ during their first term in office.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an atmosphere of sparks in the air, of anxiety,
speculation and suspicion of the government's ability to make good
its commitments to the IMF,'' Mallman said. ``People believed in
the stability of the exchange policy, and that confidence has now
been broken a bit. Everything that is going on leaves people
feeling less secure and more apprehensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about Congress' unwillingness to approve legislation
that Cardoso says is essential to reduce the huge government
deficit have also contributed to uneasiness here.
</P>
<P>
   In a boost to Cardoso, legislators approved four important
measures on Wednesday afternoon that would, among other things,
impose new taxes on financial transfers and corporate profits. The
measures are expected to generate more than $3 billion in revenues
and make up for shortfalls in other areas where the government has
been unable to carry out changes because of opposition resistance.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, President Clinton said he and members of his
economic team were closely monitoring the crisis in Brazil and had
been in contact with Brazilian authorities, the International
Monetary Fund and U.S. allies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a strong interest in seeing Brazil, with whom we have
worked on so many important things around the world, carry forward
with its economic reform plan and succeed, and we certainly hope
that they will,'' Clinton told reporters at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Cardoso, who began his second four-year term on Jan. 1,
dismissed as unreasonable any fears that Brazil could default on
the commitments it has made. ``The government has the means to meet
all of its obligations,'' he said. ``The government will always
honor all its internal and external obligations.''
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference, Cardoso described the latest measures as
a ``technical modification'' rather than a fundamental shift of
policy. ``This does not signify a change of direction,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But that explanation fell on deaf ears. Though banks here
continued to sell dollars at the very peak of the new trading band
established by the government, 1.32 reals to the dollar, most
currency exchanges were refusing to sell dollars at any price,
expecting that the real will weaken even further in days to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is certainly not a good sign that the real immediately went
to the ceiling of the new band,'' said Carlos Geraldo Langoni, a
former president of the central bank. ``This is an attempt to save
the existing exchange rate regimen, but its success depends on the
evaluation the market makes, so we will have to wait 15 days or
so.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
