<HEADLINE>
OIL REVOLUTION
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-798-0970 or fax at 310-798-7338; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 By THIERRY OGIER 
 c.1999 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    SAO PAULO, Brazil _ The Brazilian oil monopoly is finally
breaking up. The first joint venture deal was sealed last October
between the giant holding Petrobras and Argentina's oil company
YPF. The value of the contract, US$20 million, may be relatively
small, but this is only a hors d'oeuvre. Another partnership of
limited scope was established between Petrobras and U.S.-based
energy companies Coastal Corp. and Unocal, with initial investment
of $30 million.
 &HT;    ``Brazil offers significant investment opportunities for
Coastal,'' Coastal Chairman and CEO David Arledge said after the
agreement was announced.
 &HT;    The new petroleum regulatory agency has also announced which
fields will be open to free competition in the near future. The
state-owned giant will keep those areas where production has
already started, as well as several others where it has substantial
investment in research. But all in all, 90 percent of Brazilian
sedimentary basins will be opened to competition.
 &HT;    Tender documents were scheduled to be released by the end of
1998, with auctions for exclusive prospect and exploration rights
taking place in 1999, says David Zylbersztajn, director general of
the National Petroleum Agency (ANP). The new controllers of the
fields will then have three years to produce results.
 &HT;    Zylbersztajn expects more than $500 million from the first round
of auctions, and up to $7 billion in private investment in the next
five years.
 &HT;    Private cash is desperately needed. Brazil has boasted reserves
of 16 billion barrels, but most of them are located offshore in
deep waters, which make development very costly. Local production
is on the rise, but the current level of one million barrels per
day (bpd) still falls far short of average consumption, amounting
to 1.6 million bpd. The objective of the current opening policy is
to double Brazilian reserves and to guarantee self-sufficiency.
 &HT;    Zylbersztajn says that the equivalent of a further 90 billion
barrels could be discovered in Brazil, according to current
surveys. Most of the 29 sedimentary basins have remained unexplored
so far. Petrobras cannot meet the massive investment requirement
alone. All state-owned companies have seen their budgets slashed as
the result of the latest austerity drive.
 &HT;    While privatization is not formally on the government agenda,
Zylbersztajn has not ruled it out. ``It is a possibility,'' says
the 44-year-old director of the ANP, who had previously engineered
the privatization process of utilities in the state of S ao Paulo.
 &HT;    Although some 80 multinational oil companies have set up or
bolstered their presence in Rio de Janeiro in anticipation of the
new oil rush, progress toward formal commitments by the major
companies has been slower than anticipated.
 &HT;    ``Things are not happening as quickly as expected,'' says
Edmilson Santos, a professor at the oil department of the
University of Sao Paulo. ``Nor have they involved huge amounts of
money so far.''
 &HT;    The $1.5 billion that YPF has committed in investment is
targeted towards distribution, through the launch of a joint gas
station network with Petrobras both in Brazil and in Argentina.
``YPF has to get into Brazil. It is strategic for them. But that is
not enough for the others to follow,'' adds Santos.
 &HT;    There are two Brazilian factors and one external one that help
explain such caution. First, concession contracts have established
a period of three years for exploration rights, which is
deemedinsufficient by international investors. The ANP's
Zylbersztajn has admitted that this item may be reviewed. Second,
the level of taxation is deemed too high, at around 55 percent of
total revenue. Royalties were increased from 5 percent to 10
percent of sales with the market opening, and there are three other
categories of levies. Finally, investment risk in Brazil has
significantly increased.
 &HT;    Still, oil investors are thinking long term and have retained
their positive outlook. ``We have four or five contracts under
negotiations with Petrobras, but we will also compete in further
areas at the forthcoming government auctions,'' YPF President
Roberto Monti said during the signing ceremony in October. Added
Arledge: ``We firmly believe this will be the first of many
projects to be developed by Coastal in the years to come.''
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.1999 Latin Trade 
