</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONN-WITNESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH OF 8-YEAR-OLD A TESTAMENT TO VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BRIDGEPORT, Conn. _ He died at the top of the stairs, a little
boy who had seen what little boys should never see, shot in the
head after a routine run to the grocery store with his mother, who
was killed by bullets from the same gun.
</P>
<P>
   He loved basketball. He prided himself on dressing well. He
proudly displayed the products of an after-school crafts program _
treasured trinkets that his mother would fawn over when she picked
him up after work.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors and friends recall two things about 8-year-old Leroy
Brown Jr., this city's heartbreaking, terrible testament to
violence: He had a disarming smile that drew friends like a magnet.
And he was familiar with the flash of gunshots and the smell of
gunpowder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leroy was happy, enthusiastic. You'd see him bounce through
this neighborhood all the time,'' said Ronald Reed, a 16-year-old
junior at Bridgeport's Central High School, standing just yards
from where the bodies of Brown and his mother, 30-year-old Karen
Clarke, were discovered Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a typical, fun-loving 8-year-old,'' said Reed, staring
off blankly, his voice barely a whisper. ``What can you say? He'd
probably be still here if he hadn't seen what happened that day.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened to Leroy Brown and his mother is the talk of
Connecticut, where lawmakers are urgently reviewing guidelines
designed to safeguard witnesses, where police in the state's
largest city are investigating links to what Leroy saw and how he
was slain, and where family members are planning a funeral that
probably won't answer this simple, haunting question: Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any of us were prepared for something like
this,'' said the Rev. Courtney Williams, pastor of Refuge Temple
Church of God, where the mother-and-son funeral will be held
tonight. ``This act transcends race, culture, and even religion.
We're living in a very bad world that has just become so corrupt.
So corrupt.''
</P>
<P>
   The bloody trail that ended at a cedar-shingled duplex with a
basketball hoop in the driveway and a burglar-alarm notice on the
steps may have begun with a petty dispute over money that
culminated in gunfire on a September night in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   It was the day after Labor Day, and Leroy Brown was just along
for the ride.
</P>
<P>
   According to police and court documents, Brown, then 7, sat in
the back seat of a white Eagle Talon with another 7-year-old. The
boys had been at the Boys &AMP; Girls Club of Bridgeport, where they
played hoop and painted pictures. Karen Clarke's boyfriend and
intended husband, Rudolph Snead Jr., had picked them up at about 6
p.m. He was driving down Boston Avenue when a burgundy Chevy with
dark tinted windows pulled alongside.
</P>
<P>
   Snead told police that Russell Peeler, with whom he had argued
two weeks before, sat in the front passenger seat of the Chevrolet.
Snead sped off to evade Peeler, but by the time the cars had
reached Lindley Street, gunshots rang out. Police found a bullet
hole in the driver's side door. Another round grazed Snead's head.
Shattered glass littered Snead's car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both children appeared traumatized and were unwilling to talk
about the incident,'' a warrant for Peeler's arrest reads.
``Neither of the children complained or appeared to have been
injured during the shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   Snead later told authorities Peeler had leaned out his window
and begun firing at him from ``about a foot away'' _ close enough
for a back seat passenger to get a good look.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, little Leroy Brown had become a key witness in a case
of attempted murder, the charge authorities lodged against Peeler,
who was swiftly released on bail and just as swiftly reportedly
began making threats against Snead.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke told authorities that Peeler repeatedly vowed ``to get''
Snead. And that's exactly what happened, police said, eight months
after the drive-by shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities allege that Peeler, who turns 27 tomorrow, and
Snead, 28, met again on Boston Avenue, this time last May 29 in a
crowded barbershop.
</P>
<P>
   It was raining outside, and when the door opened, according to
witnesses, a black man holding a Glock semiautomatic handgun in his
left hand walked directly to the back of the shop where Snead was
on the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``This person then pointed a gun at Snead,'' court papers state.
``Snead was heard to say, `Oh man, go ahead with that (expletive).'
The person then fired several shots point blank at Snead.''
</P>
<P>
   After the gunman left, one witness said Snead gasped to
onlookers: ``It was Russell, yo.'' The witness said Snead ``was
trying to tell the people still in the shop that this was the
person who shot him.'' Snead died at Bridgeport Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Another eight months would elapse before still more gunshots
would evoke the Peeler and Snead case _ weeks of court rulings and
personal decisions that have led to a call for a statewide overhaul
of how Connecticut deals with those who commit crimes and those who
witness them.
</P>
<P>
   With Snead gunned down, Leroy Brown was the remaining witness to
the earlier drive-by shooting _ an episode authorities hope to link
to the barbershop slaying through testimony and forensic evidence
that, they say, shows the same gun was used in both attacks. The
other boy riding in the back seat with Leroy had apparently not
seen enough to be a witness, although authorities have now
contacted his parents to offer him protection, according to the
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, police moved to protect Brown, too. Clarke, who
worked in the traffic department at a U-Haul dealership in nearby
Orange, Conn., moved last summer into the duplex on Earl Avenue, a
dead-end street in a working-class neighborhood. She transferred
Leroy to a new school. For a while, police patrols were assigned to
keep watch over them.
</P>
<P>
   By some accounts, Clarke concluded the police patrols were a
neighborhood nuisance and asked that they be stopped. Critics of
the authorities' handling of the case say it is far from clear that
Clarke made that request. In any event, police surveillance was
stopped.
</P>
<P>
   That decision and a judge's ruling to let Peeler _ already out
on bail for the attempted murder charge _ post a $900,000 bail
after Snead's killingWednesday prompted a call Wednesday from
leading state lawmakers to heighten surveillance of suspects out on
bail and to streamline Connecticut's witness protection program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the state determined that this child was an eyewitness,
they placed him in harm's way. As a state and as a society, we
failed and we failed miserably,'' said state Representative
Christopher Caruso, a Democrat from Bridgeport. ``We have to find
out where the system broke down. Young Leroy Brown is telling us a
story here and it's incumbent on us to listen to what's being
said.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Police here have been careful to say that while Peeler has
not been ruled out as a suspect in last week's killings, neither is
he a main suspect. Peeler, who is required to wear an electronic
monitoring bracelet as a condition of bail, has denied through his
attorney and family members any involvement in the slayings.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut Post, quoting sources, has described Peeler as a
member of a local drug gang, and said he was spotted outside the
home of Clarke and Brown just days before they were killed.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies, found a few feet apart, were discovered after
Clarke's co-worker got worried when she did not show up for work.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had to be some kind of animal to do what he did, is all I
can tell you,'' said Louis Messina, a 79-year-old crossing guard at
Read School, where Leroy was a third-grader. ``Anyone who does that
to an 8-year-old deserves to be hanged. To tell you the truth,
Bridgeport is going down. It used to be one of the best cities in
the whole state of Connecticut, but now people are scared.''
</P>
<P>
   Rev. Williams said that when authorities searched the duplex,
they found Clarke's Bible on her bedstand open to the book of
Psalms, Chapter 20, which begins: ``The Lord hear thee in the day
of trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty sad that this young boy and Karen had to be
sacrificed in order to get the attention of our lawmakers,''
Williams said. ``Perhaps this will bring about a change in our laws
that will bring more security to our people _ not just the rich and
the famous and the upper echelons of society _ but the poor and the
disenfranchised.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
