<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2159 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-EDGE14-CO     01-13 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-EDGE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons jab, then throw deep
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Falcons rushed the ball 51.9 percent of
their plays this season, second-highest in the NFL, so the
perception that Dan Reeves' offense is stodgy and predictable was
perpetuated for another season.
</P>
<P>
   But the reality of the Falcons offense, as discovered by
Minnesota Vikings defensive coordinator Foge Fazio during his
Monday videotape review, is that the Falcons passing game has as
much ``verticality'' as any in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their signature is of a physical team, and Jamal (Anderson)
rates as one of the great backs in the league,'' Fazio said. ``But
what sometimes gets overlooked is just how accurate their
quarterback is and how well they throw deep. They want you to
commit to the run, then they sneak one of those wide receivers
behind you, usually off play-action. What most jumped out at us is
how effective they are with the deep ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons ranked sixth in both catches for 25 yards or more
(35) and yardage after the catch (1,577). But a key stat lost in
the shuffle of the Anderson-led ground stampede is that the Falcons
led the NFL in average yards per completion. Atlanta's gaudy
average of 15.8 yards was more than two yards better than runner-up
Minnesota (13.7). More significantly, it was the highest average in
the league since the Raiders posted a 16.3-yard mark in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Most teams attempt to stretch a defense down the field with
speed, using sprinters to fray the edges of the secondary. But
while Terance Mathis enhanced his quickness at age 31 by working
out with a personal trainer in the offseason, the nine-year pro
still is not regarded as a burner. And most scouts think that
partner Tony Martin has lost half a step.
</P>
<P>
   However, they share a veteran savvy that allows them to take
advantage of most coverages, and the Falcons staff does an
excellent job of picking its spots to throw the deep pass. The
success of the passing game, in fact, is as much a factor of design
as it is physical talent.
</P>
<P>
   By using Anderson as a human bludgeon, the Falcons want to force
their opponent to commit an extra man to run defense. Typically
that means bringing an eighth defender, the strong safety, closer
to the line of scrimmage. While that move allows at least one
defender to go unblocked against the run, it also creates natural
weaknesses in the secondary. The Falcons do a nice job of finding
and exploiting those voids in the pass defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because you have to respect their run so much,'' Vikings
strong safety Robert Griffith said, ``you sacrifice something in
(pass) coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   The Viking ranked just 19th against the pass this season, for
two reasons: The secondary, especially on the corners, has been
suspect since the first day of camp, and Minnesota does not exert
much pressure with its four-man rush.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings' secondary was banged up in last week's victory.
Starting free safety Orlando Thomas aggravated a hamstring injury
and missed much of the game. Nickel cornerback Ramos McDonald also
is nursing a hamstring pull and Griffith has a strained back and
sore neck. Because of the injuries, the Vikings were forced to play
Anthony Bass, who logged only two snaps from scrimmage during the
regular season, as their nickel safety.
</P>
<P>
   The problems with the nickel might not be as severe against the
Falcons, whose third wide receivers haven't been productive.
Quarterback Chris Chandler is better in two-wideout base sets. When
Atlanta used two wideouts this season, Chandler completed 64.5
percent of his attempts and his passer rating was 117.5. With three
wideouts, he completed just 47.7 percent and his passer rating was
71.2.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons typically use a lot of maximum-protection blocking,
keeping their backs and a tight end in to insulate Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
