u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-NYT &LR;      01-13 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN FINANCE BACKERS READY A NEW PUSH FOR OVERHAUL 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The leading congressional sponsors of legislation
to overhaul the way political campaigns are financed said Wednesday
that they would push hard for their bills this year so that new
restrictions could be in place for the elections in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But the sponsors conceded that it would be difficult for the
measures to avoid the fate of campaign finance legislation last
year, when a bill was passed by the House of Representatives but
died in a filibuster in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   At a briefing for congressional aides who work on the campaign
finance issue, Reps. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., and Martin Meehan,
D-Mass., said it was important to get a bill through the House
early in the year to force the Senate's hand.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that can happen depends in large part on the attitude of
the House Republican leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders on both sides of the Capitol adamantly oppose
the measures sponsored by Shays and Meehan in the House and by
Sens. John McCain, R-Ariz., and Russell Feingold, D-Wis. The main
elements of the legislation would outlaw soft money, the unlimited
and largely unregulated donations to political parties that have
proliferated in recent election campaigns, and would curb
commercials by outside groups masked as issue advocacy
advertisements in the 60 days before elections.
</P>
<P>
   Last year House Republican leaders threw up a series of
obstacles in an effort to block campaign finance legislation. Early
in the year they prohibited the Shays-Meehan measure from being
debated during consideration of related legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Later, after the sponsors had demonstrated that they had the
votes to bring their bill to the floor over the leadership's
opposition, the leaders made sure the bill was open to almost
limitless amendments, was forced to compete with 10 less
restrictive alternatives and was under consideration only
sporadically.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, after 10 weeks of off-and-on debate, the House
approved the Shays-Meehan bill on Aug. 3 by a comfortable margin,
237-186.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Shays said he received assurances late last
year from Rep. Robert Livingston, who was then set to become
speaker, that the bill would not face such rigorous and unusual
hurdles this year. Shays said that he had not had the opportunity
to discuss the matter with Rep. Dennis Hastert, who was elected
speaker after Livingston withdrew, but that he was confident
Hastert would take a similar view.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have proved we have the votes,'' Shays said. ``Why have it
fester and destroy good will among members? Let's get it out of
here and let the Senate deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Michele Davis, a spokeswoman for the House majority leader, Rep.
Dick Armey, R-Texas, said that campaign finance was one of the
topics on this year's agenda but that the leadership had not
focused on when or how it might be dealt with.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, there is scant evidence that the sponsors'
position is much stronger than it was last year, when they were
never able to muster more than 52 votes, 8 shy of the 60 needed, to
end the Republican filibuster.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Feingold said they would introduce their bill early
in the new session. ``Clearly we're going to address the issue this
year, no doubt,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a chance for success?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a long haul,'' he said, ``but sooner or later
we're going to prevail.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
