<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2161 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES14-C     01-13 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Volume cranked up to prepare for noise
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Falcons began preparing for Sunday's NFC
Championship Game against the Vikings in the Metrodome by placing
two large speakers on either side of the practice field Wednesday,
blaring tape of a Boeing 757 jet engine.
</P>
<P>
   It will be the loudest stadium Atlanta has played in this
season, but the tape was not any louder Wednesday than it has been
in practice before every road game this season.
</P>
<P>
   When quarterback Chris Chandler has to change plays at the line
of scrimmage Sunday, he'll do it a few ways. He'll yell changes to
his line and make hand signals to receivers and backs _ although
few of the changes impact receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, you come up with some sort of signals, and you walk
up and down behind the line telling them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler said there will not be a special effort to get out of
the huddle faster just so he has extra time to make the changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so much us getting out of the huddle faster, as it is
(quarterbacks coach) Jack Burns stepping up and getting the plays
in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcon offense worked against a play clock in practice
Wednesday, as usual, and worked on hand signals from coach Dan
Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   If the radios don't work Sunday, or if Chandler can't hear
backup quarterback Steve DeBerg relaying plays in once Burns calls
them to the sideline, those hand signals will be crucial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always try to have a pretty quick rhythm. We want to give
him enough lead time where Chris can regulate his own pace _ where
he can slow down or speed up as he sees fit,'' Burns said. ``We
want him to be able to get up to the line and take time to read
everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you make his time frame slower by getting the plays in
slower ... it forces him to hurry. We don't want to do that at the
line of scrimmage.''
</P>
<P>
   Practice schedule
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons practiced at team headquarters in Suwanee, but if it
rains today or looks like it will, Reeves said the team will
practice at the Georgia Dome. They worked out there three times
last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Practice was good. Our concentration was good,'' Reeves said.
``We had some mistakes, but they were minimized.''
</P>
<P>
   Critical development
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons led the NFL in time of possession, holding the ball
an average of 33:10 per game. But if they are going to win Sunday,
they'll need to do more than just keep the ball away from a Vikings
offense that set a league record by scoring 520 points
</P>
<P>
   ``That's going to be a key for us,'' Reeves said, ``to come away
with seven points rather than three.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking back
</P>
<P>
   The only other time the Falcons played the Vikings in the
playoffs, Minnesota won 30-24 on Jan. 9, 1983. Afterward, the late
Falcons owner and founder Rankin Smith Sr. fired coach Leeman
Bennett, who had a 46-41 record in six seasons. That stretch
included a 12-4 season in 1980, when the Falcons won their only
other NFC West title.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta made its first three playoff appearances under Bennett,
in 1978, '80 and '82. This year is just the third in 16 seasons
since that the Falcons have made it to the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Extra points
</P>
<P>
   Add Barrow County to the list of potential suitors if the
Falcons opt to move team headquarters. Falcons director of
corporate development Tommy Nobis met Wednesday with members of the
Barrow County Commission. Nothing is close to happening, however,
on this front. ... This will be Reeves' 15th AFC or NFC
Championship Game. He was 0-2 as a player with the Cowboys, 5-3 as
an assistant with Dallas and 3-1 as head coach of the Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   Whither DeBerg?
</P>
<P>
   DeBerg, who came out of a four-year retirement to resume his
playing career at age 44, said he plans to return next season. His
contract expires after this season, but he said he wants to play
again, and he'd prefer it be in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I know I am (going to play),'' DeBerg said. ``I
can't think of a better place. It's too much fun.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
