<HEADER>
A2163 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS14-COX     01-13 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons fever: Atlanta's shocked, overjoyed by sudden ascent of
football team
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ So maybe they lied.
</P>
<P>
   A franchise more notorious for losing than anything else in its
history hikes off to Minnesota this weekend in pursuit of a
preposterous destiny, and if this sounds like the start of the
1990s rather than the tail end, well, there you are.
</P>
<P>
   Where the Atlanta Braves first walked in 1991, the Atlanta
Falcons follow now, a disregarded urchin suddenly stalking a title,
and all the pundits, critics and armchair sociologists who
described that 1991 journey as Atlanta's once-in-a-lifetime thrill,
hah! It's happening again in the same place for some of the same
people.
</P>
<P>
   If you're not on the bandwagon by now, be prepared to scrunch in
the middle. All the window and aisle seats are long gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took some time but I think the people are getting into
it,'' said Roland Henderson, 27, nursing a late-afternoon beer at
the Racoon Lodge in Buckhead Wednesday. ``I know most of my friends
are psyched. This town is going to go nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, tell me about it in five years,'' said friend Jeff Burns
from the next stool. Burns, an old Browns fan visiting from Ohio,
is not impressed. ``What have they won?''
</P>
<P>
   The NFC West. But Burns' skepticism is a shared one, as the
Falcons' rush into the sublime has occurred while much of the
city's back was seemingly turned. Even for December games, the
Georgia Dome failed to sell out. But perhaps one man's indifference
can be another's euphoria.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the fans on an overwhelming basis are tickled that the
Falcons have accomplished what they already have because to them,
it's totally unexpected,'' said former All-Pro tackle Mike Kenn,
fresh from presiding over a budget meeting in his new job as
chairman of the Fulton County Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``That just increases the excitement level of it. If they win _
and as long as you're in a game, you have a chance to win _ I think
that euphoria would turn into giddiness.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hubert H. Humphrey Metrodome is an appropriate venue Sunday,
because for many, it was there the Falcons franchise lost its way
following the 1982 season. Leeman Bennett coached his last game
there in a 30-24 Vikings' first-round playoff victory that set in
motion's Bennett's firing. To many, the club only now has regained
its feet. To just a few, the promise of the Bennett regime is
glowing again.
</P>
<P>
   ``My memory's not gone to the point where I can't recall how
much fun that was,'' Kenn said. ``Anyone who has played football
for the Falcons would like to turn back the clock and be involved
in this process, no one more than I.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite periodic meddling in the postseason, nearly a generation
has passed since the Falcons' constructed a true contender. To
some, this may be the law of averages coming around. To others,
it's in the water.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
