<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2165 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-DOCUMENTS-BOS     01-13 1665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-DOCUMENTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON BREAKS SILENCE, SPEAKING OF LONELINESS ON TRIAL EVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER AND ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, with his fate beyond his control
on the eve of opening arguments in his impeachment trial, broke his
recent silence on the political drama Wednesday and alluded to the
lonely nature of his perilous place in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opinion is not important here,'' said Clinton, who is not
expected to testify or directly participate in the first
presidential impeachment trial in 131 years.
</P>
<P>
   Just minutes after his lawyers filed a 130-page trial brief
arguing against his conviction, Clinton said he spends ``as little
time as possible thinking about'' the trial and can do little more
than ``trust that the right thing will be done.''
</P>
<P>
   House managers will open a three-day, nationally televised
presentation at 1 p.m. Thursday to argue that two articles of
impeachment against Clinton warrant his ``conviction, removal from
office, and disqualification from holding further office.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Senate will not vote until later this month on
whether to permit witnesses in the trial, the House managers, who
act as prosecutors, said that they already have begun trying to
interview prospective witnesses, including Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is charged with lying under oath to a federal grand jury
and obstructing justice in trying to cover up his sexual affair
with Lewinsky, who was a 22-year-old White House intern when the
relationship began.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky declined, through her lawyers, to be interviewed, the
House managers said. And they braced for criticism of their early
contacts with Lewinsky's lawyers and other prospective witnesses,
including Kathleen E. Willey, who said Clinton groped her near the
Oval Office in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``The committee is duty bound to gather all relevant evidence
and to be thoroughly prepared to present its case to the Senate,''
Paul McNulty, a spokesman for the House managers, said in a
statement  &UR; last night &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Later, Representative Henry J. Hyde, the lead manager, told
reporters he also is considering asking the Senate to invite
Clinton to testify.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all interested in hearing from the president as a
witness,'' Hyde said. ``The question is whether we should call him
or not. That hasn't been resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House indicated that Clinton does not intend to
testify.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Clinton's lawyers, in one of their most scathing legal
briefs to date, assailed the charges against him as an excessive
response to the president's infidelity.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the final analysis,'' Clinton's lawyers wrote, ``the House
is asking the Senate to remove the president because he had a
wrongful relationship and sought to keep the existence of that
relationship private.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House lawyers added: ``The Senate has an obligation to
turn away an unwise and unwarranted misuse of the awesome power of
impeachment. If the Senate removes this president for a wrongful
relationship he hoped to keep private, for what will the House ask
the Senate to remove the next president and the next?''
</P>
<P>
   House managers, responding in a terse, four-page memorandum to a
pretrial brief the White House filed Monday, denied ``each and
every material allegation'' that Clinton's lawyers made in
rebutting the charges.
</P>
<P>
   The managers also submitted the complete record of the House
impeachment proceedings, including grand jury transcripts and tape
recordings gathered by the independent counsel, Kenneth W. Starr,
during the eight-month investigation into the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lawyers, with their three-day opening arguments
scheduled to begin Tuesday, can do little this week but watch
silently as the trial unfolds amid broad public opposition to
removing the president from office and keen concern in both parties
about any political consequences.
</P>
<P>
   The White House legal team will have 24 hours over three days
next week to present its case. Under a tentative schedule, the
Senate will then have 16 hours over two days to question lawyers on
both sides.
</P>
<P>
   After that, possibly on Jan. 25, the White House is expected to
file a motion to dismiss the charges, and the House is expected to
request permission to subpoena witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Most senators and House managers believe there are too few votes
in the Senate to convict Clinton, which would require a two-thirds
majority, or 67 votes. A conviction on either charge automatically
would remove him from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I know how David felt against Goliath,'' said
Representative Lindsey O. Graham of South Carolina, a House manager
who will argue that the charges rise to the standard of ``high
crimes and misdemeanors.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the senators ``keep open minds, which I believe they
will, and we can really get into the heart of the criminality here,
things may change,'' Graham said. ``It changed in the House.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who approved his legal team's brief several days ago,
portrayed himself as largely removed from the process. ``I should
be doing my job for the country,'' he said as he met with labor
leaders at the White House to discuss his State of the Union
address next Tuesday. ``Other people should be handling the defense
and dealing with this issue, and that's what I intend to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he will not mention impeachment in the State of the
Union speech, which he will deliver just hours after his lawyers
complete their first day of defense arguments in the Senate trial.
``I think the American people have heard about that quite
extensively over the last year,'' he said. ``I think they would
like it if somebody up here were putting their interests first,
their business first, and I think that's what they expect me to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's comments marked a reversal of recent weeks, as White
House aides have distanced him from reporters, fearing a possible
backlash from senators if something he said were misconstrued.
</P>
<P>
   Against the trial's political backdrop, several Republican
senators who participated last week in a crucial compromise on a
blueprint for the trial Wednesday criticized some Democratic
colleagues for ``prejudging'' the case in Clinton's favor.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats fired back. ``I suppose one could say the same thing
about Republicans,'' said Senator Kent Conrad, a North Dakota
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Senator John F. Kerry, who is weighing a possible bid for the
Democratic presidential nomination, said some Republicans are
viewing the trial through a political lens, with an eye on gaining
an advantage in the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of political strategy going on, all of which I
think is wrong, all of which is damaging to the Constitution, and
all of which I think will come home to roost with them when the
American people get to express their disgust the next time they go
to the polls,'' Kerry said.
</P>
<P>
   After reading the House's pretrial brief, Kerry criticized the
White House for attacking the document as ``reading like a cheap
mystery.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kerry was not much more charitable in assessing the House's
work. ``I don't call it a cheap mystery novel,'' Kerry said. ``I
think it's a misguided, sort of strange view of a legitimate set of
concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Democrat, Senator Joseph I. Lieberman of Connecticut,
said his colleagues should not ignore the public opinion polls,
despite their pledge to act as impartial jurors. ``Obviously no
senator should be controlled in his or her decision in this trial
by the public opinion polls,'' he said. ``But I do think it's
appropriate to take notice of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Senate guidelines, all 100 members must sit silently hour
after hour, day after day, as one House member and White House
lawyer after another argues the case, with Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist presiding. The senators also must hold all their
deliberations behind closed doors, including debate on motions and,
ultimately, on the articles of impeachment, although the votes will
be in open session.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy said he will support a motion to
permit the public to view the deliberations. Republican leaders and
some Democrats oppose the motion, which requires the approval of a
two-thirds majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's enormously important that the American people be
included in this process,'' Kennedy said. ``Their involvement is
all part of the closure of the process.''
</P>
<P>
   White House lawyers, in their brief Wednesday, essentially
compiled a compendium of their previous arguments, although they
added details aimed at undermining the House case.
</P>
<P>
   The document relies heavily not only on legal precedents for
impeachment cases but also on the opinions of constitutional and
legal scholars, including more than 400 who signed a joint
statement against impeachment. The statement buttressed the White
House argument that the charges involve private misconduct, not
public conduct that would be impeachable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Impeachment was never intended to be a remedy for private
wrongs,'' the lawyers wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Attempting to exploit the nearly party-line impeachment votes in
the House, the lawyers added: ``The closeness and partisan division
of the votes reflect the constitutionally dubious nature of the
charges.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House lawyers also warned of a prolonged trial if the
Senate authorizes House managers to call even a single witness. And
they urged senators to consider the results of the 1996 election,
which Clinton won handily. ``The vote the American people rendered
. . . is hanging in the balance,'' the lawyers wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Representative F. James Sensenbrenner Jr. of Wisconsin, who will
deliver the opening statement for the House managers, remained
unswayed by the White House argument but uncertain about the
outcome. ``I think our case is very solid,'' he said, ``if people
will listen.''
</P>
<P>
   (Anne E. Kornblut of the Globe staff contributed to this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
