<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2167 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-JORDAN-RDP-ART-NY     01-13 1296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JORDAN-RDP-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTHING MORE TO PLAY FOR
</HEADLINE>
   (See also BKN-JORDAN-RHODEN-COLUMN, BKN-JORDAN-PLAYERS,
BKN-JORDAN-KNICKS.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic on chronology of Jordan's NBA years is being sent
to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The deciding factor was not the sordid state of the
National Basketball Association after the lockout, or even an old
and bitter feud with team management. In the end, Michael Jordan
said his basketball career was over because an undeniable feeling
would not go away:
</P>
<P>
   With every challenge met, he no longer had the desire to play.
</P>
<P>
   On the same court where he spun the world on his fingertips and
brought the Chicago Bulls along for an improbable ride, Jordan
officially said goodbye Wednesday. To the franchise. To his
teammates. And, finally, to the game he helped transport to another
galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mentally, I'm exhausted,'' Jordan said at a news conference on
the United Center floor. ``I know, from a career standpoint, I've
accomplished everything I could as an individual. Right now, I just
don't have the mental challenges that I've had in the past to
proceed as a basketball player. This is perfect time for me to walk
away from the game. And I'm at peace with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounding confident and definitive about his decision, Jordan
said he had been contemplating this day in earnest since leading
the Bulls to their sixth championship in eight seasons last June.
He left the smallest window of opportunity open when he said he was
99.9 percent sure he would not return for a second time, but at 35
years old he seemed content to not play again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never say never, but 95 ... 99.9 percent I'm very secure
with my decision,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The news of his retirement had been expected for 48 hours, but
the actual announcement set off a flurry of reaction. From the
White House to gymnasiums across America, and in headlines around
the world, homage was paid to the most accomplished basketball
player ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's appropriate that the sports fans around America
take a day or two to `ooh' and `ahh' and hold their breath again
and be glad again,'' President Clinton said of Jordan, the
third-leading scorer in NBA history with 29,277 points.
</P>
<P>
   Said Miami Heat Coach Pat Riley, ``The NBA, the fans, the
players, the coaches, American society and history are losing the
greatest influence that sports has ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   The scene at the United Center featured a sea of cameras,
photographers, reporters and former teammates and friends of
Jordan's. In what was referred to often as the largest retirement
event for a sports figure _ more than 500 credentials were issued
to members of the news media _ Jordan led a procession down Section
120 about 11:15 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Seated beside him were his wife, Juanita _ who said she expected
him to be available to carpool their children more often _ NBA
Commissioner David Stern and Bulls Chairman Jerry Reinsdorf.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony had neither the emotion nor the reminiscing that
usually accompany such events. Jordan began by trying to put things
in perspective, sending his condolences to the family of a Chicago
police officer killed recently in the line of duty; the officer's
funeral was also Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   He then made a statement: ``I am here to announce my retirement
from the game of basketball.'' And he tried to answer the obvious
question for a performer still hitting the highest notes in his
profession: why?
</P>
<P>
   Saying he began to contemplate retirement after shooting down
Utah in the NBA finals last June, Jordan said he spoke to Reinsdorf
after the season, intimating that the energy spent winning a third
straight championship had taken its toll.
</P>
<P>
   Reinsdorf, he said, told him to take his time deciding to make
sure that his second retirement in five years would be final. And
there was another factor in Jordan's decision: retiring on top.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to Patrick, I've talked to Charles, I've talked to
Karl, I've talked to all of them,'' he said of Patrick Ewing,
Charles Barkley and Karl Malone, All-Star players without a
championship. ``I'm pretty sure they feel the same. They all wanted
me to come back, just so if they win a championship they can say
they've gone through Chicago and Michael Jordan to win it. That's
the good thing about it. And they won't ever have the chance to say
that. That's why I was so glad that Magic played and Bird played
when I won my titles. Because I had to go through, to some degree,
Boston and L.A.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patrick, I don't know. He won't be able to live with himself.
He can't beat Michael Jordan in a series. Charles Barkley, I told
him he would never win because he doesn't dedicate himself to
winning. All of them joked with me and hated to see the possibility
of me retiring just because they didn't have an opportunity to beat
me in the finals or get past me. That's the cute thing about
retiring. I will always hold that in high respect when I see these
guys socially.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, who had taken great pains over the past year to say he
would play for no other coach than Phil Jackson and who openly
criticized General Manager Jerry Krause and Reinsdorf, did not use
the organization as a scapegoat. Instead, he praised the Bulls and
thanked Reinsdorf for the chance to play. He also said his decision
was not influenced by the six-month lockout that fostered
disenchantment among fans and resulted in the league's first work
stoppage in 52 years.
</P>
<P>
   Of the chance he would play for Jackson if he returned, Jordan
said: ``That's a big if. I retired the first time when Phil Jackson
was the coach. I think that even with Phil the coach, I would have
a tough time mentally finding the challenge for myself. I can't
really say he would have restored that.''
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement, Jackson said: ``For our own selfish
reasons, we never wanted to see Michael Jordan retire. He
represented our personal flights of fantasy about what great things
an individual can do, and he made it look so easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Reinsdorf: ``This is the day I hoped would never come. This
has to be the toughest day in the history of the Chicago Bulls, a
tough day for the city of Chicago, a tough day for the NBA, a tough
day for basketball fans all over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern followed Reinsdorf and said: ``I disagree with Jerry. This
is a great day. The greatest basketball player in the history of
the game is getting the opportunity to retire with the grace that
described his play.''
</P>
<P>
   With the decision, the world's most prominent sports figure goes
from Air time to spare time. Jordan, who leaves with the highest
career scoring average in league history, 31.5 points, said he
would devote more time to his three children and family, and
perfect his golf game. Despite a severed tendon in his finger,
suffered when he was cutting a cigar, Jordan has agreed to play
next week in the Bob Hope Chrysler Classic in LaQuinta, Calif. He
also has an invitation to play in the AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach Pro Am in
early February.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people say, well, Michael doesn't have any challenges
away from the game of basketball,'' said Jordan, a five-time NBA
most valuable player. ``Well, I dispute that. Being a parent is
very challenging. If you have kids, you know that. I welcome that
challenge and I look forward to it. I will live vicariously through
my kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan took his children to school Wednesday morning, and tried
to contemplate life without basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was difficult because you're giving up something that you
truly, truly love,'' he said. ``My love for the game is very
strong. It's hard to give up that love.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 2203EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
