<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2168 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAZIL-BANK-BOS &LR;      01-13 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-BANK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETS PLUNGE, MONTHS AFTER $41.5B BAILOUT, AS BANK CHIEF QUITS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ This time, Brazil has only itself to blame.
</P>
<P>
   The economic bandage that had been delicately holding together
Latin America's largest economy ripped open Wednesday, amid news
that Brazil's central bank chief unexpectedly resigned and that the
country devalued its currency by nearly 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's volatility reminded many of the panic that swept
through Brazil in September, when markets dived and investors
pulled billions of dollars out of the country. At the time,
Brazilian officials blamed the reaction on uncertainty created by
crises in Asia and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-November, a few weeks after President Fernando Henrique
Cardoso was overwhelmingly reelected to a second term, the
International Monetary Fund and other lenders approved a $41.5
billion loan package for Brazil. The lenders expressed confidence
that the administration could fix the economy by reducing its
budget deficit, which now hovers around 8 percent of gross domestic
product.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, the cause of the anxiety seems rooted in
Brazil's own economic and political problems. In addition to the
instability caused by the resignation of Brazil's top bank official
and the currency devaluation, Cardoso has been unable to get
crucial constitutional reforms through the congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brazil's problems probably usher in a new round of global
contagion,'' Merrill Lynch chief economist Bruce Steinberg told
Reuters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of Latin America will now fall into recession, there
could be spillover effects into other emerging markets, and
questions have to be raised about US and European growth and
earnings prospects.''
</P>
<P>
   In Sao Paulo, the Bovespa index, Latin America's largest stock
market, reacted to the news by plunging 10 percent at Wednesday's
opening bell. The frantic sell-off triggered an electronic
circuit-breaker that suspended trading for 30 minutes. The market
ended the day down 5.05 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Other Latin American markets reacted with similar fear. The
Mexico City exchange fell 4.6 percent. The Buenos Aires market in
Argentina dropped 10.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Since last summer, Brazil has lost more than $40 billion in
foreign capital and another $1.2 billion left on Tuesday. During
the same period, the country's reserves have dwindled to about $35
billion from more than $50 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The first shock Wednesday was Gustavo Franco's resignation. He
was immediately replaced by Francisco Lopes, another highly
regarded central banker, whose first action was to allow Brazil's
currency, the real, to trade at a more flexible rate against the US
dollar. The move amounted to a devaluation.
</P>
<P>
   Although the devaluation was meant to calm anxious investors,
who believed the Brazilian currency was overvalued, many saw it as
a troubling sign that the country's nagging financial problems are
getting worse.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, an opposition governor, Itamar Franco of the eastern
industrial state of Minas Gerais, stopped payments on state loans,
and demanded that the Cardoso government refinance the state's $15
billion debt. Two other states have threatened to stop loan
payments. That has raised more concerns about political support for
Cardoso, who succeeded Franco as president, and about whether
Brazil will be able to keep its deficit-cutting commitments as part
of its agreement to the IMF package.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government will honor all its domestic and foreign
contracts,'' Cardoso asserted in a nationally televised speech
Wednesday from Brasilia, the nation's capital. ``Rules are made to
be followed.''
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Campos, a Sao Paulo-based economist, said that although
the Brazilian economy remains fairly strong, the Cardoso government
may be forced to take further action to avoid continued capital
flight and market losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take more than simply replacing the top person at the
central bank,'' said Campos. Cardoso ``will either have to force
the opposition to go along or be flexible enough to negotiate with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico, which went through its own currency crisis in 1994
and has suffered recently from record-low oil prices, the impact of
Wednesday's events were felt immediately. Mexico's currency, the
peso, weakened so much against the dollar that the central bank
stepped in to protect it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico has more discipline in its economic and fiscal
structure that it seems Brazil is trying to achieve,'' one Mexican
central bank official said Wednesday on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that doesn't mean we don't feel instability,'' the
official said. ``Just that we have less reason to panic right
now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
