<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2170 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKETS-BRAZIL-BOS &LR;      01-13 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKETS-BRAZIL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETS STRUGGLE TO DEAL WITH BRAZIL SITUATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER G. GOSSELIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The global economic crisis returned with a vengeance
Wednesday as Brazil flirted anew with a financial disaster that US
policy makers and others seemed powerless to avert.
</P>
<P>
   The Latin American nation has been struggling, with the
assistance of a $41.5 billion, US-orchestrated aid package, to
protect its currency from the kind of economy-destroying assault
that has swept Asia and other developing regions over the past 18
months.
</P>
<P>
   But the effort proved so politically painful by Wednesday that
the nation's central bank president abruptly quit; his successor
agreed to let the country's currency, the real, slide 7.6 percent
against the US dollar; and traders promptly drove the currency's
value still lower.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers took heart because world financial markets were
not nearly as panicky Wednesday as they were during the last
international crisis, when Russia devalued its currency and
defaulted on foreign debt in August.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the Dow Jones industrial average lost 12 percent of its
value in a matter of a few weeks, including 512 points in a single
day. By contrast, after an initial fright, during which the Dow
tumbled about 260 points, the bellwether market index recovered its
balance and finished off 125.12 points, or a mere 1.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But economists cautioned that the market's comparatively
tempered reaction hardly means that Brazil's problems are now
contained. Most predicted the country's troubles will push its
region into recession and will hurt already embattled US exporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brazil is really the dominant economy in South America and its
problems will have (ripple) effects on its neighbors and therefore
on us,'' said Jeffrey J. Schott, a senior fellow with the Institute
for International Economics in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Although Brazil bought only 2.3 percent of US exports in 1997,
the last year for which full figures are available, Central and
South America accounted for a much more substantial 21 percent of
exports, according to the Commerce Department. And while US exports
generally have grown a respectable 63 percent during the decade,
exports to the region have grown at almost twice that rate.
</P>
<P>
   Besides damaging important markets for US goods, analysts said
that there remains a danger of a repeat of last fall's brief, but
frightening global financial freeze-up. Market watchers said
Brazil's failure to right its economy could prompt investors to
give up on all but the very safest stocks and bonds, a move that
would leave developing nations without money to grow. And they
warned that a stampede from the Brazilian currency could provoke a
similar run on another overvalued currency _ China's _ a move that
could start the cycle of financial and economic disarray that
begain in Asia in mid-1997 all over again.
</P>
<P>
   ``A deterioration of Brazil's currency and economy would have
severe contagion effects around the world,'' said Robert D.
Hormats, vice chairman of Goldman Sachs (International) in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   In a measure of how seriously US policy makers were taking
Brazil's troubles Wednesday, President Clinton said that senior
administration officials were consulting with allies to make sure
the crisis ``will be resolved in a satisfactory way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a strong interest in seeing Brazil, with whom we have
worked on so many important things around the world, carry forward
with its economic reform plan and succeed,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   However, analysts said that there is not much the United States
can do to avert further trouble. ``They can't do much for the
actual economy, but they have to deal with the perceptions,'' said
Harvard Business School economist Robert E. Kennedy, ``so they'll
be saying a lot of soothing words today,'' he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Further trouble in Brazil would represent a substantial setback
for US Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin and his deputy, former
Harvard professor Lawrence Summers. The pair has argued vigorously
for continuing unrestricted international capital flows, which have
helped spur a global boom, but also has set the stage for the kind
of currency run that Brazil is now in danger of suffering.
</P>
<P>
   They have been sharply criticized for asserting that policy
makers could cope with trouble from increasingly volatile financial
markets by arranging rescue packages through the International
Monetary Fund like the one unveiled last month for Brazil and
earlier ones for Indonesia, Korea, Thailand and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   `It was unfortunate, predictable and extremely costly,'' Harvard
economist Jeffrey Sachs said of Brazil's latest problems. ``The IMF
has failed for a fifth straight time in a high-profile assistance
program,'' Sachs charged.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate cause of Wednesday's crisis was the unexpected
resignation of Gustavo Franco as head of Brazil's central bank. But
the stage was set last week when the governor of one of the
contry's richest states suspended debt payments to the federal
government, raising questions about whether Brazilian President
Fernando Henrique Cardoso can win budget cutbacks demanded by the
IMF as a condition for its multibillion dollar aid package.
Franco's successor, Francisco Lopes, immediately announced that he
would allow the country's currency to depreciate about 8 percent
against the dollar in a move aimed at helping the already depressed
Brazilian economy by making its exports cheaper. But he said the
central bank would fight further declines for fear of provoking
Brazil's neighbors into devaluing their currencies and beginning an
economicaly destablizing race to underprice each other.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the first signs of whether the Brazilian central
bank can hold the line on the country's currency were discouarging,
as the real slipped below the trading range set by policy makers
and the government was reportedly forced to spend $1.7 billion of
its $35 billion in foreign reserves to try to prop the currency up.
</P>
<P>
   While US investors took Brazil's new problems in stride, stocks
here still fell broadly on worries that the country's troubles will
damage profits of US firms, especially those of banks with large
loans in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of financial giant Citigroup fell 3 9/16 to 52 3/16 while
those of J.P. Morgan tumbled 5 1/4 to 106 9/16 and those of
American Express slipped 3 7/8 to 98 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   The exception was BankBoston Corp., which makes 20 percent of
its profits in Latin America and has been doing business in the
region for much of this century. Analysts said that Boston
company's long ties will help it ride out the crisis, and the bank
itself issued a press release saying it plans to ``take advantage
of market turbulence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
