<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2173 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEC-LIVENT-ART-750&AMP;AD     01-13 1455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEC-LIVENT-ART-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. CHARGES TOP LIVENT EXECUTIVES WITH FRAUD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Garth Drabinsky, the Canadian impresario who founded
Livent Inc. and brought shows like ``Ragtime'' to Broadway, was
charged Wednesday with orchestrating a criminal fraud of hundreds
of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors said that through a scheme involving
kickbacks from contractors building Livent's new theaters in New
York and Chicago and the use of two sets of accounting books,
Drabinsky and his longtime partner, Myron Gottlieb, not only lined
their own pockets but also hid losses of more than $60 million.
</P>
<P>
   The criminal charges and similar civil charges brought Wednesday
by securities regulators were the first formal government charges
brought against the two former Livent executives, who for months
have been blamed by the company's new management for its desperate
financial straits. In addition, many new details of the reputed
fraud emerged from the written complaints filed in federal court in
Manahattan.
</P>
<P>
   For example, according to the regulators' complaint, Drabinsky
and Gottlieb tried to inflate the perceived success of ``Ragtime''
in Los Angeles in 1997 by having two companies buy more than
$380,000 worth of tickets and then reimbursing them by having them
submit fake invoices for theater construction. At that time, Livent
needed the Los Angeles production of ``Ragtime'' to look
successful, regulators said, because it would soon open on
Broadway, and the company was counting on the show's New York run
to pay for a growing pile of bills.
</P>
<P>
   Drabinsky and Gottlieb, who both live in Toronto, where Livent
is based, immediately disputed the 16 criminal counts of fraud and
conspiracy brought by Mary Jo White, the Unted States attorney in
Manhattan, and the civil charges of securities fraud made by the
Securities and Exchange Commission. If found guilty of the charges,
the two men could could be sentenced to decades in prison and be
fined millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday, Drabinsky called reporters to a room in the
Crowne Plaza Hotel in Toronto and spoke publicly for the first time
since he was suspended from his executive post in August. Reading a
statement, he blamed Michael V. Ovitz and Livent's other new
executives, who took over the company in June, for his growing
legal troubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, and for reasons best known to them, new management
wanted me out,'' Drabinsky said. ``This precipitous and deliberate
action has caused incalculable pain to me and was delibertely
designed to damage my reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than run the company, new management has focused a
preponderance of its attention on bringing a civil lawsuit against
Gottlieb and me and motivating American and Canadian authorities to
take quick, ill-conceived action against us.''
</P>
<P>
   Drabinsky refused to answer any questions.
</P>
<P>
   But in court papers, federal prosecutors counted Ovitz, who
invested $20 million in the company, among the victims of the two
men's fraud.
</P>
<P>
   And while Drabinsky has said that Ovitz knew about the state of
the company's accounting books before he invested in Livent,
prosecutors said Wednesday that it did not surprise them that the
fraud had continued for eight years before being discovered in
August by Ovitz's new top financial executive.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said that Livent's accounting staff had worked day
and night to carefully cover up the fraudulent adjustments to the
accounting books that Drabinsky, Gottlieb and other former
executives had ordered them to make. In addition, they said,
several former Livent financial executives had lied to the
company's outside auditors about many transactions.
</P>
<P>
   According to the regulators' complaint, Gordon C. Eckstein,
Livent's former senior vice president for finance, even asked
Livent's computer staff to write a program that allowed the
accountants to make adjustments without leaving a trail. ``This
process had the effect of falsifying the books, record and accounts
of the company so completely,'' the regulators' complaint said,
``that the adjustments appeared as original transactions, and no
trace of the actual original entries remained in the company's
general ledger.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. White called on Drabinsky and Gottlieb to voluntarily turn
themselves in. If they do not do so quickly, she said, prosecutors
will file documents in Canadian courts to extradite them.
</P>
<P>
   As part of their actions Wednesday, regulators also filed an
administrative complaint against Livent, which the company settled
by agreeing not to violate securities laws. Richard H. Walker,
director of the SEC's enforcement division, said that regulators
decided not to take more aggressive action because the new managers
had cooperated and had dismissed all employees that the regulators
had found to be responsible for the fraud.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement, Livent, which filed for bankruptcy court
protection in November, said that the regulators' actions Wednesday
``marks an important step in efforts to move the company forward.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The government's order makes clear where responsibility lies
for this regrettable matter,'' the statement said. &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   According to the government's complaints, Drabinsky and Gottlieb
devised a kickback scheme in the early 1990s in which they had two
contractors submit false invoices to the company for millions of
dollars in construction that did not occur.
</P>
<P>
   Livent paid those fake invoices by checks signed by Drabinsky
and Gottlieb, the complaint said, and the two companies later
secretly moved about $7 million (Canadian) of that money back to
the two men's personal accounts or to a Canadian company owned by
Gottlieb.
</P>
<P>
   As for the accounting fraud, the regulators' complaint said that
Drabinsky ``generally directed'' how the improper adjustments were
made, which grew ever larger through the years. In 1996, for
example, Livent reported earnings of $14.2 million (Canadian), even
though the company actually incurred a loss of more than $20
million (Canadian).
</P>
<P>
   The improper accounting adjustments included erasing expenses
from the books at the end of a quarter so that the company would
better meet Wall Street's expectations. Those amounts would later
be moved into the next quarter's books in a continuous accounting
manipulation that the company's accountants called the ``expense
roll,'' according to the complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Lee S. Richards, a lawyer for Gottlieb, said Wednesday that the
indictment against his client ``totally misconceives'' his role at
the company and charges him with matters that were not within his
responsibility. ``What is more,'' Richards said, ``the indictment
makes charges of fraud against Canadian citizens working in a
Canadian company that the prosecution can attempt to prove only
through Canadian witnesses and Canadian documents.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Gottlieb looks forward to exonerating himself in the
appropriate forum,'' Richards said.
</P>
<P>
   Two other former executives at Livent also face criminal
charges. Prosecutors charged Eckstein with one count of conspiring
with Drabinsky and Gottlieb to carry out the fraudulent accounting
scheme, which they say resulted in Livent reporting false earnings
to investors of tens of millions of dollars. And they charged Maria
M. Messina, the company's former chief financial officer, with one
count of making false statements on financial statements filed with
the SEC. Ms. Messina worked at the accounting firm of Deloitte &AMP;
Touche and audited the company's books before she was hired by
Livent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Both Eckstein and Ms. Messina have pleaded guilty to those
charges and await sentencing. They were both also charged with
securities fraud in a civil complaint by securities regulators.
Eckstein, an accountant, settled those charges by agreeing not to
practice before the SEC for five years. He did not admit to or deny
the regulators' allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Messina is still contesting the regulators' civil charges.
``Ms. Messina was a vulnerable person and was victimized by an
exploitive management regime at Livent,'' said Barry A. Bohrer, her
lawyer. ``In fact, she helped solve a problem that others had
created.''
</P>
<P>
   Securities regulators also charged five other former Livent
employees with violating securities laws or with making profits by
trading in the company's stock with inside information. Two of
those employees have settled the charges by agreeing not to violate
federal securities laws.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
