<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. POLLSTER FOR OPPONENT OF NETANYAHU IS BURGLARIZED
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ A break-in at the Washington offices of an American
polling firm advising Ehud Barak, the leader of Israel's opposition
Labor Party, threatened to inject new venom into the election
campaign Wednesday, but the candidates exercised restraint while
awaiting results of an investigation by U.S. authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Although the aims of the burglars were not immediately clear,
there were strong suspicions that they were after material
concerning Barak's campaign to unseat Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu in national elections on May 17.
</P>
<P>
   The overnight burglary occurred late Monday or early Tuesday at
the Capitol Hill offices of Stanley Greenberg, who has worked for
President Clinton and other Democratic politicians and now is a
consultant to Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Thieves removed a roof vent and tore through the ceiling of
Greenberg Quinlan Research Inc., Greenberg's company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certain confidential records, materials, other items and petty
cash were taken,'' said Sgt. Joe Gentile, spokesman for the
Washington Metropolitan Police.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is the possibility that the burglars had targeted
certain records,'' Gentile added. ``We advised the FBI, due to the
potential sensitive nature of the investigation. The FBI
volunteered to assist, and we took them up on the offer.''
</P>
<P>
   Tal Silberstein, Barak's campaign manager, said computerized
research material related to the Israeli election campaign had been
stolen. Whoever took it ``knew exactly what he was looking for,
because the only file pulled, according to what we understand at
the moment, is the file of the election campaign in Israel,''
Silberstein told Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
   Aliza Goren, a spokeswoman for Barak, said in a separate radio
interview that the file contained ``material about election
campaign polls.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot point to any guilty party,'' Ms. Goren added, ``and
we certainly don't have any assessment who did this. I really hope
very much that this is not related to the election campaign in
Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak kept silent about the break-in, saying nothing about it in
a speech denouncing Netanyahu's policies at a Labor Party
convention Wednesday night. Netanyahu also ignored the incident in
a televised rebuttal of Barak's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   David Bar-Illan, a spokesman for Netanyahu, said that the prime
minister's office ``has no knowledge'' of who could have been
behind the break-in, and that ``we don't consider it a
possibility'' that political supporters of Netanyahu had been
involved.
</P>
<P>
   But some legislators from the Labor Party pointed a finger at
Netanyahu's Likud Party. ``I would like to hope that there was no
guiding hand or a long arm from Israel,'' said Micha Goldman, a
Labor lawmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Ronit Eckstein, a spokeswoman for the Likud retorted: ``God
forbid. We will not allow the Labor Party to exploit a criminal act
in the United States to sully our image here. We hope that the
guilty parties will be found quickly and prosecuted.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg conducted campaign polls for Clinton in 1992 and has
also advised President Nelson Mandela of South Africa and Prime
Minister Tony Blair of Britain. He is advising Barak along with
another Democratic strategist, James Carville, and a third American
consultant, Robert Shrum.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu, who recently accused Barak of using American advisers
to engage in ``character assassination,'' has his own American
consultant, Arthur Finkelstein, who has advised conservative
American politicians including former Sen. Alfonse M. D'Amato of
New York.
</P>
<P>
   While the break-in caused only mild ripples Wednesday in the
Israeli campaign, it was headline news in the Israeli press. Yediot
Ahronot, a mass circulation daily, asked in its headline: ``An
Israeli Watergate?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
