<HEADER>
A2177 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-JORDAN-BOS &LR;      01-13 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JORDAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINUS A TRUE CHALLENGE, JORDAN TAKES HIS FINAL BOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ He made it official and unequivocal. Again. Almost.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan retired from basketball for the second time
Wednesday, leaving the door open just a crack for a possible
return. This time the reasons for leaving had less to do with the
Bulls' new coach, the Bulls' old front office, the
lockout-abbreviated NBA season, or the gash on his right index
finger.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason? Michael Jordan can't be Michael Jordan, and
that is not good enough for Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically, I'm fine,'' Jordan told the world at a news
conference at the United Center, where his No. 23 was re-retired.
``The desire to play is always going to be there. But I have to
have it every time I step on the court. I've always been sure about
that before. I'm unsure about that now. Physically, it would be
easy. Mentally, it would have been tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan titillated his legion of fans and admirers by refusing to
say ``never'' when asked if he would return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never say never,'' he said. ``But I'm 99.9 percent sure. I'm
very secure with my decision. Take it for what it's worth.''
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner David Stern said Jordan was finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get off it. He's not coming back,'' Stern said. ``It's time to
move on.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what the NBA and the Bulls will now have to do. Both
organizations are confident they can do so, despite losing the most
marketable player and remarkable ratings driver in league history.
Bulls owner Jerry Reinsdorf, who saw his string of sellouts and
titles end, said the occasion ``has to be the toughest day in the
history of the Chicago Bulls. It's tough for the city of Chicago,
the NBA, basketball fans around the world, and Michael Jordan fans
around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   He urged Stern to order that No. 23 be retired by the league _
the same way baseball retired Jackie Robinson's No. 42 _ adding,
``We in Chicago think anyone who wears a basketball uniform with
No. 23 will be a pretender.'' Stern didn't bite. (The Celtics
already have retired the number in honor of Frank Ramsey.)
</P>
<P>
   Reinsdorf, Stern, Jordan, and Jordan's wife, Juanita, sat at the
podium for the announcement, which was huge news here in the City
of Broad Shoulders. Every television station with a minicam carried
it live, and it has been the lead story on every newscast for the
last two days, supplanting the weather that has turned Chicago into
Vladivostok. Camera crews from Japan were here, as well as
reporters from most major cities and as far away as Milan.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan hung around to answer a slew of questions, many of which
were inaudible because of a malfunctioning sound system. Juanita
Jordan was asked just one: What's going to happen to her life now?
</P>
<P>
   ``My life won't change at all,'' she said. ``I see Michael doing
more car-pooling. That's about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was vague about when he actually decided to retire. He
said he felt that way last June after the NBA Finals but could not
make it definite. He said his involvement in the labor talks last
September was not a sign that he was interested in returning but
rather ``an obligation to the players of tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern said he thought for a moment that Jordan's involvement in
the talks might mean another season for the alphaBull.
</P>
<P>
   ``It crossed my mind,'' the commish said.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said not even the return of coach Phil Jackson might have
been enough to bring him back. He said he was worn out from last
season and not even the delayed start of this season was enough to
bring him back. He was lacking what he knew he needed: the drive,
the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love basketball, and it's hard to give up what you love,''
he said. ``I just don't have the mental challenge that Michael
Jordan needs. I don't want to fool myself knowing that I'm not
there 100 percent mentally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even with Phil, I think I would have had a tough time finding
that challenge. He's usually good at finding them, but I don't know
if he would have been able to. I can't say he would be able to
restore that.''
</P>
<P>
   He also revealed that even if he were inclined to return, his
injured finger, which will require surgery in the next couple of
weeks, would have forced him to miss two months. He said he severed
a tendon in the finger while trying to cut a cigar. Honest.
</P>
<P>
   At his pre-retirement party Tuesday night at the Hudson Club in
Chicago, the manager cut his cigar.
</P>
<P>
   So what now? Ubiquitous agent David Falk noted that Jordan still
has many endorsements and those aren't going away. Jordan said he
wanted to spend more time with his family, although he said the
same thing in 1993 and then promptly went off to Florida to play
baseball. He has three children _ Jeffrey, 10; Marcus, 8; and
Jasmine, 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a parent is a challenge,'' he said. ``I look forward to
that . . . I want to get away from basketball a little bit and look
at it from afar.''
</P>
<P>
   But what about that one-10th of 1 percent? He's soon to turn 36
and the 1999-2000 season isn't that far off. Would he, for
instance, consider rejoining Jackson in New York as a member of the
Knicks?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty sure that's not going to happen,'' he said.
``Although I love New York. But I can't see myself coming out of
retirement to play in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said he would still live in Chicago, would still follow
the Bulls, and would be there to help them. That did not include
coaching _ Tim Floyd should get the official pronouncement as early
as Thursday _ but did not exclude ownership. He challenged them to
keep the bar high.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they welcome that challenge, and that's good,'' he
said. ``We set a high standard here. The pressure is on them to
maintain it.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``The best way to survive Michael Jordan is to
learn to live without him. Life without Michael Jordan also has to
be without Michael Jordan. But I'll be around if they want my two
cents.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
