<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons defensive backfield hobbled
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As the Falcons prepare to face the NFL's most prolific
passing offense, two defensive backs are beat up enough that their
status is uncertain for Sunday's NFC Championship Game against the
Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   Starting cornerback Ronnie Bradford, who suffered a slight
shoulder separation Dec. 27 against Miami, dressed but did not play
Saturday against the 49ers when second-year cornerback Michael
Booker started.
</P>
<P>
   His role is increasing in practice, but Booker _ who started six
games in the regular season when Bradford had a strained knee
ligament _ remains the starter.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Devin Bush, who backs up both safety spots and is the
team's nickel and dime safety, did not practice Wednesday. He has a
strained hamstring and is listed as ``doubtful'' on the team's
injury report.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota led the NFL in passing offense, averaging 270.5
passing yards per game, while scoring 41 passing touchdowns.
Atlanta was No. 21 in the NFL in pass defense, allowing an average
of 220.7 passing yards per game, and 22 passing touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Bradford played safety early in his six-year career with the
Broncos and Cardinals. Before Bush returned from a knee injury
suffered in the preseason, Bradford would move from corner to
safety in passing situations, replacing starting strong safety
William White.
</P>
<P>
   White is practicing as the nickel and dime safety, but Bradford
is expected to play Sunday and could see action at several spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt (Bradford will start at corner) because he won't take
all those reps in practice,'' defensive coordinator Rich Brooks
said. ``He might work in the nickel (corner spot, with Randy
Fuller). He'll work at both nickel and (regular) safety (spots)
this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradford's shoulder was heavily taped in practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever they ask me to do, I'll do,'' he said. ``I'm ready to
go. At this point, (the shoulder) doesn't bother me at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush had 21 tackles, two fumbles forced, one recovered and 10 of
his 13 career pass defenses in just 12 games. ``I'll test it out
(today), and try to practice,'' he said. ``When I pick up speed ...
it grabs.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-2, 203-pound Booker would match up better size-wise
with Minnesota's 6-4, 211-pound rookie receiver Randy Moss than the
5-10, 188-pound Bradford.
</P>
<P>
   But while Booker's play improved dramatically this season, his
chief weakness is still considered coverage on deep balls _ Moss'
specialty.
</P>
<P>
   In 14 games and six starts, Booker had 45 tackles, one
interception and 11 pass defenses. Bradford, in 14 games and 10
starts, had 40 tackles, three interceptions (one returned for a
touchdown) and 11 pass defenses.
</P>
<P>
   Pro Bowl cornerback Ray Buchanan is the Falcons' fastest
defensive back, but will not lock up exclusively on the speedy
Moss, in part because of his size. Buchanan is 5-9, 198 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
