<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-COKE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IOC tells sponsors scandal in hand
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Now that the International Olympic Committee has
completed its bribery probe, it will ``clean house'' and revamp its
host city selection process, an IOC executive said Wednesday in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   IOC marketing director Michael Payne, in town to shore up
support from big-money sponsors, said the committee has gathered
enough evidence to seek the expulsion of members who engaged in
unethical behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IOC is committed to root out any form of unethical and
inappropriate behavior, and we will do this decisively and
quickly,'' Payne said in an interview after huddling with
executives at Coca-Cola and United Parcel Service and speaking by
phone with officers at The Home Depot, a U.S. Olympic Committee
sponsor. He was heading today to Salt Lake City, the focal point of
four major investigations into allegations of bribery of IOC
officials to snare the 2002 Winter Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're confident that they are going to do what they said they
would do _ take swift and decisive action,'' Coca-Cola spokesman
Ben Deutsch said.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC will publish on Jan. 24 a report identifying the members
implicated in its investigation after a meeting of the
organization's executive board in Lausanne, Switzerland. The report
also will recommend changes in the selection process for host
cities, Payne said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The report will recommend that a number of members be
suspended, if they don't resign,'' he said. The IOC sent letters
this week to members implicated in the investigation, demanding an
explanation of their actions. The full IOC, at its annual meeting
slated in June, would have to agree to any expulsions.
</P>
<P>
   Between eight and a dozen members, primarily from African and
Latin American countries, will be asked to resign, according to
various news reports.
</P>
<P>
   Other investigations are under way by the U.S. Olympic
Committee, the U.S. Justice Department and the Salt Lake Organizing
Committee's internal ethics committee.
</P>
<P>
   The SLOC has had its bloodletting. President Frank Joklik and
senior vice president Dave Johnson stepped down last week,
marketing and legal affairs vice president Kelly Flint and
licensing director Rod Hamson were placed on paid leave, and former
president Tom Welch lost his $10,000-a-month consulting fee.
</P>
<P>
   The president of John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co., one of
a dozen worldwide corporate Olympic sponsors, urged the IOC to
extend its investigation of irregular bidding practices beyond Salt
Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they fail to do that and something else comes up, the rings
won't be tarnished, they'll be broken,'' David D'Alessandro told
the New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alessandro, a frequent critic of the Atlanta Games, urged the
IOC to expand its investigation to include the winning bid efforts
of Atlanta and Nagano as well as the upcoming Summer Games in
Sydney and Athens.
</P>
<P>
   Payne said the IOC investigation is complete but added the
organization wouldn't close the door on any additional
substantiated allegations. ``The IOC's commitment is to seek out
any form of inappropriate behavior that went on in Salt Lake City
and to the extent necessary to get evidence anywhere else,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Australia IOC member Kevan Gosper said Wednesday the
organization will examine claims by a senior member of Sydney's bid
team that he was approached by one IOC member and an intermediary
to offer bribes. Gosper said he spoke to Bruce Baird, a former New
South Wales state Olympics minister, about the claims.
</P>
<P>
   Payne said he would meet with the worldwide Olympic sponsors,
companies that commit at least $40 million to sponsor Winter and
Summer Games in a four-year cycle. ``Rule No. 1 is keep your
partners fully informed,'' said Payne, whose committee will spend
$150 million on image-polishing ads on the 2000 Games, a project
involving Meridian Management of Atlanta. That effort was in the
works before the scandal broke.
</P>
<P>
   Only three corporations say they have renewed their sponsorships
for Salt Lake City and Athens: t Coca-Cola, Time/Sports Illustrated
and Sema, the technology company that replaced IBM as a sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based UPS is uncertain whether to extend its Olympic
sponsorship past the 2000 Games in Sydney. Spokeswoman Susan
Rosenberg said UPS will decide this year.
</P>
<P>
   UPS executives were reassured by Payne that the IOC was taking
swift and appropriate action. ``We are very positive about the
Games and what they can do for UPS as far as our programs and
marketing initiatives,'' Rosenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I think it is going to come out better. It has forced
everybody to go back in and do some analysis and close scrutiny.
For better or worse, it may be held up to higher standards, and now
they are going to enforce and clarify what those standards are,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Payne also put a positive spin on the situation. He noted that
allegations of bribery were nothing new, but no one had ever been
willing to produce evidence. ``This has allowed us to address
unequivocally some of the rumors that have been around for some
time and be able to weed out any unacceptable and unethical
behavior,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Salt Lake organizers still need to raise $245 million of the
$859 million in sponsorship cash and services that form the bulk of
its $1.45 billion budget.
</P>
<P>
   One corporate sponsor, US West, has said it will hold up a $5
million sponsorship payment due at the end of this month until the
mess is cleared up.
</P>
<P>
   Payne said he's not concerned about Salt Lake's ability to go
ahead with the 2002 Winter Games. ``The IOC, USOC and SLOC have
already raised more money than any previous Olympic Games
committees,'' he said. ``The issue of putting the Games on in Salt
Lake is not at risk. Whether the budgets need to be amended and
they need to come back on some capital, maybe. But the core of what
is needed is more than enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
