<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCAR-NOTES14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Another Petty gets behind the wheel
 &HT;    By Al Levine and Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE _ The face of NASCAR got a bit younger Wednesday. In
fact, this face looks as if it doesn't shave yet. Adam Petty, 18,
was introduced as a new driver on the Busch Grand National division
during the Charlotte Motor Speedway media tour.
</P>
<P>
   Adam is the son of Winston Cup driver Kyle Petty, the grandson
of the legendary Richard Petty and great-grandson of Lee Petty,
who, to put it in Pettyspeak, ``started this whole deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Adam Petty will drive the No. 45 Chevrolet Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're the first fourth-generation family to be
competing in any sport,'' Richard Petty said. ``That won't get us
into the Guinness Book of Records, but if Adam's successful maybe
it will.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year was Adam's first as a professional driver. Two weeks
after graduating high school, he won his first pole in an ASA race.
Five races later, on June 27, two weeks before his 18th birthday,
he became the youngest driver to win an ASA race, at the I-70
Speedway in Odessa, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   At 18 years and 3 months, he became the youngest ARCA
superspeedway winner, surpassing his father, at Charlotte Motor
Speedway. Kyle was 18 years and 8 months when he won his first ARCA
start, at Daytona.
</P>
<P>
   The grandfather said he would have preferred that Adam have
another year of driving experience before moving to Busch. ``I
think he's more focused than Kyle was when he first started out,''
Richard said.
</P>
<P>
   Adam's main sponsor is Spree prepaid telephone cards.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of youth
</P>
<P>
   As if Adam Petty should worry about the next generation of
stock-car drivers, there was even-younger Charles Shoemaker lurking
just outside Petty's garage area news conference with his '34 Ford
Sedan Legend Car.
</P>
<P>
   Shoemaker is a 15-year-old from McDonough who apparently skipped
classes at Henry County High to pose for photos next to his car. He
was there on behalf of Speedway Children's Charities. Racing as a
Semi-Pro, Shoemaker will donate his winnings from Legends races at
Atlanta Motor Speedway and Charlotte to the Children's Charities in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   A sophomore honor student at Henry County, he has won
championships in quarter-midgets and will compete in his first Late
Model race at Lanier Speedway in May.
</P>
<P>
   It's not chicken feed
</P>
<P>
   For 10 years, poultry-farmer Dale Earnhardt has sold chickens to
Perdue. ``I made a little bit of money in the chicken business with
Perdue,'' he said. ``Finally, these guys wised up.'' Which means
that Perdue chicken will be one of Earnhardt's sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt said a recent inventory of his poultry operation
revealed more than five million eggs in the henhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
