<SLUG> BC-LUCENT-ASCEND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUCENT TO ACQUIRE ASCEND FOR $19.6B 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The telecommunications industry took another giant step toward
consolidation Wednesday as Lucent Technologies Inc. agreed to
acquire Ascend Communications Inc. in a stock deal valued at $19.6
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The widely expected deal continues the pairings of major voice
and data equipment suppliers as fast-moving technologies blur
distinctions between telephone, cable, and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   As the nation's largest and oldest supplier of telephone
switching equipment, Lucent gets three important things in its
purchase of Ascend: the number two provider of advanced equipment
that carries Internet traffic; access to overseas telephone
markets; and the opportunity to become a major player in the
convergence of data, voice, and video communications networks.
</P>
<P>
   For Lucent, which was spun out of AT&AMP;T Corp. in 1996, the Ascend
deal is the company's second this week, and the largest of its 18
acquisitions. On Monday, Lucent announced the purchase of Kenan
Systems Inc., a 16-year-old Cambridge, Mass. software developer,
for $1.45 billion in Lucent stock.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of Lucent, headquartered in Murray Hill, N.J.,
and Ascend, of Alameda, Calif., is expected to provide formidable
competition to Cisco Systems Inc. of San Jose, Calif., the leading
data networking company. A third major player is Canadian-based
Northern Telecom, a longtime Lucent rival that has followed a
similar acquisition strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is already a textbook merger success story,'' said
Richard McGinn, Lucent's chairman and chief executive, adding that
he expects the transaction to close in May, following shareholder
approval by both companies.
</P>
<P>
   Both Lucent and Ascend have a strong presence in Massachusetts _
each company owns firms here _ and some analysts believe it was
Ascend's acquisition of Cascade Communications Inc. of Westford in
1997 that set into motion the deal announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``What drove this merger was Cascade Communications, perhaps the
best move Ascend ever made,'' said Timothy P. Savageaux,
telecommunications research analyst at Volpe Brown &AMP; Whelan in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Cascade pioneered the commercialization of a line of high-speed
networking switches that are now widely used to carry Internet
traffic. With 810 people in Westford and Boxborough, plus 300
employees from its acquisition of Stratus Computer Corp. in
Marlborough, Ascend employs more people in Massachusetts than it
does in California.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent, which employs more than 140,000 worldwide, has become a
major employer in Massachusetts, with more than 7,000 workers. Most
are based in Andover at the Merrimack Valley Works, which builds
voice telephone equipment. In recent years, Lucent has also
acquired a trio of small Bay State companies and consolidated their
operations in Concord.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lucent-Ascend deal proves once again that you can build
world-class companies in Massachusetts that are second to none,''
said Desh Despande, cofounder of Cascade, who left Ascend to start
another company, Sycamore Networks of Tewksbury. He also said the
deal made sense for both Lucent and Ascend, each providing
strengths the other lacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lucent still has an oldtime flavor where engineers take a long
time to do things that are rugged and reliable, while Ascend
provides agility and speed where its engineers can more quickly
adapt the latest technology. That combination of nimbleness and
rugged reliability is what telecommunications carriers companies
want.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucent's McGinn said the company will continue to look for more
acquisitions to expand its product lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue to invest heavily to grow this businss faster
than the marketplace,'' McGinn said, adding there will be some
minor layoffs at headquarters, where there is job overlap.
</P>
<P>
   Buying smaller companies has not always worked for Lucent, and
the Ascend deal is expected to help correct some of those more
problematic acquisitions, said Maribel Lopez, telecommunications
analyst at Forrester Research in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   She pointed to several companies, including Livingston
Enterprises of Pleasanton, Calif., a developer of remote-access
equipment that was acquired for $610 million in Lucent stock that
ran into product development and sales problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lucent had a string-of-pearls acquisition strategy and the
products that some of these data networking companies developed
were just not delivering what Lucent expected and needed to compete
against Cisco,'' said Lopez. She added that Lucent's biggest
challenge will be ``getting out of Ascend's way and let them do
their thing in data networking.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Ascend's president and chief executive,
Mory Ejabat, will stay on for six to 12 months and then leave the
company. Ascend shareholders will receive 0.825 shares of Lucent
stock for every Ascend share. Based on 228 million Ascend shares
and options and Lucent's closing price of 104 1/4, the all-stock
transaction values Ascend shares at $86 each, and the total deal at
$19.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Ascend stock hit a 52-week high of 80 5/16 Wednesday, up 5 3/8,
as more than 34.8 million shares were traded _ five times its usual
volume. Rumors that both sides were negotiating and some
skittishness by investors prompted Lucent stock to tumble from 117
3/16 last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may seem like a pricey deal, but it is really a fair one
for both companies,'' said Savageaux. ``It will provide positive
earnings for Lucent, which gets into the data part of the carrier
market, and Ascend gets a very strong partner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
