<HEADER>
A2190 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-NICKLAUS-SURGERY1     01-13 0246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NICKLAUS-SURGERY14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nicklaus surgery to replace ailing hip
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After months of delaying what seemed medically
inevitable, Jack Nicklaus said Wednesday that he will undergo hip
replacement surgery later this month.
</P>
<P>
   While the operation on Nicklaus' severely arthritic hip should
enhance his future golf, it also brings a short-term penalty.
Nicklaus, who turns 59 on Jan. 21, likely will see his streak of 40
straight Masters end in April while he's recuperating.
</P>
<P>
   Without the surgery, however, Nicklaus' goal of playing all four
majors in the year 2000 _ or for that matter, playing without pain
at any level _ would have been unrealistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I feel strong enough and able to play golf at a
competitive level, I will continue to play tournament golf,'' said
the winner of 18 professional majors. ``If I want to play later
this year and in the future, now is the time for surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   A six-time Masters champion, Nicklaus finished sixth at Augusta
last year but has hardly played competitively since. Nicklaus'
streak of 154 majors for which he was eligible ended with a
withdrawal from last July's British Open field.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus had been attempting to strengthen the hip in recent
months, but he could only manage minimal stability with bone
rubbing against bone in the deteriorated socket.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
