<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-MCAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY TAKES ANOTHER LOOK AT MCAS TEST SCORES  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JORDANA HART  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Nearly a decade after a controversial takeover by
Boston University, the Chelsea schools are the state's fourth most
effective, according to an analysis of MCAS test scores released
Thursday that measures how well a school performed when family
income and other demographic factors were considered.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard, North Reading, and Stoneham were the state's three most
effective districts, according to the analysis of the Massachusetts
Comprehensive Assessment System test conducted by a senior
reseacher at the Donahue Institute, a public policy think tank at
the University of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   No one is suggesting that Chelsea's students, who scored poorly
on the MCAS test, are succeeding. But by analyzing the MCAS scores
of the state's 210,000 fourth-, eighth-, and 10th-graders who took
the test last May, researcher Robert Gaudet found that children in
Chelsea, as well as Shrewsbury, Woburn, and Brookline, outperformed
statistical predictions based on social and economic factors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have a very complicated demography,'' said Douglas
Sears, the Chelsea school superintendent. ``We are always running
hard and fast to keep up.'' Eighty percent of Chelsea students are
poor enough to qualify for free school lunch and two-thirds do not
speak English at home.
</P>
<P>
   Sears said that he had focused on having schools use days more
efficiently, even eliminating ``distractions'' like some field
trips, and has placed a premium on reading.
</P>
<P>
   Still, six years and more than $3 billion into Massachusetts'
education reform, Gaudet found that demographic factors, such as
family income, parent education, and percentage of single-parent
households, significantly overshadow the schools' efforts when it
comes to student success or failure.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Gaudet said his analysis shows that demographic
differences among the state's 200 largest school districts explain
86 percent of the variation in test scores. All of the work school
districts do _ offering extra reading classes, or increasing
teacher training, or mandating longer school days _ accounts for
only 14 percent of the difference.
</P>
<P>
   That is one reason places such as Weston and Wellesley, with
relatively high MCAS scores, do not make the state's top 50 most
effective districts, said Gaudet, a founder and former principal of
the Renaissance charter school in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Weston is statistically the state's most affluent community and
a top test-scorer; achievement there is about as it should be given
the town's demographics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schools are not playing a significant role in increasing
academic performance as measured by MCAS,'' Gaudet said in a recent
interview. ``Districts that break that cycle are the ones we need
to study.''
</P>
<P>
   Woburn is one such place. Eighth overall in effectiveness based
on Gaudet's MCAS analysis, Woburn's 1998 Iowa reading test scores
placed it in the top 5 percent statewide. Yet 17 percent of its
students qualify for free school lunch, and fewer than 1 percent
have classroom Internet access, compared to 40 percent statewide.
</P>
<P>
   On the MCAS test, given its demographics, Woburn was second most
effective in fourth-grade reading, and ninth most effective in
eighth-grade reading. Officials there said their district was
faster to implement the changes put in motion by the Education
Reform Act of 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four years ago, one of our overarching goals was to align our
curriculum'' with the state standards ``and gear up staff
development,'' said Woburn School Superintendent Carl Batchelder.
</P>
<P>
   In conversations with leaders in ``effective'' districts, Gaudet
noted a pattern: Strong leadership, regular use of data to improve
teaching practices, a strong focus on literacy, and vigorously
aligning teaching to state standards in each subject, known as
curriculum frameworks.
</P>
<P>
   One of the surprises in Gaudet's analysis is the variation in
MCAS scores among 34 similar school districts he calls ``middle
Massachusetts.'' They are the state's demographically average
districts, yet their scores varied wildly.
</P>
<P>
   Stoneham and Watertown, for example, are demographically
similar. But Stoneham's combined MCAS score of fourth-, eighth-,
and 10th-grade students averaged 2,133 points compared to
Watertown's 2,063 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't tell districts to change demographically. What you
can do is point to systems similar to them that have overcome their
demography,'' said Lou DiNatale, a senior fellow at UMass's
McCormack Institute.
</P>
<P>
   The six demographic indicators Gaudet used were income, poverty
rate, parent education level, percent of children in single-parent
households, percent of children in private schools, and percent of
non-English speakers. They were then linked statistically to
overall scores on the MCAS. Last fall, he did the same analysis
using the 1996 Massachusetts Educational Assessment Program (MEAP)
and Iowa tests.
</P>
<P>
   Gaudet said he hopes his formula for measuring school
effectiveness will shine a light on unexpectedly high-performing
systems like Woburn and others that educators have not normally
turned to when seeking out what works.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
