<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-INSIDEGOLF14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Duval's current domination falls short of the best
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Eight hits in 27 at-bats? Batting .296 is common in
baseball, but except for a handful of instances, it is virtually
unheard of in professional golf.
</P>
<P>
   What David Duval has accomplished since the fall of 1997, when
he closed with three wins in a row, through Sunday's win at the
Mercedes Championships, is the kind of stuff few players in history
have managed even to approach. Duval's nine-shot victory at Kapalua
_ on 29 birdies _ gave him eight wins in 27 tournaments and more
than $4.3 million earned in less than 18 months. If Duval is not
atop golf's official world rankings when the figures, currently
putting Tiger Woods at No. 1, are updated, then maybe it's time for
golf's computer poo-bahs to check their respective motherboards.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as dominating as Duval has been, nearly matching Nick
Price's nine wins in 27 starts in 1993-94, he can't touch the
greatest runs in golf history. In 1974-75, Johnny Miller won 11
times in 24 starts. Arnold Palmer (1962-63) and Tom Watson
(1979-80) won 10 times in 27 starts. Jack Nicklaus won 10 of 27 in
1971-73, then ran it to 12 of 30. Before the modern golf era, of
course, Byron Nelson won 11 tournaments in a row in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for those 20 players from Kapalua playing this week
in Hawaii's Sony Open, the season's first full-field event, Duval
is taking the week off to go skiing in Sun Valley, Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly don't do that as well as I play golf,'' the former
Georgia Tech player said, ``but I'm getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday special
</P>
<P>
   So what is a PGA Tour player to do when he misses a Friday cut?
In some cases this year, tee it up on Saturday, anyway. The ``Bobby
Jones Saturday Series,'' founded by Gary Hallberg in cooperation
with the family of the late Bobby Jones, will be played during 29
PGA Tour events, matching 22 pros with four-man amateur teams. The
fee is $2,000 per person, with a significant portion going to
charity. An event with 22 pros and 88 amateurs will be played April
3 at White Columns Golf Club in Alpharetta after the BellSouth
Classic cut. A 10-pro, 40-amateur tournament will be held April 10
in the Augusta area after the Friday cut at the Masters. Atlanta's
Greg Powers (770-552-4454) is tournament director for both events.
... Woods is skipping the BellSouth the week before the Masters,
even as defending champion, but others consider it an opportunity
not to be missed. Tournament director Dave Kaplan already has
granted sponsor exemptions to Scotland's Colin Montgomerie and Ian
Woosnam of Wales. ... Fred Couples, who last played the BellSouth
in 1996 when the tournament was played before the Masters because
of the Olympics, already has put Atlanta on his April schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Car wars
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth fans, irked about parking since the move to the TPC at
Sugarloaf, have some potentially good news. The tournament has
purchased 12 acres of parking space adjacent to Peachtree
Industrial Boulevard and signed a 25-year agreement with the city
of Duluth for access to another 48 acres, adding room for about
4,500 more cars. The North Gwinnett Soccer Association will use the
land for the other 51 weeks of the year. ... The Senior PGA Tour
Nationwide Championship has announced a record contribution of
$341,000 to the Scottish Rite Children's Center and a charity total
of $440,000 through proceeds from the 1998 tournament at
Alpharetta's Golf Club of Georgia. ... The Augusta National Golf
Club recently announced a $3 million charity contribution,
including $1 million to the PGA Tour's First Tee program.
</P>
<P>
   Els takes plunge
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Els, 29, recently married his longtime girlfriend, Liezl
Wehmeyer, in Stellenbosch, South Africa. ... Barbara Trammell has
been promoted to director of tournament operations for the LPGA,
replacing Suzanne Jackson, who died in November. ... Jekyll Island
celebrated 100 years of golf last week at the Great Dunes Golf
Course, with players dressed in period attire and using
reproduction antique golf clubs and balls. ... Olin Browne missed
the Mercedes Championships because of a wrist injury but still
earned last-place money of $38,700. Normally the tour makes it
mandatory for even an injured player to show up for payment, but it
waived the policy because of the traveling distance to Maui.
</P>
<P>
   WEEKEND TOURNAMENTS
</P>
<P>
   _ PGA Tour: Sony Open, today-Sunday, Waialae Country Club,
Honolulu. TV: ESPN (7:30-9:30 p.m. today; 7:30-10 p.m. Friday;
7:30-9:30 p.m. Saturday; 8-10 p.m. Sunday).
</P>
<P>
   _ LPGA Tour: HealthSouth Inaugural, Friday-Sunday, Grand Cypress
Resort, North Course, Orlando. TV: ESPN (3:30-6:30 p.m. Friday; 2-4
p.m. Saturday; 3-5 p.m. Sunday).
</P>
<P>
   _ PGA European Tour/Southern Africa Tour: South African PGA,
today-Sunday, Houghton Golf Club, Johannesburg, South Africa. TV:
The Golf Channel (9 a.m.-noon and 9-11 p.m. today-Saturday; 9
a.m.-noon and 8-10 p.m. Sunday).
</P>
<P>
   _ Nike Tour: Lakeland Classic, today-Sunday, Grasslands Golf
Club, Lakeland, Fla. TV: None.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
