<HEADER>
A2209 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-ARIZONA_ARIZSTATE     01-13 1302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARIZONA_ARIZ </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASU MAKING GAINS ON COURT  
 ARIZONA STILL LEADING WAY, EVANS PLANS TO CUT MARGIN 
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   First there was Bob Weinhauer, followed by Steve Patterson and
Bill Frieder. And let's not forget Bob Schermerhorn and Don Newman,
the temps. Hello, fellas. And goodbye. Arizona basketball Coach
Lute Olson not only rules an empire that stretches far beyond the
peaks of Tucson's Catalina Mountains, he has survived all five of
his Arizona State counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   But chances are, he will not outlast the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Evans, who coaches the Sun Devils against Olson and the
Wildcats for the first time tonight at Wells Fargo Arena, is in
Year 1 of a five-year contract, which he does not expect to be his
only. At 52, he plans on sticking around awhile. Olson, in his 16th
season at Arizona, is 64 with what amounts to a lifetime contract.
He will go when he's ready, but it likely will be sooner rather
than later.
</P>
<P>
   Since leaving his snow tires in Iowa and replacing Ben Lindsey
before the 1983-84 season, Olson has created and reigned over one
of college basketball's showpiece programs. Roll the credits: 14
straight NCAA Tournaments, 11 straight 20-win seasons, eight Pac-10
titles, three Final Fours, one national championship.
</P>
<P>
   It also is a program that has relegated ASU hoops to
second-class status within the state, with only a couple of
aberrations. One was in Olson's first season, when he cleaned up
Lindsey's 4-24 toxic spill and produced an 11-17 record, his only
losing year. ASU, meanwhile, went 13-15 under Weinhauer, and both
teams were 8-10 in conference.
</P>
<P>
   From that point, Arizona left ASU in a vapor trail.
</P>
<P>
   The other blip registered in 1994-95, when the Wildcats lost to
Miami (Ohio) in the first round of the NCAA Tournament and ASU,
coached by Frieder, made it to the Sweet 16. But even that season,
Arizona finished second in the Pac-10, ASU third. No Olson-coached
team has ever trailed ASU in the final standings.
</P>
<P>
   That also was the season the Sun Devils, led by Mario Bennett,
managed to beat the Wildcats twice, 53-52, in Tempe and, 103-98, in
double-overtime in Tucson, a game in which three Arizona starters
were either hurt or suspended because of a pending NCAA
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   It remains the only year Olson has lost two games to the Sun
Devils. In fact, it usually works the other way around. The Cats
have swept the Sun Devils in 11 of Olson's 15 seasons. Overall,
Olson is 25-5 against ASU. He was 4-0 vs. Weinhauer, 6-1 against
Patterson and 1-0 against Schermerhorn, who briefly replaced
Patterson in 1989. Frieder had a comparatively glittering 4-12
record against his Bank One commercials partner. Newman was 0-2
last year after Frieder resigned under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's Evans' turn. Although he says that catching up to
Arizona is not part of his official mandate, he doesn't pretend to
ignore the giant located just 100 miles away, nor the state
supremacy the Wildcats have earned and enjoyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Challenges? I love challenges,'' Evans said. ``And this is a
huge challenge. Lute's done a tremendous job down there and will
continue to do a tremendous job. That doesn't mean the two programs
can't coexist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a healthy challenge. The job Lute's done at Arizona makes
everybody _ not only me but Cal, Oregon, Oregon State, everybody _
step to the plate and get better. And if you don't get better
you'll get buried. It's a positive thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Certain that ASU has the resources necessary to compete with
Arizona, Evans already seems on course to narrow the gap. His first
full recruiting class was judged to be among the best in the
Pac-10, if not the nation. Significantly, Evans landed probably the
three best players in Arizona _ Donnell Knight of Tempe Corona del
Sol High School, Tanner Shell of Mesa Mountain View and Tommy Smith
of North. None fit Arizona's needs, but Evans is thrilled to have
them.
</P>
<P>
   The year before, Newman brought in Kenny Crandall of Mountain
View and Greenway's Chad Prewitt, although the plum of the
recruiting class, Richard Jefferson of Moon Valley, went to
Arizona. But no longer can it be assumed that the best in-state
players, such as Jefferson and Mike Bibby, are automatically
ticketed for Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   The potential of ASU and the presence of Evans has not been lost
on Olson, who said he has no problem with ASU getting better.
Although not ``too'' good, probably.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be great for everyone,'' he said. ``Yes, when
we play one another, it should be a war. But when we play other
people, we should be cheering for each other. There would be
nothing better than the two Arizona teams finishing 1-2 in the
Pac-10.''
</P>
<P>
   Olson said ASU asked whether he would be interested in the head
coaching job after Ned Wulk was fired in 1982. But Olson, who was
at Iowa at the time, was surprised when he heard what the job was
worth. That, he said, reflected a lack of commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me, `Well, we've got the Suns in town we can't
afford to put together a package to get it done,' '' he said. ``My
response was, `You can't afford to have 8,000 empty seats.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It's different now. Athletic Director Kevin White is a willing
and active partner with Evans in renovating the program. After
witnessing his first ASU-Arizona game in Tucson a couple of years
ago, White said there is every reason to believe the same
basketball environment can exist in Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get better,'' he said at the time. ``I think
everyone realizes that.''
</P>
<P>
   White since has taken steps toward that by increasing the scope,
functions and purpose of the entire athletic department. Basketball
has benefited from that, and will continue to be a high priority.
The ongoing fund-raising campaign is expected to produce $5 million
to $7 million in upgrades for Wells Fargo Arena, including a new
fieldhouse.
</P>
<P>
   `I've known Kevin White a long time,'' said Olson. ``Kevin
recognizes the success of the entire athletic program to the entire
university.''
</P>
<P>
   But White said the main impetus for change is Evans, whom he
hired last April.
</P>
<P>
   ``What transformed the environment at Arizona was the hiring of
Lute Olson,'' White said. ``It triggered a transformation and I
think we have the opportunity here to enjoy the same type of thing.
Rob is clearly doing what needs to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   In one aspect of the ASU-Arizona series, the teams have achieved
parity. Although the Wildcats have won six straight overall,
Arizona is 4-3 in Tempe dating to 1991-92. And every game has been
close. The Cats have averaged 78.57 points a game during that
stretch, the Sun Devils 78.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight should follow that form. The Wildcats are ranked No. 7
nationally, but no one, Olson especially, believes they are as good
as they will be. The Sun Devils, finally grasping Evans' system and
philoso phy, are playing well. Arizona is led by a pair of seniors,
guard Jason Terry and A.J. Bramlett, and probably will start three
freshmen. ASU has three proven veterans _ senior forwards Bobby
Lazor and Mike Batiste, and junior guard Eddie House.
</P>
<P>
   Terry, House and Lazor are 1-2-3, respectively, in the Pac-10 in
scoring. Batiste would be fourth, but hasn't played enough games to
qualify.
</P>
<P>
   For ASU, Crandall likely will start and Prewitt will play a
large role, too. They were teammates with Jefferson on the Arizona
Stars club team the past couple of summers. Crandall and Jefferson
never opposed each other in high school, but Prewitt knows
Jefferson all too well. Last year, Greenway was 0-5 against Moon
Valley, including a loss in the Class 4A title game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more playing against the U of A than playing against
Richard,'' Prewitt said. ``But there's that, too.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
