<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0490 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2212 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-JORDAN-RHODEN-NYT     01-13 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JORDAN-RHODEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A VERY COLD SEND-OFF FOR THE HOTTEST ATHLETE
</HEADLINE>
   (See also BKN-JORDAN-RDP, BKN-JORDAN-PLAYERS, BKN-JORDAN-KNICKS. 
(nk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Pardon me for being a little disappointed, I just
expected more. This was retirement day for Michael Jordan, a player
we have called the greatest ever, and the send-off was flat. Not
simply flat, but chilly.
</P>
<P>
   On a day that marked the retirement of arguably the most
significant athlete of this century, there was a distinct coldness
between management and player. Jordan, with his wife, Juanita, on
his right, Commissioner David Stern on his left and Chicago Bulls'
chairman Jerry Reinsdorf at the table, confirmed reports that he
was leaving the National Basketball Association. Leaving the league
he dominated; walking away from the game he loved. The man who made
winter in America bearable for Chicagoans, and enjoyable, is
history.
</P>
<P>
   This was not an emotion-filled farewell, rather an icy goodbye
that had the finality of a divorce, not the cuddly warmth of a
retirement. This was a flat ending for a man whose career has been
built on drama. On Wednesday, there was no emotion, no video
highlights.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan joked that he was thinking of showing up and simply
saying, ``I'm gone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he added, ``then I figured I owed the media and the
fans more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, Jordan ended months of speculation and announced that
he was stepping away. Was this bland atmosphere a result of poor
planning or bad blood?
</P>
<P>
   There has been little love, and little love lost, between Jordan
and team management, particularly between Jordan and Jerry Krause,
the Bulls' general manager. Krause has insisted that organization
and structure had as much, if not more, to do with the team's
astounding success as Jordan did. Jordan simply agreed with what
the world said: that he's the man.
</P>
<P>
   Reinsdorf said this was a dreaded day, yet you got the distinct
sense that the Bulls could not wait for this to come. With Jordan
finally out of the way, Reinsdorf and Krause can prove, once and
for all, the supremacy of the franchise over the players. This is
what the six-month lockout was about, and the wounds are fresh.
</P>
<P>
   On second thought, I suppose this wasn't the time to expect
cuddly. This was a day when who wasn't here and what wasn't said
put the environment in much sharper perspective. Phil Jackson, the
former head coach, was missing, as was Scottie Pippen, Jordan's
other basketball half, and Ron Harper.
</P>
<P>
   Reinsdorf read from a script Wednesday afternoon; Krause never
spoke but stood off to the side with Tim Floyd, who was hired over
the protests of Jordan, who insisted that his preference was for
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the day's potentially dramatic moments, the team
unfurled a banner with Jordan's retired number. The only problem
was that the banner was old. It read: 1984-1993, marking the day
when Jordan retired to mourn the death of his father and to try
playing professional baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan seemed surprised when Reinsdorf presented Jordan with his
1998 championship ring. Why present the ring Wednesday? It was as
if Jordan was being told not to bother coming on ring night. Ring
night _ that should be quite a scene _ a standing ovation for
Jordan, cascades of boos for Krause.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe too much is being read into all this. I just expected
more.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a player who lifted Chicago from a slaughterhouse,
backwater basketball town into a championship city. The Chicago
sports scene was a losers' scene. The Bears haven't won a
championship since 1985; the Blackhawks won their last Stanley Cup
in 1961; the White Sox haven't won a World Series since 1917; and
the Cubs haven't won a championship in 90 years. The Bulls' six
championships elevated Chicago to elite status.
</P>
<P>
   ``For what Michael has meant to the NBA,'' Reinsdorf said
Wednesday, ``this number could very well be retired in every NBA
arena.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan will still generate more than $500 million in revenue for
the NBA this year. In a survey last June, The Sports Marketing
Letter projected that Jordan would make $42 million from his
sponsors in the next year. This puts him ahead of Tiger Woods ($30
million) and Shaquille O'Neal ($28 million).
</P>
<P>
   One got the sense Wednesday that the most satisfying aspect of
retirement for Jordan was that it gave him one more opportunity to
shoot one last winning shot over the outstretched hands of an
opponent by retiring. He is denying three generations of opponents
the privilege of defeating him.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing. Karl Malone. Charles Barkley. They will spend the
rest of their careers chasing a ghost.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all wanted me to come back just so that if they win a
championship,'' Jordan said, ``they can say they had gone through
Chicago or Michael Jordan to win it, to give it the meaning of
taking the title away from Chicago. Patrick won't be able to live
with himself if he can't beat Michael Jordan in a series; and
Charles Barkley, I told him he would never win, because he doesn't
dedicate himself to winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after noon here, the retirement announcement ended, and
Jordan went home to begin his new life with his wife and family.
Reinsdorf, Krause and Floyd went back to their offices and dug into
the challenge of rebuilding the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry, Jerry and Tim. Planning for the impending slaughterhouse
blues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
