NYT-01-13-99 2234EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0493 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2215 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-JORDAN-PLAYERS-NY     01-13 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JORDAN-PLAYERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRAISE FOR JORDAN FROM ALL CORNERS
</HEADLINE>
   (See also BKN-JORDAN-RDP, BKN-JORDAN-RHODEN-COLUMN,
BKN-JORDAN-KNICKS.) 
(nk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some praised his ability to soar gracefully over defenders who
were nearly a foot taller. Others spoke reverentially of his
competitiveness, the trait that forced him to work tirelessly at
honing skills that were already legendary. Still others paid
tribute to the charisma and advertising acumen that enabled him to
become the premier pitchman in sports.
</P>
<P>
   But among all the words of homage for Michael Jordan on
Wednesday by those linked with the National Basketball Association,
one theme remained constant: No. 23 of the Bulls was the greatest
player in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael Jordan is the best player that's ever laced 'em up,''
said Bob Cousy, the Hall of Fame guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pound for pound, he was the best ever,'' said Julius Erving,
who as Dr. J first brought to the NBA the high-flying wizardry that
made Jordan so dynamic. ``He's the most electric, has the most
charisma and the most flair.''
</P>
<P>
   Current players, from former Dream Team members Reggie Miller
and Joe Dumars to up-and-coming stars like Keith Van Horn, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am telling you he's not human,'' Miller said. ``Has anyone
ever seen him bleed? I have not seen blood yet. Something is going
on here. He is not human.''
</P>
<P>
   While Jordan possessed outstanding athleticism, the consensus
was that his quickness, strength and leaping ability were not the
only attributes that set him apart. It was his capacity to combine
those qualities with a superior work ethic, an incredible degree of
mental toughness and a matchless desire to win. Jordan's dedication
to improvement and winning was renowned.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton noted that Jordan's excellence was not limited
to his physical ability. ``In my life, I don't know that I ever saw
another athlete with such a remarkable set of qualities of mind,
body and spirit,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Many said that Jordan's amazing accomplishments were born of his
tremendous drive to be the best. It was his hatred of finishing
second that led him to score 38 points while ailing from the
stomach flu in Game 5 of the 1997 NBA finals against Utah.
</P>
<P>
   The list of those he conquered in winning titles in the final
six full seasons he played is awesome: Magic Johnson, Larry Bird,
Isiah Thomas, Karl Malone, Patrick Ewing, Charles Barkley, Pat
Riley, Chuck Daly and Lenny Wilkens.
</P>
<P>
   Some current players and coaches said they wished Jordan had not
retired, so they could have had another opportunity to beat him.
But they had plenty, and failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I lay my head down on the pillow at night, I'll know
there was one guy I never had a chance to beat,'' said Riley, the
Miami Heat coach who won five championship rings before Jordan
began his reign. ``It doesn't look like I'll get another chance.
That bothers me.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's success on the court, plus his easygoing personality
and charm, enabled him to prosper just as much on Madison Avenue.
Before he entered the league, only a handful of players had
signature basketball shoes or endorsements of any kind. But his
ability to relate to Americans of all ages and colors landed him
deals with Nike, McDonald's, Gatorade, Hanes and other companies.
</P>
<P>
   When his Air Jordan sneakers helped Nike become the world's
leader in basketball apparel, marketers began giving out
million-dollar deals to dozens of players, a development that
changed the way many younger players viewed professional
basketball. To some, the game became the means to a larger pile of
cash to be made outside of basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Iverson, the 76ers' star guard, said Jordan inspired him
to not only be a basketball player, but also to be an endorsement
magnet. ``With all his off-the-court marketing and everything he
did, it makes me want to do something like that in my life,'' said
Iverson, who signed a multimillion-dollar shoe contract with Reebok
out of college. ``He set the standard for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody is not limited to America or even the Western
Hemisphere. His once-in-a-generation game and his seemingly
boundless commercial appeal turned him into not only a cultural
icon but also a global hero, one whose influence on the world
through sports is comparable only to a Muhammad Ali or a Babe Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   That was clear by the fact that newspapers throughout the world
ran front-page articles about Jordan's retirement in Wednesday's
editions. Papers in London, Rome, Spain, France, Japan and
Australia, to name a few, did that.
</P>
<P>
   La Repubblica in Rome wrote: ``America would willingly take
Clinton's retirement in exchange for Jordan's. Not only was Jordan
the best basketball player ever. He was basketball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
