<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2225 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-JORDANRETIRES-HNS     01-13 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JORDANRETIRES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MICHAEL JORDAN, THERE WERE NO MORE MOUNTAINS TO CLIMB 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MICHAEL MURPHY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The City of Big Shoulders needs a shoulder to cry on
today.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan, who redefined basketball with his
gravity-defying moves and intense will to win, officially announced
his retirement from the National Basketball Association on
Wednesday morning during a packed news conference at the United
Center.
</P>
<P>
   The reason, Jordan said, was simple. There were no more worlds
to conquer, no challenges he has not already met during his 13
years with the NBA's Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   So it was time to move on. And time for the league to move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel I have a challenge,'' Jordan said. ``Physically,
I feel great. I know from a career standpoint I've accomplished
everything I could as an individual. Right now, I don't have the
mental challenges that I've had in the past to proceed as a
basketball player. I'm pretty sure people will say, `Well, there's
a lot of different challenges that could evolve.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But for me to start something and then lose interest and my
motivation in the middle of the season, it's unfair to the people
that I'm working with and working for, and to the fans. So I
(avoided that) by saying this is a perfect time for me to walk away
from the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm at peace with that.''
</P>
<P>
   That much was obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, who was joined on a midcourt podium by his wife,
Juanita, NBA Commissioner David Stern and Bulls Chairman Jerry
Reinsdorf, seemed very much at ease, throwing out zingers at
longtime rivals Charles Barkley and Patrick Ewing and smiling
often.
</P>
<P>
   There was none of the tear-stained emotion that some expected,
which may rank among the 35-year-old Jordan's most impressive
career accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing a good job of trying to hold back the emotions, but
it's like taking away something that I truly have loved for the
last (24 years),'' he said. ``It's sad that I'm leaving the game,
but it's happy because my life is starting to go into a whole other
stage. Basketball for me was the first stage; it got me to this
point in my life. I knew it had to end.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life takes on a different stage now, and it's a different
challenge, and I welcome that, and I knew it was coming. So I'm
happy that it's gotten to this point, and I'm happy that you guys
(the media) didn't run me out of the game. I chose to walk away
knowing that I can still play the game, and that's what I've always
wished for my career to end _ that's exactly the way I wanted to
end it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not quite the way Reinsdorf wanted the Jordan era to end,
however. Reinsdorf was attempting to reunite Jordan, Scottie
Pippen, Dennis Rodman and coach Phil Jackson for one last title
run. Instead, the Bulls, the most dominant NBA team of the 1990s,
will likely be starting from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   ``This a day that I think I hoped would never come,'' said a
somber Reinsdorf. ``It has to be the toughest day in the history of
the Chicago Bulls. It's a tough day for Chicago. It's a tough day
for the NBA. It's a tough day for basketball fans all over the
world and for Michael Jordan fans all over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a sad day,'' he said. ``This is a great day,
because the greatest basketball player in the history of the game
is getting the opportunity to retire with the grace that described
his play.''
</P>
<P>
   Reinsdorf unveiled a banner celebrating Jordan's No. 23, which
has been retired by the Bulls for a second time. And contrary to
what happened after his first ``retirement'' in 1993, Jordan says
he won't return. After all, that first retirement wasn't on his own
terms.
</P>
<P>
   Still haunted by the recent murder of his father, James, Jordan
said he had accomplished everything he could in basketball and
wanted to try his hand at minor-league baseball.
</P>
<P>
   But most everyone knew he would be back.
</P>
<P>
   And in 1995, Jordan did return. It didn't take long to discover
he could no longer dominate the game the way he once did, a point
that was underscored when the Bulls were eliminated in six games by
Orlando in the Eastern Conference semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   The most stinging aspect of that loss was hearing the whispers
that he could never again be the Jordan who carried Chicago to
three straight NBA titles between 1991 and '93.
</P>
<P>
   That was all the motivation he needed.
</P>
<P>
   F. Scott Fitzgerald may have written, ``There are no second acts
in American lives,'' but Jordan went about proving him wrong. Act
II in Chicago meant three more NBA titles, and Jordan was the
motivating force behind all three.
</P>
<P>
   His goodbye kiss came last June in Salt Lake City, when Jordan's
last-second shot in Game 6 of the NBA Finals settled into the net
to beat the Jazz and lift the Bulls to their sixth title in this
decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made his last shot to win a world championship,'' said
Barkley, one of Jordan's closest friends. ``What more do you need?
That's every player's fantasy.''
</P>
<P>
   As if Jordan, whom Lakers general manager and NBA Hall of Famer
Jerry West recently called a ``modern-day Babe Ruth,'' needed
another fantasy fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
   During the course of his career, Jordan not only captured six
titles but also won five Most Valuable Player awards and six NBA
Finals MVPs. He was named Rookie of the Year (1985) and Defensive
Player of the Year (1988) and won an NBA-record 10 scoring titles.
He appeared in 11 All-Star Games (missing a 12th because of
injury), taking home the MVP trophy three times. And Jordan's
31.5-point career scoring average is the best in NBA history, as is
his playoff average of 33.4 points.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday, he walked away and said he has no intention of
looking back. Instead, Jordan said he will devote himself to being
a father to his three children, Jeffrey, Marcus and Jasmine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never say never, but I'm 95 (to) 99.9 percent (certain),''
said Jordan when asked if he would change his mind and come back.
``I'm very secure with my decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was difficult, because you're giving up something that you
truly, truly love. My love for the game is very strong. It's hard
to give up that love.''
</P>
<P>
   But give it up he did.
</P>
<P>
   All that will be left are the banners, the last of which will be
raised at some point during the Bulls' home opener this season, and
the statue that stands outside the United Center, erected in 1994
after Jordan's first retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best there ever was,'' reads the inscription. ``The best
there ever will be.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
