<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Officials waiting on word from Bush before moving on Everglades
permit
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ South Florida water managers said
Wednesday they will keep negotiating and await word from Gov. Jeb
Bush before accepting or rejecting a federal permit for part of the
$763 million Everglades cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   Sugar growers say the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency's
permit would require impossible pollution standards, adding up to
$2 billion to the costs. EPA officials say they're just enforcing
the law, and environmentalists say the limits will ensure that the
Everglades is really cleansed.
</P>
<P>
   State officials said Bush wants to review the dispute, including
whether to accept a Dec. 31 decision by then-Gov. Buddy MacKay to
go along with the EPA's plans.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
