<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-BISHOP14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Tremendous anticipation' fills new bishop
 &HT;    By Steve Gushee
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH GARDENS, Fla. _ A new bishop for the Roman Catholic
Diocese of Palm Beach began a two-day ceremony of taking office
Wednesday at St. Ignatius Loyola Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   In a solemn service of evening prayer, the papal letter
appointing the Most Rev. Anthony Joseph O'Connell bishop of the
diocese was read.
</P>
<P>
   An official delegation of senior priests in the diocese, which
includes the Treasure Coast, verified the validity of the document
before a congregation of about 700 people made up largely of
diocesan clergy civic leaders and non-Catholic religious
representatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``He presented to us, the college of consultants, his
credentials, his letter of appointment,'' said the Rev. Francis
Lechiara, pastor of St. Edward Catholic Church in Palm Beach. ``We
signed it.''
</P>
<P>
   The actual installation takes place at an invitation-only
service at 2 p.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday evening's service helped ease the requirements of
today's liturgy and allowed more people to be part of the ceremony,
O'Connell said.
</P>
<P>
   The bishop preached about his coming to Palm Beach. ``I have a
tremendous anticipation of the blessing the Lord has given us.''
</P>
<P>
   The clergy of the diocese presented him with a shepherd's staff,
the symbol of his office.
</P>
<P>
   Invited guests included U.S. Rep. Mark Foley, R-West Palm Beach;
Ted Lapkin, director of community relations for the Jewish
Federation of Palm Beach County; Joseph Russo, mayor of Palm Beach
Gardens; the Rev. Cary Robb, rector of St. Mark's Episcopal Church
in Palm Beach Gardens; and Rabbi and Mrs. Merle Singer from Temple
Beth El in Boca Raton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jewish/Catholic community has enjoyed a fine interfaith
relationship,'' Singer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel it is important to be at the prayer service leading to
his installation as part of welcoming the leader of the Catholic
church to Palm Beach County.''
</P>
<P>
   The Irish-born O'Connell has been the bishop of the Diocese of
Knoxville in Tennessee for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   He replaces Bishop J. Keith Symons, who resigned in disgrace in
June after admitting inappropriate sexual behavior early in his
ministry.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell will lead 220,000 Catholics in Palm Beach, Martin, St.
Lucie, Indian River and Okeechobee counties.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was delighted to begin his ministry here with a
congregation that represented the diversity of the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in coalitions,'' O'Connell said. ``I believe that
people of faith need to work together. No one has the fullness of
God. I think we have an obligation to work together.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
