<SLUG> BC-BKC-HOOPCOL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINAL BETTER AFTER INJURIES?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stanford rolled into town Wednesday evening, alone in first
place, ranked fourth and winner of nine straight. While the rest of
the Pacific-10 fights like siblings, scratching and clawing on the
living-room floor, the Cardinal watches from afar, an amused big
brother too mature to participate.
</P>
<P>
   Ten of 18 conference games have been decided by three points or
less. Three have ended in overtime. Through it all, Stanford sits
at 3-0, with an average victory margin of 14.3 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Stanford loses, it would be a surprise,'' Arizona coach
Lute Olson said. ``The rest of us keep banging away.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal has been so dominant, several Pac-10 coaches
believe the early-season injuries to three key reserves _ point
guard Mike McDonald (foot), shooter Ryan Mendez (knee) and center
Jason Collins (wrist), the Harvard-Westlake alum _ actually made
Stanford better.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've almost gotten stronger with the injuries,'' said
Oregon coach Ernie Kent, a former Stanford assistant whose team
lost by 18 points in Maples Pavilion two weeks ago. ``They have
forced (coach) Mike (Montgomery) to play his starters more. It's
helped their continuity and their confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   What was a fabulous 10-man rotation has dwindled to seven, with
wing man David Moseley and forward Jarron Collins as the top
reserves. Combined, they're averaging 9.7 points and 5.7 rebounds
in 32 minutes (conference games only).
</P>
<P>
   McDonald might return next week, but his injury has increased
demands on North Hollywood native Arthur Lee, who's averaging 34
minutes. Freshman Tony Giovacchini plays sparingly and never in
pressure situations.
</P>
<P>
   Mendez is not expected back anytime soon, if at all. Without
him, Montomgery must use Moseley, athletic but an erratic shooter,
as the replacement for both wing guard Kris Weems and small forward
Pete Sauer.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Collins' dislocated wrist means more minutes for his
brother, Jarron, but it also reduces Stanford's margin for error
along the front line. For the first time in two years, foul trouble
is a concern.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery is many things _ sarcastic, cynical, a superb teacher
and tactician _ but he is not a revisionist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how losing good players helps you,'' he said. ``I
don't understand that concept.''
</P>
<P>
   For comparison's sake: After beating USC and UCLA last weekend,
Oregon State guard Josh Steinthal said there's no comparison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, I thought USC was a lot better,'' Steinthal said.
``UCLA wasn't as organized. If you stopped one thing with them,
that's it. But (USC) can do a lot more things. They don't have the
national ranking, but they're a lot better than UCLA.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins and Trojans meet next Wednesday in the Sports Arena.
UCLA has won eight straight in the city series, but the gap between
the teams _ as measured by talent and experience _ is smaller this
year than at any time since 1992, when USC, led by Harold Miner,
finished second in the Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   Around the nation: Remember Brad Millard, the 7-3, 350-pound St.
Mary's center who collided with Wake Forest's Tim Duncan in the
1997 NCAA Tournament? After three surgeries on two different
injuries in his left foot the mammoth Millard is back _ well,
almost.
</P>
<P>
   Following his most recent surgery, in October, he used an
aquatics-based rehabilitation program to avoid pounding on the
brittle bones. Last week, he was cleared for floor exercises, and
St. Mary's hopes he'll return in early March....
</P>
<P>
   Looking for early candidates for national coach of the year? Try
Auburn's Cliff Ellis, Wisconsin's Dick Bennett, Cincinnati's Bob
Huggins and Ohio State's Jim O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   They won't get many votes for national player of the year, but
they should: Cincinnati's Melvin Levett and Auburn's Chris
Porter....
</P>
<P>
   Three of the best players in the West are not Pac-10 residents:
Gonzaga's Matt Santangelo, Boise State's Roberto Bergersen and
Fresno State's Courtney Alexander, a transfer from Virginia.
Bergersen and Alexander are future first-round draft picks. UCLA
fans will have a chance to assess Santangelo in person next season,
when Gonzaga visits Pauley Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   Around the Pac-10: KMTR television in Eugene, Ore., did a
frame-by-frame, stop-action examination of USC guard Adam Spanich's
game-winning half-court shot. The result: an Oregon official
started the clock 0.5 seconds late....
</P>
<P>
   Arizona had 30 turnovers last week against Washington State, its
highest total in Olson's 16 seasons....
</P>
<P>
   Oregon State's 2-2 start in conference play is its best since
1993....
</P>
<P>
   Something we'll never see again: Stanford missed 17 of 30 free
throws at home against Cal....
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's five freshmen are averaging 40.3 points and 19.1
rebounds. Their UCLA counterparts are averaging 38.7 points and
22.6 rebounds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
