<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-SANCTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE SAYS U.S. IS WILLING TO HELP IRAQ GET MORE FOOD AND MEDICINE 
</HEADLINE>
  By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Vice President Al Gore said on Wednesday night that
the White House was willing to consider ways to loosen restrictions
on Iraq's ability to buy food and medicine. He emphasized that the
administration's differences were with Saddam Hussein, not with the
Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
   With the administration facing criticism from some principal
allies over the restrictions on food and medicine, Gore told an
audience of Jewish organizations here that the White House was
considering ways to increase the flow of such essential supplies to
the Iraqi people. In keeping with other administration officials,
he heatedly disputed the notion that the United States was to blame
for food or medicine shortages in Iraq, and said that Saddam
repeatedly had chosen to spend oil revenues on his nation's
military.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saddam has consistently shown that he cares much more about
developing weapons of mass destruction than developing the welfare
of his people,'' Gore said. ``He is the direct cause of suffering
on the part of the Iraqi people.''
</P>
<P>
   Under U.N. sanctions, Iraq is able to sell a limited amount of
oil to raise money for food and medicine imports.
</P>
<P>
   Gore did not elaborate on his remarks, which he made during a
speech on the Middle East peace effort to the Israeli Policy Forum,
which brought together an audience of prominent American Jews in
New York. But a senior White House aide said the administration was
examining ways to streamline the delivery of food and medicine to
Iraq, and that the United States would raise the topic at a meeting
of the Security Council on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The aide said the administration was also considering lifting
some sanctions on the sale of oil by Iraq, which were put in place
to punish Iraq for its invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   The White House adviser said the administration was acting, in
part, in response to concerns by allies about the way the embargo
program was being portrayed. The effort to increase the delivery of
essential goods was intended to ``take the issue off the table.''
</P>
</TEXT>
