</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JORDAN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS ALSO GETTING OFF TO A LATE START ON TOGETHERNESS
</HEADLINE>
   (See also BKN-JORDAN-RDP, BKN-JORDAN-RHODEN-COLUMN,
BKN-JORDAN-PLAYERS.) 
(nk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was Patrick Ewing, committing a fraternization
sin by sunning with the enemy as he worked out with about a dozen
Heat players in Miami on Wednesday. To the chilly north, just three
New York Knicks were scrimmaging with a collection of fringe free
agents and one Toronto Raptor, Charles Oakley.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Ewing probably had a better workout against Alonzo
Mourning than he would have had facing Cleveland Cavalier free
agent Shawnelle Scott at the Knicks' facility. But it is difficult
to take the Knicks' competitive drive seriously when they lack the
togetherness other teams have displayed during this week's informal
workouts.
</P>
<P>
   Training camps will open early next week. Until then, players
are on their own. At least 10 players on each team have shown up
for workouts in Detroit, Utah, Miami and Indiana. As Coach Jeff Van
Gundy hears the reports from other cities, he is dumbfounded by the
Knicks' low turnout.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're looking for some rationale, I don't have it for why
you wouldn't be there,'' said Van Gundy on a conference call
Wednesday. ``Over all, I don't have an explanation, not a real good
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask me if I'd rather have them here and everyone
participating together? Absolutely. But they are not here, and I'm
trying my best not to think about it. I can only worry about what I
can control when we get up and running. It's going to all happen
very quickly. If I see problems because we have guys who are in
poor condition, I have no excuse for that. Whether you're here or
someplace else, you need to be doing your work. You need to be in
shape and at the correct weight. I don't see any reason for any
player not to be that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the regular Knicks working out at the State University of New
York at Purchase _ Allan Houston, John Starks, Marcus Camby and the
free agent Charlie Ward _ everyone appeared in good condition.
Although he bristles at the suggestion that he has grown pudgy,
Ewing looked about 20 pounds overweight before he left town last
Thursday to go on vacation and clear his mind. The mental strain of
leading 430 players through a six-month labor dispute had sapped
his energy. He needed a vacation, and wanted to go somewhere warm.
Ewing's old Georgetown buddy, Mourning, supplied the tropical
getaway and a practice site.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ewing was scheduled to return to New York on Thursday,
one wondered how his two-day workout with the Knicks' division
rival sat with Van Gundy. The Knicks' coach once pointed out that
Michael Jordan befriended opponents, softened them up, and then
took advantage of them on the court. But if Van Gundy was irritated
with Ewing's pick of team facilities, he didn't allow it to show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't have any feeling about that,'' Van Gundy said.
``The important thing is for Patrick to come back mentally
re-charged after a draining few months. Any way he can be at his
best is fine with me. I read where he wanted to clear his mind.
It's probably easier for him to clear his mind in the sunshine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
