<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA FACES TOUGH WEEKEND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They might not think it, and they certainly won't
admit it, but the UCLA Bruins can call this weekend a success if
they win one game against California and Stanford at Pauley
Pavilion. Such is the wallop carried by the Bay Area travel
partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question, this is the toughest tandem of anybody we play,''
Bruins sophomore forward Travis Reed said. ``They're both really,
really good. If we don't play hard and intense, we're in trouble.
We could get blown out.''
</P>
<P>
   The quality of both visitors makes this weekend unique. While
Arizona, Oregon and Washington pack a punch, their travel partners
are traditionally weak. Cal is one of the best teams in the
Pacific-10, and Stanford is one of the best teams in the nation.
There is no guaranteed win for the Bruins. They can absorb one home
loss and finish in the conference's upper division, but they cannot
afford two.
</P>
<P>
   ``This weekend will probably present our most difficult
challenge in terms of back-to-back games,'' Bruins coach Steve
Lavin said. ``Cal beat North Carolina, and Stanford is capable of
winning the national championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Extending the premise a week, tonight marks the beginning of a
four-game gauntlet _ Cal, Stanford, at USC, at Louisville _ that
will help shape the Bruins' postseason fate. Two wins and they're
in good health. No wins and suddenly the NIT casts a giant shadow.
</P>
<P>
   That said, the Bruins are better equipped to combat Cal and
Stanford than in recent years. They are bigger and deeper, with
four frontcourt players (Dan Gadzuric, Jerome Moiso, Matt Barnes
and Reed)compared to one (J.R. Henderson) last year. However, Cal
and Stanford have an enormous edge in experience. Both start four
seniors and a junior, while UCLA's most common lineup _ Lavin has
used 12 in 14 games _ features two sophomores and three freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have equated this weekend's task to the challenge
they faced in Puerto Rico in November, when they unexpectedly
played Maryland and Kentucky on consecutive days. After a passive
performance against the Terps, Lavin raged and UCLA responded with
one of its best _ certainly its grittiest _ game of the season in
losing 66-62.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to take that same approach this weekend,'' Reed said.
``Both teams can get us if we're not careful.''
</P>
<P>
   Whereas Stanford relies on its front-line strength, Cal depends
on its guards, seniors Geno Carlisle and Thomas Kilgore. Combined,
they average 31.1 points and take the majority of Cal's shots in
pressure situations. Kilgore scored 21 against both North Carolina
and Stanford. Carlisle burned the Tar Heels for 29 points, although
his shot selection last weekend frustrated coach Ben Braun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Geno forced the action for us and he didn't need
to,'' Braun said.
</P>
<P>
   The third member of Cal's scoring trio is sophomore forward Sean
Lampley, who played well last month but has struggled recently,
scoring 11 points against Oregon State and five against Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has got to be more aggressive,'' Braun said. ``He has got
to get tougher on himself and go work a little harder.''
</P>
<P>
   The same is true of UCLA. Another lethargic performance (see:
American, Arizona State, Oregon State) will mean instant trouble.
The Bruins must play as they did against Arizona and Oregon if they
hope to finish above those teams in the standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the team knows how big a weekend this is for us,''
Farnham said. ``If we win both, if solidifies us as a Pac-10 title
contender.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
