<SLUG> BC-BKN-WEST-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST: JORDAN'S TIMING RIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Jerry West watched Michael Jordan's farewell
speech Wednesday morning and saw something disconcerting. Something
even a little familiar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at him, and to be candid, he looked drained, just
emotionally drained,'' West said. ``This is an awkward day for him
... but in his mind this is going to be a day that when he looks
back at is going to say, `Thank God I walked away from it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   West should know. The Lakers' executive vice president and Hall
of Famer retired as a player under similar circumstances. When West
hung it up in 1973, he was 36 years old and still at the top of his
game. Jordan will be 36 next month.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a key difference in the exits of West and Jordan,
two of the game's brightest stars of their eras.
</P>
<P>
   When West retired, he did so during the exhibition season,
bitter with owner Jack Kent Cooke over issues of trust and to a
degree, compensation. Physically, he figured he had two good
seasons left, but mentally he no longer had the drive _ ``I felt no
excitement sitting in the locker room,'' he has said.
</P>
<P>
   West left on his own terms, but under adverse conditions. He
declines to revisit the event, saying ``I don't like to talk about
myself. It was far from perfect, that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan had his own burdens, West said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a player that, at least from maybe the public's
perception, he was carrying the NBA. And pretty soon he's asked to
be the greatest player in the league and asked to carry his team
like no other player has ever done. The weight of the world is on
your shoulders,'' West said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know when I said I retired, it felt like the weight of the
world was off my shoulders,'' he said. ``I got out from under a
burden that was crushing me. I hope (Jordan) feels the same about
walking away.''
</P>
<P>
   While so many other superstars try to prolong their careers past
their primes, Jordan leaves on top. Last season, he took the Bulls
to their sixth title in eight years, and Jordan clinched it in
storybook fashion, hitting the game-winning jumper in the decisive
Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to go out the way he did,'' West said. ``He went out
at the very highest peak of his career, with the very greatest
respect of maybe any athlete I've ever seen. That's the way I think
anyone who has given as much to a particular team or franchise
would like to go out. It's not reserved for everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my perspective, I'm happy for him,'' West said. ``I know
how hard those decisions are to make.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 2316EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
