u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-SCOTUS-NYT &LR;      01-13 0449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SCOTUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: OF FAIRNESS AND FEDERALISM 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ga.)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Jan. 14:
</P>
<P>
   A pair of provocative cases before the Supreme Court this week,
one on sexual harassment and one on welfare benefits, raise very
different legal issues. Yet the challenge for the justices in both
cases is the same _ to act firmly against discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   In the first case, the court heard oral arguments on whether
Title IX, the law that bars sex discrimination by schools that
receive federal money, requires that schools take reasonable steps
to stop sexual harassment by one student against another.
</P>
<P>
   That question was raised by the ordeal of LaShonda Davis, a
fifth-grade girl in Georgia who was subjected to months of unwanted
poking, grabbing and sexual taunting by a male classmate. Her
mother's complaints to school authorities proved unavailing. Yet a
lower appellate court tossed out her harassment lawsuit, finding
that Title IX does not cover student-on-student harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Reversing that unjust decision should be a relatively easy call
in light of the plain language of the statute and the court's
analogous decision in June holding schools liable for damages when
they know of sexual harassment of a student by a teacher and
respond with deliberate indifference. The fact that the harasser in
this case was another student should not change the school's
culpability. Some justices expressed concern about a deluge of
frivolous lawsuits. But to be actionable, the offending behavior
would have to be sufficiently egregious to effectively deny an
educational opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   In the second case, the court turned Wednesday to the terms of
welfare reform. California, like a number of states, has decided to
hold new residents, for the first year, to the level of benefits
available in their home states _ typically an inadequate amount for
subsistence in California.
</P>
<P>
   In an important 1969 case, Shapiro vs. Thompson, the court ruled
that it violated the constitutional right to travel to deny all
welfare benefits to newcomers. But defenders of California's scheme
say it does not ``penalize'' newcomers since it only holds them to
the amount of benefits in their old state. They also cite Congress'
expressed desire to allow states leeway in this area.
</P>
<P>
   But these are not acceptable excuses for tampering with the
structure of federalism and the constitutional principle Justice
Ruth Bader Ginsburg aptly termed the ``genius of the United
States.'' Americans have a right to settle in any state they choose
without being treated as second-class citizens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
