A2382 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELL-AOL-INTERNET-NYT     01-13 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELL-AOL-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AOL AND BELL ATLANTIC PLAN TO JOINTLY MARKET HIGH-SPEED INTERNET
ACCESS 
 (DW) 
</HEADLINE>
 By AMY HARMON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a move to compete with high-speed cable-modem services,
America Online and Bell Atlantic Wednesday announced a joint
marketing effort to sell high-speed Internet access to America
Online's customers.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance marks a significant step in America Online's effort
to retain its leadership as a ``portal,'' or entry point, to the
Internet in a market increasingly moving toward high-speed Internet
access. The cable-modem business currently has only about 500,000
customers nationwide but is expected to more than double this year.
</P>
<P>
   That presents a threat to local telephone companies and to
portals, which make their money primarily by selling advertising on
sites that millions of Internet users pass through daily. Of the
top portals _ which include Yahoo, NetCenter and Go _ America
Online, with 15 million members, is the largest.
</P>
<P>
   The cable modem business is dominated by At Home and Roadrunner,
which are portals as well as technologies for accessing the
Internet over TV cables. While America Online and other portals can
be used over cable modems, they are not users' first stop in
cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, local phone companies are eager to compete
with cable companies by offering asymmetrical digital subscriber
line, or ADSL, technology over existing phone lines. ADSL service
does not require customers to dial in, and connection speeds are
about 20 times faster than standard modems.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deal is part of our plan to beat cable modems,'' said Amy
McIntosh, president of consumer data services for Bell Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   America Online said many of its members in Bell Atlantic's East
Coast territory would be able to purchase the service this summer
for an extra $20 a month, bringing the total cost to $40 a month.
That is in line with the $40 a month charged by cable modem
services but about $20 less than Bell Atlantic charges for full
Internet service over ADSL.
</P>
<P>
   America Online members who have cable modems pay $10 a month,
about half the fees charged dial-up members.
</P>
<P>
   America Online's president, Robert W. Pittman, said: ``Some of
our customers are interested in speed, and we want to provide it
for them in a package that makes sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic said that close to 7.5 million customers would be
able to get ADSL by the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people who want high-speed Internet are going to look
first to their Internet service provider, not the local cable
provider or phone company,'' Andy Fuertes, a senior analyst at
Allied Business Intelligence, a research firm, said Wednesday. ``So
having someone like AOL involved who is more savvy about marketing
to the consumer is a big plus.''
</P>
<P>
   America Online shares fell $7.875 to $145.75 Wednesday, while
Bell Atlantic rose $1.1875 to $54.9375.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
