u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINORITIES-WALLST-NYT     01-13 0442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINORITIES-WALLST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK AUTO DEALER COULD BE TEST CASE FOR INCLUSION 
 (DW) 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Mich., Ohio, Texas)  By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Rev. Jesse L. Jackson opens up the Wall Street Project
conference on minorities and investment Thursday, one of the
central players is expected to be Mel Farr, who heads the nation's
largest black-owned auto dealership.
</P>
<P>
   Farr, who operates dealerships in Michigan, Ohio and Texas, has
been held up by Jackson as one of the nation's leading minority
entrepreneurs, a prime candidate for Wall Street to look to if it
is going to invest in minority businesses and neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   But Wall Street has not yet embraced Farr's effort to raise $45
million in a private placement of asset-backed securities to expand
his dealerships.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have anything concrete yet,'' said Farr, who plans to
meet this week with officials at Citigroup and Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.
``This is a test. We want inclusion. I've got a portfolio of
investment grade, and now I want to see if they're going to invest
in an African-American business that does business in the
African-American community.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Farr, 54, might be seen as an early test case for
the Wall Street Project, which Jackson and Farr, who are longtime
friends, say is all about investing in the ``emerging markets of
urban areas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He comes to Wall Street looking for access to capital,''
Jackson said last night. ``And we're going to work hard for him.''
Of Wall Street, he added: ``They can't say they can't find a guy.
They have a guy. He comes to the plate with all the qualities.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few decades, Farr, a former pro football player,
says he has turned a bunch of failing dealerships in the Detroit
area into a business with more than $600 million in revenue. He
built his business selling and leasing cars in poor neighborhoods,
to minorities with little or no credit, often at high interest
rates. He says that for many it is their only way to get
transportation for some jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Although he caters primarily to minorities, he also has
dealerships in largely white neighborhoods. His sales are often
bolstered by television ads aimed at blacks that feature
``Superstar Mel Farr'' with Farr in a suit and a red cape.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, there were also television ads that spotlighted
a white actor in commercials done for a dealership in Fairfield,
Ohio, which Farr says illustrates how difficult it is to cross over
in some areas. ``It's a market that is primarily white Americans,
and I didn't want to turn off those customers because I am black,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-13-99 2321EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990113.0514 </DOCNO>
