<HEADLINE>
ADVANCED MICRO PROFIT FAILS   TO MEET ANALYSTS' ESTIMATES 
 (DW) 
</HEADLINE>
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Advanced Micro Devices &UR;  &LR; Inc. reported
fourth-quarter earnings Wednesday that fell a few cents short of
analysts' estimates. It was the company's second consecutive
profitable quarter after it reported losses in the first half of
1998.
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth quarter, Advanced Micro reported earnings of
$22.3 million, or 15 cents a diluted share, compared with a loss of
$12.3 million in the quarter a year earlier. The company was
expected to earn 19 cents a share, the average estimate of analysts
polled by the First Call Corp., which tracks company earnings.
Revenue rose 29 percent, to $788.8 million from $613.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   For the year, Advanced Micro reported a loss of $104 million,
compared with a loss of $21.1 million in 1997. Revenue rose 8
percent, to $2.54 billion from $2.36 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Advanced Micro attributed the earnings shortfall to
manufacturing problems that prevented it from shipping more of its
fastest chips, 400- megahertz processors, which command higher
profit margins. The company has had this kind of slip-up before
with new chips. But the disappointment was all the more acute
coming in a quarter where strong results at disparate companies
such as the Intel Corp. and Apple Computer &UR;  &LR; Inc. made it clear that
demand for personal computers and microprocessors is surging.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got the problem behind us now,'' W.J. Sanders III, the
chairman and chief executive of Advanced Micro, said in a telephone
conference call with securities analysts. ``We shipped hundreds of
thousands of 400-megahertz processors but were unable to satisfy
strong overall market demand,'' he said. ``We expect to
substantially increase shipments of 400-megahertz processors in the
current quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Advanced Micro reported its results after the market closed. Its
shares fell $3.75, to $27.75, Wednesday on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a keen disappointment,'' said Mark Edelstone, an
analyst with Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``The company delivered
the unit volume we expected, but they once again had some
manufacturing execution issues that prevented them from delivering
the earnings.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
