</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPANO-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORY THAT ONE MISTRESS SHOT THE OTHER `LUDICROUS,' PROSECUTOR
SAYS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Del.)   (rk) 
 By   WILLIAM GLABERSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Del. _ In his summation at the murder trial of a
wealthy and influential Wilmington lawyer, a prosecutor urged
jurors Wednesday to dismiss as absurd the defendant's story that
one of his mistresses accidentally shot another.
</P>
<P>
   ``That story is ludicrous,'' the prosecutor, Colm F. Connolly,
told the jurors in his final remarks before they begin
deliberations. ``That story defies common sense. It is not
credible.''
</P>
<P>
   But the chief defense lawyer countered that jurors should not
convict the lawyer, Thomas J. Capano, just because he had admitted
a series of ``things that may offend you,'' such as adultery, lying
to investigators, pornography or dumping the body of his former
lover into the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't vote guilty,'' said the defense lawyer, Joseph S.
Oteri, ``because you don't like Tom Capano and what he did.'' One
thing Capano did not do, Oteri said, was kill his mistress, Anne
Marie Fahey, the 30-year old appointments secretary to Gov. Thomas
Carper of Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   The trial, which has lent a tinge of soap opera to Delaware's
elite, has focused in recent weeks on Capano's version of events.
In a rare and risky defense move, Capano took the stand to make his
own case. He admitted that he had thrown the body of Fahey into the
Atlantic in a large cooler. But he denied murdering her in June
1996. Prosecutors said he killed her because there was a new man in
her life.
</P>
<P>
   Capano, the scion of one of Delaware's wealthiest real-estate
families, blamed another mistress, Deborah A. MacIntyre. He said
she burst in on Fahey and him with a drawn pistol and incoherent
talk of suicide. ``Debby shot Anne Marie'' accidentally when he
grabbed her arm, he testified last month. Then, he said, he
panicked and began elaborate preparations to dispose of the body,
which has never been found.
</P>
<P>
   Connolly reminded the jurors Wednesday that Capano, who was
separated from his wife at the time of Fahey's death, had said for
more than two years that he knew nothing of Fahey's disappearance.
Only when the trial began this fall did Capano say for the first
time that Fahey had died as a result of what his lawyer called ``an
outrageous, horrible, tragic accident.''
</P>
<P>
   In a courtroom that was steamy from heat and more than 200
people, Connolly dwelled on what the prosecutors say were the
telltale signs of Capano's plot to have Fahey for himself, or be
sure that no one else did.
</P>
<P>
   Some witnesses have described the victim as an energetic beauty.
But there was also testimony that she was insecure and struggled
with anorexia. Connolly, a federal prosecutor who has worked with
Delaware prosecutors on the case in state Superior Court here, led
the jurors through the prosecution's version of what he called the
49-year-old Capano's manipulation of Fahey: gifts, scores of
telephone calls, e-mail messages and unexpected visits.
</P>
<P>
   But then, as Fahey's relationship with a younger man blossomed,
Connolly said, Capano needed to try to keep control. He acquired a
gun and a large picnic cooler, a long chain and a heavy lock for
disposal of the corpse.
</P>
<P>
   With relentless detail, in a closing statement that began at 9
a.m. and lasted until well after lunch, Connolly described Capano
as someone who felt he did not have to live by the rules. He asked
why Capano had delayed so long in admitting that he knew what had
happened to Fahey as her family and investigators grew frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer,'' Connolly said, ``is because the defendant
thought he would get away with murder.''
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Oteri, a renown defense lawyer from Boston, had
the harder task Wednesday. By testifying, Capano opened himself to
detailed questions about such events as an abortive plan by Capano
to have someone burglarize MacIntyre's home while he was in jail
and she was beginning to consider cooperating with the prosecutors
as a witness against him.
</P>
<P>
   Oteri seemed to take to the challenge before him with verve. He
called Capano ``Tommy'' and exuberantly reminded the jurors of the
virtues of the American justice system's requirement that no one
can be found guilty unless there is evidence beyond a reasonable
doubt.
</P>
<P>
   He portrayed Capano as a caring friend of Fahey and not the
stalker described by prosecutors. But he argued that his client was
something of a bumbler.
</P>
<P>
   Such missteps as the would-be burglary, which prosecutors have
suggested was an effort to intimidate a potential witness, were,
Oteri said, all evidence that Capano was simply a man valiantly
trying to protect MacIntyre, the ostensible real shooter.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the stupid things that happened,'' Oteri mused. ``All of
which are consistent with this being caused by Debby MacIntyre and
him reacting badly.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most difficult hurdle for the defense has been the
testimony of one of Capano's brothers, Gerard, who told the court
that he helped dispose of Fahey's body. Gerard Capano also
acknowledged drug and alcohol abuse.
</P>
<P>
   His testimony against Capano, Oteri said, was just ``the ravings
of Gerry's drug-addled mind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
