A2394 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JETS-DAVIS-NYT     01-13 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-DAVIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS' DEFENSE WILL TRY TO CHANGE DAVIS' SCRIPT 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ The best running back the Jets _ ``or anyone
else,'' according to Coach Bill Parcells _ have faced this season
loomed on the projection screen here for the defense Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos' Terrell Davis did his 2,000-yard thing via the
magic of videotape. Curtis Martin, Davis' counterpart for the Jets,
did not need to see films of his good friend. Martin knows what his
teammates must do to halt Davis on Sunday in the American Football
Conference championship at Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't let him run you over,'' Martin said simply.
</P>
<P>
   Davis ran over about everyone this season in becoming the fourth
runner in National Football League history to generate 2,000 yards.
He amassed 2,008, averaging 5.1 yards a carry, and scored 21
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   So, perhaps it was not surprising that the way the Jets
described Davis, he was a running back without weaknesses, an
athlete who compensates for his mistakes while taking advantage of
the defense's errors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some running backs, they just go out there and
run,'' defensive end Rick Lyle said. ``But he has good techniques
for avoiding tackles. He keeps his knees high. He has a great body
lean.''
</P>
<P>
   Largely because of Davis, the Broncos have been able to dispose
of many opponents by the end of the first quarter. Denver outscores
its opposition by _ and this is no misprint _ 47 points to 9 on the
opening drive. By the end of the opening quarter, the differential
is 144-55. No wonder the Broncos won their first 13 games en route
to a 14-2 regular-season record.
</P>
<P>
   ``We script the first 15 plays and we'll stick with that unless
the defense throws something different at us; so our players are
accustomed to it,'' Broncos Coach Mike Shanahan said.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, they will stick with Davis. He helped lead the
Broncos to the Super Bowl title a year ago, and now, after 17
games, he seems refreshed. He galloped for 199 yards in the
Broncos' playoff victory over Miami last Saturday. He says he was
helped by the bye week, and now he gets an extra day between games.
</P>
<P>
   ``What separates Terrell from the others is he's got the
complete package of all the backs I've ever been around,'' Shanahan
said. ``He's got power. He's got the ability to make people miss.
He's got the ability to make the big play.''
</P>
<P>
   That means the burden on quarterback John Elway to always make
the big play has eased. Despite Elway's long record of success and
Super Bowl appearances, Davis is the first Pro Bowl runner to share
his backfield. Having Davis _ as well as tight end Shannon Sharpe
and the Bronco wide receivers, Rod Smith and Ed McCaffrey _ means
Elway does not have to be the triple-threat player he once was.
</P>
<P>
   ``The obvious thing about Denver is their strong running
attack,'' Parcells said. ``Better than 150 yards per game _ and the
explosiveness with which they start their games.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Davis, Parcells said: ``I would have to put him in the
category of great backs I've played against. They can do things to
put teams in a hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis had an outstanding game the last time he faced a Parcells
team with a Bill Belichick defense. That was against the Patriots
in 1996, when Davis rushed for 154 yards and 2 touchdowns on a
season-high 32 carries. He also scored on a catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``That game got out of hand early,'' Parcells said, dismissing
any significance. But Davis said of that game, and Belichick in
particular, ``You make yourself more experienced with what he's
going to bring to the table, and that helps us.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it will. But no running back has gained 100 yards
against the Jets in 11 games. The last one was the Patriots' Robert
Edwards in Game 6, in a losing effort. Only one other runner
reached the 100-yard figure against the Jets. That was the 49ers'
Garrison Hearst, and it took his 96-yard run in overtime to crack
the barrier.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells is concerned about Davis' ability to keep drives
moving, and then score from the red zone _ the Broncos have
produced touchdowns almost two-thirds of the time they get to the
20-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their running game,'' Parcells said, ``is not a complex
running game. It's a simple game, but they do a lot of repetitions.
Davis makes his linemen look good. Our secondary will have to be
ready or we're in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   The linebackers will have to slow Davis. ``I have to be aware to
turn him inside,'' the right-side linebacker Chad Cascadden said.
``He's kind of like Fred Taylor last week with Jacksonville, only
better. He's got a great stiff arm and he breaks tackles. It's a
question of hanging on to him. You look at the tapes and you see a
defender hanging on, and then the defender falls.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best,'' backup safety Chris Hayes said. ``I've never
seen a guy hit the hole like that. We've got to bring it on this
week because this dude's everything wrapped up in one.''
</P>
<P>
   Victor Green, the Jets' safety and leading tackler, talked ``of
bringing everything I've got, because if you arm-tackle this guy,
he'll get away from you.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells was asked whether Davis' vision was why he ran so well.
``I've got good vision,'' the coach said, ``but I can't run like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA POINT
</P>
<P>
   Winston Hill, who played with the Jets from 1963-76, will be the
team's honorary captain Sunday. Hill, who owns two barbeque
restaurants in the Denver area, told a Jets official, ``You've made
my dreams come true.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
