<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-DAVIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIG PLAY IN DENVER FOR MEGGETT AND COACH
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: See also JETS-DAVIS) (DW) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ With the American Football Conference
championship game in Denver just four days away, Jets Coach Bill
Parcells and his longtime favorite kick returner, David Meggett,
both remembered the same thing about Parcells' last _ and only _
visit as a head coach to Mile High Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was snowing,'' Parcells recalled at the Jets' camp
Wednesday, telling of a game played in Meggett's rookie season of
1989.
</P>
<P>
   It snowed eight inches on that December day in Denver. That was
what Meggett said he remembered most, too.
</P>
<P>
   With a little prodding, Meggett, a 10-year veteran who signed
with the Jets on Dec. 15, remembered something else about the first
of the two games he has ever played at Mile High, a 14-7 Giants
victory over the Broncos. For it was Meggett's 57-yard touchdown
off a screen pass from Phil Simms _ a pass that Meggett initially
had juggled before he scampered through the snow _ that gave the
Giants a two-touchdown lead and put the game away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember all my touchdowns,'' Meggett said. ``There have
been only two or three of them in the league since I've been
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Meggett actually has scored 11 touchdowns receiving, 8 rushing,
6 on punt returns and 1 on a kickoff return during a career in
which he has established himself as the National Football League's
career-leading punt returner. But this touchdown was special.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was third and like a mile, or something like that,''
Meggett said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   It was third-and-31, after the Giants had lost yards on
consecutive downs following a 26-yard Meggett punt return.
</P>
<P>
   This Sunday's forecast does not include snow. But both Meggett
and Parcells hope that Meggett, who has reached a Super Bowl and a
Pro Bowl with both the Giants and the New England Patriots, has one
more big play in him resembling that Denver touchdown in his rookie
season. Especially because Meggett _ who is the only player to play
for Parcells with the Giants, the Patriots and now the Jets _ has
never scored a touchdown in 12 career post-season games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about plays like that all the time,'' Meggett said.
``A play that can change the complexion of a game. Big players make
big plays in big games. And that's what I want to be known as: a
big-time player.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he is only 5 feet 7 inches and 195 pounds, Meggett
has always had a reputation as a player who can break a game open
with one big run, catch or return.
</P>
<P>
   But last fall, Meggett was spending his time as a student at
Towson State in Maryland, working on his undergraduate degree in
sports administration.
</P>
<P>
   Because he was coming off April foot surgery, an off-season
arrest on charges of theft and assault in Toronto (a misdemeanor
theft charge is still pending) and an acrimonious salary dispute
with the Patriots _ all of which led to Meggett's departure from
New England _ Meggett said that he was prepared to not play at all
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he hit the schoolbooks, not the playbooks. In his first
go-through at Towson State, Meggett said all he cared about was
playing football, not how well he was doing in class. Now, Meggett
said, he had disciplined himself through the countless hours he had
spent in the NFL studying film, going to practice and learning to
be on time, and he became a straight-A student in three classes
last semester (with two class finals pending). He is 27 credits
short of a degree.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, Meggett kept in contact with Parcells, as Meggett
said he had always done. Parcells would ask Meggett about his
weight; Meggett would ask Parcells about his.
</P>
<P>
   Meggett's foot began to feel better, and in mid-December, the
Jets lost Leon Johnson for the season because of a broken rib. Out
went the call for Meggett, who played in the Jets' final two
regular-season games against Buffalo and New England and then
returned all the punts and kickoffs in last Sunday's 34-24 playoff
victory over Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really only had one real good opportunity,'' Parcells
said. ``And he almost ran that for a touchdown. That was against
New England. He had 10 guys behind him. On Sunday, he only had a
chance to return one punt. So, I think he'll be OK''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday against the Broncos, Meggett will again be the Jets'
primary returner, as well as a third-down back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not amazed because he's a very smart player,'' Parcells
said. ``He knew the pass protections better than the quarterbacks
when he was playing for the Giants.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
