<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 23:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2400 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINORITY-RADIO-AD-COL     01-13 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINORITY-RADIO-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AD COLUMN: STUDY FINDS DISCRIMINATION IN RADIO ADS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., N.Y.)   (nk) 
 BY STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A manager in New York for three FM radio stations _
one aimed at a black audience, the others at broader general
audiences _ reports that upscale car companies like Volvo and BMW
refuse to buy advertisements on the black station, even when shown
market surveys indicating that the black audience is more
interested in buying such cars.
</P>
<P>
   At a different company, which represents broadcasters selling
air time to advertisers, an executive writes a training memo
contending that ``the nonethnic consumer is more attractive'' and
recommending that clients be steered toward radio stations with
broader-based audiences because ``advertisers should want prospects
not suspects.''
</P>
<P>
   And in Washington, of the three leading radio stations, all with
similar ratings and audience demographics, the one owned by CBS
Corp. reported more revenues than the combined total of the other
two _ one run by Howard University and the other by Radio One Inc.,
one of the country's largest minority broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
   These accounts of disparities and discrimination in radio
advertising were detailed Wednesday in a report by the Federal
Communications Commission. The year-and-a-half-long review, which
included a survey of 3,745 stations based on 1996 data, is the
first government study on the subject. It concludes that radio
stations aimed primarily at black and Hispanic audiences receive
significantly less ad revenue per listener and have also been
forced to offer deeper discounts than their mainstream
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This report's findings are bleak and shameful,'' said Rep.
Carolyn Cheeks Kilpatrick, D-Mich., who has studied the issue.
``But they come as no surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-one percent of the minority broadcasters surveyed
encountered what are known in the industry's jargon as ``dictates''
not to buy commercials on their radio stations. On average, each of
them encountered 26 such dictates annually.
</P>
<P>
   The report, which highlighted practices that many minority
broadcasters and advertising agencies have complained about for
years, cautioned that racial discrimination might not be the only
reason for their lagging revenues. Revenues may also be affected by
demographics and ratings, and companies owning more stations often
have significantly bigger buying power.
</P>
<P>
   But while there were calls Wednesday for changes in advertising
practices, officials acknowledged that there was little legal
action that could be taken to force companies to comply. The FCC
has recently had few successes in the courts or in Congress on a
variety of civil rights-related claims. Last April, in a major
defeat, a federal appeals court here struck down a government
requirement that radio and television stations seek minority
applicants.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the agency does not technically have jurisdiction over
advertising issues, and it is not clear whether other government
agencies have any stronger authority.
</P>
<P>
   A number of minority-run advertising companies and broadcasters
have suggested that the White House consider issuing an executive
order that would impose possible sanctions on any advertisers that
discriminate and are also government contractors.
</P>
<P>
   At a forum held Wednesday at the FCC to discuss the report,
Judith Ellis, a senior vice president and manager of three FM
stations in New York _ WRKS, WQHT and WQCD _ for Emmis
Broadcasting, said she could give dozens of examples in which
advertisers refused to buy air time on WRKS, which programs adult
contemporary music aimed at black audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ellis, whose examples were cited in the report, said that
representatives of both BMW and the New York Volvo Dealers
Association had refused to place ads on WRKS, even though marketing
information clearly showed that listeners of the station closely
matched the profile of the auto companies' typical customers.
</P>
<P>
   Martha McKinley, a spokeswoman in the United States for BMW
A.G., said she could not speak about the incident reported by Ms.
Ellis. ``We don't purchase a lot of radio,'' Ms. McKinley said.
``Print is a significant portion of our advertising media mix, and
we do buy in African-American and other minority publications.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Austin, director of marketing communications for Volvo
Cars of North America, said he had not seen the report and that he
had little control over the advertising decisions of a dealers
association. But he also emphasized that the company's media
decisions were controlled by things like affluence, household
income levels and education levels and had nothing to do with
racial issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We reach successful people through Forbes and Fortune,'' he
said. ``Successful black businessmen and women read those
magazines. Successful Asian businessmen and women read those
magazines.''
</P>
<P>
   The study was supported by the American Advertising Federation
in Washington, which is composed of media companies, advertising
agencies and marketers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FCC report is a blessing in disguise if it helps us to
accelerate the pace of progress,'' said Wally Snyder, president and
chief executive of the federation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The report shows there are problems we need to overcome in the
way advertising is bought and sold,'' he added. The federation will
appoint a task force, Snyder said, to examine ways to promote what
he termed equity in media buying and selling, including the
feasibility of a voluntary code of conduct. The study is also to be
discussed at a conference on multicultural marketing and media; the
conference, to be held on Monday in Manhattan, was scheduled before
the study's release.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
