<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAME AGAINST JETS MAY BE ELWAY'S LAST  
(RK)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENGLEWOOD, Colo. _ He is old _ six months shy of his 39th
birthday _ and tired, too. More than 250 games in the National
Football League over 16 seasons means thousands of hits and months
of hurt. But John Elway got healed and got younger last year when
he drank from a career-affirming fountain.
</P>
<P>
   In San Diego. At Super Bowl XXXII.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver Broncos' 31-24 victory over the Green Bay Packers
last year brought Elway his first Super Bowl championship. It
bought him another year. He remembers sitting in his hotel room
after the game, his mind racing over a record-setting career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would anybody have a tough time getting motivated to come
back and win another one when winning a Super Bowl feels this
good?'' he remembered thinking. ``It's still a fresh memory for me.
I'd love to feel it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe just once more. Or maybe not. On the day Michael Jordan
officially announced he was satisfied with the living highlight
reel he would leave behind, Elway clutched his retirement cards
close to his flak jacket and insisted that Sunday's American
Conference championship game against the Jets was bigger than what
he may or may not do next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to even let that enter my mind, what I'm doing
next year,'' Elway said. ``I'm just going to try to enjoy what I
came back for, these situations. I'm going to enjoy it now and
cross that bridge when the season's over.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is a sense in the Broncos locker room and throughout
this city that Sunday will be the last time Elway takes a snap in
Mile High Stadium. That, in essence, the Jets will determine
whether Elway has 60 more minutes of football left in his glorious
career or whether he will take the Super Bowl stage for a fifth and
final time _ something no other National Football League
quarterback has done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think John would rather go out with one more year left than
stay and maybe find out that he should have left,'' Bronco tight
end Shannon Sharpe said.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Terrell Davis, who ran for 2,008 yards and his
first NFL rushing title, tried to sound philosophical about an
Elway-less Bronco team. ``All good things have to come to an end at
some point in time,'' he said. ``I'm just blessed I had the
opportunity to play with John for four years. If this is his last
game, let's hope it ends on a positive note.'' Then he added,
``We'll try to talk him out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos guide needs 25 pages to layout the accomplishments
of Elway's career. The highlights? He ranks second only to Dan
Marino in passing yards (51,475), attempts (7,250), completions
(4,123) and total offense (54,882).
</P>
<P>
   He has a record 46 fourth-quarter or overtime game-winning
drives, and six of them were engineered in the postseason. Elway is
the NFL's winningest quarterback with a 148-82-1 regular-season
record for a .643 winning percentage. He also is 12-7 in the
postseason and an astounding 4-1 in the AFC championship game.
</P>
<P>
   But it's an uncharacteristic poor statistic that makes Elway and
the Broncos especially dangerous heading into the Jets game: his
1-3 record in the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's victory, in Elway's thinking, erases the three
losses. ``It has taken the monkey off our back,'' he said. ``It's
going to change the attitude a little bit going into these playoffs
because we got rid of a lot of skeletons. This year, because we got
that last year, not having to think about the pressure of not ever
having won one is not there anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   While Elway may have felt the pull of another year as he sat in
his hotel room after the victory over the Packers, he spent much of
the offseason weighing his options with his wife, Janet. His
amazingly durable 6-foot-3-inch, 215-pound frame was nicked but not
battered after 15 NFL seasons. His children _ Jessica, Gwen,
Jordan, and Jack, who range in age from 13 to 7 _ were old enough
to understand and revel in his Sunday afternoons of combat.
</P>
<P>
   In Davis and Sharpe, Elway had Pro Bowl selections in the
offensive skill positions for the first time in his career. Both,
along with receiver Ed McCaffrey, were selected again this year, as
was Elway, who will start his sixth Pro Bowl and make his ninth
appearance. In short, it was an easier decision to return.
</P>
<P>
   But Elway took his lumps, missing a career-high four starts and
a part of another game with a hamstring and rib injuries as the
Broncos started the season 13-0 before losing two of their last
three and finishing 14-2. He was 210 of 356 for 2,806 yards and 22
touchdowns with 10 interceptions. It was only the third time in his
career that he did not surpass 3,000 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got frustrating, but, no, I never looked back,'' Elway
said, refusing to blame the injuries on his age. ``If we were 1-5
at the time, I'd have probably thought differently. Your back is
connected to your hamstring. And I fell on the ball. A 23-year-old
can fall on the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   But his friend and backup Bubby Brister also noticed a
contentment in Elway that probably won't translate into another
year. He said the quarterback is more relaxed, that his kids have
become a fixture around the Broncos facility and that, frankly,
Elway could have pushed himself to return to the lineup more
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think part of it was having me around,'' said Brister, who
was 4-0 and threw 10 touchdowns. ``He had some injuries that may
have caught up with him. We were winning and he was relaxed and
having fun. I think he knew that this is the time of year we needed
him healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sharpe warns that no one _ especially the Jets _ should
worry that the quarterback is intoxicated by the easy pace that
marks the twilight of his career. He threw only 23 times and for
one touchdown in the Broncos' 38-3 victory over the Dolphins last
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take my chances with No. 7,'' Sharpe said. ``A great
player doesn't forget how to be great.''
</P>
<P>
   All Elway is promising right now is another 60 minutes against
the Jets and 60 more after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I said,'' he said, smiling. ``This is what I came back
for.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
