<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALCONS KEEP TALKING A GOOD GAME
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUWANEE, Ga. _ Ray Buchanan knows that Minnesota's Randy Moss
has had a spectacular rookie season _ 17 touchdown catches, 1,313
receiving yards. So Buchanan, Atlanta's Pro Bowl cornerback, wants
to see just how tough Moss is on Sunday during the National
Football Conference championship game in the Metrodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to bring a butter knife on the football field and
I'm going to find out if he bleeds,'' Buchanan said Wednesday at
the Falcons' training facility. ``If you cut him and he bleeds,
that lets you know the man is human.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan suspects Moss and Minnesota's other starting receiver,
veteran Cris Carter, are not only human, they also are defensible,
despite their combined 2,324 receiving yards and National Football
League-record 29 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at their team,'' Buchanan said, warming up. ``They
haven't been against great corners. They haven't been against a
great defense such as ours. We're a humble football team. But if
somebody doesn't respect us, that's when we're going to come back
and bark and bite you in the behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan had just stepped out of his silver Mercedes after
having lunch with teammate Eugene Robinson, the free safety who
played on Green Bay's 1996 Super Bowl-winning team.
</P>
<P>
   The two eat at the same restaurant every Wednesday and Thursday,
sit in the same spot and order the same food. ``They're one game
ahead of us and that's about it,'' Buchanan said (the Vikings are
16-1; the Falcons are 15-2). ``I think we match up well against
those guys, and people are going to have to start recognizing
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, who is in his second season with Atlanta, has 28
interceptions in his six-year career. Robinson joined the Falcons
as a free agent during the off season. He has 50 career
interceptions, tops among active defensive backs.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dan Reeves believed Robinson could still play at age 35,
but wondered if he still had the drive to do the off-season
conditioning necessary to compete on a high level.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been all that we hoped for,'' Reeves said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson planned to bring his Super Bowl ring to Thursday's
practice, to show teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're riding high and as we enter the championship game; we're
just so hungry,'' he said. ``We just want to get out there and
taste what we can taste, get what we can get.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson has been telling teammates the importance of seizing
the moment. ``If we don't, the moment could pass us by and we're
sitting at home watching someone else do their thing,'' he said.
``It is incumbent upon us to get every fumble, get every
interception. If you don't get those plays, they don't come back
around.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons led the NFL in take-aways with 44 and in turnover
differential at plus-20. They also scored six touchdowns on
turnovers, the most in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're a very good football team,'' Robinson said.
``Just not that many people are giving us that much credit. I don't
really care if they're the favorite. All I know is that preparation
and readiness and busting someone in the mouth legally is most
likely going to win this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said he will likely divide time on Sunday between Moss
and Carter, who produced 12 touchdowns and 1,011 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want everybody,'' he said. ``I don't care who it is. I'm
going to move around.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan was so loquacious Wednesday that he inadvertently gave
a backhanded compliment to Michael Booker, another Atlanta
cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody looks at him as our weak link, but he's been doing a
great job,'' Buchanan said. ``We've been doing a good job of hiding
him and putting Eugene on top of him, where he can make some
big-time plays. When you've got Eugene Robinson covering you,
you're in great shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone asked Buchanan how playing in the Metrodome, a sea of
purple during Vikings games, might affect the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we look up and see the color purple, we're definitely
going to be color-blind,'' he said. ``This football team is going
to rise to the occasion, no matter what hurdle you put in front of
us. We're licking our chops. We're ready to compete against those
guys.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
