<SLUG> BC-NY-READING-EXAM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE EXAMINES TESTS TO SEE IF STUDENTS HAD UNFAIR ADVANTAGE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ga., Iowa, Fla., Wis.)  (nk) 
 By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the second day of the new fourth-grade reading
test that has stirred so much anxiety around the state, education
officials scrambled Wednesday to deal with a problem that appeared
on the first day: Thousands of children who took the test's first
section had already studied much of the material on which it was
based.
</P>
<P>
   Testing experts said those children would be likely to remember
information needed to answer questions. And the experts said the
test's publisher and the state Education Department should have
taken steps to prevent the problem before the test was approved and
administered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point here is that this clearly was an avoidable case,''
said Robert Berne, vice president for academic development at New
York University.
</P>
<P>
   Now officials say they will examine the tests of those children
_ as many as one out of every 12 fourth-graders in New York _
looking for irregularities like unexpectedly high scores on the
first day of the test.
</P>
<P>
   The aim is to determine whether those children had an unfair
advantage. But it is unclear what the Education Department will be
able to learn that simply by looking at the scores and what it will
do about the problem, which was first reported Wednesday in The New
York Post.
</P>
<P>
   The test, which has prompted both praise and loathing, goes
beyond the multiple-choice questions of the past by requiring
children to read and listen to complex passages of fiction and
nonfiction, and to write essays, including a personal one, with
correct spelling, grammar and punctuation.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the three portions of the three-day test did involve
multiple choice questions, and that is the portion that was given
on Monday and that the state is now investigating.
</P>
<P>
   The state plans to use the test to determine whether schools are
failing. Scores on the test are closely watched by parents looking
for the best schools for their children, and in some districts the
fourth-grade test is used to admit children to competitive middle
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Roseanne DeFabio, assistant state commissioner for curriculum,
instruction and assessment, said state education officials were
stunned to learn that large parts of the test were nearly identical
to stories in a commercial curriculum widely used in New York,
California and other states.
</P>
<P>
   But she contended that familiarity with the material did not
invalidate the results. ``I don't think it compromises the
integrity of the test,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said any conclusions drawn from the state investigation
would be used to shape the content of future tests. ``I certainly
would not go back and change every student's score,'' she said.
``But it's important to know what the impact of the curriculum
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Three of the five reading passages on the first day of the test
were similar to a curriculum called Literacy Place, published by
Scholastic Inc., that was purchased by 78 schools in New York City
and 185 in the rest of the state, according to city, state and test
company officials.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reading passages, ``Summer Fun,'' about a family
fishing for crawdads, differs by only three sentences in a page and
a half of text from a story that appears in a CD-ROM available with
the Scholastic curriculum, according to the New York City Board of
Education.
</P>
<P>
   Two other reading passages cover the Wright Brothers and the
inventor Elijah McCoy, who are among the subjects of 24 trade books
that come with the Scholastic curriculum, said the test's
publisher, CTB/McGraw-Hill.
</P>
<P>
   But the publisher said the reading passages on the Wright
brothers and McCoy were not excerpted from the books in the
Scholastic series but came from other original sources.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kean, a spokesman for the test company, said it had
never consulted the Scholastic curriculum when designing the test
and that the resemblances were sheer coincidence. Nor, he said, was
it company policy to compare tests and popular commercial
curriculums in an effort to prevent duplication. Kean said that
such curriculums included thousands of books and that it would be
impractical, if not impossible, to match them against standardized
tests.
</P>
<P>
   Scholastic officials declined to comment but issued a statement
Wednesday saying that Literacy Place, which was developed in 1996,
has been bought by schools and districts across the country,
including San Franciso, San Bernardino, Bakersfield and Long Beach,
Calif.; Atlanta; Tampa, Fla.; Des Moines and Milwaukee. It has also
been adopted by the Defense Department for elementary schools on
military bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're gratified that our program fits so well with the New
York state test,'' the company said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
