<HEADLINE>
ON TRIAL'S EVE, REPUBLICANS SECRETLY DISCUSS CALLING WITNESSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: SUBS to UPDATE with Hyde saying prosecutors are considering
asking the Senate to call Clinton as a witness; recasts lead to
emphasize that standards are for whether witnesses should be called
at all; ADDS quotes, background; story now in 2 takes. )  
 (See also IMPEACH-LEGAL, IMPEACH-CLINTON, IMPEACH-HOUSE,
IMPEACH-SCENE.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic on the key players in the Senate trial is being
sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A small group of Senate Republicans has met
secretly with the House impeachment prosecutors to devise criteria
for determining whether witnesses would be called at the Senate
trial, even as prosecutors this week approached Monica S. Lewinsky
and Kathleen E. Willey about their possible testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The question of calling witnesses to testify before the Senate
has divided Democrats and Republicans as they set procedures for
the trial. After a rare bipartisan meeting last Friday, all 100
senators agreed to vote this month on whether to call witnesses.
Such a vote would take place after opening arguments from the House
managers and the White House, which begin on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the agreement, Sen. Trent Lott, the majority
leader, announced that Democrats and Republicans had agreed to have
a bipartisan group of four senators begin meeting immediately to
try to hash out how the Senate would deal with the witness issue
later. But that group did not materialize, nor was its creation
part of the official impeachment measure passed unanimously by the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Lott then quietly went ahead on his own and appointed three
Senate Republicans who have said publicly that they favor calling
witnesses _ Jon Kyl of Arizona, Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania and
Jeff Sessions of Alabama _ to work with Rep. Henry J. Hyde of
Illinois, the lead manager, and other prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats were belatedly invited to a meeting of the new
group on Monday, but Sen. Tom Daschle, the minority leader,
rejected the offer. ``Senator Daschle's position is that we voted
on an unanimous bipartisan level to put off the question of
witnesses, so it would not be in keeping with that agreement to
start a discussion about whether to call witnesses,'' said Ranit
Schmelzer, a spokeswoman for Daschle.
</P>
<P>
   The White House spurned a similar offer from the Republican
senators after the Senate Democrats said no.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of opening arguments in the trial, still another
development over witnesses threatened to fray the Senate's fragile
bipartisan posture: Hyde said that prosecutors are considering
whether to ask the Senate to call President Clinton to testify.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the Senate rules, we don't have any right to call him,''
Hyde told reporters after a meeting. ``We can request the Senate to
invite the president over, so we may do that.''
</P>
<P>
   His comments elicited an icy response from Clinton's aides.
``The White House has carefully respected the process adopted by a
unanimous Senate, which defers the decisions on witnesses until
each side has presented its case,'' said Jim Kennedy, a White House
spokesman. ``In contrast, the House has privately and now publicly
sought to impose its will on the Senate in defiance of the
bipartisan spirit which has characterized the Senate's conduct of
the trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Senate Republicans had defended their discussions with
the House managers over witnesses, saying they were aimed at
continuing the cooperative spirit created last week in the Old
Senate Chamber. ``We conveyed the sense of the Republican caucus,
and the joint caucus, that a large number of witnesses were not
going to be permitted,'' Specter said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Specter said the meetings, which have been preliminary, so far
have been designed to help the House managers winnow the list of
possible witnesses, which had reached 15 at one point. But Specter
cautioned that senators were careful not to advise the House
managers on which witnesses to call. So far, the criteria that the
senators hope House managers will use to determine the need for
live testimony at the trial involves evaluating witnesses who can
help resolve conflicting testimony or who are ``important in tenor
and tone.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the House managers confirmed that meetings had
taken place, but said that the senators had benefited more than the
House managers from the talks.
</P>
<P>
   The maneuvering over witnesses coincided with an implicit threat
in the White House legal brief filed Wednesday, in which Clinton's
lawyers argued that any witnesses would require a lengthy full
discovery process and could lead the defense team to call
additional witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and the White House have balked at any suggestion that
senators need to hear from witnesses like Ms. Lewinsky, partly
because of the fear that the trial would spin out of control with
unpredictable testimony, and a desire to complete the proceedings
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   But Hyde and other prosecutors have persisted in trying to
examine witnesses' accounts. For example, Hyde's aides disclosed
Wednesday that Ms. Lewinsky's lawyer, Plato Cacheris, had refused a
request from one of the House managers to set up an informal
meeting with Ms. Lewinsky, the former White House intern, to
question her about her account and gauge her credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Implicit in the House's right to request witnesses is the
responsibility of the managers to determine who those witnesses
will be,'' said Paul J. McNulty, a spokesman for the House
Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from seeking to talk to Ms. Lewinsky, two of the House
managers, Reps. Asa Hutchinson of Arkansas and Lindsey Graham of
South Carolina, met on Monday with Ms. Willey, a former White House
volunteer, and her lawyer, Dan Gecker, to discuss the possibility
of her appearing as a witness, said a Republican aide and another
person familiar with the case.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers, meeting in the office of a third manager, Rep.
James E. Rogan of California, raised the accusation that Clinton
had groped Ms. Willey, but they focused mainly on whether Ms.
Willey had been pressured to change her story. The House
prosecutors are interested in Ms. Willey's case to bolster the
obstruction of justice charge.
</P>
<P>
   The House managers have also talked about summoning other
witnesses, including Betty Currie, the president's secretary, and
John D. Podesta, the White House chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we'll come in with a long list of witnesses,''
Hyde said Wednesday night on the ABC News program ``Nightline.``
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my expectation and request to our managers that they not
call a witness unless the witness has something substantive to
contribute,'' Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the managers were walking a fine line in their
presentation to senators. ``I hope we don't bore them,'' he said,
``but the more detailed information we give them, the less they
want to call witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the 105-page legal brief it filed on Monday, the
House sent each senator two boxes of material _ 60,000 pages of
documents, audiotapes and videotapes _ that make up the official
record of the House impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   The White House issued its own set of documents, filing a
130-page memorandum that urged the Senate to acquit President
Clinton of lying under oath and obstructing justice. Clinton's
lawyers went beyond legal arguments and laced the filing with
warnings that convicting Clinton would overturn the popular will.
``Removal of the president on these grounds would defy the
constitutional presumption that the removal power rests with the
people in elections, and it would do incalculable damage to the
institution of the presidency,'' the memorandum said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton on Wednesday sought to distance himself from the trial
in the Senate, telling reporters, ``The most important thing for me
is to spend as little time about that as possible.'' He said,
``They have their job to do in the Senate, and I have mine, and I
intend to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   For each defense the White House offered, the House filing
disagreed, saying each accusation ``properly states an impeachable
offense, is not subject to a motion to dismiss, and should be
considered and adjudicated by the Senate sitting as a Court of
Impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   The dueling House and White House documents, the second such
exchange of filings in a week, set the stage for opening
presentations in the first impeachment trial of a president in 131
years.
</P>
<P>
   The trial opens in earnest almost a year after Kenneth W. Starr,
the independent counsel, began investigating the accusations
against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago Wednesday, Ms. Lewinsky's erstwhile friend, Linda R.
Tripp, went undercover for Starr to meet with Ms. Lewinsky and
record their conversations about attempts by the president to get
her a job and keep her from testifying in the Paula Jones sexual
misconduct case.
</P>
<P>
   In preparation for the arguments, some of the 13 House managers
and White House lawyers walked through the Senate chamber on
Wednesday, completing last-minute logistical details and preparing
to address 100 senators in the trial with Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist presiding.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans paraded out of an afternoon meeting insisting
that over the next few weeks, they could conduct legislative
business in the mornings and the impeachment trial in the
afternoons.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how the usually deliberative Senate could pull off such a
feat, Sen. Connie Mack of Florida, a member of the Republican
leadership, borrowed an explanation often given for Clinton's
ability to juggle several complicated subjects.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a phrase we didn't use very often around here,'' Mack
said. ``It is compartmentalization.''
</P>
<P>
   But Senate Democrats voiced fears that a lengthy trial with many
witnesses would hinder regular Senate business. ``The key question
is the number of witnesses,'' said Sen. Joseph I. Lieberman,
D-Conn. ``If there are not too many witnesses, it won't take too
long to depose them. My guess is that we're done by sometime early
to mid-February.''
</P>
<P>
   But if many witnesses are called, Lieberman said, the trial
could extend into March.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
