u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GIULIANI-VIRGINIA-NYT     01-13 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIULIANI-VIRGINIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 GIULIANI: REST OF THE COUNTRY SHOULD TAKE SOME OF NEW YORK CITY'S
TRASH
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BRUCE LAMBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Facing growing resistance from other states to New
York City's garbage, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Wednesday that the
rest of the nation was obligated to take it in return for the many
cultural and financial benefits reaped from the city.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's comments came in the wake of growing opposition to
accepting New York City trash in Virginia. Concerned that a major
disposal company is preparing to increase its shipments of trash
from New York, Gov. James S. Gilmore III called for limits to
prevent his state from becoming ``a dumping ground for East Coast
garbage.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, at his daily news conference Wednesday, elaborated on
his philosophy of waste disposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York City has a specialized problem,'' he said. `'It comes
from the fact that we're so crowded and ourland mass is very small,
and that brings great benefits to the rest of the country, like
Virginia. People in Virginia like to utilize New York because we're
a cultural center, because we're a business center. What goes along
with being a cultural and a business center is you're very crowded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have the room here to handle the garbage that's
produced not just by New Yorkers,'' he continued, ``but by the 3
million more people that come here that utilize the place every
day. So this is a reciprocal relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result of that relationship, the mayor continued, the rest
of the country should help the city with waste disposal. ``We don't
do it because we're profligate, we don't do it because we're
wasteful,'' he said of exporting the city's trash. ``We do it
because there are a lot of people in the city and that brings great
benefits to the American economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilmore, in a text of his State of the State message Wednesday
night, continued his opposition to out-of-state trash. ``I believe
the commonwealth has a right _ and I would say a duty _ to ban the
use of barges for the transportation of garbage on Virginia's
waterways,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The latest criticism arose when Waste Management Inc., a major
national disposal company, recently signed a contract with a barge
company that would enable up to 4,000 tons a day to be shipped to a
new port in Charles City, Va., on the James River. Waste Management
already transfers 2,400 tons of New York City garbage a day to
Virginia and other destinations.
</P>
<P>
   The criticism from Virginia came a month after the mayor
surprised and infuriated Gov. Christie Whitman of New Jersey with a
proposal to ship residential trash to transfer stations in her
state. She issued a news release with the headline, ``Whitman to
New York's Garbage Plan: Drop Dead'' and called the plan ``a direct
assault on the beaches of New Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Giuliani dismissed such criticism as a ``knee-jerk
political issue'' and said a ``counterforce'' of communities
supports the garbage industry for the business and jobs it creates.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people move beyond just a sort of knee-jerk political
issue here,'' he said, ``there's a whole industry out there, and
this will continue and it will be part of waste disposal for the
next 50 or 100 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor raised the possibility of litigation to force other
states to accept the city's waste.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure is growing on the city's garbage disposal system as the
legal deadline for closing the city's Fresh Kills landfill on
Staten Island at the end of 2001 approaches.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
