<HEADER>
A2428 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-SFCHRON     01-13 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SENATE IMPEACHMENT TRIAL BEGINS AMID UNCERTAINTY  &HT;     By LOUIS FREEDBERG 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Three hundred and fifty eight days after President
Clinton's affair with a White House intern became public, the
Senate will begin Thursday in earnest to consider whether he should
be ousted from office for perjury and obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   The trial begins with only the barest of road maps. Still
unclear is how long it will last, whether the Senate will call
witnesses, or what the Republican strategy is in pursuing a case
that almost certainly will not result in a conviction.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the Constitution requires a two-thirds majority
in the Senate to oust a president from office. Barring some
extraordinary new and damaging revelations, it is inconceivable
that 12 Democrats will join the 55 Republicans to provide the
necessary 67 votes.
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors disclosed Wednesday that they had attempted
earlier this week to interview Monica Lewinsky, whose relationship
with Clinton is at the heart of the impeachment trial. The
prosecutors said they wanted to talk to Lewinsky to prepare for the
possibility that the Senate will vote to call her as a witness. But
her attorneys rejected the House request, and Lewinsky remains out
of sight.
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors reportedly also contacted another potential
witness, Kathleen Willey, who has alleged Clinton made a sexual
advance on her in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton tried Wednesday to reinforce the message he has been
sending for nearly a year _ that the scandal has not impaired his
presidency. Pointedly, he will not even be in Washington during
Thursday's opening arguments, but instead will be in New York with
Jesse Jackson for a meeting of Wall Street executives.
</P>
<P>
   `I think the American people would like it if somebody up here
was putting their interests first, their business first, and I
think that's what they expect me to do,'' he said before meeting
with labor leaders to discuss next week's State of the Union
address.
</P>
<P>
   The White House continued to insist that Clinton will deliver
the speech before a joint session of Congress, as is customary, on
Tuesday, despite suggestions by Republicans that he postpone giving
it, or simply send a copy of it to Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that ``900 constitutional experts'' feel strongly that
what he is accused of does not warrant removal from office. ``But
my opinion is not important here,'' he said. ``I should be doing my
job for the country, And other people should be handling the
defense and dealing with this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lawyers sent to the Senate the most detailed defense
yet of the president's actions. The brief focused on both the
broader constitutional consequences of the Senate's actions, as
well as the minutiae of who said what to whom in various legal
proceedings involving independent counsel Kenneth Starr and the
House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   `It is the citizens of these United States who will be affected
by and stand in judgment of this process,'' the concluding
paragraph of the 130-page document stated. ``It is not simply the
president _ but the vote of the American people rendered in
schools, church halls and other civic centers all across the land
26 months ago _ that is hanging in the balance.''
</P>
<P>
   The brief accused Starr of ``engaging in an unauthorized attempt
to gather embarrassing information about the president'' long
before reports about his relationship with Monica Lewinsky were
first published on Jan. 21, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lawyers allege that Starr began looking into Clinton's
connections to over a dozen women, including Paula Jones, without
getting permission from the Justice Department to expand his
investigation beyond the Whitewater land deal in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   The report quotes Jones spokeswoman Susan McMillan Carpenter as
saying in June 1997, ``I will never deny that when I first heard
about this case, I said, `OK, good, we're going to get that little
slime ball.'''
</P>
<P>
   The report also zeroes in on specific words in the articles of
impeachment. The first article, for example, accuses Clinton of
perjuring himself by saying that he was alone with Lewinsky on
``certain occasions,'' when in fact he was alone with Lewinsky ``20
times, and had 11 sexual encounters.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers argued that a measure of the House's ``extraordinary
overreaching'' is its allegation that ``11 occasions of intimate
contact over more than a year did not occur by an objective
standard `on certain occasions.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers also challenge the House ``managers,'' or
prosecutors, to explain why Clinton gave gifts to Lewinsky _ on the
very day he is accused of getting his staff to retrieve them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must therefore be assumed that on the very day the
president and Ms. Lewinsky were conspiring to hide the gifts that
he had already given to her, the president added to the pile,'' the
lawyers wrote. ``No stretch of logic will support such an
outlandish theory.''
</P>
<P>
   At 1 p.m. EDT Thursday, all 100 senators will assemble in the
Senate chambers, with Chief Justice William Rehnquist wielding the
gavel. They will first hear an opening statement from Rep. Henry
Hyde, R-Ill., chairman of the House Judiciary Committee. He will be
followed by Rep. James Sensenbrenner, R-Wis., one of the 13
impeachment managers appointed by the House, who will give a longer
statement that he says will ``lay out the case and show very
clearly that the president committed an impeachable offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the ground rules adopted by the Senate last week, the
House managers will then have 24 hours spread over three days to
make their case, and the White House will then have 24 hours
beginning next week for its defense.
</P>
<P>
   In preparation for the trial, Republican leaders issued a
one-page memo Wednesday outlining the proper decorum for the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Senators will be required to be in attendance during all
proceedings. The memo instructed typically loquacious senators to
``refrain from speaking to neighboring senators while the case is
presented.'' Nor will they be permitted to read any extraneous
materials. ``Our individual reading materials should be confined to
only those readings which pertain to the matter before the
Senate,'' the memo advised.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist must also be addressed as ``Mr. Chief Justice.'' Last
week when the trial opened, some senators addressed Rehnquist as
``Mr. president'' _ referring not to Clinton but to the president
of the Senate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
