<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CASSTEVENS-JORDAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEY, MIKE, THANKS FOR THE MEMORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's been fun writing about Michael Jordan. So many places and
big events. So many memories. Here are excerpts from a few of mine
. . .
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QC; 
They sat at a long table, on display like our first space heroes,
the Mercury astronauts.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, Johnson, Ewing, Robinson, Barkley, Pippen, Stockton . .
.
</P>
<P>
   America's finest. The Dream Team.
</P>
<P>
   As photographers' strobes washed them in stuttering bursts of
light, the greatest collection of basketball talent ever assembled
traded grins and sidelong glances and listened through earphones as
questions were translated into English.
</P>
<P>
   From Japan: ``Mr. Jordan, can you tell me how does it feel to be
called a god?''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan looked at his smirking teammates. ``I've never
seen a god, so I don't know how a god would act. I take it as a
compliment.'' &QL; 
 &UR; _ Barcelona, July 26, 1992 &QR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Black, sleek, it lay as if asleep, a panther in repose. Ferrari
Testarossa. Pirelli racing tires. Cellular phone. Vanity plates:
`M-Air-J.''
</P>
<P>
   J.R. ``Jelly'' Roll gazed admiringly at the Italian Batmobile.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just ``one'' of his cars,'' said Jelly, an employee of
Bismarck Food Services, the caterer at Chicago Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can afford a Testarossa,'' Charles Barkley said,
unimpressed. ``What is it? $100,000? $240,000?'' Then the playful
zinger, (a reference to Jordan's gambling habits): ``That's just a
couple of rounds of golf. . . .'' &QL; 
 &UR; _ Chicago, June 16, 1993 &QR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Jordan is Houdini. He should play in a tuxedo. Points appear
from his hand like endless scarves blooming from a magician's
sleeve.
</P>
<P>
   Only one man could have beaten the no-quit Suns in Game 4 of the
NBA Finals. Only one athlete in the world could have upstaged
Charles Barkley (32 points, 12 rebounds, 10 assists), and here he
came, as dreaded as a midnight telegram, with the Bulls leading by
only two points and the clock ticking down . . . 16 . . . 15 . . .
14 . . . his eyes on the basket, his shaved head beaded with sweat,
coming hard now into the red paint, driving the lane, poised and
filled with purpose. &QL; 
 &UR; _ Chicago, June 17, 1993 &QR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   There was no man in Michael Jordan's life over 6 feet tall.
Michael sometimes asked his mother, ``How tall was the milkman? How
tall was the mailman?''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was teasing. As far back as he can remember, there always
was James Jordan, provider, role model, disciplinarian, companion,
best friend.
</P>
<P>
   James Jordan sat in America West Arena and watched the Bulls
beat the Suns for their third consecutive NBA title. That was less
than two months ago . . .
</P>
<P>
   Now James Jordan is gone. Someone fired a bullet into his chest
and dumped his body into a creek.
</P>
<P>
   Who would do this? Why? As questions demand answers, Michael
Jordan has gathered with family members. He has come home, as
families do, to grieve and to remember the joys of a lifetime of a
father's love. &QL; 
 &UR; _ Aug. 15, 1993 &QR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Please tell me the greatest basketball player ever to fly
through the air hasn't played his last game. Tell me Jordan is not
retiring. Not now. Not yet.
</P>
<P>
   Michael ``is'' the Bulls. Jordan and the Bulls are as synonymous
as DiMaggio and the Yankees, Shoemaker and Churchill Downs, Hoover
and the FBI. &QL; 
 &UR; _ Chicago, Oct. 6, 1993 &QR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   I've never felt a crowd embrace an athlete so completely as the
7,454 in this little ballpark did when Michael Jordan stepped up to
bat.
</P>
<P>
   C'mon, Mike, wait for your pitch. Good eye. Be a hitter now . .
.
</P>
<P>
   At the plate, he looks so tall, and thin, like a marsh bird in
pinstripes. His strike zone is as big as his name.
</P>
<P>
   It is strange thinking of him as an underdog. We've only known
him as the best, the greatest, unstoppable. &QL; 
 &UR; _ Sarasota, Fla., March 13, 1994 &QR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Most of us thought Jordan would have a change of heart and
return to the NBA someday. His announcement that he is leaving
baseball reinforces the rumor he is about to rejoin the Bulls. Has
any professional athlete retired from two sports, and unretired
from one?
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan is the one athlete on the planet I would pay to
see come back. &QL; 
 &UR; _ March 11, 1995 &QR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   They checked out of The Phoenician. Half hour later, the
red-and-yellow charter bus eased through the back entrance at
America West Arena and pulled to a stop with a sigh.
</P>
<P>
   The coach, Phil Jackson, stepped out first, lost in thought,
trailed by the general manager, Jerry Krause.
</P>
<P>
   Then, one by one, the cast emerged.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Wennington. Toni Kukoc. Luc Longley. Dennis Rodman, the
three-ring (one in his nose, two in his ear) circus.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Harper followed.
</P>
<P>
   Jud Buechler.
</P>
<P>
   Then, from the back of the bus, the man. He wore a muted gray
business suit, silk necktie, suede shoes . . . He ambled loosely
down the hallway, smiling and nodding acknowledgment to groups of
arena employees who pressed against the wall and watched with rapt
expressions, as if viewing a one-man parade . . . &QL; 
 &UR; _ Nov. 21, 1997 &QR; 
David Casstevens can be reached at david.casstevens(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
