<SLUG> BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-TICKETS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS DEMAND DWINDLES  
 SEASON-TICKET SALES MAY DROP BY 10,000 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although the Diamondbacks have spent nearly $120 million to
upgrade their ballclub, the club will fall far short of matching
its season ticket total from its inaugural season.
</P>
<P>
   Team officials are projecting the major league-high
season-ticket base of 36,000 from last year to dip somewhere near
26,000. That's a 28 percent drop, but the figure still will place
the Diamondbacks among the top four of the 30 big-league clubs.
</P>
<P>
   The drop-off comes in the wake of a ticket price increase
averaging 12 percent, from an average of $14.69 per seat in 1998 to
$16.48 in 1999. The price increase was announced on Fan
Appreciation Weekend, inciting a wave of criticism. In addition,
many fans likely realized that a season-ticket package, even if
shared with others, was more of a time commitment than they
bargained for.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a little bit disappointed, but when you look at the
numbers across the rest of baseball, we're where we want to be,''
said vice president in charge of ticket operations Diane Aguilar.
``We still expect to be in top three or four in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Colorado, Baltimore and Atlanta are expected to have larger
season-ticket bases for the 1999 season. Cleveland, which
anticipates selling out its fifth full consecutive season shortly,
caps season-ticket sales at 26,000, leaving 17,000 single-game
tickets available for its 81 home dates.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians have already sold 3.3 million of its 3.4 million
available tickets.
</P>
<P>
   While the loss of 10,000 season tickets will surely be felt
within the organization, the Diamondbacks remain well ahead of
their expansion brother, the Tampa Bay Devil Rays, who are expected
to have a base somewhere around 19,000 for the 1999 season,
slightly down from their inaugural base of 22,000.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado, which has led the major leagues in total attendance
during each of its six years in existence, is anticipating a drop
of only 500 in its season-ticket base, a figure that would still
place the Rockies' base at 32,500. Colorado drew just under 3.8
million fans last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks ticket base, as of Wednesday, was right around
25,000, Aguilar said. She said there is a waiting list of about
1,000 new ticket holders who will be added once last year's
season-ticket holders finish buying their 1999 seats.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, the club sent out letters requesting the
final installment for 1999 season tickets. Some invoices say the
deadline for such payments is Jan. 29, but Aguilar said it has been
extended to Feb. 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only fair to extend the deadline because it took us
longer than expected to get these invoices out,'' Aguilar said.
</P>
<P>
   To help boost season-ticket sales, the Diamondbacks are strongly
considering selling mini-season ticket plans, similar to those used
by the Coyotes and Cardinals. In addition, single-game ticket sales
will begin sometime early next month. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
