<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-COL-KRUGEL-TEX </SLUG>
 
Michael's Greatest Gift 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MITCHELL KRUGEL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
The sports talk radio fodder and water cooler debates continue
today assessing Michael Jordan's greatest moments and greatest
memories.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Proceed, if you will, to discuss all the hot shots, flights of
fancy and tongue-out-of-cheek moments. Michael's greatest gift to
his public might be the you've-never-seen-it-before,
never-see-it-again aura.
</P>
<P>
   But the most memorable moment here from somebody who spent 10
seasons tracking and covering the man, his words and his life came
long before he ever won a championship ring or shaved his head.
</P>
<P>
   When Michael Jordan first signed on to play for the Chicago
Bulls, he insisted his contract include a ``love-of-the-game''
clause. This, he insisted, would give him the OK to play
basketball, no matter where, no matter when, no matter who else was
on the court.
</P>
<P>
   And so what we will miss most now that His Highness has left the
building is that love of the game.
</P>
<P>
   You must love the game when you sprain an ankle in the third
quarter of a playoff game in Atlanta, have to be carried to the
locker room, then come back to score 14 fourth-quarter points as MJ
did in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   You have to love the game when some guy named LaBradford Smith
has a career-high 36 points on you one night in Washington, and you
come back to score 36 points on him the next night.
</P>
<P>
   You have to love the game when you go to a local mall to buy a
pair of shoes only to have the entire shopping public find out you
are there and trap you inside that store.
</P>
<P>
   You must love the game when you want to go Christmas shopping
for your newborn daughter Jasmine, but are resigned to sitting in
the manager's office of a downtown Chicago mall while merchants
bring you presents to choose from.
</P>
<P>
   The love-of-the-game clauses for this tribute could easily
become a glut of run-on sentences, but that wouldn't be the parting
message Michael Jordan wants to submit.
</P>
<P>
   No, Michael made his last will and testament during his farewell
sequel yesterday from Chicago. He took responsibility for what the
NBA has become for better and for worse, and hereby bequeathed the
following.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unfortunate thing either myself or some of the other
players before me has brought more to focus is the financial aspect
of the game,'' he preached. ``I think that's going to have to
dissipate a little bit and get more back to the love of the game.
The love of the game is what you do on the basketball court.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Michael was sticking his tongue out at his NBA brood one
last time yesterday. Love the game. Don't play it for money, play
it to win.
</P>
<P>
   And, oh yes, Michael Jordan loved the game because he loved to
win. We will miss that, too, that Air for the dramatic of scoring
50 in mid-February in Sacramento or stealing the ball from Karl
Malone or whatever it takes to win.
</P>
<P>
   Another great athlete of this century had a similar will to win.
Not Ali. Not Ruth. A legendary tale about Secretariat suggested
that after the great horse died, an examination of his heart found
that it was twice as big as that of a normal thoroughbred
racehorse.
</P>
<P>
   My theory is that Jordan had the same anatomical advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The magic of television will keep us from missing the hot shots,
flights of fancy and tongue-out-of-cheek moments. ESPN Classic
Sports will give us 56 consecutive hours of those this weekend, and
we will never have to settle for just telling our kids what it was
like to see Michael play.
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Jordan's retirement unquestionably leaves us with
love lost.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
